<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-POSTSEASON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The baseball playoffs have provided enough edge-of-your-seat
moments and spellbinding twists and turns to take us into the next
millennium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the World Series hasn't begun.
</P>
<P>
   But does it have a tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   How can the Fall Classic possibly top a postseason that already
has produced one amazing comeback, another that fell just short and
a matchup between two of most storied organizations in history?
</P>
<P>
   While fans look ahead in anticipation of a World Series showdown
between the New York Yankees and Atlanta Braves for the title of
``Team of the '90s,'' there has been plenty of reflection on what
many regard as one of the best National League Championship Series
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to die, the New York Mets mounted a furious comeback
against Atlanta before falling short of becoming the first team to
overcome a 3-0 postseason deficit. The tug-of-war series featured
five games decided by one run and one by two. Two games went extra
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The defining moment of the series came in Game 5, when the Mets
and Braves staged an epic 15-inning battle won by New York on Robin
Ventura's grand-slam-turned-single.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets rallied from 5-0 and 7-3 deficits to take the
lead, twice, in Game 6, the Braves used a bases-loaded, 11th-inning
walk to set up a rematch of the 1996 Series with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take some time during the winter to watch these
games and try to enjoy them like I think millions of people got to
enjoy them,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said after the
exhausting yet exhilarating series.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Mets played during the final week of the regular
season and on through the NLCS, Valentine could build a video
library.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing a page from their history book, the Mets were amazin'
in the playoffs, with a late push on the season's final weekend, a
tiebreaker playoff win at Cincinnati to earn the NL wild-card spot,
and a first-round upset of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the thrilling six-game series with Atlanta, which
ranks with the 1986 NLCS between the Astros and Mets and the 1980
Astros-Phillies war as possibly the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a broadcaster's standpoint, I think the LCS we just
finished doing was the best one I've ever seen or been involved
with as an analyst,'' said former major-leaguer Joe Morgan, who
teamed with Bob Costas during NBC's coverage and who played for the
1980 Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mets and Yankees kept alive the idea of the first
Subway Series since 1956.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, What would a Subway Series be like? I don't
think any of us could imagine what it would have been like. It
would have been a once-in-a-lifetime experience,'' said Yankees
pitcher David Cone, who played six seasons with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The postseason excitement has not been limited to the NL.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox, known more for heartbreak than for success,
completed a stunning turnaround in their AL Division Series against
Cleveland, becoming only the fifth team to rally from an 0-2
deficit to win a best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball got its wish _ an ALCS featuring the Yankees and Red
Sox, arguably the fiercest rivalry in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have a better scenario to close out the
millennium than the Red Sox against the Yankees for the pennant,''
Yankees pinch hitter Jim Leyritz said.
</P>
<P>
   New York took the first two games, both by one run, before Cy
Young Award favorite Pedro Martinez and the Red Sox handed the
Yankees their most lopsided playoff loss ever, 13-1, in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won the final two games for their 36th AL pennant.
</P>
<P>
   In the six playoff series (AL and NL) this year, 13 games were
decided by one or two runs and five have gone extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reinforces how many things have to go right to advance,''
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``There are some very
good baseball teams sitting home now.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is making its fifth trip to the World Series in the
1990s but is looking for an elusive second title. The Yankees are
trying for their third title in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says something for having been there and knowing what it's
like where you can settle in and do your job,'' Yankees manager Joe
Torre said. ``To repeat after the incredible year we had last year
is quite an accomplishment. Hopefully, we can hold up well in the
World Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
