   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Oct. 22
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-FOREST (Bella, Bella British Columbia) _ Canadian logging
companies are now moving into what environmentalists call ``the
Brazil of the north'' _ a vast, barely disturbed sea of trees,
one-quarter of the world's remaining temperate rain forest. Over
the next 25 years, 50 of the coastal forest's largest valleys are
scheduled be logged. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT32) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMER (Undated) _ The long, brutal process that leads to
Alzheimer's disease starts when a single enzyme snips a protein
that protrudes from brain cells, leading to the release of toxic
shards. Now scientists report that they have found that enzyme,
opening the door to developing drugs that might block it and _ if
the drugs prove safe _ prevent or slow the disease. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAIRY-FARMS (Chino, Calif.) _ As suburban sprawl once
again forces dairy farms to move beyond Los Angeles, one of the
striking things is that, just as happened in the move from Los
Angeles County several decades ago, a big increase in farmers' land
values is financing a transition that will result in a new
generation of highly efficient dairies that will only widen
California's lead over Wisconsin. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT33,34) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE (Washington) _ A 20-year study shows early-childhood
education dramatically affects success. Researchers at the
University of North Carolina followed 111 poor, African-American
babies, half of whom had high-quality child care from infancy. As
they turn 21, those in the child-care program are more likely to be
in college or have graduated (35 percent compared to 14 percent)
and hold jobs (65 percent versus 50 percent). They also have higher
IQs (by 14 points) and, on average, had their first baby at age 19
rather than 17. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLDEST-DINOSAURS (Undated) _ Fossils from two calf-sized
animals that lived in a period before the Jurassic era are thought
to be the oldest dinosaur remains ever found, researchers report
Friday in Science. The upper and lower jaw bones, from two new
dinosaur species, are more than 227 million years old and shed
light on the time when dinosaurs were dividing into the meat-eaters
and the plant-eaters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-WEB (Undated) _ The launch of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's new online stock trading service was not as easy as
planned, and one reason involves a tangled tale of either youthful
innocence or cybersquatting. By Patrick McGeehan and Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ It was only eight months ago that Alan
Greenspan was on the cover of Time as the most prominent member of
``The Committee to Save the World,'' a man who had prevented a
global economic meltdown by reducing interest rates. But now his
halo is slipping, and the muttering is increasing. How dare he
raise interest rates? Who is he to question the stock market's
valuation? By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SYCAMORE-IPO (Undated) _ When Cisco Systems Inc. agreed to
acquire Cerent Corp. for almost $7 billion, many everyday investors
had a common reaction: Who's Cerent? They may well have a similar
feeling now because another small company, Sycamore Networks Inc.,
appears set to make a big financial wave _ only this time investors
will have a chance to catch it. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   CONSULTING-FIRMS (Undated) _ Top consulting firms battle the
e-commerce tide that is stealing many of their best job candidates
and employees. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Decrying what they see as an
unfair and conflict-ridden manipulation of the young, a group of
psychologists and other professionals has called on the American
Psychological Association to restrict the use of psychological
research by advertisers pitching toys, videogames, snack food and
other products to children. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-CHIPS (Singapore) _ The personal-computer industry has
a variety of things to worry about this holiday season, but supply
problems from last month's deadly earthquake in Taiwan may not be
one of them. Although several American companies have warned that
semiconductor shortages could crimp earnings and make it hard to
meet demand for personal computers this Christmas, some of the
biggest suppliers to those companies say a month later that they
are not only back to normal, but filled most of their September
orders. By Martin Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-OWNERSHIP (Undated) _ The number of stock owners in the
nation soared to 78.7 million people early this year, 85 percent
more than in 1983 when the long bull market was getting under way.
Among households, 48.2 percent now own stock directly or through
mutual funds, more than double the 19 percent with such a stake in
1983, according to a survey by Investment Company Institute and the
Securities Industry Association. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
