<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BROOKS-LADN     10-22 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BROOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKS: TYSON OLDER, WISER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It's Tommy Brooks' job to pump up his fighter, to
make the world _ and the fighter _ believe he can accomplish
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he will elicit some chuckles with his response to this
question: Could Mike Tyson ever again resemble the fighter he was a
decade ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually think Mike can be a !ital!better!off! fighter
through maturity,'' said Brooks, whose protege takes on Orlin
Norris in his latest comeback fight here on Saturday. ``Look at the
(Joe) Louises, the (Ray) Robinsons, you learn how to do certain
things after a period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You become fluent in it. I think that's the point Mike is
coming to in this part of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was among those who suspected that the Tyson who swept
through the heavyweight division like a bowling ball through pins
in the '80s is a memory.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't thrown combinations as he once did, he hasn't jabbed,
he hasn't punched to the body, he hasn't bobbed his head and moved
his feet to avoid taking punishment. He has relied solely on his
considerable power to get the job done and that's not always good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks could attest to this first hand: He was in the corner of
Evander Holyfield as an assistant trainer for both victories over
Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   So, Brooks feared the worst when he took over as Tyson's trainer
before his knockout victory over Francois Botha in January. He
wondered about Tyson both as a person and as a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   He swears he was pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, first, I expected him to be a spoiled-rotten kid, a hood
rat who just got lucky and got a lot of money,'' said Brooks, who
is as conservative as Tyson can be wild. ``I was totally wrong.
He's one of the nicest guys I've ever met. I put him in the same
category as Evander.
</P>
<P>
   ``... And he possessed more talent than I thought he had. He can
box, he knows how to fight. He's just been fed the wrong
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he has yet to have a philosophical chat with Tyson,
so he's not the authority on Mike Tyson the person.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has spent six months with him in training camps. He
knows what the 33-year-old former two-time champion is capable of
doing in the ring, at least the ring in the gym. And he likes what
he sees.
</P>
<P>
   How does he explain Tyson's deterioration? Bad habits that were
re-enforced through repetition and the fact no one around him could
convince him he was doing anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks attributed Holyfield's pummeling of Tyson in 1996 _ a
stunning 11th-round knockout _ in part to the fact he had taken
Holyfield lightly and had undertrained. He said he learned recently
that Tyson was in camp only four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   However, he admitted Tyson also was ill-equipped in terms of his
skills: He did nothing right that night.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks also conceded that Tyson's performance against Botha was
a disappointment, at least until he ended a fight he was losing
with one big punch in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, coming off a 1{-year layoff at that time because of his
suspension for biting Holyfield's ear, fought in the gym the way
Brooks wanted him to fight but reverted to his inferior style once
the fight began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike was trying to prove something, not only to the public but
to himself,'' Brooks said. ``He wanted people to say, `Mike Tyson
is the baddest man on the planet' again by knocking (Botha) out
with one punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what he was doing instead of putting his punches
together like we worked on.''
</P>
<P>
   So where is Tyson now after another layoff, this one nine months
after his second stint in prison?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Brooks doesn't see him as an old fighter. He's
taken only two beatings in his career _ against Buster Douglas and
Holyfield _ and the long hiatuses have spared his body punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Brooks insists, Tyson has a lot left physically. He
remains quick, both in hand and foot speed, has perfectly good
reflexes and the power will always be there.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson also listens to his trainers, Brooks and Jay Bright, his
former head trainer who goes back to the Cus D'Amato days. Brooks
said Tyson refers to him as ``sir,'' a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the results are good much of the time in the gym, Brooks
said. Tyson shows glimpses of the terrorizing fighter he once was:
He throws more than one punch at a time and he doesn't telegraph
them, he doesn't stand directly in front of his sparring partners
waiting to be hit and he fights with spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his motivation _ which appears more than ever to be
money, which he needs to pay off debts and support his family _ he
seems to understand what it will take to succeed the fourth time
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier for me to prepare now than when I was younger,''
Tyson said. ``Before, I was more of a loose cannon. I thought I
could conquer the world, but I know it takes a lot of hard work and
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still young. I feel strong and believe I can compete with
the best of the current crop of heavyweights.''
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming he brings what he learns and does in the gym
into his fights over an extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
   If he does, Brooks is convinced, Tyson could surprise a lot of
people in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of 1 to 10, Mike is about a seven right now,''
Brooks said. ``How long it will take him to get to 10 is up to him.
We're taking it step by step. He has to be able to do what we're
working on in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``... And I think he understands. He's got a family to look out
for. He just can't throw caution to the wind anymore. You'll see.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I see Mike retiring as heavyweight champion of the world,
riding off into the sunset with one of his kids on his knee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
