<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN DROPS AIR-TOUR PHRASE, KEEPS NOISY FLIGHTS OUT OF CANYON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Working to patch his relations with environmentalists,
Ari zona Sen. John McCain on Oct. 21 removed language in a bill
that could have allowed a noisy air-tour ``free-for-all'' over
Grand Canyon National Park.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candi date dropped a plan that could
have automatically allowed all air-tour aircraft to be considered
``quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a designation would have allowed unlimited numbers of
air-tour flights. McCain's old amend ment, passed last week by the
U.S. Senate, also would have eliminated the curfew on flights over
the eastern end of the Canyon within an hour of sunrise and sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, new language McCain in serted into the bill, which
re-author izes the Federal Aviation Administration, would require
that agency to establish standards for what constitutes ``quiet
aircraft tech nology.''
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters and fixed-wing airplanes that use less noisy
technology would be allowed to fly in newly designated ``quiet
aircraft'' corridors over the Canyon, according to the language
pushed Oct. 21 by McCain through a House-Senate conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   However, environmentalists and Na tional Park Service officials
argue that no aircraft is ``quiet,'' just less noisy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the language, less noisy air craft would be exempt from
caps on the number of flights over the Canyon set to take effect
Jan. 31, as long as the number of aircraft did not diminish
McCain's 1987 legisla tion calling for ``the substantial
restoration of the natural quiet'' at the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal from the beginning was to get the action necessary to
address the noise problem at Grand Can yon,'' McCain said. ``I'm
pleased that the agreement will achieve that objective in a manner
that all parties find acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the new language was praised by three prominent envi
ronmental &QL; 
groups, Sierra Club spokesman Rob Smith continued to express
reserva tions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an improvement &QL; 
from the disaster it was going to be,'' Smith said. ``But there are
no quiet aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that if more flights are allowed, there will be more
noise.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Smith called for a complete ban, perhaps in three to
five years, of all aircraft that does not employ so-called quiet
technology.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his measure, which still must be approved by the
full House and Senate and signed by President Clinton, would create
``appropriate incentives to encourage the transi tion'' to quieter
aircraft ``in a timely manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill also calls for the FAA and the Park Service to develop
``air-tour management plans'' to govern where, when, how and even
if tourist aircraft may fly over the nation's parks. Currently, air
tours are con ducted over nearly 100 national parks.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's plan was praised by other environmental groups as a
compro mise with the air-tour industry, which currently makes
117,000 flights annu ally over the Canyon. Environmen talists said
noise from those flights drown ``the natural sounds that are a
unique part of the Canyon's character.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Barnard, president of the Flagstaff-based Grand Canyon
Trust, said, ``Senator McCain has retaken the hill, and once again
served notice that he is serious about his defense of the Grand
Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kiernan, president of the Na tional Parks and Conservation
Asso ciation, said, ``(McCain's) advocacy of quiet technology will,
over time, make a difference in how park visitors see and hear the
Canyon.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
