<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME OPENER LEFT ITS MARK ON KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the morning after the Kings' home opener, there
was little trace of the club at the Staples Center. The ice was
covered over and the stage put back in place for Thursday night's
Bruce Springsteen concert.
</P>
<P>
   But third-line winger Marko Tuomainen isn't likely to forget his
first game in the new building. He was poked in the left eye during
the second period against Boston and is expected to miss 10 days
beginning with tonight's game against the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is blood in the eye and it will be awhile before he gets
back,'' coach Andy Murray said Thursday at the Iceoplex. ``We'll
have to make a few adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Left winger Steve McKenna, who has missed all but one game due
to a torn retina in his left eye, has been cleared to return, but
Murray will decide how soon McKenna plays during today's morning
workout at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Eye injuries are part of hockey, although the numbers are down
because more players, including Kings first-liners Luc Robitaille,
Ziggy Palffy and Jozef Stumpel, are wearing plastic shields on
their helmets. Often that is not enough, though, because stick
blades can get between the face and the shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a lot of guys still do not like to wear them,'' Murray
said. ``You grow up playing a certain way and it is hard to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisheye: There were some complaints from fans in the lower bowl
of the Staples Center that the glass along the boards distorts the
action.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many new arenas that have a clear-glass view of the ice,
the Staples Center uses an older style in which the glass is fitted
into metal slats. One reason is for quick event changes. After
Thursday's concert, the Springsteen stage was struck and the Kings
ice was uncovered. This will happen two more times in the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Kings are complaining about the older glass. The
newer version is heavier and very inflexible. There is very little
give, making checks into the boards far more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is hot: The Coyotes, who lost to St. Louis in the first
round of the playoffs last spring, are off to their best start in
franchise history. They are 4-1-2 under new coach Bob Francis and
tied with the Kings for third in the Pacific Division despite
playing without top scorer Jeremy Roenick the past four games
during to a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick, who led the Coyotes with 72 points last season, will
finish the suspension tonight and is scheduled to return Saturday
against the Washington Capitals in Phoenix. He was suspended for
slashing close friend and former Chicago Black Hawks teammate Tony
Amonte on the chin Oct. 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
