<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GAMBINA-SHOOTING-LADN     10-22 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBINA-SHOOTING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORE OWNER DETAILS GUN BATTLE WITH ROBBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY HARRISON SHEPPARD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Three days after a wild shootout with two
robbers, market owner Ralph Gambina recalled the harrowing
experience clearly.
</P>
<P>
   When the two men burst into his store in the Tujunga community
20 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles and demanded cash, he
said, he was ready for trouble: He had a 9 mm Ruger pistol tucked
in the back of his waistband and he wasn't afraid to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a gun in his face, he kept waiting for his moment, for
the time the robbers would slip up and give him a chance to draw.
</P>
<P>
   He would soon get his chance, and when it was all over, a
16-year was lying dead on the floor, and Gambina had a bullet in
his lung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't breathe'' after being shot, he said Thursday in a
telephone interview from his hospital bed. ``It felt like a knife
in my back. My lung was filling with blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the pain, he was determined to chase after the
robber who had shot him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lying on the floor. I wiggled my hands and feet and said
I'm all right. Let's go. So I jumped up and went after him. By the
time I got to the door, he was gone. I went around the corner and
saw his silhouette in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambina said he always carries a gun on him at the store. His
father was killed in a 1981 robbery and his own store had been
robbed twice in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The latest robbery began around 11:40 p.m. Monday. Gambina was
alone in the store when two men burst in and demanded cash from the
register.
</P>
<P>
   The larger man, who had a gun, was wearing a ski mask, while the
other had a hood pulled around his face with a drawstring, Gambina
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Coroner's Office later identified the
smaller suspect as 16-year-old Louis Manuel Chavez of Altadena, a
city 20 miles northeast of Los Angeles. The other suspect is still
at large.
</P>
<P>
   Gambina acted nervous, telling them ``Don't shoot me, I got four
kids. I'll give you everything I got.'' But in his head, he said,
he thought of the Ruger, and waited for them to make just one
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Since the register was nearly empty, they ordered him to open
the safe. Gambina led the larger man to the back of the store,
while the smaller one rifled through the front counter area and
ripped a telephone out of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   His safe was closed, but unlocked. Gambina turned the dials,
locking it, as he pretended to forget the combination under the
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   He was still waiting for his moment. After the robber gave up on
the safe, they walked back to the front of the store. As he passed
through the doorway, his moment came. Gambina dived behind an
aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big guy didn't have a clear shot at me,'' he recalled. ``I
drew my weapon and popped the little guy twice.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger man fired at him, hitting some boxes. Gambina took a
few steps back and tried to fire again, but his gun jammed. He
banged it against the wall, and that was when he got shot once. The
bullet pierced his left side and went through to his lung, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gambina hit the ground. His body hurt, but once he realized he
was going to survive, he stood up. He tried chasing after the other
man, but decided not to follow him into the neighborhood. He
returned to the store and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   As for the young man lying on the floor of his store in a pool
of blood?
</P>
<P>
   ``I kicked him in the head and I said, Was it worth it?''
</P>
<P>
   He had thought the 16-year-old was armed as well, but it turned
out the object in his hand was the store's telephone, Gambina said.
</P>
<P>
   Gambina said he regrets the death of the teen, but felt
justified in defending himself. Police agreed, deciding not to
arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a plain working stiff who wants to do a decent job,'' he
said. He was born in the family's store, he added, and ``I want to
die of old age there.''
</P>
<P>
   Once some gang members tried to steal some beer from his store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat them both in the head with a pistol and got my beer
back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-MAGIC-ROCKETS-HNS     10-22 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAGIC-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
On the practice court, the extra pass is made. The defensive switch
comes over. Teammates cover each other's back. Open shots fall.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rockets gush about the collective talent they see. Coaches
see pieces that seem to fit together. And then the Rockets take a
real court, with loud music and a scoreboard that on occasion
successfully keeps score, and everything but the talent disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich will suffer preseason defeats as part of
the process. The latest, a 110-98 loss Thursday night at Compaq
Center to the even more rebuilt Magic, drove the Rockets' preseason
record to 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a problem with no easy solution. How does he fix
something that isn't broken when it is time for repairs?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the negatives outweighed the positives,''
Tomjanovich said. ``The thing that really disappointed me was I
thought we were just too anxious on offense by far. We took a lot
of bad shots. We definitely have skills I think will mesh together.
We never gave it a chance. We didn't deserve to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Magic) played as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets called for patience given the changes in their
roster and style. But they played a team that has been almost
completely overhauled, with 24 transactions involving 34 players
since Doc Rivers replaced Chuck Daly as Magic coach. The Magic
(5-0) has two wins over the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I thought we were struggling,'' Rivers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win and are willing to sacrifice our individual
games,'' said guard Tariq Abdul-Wahad, one of 12 new Magic players.
``It's a brand-new team. Doc and the coaches are doing a great job,
and it's a lot of fun to be in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Orlando struggled, the Rockets showed few strides in
getting their retooled roster in sync with only three preseason
games left before the start of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forget about the record,'' Tomjanovich said. ``What concerns
me is I saw individual play. I thought this team on paper,
chemistry-wise, fits. We had too many possessions out there where
we didn't make the right pass. It was very contagious. We were
shooting it with guys in our face. In practice, we pass the heck
out of the ball. But some of the things we work on are not
translating to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets did finally reduce their turnovers. Averaging 27.5
in their first four games, they had 20. Guards Steve Francis and
Shandon Anderson each had four in 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the perimeter players barely had time to turn the ball over.
They shot quickly and often. Francis, Anderson, Cuttino Mobley and
Bryce Drew combined to make 18 of 48 shots, leaving little time to
get the ball inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played like some garbage,'' said Francis, who had 20 points,
seven assists, four steals and seven rebounds. ``I couldn't buy a
layup. I was missing a lot of layups.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Hakeem Olajuwon made just three of eight shots. Kelvin
Cato had his first poor game offensively, making one of seven
shots.
</P>
<P>
   With Charles Barkley still out with a strained right elbow, many
of the usual low-post options were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to work toward playing winning basketball and learning
from games like tonight,'' Olajuwon said. ``We need to make a
conscious effort to get good shots every time downcourt. The only
way to win is to play together as a team and feed off each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a conscious effort to make sure we get something every
time, to get good shots. If you get good shots and miss good shots,
nobody can fault you for missing good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Rockets insisted the time will come. Even with
Barkley and Matt Bullard (sore knee) out, the Rockets used 11
players. Carlos Rogers worked at small forward. Center Thomas
Hamilton played by far the most minutes, 17, that he has in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main problem is that we don't know each other, and at
times it shows,'' forward Tony Massenburg said. ``A lot of people
have high expectations of us, and we need to work on some things. I
sense that we don't know our roles well so we need to learn what
everybody does best and work together to take advantage of each
person's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have everyone trying to do everything. We need
to apply on the game floor what we do well in practice and to
adjust as a team. We need some games under our belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tomjanovich seemed to feel the problem could be greater
than getting acquainted. With practices offering few signs of the
game-time troubles, solutions might have to come in the remaining
preseason games and in the early season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I'm worried,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I respect
the league. You don't get a bunch of new guys, put them together
and go out and win. I accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not ready to accept what he saw Thursday. But the
solution remains less clear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
