<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-HNS &LR;      10-22 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LAS VEGAS _ It was, Mike Tyson said, a slip of the tongue, not an
exercise to determine whether the chompers were in prime biting,
er, fighting shape.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But in a recent interview with the Los Angeles Times, the
two-time former world heavyweight boxing champion was quoted as
saying were he put in another circumstance similar to his second
fight with Evander Holyfield, he would ``bite again.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the new and improved Mike Tyson? The tamer, gentler soul
supposedly humbled by two prison stays in the last six years and
the 18-month suspension of his boxing license?
</P>
<P>
   In a session with the media Wednesday during the final news
conference before Tyson faces Orlin Norris (50-5, 27 knockouts) at
the MGM Grand Hotel-Casino's Grand Garden Arena on Saturday night,
the ex-champ/ex-con said he should have commented differently to
the LA Times.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Saturday's non-title fight with Norris starts to
mirror the Holyfield bout would he bite Norris, Tyson on Wednesday
said: ``No, I would never do that again. When I said that, I was
just blowing off hot air. I would never bite anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from his demeanor at Wednesday's news conference, there
has been a change in Tyson. Oh, there were moments when, seated at
the table with the other fighters on the card and their handlers,
Tyson seemed bored and detached. But he was far less testy, much
more comfortable with the media than has been the case at any point
in his career.
</P>
<P>
   He is, according to his manager of two years, Shelly Finkel,
more at ease on those rare occasions he mingles with the public.
But unfortunately, Tyson, 33, might never shed the image of that
night in July 1997 at the Grand Garden Arena when he bit
Holyfield's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Tyson was taking a beating like none he had received in a
boxing ring, save perhaps for his upset loss to James ``Buster''
Douglas in Tokyo seven years before.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked by the Times, ``When you look back on the second
Holyfield fight, is it hard for you to believe you acted the way
you did and resorted to ear-biting?''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said, ``I would do it again under those circumstances.
Mills Lane (the referee) wasn't protecting me (from Holyfield
head-butts). He didn't handle the situation appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of biting Holyfield, Tyson was fined heavily. His
license was put in the deep freeze by the Nevada Athletic
Commission. He got it back in 1998 after protracted commission
hearings during which the contrite Tyson said he never would bite
again, that he was no threat to himself or the sport of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   As his comeback opponent, Tyson chose former International
Boxing Federation heavyweight champ Francois Botha. For four rounds
Jan. 16, 1998, Botha had gotten the best of the once-acclaimed
``baddest man on the planet.'' Then, he became too bold. It opened
the door for Tyson to stave off embarrassment by knocking out Botha
in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Though he lived up to the no-bite promise, the rusty Tyson
couldn't avoid controversy. At one point, when he had little or no
offense and his defense was porous, Tyson locked arms with the
South African and gave them a hard twist.
</P>
<P>
   During the postfight news conference, Tyson admitted he was
``trying to break it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Tyson was back behind bars. A fender-bender in
Maryland during the summer of '97, after which he punched and
kicked two of the drivers involved, netted him a three-month stay
in jail.
</P>
<P>
   It started badly. Reportedly angered by a guard, Tyson responded
by throwing a television set at him. But for the rest of his
incarceration, Tyson was a model prisoner, earning time off from
the original six-month sentence for good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tyson (46-3, 40 knockouts) is back and ready to fight.
Though his weight ballooned to over 280 pounds when he was released
from jail, Tyson is down to 220. Using Phoenix as a training base
most of the last three months, Tyson has honed his skills to a
level close to what he achieved as heavyweight champion, Finkel
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Tyson says all the controversial comments _ about biting
again; about his intent in twisting the arm of Botha _ shouldn't be
taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fight talk, that's all,'' he said. ``Get the people
interested. Make them want to see you do what you do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever watched wrestling on TV? When you hear `Stone
Cold' Steve Austin say he's going to give the other guy a
neck-breaker and do this and do that to him, doesn't it make you
want to go out and see the next match or buy the pay-per-view?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they get me with that; I want to go see it. This is the
same thing. It's just talk, nothing else. You just have to
understand the business. We need to get people out to watch us.
That's how we make our living.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkel, hired as Tyson's adviser around the time the former
champ fired Don King as his promoter and filed a $100 million
lawsuit against him, is amazed at the physical and psychological
changes Tyson has undergone in the past 48 months. The Tyson with
whom he now works, Finkel said, is indeed a kinder, gentler soul,
regardless of the occasional slip of the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully it will continue, because it's wonderful,'' Finkel
said. ``He's doing in and out of the ring what he has to do now.
Look, he's going to say some things because he talks what he
believes or thinks at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always going to be, `Hey, let me think this thing
through before I answer.' So a lot of times he's going to say some
things that later he's sorry he's said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's told me, `Shel, I don't ever want to be in that
situation (the second Holyfield bout) again, I don't want to be in
prison again. I have some lawsuits I've got to clean up. (But) I
don't want to see court again, I don't ever want to see jail
again.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
