<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS &LR;      10-22 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LINCOLN, Neb. _ It was like the final bellow from a train
conductor.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All aboard!''
</P>
<P>
   In two words, the conductor lets everyone know this is the last
chance: Come on if you're coming; stay if you're not.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska's team captains _ cornerback Ralph Brown, rover Mike
Brown, tight end T.J. DeBates and offensive lineman Adam Julch _
called a team meeting and did the same a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   When starting I-back D'Angelo Evans quit the team in September
because he was unhappy with his playing time, the Cornhuskers'
leaders felt they needed to know definitively who wanted to be part
of this year's team.
</P>
<P>
   Evans was not pleased. But the Cornhuskers were 2-0 and had
outscored their opponents 87-7 at the time. When Evans asked to be
reinstated, coach Frank Solich sought input from the team and
eventually told Evans he was not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Though the decision to deny Evans' return was made by Solich,
the players believed there was no room on the train for anyone who
put his well-being before the team's. That was what was said at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   All aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The captains basically just said, `Hey, people that want to be
here, stay. But after all this stuff, we're not going to deal with
it anymore. If you don't want to be here, you can leave now, and no
one is going to say anything,''' junior I-back Dan Alexander said.
``We just advised every player, `If you are going to be here, then
you're going to be a team player. If not, we don't want you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to realize that the program is bigger than any
individual. If any individual is going to bring the program down,
then either that individual has to change or leave. If everybody
understands that, it really helps us get over any petty differences
or petty troubles that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize this program's going to survive, with or without
us,'' Alexander said. ``We can either add to it or subtract from
it. The goal of everybody that came here was a national
championship, and we all wanted to be a part of a high-caliber
program, so we're all looking to make things better.''
</P>
<P>
   No one accepted the offer to leave. And now, to a man, the
Cornhuskers point to that meeting as the turning point in what they
hope will be a championship season.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said a ``team-first'' attitude is not an option at
Nebraska; it is a requirement. It is also part of the reason for
the Cornhuskers' success.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska, which is ranked No. 3, takes a 6-0 record to Austin to
face Texas this week. Not many thought the team would handle its
early troubles so well.
</P>
<P>
   They should have known better.
</P>
<P>
   Many times in the past, Nebraska continued to win after dealing
with off-the-field incidents, most notably running back Lawrence
Phillips' six-game sabbatical for assaulting his former girlfriend
during the national championship season of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But this season's distractions _ which included running back
Correll Buckhalter leaving the team for a few days because he also
objected to a lack of playing time, and quarterback Eric Crouch
coming close to doing the same after he was not awarded the
starting job _ were different.
</P>
<P>
   They were different because they came under the watch of Solich,
the second-year coach, whose watch already had gotten off to a
sluggish start. The Cornhuskers lost four games last year, their
first four-loss season since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (distractions) happen every year, but I think this year
it was magnified a lot because of the positions and players
involved who wanted to leave,'' Ralph Brown said. ``It was kind of
tough. But we pulled together for coach Solich because he was going
through a lot and we pulled together as a team to get back focused
on our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   How Solich handled the situation said a lot about his leadership
ability. He made the difficult choice of denying the talented
Evans, ending an injury-plagued career. On the same day, he moved
quarterback Bobby Newcombe to wingback and inserted Crouch as the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else he did, he was able to get his team refocused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we went through a point in time there early in the
season where our squad was disrupted, but I thought they worked
through that very well, and right now our chemistry is good,''
Solich said. ``As you go through each year, and as you go through
each week of practice, there are a number of things that jump up at
you and start to slow you down if you're not very careful. I think
this football team has been very good at not letting things get in
their way. I appreciate how they as a team have handled the things
that they have gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   With the distractions behind them, the Cornhuskers seem to have
put it in cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   The week Evans left, Nebraska struggled to beat Southern
Mississippi 20-13. Since then, the Cornhuskers have rolled over
Missouri (40-10), Oklahoma State (38-14) and Iowa State (49-14).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough this year, but everyone just understood their
role and did it,'' Brown said. ``I think in the beginning of the
season a couple of players didn't understand their role. Now
everybody does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that it would pull us together because we have great
character on this team. That's why we're in the position we're in
now _ character. People just want to go out and do it for the team,
not for themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
