<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD     10-22 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 100 KILLED IN DEVASTATING GROZNY MISSILE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede graf to replace the word `bombs' with `explosions') (lh) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ At least 10 explosions devastated a downtown market and
maternity hospital in Grozny, Chechnya, on Thursday evening,
according to reports from the breakaway Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions killed scores of people and injured hundreds
more. Chechen officials told The Associated Press that at least 118
people died and upward of 400 were injured, though the reports
could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters on the scene told of body parts strewn across market
stalls and corpses stacked in the city's darkened main hospital
after the attacks, which occurred about 6:15 p.m. Thursday, local
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge number of people were killed,'' said Alkha Tosuyev, a
cameraman for the Reuters news agency, describing the scene at the
market. ``Some who were sitting in a cafe, some who were selling
things at booths, some just walking by. Teen-agers. Children. It
was a horror. Counting the wounded was nightmarish.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosuyev said he had counted 60 dead at the market alone.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen officials said the explosions came from ground-to-ground
missiles fired by Russian forces that now are barely more than
eight miles from downtown Grozny. The Associated Press quoted
witnesses as saying Russian warplanes, which were buzzing the city
Thursday night, had bombed the central market.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Russian Defense Ministry flatly denied any
role in the attacks, many of which clustered around the residence
of Chechnya's president, Aslan Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   Other senior officials, including Prime Minister Vladimir Putin,
pointedly left open the prospect that troops would invade Grozny.
Putin, in Helsinki, Finland, for a meeting with leaders of the
European Union, said that military moves would ``depend on the
concrete situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Itar-Tass news agency quoted a senior Russian official as
saying troops planned to consolidate their positions around Grozny.
And the deputy defense minister, Gen. Vladimir Toporov, said
Russian soldiers or civil authorities would enter Grozny ``sooner
or later.''
</P>
<P>
   That would set up a confrontation with Chechen armed forces and
rebel guerrillas that the Russian authorities have repeatedly said
they want to avoid. The last time Russian troops tried to crush an
internal revolt in Chechnya, in a two-year war that ended in 1996,
some 80,000 people died, and Grozny was all but leveled by Russian
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin ended that stalemated war by granting
the Chechens an unspoken form of independence and postponing any
official decision on the state of the republic until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But after Islamic fundamentalists left Chechnya and invaded
neighboring Dagestan this summer and a series of terrorist bombs in
Moscow and elsewhere killed nearly 300 Russians, Russian troops
struck back hard, marching into Chechnya last month.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Kremlin's assurances that troops were only seeking
to build a security zone around Chechnya, Russian forces have
steadily advanced toward the capital. At last count, nearly 90,000
Russian soldiers were involved in the operation, far more than were
involved in the 21-month Chechen war of three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have played down the conflict, shunning terms
like ``rebellion'' in favor of labeling their military action as an
antiterrorist operation.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, many Chechens are said to oppose the uprising, and the
Russian government has seized on that possibility. A statement
issued Thursday assured Chechen citizens that its soldiers were
defending them against bandits and that they ``should know that
they will receive protection and help from the Russian
government.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday evening's attacks, which went largely unmentioned
on Moscow's main television news programs, seemed to be
distinguished by their grisly nature.
</P>
<P>
   By various reports, five or six rockets or aerial bombs were
said to have struck the central market at rush hour, sending
hundreds of screaming shoppers into the streets and leaving behind
scores of dead and pools of blood.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Umar Madayev, told The Associated Press: ``It was
dark and then all of a sudden the place was illuminated and
something was sparkling in the air. Then we heard the explosions.''
</P>
<P>
   Agence France-Presse reported that at least 27 people, many of
them mothers and newborn children, died when a rocket or bomb
struck a maternity hospital wing some 80 feet from the presidential
residence on Grozny's central square.
</P>
<P>
   Other rockets or bombs were said to have hit a mosque, killing
perhaps a dozen people, but that report too was unverified.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening's attacks seemed destined to raise a din of
protest among members of the European Union, who already had
elevated the situation in Chechnya to a major topic at their
Helsinki meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A number of nations have expressed concern at the unsparing
nature of the Russian military thrust, which has killed countless
civilians, spurred an exodus of two-thirds of Grozny's 150,000
residents and forced 150,000 refugees across the Chechen border
into Ingushettia, according to the Red Cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
