A4860 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LB     10-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NESBY'S GAME HAS SOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As he approaches the second furlong of his NBA
career, Tyrone Nesby is positioning his agenda in the following
order:
</P>
<P>
   Win, place and shoe.
</P>
<P>
   The lead priority winning is automatic; nothing is fun about
9-41.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby's notion of place also seems to be established. After
somehow slipping through the 1998 NBA Draft unselected, he took a
spin through the CBA, went post-lockout camping with the Clips and
eventually took the starting small forward job away from slumping
Lamond Murray. When that 9-41 season was over, league stat geeks
had Nesby ranked among the top 10 rookies in nine of 10 statistical
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool playing with these guys,'' Nesby said of life in the
NBA at large. ``First, you're watchin' 'em on TV; then you're out
there checkin' 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Then you cash in.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby's metamorphosis was rewarded with a three-year, $8.9
million contract, which is how much the Clippers are coughing up to
match the offer sheet he signed with the NBA champion San Antonio
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   But Nesby, a 6-foot-6 contradiction to the laws of gravity,
continues to wait for shoe time.
</P>
<P>
   While outplaying Scottie Pippen in one game last season, Nesby
found time to request a test drive of Pippen's signature Nikes.
After Shaquille O'Neal clobbered the fearless newcomer on an
attempted dunk, the Laker center's belated apology was interrupted
by another Nesby pitch for shoes.
</P>
<P>
   During the dog days of summer free agency, Nesby was offered a
shoe deal with a caveat from a company called And 1. And 1 would
bring Nesby into the fold if he played for any team BUT the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was out of Nesby's hands. The Clippers had the
right to match, said they would match, did match.
</P>
<P>
   So no And 1 deal for Nesby. No chance to replace Sean Elliott as
the starting forward for the defending champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think about that,'' Nesby said of the occasional daydream
that features him playing alongside Tim Duncan and David Robinson.
``I won't lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I love it here; I think we're going to be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Nesby waits for the shoe contract to drop (Converse
possibly, Nike more likely), rookie Lamar Odom has rolled in to
claim the starting small forward spot. Nesby, who spent most of the
off-season chipping away the rough edges on his perimeter game,
doesn't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can live with it,'' he said of what has become his sixth-man
role. ``It's just about knowing you're going to get out there.
Finishing the game is more important than starting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chris Ford can live with that attitude, as long was Nesby
picks up the defensive pace and rebounds with more conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixth man is an ideal role for him,'' Ford said. ``Nez is
always going to be an offensive weapon for us. But with his
athletic ability, he has to be more of a presence on defense and on
the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he knows that; I get on him all the time about it. He asks
why I always single him out, and I tell him he's the guy I always
see out of position on defense when I look at the films.''
</P>
<P>
   If Nesby realizes the shoe fits, he figures to make the
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Fast breaks
</P>
<P>
   Brian Skinner (upset tummy) and Maurice Taylor
</P>
<P>
   (sore shoulder) didn't participate in Wednesday night's public
scrimmage, but practiced without restrictions Thursday and will
play against the Grizzlies tonight (7 p.m., KXTA AM/1150) in
Vancouver. ... Point guard Eric Murdock
</P>
<P>
   whose injured left ankle passed Wednesday's test will make his
Clipper debut tonight. ... Taylor has provided the official
nickname for 34-year-old point guard Scott Brooks
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Faithful.'' ... In response to a recent newspaper report
that indicated they will get nothing, a team official said the
Clippers will receive ``seven figures'' this season as their share
of the Staples Center luxury-suite revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     10-22 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S VANNEY IS MENTALLY TOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- By the end of last season, Greg Vanney had finished
his path to bench and felt like his spirit was shaken.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's left-back was a regular starter since establishing
himself as a rookie in 1996, and he had trouble understanding why
he was losing his starting job to Joey Franchino a few weeks before
the 1998 MLS playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never explained to me,'' said Vanney.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of storming into then-coach Octavio Zambrano's
office to voice his frustrations, Vanney chose to hold his emotions
in check.
</P>
<P>
   When he did get a rare nod over Franchino, Vanney didn't seem to
have the same spirit that he had become known for during the team's
inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   During the playoffs, Vanney sat helplessly on the bench while
the Chicago Fire eliminated the Galaxy from the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Vanney's playoff contribution? Only two minutes -- this from a
guy who piled up 694 playoff minutes during the league's first two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a year and a coaching change ago.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find a mentally tougher Galaxy player than Vanney
today as the Galaxy prepares for Sunday's playoff match at
Colorado. The Galaxy leads the first-round, best-of-three series
1-0 following Sunday's 3-0 victory over the Rapids at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Vanney returned to his starting role for new coach
Sigi Schmid, he also earned an invitation to join the U.S. National
team for a recent friendly in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should never lose confidence in yourself, which is
something that started to happen to me last year,'' said Vanney.
``Your mind has to be focused and completely in the game. There
were times when I was wondering why I was not playing. I was
frustrated and started looking over my shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't play that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The change is the result of a lot of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had seen Vanney in the off-season, then you would know
why Vanney is where he's at right now,'' said defensive midfielder
Danny Pena. ``He came into camp at the beginning of the season and
was by far the fittest player on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanney and some other Galaxy players joined fitness coach Jim
Liston for winter workouts. While others trained Monday through
Thursday, Vanney added Friday and Saturday workouts on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg made a decision to go beyond what was asked of him,''
said Liston. ``There was no way he was going to come into this
season and give anyone an opportunity to take his position. Now
he's reaping the rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanney said the motivation was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate when somebody tells me I can't do something or that I'm
not good enough to start on this team,'' said Vanney. ``You can do
one of two things when that happens: You can quit or prove someone
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `I'm going to prove Octavio was wrong.' That
was my approach every day at the gym. It was grueling and tough but
when you have focus and you set goals, it really gets you through
the hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid coached Vanney at UCLA. He said he noticed Vanney's
physical improvement in March, when Schmid took over for Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed right away,'' said Schmid. ``He's improved himself
and adapted better because of his physical strength. ``He's been
able to handle a marking role and get matched up with physical
players like (Jorge Dely) Valdes and (Eduardo) Hurtado. A year ago
he wasn't ready for those matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything Greg has done has allowed him to play with
a lot more confidence and resolve. And he has more bite in his
tackles. Greg is not usually a demonstrative player, but you can
see that quiet fire that burns inside him.''
</P>
<P>
   His effort has sure caught the attention of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Vanney) had one mission in mind, to gain his position back
and to gain the respect back from players whom maybe Greg feels
lost confidence in him,'' said Pena. ``That's how you're supposed
to respond. Any time you hit a bump in the road you have to bounce
back and Vanney showed that type of character.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one thing he has that a lot of players don't is that
professional attitude. Anything we do, Vanney is right there at the
front of the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow defender Paul Caligiuri says this is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see a young player mature like he did was great,'' said
Caligiuri. ``Greg is one of the best defenders in this league and
we still haven't seen the best of him yet. He will not only get
more caps on the National team, but he's going to become a regular
starter someday and he won't lose that role until he's ready to
give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The new and improved Vanney doesn't plan on letting up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already talked with Robin (Fraser) about setting a
workout schedule again,'' said Vanney. ``I've learned a lot from my
experience and I'm not going to get caught questioning myself
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
