<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-RAIL-STUDY-Kansas-KAN     10-22 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-STUDY-Kansas-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHT RAIL IS HOT TREND, BUT STUDIES CAST DOUBT ON ITS WORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Light rail transit is
the latest game of municipal follow-the-leader.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the recent rages to expand convention centers and build new
state-of-the-art sports stadiums, city after city across the
country either has built a streetcar-like light rail line on urban
streets or wants to build one.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to rail, contends John Kain, a Harvard University
economics professor, is attributable to ``boosterism, appeals to
civic pride...and a fondness of politicians for building
monuments.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because when light rail is analyzed in terms of costs and
benefits, its performance fails, according to transportation
economists who have studied the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Study after study in the last few years has concluded that light
rail does not improve transit usage noticeably, does not reduce
traffic congestion and, in effect, requires a taxpayers' subsidy
equal to buying every rider a new Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``While light rail may bolster civic psyche, its popularity has
nothing to do with genuine transportation objectives,'' wrote
Wendell Cox, a transportation consultant, in a national report last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Or as a California grand jury, investigating Orange County's
decision-making process on light rail, determined earlier this
year: ``The national experience with urban light rail systems'
ability to solve traffic congestion, air pollution and related
urban problems has been poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, transit advocates see the issue differently. They
contend light rail does increase transit ridership. But even they
have trouble citing one evaluation of rail systems nationally that
demonstrated those systems had met their cost and transportation
goals.
</P>
<P>
   So transit advocates play up the game of municipal
follow-the-leader.
</P>
<P>
   William Millar, president of the American Public Transit
Association, described light rail this way: ``That is what the
successful communities are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is engaged in the same debate.
</P>
<P>
   Question 5 on the Nov. 2 ballot proposes to extend two half-cent
sales taxes. One half-cent would fix roads and bridges and the
other would build a light rail line that its sponsor, Clay
Chastain, envisions running between south Kansas City and Kansas
City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign flier for Question 5 asks in big letters, ``Who is
Missing from these light rail cities?'' It then lists 21 major
cities _ but not Kansas City. The flier goes on to catalog light
rail's benefits: ``reduce traffic congestion'' and ``boost
community pride,'' among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The flier does not mention how much the roughly 25- to 40-mile
system would cost or how many people would ride it instead of
driving. Chastain, however, has estimated costs at $900 million to
$1.5 billion, depending on how long the line is.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain argues that light rail will be successful in combating
traffic congestion and urban sprawl. If it isn't working elsewhere,
he asked, ``why are 190 cities vying for light rail funding? There
are more vying for it than there are available funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is no doubt light rail is popular. In the last two
decades, it has been built in cities from Baltimore to San Diego,
Buffalo to Dallas. Also, the federal government's transportation
plan, called TEA-21, has a long waiting list of places wanting rail
funding.
</P>
<P>
   But when cities have asked their residents for tax money for
those projects or expansions, they're often turned down. This
decade, only five of 25 rail referendums passed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, cities typically crow about the systems they have. St.
Louis leaders boast how ridership has exceeded projections. Dallas'
supporters point to private development popping up near rail stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the cities happy with it?'' asked Ron Fisher, who oversees
rail planning for the Federal Transit Administration. ``Frequently,
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, studies on light rail's performance find it
falling short. Researchers' judgments go beyond the usual beefs
that rail construction costs more and carries fewer riders than
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Other arguments can be boiled down to basically two issues:
traffic congestion and cost effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   With traffic congestion, rail proponents frequently point out
that a single rail line can carry the same number of people as six
lanes of highway. Yet transportation consultant Cox studied traffic
in 10 cities with new rail systems and found congestion had
worsened more in those cities than in those without new rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually everywhere these things are proposed, proponents
talk about traffic congestion, even though there's not a single
study anywhere in the country that shows a perceivable reduction in
traffic congestion as a result of light rail,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   As for cost effectiveness, light rail costs hundreds of millions
of dollars to build and only accounted for 0.3 percent of new
passenger travel during the first half of this decade, according to
John Semmens, who criticized transit in a 1997 report for the
nonpartisan Goldwater Institute in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The overall cost of new light rail lines translates to roughly
$8,000 per new commuter _ which is more than the annual payment on
a five-year loan for a Ford Explorer or the lease of a Lincoln Town
Car, according to calculations by transportation economists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the actual impact it has on the region,''
Semmens said, ``it's pitifully small. You're kidding yourself if
you think that's the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   When the FTA's Fisher was asked how light rail was performing,
even he didn't sound too upbeat: ``It's hard to say one way or
another on that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, whether or not light rail performs as planned, it
still is one of the hottest big-ticket items that cities are
chasing today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happening in too many places to be a fluke,'' said the
transit association's Millar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
