<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' FORUM ERA TO END WITH EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A proud arena whose walls are lined with six
championship banners and the retired jerseys of five Hall of Famers
will witness its last NBA tipoff tonight, in the least fitting
farewell imaginable. An exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Western Forum, bearing the name of a bank that no
longer exists, will soon bear only the memories of its most famous
tenant. The Lakers play a meaningless game tonight at 8 and close
out a 32-year relationship with the formerly Fabulous arena.
</P>
<P>
   The oddity of the moment will not be lost on Lakers coach Phil
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unique for us to be able to play on this floor and to be
in these type of games, where the Forum is being closed in such a
strange way, an exhibition after so many championships have been
played here,'' Jackson said Thursday, before the Lakers' 93-89
overtime victory over Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Championship series hold the fondest memories for Jackson, who
played in three as a New York Knick and coached in one, leading the
Chicago Bulls to the first of six titles in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I feel like this has been a building that I've had a lot of
fun in, had a lot of success in,'' he said. ``Three of those four
championship attempts were successful, the teams I was on. Not with
the Lakers. . . . So there's some real fond memories here and
there's been wonderful basketball here.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of it belonging to the home team, including the four
championships won in the 1980s. A.C. Green, a member of the last
two of those teams, is elated to be back to pay his final respects
to the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously been a lot of fun. A lot of great memories,''
he said. ``It's just a blessing, it really is, no matter how you
want to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green might miss the familiar digs, but he's looking forward to
playing at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is full of changes,'' he said. ``I'm just happy to be
able to proceed along with the franchise. Change of the century,
there's a lot of ways to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   To close out the Forum, the Lakers will air a video montage at
the end of tonight's game. The team will give away a CD called
``Fabulous Finale'' to the first 10,000 fans and will also give
away a number of commemorative videos, produced by the History
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's tipoff against the Phoenix Suns has been moved to
7:45.
</P>
<P>
   Dribbles: Shaquille O'Neal missed his first 10 free-throw
attempts Thursday but, in dramatic fashion, swished his 11th try to
forge an 85-85 tie with the Warriors with 1.6 seconds remaining and
send the game into overtime. O'Neal finished with a game-high 21
points, including four points in overtime, and made the game-saving
defensive rebound to lock up the win.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is now 2 for 19 from the line in the last two games and 9
for 33 (.273) in the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made one alteration to the starting lineup Thursday,
giving Robert Horry the nod at power forward over A.C. Green.
Horry, who has struggled this exhibition season, played 17 minutes,
netting six points and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Devean George continued to impress, with 13 points, four
rebounds and two assists. He played 21 minutes, including the
entire overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering Wilt: The Lakers honored the late Wilt Chamberlain
with a moment of silence and a short video tribute before tipoff.
The team also plans to wear a commemorative patch on its uniforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
