<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-GUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA LAWMAKER URGES ARMING TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Rep. Barbara Blewster has a novel solution to school
violence: Let every teacher carry a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican legislator said Thursday that if teachers and
school administrators could carry concealed weapons to work, it
would keep violence out of Arizona schools.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and school officials immediately derided the idea. The
president of one of the the largest school boards in Blewster's
district called her a ``fruitcake.''
</P>
<P>
   But gun rights advocates say the idea should be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Froman, second vice president of the National Rifle
Association, pointed out that in countries where teachers are
armed, such as Israel, school shootings are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Froman said the NRA has not taken a position on allowing
teachers to carry guns at schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult issue, and it involves a lot of
uncomfortable questions. Would it save lives or put more lives in
danger?'' Froman said. ``If you're a deranged person and you want
to do some damage, are you going to a police station, where
everybody is armed, or to a school?''
</P>
<P>
   Blewster said the situation can't get any more dangerous than it
is now, when a shooter can walk into a school and open fire. That
would be less likely if those inside were armed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she said, ``An armed society is a polite society. I
think you would have a lot better manners from the students toward
the teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dewey Republican made a name for herself in her first year
at the Capitol by comparing homosexuality to ``bestiality, human
sacrifice and cannibalism.'' She told another colleague that she
didn't look Jewish because she didn't have a ``hooked nose.''
</P>
<P>
   She later suggested to an African-American colleague, Rep. Leah
Landrum, that slavery wasn't that bad and that Native Americans
weren't very smart.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Maddux, president of the Prescott Unified School Board,
said he wasn't surprised by Blewster's latest proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds just like her. What a fruitcake. She's a clown.
Arizona politics is interesting enough without her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said her suggestion is in direct opposition to the current
no-tolerance policy toward weapons in schools.
</P>
<P>
   State schools Superintendent Lisa Graham Keegan said arming
teachers is a bad idea, and state Sen. Chris Cummiskey called it
``outlandish.''
</P>
<P>
   The two attended a meeting of the Safety Answers for Education
Committee in Prescott on Wednesday. Blewster also attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the craziest thing I've ever heard,'' said Cummiskey,
D-central Phoenix. ``The things we keep hearing is not to create a
Fort Apache situation on these campuses but to try and get the guns
out of the schools.'' &QL; 
Chris Moeser can be reached at (602) 444-8069 or at
chris.moeser(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
