<HEADER>
A4876 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-NELSON-CHILDKILLING-K     10-22 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELSON-CHILD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PROSECUTORS VOW TO SEEK DEATH PENALTY IN CHILD'S MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
 KILLING-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and ANNE LAMOY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Federal prosecutors
vowed Thursday to seek the death penalty against Keith D. Nelson
for the kidnapping, sexual abuse and killing of 10-year-old Pamela
Butler last week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr. said he already has asked U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno for permission to seek the death
penalty. Reno has granted such permission in four previous cases in
western Missouri during Hill's tenure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make the best case possible for the death penalty,''
Hill told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's announcement Thursday capped a concentrated flurry of
legal action on Nelson's case.
</P>
<P>
   Just after noon, a federal grand jury returned an indictment
against Nelson, restating a kidnapping count and charging him with
taking Pamela across a state line to commit sexual abuse that
resulted in her death. Both counts could carry the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the allegation of sexual abuse, the two-page
indictment contained little new information about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Should Nelson not be sentenced to death in federal court, Hill
said he would work with Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird for a
murder prosecution in state court.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's attorney, Daniel Franco, was not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize there is a specific purpose for the way he's
charged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela's mother, Cherri West, was pleased with the prosecutors'
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this man to be dead,'' she said. ``I will seek the
death penalty all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege Nelson kidnapped Pamela on Oct. 12 while she
was skating near her family's Kansas City, Kan., home, drove her
into Jackson County and killed her there.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 14, authorities arrested Nelson near the Kansas River
and took him to a hospital for medical treatment for an injured
leg. The following day, searchers recovered Pamela's body near a
Grain Valley, Mo., church.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on her front porch Thursday, Pamela's mother carefully
read the indictments during a temporary lull in the stream of
visitors who have left hundreds of cards and flowers at the little
house in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   West looked for clues to her daughter's murder. But nothing in
the indictment indicated motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want to know why he did this to her,'' West said.
``Why did he pick her?''
</P>
<P>
   After the indictment was returned, several members of the grand
jury waited an hour at the courthouse to attend Nelson's first
court appearance in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   A deputy U.S. marshal pushed Nelson in a wheelchair into the
packed courtroom. Nelson, 24, was dressed in orange prison scrubs.
Nelson closely watched U.S. Magistrate Judge Sarah Hays as she read
the indictment to him, glancing down occasionally to check a copy
on the table in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson did not enter a plea and was not asked for one.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Nelson's family watched from the second row of
benches and said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Hays announced she would appoint a lawyer from the federal
public defender's office to join Franco in Nelson's defense. Hays
also denied bond for Nelson, leaving him in federal custody.
</P>
<P>
   Franco said, ``From my point of view, things went as expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Nelson's family declined to comment. Members of
Pamela's family did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   At Hill's press conference, prosecutors and investigators said
that with the new indictment, they would have much less to say
publicly about evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has generated an intense amount of public attention,
but from this point on, the kind of information we can provide to
you will be very, very limited,'' Hill said. ``Our primary concern
is to bring justice in this case. The proper forum for our evidence
is in a courtroom upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials hinted at some lingering questions.
</P>
<P>
   While they did not rule out the possibility of charges against
others who may have been involved in Pamela's kidnapping, they
expressed no urgency about warning the public of any accomplices
still at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not say there is a public safety issue,'' said FBI
Special Agent Larry McCormick, who also asked the public to
continue feeding the bureau tips on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Other authorities have said that since his capture, Nelson has
not made a statement or cooperated with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said the FBI is still awaiting the results of some
laboratory tests. In an affidavit submitted last week, an FBI agent
said that tests for blood in a white Ford pickup Nelson allegedly
drove were inconclusive and needed more refined testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence has been submitted to Washington,'' McCormick
said. ``We have no results as of this date.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
