<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4877 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KCSCHOOLS-ACCREDITATI     10-22 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SCHOOL DISTRICT STRIPPED OF CERTIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
 SCHOOLS-ACCREDITATION-2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR, KEVIN HOFFMAN and LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri Board
of Education voted unanimously Thursday to strip the Kansas City
School District of accreditation despite pleas to delay the action
for the sake of students.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board agreed to postpone the decision's effective date until
May 1, a move state officials said was aimed at eliminating
concerns that students would flee the district in the middle of the
school year.
</P>
<P>
   But state board members said they could no longer accept the
district's dismal performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very difficult vote for all of us,'' said state
board member Rice Burns Jr. of Sikeston. ``To a person, all of us
are thinking about your kids, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The district has until June 30, 2002, to raise test scores or
meet other requirements, such as improving attendance and
graduation rates, to regain accreditation. If that doesn't happen,
then state officials take over the district, split it into smaller
districts or divide up its students and send them to other
districts.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr. said he
wouldn't be diverted from his goal of raising the academic
achievement of all district students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of work to do,'' Demps said. ``I've got a tough
job ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Demps said the district would pursue its legal options. The
district tried unsuccessfully in both state and federal court to
bar the state from taking action Thursday. U.S. District Judge Dean
Whipple set a hearing for Tuesday on a district request to keep the
action from taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   Should that effort fail, some Kansas City school board members
say the district could be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still makes it a complete disaster for the district,'' said
board member Lance Loewenstein. ``(They) may think the children
won't leave the district, but they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Joy West-Spearman said her stomach turned when she got a phone
call Thursday from her daughter, a junior at Lincoln College Prep,
informing her of the decision. West-Spearman thinks that it will
hurt her daughter's chance to attend a private college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that (graduation) certificate is going to
be worthless,'' she said, citing a concern raised by many parents.
</P>
<P>
   However, several college officials have said that the state's
decision would not prevent Kansas City students from getting into
college.
</P>
<P>
   West-Spearman said her daughter was already looking at other
schools in case she decides to leave the district.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at many of the city's 15 charter schools said they had
received numerous calls from parents in the last week asking about
openings, particularly for high school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so upset,'' said Erik Harvey, on-site manager at
Southwest Charter School. ``The rumors of losing accreditation
started it all. It was the straw that broke the camel's back. It
was all over the papers and it made them think.''
</P>
<P>
   Even school board President John Rios said he would weigh
whether to remove his children from the district.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Clark, president of the Urban League of Greater Kansas
City, cautioned the community against panicking and urged support
for the district.
</P>
<P>
   The state board vote came after several officials voiced concern
about how the loss of accreditation would affect the district,
especially in view of recent progress under Demps.
</P>
<P>
   ``To withdraw accreditation for the acknowledged failures of
earlier administrations imposes hardships on the children while
undermining efforts of this administration, newly appointed and
focused on the very educational reforms we all recognize as
essential to improve student achievement,'' said Arthur A. Benson
II, attorney for the plaintiff schoolchildren in the Kansas City
desegregation lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mary Groves Bland, a Kansas City Democrat, told the
state board that community, political and religious leaders were
committed to seeing the district improve. Already, she said,
notices are being posted in schools, churches and other public
places encouraging parents to keep faith in the district. She urged
the board to delay its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Demps told the board he was hired in August solely to implement
a federal court order to improve academic achievement. He said the
uncertainties of being unaccredited could make it difficult to meet
court-ordered goals to enact a new core curriculum, improve teacher
training, introduce new tests designed to better gauge student
performance and develop a plan to hold students, teachers and
administrators accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Student performance is why I'm here,'' Demps said. ``That is
my passion. If we were to become unaccredited, things would happen
that would deter us from that cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Demps said being unaccredited would make the difficult task of
luring and keeping high quality employees even harder.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City teachers union President Judy Morgan said she had
already heard from teachers. She said the loss of accreditation
could cause some veteran teachers to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support subdividing or dissolving the district,''
Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   State Board of Education President Betty Preston of Chillicothe
called the lack of improvement in the five years since Kansas City
last underwent a state review inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't set the benchmark...we are imposing a hardship on
children who grow up and don't have the skills they need,'' Preston
said.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Russell Thompson of Columbia said troubled
districts always asked the board to consider the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet we don't see any change or difference,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Education Commissioner Robert Bartman agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time we've learned that good intentions don't move a
district forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bartman had recommended that both the Kansas City and St. Louis
districts lose their accreditation after their students posted
dismal scores on the latest state standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   The state board on Thursday tabled the decision on St. Louis in
accordance with a provision in the settlement of that city's
desegregation lawsuit. The provision defers any sanctions
associated with the loss of accreditation until June 2002. The St.
Louis district would retain accreditation in the interim, but also
must show progress or become unaccredited.
</P>
<P>
   Bartman told state board members that there was no state or
federal money set aside to help either district with its problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Bartman said Gov. Mel Carnahan told him recently that he
remained committed to helping the state's two largest public school
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how that will play out,'' Bartman said. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
