<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-CSUN-SHOWBIZ-LADN     10-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSUN-SHOWBIZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN CONFERENCE TARGETS SHOW BIZ ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, CALIF. -- Facing the challenge of establishing
itself as a Hollywood player 20 miles away from Tinseltown,
California State University, Northridge, will attempt to
``demystify'' the economics of show business Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The campus' 2-year-old Entertainment Industry Institute has
organized a daylong conference dubbed Adam Smith Goes to Hollywood,
with panels covering profit predictions, labor markets, the
regional economy and the arts. Participants include studio
executives, consultants and university professors.
</P>
<P>
   Lani Daniels, a former Hollywood executive who heads the
institute, said the event is part of CSUN's ongoing efforts to
improve its recognition among industry professionals. ``The
conference is targeting a high-profile audience rather than those
interested in breaking into the business,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our original marching orders were pretty clear _ create more
interdisciplinary courses and build bridges with the industry,''
Daniels said. ``I'm not aware of many events like this that bring
together people from the industry and academia, so we're going to
get a richer discussion as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping create classes in cinematography and
editing, the institute has sponsored the California SUN
International Animation Festival, a teleconference on the issue of
news vs. entertainment and an entertainment career conference. The
animation festival drew about 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Cody Cluff, president of the Entertainment Industry Development
Corp., will be today's keynote speaker and plans to stress the need
to acknowledge the unprecedented amount of change that the industry
faces due to the emergence of digital cameras and powerful desktop
computers for editing and animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are changes everywhere, from the basic
economic model all the way to the technology of production,'' Cluff
said Thursday in an interview. ``The fact that we're telling
stories will not change, but the tools we're using are changing and
the way we deliver them will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Cluff predicted major shifts will come soon in areas such as
high-definition TV production, satellite delivery of movies to
theaters and using computers for set and costume design. ``To
survive, people will need to match creative abilities with a solid
understanding of the business, so they need to be very cognizant of
both the latest and least expensive technology,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff said the blockbuster success of ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' which topped $140 million in domestic box office gross
after being shot for $35,000, underscored the profound shifts in
the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital video cameras have forever changed Hollywood,'' he
asserted. ``We're seeing filmmaking heading to an environment
that's very much like the recording industry, where people have the
equipment to make a completed product in their living rooms. We're
fast approaching the same level of sophistication in animated TV
and theatrical productions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project'' should also be a signal that the
world's film schools are turning out thousands of graduates who
know how to use low-cost filmmaking technology, according to Cluff.
``People in the business are going to have to educate themselves on
uses of technology or they'll no longer be able to compete. `Blair
Witch' will look like a sad prototype five years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cluff credited the leadership of Hollywood's major studios with
adjusting to the fast pace of technological shifts but warned that
location shooting _ the area of the business his agency monitors in
Los Angeles County _ is likely to see profound alterations soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The production and planning processes have not changed much in
50 years,'' he added. ``I don't mean that computers are going to
replace actors, but we may see less of going out to a specific
location to get a genuine look.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
