<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-CAMPUS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENDALE GETS DISNEY BALL ROLLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, CALIF. _ The city of Glendale took the first official
step Thursday toward creating a major new entertainment industry
campus for Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   The city's redevelopment agency issued a ``notice of
preparation'' to state officials that it had launched the
environmental review process for Disney's proposed Grand Central
Creative Campus. Redevelopment director Jeanne Armstrong said the
draft environmental impact report, prepared by Los Angeles-based
environmental consultants PCR, should be ready in March following
extensive information gathering and public meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The project would transform the dozens of tilt-up concrete
buildings in Grand Central industrial park into a high-tech hub
with four- to six-story buildings surrounded by green belts,
courtyards, walkways, tree-lined streets and planted medians. The
first new buildings would be ready for occupancy in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said local reaction to the project, unveiled by Disney
in early September, has been positive. ``I think Disney has been in
Glendale for so long that they are perceived as a very good
employer and a company that gives back to the community,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Imagineering, the research and development operation
that designs theme-park rides, has been headquartered in the
industrial park since 1961. Disney bought the property, which lies
within the city's 7-year-old San Fernando Road Redevelopment
Corridor, in 1997 and has about 3,000 employees there.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's plans include restoring the now-vacant Grand Central
Air Terminal, the first major airport in the Los Angeles area, and
converting it into office space. When completed, the entire project
will be anchored by Disney's Imagineering and new media divisions.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
