<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SCHOOL DISTRICT STRIPPED OF CERTIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
 SCHOOLS-ACCREDITATION-2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR, KEVIN HOFFMAN and LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ how that will play
out,'' Bartman said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In addition, Bartman said top administrators from the state
Department of Elementary and Secondary Education would be in Kansas
City and St. Louis Monday to begin assisting both districts in
meeting the state-ordered improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City officials were concerned that once the district
became unaccredited, its students could begin enrolling in
neighboring districts willing to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the surrounding districts prohibit out-of-district
students from enrolling. But Kansas City board members think
districts could change their policies in light of Thursday's
decision. The Kansas City district would have to pay tuition and
transportation costs for students who choose to go to different
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City school board members say those costs, when combined
with the loss of per-pupil state aid to charter schools and a
decrease in annual state funding, could doom the district to
financial failure.
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said loss of accreditation was the best tool the state
had to spur academic improvement in Kansas City and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's extremely important that the two major districts
in our state be successful,'' Bartman said. ``This is the wake-up
call to the communities to galvanize around the importance of
education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
