<SLUG> BC-LIGHT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST GIVES DETAILS OF HIS LIGHT RAIL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
 RAIL-PLAN-2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN HORSLEY and MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Transportation
activist Clay Chastain this week outlined his vision for light rail
in Kansas City, although he emphasized that the details should be
left to the professional planners.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I am not the emperor of light rail,'' Chastain said as he
discussed his initiative on the Nov. 2 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain's Question 5 asks voters to extend a 1-cent sales tax
for 15 years, with half the money going for basic infrastructure
improvements. The other half would build a light rail line from
south Kansas City to Kansas City International Airport that is
estimated to cost from $900 million to $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The city is backing a rival proposal, Question 1, which asks
voters to support an eight-year tax extension of the 1-cent tax.
All the money, estimated at more than $500 million, will go for
basic infrastructure such as bridges, roads, sewers and sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said that if his proposal passes, he envisions a
downtown corridor being dedicated to light rail trains traveling in
both directions down the middle, with one lane for emergency and
delivery vehicles on either side. That would reduce traffic
congestion and make the area more friendly to bicyclists and
pedestrians, Chastain said.
</P>
<P>
   At the cross streets, Chastain said, light rail would get
priority for green lights. He said the city could also have
mechanical crossing guards to ensure safety at major intersections.
</P>
<P>
   Where there is existing right of way, such as in the Brookside
area or along Waukomis Drive in the Northland, the light rail line
could be built there.
</P>
<P>
   To cross the Missouri River, Chastain proposed light rail use
the ASB bridge upper rail bed, between the Hannibal and Heart of
America bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said he envisioned trains going by about every 15
minutes, stopping every few blocks in congested areas, but
traveling 70 to 80 mph as they approach the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot initiative also calls for a new terminal connecting
the light rail line with the planned Johnson County Commuter Rail
line in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Pritchett, director of rail planning for the Kansas City
Area Transportation Authority, said the ATA's plans have always
assumed that large portions of a light rail line would operate on
city streets. But identifying those streets and gaining public
consensus on the details has been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   When the ATA several years ago proposed a line along Grand
Boulevard, business leaders feared construction disruptions. Parks
board representatives also balked at the use of a boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ideal, to have a street dedicated to light rail. But
the question is whether people would accept that,'' Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchett said another complication would be going over the
Missouri River. He pointed out that the ASB bridge's upper rail
does not extend all the way from one side of the river to the
other. It is also only one lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have to do a tremendous amount of retrofitting,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchett said the ATA also is concerned about whether Kansas
City realistically could expect to receive the $500 million to $1
billion in federal funding that would be needed to build the
35-mile line. Other officials think Kansas City should anticipate
only $300 million in federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also have questioned why Kansas Citians should pay for a
terminal that will benefit the Johnson County rail project.
Chastain, however, said that Kansas Citians must provide the
leadership and funding to get light rail going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be too cumbersome to try to get it funded with a bistate
tax,'' Chastain said. ``History will have passed us by by that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities have unique situations that require tailored approaches
to light rail. /{The Kansas City Star/} looked at a handful that
have embarked upon that path, or are just beginning. The cities
were chosen for geographical diversity as well as comparable size.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half the population of the state of Washington is
squeezed into an hourglass shape constricted by Puget Sound and
Lake Washington. Seattle's a beautiful place to live, but ``rush
hour'' can stretch to four or five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of light rail were sown in 1992, when the state created a
regional bus and rail district known as Sound Transit. But voters
in 1995 rejected a nearly $7 billion rail plan as too expensive. A
scaled-back $3.9 billion plan, based on a 0.4 percent sales tax and
a 0.3 percent motor vehicle license tax, passed the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The system also relies on a 20 percent federal contribution.
</P>
<P>
   A two-mile light rail line in Tacoma, Wash., is on a fast track
toward completion in 2001. Environmental impact studies are being
completed for a separate spine to link downtown Seattle and the
SeaTac airport. It is scheduled to be in service by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Light rail is to be augmented by 82 miles of commuter rail on
existing Burlington Northern railroad tracks linking Seattle and
Tacoma by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   The system will combine surface lines with tunnels and elevated
sections. Light-rail ridership is projected at 125,000 initially,
with about 40 percent of operating costs recovered in fares.
</P>
<P>
   Rail opponents who prefer buses have argued fixed lines cannot
buck the 20th-century trend toward more mobility and flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The situation became complicated in 1997, when Seattle voters
approved an initiative petition placed on the ballot by a former
cabdriver. It called for expanding the city's one-mile monorail
left over from the 1962 World's Fair into a 40-mile system cutting
an X-shape through the city. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 0223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4884 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-LIGHTRAIL-PLAN-2NDTAK     10-22 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST GIVES DETAILS OF HIS LIGHT RAIL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
 RAIL-PLAN-2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN HORSLEY and MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ cutting an X-shape
through the city.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the monorail has no funding and its likely routes would
overlap those of Sound Transit.
</P>
<P>
   City planners view Portland, Ore., as a progressive city in
containing urban sprawl, and the light-rail system plays a key part
in that policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Tri-Met transit authority built its first 15-mile line from
downtown to suburbs on the east. Last year, it opened an 18-mile
westward line to connect workers with high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ridership has been higher than expected, and large employers
such as Intel and Nike provide yearly rail passes to employees. On
the west side, home builders have planned communities around rail
stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen $2.4 billion in new development within walking
distance from the stations since the 1979 decision to build the
line,'' said G.B. Arrington, director of strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the rail system take the Libertarian view that it and
other restrictive-growth policies impose too much government
control.
</P>
<P>
   The existing lines depended largely on federal money but part of
the airport spur under construction is being paid for by a large
private employer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rail line is at street level within dedicated
roadway lanes. The newest trains are very quiet. Five persons have
been killed after being struck by the trains, but Tri-Met says in
most cases the victim was partially at fault.
</P>
<P>
   Fares range from $1.10 to $1.45, depending on distance, and
revenue from fares covers nearly half the light-rail operating
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Voters a year ago rejected a property tax increase to build a
22-mile north-south line. But Tri-Met and Portland are seeking to
pool local funds with a federal grant to proceed with a $350
million northern spur.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Denver hugs a mountainous wall, but the population
density is centered on land almost as flat as Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Voters approved a Regional Transportation District nearly 30
years ago. The integrated bus and rail system now encompasses 41
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Local funding from a 0.6 percent sales tax allowed Denver to
build its first light-rail line without federal help, but spurs to
the southwest and southeast will require nearly $1 billion from
Washington, leveraged by a local bond issue planned for Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Central Denver suffers a parking shortage, which officials think
has contributed to high ridership on light rail. About 15,000
riders a day were projected at this point, but the number is closer
to 17,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking 4,000to 5,000 cars from the central business
district every day,'' said district spokesman Scott Reed. ``Plus
we're eliminating nearly 500 bus trips that formerly came into
downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   About 37 percent of total bus and rail system operating costs
are covered by fares.
</P>
<P>
   The southwest extension to Littleton is to open in July and is
projected to carry 8,400 daily riders initially, but is expected to
grow to 22,000 by 2015, according to the district. The southeast
extension is projected to carry 30,000 riders a day.
</P>
<P>
   Many property owners, however, oppose rail routes down the
middle of interstate highways because they force the roadways to
encroach outward.
</P>
<P>
   The central light-rail line is at surface level, requiring
traffic to yield to trains. The extensions are planned with no
at-grade crossings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 3 years since two interconnecting light-rail lines went
into service in Dallas, initial ridership projections of 33,000
have been exceeded by about 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with an estimated $600 million in private-sector
investment near the station points, causes the Dallas Area Rapid
Transit system to think it is on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   Studies by the University of North Texas project that the
economic impact of the planned extensions will bring a 2-to-1
return on the public investment. Property values near the
light-rail stations have increased by as much as 25 percent,
according to one of the university studies.
</P>
<P>
   Bus and rail systems are integrated in Dallas, but officials
said that light rail has proven an effective tool in influencing
the direction of growth, as well as bolstering redevelopment
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   High-rent lofts are being snatched up in the city center. To the
northeast, the suburb of Richardson, already home to many high-tech
companies, is anticipating an expansion station by planning for new
residential, office, hotel and performing arts developments.
</P>
<P>
   But some suburban merchants oppose street-level rail, saying it
will disrupt traffic and business.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas rail system incorporates at-grade crossings, tunnels
and elevated sections.
</P>
<P>
   The network was built with a 1-cent transportation sales tax in
each member city. The two rail extensions will cost about $1
billion. But earlier this month, Dallas Area Rapid Transit became
the first transit authority to sign an agreement for a full
light-rail grant of $333 million under the new federal
transportation act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the impact and the reception can be found not only in
ridership, but also in the investment people have been willing to
make in developing around the system,'' said system spokesman
Morgan Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a light-rail spine in traffic-congested St. Louis
had been bandied about since 1984 but the fear was always that
people could not be pried from their cars.
</P>
<P>
   But early projections of 12,000 riders a day have ballooned to
about 40,000 people on the 17-mile MetroLink line between
Lambert-St. Louis International Airport and East St. Louis in
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Now the problem for the Bi-State Development Agency, which also
provides bus service, is how to keep up with growing demand for
light rail.
</P>
<P>
   The original MetroLink line was built with $348 million in
federal funds and a local in-kind property match worth $116
million. A quarter-cent sales tax will pay for future rail lines.
Extensions to Belleville and Scott Air Force Base in Illinois are
under way, but voters in 1997 rejected a new one-quarter cent sales
tax to speed up future work.
</P>
<P>
   A planning group called the East-West Gateway Coordinating
Council is studying alignments to take MetroLink out into St. Louis
County. Suburban cities, including upscale Clayton, are concerned
about the aesthetic effect of elevated rail and the disruptions
from at-grade crossings.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroLink combines elevated sections, at-grade crossings and
tunnels. The basic one-way fare is $1.25; fares make up about 25
percent of the transit district's total operating costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
