<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LCS RATINGS REQUIRE CLOSER INSPECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ital) The TV sports world according to me: (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   NUMEROLOGY: Numbers being as pliable as silly string, you're
going to hear some baseball experts raving about the League
Championship Series (LCS) ratings as another sign that the good old
days are back.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not so fast. The completed Mets-Braves and Yankees-Red Sox
LCS posted the highest Nielsens since 1993, which was the year
before the 1994 strike which cancelled a World Series. But the
numbers didn't soar to the top of the week's Nielsen chart or even
beat the NFL in head-to-head occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The average rating for the LCS games shared by NBC and Fox was a
10.3, a 21 percent increase over last year's 8.5 and the best since
an 11.8 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's five-game average for the ALCS was a 9.2, its
highest-rated LCS ever, a 21 percent increase over its 7.6 for the
NLCS in '98 and a six percent increase over its 8.7 for the ALCS in
'97. Fox earned these numbers, too, despite some stiff obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3's dream matchup of Pedro Martinez and Roger Clemens was a
daytime telecast that fizzled as the Sox KO'd Rocket en route to a
13-1 win. The Nielsen was 7.5, which was a tenth better than the
7.4 for Game 4 Sunday night, which had competition for two hours
from the extra-inning Braves-Mets game as well as ESPN's Sunday
night NFL cablecast.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's 9.6 for Game 5 came opposite ABC's Monday Night NFL
game between Dallas and the New York Giants, a snoozer that still
beat baseball head-to-head with a 12.1 rating.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's six-game NLCS average was 11.3, an increase of 20 percent
from NBC's ALCS last season and 49 percent from Fox's NLCS in 1998.
The almost six-hour, 15-inning Game 5 between the Braves and Mets
earned a 12.0, while the Game 6 clinching win for the Braves earned
a 15.4, the highest national mark for a NLCS game since 1993 when a
Braves-Phillies game earned a 17.4. One network ratings point
represents 994,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   The divisional series ratings indicate that baseball fans are
sharp enough to know a qualifier when they see one. NBC averaged a
7.0 for three telecasts, down 10 percent, and Fox a 6.9 for five
games, down three percent. Game 5 of the Boston-Cleveland series on
Fox did a 9.0 and cut into ABC's Monday night game, which did a
10.4, down 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) Happy New Year
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this stage of the baseball season, NBC's Bob
Costas and Joe Morgan were coming off their postseason baseball
work amid more criticism than either had ever heard during their
broadcast careers.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus said Costas was rusty from not having any regular
season baseball work and that the two lacked any spark or chemistry
in the booth.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite is now true. Costas and Morgan worked together on a
few ESPN regular season games, and they meshed well on the NLCS and
go into the World Series on a high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucky for us, one of the two games we did this year was a
Mets-Braves game, so some feeling carried over,'' Costas said. ``It
was a matter of getting the mechanics and a rhythm down, and we
were lucky that the NLCS had so many good games. Once things got
going, we found a flow.''
</P>
<P>
   It had to be strange for both men to read unflattering reviews.
Costas has been a standard bearer in the industry for years, and
Morgan, at least until a recent article that said players thought
he was too blunt, was always considered one of the best analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who watches isn't going to like you or love you,''
Morgan said. ``I can only do a game through my eyes. I don't
broadcast the games for the players, I broadcast for the fans. I
think in many cases, players are getting things thirdhand, because
I know they're not watching the telecast. But in truth, I don't
think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By my own assessment, I felt I was rusty (last season),''
Costas said. ``The broadcasts were good, but not as good as in the
past and what we should be able to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's true that if you're around for a long time, and
have been treated well, there may be some people who jump at the
first sign that things are falling. I understand that. I just try
to keep my perspective that overall I've been very well treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports NFL pregame anchor Terry Bradshaw, on his KXTA (1150
AM) radio show this week, savaged Costas for his on-air work and a
condescending attitude, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one person,'' Costas said. ``I've never had a problem
with Terry. I've never said anything public or private about him.
We do have different approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) And now the news
</P>
<P>
   More ball notes. Costas and Morgan declined to pick a winner.
But Costas expects the series to have a moment along the lines of a
Bill Buckner
</P>
<P>
   roller or Kirk Gibson
</P>
<P>
   home run. Costas says the Yankees' Darryl Strawberry
</P>
<P>
   is the X factor, and Morgan says the Braves will need a dynamic
series by Andruw Jones
</P>
<P>
   to win. ... Costas has joined the growing number of
sportscasters who believe instant replay should be used on select
occasions, like the tag play in Game 4 of the ALCS. ... Costas will
host two specials Saturday before Game 1, ``The Sporting News 25
Greatest Moments in Baseball History'' and the ``MLB All-Century
Team.'' The members of the All-Century Team will be introduced
before the start of Game 2 in Atlanta, and Vin Scully
</P>
<P>
   will handle those on-air introductions. ... XTRA (690 AM) and
KXTA will carry the World Series broadcasts via ESPN Radio, with
the teams to include Jon Miller
</P>
<P>
   , Rick Sutcliffe
</P>
<P>
   , Charley Steiner
</P>
<P>
   and Dave Campbell
</P>
<P>
