<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANINA-WINTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER WET LA NINA WINTER PREDICTED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  A NASA satellite is warning weather-watchers to prepare for
another ``wet and wild'' winter, with cold storms blasting the
Pacific coast from Alaska to San Francisco.
<P>
   ``We're in for another La Nina,'' said oceanographer William
Patzert, who monitors the satellite's findings every 10 days from
his station at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite, dubbed TOPEX/Poseidon, orbits Earth from pole to
pole and measures how high the sea surface across the entire
Pacific rises above its normal level. It is so precise that it can
detect the rises and falls of just a few inches that indicate
significant changes in weather patterns in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   When the ocean's temperature rises, so does the height of the
sea, but in areas where it cools down, the level of the surface
drops, Patzert explained.
</P>
<P>
   Maps created from the satellite's latest data show that the
Pacific's surface height dipped about six inches below normal
during a 10-day cycle that ended last Friday, Patzert said. At the
same time, the surface of the western part of the Pacific is higher
than normal, which indicates that temperatures will be higher than
usual in that part of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Patzert is now forecasting a wet and stormy winter in the
northeastern Pacific and a dry and warmer-than-usual winter in
Southern California and much of the Southwest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the mark of a La Nina winter _ the reverse of weather
conditions known as El Nino, when the Pacific's waters are
unusually warm along the Northern California coast and colder than
usual down south.
</P>
<P>
   These extremely unbalanced conditions, Patzert said, exert a
powerful influence on the weather system that sends the jet stream
out of the North Pacific across North America.  &LR;   &LR;  To Patzert, the
unstable atmosphere above the ponderous Pacific is like ``a
ballerina dancing on top of an elephant,'' and as a result, he
said, ``we're definitely going through a decade of wild climatic
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The La Nina phenomenon usually follows an El Nino year and
creates the opposite weather conditions. So during the 1997-98 El
Nino winter, for example, the waters off the Northern California
coast reached record high temperatures, and offshore fishermen
found themselves catching all kinds of tropical creatures, some
edible and some not.
</P>
<P>
   Then last winter's cold La Nina followed, when precipitation
throughout Northern California was 45 percent above normal and the
Pacific Northwest was lashed with one heavy winter storm after
another.
</P>
<P>
   Similar abnormally cold and wet La Nina weather has also
followed El Ninos three times in the past 15 years: after the
1982-83 El Nino event, and after those of 1986-87 and 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat unusual for two La Nina events to occur in
successive years, Patzert said, adding, ``And as some distinguished
person remarked, this coming winter is `deja vu all over again.' ''
Scientists at the government's Climate Prediction Center in Camp
Springs, Md., use a wide array of surface buoys to watch changing
sea temperatures across the entire Pacific, and they, too, are
predicting a second episode of La Nina weather for the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above-normal precipitation and below-normal temperatures'' is
the forecast for the coming winter in Northern California and the
Northwest, said Ants Leetma of the federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Leetma and his colleagues keep long-term climate records for the
entire country, and ``it's pretty clear'' that there was a gradual
warming of sea surface temperatures all along the Pacific Coast
during the 1970s, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that pattern seems to be reversing, and it looks as though
the coast is in for a gradual return to a warmer, long-term El Nino
weather pattern, despite the coming winter wet and cold, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether this pattern will persist, and if it
does, it could have profound effects'' on California climate
trends, he said. But the evidence for long-term changes is still
unclear, so the return of La Nina is still the most likely outcome
for the coming winter months, Leetma said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
