r w BC-VISAS-HIGHTECH-SFCHRO     10-22 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISAS-HIGHTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH LEADERS BEG RELUCTANT SENATORS FOR MORE WORK VISAS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Silicon Valley lobbyists warned a Senate
subcommittee Thursday of a dire shortage of high-tech workers, but
despite broad sympathy in Congress, there is little chance that the
ceiling on temporary work visas will be lifted this year.
<P>
   Senator Dianne Feinstein said she supports another increase in
the number of so-called H-1B visas, which grant temporary entry to
highly skilled workers. But the California Democrat pointedly added
that she thinks more should be done to train U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been besieged by CEOs from high-tech companies year
after year,'' Feinstein said, citing statistics to demonstrate that
she understands the vital role high-tech plays in the California
economy. ``I've heard, firsthand, CEOs saying we can't find
educated Californians who can do these jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   But unless American native  &LR; workers are better educated, she
added, ``what we're going to have in California is an increasing
division between those who have and those who have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Republican Spencer Abraham called the Senate
immigration subcommittee hearing to rally support for lifting the
current 115,000 per year ceiling on H-1B visas. Even though the cap
was nearly doubled just last year, it was reached in June.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has complained vociferously that an explosive
demand for skilled workers, a shortage of U.S. science and computer
graduates, and visa backlogs from previous years are creating a
critical labor shortage that threatens to strangle high-tech's
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Several bills to raise the limit have been introduced. Yet
despite a full-court press in both parties to please the high-tech
industry, the visa issue is divisive, splitting off pro-labor
factions among Democrats and anti-immigration factions among
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republican Lamar Smith, who chairs the House immigration
subcommittee, strongly opposes further H-1B increases, and is not
about to move such a bill in the few weeks left before Congress
adjourns. Instead, Smith has highlighted visa fraud and the recent
admission by the Immigration and Naturalization service that it
mistakenly granted anywhere from 10,000 to 20,000 extra H-1B visas
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., also signaled his
potential opposition, rattling off a survey showing high-tech
industry salaries in the $40,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one graduate of Harvard Law School who starts off
making less than $100,000,'' Kennedy said, calling the
comparatively low salaries in high-tech ``surprising,'' given the
industry's complaints of shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Susan DeFife, president of womenConnect.com, an Internet company
in Virginia, answered that companies rely more on stock options to
attract workers.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Katz, president of TechNet, a Silicon Valley lobbying
group, assured Feinstein that the industry's top worry is the poor
performance of U.S. schools and that companies are pouring hundreds
of millions of dollars into training and education.
</P>
<P>
   Katz and others said Intel Corp. spends more than $100 million a
year and Hewlett-Packard $50 million to improve lower education,
while Cisco Systems has 17,000 students enrolled in its Networking
Academies.
</P>
<P>
   But Katz insisted that until U.S. schools produce enough trained
workers, skilled foreigners should not be rebuffed, especially
since many received their advanced degrees from U.S. universities.
``To turn these highly skilled scientists and engineers away after
we have trained them in the United States _ encouraging them to
seek employment by foreign companies who may be our competitors _
simply does not make sense,'' Katz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 0339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OLDEST-DINOSAUR-SFCHR     10-22 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDEST-DINOSAUR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DINOSAUR FOSSILS COULD BE THE OLDEST YET  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A villager in a remote and roadless valley of Madagascar led a
team of scientists to a clutter of old bones in a nearby hill four
years ago, opening the door to one of the most remarkable fossil
discoveries of recent times.
</P>
<P>
   Digging into that hill, the scientists found the fossil jawbones
of what may be the two oldest dinosaurs ever known _ calf-size
creatures that were probably the ancestors of the huge beasts that
later dominated Earth for millions of years, according to a report
being published Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the same hill, the scientists also found the fossilized
skulls and bones of at least eight primitive mammal-like reptiles
whose remains point to a critical period in the early evolution of
both mammals and reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the scientists say, their discoveries could provide
new clues to the process of evolution during the long years of a
geologic period known as the middle to late Triassic, around 230
million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the expedition, John J. Flynn of the Field Museum
in Chicago and Andrew Wyss of the University of California at Santa
Barbara _ together with their American and Madagascar colleagues _
are reporting their discoveries in Friday's issue of the journal
Science.
</P>
<P>
   Wyss called the discovery of the varied animal fossils ``a
spectacular fauna of this age'' and said their condition is
``superb, rivaling that of anything in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is more to come, he said, because ``a wealth of bones
is pouring out of our quarries _ a host of other novel animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said the teeth in the two jawbones indicate the creatures
were long-necked prosauropods, the earliest of all dinosaurs. They
were probably four to eight feet long and no larger than calves.
And they were both bipedal and quadrupedal, Flynn said, meaning
that they could use their forefeet like hands to forage on the lush
vegetation of the ancient region but could run swiftly on all four
feet to avoid predators.
</P>
<P>
   Their bone structure indicates that they were probably the
ancestors of a long line of plant-eating dinosaurs, including the
huge Apatosaurus that weighed 36 tons and was the largest animal
ever known, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Wyss, the bones of the reptile-like creatures in
the same dig indicate they must have lived at a time when evolution
was dividing their lineage in two directions _ some descendants
toward true mammals and the others to the abundant reptilian world.
</P>
<P>
   Madagascar, lying isolated in the Indian Ocean off the east
coast of southern Africa, was once joined to that continent, but it
separated when the ancient world's massive supercontinent known as
Pangaea began splitting apart about 250 million years ago, at the
very beginning of the Triassic period.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Madagascar's Morondava Basin is known to contain a vast
variety of fossils from the middle to late Triassic period, which
spanned the time from 230 million to 200 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That was the epoch when true dinosaurs began emerging _ some as
small as foxes and others far bigger than elephants and whales.
They flourished, multiplied and dominated the landscape, only to
become extinct in a spasm of destruction 65 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The prosauropod skulls discovered in Madagascar resemble the
fossils of early dinosaur forms from Argentina, which have been
firmly dated with radioisotope techniques at 227 million years old.
</P>
<P>
   But the Madagascar finds may well be a good 5 million years
older, according to Wyss, and the final date must await the use of
laboratory techniques that are unavailable at the excavation site.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can say at this point is that all indications point to
its being older than 227,'' Wyss said.
</P>
<P>
   The team of scientists has already opened three new sites in the
same region of Madagascar, where there are rich fossil deposits
from the late Triassic and early Jurassic periods _ a time when
dinosaurs began flourishing as the dominant beasts on every
continent.
</P>
<P>
   As for the young man who led the team of paleontologists to
their first discovery site, his name is Mena, which in the Malagasy
language means red _ red for the color of the island's soil. Now,
the scientists plan to name at least one of their fossil species
after him _ a true honor in the world of fossil-hunters, who must
still classify and name the unnamed creatures they have found in
their Madagascar treasure trove.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
