<HEADLINE>
YOUNG VIEWERS FUEL SUCCESS OF THE WB 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Pokemon) 
(Eds.: Optional trim included) 
 
By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The WB's ``Angel,'' a ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
spinoff, has higher ratings than ``Buffy.''
</P>
<P>
   The WB moves ``Felicity'' to highly competitive Sundays and
gains viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Fox passes on ``Roswell,'' and the WB launches another instant
teen hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon'' rules. ``7th Heaven'' captivates. ``Charmed''
charms.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only the WB could make some money.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. The WB will break even the fourth quarter of this
year, its CEO said this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be an avalanche of money but it will be a
profit,'' said Jamie Kellner. ``With my business hat on, I judge
myself on making a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner likes to point out in public addresses, as he did at a
luncheon of the Houston Advertising Federation, that 48 percent of
the U.S. population is 18-49, and 50 percent of the WB viewers are
18-49.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use that because our competitors, and sometimes the press,
try to make us into a teeny-bopper network,'' he said. ``We're not
under-delivering the 18-49 audience. We're over-delivering the
18-34 audience and over-delivering the teen audience, which are the
harder-to-reach viewers. I just twist that criticism into a
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who are studying our industry are paying more and
more attention every year to young demographics. All the big
package goods companies are targeting teens and younger adults,
because they can't let their competitors establish the competitor's
brand with younger people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner has followed this principal most of his 30-year
television career. He left as president and chief operating officer
of Fox in 1993 because his vision collided with owner Rupert
Murdoch's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a single show on CBS I ever watch,'' he said. ``I
don't like any programs that are older-skewing.''
</P>
<P>
   As WB CEO, he expects to continue to go after the 18-34 crowd _
and younger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be No. 1 with teens, you want to be No. 1 with
kids because you don't want anybody to outflank you,'' he said.
``If I were selling Ford automobiles, I'd have a very low-priced,
entry-level car that every kid would want to have when they got
their first car. And I would want them to have a great experience
with that car.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'd even make bicycles for teen-agers. I'd want them to
think my company, Ford, was the best way to get your transportation
as early as possible. I'd want them to think we're the coolest and
best mode of transportation in their whole lives. That's my network
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   That strategy works with teens, it's been proved. And now it's
working with youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to believe cable had a lock on the kid business until
we went past Nickelodeon on Saturday mornings,'' Kellner said. ``It
shows the power of programming,'' with ``Pokemon'' and ``Batman
Beyond'' among the WB shows leading the way. ``We've got the
boys,'' Kellner said. ``They've (Nickelodeon) got the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner believes the WB can also schedule a successful comedy
and does not oppose WB stations carrying local sports programs. He
also addressed such issues as diversity, sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   _ On stretching the WB's programming to a seventh night,
Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scheduled for next year. Quite frankly, I look at
Saturday as like driving a car in the fog. If there's a night
(young people) are going to be out, it's going to be Saturday
nights. So it's a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On developing a sitcom in what has proved a poor comedy
season:
</P>
<P>
   The blight in comedy ``makes it easier right now'' for the WB to
develop a comedy, he said. ``We've worked on a couple of shows that
have shown promise, like ''Zoe,`` ''Duncan,`` ``Jack and Jane``
(which is on the midseason roster). The problem is (the characters)
were aged too young so we couldn't deal with significant issues.''
That is being fixed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teen hormones rage. Should they rage on TV?
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of teen-agers have sex at a fairly early age,''
he said. ``I don't think they should feel they've done something
wrong, but I do feel they should understand they have a choice
before they make that decision. If really cool people, like the
stars (of ''Dawson's Creek``), say they don't have to have sex,
then (real-life teens) can say they don't have to have sex, either.
And other kids that have done it aren't bad; they've made a choice.
In most cases, they regret it. You have to show consequences and
deal with the issue of STDs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On violence:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I watch Buffy do the chop-socky on vampires and take a
wooden stake and turn them into dust, I believe that's acceptable
viewing for people above the age of 10 or 11.'' Incidents like the
one at Columbine High are not TV's fault ``any more than scary
stories told around campfires hundreds of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On diversity:
</P>
<P>
   The WB doesn't necessarily look for minorities to fill
positions, Kellner said. ``We're looking for someone with a track
record, who can execute, has a unique take on something and fits
into the interest areas of our younger demos.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a network of younger people, we're far less color-blind.
(The WB and UPN were not targeted for boycotts recently by the
NAACP and Hispanic groups). I was raised in a world where there was
far more black and white. My son lives in a world where he doesn't
really care what anybody's skin color is. Between those posts is
where America lies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4995 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-BOYS-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      10-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOYS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARTLAND TEEN STAYS TRUE TO HIMSELF IN EMOTIONAL `BOYS DON'T CRY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: two dots needed over e in Chloe) 
 
By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry'' is an emotionally wrenching film about trying
to find your identity in a world that already has you labeled and
neatly filed away.
</P>
<P>
   If this was just the true story of Teena Brandon, a young woman
of the American heartland who tried to pass as a boy named Brandon
Teena and paid dearly for her fantasy, this might be a
limited-interest pseudo-documentary, trying to make us feel sorry
for her.
</P>
<P>
   But in the skillful hands of director and co-writer Kimberly
Pierce, and with an excellent cast, this film, shot in Texas, has
much broader appeal and a deeper resonance. It has already been
compared to a host of classic films about lost and disaffected
youth. Perhaps none fits it so well in tone and title as ``Rebel
Without a Cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Brandon _ we see the character almost exclusively in her
boy mode _ may represent a lot of things to some people, to her she
is representing only herself. Like Jim in ``Rebel Without a
Cause,'' she is not a crusader. She is not fighting for gay rights
or cross-dressing or freedom. (She does not seem to regard herself
as a lesbian.)
</P>
<P>
   She is just a confused and bursting-with-life 21-year-old
wanting to live as the person she feels inside _ a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's unsentimental, nonjudgmental approach makes the story
more powerful than if it had gone for our hearts or tried to be a
lesson on equality.
</P>
<P>
   Her only visual tricks, mostly speeded-up camera work in
transitional scenery shots, work to emphasize the out-of-control
nature of Brandon's life.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon is not a hero.
</P>
<P>
   She's self-centered, a petty thief, a belligerent drunk and a
person without even a simple monitor on her self-control.
</P>
<P>
   But she makes a good boyfriend, at least as far as her
girlfriends (who think she is a boy) are concerned. Since Brandon
is something of a low-class barfly, she tends toward the same in
women, and they are thrilled to find a considerate man.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with Teena trying out her Brandon persona in a
country-western bar. She gets into a fight with an older, bigger
man over the right to sit next to a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon gets her brains beat out, but she's got a lot more guts
than brains, and keeps coming back for more.
</P>
<P>
   The drunken Brandon winds up in the small town of Falls City,
Neb., where she spots Lana. We first see Lana as a boring, poorly
educated frump slumped over a drink.
</P>
<P>
   As their relationship progresses, we see Lana more as Brandon
comes to see her, as an attractive young woman with potential,
given some encouragement, and feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon begins to hang out with Lana and her low-life family and
friends, including a couple of rough-edged boys, John and Tom, the
former a paroled convict. We do not sense that either is really
bad, certainly not capable of what we suspect might happen. But
that is another pleasure of this movie. It treats all its
characters with the same disinterested eye and emphasizes how
events in some lives just develop, with little planning or
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware that the film, while excessively graphic, is extremely
powerful in portraying the two final tragic events in Brandon's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Swank, who has appeared in numerous films (The Next
Karate Kid) and television (Beverly Hills, 90210), is amazing as
Brandon. If the real Brandon was as skilled at playing a boy, it's
no wonder she was able to pass so well.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the cast is also excellent: Chloe Sevigny (Kids and
The Last Days of Disco) plays Lana, Peter Sarsgaard (Dead Man
Walking) is John and Brendan Sexton III (Welcome to the Doll's
House) is Tom.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, by Pierce and Andy Bienen, is a wonder of
efficiency and subtlety. They simply tell the story and let us
figure out what is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's direction is, for the most part, straightforward,
powerful and unpretentious. But there is one terrific shot of the
underside of an electricity tower, shot at night with special
lenses, that is a disorienting treat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Boys Don't Cry &QL; 
Starring: Hilary Swank, Peter Sarsgaard, Chloe Sevigny &QL; 
Rated: R for violence, including an intense, brutal rape scene,
sexuality, language and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
