<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-TANGO-REVIEW-HNS     10-22 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TANGO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITTY `TANGO' CAN BE TOO COY FOR COMFORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, ``Three to Tango'' is a refreshing change of pace
for its TV-star cast.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Perry gets to play a lovelorn leading man, Dylan
McDermott gets to play the bad guy and Neve Campbell gets to smile,
unlike her chronically pained character on ``Party of Five.''
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways, this romantic comedy is stale _ or, more
precisely, dated.
</P>
<P>
   Its eventful story presents a complex tangle of relationships,
and the key to the equation is whether Perry's character is gay.
</P>
<P>
   But the subject is addressed as if the setting was a sleepy town
in 1989, not Chicago in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's _ well, you know ... '' say these allegedly sophisticated
city folk, who often can't even bring themselves to say the word.
</P>
<P>
   By contrivance, Perry is perceived to be as gay as his architect
partner (Oliver Platt) when they court a billionaire (McDermott)
for a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   That makes him seem a safe companion for the mistress (Campbell)
of the married and jealous tycoon, who dangles the carrot of a big
contract in exchange for Perry's spying.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Perry falls madly _ and secretly _ in love with her,
jeopardizing the job. But he can't ``come out,'' especially when
the media trumpet him as ``gay professional of the year'' for
bravely admitting his homosexuality (another dated and patronizing
ploy).
</P>
<P>
   In short, this plays like a cross between ``In and Out'' (is he
gay or not?) and ``The Object of My Affection'' (can a straight
woman love a gay man?), only without the contemporary urban
sensibilities it needs.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Damon Santostefano, and writer, Rodney Vaccaro,
are first-timers, so we'll cut them some slack. Besides, once you
adjust to the embarrassment and snickering, ``Three to Tango''
generates a genial charm.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking to his ``Friends'' shtick, Perry tries too hard, but
that's part of his hapless charm, and at least he doesn't play gay
with silly mannerisms.
</P>
<P>
   During funny fits of discomfiture, he tempers his manic nature
with a sensitive side, and he clicks well with Campbell, though
mostly as a guy she treats as a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Her romance with the billionaire is ludicrously unlikely. Eking
out a living as a glass blower, she's impulsive, earthy, immature
and no model of discretion.
</P>
<P>
   But McDermott is just as unlikely as the billionaire. He's too
young and not driven enough _ especially since we're accustomed to
his zeal in ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many movies, this also hinges on instant familiarity, if
not bonding, between strangers. The love-hate threesome seem as
tight as old school chums.
</P>
<P>
   Realism aside, ``Three to Tango'' offers snappy repartee, clever
one-liners and amusing turns by Platt, two rival architects (Bob
Balaban and John C. McGinley), and three guys who play Perry's
beer-drinking pals.
</P>
<P>
   Overall it's _ well, you know _ an entertaining lark that's
often spry and even radiant, with an end-credit wrap-up that's a
hoot. It just should have been made a decade ago. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Three to Tango &QL; 
Starring: Matthew Perry, Neve Campbell and Dylan McDermott &QL; 
Rating: PG-13 for sex-related situations and language &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
