<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4997 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-CRAZY-REVIEW-HNS     10-22 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRAZY-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWISTING BLACK COMEDY IS `CRAZY' BUT EFFECTIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MELISSA WARD AGUILAR 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something familiar about Melanie Griffith's character in
``Crazy in Alabama.'' Something reckless. Something wild.
</P>
<P>
   She's a little bit Marilyn Monroe, a little bit Scarlett O'Hara,
a little bit of the character she played in ``Something Wild.'' The
comedy-drama is a return to the kind of role Griffith does best.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith wears a black wig, heavy eyeliner and just-applied
lipstick for the role. She pours herself into a variety of
Monroe-esque outfits. Her Lucille is a sexy, bold, yet somewhat
pitiful character _ a loving mother of seven small children who has
just poisoned their mean, old father and decapitated him with her
electric knife. She carries his head around in Tupperware. (``It's
amazing how fresh he stays in plastic.'')
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention this is black comedy?
</P>
<P>
   Now free from her husband's mistreatment, Lucille drops the kids
with MeeMaw (well, this is Alabama) and heads out to California to
find stardom.
</P>
<P>
   We learn all about crazy Lucille from her adoring nephew,
Peejoe, who narrates the film, which Mark Childress adapated from
his novel. If you were casting a movie called ``Crazy in Alabama,''
you would also want to hire as narrator 16-year-old Lucas Black,
who proved in ``Sling Blade'' that he does the best Deep South
accent in Hollywood. Maybe in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   Peejoe doesn't just tell us about crazy Aunt Lucille and her
trip to Hollywood. The orphaned boy who, with his brother, has been
sent to live with his funeral-director uncle (David Morse) has his
own story to tell. That's where the movie gets tricky.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Banderas has chosen, for his directorial debut, a film
with two divergent storylines that are sometimes hard to weave
together.
</P>
<P>
   This is the South in 1965. PeeJoe is watching the stirrings of
the civil rights movement. He wonders why black people can't vote.
Or swim in the pool. He's told that's just the way things are. He
doesn't think it's fair.
</P>
<P>
   Then he sees an African-American boy his age, Taylor Jackson,
take a stand. Peejoe takes his side.
</P>
<P>
   When Taylor (Louis Miller) leads a group of boys to integrate
the swimming pool, Sheriff John Doggett (played menacingly by Meat
Loaf Aday) won't have it.
</P>
<P>
   As Taylor tries to run away and scale the fence, the sheriff
pulls him to his death _ with Peejoe as the only witness. It won't
be the last time the sheriff and PeeJoe are at odds.
</P>
<P>
   As the racial strife escalates, Banderas blurs the scenes of
white men beating peaceful protesters. Then the film flashes to
black and white. The camera work is effective in conveying the
anonymous nature of the violence, but sometimes it's unsettling to
make the switch back to the film's lush colors and comic lines.
</P>
<P>
   But back to Lucille's story: After pulling a gun, stealing a car
and conning a cop, she ends up in Vegas _ and wins big. She heads
to Hollywood in style, and fulfills her dream in no time, landing a
role on ``Bewitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucille may sound like a bad girl, but she's really warm and
endearing. It's hard to imagine her killing her husband. Or taking
his abuse. She talks fondly to his head, which she now has encased
in a stylish hatbox.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there will be hell to pay back home. And you know
she'll have to go back.
</P>
<P>
   A courtroom scene brings everyone together and attempts to tie
up the loose ends of the two stories _ both are about freedom. The
scene's longer than it needs to be; the judge finally dispenses
with formalities and lets Lucille tell her side and recount her
husband's abuses.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a strong denouncement, but Rod Steiger, as the Southern
judge, has some funny lines. And Griffith, draped in green, evokes
the spirit of Scarlett O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   Like Griffith, the film is lovely to look at, with its saturated
colors and moss-laden locales.
</P>
<P>
   The film should appeal to teens as well as adults; they can
identify with the point-of-view character and appreciate the civil
rights story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy in Alabama'' leaves a strong impression; in the end, the
drama adds depth to the comic tone. Despite some rough
intertwining, ``Crazy'' is an impressive directing debut from
Banderas; he gets good performances from the actors. And Black's
eyebrows are as expressive as his drawl.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Crazy in Alabama &QL; 
Starring: Melanie Griffith, Lucas Black and David Morse. &QL; 
Rated: PG-13 for some violence, thematic material, language and a
scene of sensuality. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
