<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4998 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CROSSBURNINGS23-COX     10-22 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSSBURNINGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cross burnings concern Texas community
 &HT;    By Emily Morris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN AUGUSTINE, Texas _ On the back roads of rural San Augustine
County, two recent cross burnings have caused concern among people
in both the black community and white communities here.
</P>
<P>
   The two separate incidents, reported within two weeks of each
other, are being investigated by the San Augustine County sheriff's
deputies and the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The first cross burning was reported to sheriff's deputies
around midnight Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The victim seemed an unlikely victim of a racially motivated
hate crime _ she is a single white woman with two children lit home.
</P>
<P>
   She is neither Jewish nor Catholic, and she said she has not
recently had black visitors in her home. Sheriff's officials first
believed the cross burning at the white woman's house to be an
isolated incident_ probably meant to be taken as a prank.
</P>
<P>
   But then, less than two weeks later, a cross was set ablaze on
the church grounds of a small country church _ a black church.
</P>
<P>
   The second incident occurred in the same area of the county as
the first incident. Pisgah Baptist Church is a small wooden
building nestled amid trees on national forest lands off
farm-to-market Road 705.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation is made up of nearly 20 members _ all of them
black. Only eight or 10 of the members are able to attend
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   As the membership of Pisgah has aged, the frequency of services
there has decreased.
</P>
<P>
   At the present time, there is no full-time pastor.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime member of Pisgah, C.J. Jones, said members of the
church and usually a few visitors meet every third Wednesday night
for prayer meeting and every third Sunday morning for worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a pastor, now,'' he said. ``But we have someone
come preach once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been a member of Pisgah since 1962. His wife, Vada
Jones, 63, has been a member since she was born.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jones or his wife knows how old the church is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's old,'' Jones said. ``That's all I know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jones live less than a mile from the church grounds, and
they have taken it upon themselves to look after the building,
whenever they take a trip to town.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he drove past the church last week and saw the sun
glaring off the windshield of a truck parked in the drive.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled in and recognized the pickup as a green National
Forest Service vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw the driver of the truck standing nearby, but it
was what he saw next that made his heart skip a beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a burned cross standing upright, stuck in some
cinder blocks,'' he said. ``I don't know exactly how long it had
been there, but it wasn't there two days earlier, when I went to
town.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones asked the forest service employee if the cross was there
that morning when he arrived to do his work in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The man told him it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home and called the sheriff,'' Jones said. ``Then I
called some of the other church members who live around here, and
they came over to my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Sheriff John Cartwright met him at the church later
that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff took pictures of the cross, and then he took the
cross with him,'' Jones said. ``We were having church that night,
and I knew some people were afraid to come. We asked him if the
deputies could patrol the area during our prayer meeting, and they
did. They patrol this area pretty regularly, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said members of the church congregated the following
Sunday for worship services, but their attitude was somber.
</P>
<P>
   During their noon meal at church that day, doors leading into
the front of the building were locked. Jones said this is one of
the few times in the history of the church that problems of any
kind have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 25 years ago, some heaters were stolen,'' he said. ``But
we've never had anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he was surprised and shaken by the cross burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get along real good here,'' he said of the relationship
between blacks and whites. ``We have good relations, and we have
white company over at our house all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and his wife are both lifelong residents of San Augustine
County.
</P>
<P>
   When their first home in the city limits burned more than 15
years ago, they moved into their current house in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they raise collard greens and other vegetables, and a
long row of marigolds line the drive up to their house.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for white people or black people to pull up in
the driveway for a chat, and more often than not _ visitors take
something with them when they leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raise sugar cane, and people are always asking us when it
will be ready,'' Ms. Jones said. ``People come out here to see us
all the time. And they don't leave empty-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   To think that someone has animosity toward them or the people
living in their community is almost unimaginable, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never would have thought something like this would have
happened, either,'' he said. ``I've never been afraid to knock on
anyone's door as long as I've lived here, and I've never been
afraid of letting anyone in my house. I don't know what to think
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff John Cartwright said the case has been referred to the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this is classified as a hate crime these
days,'' he said. ``We've been advised to turn cases like this over
to the FBI, and they have already come for copies of our reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright said both burned crosses appeared to have been soaked
in either gasoline or some type of lighter fluid.
</P>
<P>
   The cross in the first victim's yard was laid upon the grass.
</P>
<P>
   The first victim, who asked that her name be withheld, said she
was at home when the incident happened.
</P>
<P>
   She said she saw a pickup pull into the drive around 11:30 p.m.
Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The driver turned off the headlights and got out of the truck,
and the woman said it appeared he set her grass on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter came into the room where I was, and then went in
and woke my son,'' she said. ``The people in the yard drove away in
a loud truck, but I don't know what kind it was. It was dark, and I
couldn't see. Also, I didn't really know what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   When the woman and her two children ran outside, the fire was
beginning to go out. They realized it wasn't the grass burning, but
a wooden cross that would have been about as tall as a person, had
it been standing upright.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just laid it on the ground and set it on fire,'' the
woman said. ``It was very dewy that night, or the fire might have
spread.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman said she has no idea why she might have been the
target of a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary,'' she said. ``Very, very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he is also still very frightened by what happened at
the church.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said an FBI agent asked him whether he thought the cross
burning might have any link to the trial
</P>
<P>
   of the third suspect in the dragging death of James Byrd Jr.,
which proceeds Monday in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine anyone doing anything like that in San
Augustine County,'' Jones said. ``Jasper is 40 miles from here. I
know they call this a hate crime, but there has never been any hate
in our community before.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he believes the incident in San Augustine County
could possibly have been the work of pranksters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a funny prank to play, if that's the case,'' he
said. ``This is the kind of thing that would shake anyone up. It
just wasn't the thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
