<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Friday, Oct. 22, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Saturday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BUS-ACCIDENT (Schoharie, N.Y.) _ ``I never saw so many
kids crying,'' said fireman Cliff Dorrough. ``It was a mess all
over the place.'' He was describing the wreck of a school bus and a
26 1/2-ton dump truck that left several dozen children injured, one
critically. By The Albany Times Union.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-GAYS (San Francisco) _ Gay and lesbian subscribers to
America Online and gay online organizations are considering
boycotting the Internet giant for what they see as discrimination
against gay content online. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CARE-PACKAGES (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ In an age of electronic
mail and cellular phones, technology cannot displace the powerful
message of the college care package. ``They're wonderful,'' said
Sarah Kottmeier, a senior at Skidmore College. ``Nothing is better
than care packages.'' By MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-WASH-SHOPPING (San Francisco) _ Car washes all over the Bay
Area are dolling up their stores with surprisingly exclusive gifts,
hoping to cash in on impulse buying as well as the ultimate goal of
working families in the '90s: saving time. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-DEAD (Undated) _ ``Bringing Out the Dead'' offers us
the burnt-out ruminations of one Frank Pierce, a wee-hours
paramedic who twirls around New York in an ambulance, looking for
meaning. The film isn't always coherent and is nowhere near the
best film director Martin Scorsese has done, but at least it's
entertaining. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LIMEY (Undated) _ Steven Soderbergh's newest film,
``The Limey,'' is both a return to experimental territory and an
exercise in creative moderation. This small, crafty crime tale
never seems indulgent; with an 88-minute running time and a
staccato script that packs potent asymmetry into a few small
scenes, the movie has the blackness and economy of classic film
noir. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BESTMAN (Undated) _ ``The Best Man'' is as innocuous
as the love songs on its soundtrack, and as comely as the members
of its nimble ensemble. The movie poster reads: ``The flower
arrangements have all been ordered. The sleeping arrangements are
still being worked out.'' Things never get as ribald or as
complicated as that. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-STRAIGHT (Undated) _ ``The Straight Story'' is a
G-rated tale about a man who drives his 1966 John Deere riding
mower from Iowa to Wisconsin to bring his ailing, estranged brother
his love. Anyone looking for a sign that Doomsday is nigh won't
find it in the David Lynch-directed, Walt Disney-produced film. By
WELSEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-KELLER-WB (Houston) _ ``Angel,'' a ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' spinoff, does better ratings than ``Buffy.'' ``Felicity''
gets moved to Sunday and it gains viewers. FOX passes on
``Roswell,'' and the WB launches another instant teen hit. The WB,
which is targeting the 18-49 audience, will break even the fourth
quarter of this year, CEO Jamie Kellner said. ``It's not going to
be an avalanche of money but it will be a profit.'' By MIKE
MCDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRAZY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Antonio Banderas gets good
performances from actors Melanie Griffith, Lucas Black and David
Moorse in his impressive directoral debut, ``Crazy in Alabama.'' By
MELISSA WARD AGUILAR.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BOYS-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Boys Don't Cry'' is an
emotionally wrenching film about trying to find your identity in a
world that already has you labeled and neatly filed away. By LOUIS
B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TANGO-REVIEW (Undated) _ In some ways, ``Three to Tango''
is a refreshing change of pace for its TV-star cast, Matthew Perry
(Friends), Dylan McDermott (The Practice) and Neve Campbell (Party
of Five). But in other ways, this romantic comedy is stale _ or,
more precisely, dated. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL/BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARM-BALLOT (San Francisco) _ Banks have raised almost $400,000
in an effort to persuade San Francisco voters to defeat a city
ballot measure to ban ATM surcharge fees. The total included
$100,000 contributions each from Bank of America and Wells Fargo.
By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-RATTO-COLUMN (Atlanta, Ga.) _ The New York Yankees and
Atlanta Braves have been told that this World Series will bestow
upon the winner the profoundly mythical title of Team Of The '90s.
Hence, their confusion. They thought they were just playing for the
here and now. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Jeff Garcia sat at his locker
earlier this week, picking at a light lunch and awaiting the start
of another practice. 49ers general manager Bill Walsh took a seat
on the bench and spoke to the 49ers quarterback in a soothing tone,
looking every bit like a learned father offering advice to a son
who had hit hard times. By JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ ``It looks like it's going to be
a `none of the above' election,'' said a friend, who advocates such
a choice on every ballot. Think of how the country would look if we
had such a choice. No one in the White House, no one in the
governor's office, no one as mayor, no one as district attorney and
no one on the Board of Supervisors. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ He was wearing the black suit, the
double-breasted one. Mayor Al always wears the black,
double-breasted suit when he gets serious about something. Al
Jurczynski is the Republican mayor of Schenectady. He's a burly,
bespectacled guy in his early 40s who used to operate a furniture
store. Mayor Al is roughly the size of a Lincoln Town Car. By DAN
LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
