<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carrier's story well-told
 &HT;    By Jim Cinter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Jeff Nesmith is the only Pulitzer
prize-winning journalist I know who will overnight a coop of laying
hens to bail out a friend.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago (more than either of us care to count), Jeff and
I worked the night shift on The Atlanta Constitution. One midnight
I got a distress call from my wife. Our Irish setter had gotten
into Forrest Ballard's chicken house and killed six hens.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest is a good fellow. In one place or another, we've been
next-door neighbors for most of our lives. I knew he would be
forgiving and wouldn't make a fuss, but I was embarrassed, and
wanted to make amends. I mentioned my predicament to Jeff, a farm
boy from Florida who was in a semirural mode on some acreage out
near Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, Jeff showed up for work with six white Leghorns
in the trunk of his car. I delivered the hens to Forrest with
apologies on behalf of my Irish setter.
</P>
<P>
   After a good run reporting and editing for The Constitution,
Jeff moved on to Philadelphia and then back to Cox Newspapers as an
investigative reporter in the Washington bureau. His wife, also a
former Constitution reporter, worked in the White House writing
speeches for Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   When I hear people complain about biased and sloppy reporting,
often with justification, I'd like to introduce them to Jeff
Nesmith. He bends over backward to be fair. He checks and rechecks,
listens to all sides, never turns in a story until he has touched
all the bases. If more reporters and editors were as skilled and
conscientious as Jeff, critics wouldn't have much to complain
about.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago I got a book in the mail, along with a note from
Chuck Perry, the founding editor-chief executive of Longstreet
Press in Atlanta. ``I think you will enjoy this book,'' Chuck
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The title was ``No Higher Honor,'' the story of the USS Yorktown
in World War II's battles of Coral Sea and Midway, the two great
carrier battles that began to turn the tide when it looked as if
the Japanese would never be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know much about literary stuff, and certainly I've never
been asked to do a book review for the New York Times or anything
like that, but there is one area where I'm not exactly ignorant.
I've read a lot of World War II books. Thanks to our Fayetteville
neighbor Weyman Grubbs, who keeps lending me his books even when I
forget to return them, I've read most of what's been written about
naval warfare in the Pacific. All I can say is, I've never read a
better book about World War II naval warfare than Jeff's.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Higher Honor,'' the title taken from the Yorktown captain's
after-action report following the Battle of Coral Sea, is easy to
describe. It is Stephen Ambrose's ``Citizen Soldiers,'' Tom
Brokaw's ``The Greatest Generation'' and the movie ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' wrapped up in 268 pages of tremendous reporting and
skillful writing. It is also a page-turner.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered how Jeff had managed to track down so many surviving
members of the Yorktown's crew and unlock memories over half a
century old. I found the answer in the last chapter. His uncle Joe
Weatherington, his mother's youngest brother, was a Yorktown
sailor.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yorktown, torpedoed and sunk after the great victory at
Midway, was discovered in its Pacific grave in 1998, Jeff was
assigned to write the story for Cox Newspapers. Thinking it would
be good to have reaction from surviving crew, he called his Uncle
Joe for names.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I said my uncle had been a member of the ship's crew, I
could almost feel the telephone warming in my hand, as if I were a
member of the family,'' he wrote. ``Almost invariably I then got
this question from the other end of the line: `Did he get off?' So
many didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   When he found old sailors in their 70s and 80s anxious to tell
their stories, to talk about their buddies and the great carrier's
brave and often bloody odyssey, Nesmith began to think of a book.
Chuck Perry bought the idea and now ``No Higher Honor'' is
Longstreet's book of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A practiced investigative reporter, Nesmith made extensive use
of naval archives, both Japanese and American. Although told mostly
through words of participants, the book is a creditable history of
the naval war in the Pacific. Typically, every person interviewed
got a chance to read what Jeff wrote and to make corrections.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine a better read for those who were there, or for
those who waited and wondered at home, or for those to young to
know and who ought to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Higher Honor'' should be a national best-seller. It might
not be, because Jeff is a modest fellow, not one to push for the
``Today Show'' and high-powered publicity that many authors covet.
</P>
<P>
   When I told him I thought the book was terrific, he said he
appreciated the compliment. ``My mother called and said it was a
classic,'' he said, ``but she had only read the first page.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
