<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting rid of squirrels just requires talking them to death
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ More than a year ago, I used this space to
solicit ideas from readers on how to get squirrels out of an attic.
I received numerous nice replies, most of them ending with a phrase
which, roughly translated, meant, ``lots of luck, buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The most consistent advice given was to use mothballs. First I
used one box of mothballs and, when that failed to do the job, I
used 15 boxes. The squirrels stayed though it all, but since then,
a moth hasn't been spotted within miles of my house.
</P>
<P>
   Still and all, the squirrels did leave for a long time, probably
for more posh digs down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, just maybe, they moved out for a quieter place to
live. With four children, my house will never be mistaken for a
chapel. Neighbors Ben and Margaret just across the street could
bring civilization to the hectic world of a squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   The noise factor is what I am counting on now that the Squirrel
family has decided to re-enter my life. I've decided I'm going to
use noise terrorism to drive out the little buggers.
</P>
<P>
   That is, I'm gonna put a radio in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, before you laugh, remember that the exact same tactic
worked on Manuel Noriega when the Marines were trying to flush him
out in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, I'm guessing that the first farmer who put up a
scarecrow in his field was the target of jeering from his farmer
friends. When you're on the cutting edge of animal control, people
are always taking shots at you.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is: What kind of music?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously all the great classical masters are out. Squirrels
might well benefit from the ``Mozart effect,'' figure out how to
release the attic stairs and take over the entire house.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we won't be tuning in to Alvin and the Chipmunks,
either. That would likely bring the entire neighborhood of furry
rodents out to see their ``brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Country music would be the easiest choice, of course, as it
dominates the airwaves in Texas. Still, I can see problems with
that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ken down the street drives a pickup truck and, given enough
country music, those squirrels would be giving it the eye, I'm
sure. Then there is always the chance the music would only depress
them, making them misty-eyed about lost squirrel girlfriends,
hunting dogs they have known and those nuts that were stolen by
their best squirrel friends.
</P>
<P>
   No, country music is out.
</P>
<P>
   Rock and rap might work. After all it was rock that drove
Noriega out from his hiding place. Selections from the Animals, the
Yardbirds and the Monkees might just do the trick. It would be a
regular zoo in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   I'm always tempted by the Temptations, but, before you know it,
those squirrels would be dancing in unison and my house would be
nothing but a ball, ball, ball, ball of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   (And that's what my home is today. Hey, hey.)
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking that the answer may be radio that has no music at
all: That's right, talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   I know that some animal lovers may think I've gone too far,
here, but desperation is creeping in. Desperation, of course, is
what talk radio is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it the squirrels would be thinking that everyone
and everything was out to get them, that the world was going to
hell in a handbasket.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking for effect I could get a few toy helicopters, paint
them black and stick them in the attic. You talk about paranoid
squirrels. Maybe I'd even add some toy soldiers with the U.N. logo
on their helmets. The squirrels wouldn't be sleeping at night.
</P>
<P>
   A few months of talk radio and those squirrels would be
disgusted, ready to pack up and move to Australia or Austria,
taking their upside-down American flag with them.
</P>
<P>
   Fine with me. My motto has always been: Love it or leave it.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
