<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet SCIHEALTH 1019 -- More children are bringing pre-packaged
lunches to school and going for grab-and-go snacks after school
than ever before. For the kids, the attraction is fun foods in fun
packages. For parents, it's convenience. But for nutritionists, the
trend is a measured concern. (Lore, Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 3-column color photo of a girl
preparing her lunch.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: LUNCH TIPS -- Some quick ideas for nutritious lunches.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SILENT KILLER -- Many places in your home can be the souce
of carbon monoxide, a silent killer. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 2-column B&AMP;W graphic of a home
and sources of carbon Monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FLU PREVENTION -- A new drug arrives just in time for the
flu season. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: OUTDOOR EXERCISE -- As the days get shorter, more outdoor
exercise will take place in semi-darkness. Here are some things to
keep in mind. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH &AMP; MEDIA -- Health books and Internet sites on breast
cancer. (Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes three 6-pica color
photos of book jackets and one 6-pica color illustration of a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ This column will not move today.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-CENTURY _ Our Century in the Arts series continues
with a look at the past 100 years of architecture. Call this ``To
the suburbs and back,'' or ``From Levittown to lofts.'' We examine
the growth of the suburbs and their affect on cities; modernism's
effect on surburban residential architecture; sprawl, new urbanism,
edge cities and the rebirth of city living. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 75. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-FUTURE _ No one has a crystal ball to show us what
our architectural environment will look like in the next century,
but chances are it will be designed differently. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-TIMELINE _ Timeline to main story on architecture
during the last 100 years. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   COALMINING-NOVELIST _ It takes nerve to take on the coal
companies in the small towns of West Virginia. A rather unlikely
looking David has emerged: Denise Giardina, an author, college
professor and Episcopal preacher, is running as independent
candidate for governor. She doesn't really expect to win, but she
hopes to draw attention to the razing of this Southern town's
landscape, which in some places is beginning to look like a lunar
landscape thanks to Big Coal's latest technique, called
``mountaintop removal,'' which is as bad as it sounds. ``Storming
Heaven,'' her first coal-mining novel, is required reading for
incoming freshmen at a couple of Georgia universities and TNT has
just signed on to make a John Frankenheimer film of it. (Weaver,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 60.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   CRABBERS _ NORTH BEACH, Md. _ America's blue crab industry,
which hugs the Southern coastline from Maryland to Texas, is
threatened by imported crabs from Asia. This has caused
consternation around the Chesapeake Bay, where crabs have long been
the staple for watermen and packing houses. (Dart, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Monday in (a) national, (l) lifestyle and (f)
business categories.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SUNDAY
</P>
