<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, October 23 and Sunday,
October 24, 1999 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ More than a year ago, I used
this space to solicit ideas from readers on how to get squirrels
out of an attic. I received numerous nice replies, most of them
ending with a phrase which, roughly translated, meant, ``lots of
luck, buddy.'' (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Jeff Nesmith is the only
Pulitzer prize-winning journalist I know who will overnight a coop
of laying hens to bail out a friend. He also has written a
wonderful new book, ``No Higher Honor.'' (Jim Minter is a former
editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ A profile of Damienne Grismer, a
nun who was first attracted to service because of the community it
brings. Young women have gained many more opportunities to serve
without joining a convent, she says. ``What they have lost _ though
I'm not sure they'll recognize it as a loss _ is the picture of a
large group of people committed to service. That image is from the
past.'' But that spirit is very much present in Sister Damienne
Grismer. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Jean Shepherd helped to rear me during a couple
of pivotal years in my early adolescence, but don't blame him for
the outcome. He didn't know he was implicated. Shepherd died a few
days ago, long since replaced as a tutor to today's adolescents by
MTV. Their loss. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ ZURICH, Switzerland _ The other day my wife
and I zipped through portions of this little country. Armed with a
SwissRail ticket that allows unlimited transportation on trains,
boats, buses and trams, it wasn't so much a case of ``If It's
Tuesday, It Must Be Belgium''; it was more like ``If It's 1 p.m.,
It Must Be Interlaken.'' (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox
News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ BERLIN _ It has been noted that a third of the
world's construction cranes are now at work in Shanghai. If that's
so, Berlin must be running a close second as the Germans strive to
restore some stately Prussian grandeur to their reclaimed capital,
along with a fresh topping of high-tech gloss. (Andy Glass is a
columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
