<HEADLINE>
ROSALIE HEARST, PHILANTHROPIST AND COMMUNITY LEADER, DEAD AT 84. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM SPRINGS, Calif. _ Rosalie Hearst, prominent Palm Springs
community leader, philanthropist and ``den mother'' of the Hearst
Foundation's U.S. Senate Youth Program, died Friday at her home
here.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hearst, 84 years old, died of circulatory ailments,
according to Gladys Hundley, her long-time assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hearst, who was a resident of the Las Palmas area of Palm
Springs since 1962, was the widow of George R. Hearst, the oldest
of the five sons of William Randolph Hearst. Her step-son, George
Randolph Hearst Jr., of Paso Robles, Calif., is chairman of the
board of The Hearst Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hearst devoted much of her time to the U.S. Senate Youth
Program, founded in 1962 by the William Randolph Hearst Foundation
and created by an act of Congress. Each year, the program brings
104 high school student leaders _ two from each state and the
District of Columbia and U.S. military schools in Asia and Europe _
to Washington, D.C., for an intense week of immersion in government
and focus on public issues.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni of the program include Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, Mack
McLarty, President Clinton's first White House chief of staff, and
Franklin Raines, former director of the Office of Management and
Budget and now CEO of the Federal National Mortgage Corp. (Fannie
Mae.)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hearst was affectionately known as ``Mom'' because of her
role as ``den mother'' for the students during their week in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When the delegates arrived each year in Washington to attend the
program, they were greeted individually at their hotel by Mrs.
Hearst. With the student standing by, she would make a long
distance telephone call to the delegate's parents to let them know
that their son or daughter had arrived safely. She would then turn
the phone over to the delegate for a chat with the homefront.
</P>
<P>
   When former delegates began sending her Christmas letters and
telling about their lives as college students or working adults,
Mrs. Hearst began compiling a newsletter, known as ``Mom's
Christmas Newsletter,'' based on those alumni letters.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph A. Hearst, Mrs. Hearst's brother-in-law, former
chairman of The Hearst Corporation and president of the William
Randolph Hearst Foundation, said, ``Rosalie was known as a very
special and gracious person, a genuine lady who inspired affection
from all who knew and worked with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her strong interest in these high school delegates made her
beloved among the program's 3,900 alumni. She will be deeply missed
by all of us in the family of my late brother and by her adopted
`family' at the Senate Youth Program.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank A. Bennack, Jr., president and chief executive officer of
The Hearst Corporation and a director of the Hearst Foundation,
also cited her work for the Senate Youth Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her vivacity and charm will be long remembered,'' Bennack
said, ``along with the legacy she has left from her valuable
contributions to this important program for the nation's future
achievers. It was an obvious source of joy and inspiration to her
and, therefore, to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosalie May Wynn was born in Oklahoma City, the daughter of
Audell Clary and Ora Wynn, and attended the University of
California at Los Angeles where she studied psychology. During
World War II, she coordinated volunteer services at Dibble General
Hospital, Palo Alto, Calif. After the war she worked in the same
capacity at Sawtelle Veteran's Hospital in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Her late husband held various executive assignments in the
Hearst organization _ including the post of publisher of the San
Francisco Examiner at the age of 25. Mr. Hearst was a diabetic and,
after they were married in 1960, the couple committed themselves to
learning everything they could about the disease and became
informal counselors to help other diabetics cope.
</P>
<P>
   When Mr. Hearst died in 1972 at age 68, Rosalie Hearst founded
the George Randolph Hearst Memorial Foundation for Diabetes
Education and became its first president. She was a former director
of the Joslin Diabetes Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hearst was a well-known leader in the Palm Springs
community because of her involvement in a wide range of charitable
and civic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   She served as a director of the Warner Guidance Center for
Emotionally Disturbed Children, the Palm Springs Youth Center,
Friends of the College of the Desert Cultural Center and the
Pathfinders Boys and Girls Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   She was a founding member of the Assistance League of the Desert
Area, an organization dedicated to community service.
</P>
<P>
   During her long career in philanthropy, Mrs. Hearst was honored
by the Palm Springs Senior Center; the Palm Springs Stroke Activity
Center, the Palm Springs Youth Center; Palm Springs Desert
Charities; the City of Hope; the American Health Assistance
Foundation; Northwood University of Midland, Mich., the Paralyzed
Veterans of America and the World Opportunities International Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her step-son, Mrs. Hearst is survived by a
step-daughter, Phoebe Hearst Cooke, of Woodside, Calif. Mrs. Hearst
was preceded in death by her parents, her husband, a brother and a
sister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
