<HEADLINE>
IN ELECTRONIC AGE, STUDENTS STILL CHERISH CARE PACKAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The atmosphere at Skidmore College's
Case Center one recent afternoon borders on frenetic as students
hurriedly check their mailboxes or browse at a vendor's jewelry
display, but for Emily Warner, a single brown package dispels the
drone and clatter.
</P>
<P>
   Warner _ through a care package she's just received _ is
communing with her parents, Dr. Neal and Diane Warner.
</P>
<P>
   If they could just see her face.
</P>
<P>
   From the campus post office at Skidmore, Warner, like a squirrel
with a fall acorn, whisks the brown box to a nearby ledge and
slowly unwraps its contents.
</P>
<P>
   It is show and tell. First, an orange plastic pumpkin light.
``You stick it on the window and you put the batteries in and it
lights up.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, those marshmallow puffs, normally bright yellow Easter
chicks, refashioned as bright orange pumpkins. Disgustingly sweet,
but irresistible. ``My best friend and I share them all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Cheez-Its. ``My favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner begins, and ends, this unveiling with the same few
sentences. ``I love my mom. My mom is the best. I love my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age of electronic mail and cellular phones, technology
cannot displace the powerful message of the college care package.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wonderful,'' said Skidmore senior Sarah Kottmeier,
who, on the same afternoon that Warner got her package, received a
birthday card from her best friend's mom. ``Nothing is better than
care packages. I think it takes more effort than e-mail. It makes
me realize that people are thinking of me.''
</P>
<P>
   A certain amount of homesickness is built into college life, but
its effects are not general. A few, rare students become so
homesick that they become physically ill, but most in fact ride out
the bouts, alleviated once students make a few friends and become
involved in campus life, said Anita Steigerwald, the dean for
first-year students at Skidmore College, an independent liberal
arts school of 2,200 students in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general variety of homesickness is really kind of waiting
it out and getting involved in campus life to whatever extent they
can, because sitting around in the residence hall room and pining
away for friends who aren't with you or family members who aren't
with you really doesn't help,'' Steigerwald said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations between parents, students and the dean, counselors
and peer resident assistants can help those pained by being away
from home.
</P>
<P>
   Like most colleges, Skidmore holds a family weekend in October:
Besides taking advantage of the foliage season, the weekend is
well-timed with the students' transition from home to school.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``Those care packages help a lot,'' Steigerwald said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, a junior studying education and Spanish, had not been
home to Newtown, Conn., since leaving for Skidmore in September.
Caught up in a whirl of fall semester activity, Warner said she was
homesick only in those first September days.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother had hinted that a package might or might not arrive,
adding just enough uncertainty to heighten the surprise, Emily
Warner said. She recognized the earmarks: the Halloween package
most likely was her mother's in concept, but she saw her father _
including the clear Christmas lights, with small orange
jack-o'-lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   The family communicates by e-mail, phone and letters, and
squeezes in a visit about every six weeks. But the college treasure
amounts to the brown parcel, bubble wrap and the box of Cheez-Its.
</P>
<P>
   ``A package in the mail is something more tangible from home.
This is a good break from words on a computer screen, or a voice on
the phone, or words on a page.''
</P>
<P>
   Kottmeier, the senior who read her birthday card as if she'd won
a sweepstakes, described the reason why care packages in 1999 are
just that. ``It takes more effort to drop it in the mailbox, or to
pack a package.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
