<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-DEAD-HNS &LR;      10-22 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DEAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BRINGING OUT THE DEAD' IS ALIVE, ENTERTAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bringing Out the Dead'' is what you might get if you took a
cast-iron pot, tossed in ``Taxi Driver,'' buzzy rock songs and an
especially jokey episode of ``ER,'' then stirred it with a
jackhammer.
</P>
<P>
   The result would be quite a stew. It also would bear the
inimitable hand of Martin Scorsese, whose febrile camerawork gives
the film a restless, just-sprung energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing Out the Dead'' isn't always coherent and is nowhere
near the director's best film, but at least it's entertaining and
it's a dervish-whirl away from his most recent movie, the beautiful
but static ``Kundun.'' That one sat there, looking gorgeous. This
one moves.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Joe Connelly's novel, ``Bringing Out the Dead'' offers
us the burnt-out ruminations of one Frank Pierce, a wee-hours
paramedic who twirls around New York in an ambulance, looking for
meaning. In exhausted narration, Frank tells us he hasn't saved a
life in months. He's wiped out. He drinks. He's chronically late
for work and keeps begging his boss to fire him (``Next time I see
you, I'll fire you I promise'').
</P>
<P>
   And to top it all off, he's started seeing ghosts. He's haunted
by one in particular: Rose, a homeless, 18-year-old asthmatic who
died on the street and now seems to lurk on every corner. ``She had
come to bear witness for all of them _ all that had been lost,'' he
says, and as the camera dwells on his milky, bloodless face, it's
clear that no one's more lost than Frank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing Out the Dead'' follows Frank over the course of a
weekend, during which he meets a cavalcade of ghastly urbanites.
(Credit Scorsese for setting the action in the early '90s, when
crime had reached its mythic worst; had he bumped it up to 1999, he
might have made a film about jaywalkers.) Most of them are
banged-up but benevolent souls junkies, smelly drunks, squatters
who weave in and out of Frank's world with the concise idiosyncrasy
of sitcom characters.
</P>
<P>
   The film is chockablock with extraordinary supporting
performances: Cliff Curtis as a honey-tongued drug dealer, salsa
crooner Marc Anthony as a dreadlocked, pop-eyed street creature,
Tom Sizemore as a chillingly off-kilter medic. John Goodman has a
brief, hale role as one of Frank's partners, but it's the
ever-more-wonderful Ving Rhames as an evangelizing, womanizing
paramedic who steals the show. Few scenes are as marvelously
out-there as the bit in which Rhames ``resurrects'' an OD'd club
crawler.
</P>
<P>
   The weak point in the cast is Patricia Arquette (Cage's wife),
who plays Frank's hesitant love interest the daughter of a
heart-attack victim in an unwavering monotone. If Arquette is
capable of expressing something other than terminal boredom, she
ought to start now. As for Cage, he makes a welcome and mostly
successful escape from the idiotic action vehicles he's been
slumming around in lately, bringing sweetness, crazy energy and
pale-cheeked earnestness to the plight of a man in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   When Frank and his partners cruise a corner of hookers, you
can't help but recall Robert De Niro nosing his cab past Jodie
Foster in ``Taxi Driver.'' To be sure, Scorsese has covered this
ground before the isolation, the urban nocturne, even the insomnia.
And he's culled comedy from New York before, in ``After Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Bringing Out the Dead'' he aims a little higher, trying
to find life in death and metaphysics in the manic spin of an
ambulance's nightly tour. He doesn't always find it. But it's fun
watching him try.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-LIMEY-HNS     10-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LIMEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SODERBERGH TOYS WITH FILM NOIR IN `THE LIMEY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Soderbergh is an adamantly odd duck. Like David Lynch, he
seems bored with the usual way of telling a story _ once upon a
time, blah, blah, blah _ and challenges the most basic narrative
assumptions of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   In his world, movies begin at their endings. Time is stilted,
jerky, likely to lurch forward or fall back at any moment. Dialogue
springs from closed mouths and motionless faces. Characters flash
forward to imagined conversations, flash back to fractured
memories, then speak at the shifting juncture of both.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh is best known for his first movie (``sex, lies, and
videotape'') and his last one (``Out of Sight''), but neither is as
dark, or as bristlingly experimental, as some of the films he made
in between. Not many folks saw the surreal ``Schizopolis,'' in
which the director played a blanched suburbanite who swaps
identities with a dentist, but believe you us _ it's a triumph of
weirdness.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed in this context, Soderbergh's newest film _ ``The
Limey,'' is both a return to experimental territory and an exercise
in creative moderation. As non-linear as it is, this small, crafty
crime tale never seems indulgent; with an 88-minute running time
and a staccato script that packs potent asymmetry into a few small
scenes, the movie has the blackness and economy of classic film
noir.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Limey'' features the latest in a long string of comebacks
for Terence Stamp, who began his career as the ethereally beautiful
star of 1962's ``Billy Budd'' and made a string of films before
fading into relative obscurity (and an Indian ashram) in the 1970s.
Of late he's popped up in an eclectic assortment of movies _ as a
transsexual in ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the
Desert,'' as Chancellor Valorum in ``Star Wars _ Episode I: The
Phantom Menace'' and as a slippery New Age guru in ``Bowfinger.''
But none of these roles has plumbed the latent danger at the core
of the man, the thrilling sense that he's stuffed with plastique
and might explode at any moment. When he does, duck.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Limey,'' Stamp plays the titular Wilson, a career
criminal whose daughter, Jenny, was killed in a car crash along a
serpentine California road. He believes she was murdered. So after
nine years in an English prison, Wilson brings his ire and his
Cockney rhyming slang to the West Coast, where he looks up a pair
of Jenny's old friends (Lesley Ann Warren and Luis Guzman, in two
affable character bits) and sniffs out her record-producing
boyfriend, a superficial snake of a man named Terry Valentine
(Peter Fonda, putting a Lemon Joy gloss on evil).
</P>
<P>
   Valentine has bad friends with bad acquaintances who do bad
things involving heroin and corrupt narcs and large muscular men in
warehouses. Included among such lowlifes are Joe Dallesandro, nee
Andy Warhol's nude hunk, as a dim hit man, Nicky Katt as a cocky
hit man and Barry Newman (``Bowfinger'') as the hit men's venal
contact in Valentine's house. The details of their wicked doings
are never quite made clear, but Wilson makes short work of the
business and winds up terrorizing all involved.
</P>
<P>
   It's a testament to Stamp's controlled fury _ and the crazy
paternal love he's able to project _ that when Wilson turns
murderous, he doesn't lose an ounce of sympathy. Or credibility:
There's no question that this small, wisp-haired man in white socks
and highwaters is capable of kicking major arse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell him. Tell him I'm coming. Tell him I'm (bleeping)
coming,'' he says, after putting away a few thick goons stupid
enough to call him ``pop.'' That's the gist of the film right there
_ in Wilson's bloody, righteous pragmatism, which harks back to
early Eastwood at his most taciturn. He's a man on a tragic
mission.
</P>
<P>
   That ``The Limey'' ultimately backs away from tragedy detracts,
a touch, from its effectiveness. Wilson is never made to reap what
he's sown. But the film is less a morality tale than a character
study, and Stamp's furiously grieving papa is one of the more
interesting incendiaries to spark the screen this year.
</P>
<P>
   He's helped by Soderbergh's direction, which works a cool visual
witchery on Lem Dobbs' pungent script. Incorporating flashbacks,
flashforwards, repetition, clips from an old Stamp film (``Poor
Cow,'' 1967), handheld camerawork and disjunctive editing
techniques that weave exterior and interior dialogue, the film
manages to convey the dreamlike quest of a man from another world.
The result is more disorienting and effective than all the
pumped-up, faux-nihilistic theatrics of the hugely overrated
``Fight Club''; it's amazing what a little thematic cohesion will
do for a movie. (That, and a good score: Cliff Martinez's spooky
minimalism is worth a thousand drum machines.)
</P>
<P>
   If, in the end, ``The Limey'' doesn't quite satisfy, at least
this dusky portrait of revenge lingers like a London fog. Any
nightmare would.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BESTMAN-H     10-22 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BESTMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEST MAN' IS HANDSOME BUT INNOCUOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Best Man,'' by first-time writer/director Malcolm D. Lee,
is as innocuous as the love songs on its soundtrack, and as comely
as the members of its nimble ensemble, but the movie poster reads:
``The flower arrangements have all been ordered. The sleeping
arrangements are still being worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Things never get as ribald or as complicated as that, though.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is comfortable with the convention of the wedding surprise,
contributing his own auspicious hook in the form of a juicy
semi-autobiographical novel by the best man, but never maximizing
the screwball potential.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah herself, as Oprah, has picked the book by best man Harper
Stewart (played by fetching Taye Diggs) before it officially goes
to press. The book is an E. Lynn Harris-y affair-a-thon, and the
manuscript makes its way from Washington, D.C., to New York just in
time for Harper's arrival for the wedding of Lance and Mia (Morris
Chestnut and Monica Calhoun). Jordan (Nia Long) gave the paperback
to Murch (Harold Perrineau Jr.), who shared it with Quentin
(Terrence Howard), and before long the only member of the wedding
who hasn't read it is the groom. And he stands to be the most
offended because Harper wrote ``Unfinished Business'' using his
college buddies and their sex lives as mannequins for his
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there's something in the book that promises to give
the God-fearing Lance, now in the National Football League, a case
of the Warren Moons. (Chestnut is commandingly reincarnated after
the ``Boyz N the Hood'' drive-by that took the life of his aspiring
football player.)
</P>
<P>
   Lee exhibits a knack for disclosing what men want. In the film's
best scene, the four male friends play cards and exhale about the
differences between men and women. It's a keenly written,
improvisatory scene among four engagingly dissimilar actors _ with
the seductively insinuating, Dexter Gordon-looking Howard doing the
most surprising damage _ that feels too weighty and raw to be in a
movie this frothy. (When's the last time you saw a group of
brothers sitting around a movie just talking about sex?)
</P>
<P>
   That scene, along with a few others in which the too-subdued
Diggs and Long have new adventures in chemistry, seems to set up a
demystification of The Booty Myth, lifting it to more refined air.
</P>
<P>
   But, ultimately, Lee suspects he's damned either way. So, he
self-consciously plays the film down the crowd-pleasing middle,
sneaking in some fine Buppie jokes, including Shelby (Melissa De
Sousa), Murch's ``bougie-monster'' (bourgeois African-American)
girlfriend who address Harper as ``Richard Wrong-Langston Snooze.''
</P>
<P>
   But the men never really communicate with their women, none of
whom is written as very deep, just very successful and deeply
needy, meaning the exuberant Long is shortchanged again. But
there's just enough incongruous calm behind Calhoun's passive
demeanor _ her character's engaged to a man who's in love with her
because he thinks he's the only guy she's been with _ that you can
catch that otherwise absent glint of Terry McMillan crazy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
