A5063 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-ATM-BALLOT-HNS &LR;      10-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATM-BALLOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS CHIP IN TO THWART INITIATIVE ON ATM FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RYAN KIM  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Banks have raised nearly $400,000 in an effort
to persuade San Francisco voters to defeat a city ballot measure
that would ban surcharges on automated teller machines, or ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for ATM Choice, made up largely of banks, reported
$379,078 in contributions for the campaign against Proposition F,
with about two-thirds donated in the last month, according to
campaign finance reports filed Thursday with the San Francisco
Ethics Commission. The municipal election is Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The total included $100,000 contributions each from the Bank of
America, which is based in Charlotte, N.C., and the San
Francisco-based Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Committee to End Extra ATM Fees has raised
$14,292. The largest recent donation _ $4,750 _ came from the
California Public Interest Research Group, which is leading the
fight against the surcharge fees that have become common at banks
throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition F would eliminate surcharges that are levied by
banks when non-customers use their ATMs. The fees, about $1.50 per
transaction, are in addition to the $1 to $2 access fees that are
paid to a customer's home bank for every transaction at another
bank's ATM.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the fund-raising by the banks indicate they are
taking the campaign seriously for fear it may embolden other cities
to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that if this is approved, it will spread like
wildfire and that is what strikes fear in the hearts of Bank of
America and Wells Fargo,'' said Jon Golinger, a spokesman for the
California Public Interest Research Group, a consumer organization.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barnes, campaign manager for the No on F Campaign, said
opponents of the measure have to raise more money because they have
a more difficult task of educating voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a simple populist measure and we have to explain why
that won't work,'' Barnes said. ``We needed to spend money to make
sure people are aware of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that even if the proposition were approved, it would not
affect most of the banks in San Francisco that are federally
chartered because they would be exempt from local laws. But to
press that issue, the banks would have to file a lawsuit against
the city, said Barnes, which eventually would require taxpayer
money to defend.
</P>
<P>
   Golinger, however, said he was confident Proposition F would
survive a legal challenge. And he took issue with Barnes'
educational campaign, saying it is aimed more at confusing voters
than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the ballot initiative have spent $243,384 to date,
mostly on targeted mailers and advertising in neighborhood and
ethnic newspapers. The Committee to End Extra ATM Fees plans to
produce an information sheet which supporters expect to deliver by
hand to voters before the election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
