</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RX FOR Y2K: GO INTO HIDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: What if you haven't been keeping up to date
with Windows 95 Y2K updates? I went to Microsoft's site to see what
was available, and there was quite a long list. Do I need to
install all of them?
</P>
<P>
   _ Millennium Bugged
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BUGGED: Don't you have enough to worry about without all
this Y2K mess? You don't make enough money, you're getting older,
you're not living up to your potential, and you have the fashion
sense of Andy Kaufman. At least that's what Momma Bombay keeps
telling me. So how much worse could things get if you do absolutely
nothing to prepare for 2000?
</P>
<P>
   It's not like you're an air-traffic controller. You might have a
little trouble balancing your checkbook _ as if that's anything new
_ but you won't be steering any 767s. Relax. All versions of
Windows 95 and 98 are 2000-compliant, meaning they won't think 2000
is really 1900 and refuse to let you play Quake III because you
haven't been born yet.
</P>
<P>
   True, since the first release of Windows 95, there have been
about a jillion service packs (Microsoft-ese for ``bug fixes'').
That's understandable. There are tens of millions of lines of
computer code in Windows, and bugs happen. Who knows? Maybe the
cafeteria was out of Jolt cola the day they wrote line 4,837,382.
At least Microsoft is good about making patches easily available.
Trouble is, you have to keep up with them, or you get way behind
way fast.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to avoid the hassle of catching up piecemeal, go
plunk down 75 bucks for Windows 98 Second Edition. After
installation, the Windows Update feature can take you directly to
an upgrade download center, where a very curious program will delve
deep into your computer's darkest recesses to see what else you
might need.
</P>
<P>
   Bet you thought you were done. Not by a long shot. Windows is
the least of your worries. The real problems are likely to come
from your older applications _ word processors, checkbook programs,
Reader Rabbit, whatever _ and the startup chip on your computer's
motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   Go to 
download.microsoft.com/download/win2000pro/Install/2.0/WIN98/EN-US/y
2k.exe to start downloading Microsoft's Y2K Product Analyzer, or
just poke around their download center until you find it. Running
it tells you if Windows and your Microsoft stuff are compliant. The
report has hyperlinks to technical help.
</P>
<P>
   If everything checks out, you still need to examine your other
apps and that chip, called the BIOS (don't ask _ geeks just like
acronyms). Get the 2000 Toolbox from www.mcafee.com. It's a
try-before-you-buy download, which seems pretty silly, since after
the first time you try it you won't need to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these programs will fix all potential problems, but
at least they'll point them out for you. If you've got BIOS
trouble, go to your manufacturer's site and see if it has an update
to fix the chip. If not, you'll need to find a software utility
that will interpret what your BIOS thinks at boot time into
something that will work after Dec. 31. Try cruising shareware
sites like www.shareware.com or maybe www.hotfiles.com and do a
search for ``Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   Or do what I intend to do: Hide in a cave without electricity or
running water until all the Y2K consultants find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay thinks the Luddites didn't go nearly far
enough and probably should have pounded the people who designed the
machines into tiny bits, too. Reach him by carrier pigeon or at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is editorial systems manager for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
