<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-STRAIGHT-     10-22 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-STRAIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRAIGHT STORY' IS BATHED IN TOUCHING REALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Lost Highway'' of David Lynch's last film was a nebulous
strip of Twilight Zone that contorted time into a nightmarish ball
of confusion. One man became another without so much as a narrative
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lynch takes to a lost highway of his own, telling a G-rated
story about a man who drives his 1966 John Deere riding mower from
Iowa to Wisconsin to bring his ailing, estranged brother his love.
Anyone looking for a sign that Doomsday is nigh won't find it in
the David Lynch-directed, Walt Disney-produced ``The Straight
Story,'' a momentously, shockingly moving fit of shape-shifting by
a filmmaker grown tired of the macabre.
</P>
<P>
   Another director in Lynch's position, a fiercely idiosyncratic
storyteller struggling to surmount his thorough lack of commercial
instinct, would have wrung the true tale of Alvin Straight for
melodrama. In Lynch's hands, it's a beguiling case of a man buying
into something larger than his demons. The film is so simple,
straightforwardly American and unwavering in its trajectory that it
seems watched over as opposed to directed, but Lynch's traceless
touch demonstrates a newfound faith in emotional truth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``The Straight Story'' is a David Lynch film in all the
ways that count. The apocalyptic conflagrations, Grand Guignol
bloodbaths and lurid, lewd, erotic freak shows from ``Blue
Velvet,'' ``Wild at Heart'' and ``Fire Walk with Me'' may be gone,
but the moment a corpulent, sunbathing neighbor misses the crashing
thud next door because she ran inside to grab a couple of Hostess
Snowballs, it's obvious Lynch's Midwest eccentricities are still
intact. The crash she missed was Alvin Straight's (Richard
Farnsworth) hip giving out, landing him on the kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   Proud, stubborn and 73, Alvin's a study in deteriorating health:
bad hips force him to walk with two canes; his vision is waning,
and his smoking has left him with his doctor thinking he has
emphysema. And his mentally ill daughter Rose (marvelous Sissy
Spacek), with whom he shares his house, has to demand that he see
the doctor. When he gets a call that his brother (Harry Dean
Stanton, here briefly and poignantly) has had a stroke, she
practically insists he not go.
</P>
<P>
   Most things move slowly in ``The Straight Story.'' The rain that
falls down the side of the Straight house, the spaces between
Rose's sputtered manner of speaking, Alvin's walk, Freddie Francis'
handsome photography and co-writer/editor Mary Sweeney's fade-outs
so gorgeously protracted that shots have to be peeled off each
other. Slowest of all though is that mower and the caboose he
hitches to the back of it. Not well enough to drive a car, he
chooses this as his chariot, and when he puts his original mower
out of its misery, the John Deere replacement doesn't go much
faster. But time here isn't so important as who Alvin shares it
with.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, ``The Straight Story'' is a yellow-brick-road
movie, a journey film kissed by tiny magic. He meets handfuls of
people in his travels with comic results. The fragile beauty of
Farnsworth's performance is that he makes Alvin appear to be
listening to, learning from and entertained by every one he meets.
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth has eyes as big and chlorine-blue as swimming pools
and sometimes the wind makes them leak a little. Other times, he's
moved by the kindness of strangers and the quiet, religious
magnitude of his own pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth's mouth is collapsed, pushed in as though he's
missing a row of his teeth behind the snowy scraggliness that
passes for a beard. The role, as written by Lynch and Sweeney,
gives Alvin dignity. What the veteran actor brings is a bemusement
_ wonder at how fast the world moves around him, at how the years
have ravaged him. He may be the only actor I've ever seen whose
pensive silences and long drags of contemplative staring have made
me want to know what he's thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet a warm bed and roof over your head sure beats eating
hot dogs off a stick with a geezer driving around on a lawnmower,''
Alvin tells a young runaway (Anastasia Webb) one starry night.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's right, but camped out under the cosmos like this with
Farnsworth and a newly sentimental _ dear God, ethereal _ Lynch for
two hours is just as warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
