<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WASH-SHOPPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WASH AND WAX FOR YOUR CAR, AND A LATTE TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Once associated with wet rags, loud machinery
and air fresheners, car washes are finding their niche in the
upscale shopping market.
</P>
<P>
   The Autopia and suds shops like it in the San Francisco area are
dolling up their stores with exclusive gifts, hoping to cash in on
impulse buying as well as the ultimate goal of working people in
the '90s: convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Besides expensive gifts, car washes are increasingly offering
coffee bars and greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling at some ``gourmet'' car washes includes aroma-therapy
bath salts, massage oil, designer eyeglass cases, hand-painted
Winnie-the-Pooh boxes, hand-made birdhouses, fabric gift wrap,
eucalyptus-scented sinus pillows, soaps with names like ``Facets of
the Sea,'' and, for the man who has everything, an inflatable moose
head. Shoppers waiting for their cars can eat organic scones,
veggie burgers and focaccia, and sip lattes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to do something if you're going to be here 45
minutes,'' said Frances Wright, a nurse from Pacifica who picked up
four greeting cards at Ducky's Brushless Car Wash in Burlingame.
</P>
<P>
   Although the concept of a sloshy car wash and boutique-style
presents seems contradictory, pop culture observer Rodney Buxton of
the University of Colorado said it makes perfect sense. In a
society that seems to value productivity and finds wasting time
anathema, this was just a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real corporate mentality. ... You feel guilty if you're
not doing something,'' Buxton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Frahm, site manager at Divisadero Touchless Car Wash in San
Francisco, which pumps out 1,500 clean cars on a busy Saturday,
said people buy on impulse.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannie McCullough, 40, would know something about that. She
takes her car for a bath every three weeks at the Touchless and
admitted she rarely makes it out without buying something for
herself or a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I come here is because it's a great car wash,''
McCullough said. ``But this is the icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it was usually the bath products that snare her. But
she also has bought pricey lip gloss for a cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to someone's house for dinner and there's
something I should bring, I'll get something for someone that they
wouldn't normally buy for themselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't it be awkward, McCullough was asked, if the friend
asked where the gift had been purchased, and she was forced to
answer, ``my car wash''?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's asked where I got it,'' McCullough said. ``But I
wouldn't relish saying it. I'd rather say I got it at some cute
boutique over on Union Street. But they carry the same things
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Shimmick, the owner of the Touchless as well as similar
trendy car washes in Berkeley and San Rafael, said she and her
husband decided to open a store at the car wash more than 10 years
ago. He was thinking ``chilly-willies, hot dogs and six-packs,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shimmick, an admitted shopper, nixed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started putting out stuff we wanted to buy ourselves,'' she
said, adding that if people need to pick up cards or gifts anyway
``they might as well do it here. People are in a crunch for time.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy has struck a chord among customers, who
invariably seem so busy that saving one more shopping trip to the
mall or the card store is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's convenience,'' said Linda Rossi of Crockett, who pulled
her Chevy into the Autopia in Walnut Creek and ate at the outdoor
cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big word in today's world,'' she said. ``What's the
easiest thing?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
