<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MITCH-HONDURAS-ART-2T     10-22 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-HONDURAS-ART-2TAKES-ADV24-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDURAS INCHES ALONG A YEAR AFTER HURRICANE MITCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: For release Sunday, Oct. 24) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PESPIRE, Honduras _ Determined to press on, 83-year-old Pedro
Castro has spent the past year clawing out of the ruin that a storm
called Mitch made of his world.
</P>
<P>
   With his grandchildren's help, Castro shoveled away the
rafters-high mud and debris that the storm left inside the house
that has always been his home.
</P>
<P>
   He put up solid brick to replace the old adobe, which had melted
like meringue in the floodwaters, then plastered the new walls
smooth and painted them a soothing white.
</P>
<P>
   He raised the hard-packed dirt floor a few feet higher and laid
terra cotta tile. He bought new glass display cases for the small
general store at the front of the house, then filled them with the
candy, school supplies and whatnots that his neighbors want.
</P>
<P>
   In putting his life back together, Castro says, he, in many
ways, made it better than it was before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was total destruction here,'' Castro says of Pespire, a
town of 15,000 in the mountains of southern Honduras that was half
destroyed by Mitch's flooding. ``But we're coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Honduras, hundreds of thousands of people like Castro
toil to recover from Mitch, a powerful hurricane that formed in the
Caribbean late last October.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeping across Central America as a weakening tropical storm,
Mitch killed as many as 10,000 people in Honduras, Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Costa Rica, and left hundreds of thousands
homeless. In Honduras, the country hit hardest by the storm,
officials claim that nearly 6,000 people lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Now, despite stubborn obstacles, Honduras seems on the mend. A
fresh coat of green vegetation covers the raw scars of Mitch's
mudslides in the central mountains. Thousands of new houses, most
of them built with the help of foreign church groups and aid
organizations, dot neighborhoods across the country. Bananas and
other crops have been replanted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
25,000 REMAIN IN SHELTERS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But 25,000 Hondurans made homeless by Mitch remain in shelters.
Many people have left the country to seek work in the United
States, Costa Rica and elsewhere. Despite extensive work, the
country's principal highways remain in precarious shape. Many
smaller roads and bridges have not been repaired.
</P>
<P>
   A new round of flooding and mudslides that began in late summer
has set back the rebuilding and erased some repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, amid the often sluggish and sometimes helter-skelter
reconstruction effort, many Hondurans and their foreign benefactors
hope to remake _ rather than merely restore _ the nation that Mitch
unhinged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see Mitch as a disaster but also as an opportunity,''
says Victor Meza, director of a think tank in the Honduran capital
of Tegucigalpa that is devoted to social and political issues. ``We
could see it as a chance to make a better country: less poor, less
corrupt, more democratic, more tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to only rebuild the country physically,'' Meza
says, ``but also culturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say such change will be decades in the making, if it
comes at all. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Nevertheless, the effort has received support from
international donors, such as the United States, Canada, the
European Community and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   At a May meeting in Stockholm, Sweden, lenders and
representatives of the Central American countries hit by Mitch
declared their intentions to re-engineer societies and governments
that have long been considered corrupt and rigid.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for their massive economic help _ some $2.7 billion
to Honduras in the coming years and about $9 billion to the region
as a whole _ donors are pressing demands for crackdowns on
corruption, respect for human rights, rehabilitation of the
environment and the reform of political systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Stockholm agreement reflects an international desire that
``this significant flow of outside resources would facilitate the
process of strengthening the voice of local government and civil
society, to strengthen democracy at the grass roots,'' says Frank
Almaguer, the recently arrived U.S. ambassador to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Private aid agencies are working with local governments and
civic groups to provide houses, schools and services to places
pummeled by Mitch. In doing so, proponents say, the aid is
strengthening the ability of communities to determine their own
futures. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Honduras was spared the bloody civil wars suffered in recent
decades by Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala. But political
power long has been concentrated in a national government that too
often was repressive or unresponsive to the needs of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of U.S. economic aid and increased
industrialization, the country remains the third poorest in the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ENVIRONMENTAL PRESSURES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exploding population, which is doubling every 20 years, has
put intense pressure on the environment. Deforestation and other
environmental problems that worsened the flooding and mudslides
caused by Mitch have only begun to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to make decisions,'' says Mario Rietti, a
Honduran businessman who helped found the local chapter of
Transparency International, an anti-corruption group. ``The great
fear is that there is not a vision of sustainable development.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, only a fraction of the money pledged at Stockholm has
arrived. Much of the aid involves financial transactions _ the
trading of old debt for new, for example _ and never will translate
into cash for villages or neighborhoods where Mitch caused the most
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Some rebuilding projects have been held up in government
planning committees or put on hold because of funding snags or
concerns about fraud.
</P>
<P>
   According to Transparency International, Honduras ranks among
the most corrupt countries in the world. Many donors are releasing
funds only when they feel certain that the money won't disappear
into officials' personal bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But President Carlos Flores has insisted on accountability,
Honduran government officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been known as a banana republic,'' says Moises Starkman,
the Cabinet minister in charge of coordinating international
assistance. ``We have not had a very positive image. Now we are
trying to clean it up with the handling of Mitch aid.''
</P>
<P>
   More than image is at stake. The world has been racked by
disaster in the year since Mitch. Earthquakes have shaken Colombia,
Turkey, Greece and Taiwan; hurricanes have slammed the United
States; war has roiled the Balkans and Africa. There are many
competing needs for a shrinking pot of aid money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honduras isn't the only country that needs help. People know
that we have eyes upon us,'' says Glenda Gallardo, a U.S.-educated
economist who directs the agency overseeing the national
government's recovery plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that the donors want to see that the money is
being used properly,'' she says. ``We know that if they don't think
the money is being used right, or is being stolen, the funds might
stop coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreign pressure seems to be keeping corruption in check so
far. Though there have been many allegations of bill padding and
other minor frauds, no major scandals involving relief money have
erupted so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of corruption, but it is harder now to be
corrupt than 10 years ago,'' says Meza, whose think tank has
produced detailed studies of official fraud. ``People are becoming
more vigilant.''
</P>
<P>
   But safeguarding against corruption has helped slow the
reconstruction, many Honduran and foreign officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts for roads and bridges are taking longer to be
approved, as donors' accountants review them. Some midlevel
bureaucrats hesitate to make decisions that could haunt them later,
aid officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern about corruption in a certain sense is slowing
down the process, because we are all watching,'' says Zoraida Mesa,
the top U.N. official in Honduras. ``Since the amount of money
pledged was so huge, we're going to be included in decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Construction delays have contributed to the severity with which
this season's tropical rains have affected the country, officials
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers and canals that were never dredged of Mitch's silt and
debris have flooded more easily. Temporary bridges and river levees
thrown up just before the rains began have collapsed in the rising
waters. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
DEADLY FLOODS CONTINUE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people have died in the floods in recent weeks, and
thousands more have been made homeless. Tens of millions of dollars
worth of crops have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rebuilding has been slower than promised, many
Hondurans who suffered most from Mitch believe that the promised
foreign cash will simply disappear or be misused, as it often has
been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps things are happening in Tegucigalpa or San Pedro
Sula,'' says Marvin Umana, 35, the mayor of the town of Pimienta
near Honduras' Caribbean coast that was flooded earlier this month
by rain-swollen rivers. ``But help has never arrived in the smaller
towns.''
</P>
<P>
   Pimienta's farmers had replanted hundreds of acres of bananas
and other crops destroyed by Mitch after the central government
promised that improved dikes would be built. The new crops have
been ruined by the recent flooding, Umana says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came, they measured, they studied, but nothing
happened,'' the mayor says of national officials who promised to
build new dikes. ``They said they didn't have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say that they are moving as quickly as
possible, that the still-scarce financial resources and the
enormity of the rebuilding effort make it inevitable that people
will be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we want the bridges built, the rivers dredged, the
highways fixed. But it's going to take some time,'' says Gallardo,
the Honduran government planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have shelter. They have food to eat,'' she says. ``In
spite of the rainy season, we haven't had any epidemics. People
have a lot better houses than they had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Some private aid officials say that the larger remaking of
Honduran society matters more than a quick rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we have to watch for,'' says Maribel Suazo, an
official for a coalition of private aid groups in Honduras. ``Not
whether a certain bridge or road is being built, but whether real
change is taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides requiring more stringent accounting of the money spent,
many foreign donors are seeking assurances that the projects
they're funding are worthwhile and necessary.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the case in Pespire, a village of tile-roofed
houses wedged on a mountainside between a swift river and the main
highway from Tegucigalpa to the Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   About half of Pespire's houses were either destroyed or badly
damaged when the Mitch-fed Nacaome River surged dozens of feet
above its banks. About 60 townspeople were killed in the flooding,
according to the local Roman Catholic priest, and thousands were
left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding also contaminated Pespire's wells and ruined its
water pumps, further debilitating a system that hadn't worked well
for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a Swiss aid group has offered to upgrade the town's water
network. But first, the donors want the town to do its part by
forming a board that will force residents to conserve water and to
pay for what they use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PRECIOUS WATER IS WASTED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With water flowing in the pipes only a few hours each day at
best, few people in Pespire bother to pay for the service. Untold
gallons are wasted, because many leave taps untended and open to
replenish barrels and tanks when the water does come on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foreign money is only going to pay for things when there
is need,'' Antonio Guillen, a Honduran civil engineer who works as
a consultant for the Swiss aid agency, tells Mayor Antonio
Matamoros and his city council. ``They want to help, but they want
to know what they are getting into.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a national problem. We only know how to say help me,''
Guillen tells the officials. ``But that doesn't work anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials and engineers meet in the mayor's office, a
Spartan room outfitted with a large crucifix, a half dozen metal
folding chairs, a battered desk and a filing cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our town, our development,'' declares a bumper sticker slapped
on the cabinet. ``Everyone to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor belongs to the opposition Nationalist Party. For
that reason, he says, Pespire is getting less help from the central
government than other towns. Matamoros says he has had to court
foreign aid groups himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the news about the aid, you hear about it, but nothing
has arrived here,'' the 34-year-old mayor says with a
what-can-you-do smile.
</P>
<P>
   Across Pespire's sullen, tree-shaded plaza, the town's priest,
French Canadian Ivan Bouffard, doles out cash to local men and
women who are building houses for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   With 250 people on his payroll, Bouffard has become the biggest
employer in the area. He says he took on the building job because
government officials _ both at city hall and in Tegucigalpa _
failed to deliver enough help to Pespire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big task, an enormous effort,'' Bouffard says of the
government's rebuilding effort. ``But things are not arriving to
people on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BUILDING NEW HOUSES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bouffard is financing the construction of 325 small houses with
money sent by Canadian, U.S. and European aid groups and with
private donations, including those from a network of Catholic and
Lutheran congregations in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   He has hired masons and carpenters. The men and women who will
live in the dwellings work as laborers, earning wages three days a
week, working free another two as a down payment on their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bouffard has added house building to the list of his parish's
other community projects. The church runs primary and secondary
schools; sponsors workshops on health care; and provides storage
bins for grain, so farmers can wait for the best market prices to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future we see is a country which doesn't depend upon the
government for anything,'' Bouffard says as he finishes the
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Many Pespire residents say they increasingly rely upon foreign
charity and their own initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Like people elsewhere in Honduras, residents of Pespire who lost
everything in last year's floods now dress in hand-me-down clothes
sent from abroad. Men and women wear ill-fitting pants, shirts and
dresses. Children sport T-shirts boasting of vacations to Disney
World or Hilton Head that they never took, of summer camps they
never attended.
</P>
<P>
   Though volunteers from aid organizations and evangelical
churches in the United States and other countries are constructing
some houses, many Pespire residents are rebuilding their own homes
with the help of neighbors and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're recovering with our own efforts,'' says Praxedes
Contreras, a 35-year-old mother of three whose rented home near
Pespire's river bank was all but destroyed by Mitch. ``We've
learned to rely upon each other in a way I never thought we could.
We have more faith in ourselves, more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the steep hill from the priest's office on the plaza, Pedro
Castro and his neighbors keep a wary watch on the rising river.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains in the mountains to the north have been fattening
the stream for days. Tree trunks caught beneath the low bridge that
connects Pespire to farms across the river have blocked the flow.
Water several feet deep has been rushing over the center of the
bridge, cutting off people who live across the river from the town.
</P>
<P>
   As great gray thunderheads build over the low mountains, a crowd
gathers at the Pespire side of the bridge to watch young men swim
to the far bank with food supplies for their hungry families. Talk
turns to what people would do if the floods inundate the town
again.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty yards away, Pedro Castro sits on his porch and eyes the
action.
</P>
<P>
   He's not going anywhere, Castro says with a whimsical grin,
whatever the river decides to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in this house, and I'm going to die here,'' Castro
says. ``We've never seen anything like Mitch before, and we're not
going to see it again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
