<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5106 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MITCH-VILLAGE-ART-2TA     10-22 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-VILLAGE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV24-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPERS OF DIGNITY: VIDA NUEVA PLAN GOES FAR BEYOND BUILDING
HOUSES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 24) 
(Eds: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIDA NUEVA, Honduras _ A year into the recovery from its worst
natural disaster in decades, Honduras swirls with talk of a new
society that will rise from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   No idea reaches further toward that envisioned new dawn,
perhaps, than Vida Nueva, a sprawling development of bleak rows of
houses under construction outside San Pedro Sula, a no-nonsense
city near the Caribbean coast that is Honduras' economic dynamo.
</P>
<P>
   Some 4,000 homes planned for Vida Nueva will house about 500
families displaced by Hurricane Mitch's flooding last October as
well as residents of neighborhoods at risk in future disasters and
poor people who simply want to trade up from their shacks.
</P>
<P>
   Planners hope Vida Nueva, which means ``new life'' in Spanish,
does more than simply provide homes to those who need them. Vida
Nueva, they say, aims to create renewed human beings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea isn't just to build houses, but to formulate within
people the idea that they have a dignified place to live,'' says
Luis Fernando Rivera, a building contractor who serves as the Vida
Nueva Foundation's executive director. ``It's a sort of social
engineering.''
</P>
<P>
   Vida Nueva is the brainchild of San Pedro Sula Mayor Roberto
Larios, who has enlisted local businessmen and evangelical
Christian activists from the United States and Mexico for the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Larios' idea, Vida Nueva officials say, is to replace a culture
of poverty framed by joblessness, street gangs, alcoholism and
illegitimate births with a stable, God-fearing community.
</P>
<P>
   Some international donors already have expressed concerns about
using public funds on a project with such an apparent religious
purpose. And even some planners have expressed doubts about the
intended exclusion of prostitutes, alcoholics and gang members from
the community. Some who will get houses in Vida Nueva complain that
the development is too far from jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Buckman, the Honduras director of Samaritan's Purse, a
U.S.-based Christian charity that is building a quarter of Vida
Nueva's houses, says Mayor Larios ``wants to build a society that
is way above'' what residents of the community have ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larios is trying to make these people working citizens,''
Buckman says.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the mayor has contracted the services of the
Institute in Basic Life Principles, an Illinois-based organization
that applies Bible teachings to social problems. Vida Nueva's
planners say a training center operated by the institute will teach
moral values and job skills to community residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to do is transform the culture,'' says Alfredo de
Hoyos, a 40-year-old lawyer from the Mexican city of Monterrey who
is designing the institute's strategy for Vida Nueva.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sick group,'' de Hoyos says of the poor Hondurans
who will live in Vida Nueva. ``This is not a healthy society. We
have to break them of their old ways of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   As it did elsewhere in Central America, Mitch's devastation fell
hardest on San Pedro Sula's poorest. Most of the houses that were
severely damaged sat in working-class neighborhoods along the
Chamelecon River to which many residents had immigrated from
Honduras' rural highlands.
</P>
<P>
   Like many cities in the region, San Pedro Sula contends with a
wave of gang violence. Two large street gangs with the same names
as counterparts in Los Angeles _ 18th Street and Mara Salvatrucha _
battle each other in poor neighborhoods and commit crimes citywide.
</P>
<P>
   The Honduran government's human rights office claims that recent
killings of street gang members appeared to be carried out in an
organized fashion, raising the specter of death squads taking
justice into their own hands. Such killings have been common in
neighboring El Salvador, where gang members deported from the
United States have fueled a crime wave through much of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Vida Nueva's promoters intend to offer a gang- and crime-free
environment that promotes family values. Planners have designed the
community with few intersections, on the theory that gangs tend to
square off by blocks, as well as a lot of green space.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also have banned the sale of alcohol and cigarettes in
the small stores that serve people living in the community's
temporary shelters.
</P>
<P>
   In a more controversial move, Vida Nueva officials have
attempted to weed out gang members, prostitutes and drug users from
the people who will be permitted to get houses in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a sensitive question, because the foundation
can't discriminate. It's against its principles,'' Rivera says.
``But we also can't permit the project to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Boosters say that Vida Nueva is the first planned community for
poor families of its kind in Honduras .
</P>
<P>
   The $16 million project will boast electricity and a water and
sewer system that includes a treatment plant. Parks, day-care
centers, schools and community halls are planned.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those supplied by Samaritan's Purse _ a charity
run by the Rev. Billy Graham's son, Franklin _ thousands of houses
are slated to be built by Habitat for Humanity and Spanish aid
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has pledged $1.8 million for the
development's water system and shelters, where 2,000 people live
while their homes are under construction. Private foundations as
well as a 40-year loan from the Inter-American Development Bank are
supplying additional funding, Vida Nueva officials say.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The houses built by charities and aid agencies will be given to
the foundation operating Vida Nueva, which will then sell them to
families at cost. People will make down payments through community
service, Rivera says, and pay off their mortgages at a rate of
about $20 a month over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad message to give something away,'' Rivera says.
``What we need to do is recover the investment we have made.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of community planning, Vida Nueva contrasts starkly
with impoverished neighborhoods throughout Latin America, which
develop haphazardly as families squat on land or buy small lots,
then build homes as their wallets and time allow. Such
neighborhoods either wait years for electricity, water and sewer
services or never get them at all.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no other place in Honduras could either afford or
organize a project like Vida Nueva. Although San Pedro Sula and
nearby towns account for only about 20 percent of Honduras'
population of nearly 6 million people, the region produces
two-thirds of the country's economic output.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Vida Nueva is a work in progress. About a quarter of the
houses planned for the development are under construction. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The much-delayed first stage of the drinking-water system was
finally installed in September. The sewage treatment plant won't be
built for months.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand people already living on the grounds of the
project have been crowded into shelters for half a year, rather
than the several months originally envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Samaritan's Purse is working to complete its promised 1,000
houses, Buckman says, with the first 600 to be ready by the end of
the month. But other charities and agencies have not yet started to
build in their sections of the development.
</P>
<P>
   Vida Nueva's houses, though an improvement on what many people
who will live here are accustomed to, are tiny and threadbare.
Measuring only 18 feet by 12 feet, each house consists of a
closet-sized kitchen and bathroom and a single room that will serve
as bedroom and living room.
</P>
<P>
   Plans allow for an additional two rooms to be added to the back
of the houses later, as families can afford them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those aren't houses. They're rabbit hutches,'' says Antonio
Gonzalez, 51, a resident of a flood-ravaged neighborhood in San
Pedro Sula who says he can't imagine living in Vida Nueva with his
nine family members.
</P>
<P>
   The houses line up in monotonous gray rows, their walls
unpainted and their tin roofs exposed to the tropical sun. Each
family will receive a few trees to plant. Each lot has room for a
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Vida Nueva lies 18 miles outside San Pedro Sula, far from the
foreign-owned clothing assembly plants that provide jobs for many
of the people expected to live in the development. Bus rides to and
from the factories cost about a dollar each day, or about a fifth
of a daily wage.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters say they plan to develop an industrial park near the
new development to provide jobs. But only one factory exists there
now, and the once-rapid growth of San Pedro Sula's assembly-plant
sector has stagnated.
</P>
<P>
   People living in the temporary shelters complain that food sold
inside the Vida Nueva compound is more expensive than in the city.
And, they say, life has been boring and far too regimented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us moved from the country to the city in order to live
better,'' Horacio Romero, a 48-year-old father of eight, says with
a toothless grin. ``Now they are moving us back to the country
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call this new life,'' he says. ``But this doesn't seem
like living to me.''
</P>
<P>
   De Hoyos, the Mexican lawyer charged with instilling new values
in Vida Nueva's residents, says complaints are to be expected. But,
he says, the doubts will evaporate as Vida Nueva takes shape in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how this is going to fail,'' de Hoyos says. ``We
have the resources and experience to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new society we are building.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
