<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CENTAM-MITCH _ MARCOVIA, Honduras _ Maritza Espinar spent four
terrifying days clinging to the high branches of a tree last year
after Hurricane Mitch flattened her home in a village near here.
When new floods in September sent a tributary of the Choluteca
River once again rising toward the place she lived, she didn't
waste any time evacuating. Such stories are not uncommon around
this poor, mountainous nation of 5 million people. Mitch was the
worst disaster in more than a century, killing some 9,000 people
and leveling or damaging more than 50,000 homes. Most people had
hoped that by now, a year after Mitch blew ashore on Oct. 25, the
storm would be nothing more than a frightful memory. But the recent
floods are evidence that Mitch is still having an impact.
(Williams, Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-REBUILD _ MARCOVIA, Honduras _ The walls are unadorned
cement blocks, the floor is poured concrete, the roof made from
plain sheets of metal. The kitchen is a lean-to out back with a
small, smoky cooking fire. But Rita Galvez proudly sits inside the
tiny structure, holding her breath. To her, this diminutive house _
the size of a typical two-car American garage _ may as well be a
millionaire's mansion. One year after Hurricane Mitch devastated
Central America, life is getting better for thousands of the killer
storm's victims. Although new flooding has brought more misery to
many of those left homeless by Mitch, a massive rebuilding program
spearheaded by charities worldwide has made significant progress.
(Williams, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories moved Wed. Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SKEPTICISM _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexicans live in a perpetual
state of suspicion. From professional economists down to flower
venders, many believe the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party's new commitment to democracy could be a hoax. A look at the
culture of conspiracy that runs long and deep in Mexico. (Ferriss,
Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Thurs. Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CROSSBURNINGS _ SAN AUGUSTINE, Texas _ On the back roads of
rural San Augustine County, two recent cross burnings have caused
concern among people in both the black community and white
communities here. The two separate incidents, reported within two
weeks of each other, are being investigated by the San Augustine
County sheriff's deputies and the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
(Morris, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PRISONER-CAGES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Allegations of abuse of Texas
state prisoners by putting them in cages hits the airwaves Thursday
night in a Court TV segment. Prison officials respond that the
cages have been used routinely for years to secure prisoners
working on prison farms until more guards can be called in as
reinforcements. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WATER-PARASITE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _Jeffrey Rosenthal is
dead and his last dip in Lake Ida may be to blame. The 19-year-old
was riding a friend's personal watercraft on Oct. 6 when, like most
newcomers to the popular watersport, he fell off it into the waters
of Lake Ida in Delray Beach. He swam to his watercraft, mounted it
and kept cruising. Nine days later, Rosenthal was dead, his brain
so swollen it cut off its own blood supply. Despite are waiting for
results from special lab tests to determine whether a common
parasite found in most freshwater lakes in Florida caused him to
become mortally ill. (Bhatt, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-SUIT _WACO, TEXAS _ U.S. District Judge Walter Smith
ruled Friday on several issues related to Davidian civil lawsuit.
Set trial for May 15 in Waco and separated liability portion of
trial from damages portion. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SPRAWL - WASHINGTON _ The National Building Museum unveils its
``Reimagining the Suburbs: Smart Growth and Choices for Change''
exhibit. The exhibition is the second of the museum's four-part
series on alternatives to sprawl. (Schultz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
