 Friday, Oct. 22, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file or has filed the
following for Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please
call Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WAR-POWERS (Washington) _ Does the White House or
Congress have the right to send American troops into battle? That
constitutional question is argued before a federal appeals court
here as 31 House members urge the three-judge panel to let them
challenge President Clinton's authority when he ordered the bombing
of Yugoslavia. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-AMERICAN-MEMORIAL (Washington) _ A groundbreaking
ceremony is held here for the new National Japanese American
Memorial honoring those Japanese Americans who served in World War
II even as their families were confined to U.S. internment camps.
The memorial is due for completion next fall. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ There is a parallel between the
defeat of the League of Nations favored by President Woodrow Wilson
80 years ago and Bill Clinton's recent loss on the nuclear test ban
treaty. In both instances, the president was a victim of his own
stubbornness as well as the obstructionist tactics of his
Republican opponents. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday for
Sunday release.)
</P>
</TEXT>
