<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS MAY CURE WHAT AILS THE 49ERS OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Jeff Garcia sat at his locker earlier this
week, picking at a light lunch and awaiting the start of another
practice. He never saw San Francisco 49ers general manager Bill
Walsh coming until Walsh was nearly on top of him.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh took a seat on the bench and spoke to the 49ers
quarterback in a soothing tone, looking every bit like a learned
father offering advice to a son who had hit hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wanted to be a starting NFL quarterback,'' Walsh said.
``Well, now you are one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowering his voice, Walsh spoke to Garcia for the next few
minutes. Only those two will ever know the rest of that
conversation, but this much is true: Walsh couldn't have picked a
better time to give Garcia a lift.
</P>
<P>
   Since a masterful debut in a win over the Tennessee Titans on
Oct. 3, Garcia's world has shifted along with the rest of the
49ers. In the wake of a 42-20 dismantling at St. Louis and a 31-29
disappointment against Carolina, the 49ers are searching for
answers to all kinds of questions, including how to jump-start
their offense. After all, the defense has scored more touchdowns
than the offense in the last two weeks (three to two).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struggled all year to put the ball in the end zone,''
Garcia said. ``We certainly haven't done it as much as we would've
liked. But a lot of this falls on my shoulders, with my being the
quarterback. Whether it's making a throw or the right read, I have
to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a lot of weight for a backup quarterback to take on,
especially one who has been asked to fill in for a Hall-of-Fame
player like Steve Young. But this is Garcia's way. No doubt, that
willingness to take on a burden is one that made Walsh want to sign
the guy in the first place. But Garcia isn't solely responsible for
what's been troubling the 49ers offense of late.
</P>
<P>
   This team's problems include poor pass protection, an
inconsistent running game, dropped passes, turnovers and a horrid
third-down conversion rate (30.4 percent). These same issues are
largely to blame for Young's current status as a quarterback on the
verge of retirement. The past two weeks have been no different.
</P>
<P>
   Both the St. Louis Rams and the Carolina Panthers blitzed Garcia
heavily while taking advantage of double-digit leads. Against
Carolina, Garcia rarely had enough time to even look downfield
before finding himself in the midst of heavy pressure. He completed
only 22 of 45 passes in that game, leading the team to only one
offensive touchdown. Such has been the life of 49ers quarterbacks
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams have been saying, `Let's blitz the 49ers,'''
wide receiver Jerry Rice said. ``Until we prove we can get the job
done against the blitz, teams will continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be a glimmer of hope for the 49ers this week. With
the Minnesota Vikings next on the schedule, the offense will meet
what they face in practice every week _ one of the league's most
vulnerable defenses. The Vikings rank 29th in the league in total
yards allowed (362.8 per game) and 30th in pass defense (260 yards
per game). In fact, those numbers are even worse than those
surrendered by the 49ers' defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings major weakness _ and the 49ers should empathize _ is
at cornerback. Neither Kenny Wright nor Ramos McDonald has proved
to be adequate replacements for the departed Corey Fuller at left
cornerback, while right cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock is an average
player. Still, the 49ers aren't so willing to consider the Vikings
defense as porous as those numbers suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the yardage they have allowed has come between the
20-yard lines,'' 49ers offensive coordinator Marty Mornhinweg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistics don't look great but on the field it doesn't
look that bad. They're doing a good job of stopping teams in the
red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are allowing 20 points per game but Mornhinweg is
being respectful. If there is a team the 49ers will face in the
near future that could cure their offensive woes, it is Minnesota.
And the 49ers, though loathe to admit this, realize they can
capitalize on the Vikings' problems. In fact, Garcia understands
that this team must do that if it wants to steer this season in a
more positive direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone believes in this system and knows that we can
put up some points,'' Garcia said. ``We've had little mistakes that
have turned into big problems for us. We need to be better focused
and stop killing ourselves. If we can eliminate some of those
things, we'll have more success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
