<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 THIS ELECTION LOOKS LIKE `NONE OF THE ABOVE'
 (For use by New York Times News Service cients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``It looks like it's going to be a `None of the
above' election,'' said a friend, who advocates such a choice on
every ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Think of how the country would look if we had such a choice.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the White House, no one in the governor's office, no
one as mayor, no one as district attorney and no one on the Board
of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much the way it is now, but we'd make it official,
and not have to waste all that money in salaries and contracts for
the nobody friends of all the nobodies in office.
</P>
<P>
   I got to thinking. This is San Francisco. We've got all kinds of
pranksters who run around in nuns' habits. Why doesn't one of them
run as Nun of the Above?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someone should just run around in a mayor's costume.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a great town, despite the idiots who run it. Every once
in a while there's a glimmer of passion and flesh that lets you
know this is still San Francisco and not Yuptown USA.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-sweatshop demonstrators stripped naked and invaded the
grand opening of the new Old Navy store on Market Street. And the
only bargain hunters who looked up were those shocked to see people
without the words ``Old Navy'' on them.
</P>
<P>
   Does Old Navy sell anything that doesn't have the words ``Old
Navy'' on it?
</P>
<P>
   What do old Navy guys think of all those sweat shirts? Should I
get one for my father-in-law, the retired Navy captain?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the only photograph we got from Old Navy was of
the backs of some demonstrators' heads.
</P>
<P>
   We weren't buttless because we were gutless, but because the
demonstrators were much faster than those naked guys we always
shoot from behind in the Bay to Breakers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations keep right on coming. At noon on Nov. 1, the
day before the election, there will be a ``Let them eat cake''
demonstration in front of City Hall, complete with a guillotining
of the effigies of the three major candidates for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, according to someone who calls himself Pierre, Le
Marquis du Gateau, cake will be served to the homeless by
``aristocrats'' in elaborate 18th century French dress.
</P>
<P>
   Nudity is optional, except for the Emperor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A popular local band called Buddhakowski (whose name is a nice
tribute to one of our favorite religious figures and one of our
favorite Beat curmudgeons) has donated the use of a Dylanesque song
called ``Great Town'' to Tom Ammiano's write-in campaign for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great town, except for the idiots who run it,'' go the
lyrics written by Matt Langlois. ``It's a great town if you can
afford the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The song rips into lofts, the demise of nightclubs South of
Market and our mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely doing whatever we can do to get behind
Ammiano's campaign,'' says lead singer Philip Golden, who goes by
Philip Mars. ``Musicians are leaving in droves because they can't
afford to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite lyric from ``Great Town'' is: ``If you think that
something's wrong, there are the words of some old song about the
colors that have gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps worst of all, people are going away without leaving
their hearts here.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Muni took delivery of some new buses painted shocking white, and
then started painting old buses white. What's the story? Are these
meant to be canvases for graffiti artists or for advertisers? Or is
Muni looking for a new, pristine image?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, it takes some guts to send such white buses
into such dirty streets. And now when three buses are running in a
row, it looks like a school of Moby Dicks to us Ahabs who have been
waiting so long for them.
</P>
<P>
   Buses as white as white Rolls-Royces. I think I know who's
behind this.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparent Lesbianism in Beetle Actually May Be Ruse to Lure
Males, Scientists Say.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a plot from a sitcom made by Pixar, but
scientists really are saying that some female beetles of the
species Diaprepes abbreviatus fake mating to attract a male.
</P>
<P>
   Typical male cockroaches, these guys. It seems their sight is
often bad, so the only way they can tell males from females is that
females are slightly larger. Therefore two females get on top of
each other to look bigger, and the dumb males hop right on.
</P>
<P>
   I could make a lot of dumb comments right now, but I can think
of a couple of females who'll bug me if I say anything.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boot-up 'n' sniff? ``Look who's teaching your computer to
smell,'' says the cover of the November Wired magazine. The article
is about a Bay Area company with the name of DigiScents (no
kidding) that plans to take Smell-O-Vision to new heights via
computer.
</P>
<P>
   So far DigiScents can generate the smell of wood smoke, orange
peels and bananas. Hey, I can do that when I smoke ribs in the back
yard out near the garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   Our olfactory sense does seem to be in decline, but the fact is,
Americans don't really like to smell things. Besides, the computer
I'm working on right now already stinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
