<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BANKING LEGISLATION &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional and White House
negotiators hammer out a historic deal early Friday that is
expected to complete a long-sought overhaul of the nation's laws
governing financial services. The breakthrough came after Sen. Phil
Gramm and Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers reached a compromise
on the Community Reinvestment Act. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-LOBBY (Washington) _ Examining the cost of the 20-year
battle: where the money came from, and where it went. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-IMPACT (Undated) _ The impact of the bill on the financial
services industry and consumers. Who are the winners and losers?
Will it lead to more deals like 1998's Citicorp-Travelers merger.
By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-COMMUNITY How the compromise will affect the laws
affecting lending to the disadvantaged. By Richard A. Oppel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PAPON (Paris) _ Maurice Papon, the fugitive 89-year-old
war criminal, is arrested in Switzerland after fleeing France to
escape imprisonment. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Developments on Chechnya in the wake
of a lethal Russian Army attack on a market in Grozny, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-GUSMAO (Jakarta) _ Independence leader Jose Alexandre
Gusmao makes a triumphant, emotional return to East Timor. By Seth
Myans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (United Nations) _ The U.N. Security Council
is to authorize a peacekeeping force of 6,000 for Sierra Leone
today. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the various
appropriations bills. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Nashua, N.H.) _ A look at the rivalry and
maneuvering between the Gore and Bradley camps. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NH (Dateline to kum, N.H.) _ George W. Bush meets with
voters in the state, but leaves before a debate among other GOP
candidates begins. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MODEL-EGGS-FOR-SALE (Boston) _ A fashion photographer puts up
Web site advertising an auction for donor eggs from models ``to
correct your genetic flaws.'' Bids start at $15,000 and go up to
$150,000. ``Choosing eggs from beautiful women will profoundly
increase the chances of success of your children and your
children's children,'' claims the Web site. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BOOK (New York) _ How St. Martin's Press vetted J.H.
Hatfield's book about George W. Bush. The book's promotion and
distribution was suspended following reports that the author was a
convicted felon. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BOOK-MEDIA (Undated) _ How the media covered the book's
allegation that George W. Bush was once arrested on cocaine
charges. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
