<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-AIR-CONTROLLERS (Toronto) _ U.S. aviation regulators, air
traffic controllers and airline executives _ frustrated with the
inadequacies of the air traffic system _ have been taking a close
look at Canada, which three years ago took the government agency
that had run its air traffic control system for decades and sold it
to a nonprofit company. The company, Nav Canada, is using new
technology and while making some missteps has also won rave
reviews. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-WARNING (Undated) _ Waste Management Inc. confirms that
its third quarter and year-end results will be hurt by the findings
of an internal audit that is nearing completion. Its shares tumble
11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-BARNES&AMP;NOBLE (Undated) _ Amazon.com sues rival
Barnesandnoble.com, accusing its rival of copying Amazon technology
that lets shoppers make their purchases with one click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:50 p.m., stocks were higher. The Dow
Jones industrial average was up 119 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 16
points and the Nasdaq composite up 31 points. The 30-year bond
yield was priced to yield 6.36 percent. European markets were also
higher, with London up 1.42 percent and Frankfurt 2.11 percent. In
Asia, Japan's Nikkei ended down 0.5 percent, while the Hang Seng in
Hong Kong closed up 2.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ELAL-JETS (Jerusalem) _ Looking at the fierce battle between
Boeing and Airbus to win from El Al, Israel's airline, an order
valued at $400 million. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OIL (Moscow) _ BP Amoco's campaign to preserve its $571
million investment in the bankrupt Russian oil company Sidanko
suffers a harsh blow when a rival oil company buys a Sidanko
subsidiary. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
