<HEADLINE>
MANY OLD INDUSTRIAL CITIES FACE HARD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union -
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ He was wearing the black suit, the
double-breasted one. Mayor Al always wears the black,
double-breasted suit when he gets serious about something.
</P>
<P>
   Al Jurczynski is the Republican mayor of Schenectady. He's a
burly, bespectacled guy in his early 40s who used to operate a
furniture store. Mayor Al is roughly the size of a Lincoln Town
Car. The black suit makes him look a bit more like a statesman and
a bit less like a nose guard for the Jets _ a job in which he would
sustain fewer bruises, actually, than the rotten job he has now.
</P>
<P>
   This was the other night, at the Ramada on Nott Street. About
400 people were crowded into a hotel ballroom for Mayor Al's debate
with his opponent. That's Gary McCarthy, Schenectady's city council
president.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Al is the incumbent, which is to his advantage. Gary
McCarthy is a Democrat, which is to his advantage. The Democrats
hold a slight enrollment edge in Schenectady. All seven city
council members are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Al and Gary McCarthy do not enjoy a warm relationship.
Mayor Al is earnest, affable and well-intentioned. Gary McCarthy is
smart, well-intentioned and has a tongue you could use to trim a
hedge.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Mayor Al complained that Gary McCarthy
displays an annoying gift for sarcasm. In response, Gary McCarthy
complained that Mayor Al suffers from an unfortunate penchant for
portr
</P>
</TEXT>
