<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY OLD INDUSTRIAL CITIES FACE HARD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union -
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ He was wearing the black suit, the
double-breasted one. Mayor Al always wears the black,
double-breasted suit when he gets serious about something.
</P>
<P>
   Al Jurczynski is the Republican mayor of Schenectady. He's a
burly, bespectacled guy in his early 40s who used to operate a
furniture store. Mayor Al is roughly the size of a Lincoln Town
Car. The black suit makes him look a bit more like a statesman and
a bit less like a nose guard for the Jets _ a job in which he would
sustain fewer bruises, actually, than the rotten job he has now.
</P>
<P>
   This was the other night, at the Ramada on Nott Street. About
400 people were crowded into a hotel ballroom for Mayor Al's debate
with his opponent. That's Gary McCarthy, Schenectady's city council
president.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Al is the incumbent, which is to his advantage. Gary
McCarthy is a Democrat, which is to his advantage. The Democrats
hold a slight enrollment edge in Schenectady. All seven city
council members are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Al and Gary McCarthy do not enjoy a warm relationship.
Mayor Al is earnest, affable and well-intentioned. Gary McCarthy is
smart, well-intentioned and has a tongue you could use to trim a
hedge.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Mayor Al complained that Gary McCarthy
displays an annoying gift for sarcasm. In response, Gary McCarthy
complained that Mayor Al suffers from an unfortunate penchant for
portraying himself as a victim.
</P>
<P>
   Each nasty remark produced a round of spirited applause. That's
because each candidate had the good sense to stack the crowd with
supporters. Besides, everybody loves it when politicians complain
about one another's personal failings. Just look at how popular
professional wrestling is these days.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the exterior of what might seem like just another local
political campaign, though, lurked the harsh reality that this is
not just another exercise in the fun and games of the democratic
process.
</P>
<P>
   Schenectady, population 65,000, is a city in dire trouble. The
issue of which of these candidates is elected mayor on Nov. 2 is
far less crucial than the issue of what this state _ and this
country, for this matter _ plans to to do about these old,
industrial cities whose tax base is eroding, whose neighborhoods
are crumbling and whose residents are aging at a far faster rate
than the population of the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   In Schenectady, jobs have evaporated like mist on a windshield
in the morning sun. General Electric, the city's economic mainstay
for nearly a century, has sent jobs south and west, until a plant
that once employed nearly 40,000 now employs one-tenth that number
and shows every sign of abandoning its birthplace at the first
convenient opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you're the mayor. What do you do about it? What do you do
about a tax base that's fading, about a city where the sale price
of the average house has slipped from $70,000 four years ago to
closer to $60,000 today? What do you do about continuing to provide
people who live in this town with adequate fire protection,
adequate police protection, adequate schools?
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Al had his ideas. So did Gary McCarthy. The depressing
truth, though, is that this same sad drama is being acted out year
after year in old, industrial cities across the Northeast and the
Midwest _ in Utica, in Buffalo, in Sandusky, Ohio, in Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The world has changed. Political boundaries once created to
conform with economic boundaries bear no relationship to today's
economic realities. Local politicians do what they can. The sad
truth, though, is that it matters little which local politician
ends up at the ship's helm.
</P>
<P>
   Without outside help, the ship continues to sink.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Times Union, Box 15000,
Albany, N.Y. 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
