<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LEAD ON FOREIGN DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crushed by debt, extremely poor countries won support Monday
from President Clinton, who wisely vetoed a foreign operations
budget that contained no money for international debt relief. ``We
can't not fulfill our responsibilities to the rest of the world,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The need is glaring. Zambia, for example, spends $17 per person
on health each year but $30 per person to service its $6.6 billion
debt. In other countries, debt drains money from education,
development, and social services.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS increases the financial devastation. In Africa the disease
has not only killed millions but swamped health systems and created
millions of orphans. Callisto Madavo, a vice president of the World
Bank, has said that ``HIV is now the single greatest threat to
future economic development in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed to ease that burden, following up on a promise
of faster, broader debt relief made at a June meeting of the Group
of Seven leading industrial nations in Cologne. Congress sent
Clinton a foreign aid budget earlier this month that omitted the $1
billion debt forgiveness program he had announced. What the
president needs now is congressional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the poor nations, the debt crisis has made
unexpected allies. Representatives Spencer Bachus, an Alabama
Republican, and Maxine Waters, a California Democrat, agree on debt
relief as chairman and ranking member, respectively, of the House
subcommittee on domestic and international monetary policy. They
join Iowa Republican Jim Leach and Democrat Barney Frank of
Massachusetts as sponsors of a separate bill that calls on the
president to ``cancel all amounts owed to the United States . . .
by heavily indebted poor countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The essential caveat is that relief should be given only to
countries willing to invest in human needs such as education,
poverty relief, and social services. Debt relief is also an
opportunity to steer countries toward more sustainable development
and better economic management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
