<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULE WORKS AGAINST VIRGINIA TECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The surge by Virginia Tech in the polls has been a boost for the
Big East, which has been battered by critics for years. But can the
Hokies remain undefeated and make the quantum leap into the Bowl
Championship Series title game in the Sugar Bowl Jan. 4?
</P>
<P>
   The answers: yes and maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's schedule is favorable the rest of the way. The Hokies
have a week off before playing back-to-back road games at
Pittsburgh and West Virginia. Both are winnable. Then comes a
gut-check game at home against Miami, a team the Hokies have
dominated recently, winning the last four meetings.
</P>
<P>
   After that they play at Temple and are home against Boston
College.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-0 record looks not only possible, but probable.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the tough part. Suppose Florida defeats archrival
Florida State (the game is in Gainesville) and Alabama in the
Southeastern Conference championship game. The Gators would be
11-1, with wins over Tennessee and Florida State, both top 5 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Tech does not have anything close to those wins on its schedule
and two of its victories are over Division 1-AA James Madison and
lightly-regarded Alabama-Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, or any other once-beaten team with a tougher
schedule, could jump over Tech into the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is Kansas State revisited: A good team that
people are not willing to call a great team because of a soft
nonconference schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese recognizes the problem.
``Everyone knew what the rules were going into it,'' said
Tranghese, referring to the BCS guidelines that factor in strength
of schedule. ``I told (BCS chairman) Roy Kramer that he wasn't
going to hear a squawk from me about the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese has told the schools in his conference that they must
play good teams.
</P>
<P>
   Tech has done that to some extent. Clemson and Virginia are
legitimate nonconference opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Any Division 1-AA team is not legitimate and Alabama-Birmingham
has only a fledgling Division 1-A program.
</P>
<P>
   Things could work out for Tech. Any of the teams above them
could lose and the Hokies could be the lone unbeaten team in the
country, which would almost guarantee a Sugar Bowl berth.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Hokies should end up outside the gates, there should
be no grumbling about the system from people in Blacksburg.
</P>
<P>
   They knew the rules and chose the easier path.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling here is that things will sort themselves out and if
Virginia Tech is unbeaten, it will go to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But that is hardly a lock, which is too bad because they can
match up with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC bowl picture
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal with Boston College and its bowl hopes. The
first order of business is to get one more win, which will make the
Eagles eligible for a bowl. A home game against West Virginia Nov.
13 looks like their best shot.
</P>
<P>
   If they beat the Mountaineers they likely will have two options.
Grab a spot in the Motor City Bowl in Pontiac, Mich., against
probable Mid-American Conference champion Marshall, or take a spot
in one of the bowl games in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles need some help and luck. Two of the bowl slots in
Hawaii are committed to Pacific-10 teams. The resurgent University
of Hawaii squad could take another slot. If the Rainbows are
bowl-eligible, they will get a bid because of the ticket-sale
factor. And the Atlantic Coast Conference could become a factor
since a team like Clemson, which has a traditionally strong
following on the road, might be more attractive than BC.
</P>
<P>
   The other variable is Notre Dame. The Big East has commitments
from four bowls: a BCS bowl, the Gator, the Insight.com, and the
Music City.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like Virginia Tech is the BCS team; Miami and Syracuse
will battle for the Gator, with the loser in the Insight.com; and
West Virginia likely to go to the Music City Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But Notre Dame has an arrangement with the Big East that it can
grab any of those bowl slots if eligible. The Gator or Insight.com
would grab the Irish in a heartbeat, which would squeeze a team
like West Virginia or BC out of a slot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southern exposure
</P>
<P>
   One of the sleeper teams this season has been Southern
Mississippi, which shouldn't surprise those who know how good a job
coach Jeff Bower has done. Southern Miss, , which is one of three
ranked teams from the state of Mississippi, enters Saturday's game
against Cincinnati with a 4-2 mark (3-0 in Conference USA). The
Golden Eagles are a perennial power in Conference USA (winning
titles in 1996 and '97, and finishing second in '98) and have been
national spoilers as well, particularly against Southeastern
Conference teams such as Alabama, which the Golden Eagles play next
week. Over the last four seasons, the Golden Eagles have compiled
the second-best conference record (18-2) of any team in Division
1-A, trailing only Florida State's (28-1) record in the ACC . . .
Usually one of the signs of a good team is a plus figure in
turnover ratio. Not so Virginia Tech. The Hokies have committed 13
turnovers and forced 13 . . . Those of you looking for a Miami
blowout of BC Saturday at Alumni Stadium should consider these last
four scores against the Eagles at Alumni Stadium: 19-14 in 1991,
23-7 in '93, 17-14 in '95, and 45-44 (2 OT) in '97.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family affair
</P>
<P>
   Saturday is family reunion day at Clemson. No. 1 Florida State
is in Death Valley but that's only a minor attraction of the
weekend. It will be Florida State's Bobby Bowden coaching against
his son Tommy for the first time, and a Florida State win would
mark the 300th of the senior Bowden's career . . . Saturday's games
should clear up the Heisman picture quite a bit. Purdue quarterback
Drew Brees, who has moved up several notches after his
five-touchdown performance against Michigan State last week, will
face Penn State's athletic defense. A big game against the Nittany
Lions could move Brees to the top. Alabama running back Shaun
Alexander will be tested against Tennessee's defense Saturday. A
Tide win and a strong effort by Alexander will move him among the
leaders. The other leading contender is Georgia Tech QB Joe
Hamilton, who has been spectacularly steady all season . . . Latest
coach on the hot seat is LSU's Gerry DiNardo, whose 2-4 Tigers are
again struggling. ``Gerry DiNardo is our coach and will continue to
be our coach,'' said LSU chancellor Mark Emmert. ``I expect him to
be our coach until the end of the season. We're going to play out
the rest of our schedule. It's obvious that we need improvement.''
Sounds like a solid vote of confidence to me . . . Speaking of
votes of confidence, Rutgers announced Thursday it will stick with
Terry Shea for one more year. The question is, why? The Scarlet
Knights are winless and could finish 0-11. There has been no sign
of progress in the program in Shea's four years. Here's the Rutgers
statistic of the week: The Scarlet Knights are the only team (of
114) in Division 1-A not to have an interception this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
