<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEAM PEOPLE LOVE TO HATE DESERVES SOME RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York Yankees and Atlanta Braves have been told
that this World Series will bestow upon the winner the profoundly
mythical title of Team Of The '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, their confusion. They thought they were just playing for
the here and now.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, players have always distrusted mythical titles, let
alone mythical titles given by sportswriters. Myth has nothing to
do with the nasty 91-mph slider on the black with men on second and
third and two outs in the bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   That, they understand. History, they are determined to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Especially the Braves. History has not been nearly as kind to
the Braves as it should have been, based on _ if nothing else _ the
widely held belief that America is bored e Braves.
</P>
<P>
   They win too often, but they don't win enough. They have the
same manager and the same pitchers and the same tedious
chant-and-chop, and they're just, well, the same old Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they're not, but why let the details get in the way
of the greater truth? Yes, Ted Turner is still about sneaking
late-inning naps, and general manager John Schuerholz is walking
around seeming slightly above it all.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox still has the eternally pained look and crab
walk of a man who has played and managed a very long time, and
pitching coach Leo Mazzone still rocks back and forth whether his
pitcher is throwing a three-hitter or has just loaded the bases.
</P>
<P>
   And of course there is that pitching staff. Greg Maddux, Tom
Glavine, John Smoltz, and in the role of Steve Avery and Denny
Neagle, Kevin Millwood. They are as omnipresent as 20/20, and in
every significant way explain the pitchers' art in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and they win all the time. Except for those four pesky World
Series failures, their place in history would be platinum on gold.
As it is, they are as we stand here now, the Brooklyn Dodgers of
the '50s back from the land of shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there are a few structural differences, of course.
</P>
<P>
   There is no equivalent for Jackie Robinson for a number of
salient reasons, Pee Wee Reese was better than the Atlanta
shortstops of the era, and Chipper Jones is a serious improvement
on Billy Cox, but by and large around the diamond, those Dodgers
are these Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Why, if America could have embraced these Braves as it has those
Dodgers, you'd have a near dead-on four-point match.
</P>
<P>
   Such is not the case, of course. America in the '40s and '50s
didn't get tired of the Dodgers, but more charmed. Losing the
Series in 1947, then 1949, then 1952, then 1953, every time to the
Yankees, made them the obvious antidote to Yankee dominance of the
day. Breaking the color line had won the Dodgers a place in
baseball history, to be sure, but once done, the Dodgers took on
the persona of the game loser, the eternal silver medalist, the
conscience and identity of a borough as big as most American
cities. The Dodgers were inflated out of all proportion to their
baseball, and when they won the '55 Series, the heavens all but
opened for them all.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine. That's what history is for, after all. What
doesn't translate, though, is how, by doing essentially the same
things the same way and getting the same results, the Braves
haven't won a greater share of the nation's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, the Braves have done no such thing. They didn't
have an oppressive Yankee myth off which to play, but had been
beaten by the Minnesota Twins, Toronto Blue Jays and a '96 Yankee
team that had been so long without a Series appearance that the
Braves seemed the oppressors. Ever their '95 title came over the
Cleveland Long Suffering Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody sees the Braves as long-suffering. They see them as
an almost tedious perennial of the decade, to the point of having
rooted for the Mets to catch and beat them in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been deemed by the great amorphous mass to be,
well, unhuggable, and as is often the case, the loss is the
nation's.
</P>
<P>
   There is, though, one way out of this grinding dilemma for the
Braves, and it is not an easy road. They must beat the Yankees in
the Series. Not come close, not force a seventh game, not even
outdo their thrilling performances against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   They have to win.
</P>
<P>
   They have to win because it is their only way of avoiding the
cavalier dismissal of the nation as the Team That Didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Cruel? Yeah, maybe. Unfair? You betcha. But those are the facts.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves couldn't be long-suffering because America wasn't
interested in it, and they couldn't be the Brooklyn Dodgers because
myths only work once.
</P>
<P>
   They can, however, be the last team standing this century, and
that counts for something in the long run, doesn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
