<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIOLOGY'S PATHFINDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You never know what you ultimately think until you write it
down. And his remarkable talents for thinking and then writing down
are what drew a full house of academics and intellectuals _ they
are not always the same people, after all _ to an elegant
amphitheater in Cambridge, Mass., Wednesday in honor of a grand old
man of American intellectual life, David Riesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lonely Crowd'' is but one of the texts which he
co-authored in a long lifetime of hammering together the tenets and
tendencies of the social science that came to be known as
sociology. Now 90 and in a wheelchair, the kindly old gent was
feted by a galaxy of colleagues, old students, and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a cold rain at dusk prevented the assembly of a
standing-room only crowd at the American Academy of Arts and
Sciences for three assessments of his career. Riesman sat patiently
through a two-hour program in which he heard his work linked to
that of Alexis de Tocqueville, the pioneering Frenchman whose
writings in the 1830s alerted the Old World to the brawny,
boisterous New World spawned on the American continent.
</P>
<P>
   Telling Americans who we are and why we are that way was the
work of a long lifetime for Riesman, who became Harvard's Henry
Ford II professor in 1958 and retired 19 years ago. His seminal
work was ``The Lonely Crowd,'' which he coauthored with professor
Nathan Glazer and the late Reuel Denney.
</P>
<P>
   Nate Glazer gave the principal speech Wednesday and generously
credited Riesman with being the guiding force of that book,
described in the program as ``a study of changing American society
and character . . . the most widely noted and most influential
sociological work on American society of the past century.'' With
that work, Riesman became the Babe Ruth of sociology.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you never read it, you were taught or informed or
influenced in some manner or fashion by someone who had. It was the
book that as much as any other explained Americans to themselves.
That book ``was not afraid to tackle the largest questions,'' said
Glazer, of who we were, and how we became that way. ``It
established itself by readers saying: `How true!' '' It also
established the sidelines and goal posts of sociology, a social
science whose place in the ladder of academic prestige was the
subject of many wry asides and sardonic comparisons in the lectures
by Glazer and professors Daniel Bell and Christopher Jencks.
</P>
<P>
   Bell asserted that the field has become ``more stilted and
stunted'' since Riesman's heyday, that ``pop psychology'' gave way
to ``plop psychology.'' Jencks suggested that faculties
reinvigorate their social science faculties ``by hiring fewer
people with degrees in sociology.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Riesman's gentle humanity and ``generosity of mind and
time'' that Glazer cited, with a lot of gray heads from Harvard,
MIT, and further campuses nodding assent. Riesman melded the
charts, statistics, and dry bones of academic studies with lively
insights from hands-on studies of real people and telling
observations from popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Riesman was a sort of Christopher Columbus of the field, sending
hundreds of students and teaching assistants forth with the
confidence and skills gained under his tutelage, under the general
admonition to study your fellow humans, analyze your data, draw
inferences and conclusions, and contribute to the literature of
scholarship. Or journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Jencks, noting how he, Glazer, and Bell all started careers in
opinion journalism, offered a cheeky aside that sociology, in the
end, ``is just slow journalism,'' which drew an uncomfortable
chortle from some. Glazer drew parallels from the fact that Riesman
and de Tocqueville were both initially trained as lawyers, not
historians or social scientists. By being flexible, receptive, and
ultimately artistic in his weaving together of themes and
conclusions, all three agreed, Riesman became a pathfinder.
</P>
<P>
   His rule of thumb, said Bell, was: ``Go out and observe. Be
mindful of history.'' And Bell told a joke about a student
badgering his rabbi for guidance on distilling judgments from
experience: ``Rabbi, how do you have good judgment?'' Rabbi: ``By
having bad experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   You could not become a college president or think seriously
about American education without encountering Riesman's thoughtful,
rigorous, and empathetic canvases of the forces shaping the
immigrant land that turned into the American colossus. His genial
and collaborative style drew hundreds of acolytes into his orbit.
His division of Americans between ``inner-directed'' and
``other-directed'' was brilliant. The former marched to their own
drummers despite the conformist, consumerist pressure of the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the other-directed people should discover how much needless
work they do, discover that their own thoughts and their own lives
are quite as interesting as other people's, that indeed, they no
more assuage their loneliness in a crowd of peers than one can
assuage one's thirst by drinking sea water, then we might expect
them to become more attentive to their own feelings and
aspirations.'' De Tocqueville's great idea was to explain the
American experiment in equality to the world, Riesman's to explain
to Americans what we did with all of that.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
