<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STRAIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYNCH AIMS `STRAIGHT' FOR THE HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the hands of many directors, simplicity seems pretentious.
But in a 180-degree turn from the surrealistic weirdness of his
previous films, David Lynch makes simplicity seem pure, eloquent,
and deeply moving in ``The Straight Story.'' Unlike his views of
small-town America in ``Blue Velvet,'' ``Wild at Heart,'' and
``Lost Highway,'' there's no irony at all in his sunlit take of the
farm town in Iowa where the story begins, in what we think will be
``Blue Velvet'' fashion as an overhead camera drops down into a
yard to show us a banal shot of a woman sunbathing between two
modest frame houses. But there's nothing even remotely campy on
Lynch's menu. In no time, we've made the acquaintance of the
woman's next-door neighbor, a geezer in declining health played by
that ex-rodeo rider, stuntman, and twinkling old gent who has Old
West written all over him, Richard Farnsworth.
</P>
<P>
   It's Farnsworth's Alvin Straight who gives the film its
deep-breathing quality, its unhurried authority, and its courtly
nobility. He grumps about the fact that in addition to emphysema,
he's got to use two canes to get around, because of a fall in his
kitchen and some newly discovered circulatory problems. At that,
he's better off than his stroke victim brother Lyle, who lives in
Wisconsin. They haven't spoken in 10 years, he tells us, for no
better reasons than drinking and pride. All the background we need
is sketched in minimal but, we are convinced, emotion-loaded
exchanges with his speech-impaired daughter Rose, played with
uncommon rightness by Sissy Spacek. She's carrying her own load of
pain, having been declared an unfit mother by a state agency after
a fire, and having her four kids taken away from her.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Straight Story'' is Farnsworth's film all the way,
once Alvin decides he ought to reconcile with Lyle before they die.
He is not about to be stopped by the fact that not only doesn't he
have a driver's license, he doesn't have a car. He simply hitches a
wagonful of supplies to his lawnmower and takes off. When it blows
a gasket not far up the road, he patiently has it towed back,
trades it in on an old John Deere, and takes off again, at a none
too speedy but infinitely resolute 10 miles per hour, unfazed by
rumbling 18-wheelers that blow by him like speeding cliffs. That
there is nothing lovably eccentric or silly about his mission or
his way of accomplishing it comes from the sense we must get _ and
do _ that Farnsworth's 73-year-old self-sufficient World War II vet
is what sociologists used to call inner-directed.
</P>
<P>
   His gentlemanliness, sincerity, and dignity make a difference
during a roadside stopover when he meets a young woman running away
because she's afraid to tell her family she's pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it makes no difference at all when he meets
another woman who is hysterical because she hit a deer, not for the
first time, on her commute.
</P>
<P>
   The film _ based on an actual journey made in 1994 _ doesn't use
flashbacks, but we get enough of Alvin's history to deepen him,
including his stifled pain at mistakes he made and his candor in
facing up to years he wasted drinking hard. But that was then, the
film seems to say, and this is now, and Alvin, who hasn't much
future, lives for as much now as he can still get.
</P>
<P>
   His understated but unmistakable tenacity generates sympathy,
but maybe Lynch, who grew up in rural Montana, is simply saying
that most people along the way will respond to decent behavior in
kind. Alvin makes minimal demands on his benefactors, and is
grateful for the help he gets from some kind locals when his brakes
and tires fail near the hilly state border. One of the film's
scenes of sly country humor comes when Alvin gently makes clear to
some twins that he isn't going to overpay for a pair of tires and
bargains them back down to earth. ``The Straight Story'' is a
beguiling piece of Americana populated by Deere hearts and gentle
people. Farnsworth's embodiment of old American values, with their
combination of delicacy, reserve, and stand-alone independence, is
a one-of-a-kind treasure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE STRAIGHT STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: David Lynch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: John Roach, Mary Sweeney &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Richard Farnsworth, Sissy Spacek, Jane Galloway Heitz,
Everett McGill, Jennifer Edwards-Hughes, Barbara Robertson, John
Farley, John Lordan, Harry Dean Stanton &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 111 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: G &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
