<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5150 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-DEAD-BOS &LR;      10-22 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DEAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORSESE'S `DEAD' IS FLIP SIDE TO `TAXI DRIVER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' Martin Scorsese's film about EMS
drivers, isn't a thrill ride. It's a soul ride. For all of the
blood and suffering splashed through every draining shift worked by
Nicolas Cage's paramedic, for all the shrieking sirens and
high-speed careening up and down Manhattan's harsh streets in the
early '90s, the real crisis is the one buffeting the spirit of
Cage's Frank Pierce. Frank's problem is that there are none of the
usual defenses between him and his job. Most of his colleagues
detach, take refuge in mock-callous survivor's humor, or focus on
other things _ food in the case of John Goodman's Larry, religion
in the case of Ving Rhames's Marcus. But for Frank _ surrogate for
EMS driver Joe Connelly, whose autobiographical novel is the film's
source _ there is no relief. What his tormented customers feel, he
feels.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may loom as an extension of ``Taxi Driver,''
``Bringing Out the Dead'' would more accurately be called that
nihilistic film's flip side. While there's a lot of death on the
streets of Hell's Kitchen and in the apartments lining them,
there's also hope. Unlike the alcoholic he played in ``Leaving Las
Vegas,'' Cage's character isn't seeking death. What he wants is
redemption, peace, or, failing that, a little sleep. He's the
opposite of Travis Bickle's boiling taxi driver. His conscience
won't let him quit, although he'd like to. The most amusing piece
of black humor comes from his harried boss, played by Scorsese.
When he threatens to fire Frank for coming in late, he knows it
would be a relief to Frank, who then would be let off the moral
hook. But, of course, Scorsese's dispatcher is perpetually
short-handed. So Frank's punishment is to be kept in his job.
</P>
<P>
   You will by now sense the large presence of Catholic guilt here.
It is an element that figures in many of Scorsese's films, from
``Mean Streets'' on. Like that film's hero, Frank has something of
a savior complex. He feels guilty about the people he can't save. A
recurring hallucinatory image of a young woman personifies all the
snuffed-out life Frank regards as his responsibility. At one point,
a voice tells him that nobody asked him to suffer, that suffering
was his idea. Although the film never makes anything of it, he may
be guilty of the sin of pride, of taking on more of the
responsibility of running the universe than is rightly his. It
speaks well for his heart, but unless you identify with his guilt,
a lot of Frank's anguish seems like pointless self-laceration and,
from the dramatic point of view, relegates to secondary status a
lot of the more immediate suffering. While Scorsese was right to
avoid an overemphasis on rescue heroics, it seems a miscalculation
to make Frank's agonizing the film's center.
</P>
<P>
   A scene in a drug pad seems artful rather than visceral in its
impact. A recurring street figure who survives brutal treatment
seems more symbolic than actual. The film does reach some of the
contrasting tender emotion it's after in a few exchanges between
Cage and Patricia Arquette, as a troubled but compassionate
neighbor named, yes, Mary. They meet when he responds to her
father's heart attack. But when solace works its way around to a
pieta, it seems more emblematic than immediate. There's a little
too much docu in this docudrama and not enough drama. This seems a
curious thing to say about so pain-drenched a film, in which a lot
of emergency room footage adds to the verisimilitude of the images.
There would seem no surer bet this season than America's foremost
film artist going back to Manhattan's mean streets to bookend
``Taxi Driver.'' But while heartfelt and beautifully crafted,
``Bringing Out the Dead'' is too freighted with its protagonist's
failed savior complex and is surprisingly lacking in primal impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRINGING OUT THE DEAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Martin Scorsese &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Paul Schrader (novel: Joe Connelly) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Nicolas Cage, Patricia Arquette, John Goodman, Ving
Rhames, Tom Sizemore, Marc Anthony, Cliff Curtis &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 118 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (gritty violent content, drug use and language) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
