u e BC-MOVIE-ROSIE-BOS &LR;      10-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ROSIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POWERFUL TALE OF A 13-YEAR-OLD DREAMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rosie,'' from a new Belgian director, Patrice Toye, is a
devastatingly understated powerhouse of a film. With its
13-year-old nonprofessional in the title role, it could have been
rigged with over-the-top adolescent angst. Instead, it achieves
enormous impact through the restraint with which it unfolds. Rosie,
played by Aranka Coppens, is an alienated girl clapped into a
juvenile facility as the film opens. In flashback, we see what got
her there. She acts out, but she's far from wild by nature. She's
dreamy. Toye came to this feature film debut from documentaries,
one of which focused on 13-year-old girls. Certainly this one
succeeds as few films do in convincing us that Rosie lives a lot of
her life in her head, in fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   She spends a lot of her time in her personal refuge, an
abandoned refinery in the bleak, weed-covered outskirts of Antwerp,
where she lives with her mother in cramped public housing. She
doesn't know her father, and while her mother loves her, she passes
Rosie off as her sister, not wanting to admit that she gave birth
to Rosie when she was young and unmarried. Although the bond is
strong and deep between Rosie and her mother, living this lie
troubles Rosie. Pressure builds when her Uncle Michelk moves in
with them, making his own demands and gambling money away at a time
when Rosie's mother is trying to make a go of it with a nice-guy
lover.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie takes refuge from the exacerbated tensions in the
claustrophobic flat by escaping into fantasies with a boyfriend
transformed in her mind into a romantic deliverer. They play house,
go joy riding, then go too far by kidnapping a baby. Part of the
film's impact derives from the fact that the boyfriend (Joost
Wijnant) is no real desperado, just slightly delinquent. Toye cast
members of Antwerp's leading acting cooperative, Sara de Roo and
Frank Vercruyssen, as Rosie's mother and uncle. They, too, are
remarkable at suggesting the gravitational pull of the lifelong
brother-sister baggage borne by their characters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most of the film takes place in Rosie's eyes. As it
proceeds, and you tie into all the characters, you keep hoping
they'll find a way out. But while Toye projects their world with
surprising poetry, she's clear-eyed enough to avoid easy, much less
sentimental, solutions. She also keeps the yearning, emotionally
malnourished Rosie at the center of the film's troubled but always
beating heart. ``Rosie'' is a dynamic and unflinching film, but
it's also a tenderly observed one that delicately but
invigoratingly pulses with the energies of film renewing itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROSIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by: Patrice Toye &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Aranka Coppens, Sara De Roo, Dirk Roofthooft, Joost
Wijnant, Frank Vercruyssen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 97 minutes(in Flemish with subtitles) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Unrated &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
