<HEADER>
A5158 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CRAZY-BOS &LR;      10-22 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CRAZY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANDERAS'S `CRAZY IN ALABAMA' IS SERIOUS FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juggling Southern gothic eccentricity and civil rights advocacy,
``Crazy in Alabama'' represents a challenging directing debut for
Antonio Banderas. To his credit, he and the film land on their
feet. Although it's ungainly and disjointed in places, ``Crazy in
Alabama'' is carried by the larger-than-life character played by
Melanie Griffith. Never has a woman been more lovingly directed by
her real-life husband in a Hollywood film. But the effort is well
invested. Griffith makes her character's sexual flamboyance work.
She makes it seem simultaneously easy and over the top as an
oppressed woman determined to break out of her Alabama backwater
and become a Hollywood star.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part is getting out from under the thumb of her abusive
brute of a husband. Once she murders him and flees with his severed
head in a hatbox, such details as car theft and batting her eyes at
a succession of men ranging from smalltown sheriffs to Hollywood
agents are, to Griffith's Lucille, child's play. Griffith and
Banderas poke sly fun at the roles to which a woman like Lucille is
limited in the 1960s, when the film takes place, making her a
cheerful survivor who just plunges in and makes the best of things.
Not only does she have to make Lucille's extreme behavior
entertaining and funny, which she does, she must keep Lucille
sympathetic. This she does too. Irresponsible as it may seem that
she should have placed her brood of children in the care of others,
Lucille convinces us that she loves them in her outsize way.
</P>
<P>
   The story is narrated by Lucille's oldest teenage son, Peejoe,
played with dewy sentience and stubborn decency by Lucas Black in
an appealing performance. He and his younger brother are stashed
with their uncle, Lucille's older brother, Dove, who works in a
funeral home. David Morse is always affecting in his understated
way, and he makes this role work too, although he and the boys have
their hands full sustaining the film's other major plot strand, the
serious one focused on the civil strife of the '60s. Meat Loaf Aday
brings presence to a caricatured mean bigot sheriff. And the film
deftly handles the part of the story that involves the boys nudging
their uncle into the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces don't always fit together smoothly, but there's a lot
of flavorful work to savor, including Rod Steiger's judge, who
brings off the tough job of tying together the film's comic and
serious strands in a spirited climactic trial scene. There's not
quite enough craziness in the slightly overlong ``Crazy in
Alabama,'' but neither is it negligible. The civil rights story is
played with conviction and achieves impact. Griffith tempers
Lucille's lunatic kewpie doll quality with scatty warmth, to say
nothing of strategically deployed slashes of scarlet lipstick.
Lucille becomes sympathetic because she convinces us she's a woman
who will not be defeated by an unpromising set of day-in-day-out
circumstances, even if she has to stage her own civil rights
protest. So it is with ``Crazy in Alabama.'' Its joinery can be
faulted, but it's always simpatico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRAZY IN ALABAMA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Antonio Banderas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Mark Childress, based on his novel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Melanie Griffith, David Morse, Lucas Black, Cathy
Moriarty, Meat Loaf Aday, Rod Steiger, Richard Schiff, John
Beasley, Robert Wagner, Sandra Seacat &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 112 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (some violence, thematic material, language and a
scene of sexuality) &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BESTMAN-BOS &LR;      10-22 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BESTMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEST MAN': A CAUSE FOR CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Malcolm D. Lee's ``The Best Man'' is a romantic comedy that gets
the important things right. It fills the screen with appealing
characters and, unlike most such films, deepens our involvement
with them as the film proceeds, thanks to a warm ensemble
performance and sophisticated finesse from Lee, both at the word
processor and behind the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the end do we feel a too-apparent hand of the writer,
wrapping things up with a neatness more convenient than believable.
Still, ``The Best Man'' is an enormously engaging and quite
impressive debut for Lee. Not since ``How Stella Got Her Groove
Back'' has a mainstream film about successful African-Americans
arrived with so much going for it.
</P>
<P>
   It perhaps is no coincidence that the star of that Angela
Bassett romance, Taye Diggs, is the male lead here, too. In this
case, though, he's a full-fledged American buppie, a writer named
Harper with a steamy semiautobiographical novel about to be
published as he heads for a weekend reunion with his pals. It's
built around the wedding of one of them, Morris Chestnut's star pro
football running back. Harper's counting on the fact that the book
won't hit the stores until after the wedding. But one of his old
crowd gets a preview copy, and before long they're all reading it
to see which character might be a thinly veiled version of
themselves, complete with what could be compromising secrets about
sexual liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it isn't long before the skies are thick with the
chickens coming home to roost. Relationships are shaken up and the
wedding itself seems in jeopardy, even though the footballer and
the sweet woman in his life, played by Monica Calhoun, obviously
love one another.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trouble that develops arises because Harper several
years ago backed away from a romantic involvement with Nia Long's
equally career-focused TV producer, Jordan. Sanaa Lathan's Robin,
the current woman in Harper's life, isn't due to arrive until
Sunday, which gives Harper and Jordan some time to get into
trouble. Of course they all get into trouble of one kind or
another, partly because, the film makes clear, they all have
unresolved issues or parts of themselves they haven't acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Although the wedding isn't a shotgun wedding, the intense
emotions detonated by the reunions generate some shotgun maturing.
Still, there's nothing to really throw the film off track. We get
hooked by these bright, attractive characters and we stay hooked.
One of the things you've got to like about Lee's writing is that
when the characters start talking trash, it's more earthy and frank
than mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   Lee likes his characters, and we keep liking them, too, even
when Diggs's writer wavers, even when Chestnut's athlete is forced
to confront the pain caused by his double standard. As the jock who
convinces us he has a religious side, his character is the most
heartfelt and the most moving. But there are no throwaway roles
here. Even Lathan, given the least screen time as the woman the
writer might possibly throw over to conclude the unfinished
business with Long's producer, weighs in strongly and warmly. ``The
Best Man'' breathes fresh life into old formulas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST MAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by: Malcolm D. Lee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Taye Diggs, Nia Long, Morris Chestnut, Harold
Perrineau, Terrence Howard, Sanaa Lathan, Monica Calhoun, Melissa
DeSousa &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 121 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (language and sexuality) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5164 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-SHOTS-BOS &LR;      10-22 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SHOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLICK BUT TOUGH LOOK AT SEX, RAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most so-called date movies are eye candy. But ``Body Shots''
goes to some uncomfortable places to show some ugly situations
beneath its pretty pictures. Even if it doesn't achieve its
ambitions, it at least has some and is a generally absorbing
ensemble piece that will be regarded as something of an anti-date
movie. Still, it'll give couples something to talk about if they
make it to the end. Beneath its glitz, poses, and pub crawlers and
club prowlers, it's an old-fashioned morality tale whose central
event is a date rape at the end of an evening spent by four LA
couples who pair off.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Cristofer and an attractive cast find ways to
give dimension to the script's sexual stereotyping, in which the
guys just want one thing, at least to hear them make their barroom
chat sound like locker room bravado, and the women don't want much
more. Actually, a couple of the guys seem poised to grow beyond
behavior patterns that don't travel well to adulthood: Sean Patrick
Flanery's lawyer, Rick, who at least feels he ought to grow up, and
Brad Rowe's Shawn, who says that sex without love is violence,
although when a sexual opportunity presents itself in an alley with
a too-desperate woman, he doesn't say no.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, Flanery's lawyer wakes up in the early
morning in the bed of a woman named Jane (Amanda Peet), who also is
a lawyer. They're quickly yanked out of man-woman stuff into their
professional modes when Tara Reid's Sara shows up, bruised and
beaten, charging that the guys' ex-pro-football-playing pal, Jerry
O'Connell's Mike, raped her. Of course, there are conflicting
stories about what happened. The respective accounts are played out
in flashback. So are the other events of the evening as the
characters stagger into the morning in states ranging from shaken
to wasted.
</P>
<P>
   The film's style is pretty assaultive, paralleling the evening.
And it's as fractured as the characters' thought processes.
Obviously the film means to switch our view of them from hip to
lost, although it's too cool to attempt anything like a definitive
resolution. It also adheres to the Hollywood credo that just
because you have the intellectual firepower of kelp, it doesn't
mean you can't be good-looking. Looks fuel the evening's nod to
humor. Ron Livingston's eccentric Trent gets the leper treatment
for wearing golf knickers and an argyle sweater to the club and
Emily Procter's bargirl amusingly extends the Southern Cal blond
babe look into dominatrix territory.
</P>
<P>
   Trent never sees the handcuffs coming. He and the others
believably receive just enough of a jolt to make us forgive the
film its own relentless style-hound approach and airhead banalities
that pass for profundity in the LA club scene. ``Body Shots''
behaves like a slick TV movie, with platitudes that seem suspended
above the characters in comic-strip balloons. It looks good and
generates a few fleeting moments of sympathy in its washes of
overstatement. But for a movie that seems to think it's Neil LaBute
with palm trees and a beach scene, it's only ``The Breakfast Club''
pulling an all-nighter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BODY SHOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Michael Cristofer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: David McKenna &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Amanda Peet, Sean Patrick Flannery, Tara Reed, Jerry
O'Connell, Emily Procter, Ron Livingston, Sybil Temchen, Brad Rowe &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 99 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (strong sexual content including graphic sex-related
dialogue, language, violence, and scenes of alcohol abuse) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
