<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      10-22 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHEMISTRY IS STILL THERE FOR STONE TEMPLE PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anxiety reigned when the Stone Temple Pilots, who hadn't played
together in two years, regrouped earlier this year to see if they
had any chemistry left. It was late January in Los Angeles. Singer
Scott Weiland, whose well-publicized heroin problems have often
derailed the group, greeted his three bandmates _ brothers Dean and
Robert DeLeo and Eric Kretz _ and the music began.
</P>
<P>
   Robert brought in the riff to a new song, ``Down,'' and the band
got right to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a small room cranking out that song,'' Dean DeLeo
recalled this week. ``And, at 119 decibels, the anxiety left rather
quickly, as the paint peeled from the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just this thing we have together,'' he added of the
group's still-vibrant chemistry. ``There's never a lot of
discussion in STP. Everybody knows what the others want in their
music.''
</P>
<P>
   The chemistry that has made STP a hard-rock powerhouse _
resulting in 14 million combined sales of their first three albums,
``Core,'' ``Plush,'' and ``Tiny Music _ Songs From the Vatican Gift
Shop'' _ bursts forth again on the new CD, ``No. 4,'' which comes
out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It packs a worthy wallop and is laced with pent-up guitar rock
and Weiland's brilliant-when-not-smacked-out lyrics, but STP now
has another dilemma to overcome. Weiland finished the record, but
violated parole (he failed to show up for a drug test) and in
August was jailed for a year. With good behavior, he could be out
in March _ in time for a summer tour _ but that's a wait-and-see
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very aware that there's no guarantee he'll be out in
March,'' said DeLeo. ``To feel differently is setting us up for a
downfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiland entered a rehab division of the LA County Jail on Friday
the 13th, after having been sentenced on the 13th floor of an LA
courthouse. ``He never moaned about what he was going to face,''
said DeLeo. ``He was truly noble about facing the burden of his
actions. He had also been sober for 2 1/2 months _ the longest
stint of his sobriety in a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Weiland ran into a judge who had already seen
him twice before and couldn't hack it anymore. Weiland missed his
drug test and then overdosed in the halfway house where he was
living while making the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott was taken to the emergency room in the middle of the
night, and when that happens, the courts are notified within 24
hours,'' said DeLeo. ``The sequence of events after that was
surreal. We finished the record and were getting ready to do a show
in Las Vegas in mid-August. The court said, `OK, if you want to
leave the state, we want you to turn yourself in on Aug. 13.' And
that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vegas show, taped at the House of Blues, will air on MTV
later this fall. The album will start its march up the charts
shortly and, at the very least, is a high-decibel present to fans
who needed a reunion disc after the disappointment of the
participants' non-STP efforts. Weiland made a spotty solo CD, ``12
Bar Blues,'' while the other three members, renaming themselves
Talk Show, made an album by that name that had some great
arrangements, but lacked strong vocals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if Scott was in the same frame of mind as the rest of
us, then Talk Show and `12 Bar Blues' would have never existed,''
said DeLeo. ``He was leading his life in a certain way that took
precedence over everything else. . . . It's tough seeing your
brother spiraling out of control downward. You're beside yourself
and there's no way you can help in a situation like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tensions were tough at that time, but anger soon gave way to
regret and a genuine missing of each other. ``Talk Show wasn't even
out of the rehearsal room for our tour when I said, `I miss Scott,'
'' DeLeo recalled. ``And when he hit the road with a whole
different band, he called up and said, `Dude, I miss you guys,
too.' Then one thing led to another and when our tours brought us
back to LA, we all expressed feelings about making some more music
together.''
</P>
<P>
   While Weiland tries to get his act together, the remaining
members have at least had some fun learning the songs to the
musical ``Hedwig and the Angry Inch'' (``I was absolutely blown
away by that,'' said DeLeo) and playing them at an opening-night
cast party in Los Angeles. And DeLeo is getting married on Nov. 14
and plans to hide out for a while on his farm in Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   ``When STP is up and running, it's like jumping on a carousel,''
said DeLeo. ``But when I get home, I punch the off button and just
enjoy country living.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VH1's Concert of the Century: It's a heady notion, but then, VH1
is a heady channel. It gets especially ambitious with Saturday's
``Concert of the Century,'' broadcast live from an undisclosed
location in Washington, D.C., starting at 4 p.m. Performers include
Eric Clapton, Aretha Franklin, Garth Brooks, John Mellencamp,
Sheryl Crow, Susan Tedeschi, B. B. King, Lenny Kravitz, Bono, 'N
Sync, Gloria Estefan, and John Fogerty. President and Hillary
Rodham Clinton will also participate, while presenters include
Robert De Niro, Gwyneth Paltrow, and Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
