<HEADLINE>
TAKING ON CHALLENGE OF REBUILDING TRUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig Bradley wasn't at Thursday's hearing at the Massachusetts
Division of Insurance. It was too bad. Probably only Bradley could
explain how his once-successful insurance company could have fallen
so far.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the hearing was called to review a plan by
businessman David ``Duddie'' Massad to take control of Bradley's
company, Trust Insurance of Taunton, Mass. In reality, the deal is
a bankruptcy workout that is being handled outside bankruptcy
court.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes through, Bradley's role and ownership of Trust
will be sharply reduced. If the deal fails, say industry sources,
the company could wind up in receivership.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the Bradley era was a lot more hopeful. He
founded Trust in 1989 after leaving Commerce Insurance in Webster
following a dispute with Commerce boss Arthur Remillard. Bradley
got his revenge by building Trust into a decent-sized insurer and a
pesky rival to Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig is a brilliant individual,'' says an insurance executive
who knows him. Others say Bradley was a master salesmen whose skill
at wooing insurance agents helped him build the eighth-largest auto
insurance company in the state. About 175,000 consumers in
Massachusetts buy their insurance through Trust. In his spare time
Bradley became a major Democratic fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, Bradley's interest in his company waned,
say former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took his eye off the ball,'' says one. Bradley began
spending less time at the company, leaving day-to-day operations in
the hands of his lieutenants and a variety of relatives he put on
the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a good time to be away. The past few years have been
difficult ones for the auto insurance industry in Massachusetts.
Rates have fallen and profits have dropped along with them.
</P>
<P>
   At Trust profits disappeared altogether. In May Trust said it
lost $21 million in 1998. In June the loss was boosted to $26
million, enough to wipe out half of the company's reserves. Trust
blamed the loss on computer glitches and problems with its
reinsurers. The explanation was skimpy and, according to industry
sources, not entirely plausible. Neither Trust nor the Division of
Insurance has elaborated on the reasons for the losses.
</P>
<P>
   But Trust had an ace in the hole: Massad, an investor who has
turned around car dealerships and a Worcester bank. Massad said he
would put $20 million into Trust in exchange for controlling
interest.
</P>
<P>
   That's how matters stood until Sept. 28, when in the space of
one day, Massad withdrew his offer and then changed his mind and
said he was back in. What happened in those few hours? Based on
documents filed with the Division of Insurance, it is clear Massad
demanded and won important changes in the terms of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Bank, which had lent Trust $20 million, agreed to cut the
debt to $10 million. Why? Fleet isn't saying, but it's a good bet
the bank realized that if it didn't make the concession, it might
have wound up with nothing. ``If Fleet didn't make the adjustment,
we could not have pursued this matter,'' Massad said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also took a major haircut. He agreed to quit as chief
executive, to turn over part of his stock to Massad for nothing, to
accept a major reduction in his $1.6 million termination package,
to repay $841,000 he borrowed from Trust, and to remove his wife
and daughter from the payroll. Presumably Bradley, like Fleet,
agreed because the alternative would have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   Massad promised to make Trust ``efficient and profitable.''
Rival insurers say he will have his work cut out for him. The
state's auto insurance business is a rough-and-tumble one, and it
is all but certain other insurers will try to lure away Trust's
best agents. In this state, customers are loyal to their agents,
not to companies.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives also wondered whether all the bad news at
Trust has been disclosed. A lawyer representing some of Trust's
minority shareholders complained that no up-to-date information
about the company's financial situation has been made public. A
spokesman for the Division of Insurance said only that Trust ``is
under examination'' and that the division is monitoring the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   The division has 30 days to approve or deny Massad's offer. Stay
tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
