<HEADLINE>
GAY SUBSCRIBERS MAY BOYCOTT AMERICA ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gay and lesbian subscribers to America Online
and gay online organizations are considering boycotting the
Internet giant for what they see as discrimination against gay
content online.
</P>
<P>
   NationalGayLobby.org began polling its members earlier this week
about boycotting AOL if the company refuses to come up with a new
set of standards to erase what the lobby believes may be a practice
of censoring gay content much more frequently than content that
includes profanities, sexual content or even hate speech by non-gay
members.
</P>
<P>
   Absent that, the organization wants a clear explanation from AOL
why it won't stop the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure nobody wants to boycott AOL, but they have been
totally unresponsive to traditional forms of communication,'' said
Mike Romanello, the executive director of NationalGayLobby.org.
``They can end this whole thing with a phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mails began flying back and forth this week among gay online
groups criticizing the online giant for its decision to delete the
online member profile of a gay AOL subscriber who described himself
as a ``submissive bottom.'' The subscriber alerted his local
American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) chapter in Fort Worth, Texas,
which, in turn, took the issue to the media and online gay
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Romanello said Thursday that more than 400 organization members
so far had responded to the poll. Of that group, 36 percent
identified themselves as AOL users and said they would support the
boycott. Another 43 percent who were not AOL users said they would
also support the effort.
</P>
<P>
   AOL has been caught in controversy with the gay community
before. Last year, the Sterling, Va.-based company was criticized
when one of its employees turned over a gay member's name to a Navy
investigator who then initiated discharge proceedings against the
serviceman.
</P>
<P>
   AOL spokesman Rich D'Amato on Thursday denied that the company
discriminates against gays. He said it tries to be ``even-handed
and fair across the board'' when dealing with questions of
objectionable profile content.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has 18 million members, relies on its users
to alert it to objectionable content, D'Amato said. Then a team
within the company reviews the complaint based on the company
policy. The policy does not allow strong sexual content or hate
speech, D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to be as narrow and as broad as possible,'' D'Amato
said. ``We do not want to interfere with a community's prerogatives
to express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   If a profile _ a guide that allows AOL members to post details
about themselves _ has been deemed inappropriate, it is deleted and
the member is given a written explanation. Members are encouraged
to review the terms and submit altered profiles, D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Provasek, president of the ACLU's Fort Worth chapter, said
his group has general concerns with AOL over free speech issues,
but was pushed into action over the deletion of the profile using
what he called the ``innocuous'' term ``submissive bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Provasek said he took up the cause out of concern that gay
content was being censored more frequently than straight content.
</P>
<P>
   He ran the word ``censored'' through AOL's search engines and
pulled up 100 profiles. Of those, the majority had used the word
``censored'' to indicate that AOL had deleted their profiles
because of gay content. All of those cases involved gay men, he
said, which raised the question whether gay content is censored
more than straight content.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're either not censoring non-gays, or gay men are more
naughty from anyone else and AOL thinks they need to be censored,''
Provasek said. ``We just have a real problem with the fact that
(AOL censors) are treating these adults like children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV24     10-22 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV24-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE ADVISED TO SAVE MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are 38 and 31 years old, respectively, and
we hope to have two children over the course of the next three
years. My husband is a self-employed management consultant. I
recently left my job and plan to work part-time, but may not return
to work once we have our first child. We typically earn about
$100,000 a year and save about 20 percent of our gross income, with
the majority going into my husbands SEP-IRA. Here is our retirement
savings: In taxable accounts, we have $18,900 in Vanguard Index
500, $13,340 in Acorn fund, $13,848 in Janus Worldwide, and $6,942
in Fidelity Latin America funds, plus $11,013 in a brokerage
account invested in blue chip stocks. SEP-IRA accounts consist of
$15,593 in Fidelity Spartan Market Index and $6,825 in a Fidelity
brokerage account. Traditional IRAs include $4,666 in Fidelity
Diversified International and $4,033 in Fidelity Low-Priced Stock
funds. And we have Roth IRAs of $4,155 in Fidelity Dividend Growth
and $8,364 in Fidelity Export and Multinational funds. My husband
also has a $69,333 rollover IRA in brokerage accounts, and returns
there have been below average for the past few years. I also have
$16,115 in a tax-deferred account with TIAA. We also have $36,041
in a blue chip stock account from which we give approximately 10
percent a year to charity. Finally, we have a large emergency fund
in Fidelity Spartan Massachusetts Municipal Income, which is the
only savings not earmarked for retirement. Are we saving enough? Do
we have the correct asset allocation for retirement in 20 years?
</P>
<P>
   E.M., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, at the rate you are now saving, you will build your
nestegg to nearly $2.5 million, presuming average 10 percent
portfolio growth.
</P>
<P>
   This calculation includes neither the stock fund you use to fund
charity contributions, nor your emergency fund, which if untouched
would add a further $121,483, presuming average 5 percent returns
there.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds great, no? But if inflation runs at a 3.5 percent
average, you can figure that youll need about double the number of
dollars to maintain your current standard of living, which is to
say about $160,000 a year. If your $2.5 million were invested in a
fixed-income portfolio which averaged 6.5 percent returns, it would
indeed produce that income stream -- but with very little left over
to protect you from inflation in the later years of your
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a couple of mitigating circumstances. For one
thing, if you continue to save 20 percent of your gross income, the
contributions and projected accumulation would rise as your income
rises. For another, most people dont need the same level of income
in retirement as during their working years. For one thing, usually
mortgages are paid off by that time. And having the time do things
yourself rather than pay for services usually allows people to
reduce their budgets by 20 to 40 percent once they retire.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even though its always a question mark, there is
always the prospect that Social Security will be kicking in when
your husband reaches age 62, or, if he so elects, at a later age.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Id feel a little more secure if you could advance your
savings level a bit, but probably things should work out fairly
well on your current course.
</P>
<P>
   As for the portfolio I think its well diversified. I'd probably
have chosen Janus Overseas rather than Janus Worldwide, since the
latter holds a good dollop of U.S. large-cap stocks, which are
already well-represented in the portfolio. But if a change would
bring you an ugly tax bill, probably just as well to leave it as it
is. And if your TIAA account is in an annuity rather than the CREF
stock funds, I would change that. In addition, if the brokerage
account in which your husbands rollover IRA is invested has been
underperforming recently, you should analyze how its invested, and
if youre not satisfied with the performance, consider a different
investment. After all, at this point, its the largest single
segment of your retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while I applaud your program of charitable giving, you
also might consider that without additions or withdrawals, that
$36,041 would grow to $242,465 over 20 years, presuming 10 percent
average growth. You might then factor that in as money to protect
you against inflation in the later years of retirement _ and also
earmark that money for charitable bequests in your estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In this age of high technology, I am becoming increasingly
concerned about the safety of my assets which are currently
invested with one of the biggest mutual fund companies. As I
approach retirement age and reliance upon the funds I have
accumulated in my IRA accounts, the ease with which a computer
nerd, hacker, or even a high school kid with computer savvy could
gain access to these accounts is alarming to me -- to the point of
my considering the transfer of these funds to CDs at my local bank,
where at least I am recognized. The company with which I am
invested -- one of your favorites -- allows withdrawals with just a
telephone call, their only safeguards being that you provide your
name and address as it is on the account, provide your account
number, and give your Social Security number. Apparently these
safeguards absolve the company from all responsibility. I may sound
paranoid, but I dont want to have to be flipping burgers at
McDonald's in my golden years. Can you address these concerns?
</P>
<P>
   L.S., Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I presume that my one of my favorites you mean the Vanguard
fund family. When you opened your IRA account, you were given a
choice of authorizing -- or not authorizing -- telephone
withdrawals. You can simply write Vanguard and change that
election, at which point neither you nor anybody else can direct a
withdrawal by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even if a telephone withdrawal has been approved, the
funds cannot be sent anywhere but to the address of record of the
owner of the account, thus considerably reducing the possibility of
interception by a hacker or thief.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that you simply inform Vanguard, or any other trustee
that you may use, in writing of the conditions which you require
for an authorized withdrawal from your accounts.
</P>
<P>
   You're right, in this modern electronic age there is a hazy
middle ground between being prudent and being paranoid. But if your
account is set up properly, I think you have very little to worry
about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
