<HEADLINE>
FALLOUT FROM MUSEUM FIRINGS CROSSES POND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He said he was sorry about firing those prestigious curators,
and he even gave them meaningless ``emeritus'' jobs to keep them
quiet. And yet bad publicity continues to dog the Boston Museum of
Fine Arts boss Malcolm Rogers's controversial four-month-old
``restructuring'' plan, better known as the Boston Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Item: Art collector and longtime MFA overseer Robert Pirie
penned an astonishing letter to London's Art Newspaper, accusing
Rogers of padding the MFA's record-breaking attendance figures and
taking credit for exhibitions and fund-raising achievements that
should properly belong to others. Pirie, a friend and supporter of
sacked European decorative arts curator Anne Poulet, states that he
is not ``a recent member of the anti-Rogers bandwagon . . . when he
first became director, I found his combination of arrogance and
pathetic insecurity so unsettling that I called one of the trustees
to express my deep concern.''
</P>
<P>
   A museum spokeswoman called the letter ``mean-spirited,
outrageous, and inaccurate. It's perfectly natural for the director
to take pride in the achievements of the staff and the trustees.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pointed envoi to his missive, Pirie wrote that several
years ago he alerted Rogers to ``serious questions as to the ethics
and integrity of a member of staff. He informed me that he was
aware of the problem and that (he) had been authorized by the
trustees to fire the individual in question. It is particularly
disappointing to discover that under the new plan the individual
has been promoted to one of the most senior positions in the
museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Item: In response to an all-points bulletin from art historians
Ruth Butler and Paul Tucker of the University of Massachusetts, and
Patricia Hills of Boston University, about 30 academics from every
major area college and university gathered at the Friends Meeting
House in Cambridge Wednesday evening to discuss the impact of
Rogers's MFA reorganization on educational programs. ``We talked a
lot about plans for museum education, and it seems that there is no
plan,'' said one participant. ``The trustees seem to be totally
oblivious about what we do.'' The group plans to write a letter to
the trustees asking for a meeting to discuss educational and
curatorial concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Item: An icy editorial in London's prestigious Burlington
Magazine compares Rogers's reorg to a similar mixmastering at the
Victoria and Albert Museum 10 years ago. (Interest in the
British-born Rogers is intense in London, where he spent many years
at the National Portrait Gallery.) ``It is a source of unease for
British observers that an approach to museum restructuring thought
to be derived from US practices and tried out in Britain with
disastrous results in the 1980s should now have been re-exported
across the Atlantic. And it is hard to imagine how anyone who lived
through the aftermath of the V &AMP; A affair could imagine that a `big
bang' restructuring would prove acceptable, or that its `collateral
damage' _ to borrow a euphemism from the US military _ would be
swiftly forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Item: The MFA has decided to loan out one of its most precious
paintings, a 12-foot-long Paul Gauguin canvas called ``Where Do We
Come From? What Are We? Where Are We Going?'' In the past, the
painting has been deemed too frail to travel, and hasn't left the
building since 1951. Most notably, it was not loaned out to the Art
Institute of Chicago's Gauguin megashow of 1988-1989 that traveled
to Washington's National Gallery and to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Now ``Come From etc.'' is slated to travel to Paris's Musee
D'Orsay for an important exhibit of Gauguin's later work, on the
100th anniversary of the artist's death. Loaning out the painting
for the Boston-Paris collaboration, explains one art maven, ``is
all about Malcolm's next job, which isn't going to be in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers's great protector, Ned Johnson, hates controversies that
he can't contain. I wonder what he thinks of this?
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
