<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE HEARTLAND, A DARKLY POETIC `BOYS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In Cold Blood,'' ``Badlands,'' ``The Executioner's Song,'' and
now, joining those grisly milestones on the heartland hit list, and
every bit their equal, is ``Boys Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   While all four films are based on brutal killings that took
place in so-called real life, the circumstances attached to the
heartbreakingly brief life of Teena Brandon, who yearned to be male
and reinvented herself as Brandon Teena, are both more wistful and
more complex. They're captured rivetingly in Kimberly Peirce's
extraordinarily layered film, which is as much about isolation and
identity as about passions that boiled over into bloodshed. Driven
by astonishing performances from Hilary Swank and Chloe Sevigny,
``Boys Don't Cry'' not only revisits the crime, but convinces us
we're being taken inside it.
</P>
<P>
   The film is as much a meditation on identity and the need of
people to live in their fantasies as it is a thriller, although no
film this year piles up the dread like ``Boys Don't Cry.'' Again
and again you ask yourself why, if Brandon needed to flee Lincoln,
Neb., he went only 75 miles down the road to the forlornly
homogeneous town of Falls City and not to the kind of large urban
center that would have offered better survival odds. The answer, as
Hilary Swank makes clear in only one facet of a richly complex
character, is that Brandon was drawn by his own hunger for
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Warped as it may seem, it doesn't take Swank's Brandon long to
stand on its ear the American myth of the stranger in town.
Although slightly built and nowhere near as strapping as the local
guys, Brandon's energy and spirit draw people to him. He's high on
the locals' acceptance of his reinvented self, and they're high on
him. He's a fun guy who works at making people like him, especially
the girls. He's more sensitive to them than any of the guys they
grew up with, knows how to please them, offers them intimacy.
Before long, he's regarded as the best kisser in town, and the guys
he joshed with over six-packs and went bumper surfing with suddenly
are markedly cooler toward the new guy in town.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't know is that Brandon is conflicted, has identity
problems, and is fleeing trouble with the law. The treats he buys
his friends and the girls he romances come from the proceeds of
stolen checks and ATM cards, and it's only a matter of time before
he slips up. At the moment, he's too happy to care because he's
actually found a girl who accepts him, reciprocates his romantic
attentions, regards his differentness as an asset. Swank does an
electrifying job of getting under Brandon's complicated skin.
Brandon is spunky, even when he's scared, even when he should be
able to sense the gathering of ominous energies and flee.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, you can feel Brandon fighting to try to finish
sculpting an identity, yet also throwing himself at partying with a
reckless exhilaration. It's his venturesomeness in the face of
their own clipped wings that lies at the heart of the threat he
poses to the two guys who befriended him, then can't handle the
energies he releases. When Brandon wins the heart of Chloe
Sevigny's local queen of cool by appealing to her wish to break out
of her confining environment, you can feel her ex-boyfriend begin
to unravel, lose what little control he has, and will his buddy
into a downward spiral that ends with bodies lying dead on the
floor of a shabby little farmhouse in a stark tundra.
</P>
<P>
   Swank's identification with the buoyant, gutsy, confused Brandon
is so complete that you don't realize until the scene is over that
you've been holding your breath, hoping that Brandon's hard-won
identity won't unravel after one of the most pitiless rape scenes
on film. The others are uniformly excellent, too, especially
Sevigny, who takes the smoky cool she summoned for ``The Last Days
of Disco'' and turns it into something anchored in documentary and
behavioral realism, yet instantly mythic. Beneath her affectless
exterior beats a warrior's heart. Brandon's yearning enkindles
hers. That's part of the reason she loves him and refuses to be put
off by him. Swank and Sevigny convince us that theirs is a
spirit-to-spirit union.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Sarsgaard, as the threatened end of the triangle, makes
the killer's terrible trajectory not only believable, but grounded
in the most mundane clodhopper behavior. He isn't a drooling
monster, he's a guy you wouldn't look at twice at a bar or a
convenience store. Without ever trying too hard, Peirce makes us
feel the ironic contrast between the wide-open spaces and the
fear-driven narrowness that rules them. The texture is unerring in
``Boys Don't Cry.'' The sullen vulnerability we can feel in
Sarsgaard and Brad Sexton's damaged misfits flies off the screen
like a distant early warning of the rage that's also gathering in
their inadequate innards.
</P>
<P>
   The flat, dilapidated world of the film defines hell as a
Nebraska of the soul, where bleakness is all, where social life
consists of leaning, stoned, against the wall of a Qwik Stop in the
middle of the night after the bars close. You can feel the force of
aborted dreams morphing into a thunderbolt of horror bent on
striking down the outsider who dares to deviate from the prevailing
misery. It's rare when a film compels you to identify with a
character on any level. In the case of ``Boys Don't Cry,'' with its
characters dancing on the line between liberation and
self-destruction, we identify with their longing souls. Peirce
turns hate crimes into felt knowledge as she turns ``Boys Don't
Cry'' into a dark poem of emotional nuking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOYS DON'T CRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed and written by: Kimberly Peirce &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Hilary Swank, Chloe Sevigny, Peter Sarsgaard, Brendan
Sexton III, Alison Folland, Alicia Goranson, Matt McGrath, Rob
Campbell, Jeannetta Arnette &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 114 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (violence, including an intense brutal rape scene,
sexuality, language, and drug use) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
