<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE TECHNOLOGY, `BATS' FLIES AT B-MOVIE LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bats'' is a reassuring little cheeseball of a movie. It proves
that if you use the latest computerized technology and you really,
really try, you can make a film that's just as cheesy as
yesteryear's B-movies in which budget-disadvantaged directors
dangled rubber bats that would absurdly bob up and down in the
frame while we went out for popcorn. Those bats were less scary
than the ones kids used to pull out of cereal boxes. The bats in
``Bats'' are superbats, genetically altered, we're told, but
they're not much scarier. Big, mean, and fast, they seem modeled on
gargoyles, which in turn were modeled on bats, so fair enough, I
guess.
</P>
<P>
   As a rural Texas sheriff, Lou Diamond Phillips looks as if he,
too, might have climbed down from a niche in a Gothic cathedral,
especially when he narrows his eyes and says, ``I'm not gonna let
'em blow my town off the face of the earth without a fight.'' The
military, whose experiments in weapons development started all the
trouble, offers its usual solution, which is to bomb the whole area
into rubble. What it doesn't realize is that doing so will only
scatter the bats. So Phillips and Dina Meyer's batologist descend
into a cave that's filled with all the guano you could hope for,
having hatched a plan to eliminate the bats with more finesse then
the Army could, although not much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bats'' is too silly to warrant further discussion, except
perhaps to note that it's the first film from a new company,
Destination Films. It now occupies the coveted nowhere-to-go-but-up
mode and soon will escalate, one assumes, from films with two
dimensions to films with three. At least ``Bats'' has enough of a
sense of humor to feature ``Nosferatu'' on the marquee of the only
theater in town. Still, ``Bats'' leaves us little to ponder, except
possibly how the intrepid bat fighters, zipped into their
contamination suits, can fall head first into a pool of liquid
guano and sport clear visors a moment later. Or why, with a swarm
of hundreds of computerized bats flying at them, they bother to
fire their pistols as often as they do, given a 1-bullet-to-1-bat
ratio. ``Bats'' bats zero.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BATS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Louis Morneau &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: John Logan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Lou Diamond Phillips, Dina Meyer, Leon, Carlos Jacott,
Bob Gunton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (intense sequences of bat attacks, and brief
language) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
