<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TANGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE TO TANGO' IS OUT OF STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Three to Tango,'' Matthew Perry and Neve Campbell come
across as cute people saddled with a lame romantic sitcom based on
mistaken gay identity.
</P>
<P>
   The character sketching is OK, especially on Campbell's part, as
she plays the mistress of Chicago tycoon Dylan McDermott, one who's
sassy and independent and no doormat. Unlike movie mistresses of
the past, she doesn't just sit around a gilded-cage love nest. She
sculpts in metal and maintains her own social life. This keeps her
rich married boyfriend insecure enough to want to keep tabs on her.
Since he can't always be around, he bullies struggling architect
Perry, whom he erroneously assumes is gay, into acting as his eyes
and ears.
</P>
<P>
   Although his partner (Oliver Platt) is gay, Perry's character is
straight. Given the large amount of time the neglected woman and
the unhappy spy spend in each other's company, and the deepening
sympathy between them, the inevitable occurs. Until it does,
however, a panopoly of gay jokes stretches drearily through a
styrofoamlike screenplay. But so labored and unfunny is the often
gay-bashing humor that it wouldn't raise a single eyelash of the
most trigger-happy network censor. McDermott labors unceasingly to
make us keep hating the rich guy's sadistic arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Platt throws a lot of resourcefulness at the thankless role of
the gay sidekick. Perry understandably spends most of the evening
looking trapped and uncomfortable. And Campbell's smart, spunky
character seems to have wandered in from some really sophisticated
comedy she can't find her way back to. ``Three to Tango'' trips
early and never gets up off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THREE TO TANGO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Damon Santostefano &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Aline Brosh McKenna, Robert Patrick Vaccaro &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Matthew Perry, Neve Campbell, Dylan McDermott, Oliver
Platt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 98 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (sex-related situations and language) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
