<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUD     10-22 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEGO-ROBOTS (Undated) _ The latest Lego robots not only
illustrate the evolution of technological play, but reveal
something about how computer technology itself might be understood
and even taught. By Edward Rothstein. (1850 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-ILLUSTRATION (New York) _ An exhibit at the New York
Public Library makes the case that scientific illustrations play a
critical role in the history of scientific and medical ideas. By
Eric Messinger.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-MERIT (Undated) _ How to define and judge merit has been at
the center of bitter debates over college admissions and
affirmative action. Reports last month that the Educational Testing
Service, creator of the most widely used college entrance
examinations, was considering a program to identify disadvantaged
students set off a whirl of protest. The plan, labeled
``Strivers,'' has been shelved, but the debate over merit
continues. The Times asked six educators how they would define that
elusive term. Joyce Jensen compiled their responses. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS-GUILD (Undated) _ A heated election for the Screen Actors
Guild. By Rich Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   POUND-BARRED (New York) _ The Cathedral Church of St. John the
Divine here bars Ezra Pound from its Poets Corner. By Dinitia
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
