<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-22 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LINES ARE DRAWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first-and-10 technology is one of those innovations that
cause viewers to ponder just how they managed to watch a football
game without it.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow line superimposed on the field has added a new
dimension to watching the game. Since its unveiling on ESPN last
season, viewers have been able to follow the chains easier than
fans attending the game.
</P>
<P>
   As new products go, this is right up there with SportsCenter _
revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this story about algorithms and three-dimensional
image processing is not without its unseemly human side.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Princeton Video Image, Inc. filed a claim
against its chief competitor, Sportvision, Inc., with the US Patent
and Trademark Office.
</P>
<P>
   PVI wants the federal government to determine who owns the
technology. One patent was issued to Fox Sports and licensed to
Sportvision and covers the technology that combines television
camera images with a tracking system to produce precise virtual
inserts.
</P>
<P>
   PVI claims it invented the technology in the late '70s, received
patents for it then, and wants the government to admit it made an
oversight in granting Fox Sports a similiar one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been aggressive in maintaining and defending our
patent position,'' said Carlo Basile, PVI's chief technology
officer. PVI is no stranger to court. Last June, it filed suit in
US District Court in Delaware against another rival, Scidel USA
Ltd., for infringement.
</P>
<P>
   At the filing of that suit, Brown Williams, cofounder and PVI
chairman, told reporters that he is intent on protecting the
company's investment. ``Our shareholders and industry colleagues
need to know that we will take vigorous action and use our patents
to protect our unique intellectual property,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   PVI's rivals are not rolling over. In response to PVI's claim,
Sportvision, which provided services to ABC, ESPN, and Fox, filed a
lawsuit against PVI for patent infringement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology was stuff we were working on in the final
stages of FoxTrax,'' said Sportvision's chief technology officer
Stan Honey in a recent issue of Broadcast &AMP; Cable magazine. ``The
way we do first and 10 doesn't practice that patent, but we're
asserting that the way PVI implements their system does practice
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology is worth the fight. At stake is the ability to
use the first-and-10 marker as well as insert advertisements. Its
revenue potential is limitless. Instead of getting permission from
individual teams or stadiums, an advertiser can have its logo
imposed behind home plate or in the end zone without interfering
with fans in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   PVI works with CBS and during last week's Patriots-Dolphins game
the network employed its first-and-10 marker.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the process works: PVI's equipment is integrated with
CBS's three main field cameras stationed at the 20-yard lines and
the 50.
</P>
<P>
   Those cameras are on the same side of the field and shoot about
90 percent of the game. The key person in the process is the PVI
spotter, who is on the sidelines and tells operators in the
production truck the line of scrimmage. The yard line is entered
into the computer and the rest is left to mathematical
computations.
</P>
<P>
   The complications are many, the most notable of which is what
Basile described as occlusion. When a running back, for instance,
crosses the virtual line he is seen without interruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The software enables the computer to determine whether
something on the field should be seen or whether the line should be
seen on a pixel-by-pixel basis,'' Basile said.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing occurs with virtual advertisements. If they are
placed behind home plate, viewers see not only the batter, catcher,
and umpire but also the advertisement in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual advertisments have not made as big an impact on the
viewing public as the first-and-10 technology. Nor has it generated
any lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. Court cases are often the unintended result of
well-intentioned ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't take the first-and-10 marker _ whoever owns it _ off
the air.
</P>
<P>
   It would be like making fans watch their local sports broadcasts
for national stories.
</P>
<P>
   It just isn't the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
