<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      10-22 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Oct. 23. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   DIST:Kansas City school district goes to federal court Friday to
ask for a hearing to have the state named once again as a defendant
in the desegregation lawsuit. That means, if granted, Judge Whipple
could halt the accreditation withdrawal. The Desegregation
Monitoring Committee's semi-annual status report on the Kansas City
School District was filed Friday, too. It's expected to be a harsh
assessment of district operations. Phil O'Connor. 25.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEG (with DIST: The state Board of Education's decision to
strip the Kansas City district of accreditation is creating lots of
anxiety for high school students who fear the decision could put a
crimp in their college plans. Seniors aren't affected because the
accreditation wouldn't disappear until the end of the school year.
But underclassmen are worried. Although the principal at Lincoln
College Prep told students in an assembly Friday morning not to
worry, they're still anxious. Some college admissions people say
they look more critically at test scores when students come from
unaccredited schools, such as home schools. And test scores are one
of the areas in which district students do poorly. Students at Van
Horn High School have scheduled a protest for Tuesday over the
accreditation decision. Photo. Lynn Franey and Kevin Hoffmann. 30.
</P>
<P>
   STARVE: Gary Bass, the second boy in the Mary Bass neglect case,
died today. The boy was malnourished and suffered third-degree
burns to his feet _ the same as his brother Larry. We're checking
with prosecutors for possible additional charges. Also will ask
school and Family Services officials for comment; they said little
on Thursday. Also will call to get more information on the mother,
who remains in custody. Christine Vendel. 20. File photo.
</P>
<P>
   BALL: A perfect story for Saturday, the day the World Series
begins: As a researcher on the Human Genome Project, Phil Ozersky
knows that just a tiny deviation can change a person entirely. So
what if that white sphere had been struck at an angle 5 degrees
greater? What if the wind would have been blowing 5 mph stronger?
Than maybe Ozersky wouldn't have caught Mark McGwire's 70th home
run ball a year ago and seen his life change. He became one of the
most sought-after and one of the most hated men in town when he
decided to sell it. But he learned about what makes life important.
His story is part of a new book called simply ``The Ball.'' Oscar
Avila. 35.
</P>
<P>
   WATER: Allied Environmental Service, an Overland Park
consultant, is convicted in Tulsa of dumping waste. Michael Mansur.
6.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD: Environmental groups upset that numerous provisions in the
Interior Dept. bill approved by Congress Friday opens the door for
lead mining in the Ozarks. Michael Mansur. 10.
</P>
<P>
   LONER. Keith D. Nelson, accused of kidnapping and murdering
Pamela Butler, showered one girlfriend with gifts on her 16th
birthday, and he went out of his way to repay a $33 loan from the
girl's mother, two years after she'd given him the money; but he
also was convicted in several burglaries and thefts, and he has
spent much of his adult life behind bars. Trisha Howard, other
staffers.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   DIP _ The nation's largest manufacturers of water heaters have
agreed to fix more than 14 million defective water heaters, making
it the largest and most expensive effort in the industry's history
to fix a product defect. By Steve Everly
</P>
<P>
   ALLIED _ The Department of Energy for the first time in 50 years
will put its contract with AlliedSignal in Kansas City up for bid.
The plant, which has suffered steady declines in employment for
more than a decade, has more than 3,000 employees. By Randolph
Heaster and Mark P. Couch. Photo
</P>
<P>
   GOVCON _ Economist David Jones and other discuss the economy at
a University of Kansas economic summit Friday. By Eric Palmer
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Y2K column. David Hayes, Finn Bullar
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER _ Jerry Heaster column
</P>
<P>
   YELLOW_ Yellow Corp. said third quarter profits rose 18 percent
as it hauled more freight and benefited from an acquisition. The
results exceeded analyst expectations. Randy Heaster
</P>
