<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; SATURDAY &LR; , Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORLD SERIES PREVIEW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-WORLDSERIES (Atlanta) _ The Yankees have won two of the past
three World Series, the Braves are in their fifth World Series of
the decade, but have won only one so far. Is the winner of this
Series the team of the '90s? And is there more pressure on the
Braves, considering their many post-season opportunities that have
ended in defeat? By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-WORLDSERIES-VECSEY-COLUMN (Atlanta) _ Sports of The Times
column: Bobby Cox had as many bad knees as his teammate, Mickey
Mantle _ just not as many home runs. Most people do not remember
that Cox escaped the minor leagues after eight long years, and in
1968 and 1969 he played third base for a Yankee team that had
fallen on hard times. ``We had players like me,'' Cox says,
alluding to his .229 and .215 batting averages. ``But it was great
to be around Hall of Famers like Whitey Ford and Mickey Mantle. My
first season was Mickey's last. He could still play.'' By George
Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS (Atlanta) _ During last year's World
Series, it was the cloud of Bernie Williams's upcoming free-agent
negotiations hovering over the Yankees. This season, the Yankees
have even more concerns on the minds as they prepare to face the
Braves: What will happen to David Cone, who doesn't seem to have a
future in the Bronx? What about Jorge Posada, who finds himself the
catcher the starting pitchers generally don't want behind the
plate? And what about the lingering bad feelings connected to the
unofficial demotion of General Manager Brian Cashman? The Yankees
are the favorites in this Series, but there all sorts of tensions
lurking beneath their surface. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-WORLDSERIES-BRAVES (Atlanta) _ Braves feature, probably
focusing on Tom Glavine, the Game 1 starter. In 1996, Glavine would
have started Game 7 against the Yankees, if the Yankees hadn't
closed out the Series in Game 6. So, in effect, Glavine is picking
up where the Braves left off three years ago. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
