<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV10-B     10-22 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR MATERIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first outside-the-box candidate for Massachusetts governor
in 2002 is Steve Grossman, a philanthropist who resuscitated the
Democratic National Committee for Bill Clinton and who now ponders
resurrecting the Massachusetts party, loser of three straight
gubernatorial races.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the field probably consists of three Irish guys
who've hung around the State House for decades, and another Irish
guy who's broken his term limits pledge to run for another
congressional term. There's no woman in the mix _ yet _ and no
Italian-American, despite the success of Italo candidates winning
the governorship and the mayor's job in the state's three biggest
cities.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Grossman has the Jewish-liberal niche nailed down. If
you're looking for a well-heeled businessman with a national track
record in party operations and a truly impressive list of
charitable, educational, and assorted do-gooder causes, this
53-year-old father of three sons may be your man.
</P>
<P>
   As yet another Princeton man in politics (Bill Bradley and Steve
Forbes are Olde Nassau grads) who holds an MBA from Harvard and is
a successful business executive, Grossman will have pots of dough
to go with his experience in political organizing and fund-raising.
And while it is true that money men and backroom guys rarely make
the leap from behind the curtain to out-front candidate, Grossman
shows signs of being the kind of coalition-builder the Democrats
have not had at the top of their last three state tickets.
</P>
<P>
   John Silber, Mark Roosevelt, and Scott Harshbarger are all
estimable chaps in many ways, but none succeeded in bringing to
heel the sullen and surly satraps of the various fiefdoms that make
up the Democratic Party hereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   As a deeply devout heir to a prosperous family business in
envelopes, printing, and design _ a business that has blossomed
under his stewardship _ Grossman has made a steady, unspectacular
climb up the rungs of the civic leadership ladder.
</P>
<P>
   He's chairman of the Brandeis University trustees, and sits on a
dozen other boards (including the Museum of Fine Arts, Children's
Hospital, Combined Jewish Philanthropies, Anti-Defamation League,
Robert Kennedy Memorial). He's been chairman of the Massachusetts
Democrats, the Democratic National Committee from '97 to '99, and
formerly headed AIPAC, the domestic Israel lobby that exercises
great clout in Congress. He's married to Barbara Grossman, a
professor and theater historian at Tufts.
</P>
<P>
   He's never been elected to public office, which used to be a
drawback, but is now almost a sine qua non for outside challengers
who bring success from the private sector into races for high
public office. He is a demon organizer: ``You write the script for
a general election victory by how many Democrats and unenrolled
voters you can organize and get to the polls on primary day.'' Both
Silber ('90) and Harshbarger ('98) lost what Grossman calls
``winnable elections because of the virtual absence of party
unity.''
</P>
<P>
   While not officially declared, Grossman is recruiting top-flight
national political talent skilled in building turnout using
precinct organization, phone banks, and direct mail. He is a
student of the biz. He'd like to see experiments on the local level
with weekend elections and interactive voting via the Internet in
order to boost civic involvement. ``We're still voting the way we
were when we were an agrarian society,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to run,'' Grossman allows. ``I think I have a good
story to tell.'' His ancestors came to Massachusetts from Eastern
Europe at the turn of the century. Max Grossman, his grandfather,
and then Edgar Gossman, his father, drilled into him ``the
importance of always reinvesting in the life of the community.''
The family ethic, ``try to enrich, enlarge, and enlighten the life
of the community,'' is writ large in the Grossman clan.
</P>
<P>
   MassEnvelopePlus is a union shop of 120 employees, who average
20 years with the company. Grossman's salesman's drill translates
to politics: ``Every voter has to be treated like a customer, with
all that entails, if you want to keep his or her trust.''
</P>
<P>
   He approaches vote-seeking in businesslike fashion. ``People
want to follow people who can clearly define a sense of priorities.
We have a right to expect better than `ordinary,' better than
`run-of-the-mill.' '' Citing his stewardship at the DNC, where he
reduced the debt from $18 million to $5 million in the teeth of the
Clinton scandals gale, Grossman said, ``I have certainly
demonstrated that I can throw a punch. I think I can demonstrate
that I can take a punch. I really want to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get that opportunity. The early line on the Democratic
field to confront the plodding Cellucci administration's record is
that both legislative leaders, Senate President Tom Birmingham and
House Speaker Tom Finneran, will explore the race, as well as
Secretary of State William Galvin, and US Representative Marty
Meehan of Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman will not be the kind of candidate whose bid revolves
around the State House. His model is the 1982 campaign of Mike
Dukakis, a triumph of field organizing that toppled incumbent
Democrat Ed King in a high primary turnout of around 50 percent. He
knows he'll have to take some flak along his flight plan. ``I will
know when I'm a serious candidate, when people start training the
heavy artillery on me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Grossman does not have the service stripes of the
aforementioned four, neither is he tainted by State House longevity
or congressional hangover. Moving up statewide from either
background is problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman's career is grounded in a Jewish tradition of community
service. He recites by heart a biblical proverb: ``If you offer
your compassion to the hungry and satisfy the famished creature,
then shall your light shine in darkness and your gloom shall be
like noonday. . . . And you shall be known as the rebuilder of
ancient ruins, the restorer of dwelling places, the repairer of the
breach.'' (Isaiah: 58)
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats are looking for someone to take them back to
the ancient ruin of the Corner Office, here's a man who says he has
a plan.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
