<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-MTV-VIOLENCE-TEX     10-22 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-VIOLENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIEW FROM THE STREET IS BRUTAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The violence on the screen is shocking: A handful of young men
set upon another young man in a field and beat him into the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   They pound him, fists flailing, raining blows. They kick him as
he lies there; one leans down and punches him full in the face.
Hard.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a scene out of ``Fight Club''. It is the real world
of gang activity on Fort Worth's south side _ a new member being
``beaten in'' to membership, as captured by J.B. Sanchez, a
20-year-old Cassata High School graduate who, for the past four
years, has been a member of the SUR Trece (Southern United Raza
Thirteen) gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I've seen everything from domestic violence to
straight-up someone getting their brains blown out in front of
me,'' Sanchez says. ``I've seen everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sanchez is showing the nation via ``Fight for Your Rights:
Through My Eyes,'' the latest installment of MTV's ``Fight for Your
Rights: Take a Stand Against Violence,'' a yearlong anti-violence
campaign. Sanchez is one of three young people given video cameras
by the music network and told to film examples of how violence
affects their lives. The 30-minute show premieres Sunday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   This past Tuesday, Sanchez was in Washington, D.C., speaking
about his experiences at a congressional conference on youth
violence. Sanchez was part of a panel discussion that followed the
premiere of ``Through My Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the program is footage and commentary from
19-year-old Betina Lynn, who was wounded in May 1998 in a shooting
at her Oregon high school, and Rick Godoy Jr., a 23-year-old from
Long Island who is trying to come to terms with the abuse he
suffered at the hands of his father, with whom he still lives.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the three stories make for an intense, fascinating
program _ albeit one that may well leave a viewer with a desire to
know more about the three. Lynn talks about feeling alienated from
her peers even as she's leaving for her first semester of college;
Godoy's segment is heartbreaking as he confronts his father about
his beatings (which regularly escalated to 50 ``hits'' or more with
a belt) and recognizes that he, too, may become violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to hear those kids,'' Sanchez says of the
conference. ``We were all there to stop one thing; people are tired
of this, but nobody knows how to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez says he joined the gang to feel a sense of family; he
was adopted, and even though he had a ``good life'' and enjoyed
gymnastics and journalism, ``blood mattered, and I didn't know any
people that were my blood. The gang became my substitute family. I
wanted a family atmosphere. A few of them became my real family;
one is my son's godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez says a friend was killed in a drive-by shooting several
years ago while he was in the next room; his footage shows other
gang members proudly displaying their weapons and one showing where
bullets from another drive-by are lodged in the walls of his house.
It also shows another gang member being ``beaten out'' of the gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned violence can happen anywhere to anybody _ it's just
the shape the world's in,'' he says, adding that the random
shootings at Columbine High School and Fort Worth's Wedgwood
Baptist Church are ``the worst type of crime. They're so hard to
prevent. It's the outcasts. It's impossible to tell who is going to
go off.''
</P>
<P>
   J.B.'s perspective changed Feb. 11, 1998, the day his son,
Isaiah, was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `You have a child in your hands _ God gave you
the responsibility,' '' he says. ``We pollute kids with violence,
and I decided my son was not going to go that route.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, he says, he just wanted to ``slow down'' his gang
activity (''I was haywire''), but then he decided he had to ``step
away.'' So this summer, he took a job as a salesman at a Fort Worth
company and is settling into the life of a working joe, even as he
and his wife, Carmen, prepare for the arrival of a second son, due
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   He is still part of SUR Trece, but not active, and he is
weighing the options of continuing to work, enrolling in a
community college or joining the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, my job is to take care of my family,'' he says.
``All the gang members want to see the best for him (Isaiah). But
if it comes down to it, if they're getting jumped or something, I'm
gonna be right there. They're my heart, and they always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is a pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
