<HEADLINE>
SENDING MASS E-MAILS NOT AGAINST LAW IF YOU ONLY SEND TO THOSE WHO
WANT IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I am an 82-year-old novice at e-mail and I need
some help. About 18 months ago I established a Web site where I
sell queen bees and beekeeping books. Now, I want to send e-mail
advertising to my customer list, but I do not know the rules,
regulations and laws governing such use of e-mail. When I called my
provider, a technician told me that sending unsolicited advertising
by e-mail is illegal. However, I get a monthly letter from Lycos.
How do they get away with sending thousands of copies of their
advertising? Can you help me? Will you help me?
</P>
<P>
   A: The person at your Internet service provider told you wrong.
Sending unsolicited commercial e-mail, or spam, is not illegal.
There's no legislation against it. However, it probably is against
your provider's rules. So, if you do it, you can be kicked off that
particular service.
</P>
<P>
   But, the key word here is ``unsolicited.'' If you have customers
who want to get an e-mail from you about your business, that's not
spam. The key is to get their permission.
</P>
<P>
   At Lycos, when you signed up for access to certain areas of that
Web site, there probably was a check box that indicated you were
willing to receive the Lycos newsletter. You can do the same. When
someone buys from you online, set up some way to ask whether they
would like to receive information from you about your business.
Those who say ``yes'' can get the e-mail; those that say ``no''
won't.
</P>
<P>
   It's important that you let people know that you are going to
send them mail if they indicate they want it. In the mail you send
them, always indicate that you're willing to remove them should
they request it _ and then honor that request.
</P>
<P>
   You also should work with your provider so he or she knows what
you're doing. If you're sending out several thousand e-mails _
which, given the nature of your business, is probably not the case
_ you should make sure your provider can handle it. Make contact
with the provider and explain exactly what you're doing and ask for
help. That way, there are no surprises. Internet providers hate
surprises of this kind.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, regarding the legality of unsolicited commercial
e-mail ... You may see at the bottom of some spam a notice saying
the e-mail complies with a federal legislation. This is bogus, an
attempt to make the recipient think there's nothing to be done
about receiving the spam. There was a proposed bill in the Senate
that would have regulated spam, but it went nowhere. Don't be
fooled.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, remember never to respond to the instructions for
removing yourself from a spam list that appears at the bottom of
many spammers' e-mails. This is, in almost all cases, a way for the
spammer to verify that an e-mail address is good.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Thanks to the stories on MP3 music files that have appeared
in the Chronicle over the past few months, I've really gotten into
them. They sound great! But I have been trying to download some of
my favorite tunes from pirate sites without much luck. Some say to
upload something _ when I do, I still don't have access.
</P>
<P>
   A: Remember that when you grab a song from a site that illegally
posts music _ usually taken off a compact disc _ you're violating
copyright laws. By downloading these songs, you're denying the
artists who made them royalties.
</P>
<P>
   You have a right to convert songs on a CD to MP3 files _ done
using a type of software program known as a ``ripper'' _ for your
own personal use, so long as you also own a copy of the CD.
However, once you give away that file, you've violated the artist's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   On sites such as MP3.com, which are full of songs for the
taking, most of the artists essentially have given up some of their
rights, hoping to get greater exposure for their music.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
