<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-22 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENDS MAY LEAVE TRAVEL AGENTS ZERO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ How low can it go? How about zero? That's the amount
of commission airlines will someday pay travel agents to sell
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have long sold 80 percent of their tickets through
travel agents. Now, they're doing their best to directly sell
tickets to most customers, cutting out agents. Five years ago,
travel agents received a straight 10 percent commission on air
tickets. Then came commission cuts and caps. Last week, major U.S.
airlines cut agent commissions to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. It used to cost airlines 22 percent of the retail
ticket price for distribution. That included selling, delivering
and accounting for the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with a 6 percent distribution cost in manufacturing
and 2 percent in banking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AIRLINE ADVANCES PUT SQUEEZE ON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then technological advances cut costs, allowing airlines to save
money by cutting out travel agents:
</P>
<P>
   _ Long-distance telephone deregulation: Airlines no longer had
to staff telephone reservation centers everywhere they operated.
Long-distance costs plunged, so airlines could have fewer, but more
efficient, centers located in areas where land, buildings and labor
costs were less.
</P>
<P>
   _ Electronic ticketing: Paper airline tickets had to be mailed
or hand-delivered _ usually by a travel agent. Now, half of all
tickets are paperless. The passenger gets a confirmation number,
the same system used by hotels for decades. Take the number to the
airline counter, flash personal identification and get a boarding
pass. Issuing the boarding pass completes the bookkeeping process.
The airlines don't have to pay big bucks to reconcile computer
records with millions of paper tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet: It costs the airlines pennies, instead of
dollars, to distribute their tickets when you book directly on
their Internet Web sites. That's why many airlines are giving those
who book on their Web sites special deals _ 10 percent off the
regular price, Internet-only deals or extra frequent flier miles.
Internet Web sites also allow airlines to bypass the existing
computerized reservation systems that charge the airlines for
booking tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DIFFERENT CLASSES, DIFFERENT EFFECTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commission cuts will hit different classes of customers in
different ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ Large corporations: Many of these already are paying so-called
net fares. That is, the travel agency gives the corporation its
commission and charges a booking fee. The commission cuts mean
corporations will put pressure on agents to renegotiate those
booking fees. The travel agents will in turn put pressure on their
corporate customers to book more tickets on air carriers that give
the agency a price cut on tickets. Airlines are willing to make
those deals if they offer substantially more business. The
agency-corporate client customer struggle is complicated by the
fact that airlines now let corporations deal directly with them by
setting up in-house travel agencies owned by the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle will force the large travel agencies to become even
more efficient, or see their deals with large corporations
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small businesses and consumers buying air-only travel: Most
travel agents now are charging those customers fees of $10 to $15
for the booking. Expect those fees to jump by $10. These
travel-agent clients will have essentially the same choice many of
us make when we hire someone to do our income taxes. Is it
worthwhile to spend the time learning and using the Internet to
find the best fare? Or do we pay a fee to the travel agent to do it
for us?
</P>
<P>
   _ Vacation travelers: Those who buy package deals _ air plus
hotel or resort stays, rental cars and the like, will see little
change due to the commission cuts. Airlines are still paying
commissions of 10 percent or more on air fares when they are part
of a package. They don't want to take the time necessary to deal
with these kinds of customers who require much more hand-holding
than the business traveler who knows where he wants to go and when.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's going to happen to travel agents? The efficient ones
_ and that generally means big ones _ will be able to provide
cost-effective services to business travelers and will survive.
Smaller travel agencies will increasingly shift their business away
from air travel to vacation packages and cruises that still carry
commissions of 10 percent or better.
</P>
<P>
   However, inevitably, the distribution revolution also will move
into the vacation business. Leisure travel agencies must be more
than order-takers. They must really know the kinds of travel they
are selling so well that clients are willing to pay for their
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
