<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS GATHER UNDER SIX FLAGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The labor market is tight and it's hard for employers
to find good workers. So, where can a company turn when it has to
hire a lot of workers for a short time?
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags Astroworld in Houston has hit upon a winning formula _
it finds charitable groups to bring in volunteers to work each
weekend in October during the park's Halloween promotion. The
volunteers serve food, work the cash registers and sell souvenirs
in the gift shop in exchange for a donation to their organization.
</P>
<P>
   For every worker, Astroworld donates between $5.50 and $7 an
hour, depending on how long the group has been working at the park
and how many of the scheduled volunteers show up for each shift.
</P>
<P>
   It's an appealing way to raise money for groups that are tired
of going door to door selling candy, greeting cards and wrapping
paper, said Linda Aleman, director of human resources for Six Flags
Astroworld.
</P>
<P>
   The park has a regular staff during the summer, but when the
park cranks up for Halloween, it's a struggle to find workers just
for the weekends, Aleman said. She estimates she has about 200
volunteers working each Friday, Saturday and Sunday during October.
</P>
<P>
   SixFlags has 117 registered groups, ranging from churches to
sporting teams to sororities that are doing everything from raising
money for a trip to buying baseball uniforms. Typically, each group
provides 10 to 20 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   To make it even more appealing, the park also gives five
complimentary tickets for every 100 hours worked with at least 90
percent coming as promised, Aleman said. The group can then raffle
the tickets during a charity auction or give them away to their
volunteers who have logged the most hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PARK PLEASED WITH PROGRAM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten great people,'' said Aleman. Some have had so
much fun that they've come back as regular employees.
</P>
<P>
   And the program has been popular with the supervisors in the
park, Aleman said. Some of the managers request certain groups as
well as particular volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers must be at least 16 years old, undergo a criminal
background check and adhere to the same rules that govern
Astroworld employees: no fingernail polish, no beards except if the
wearer has a medical condition and no multiple earrings.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers are also asked to wear khaki bottoms _ skirt,
pants or shorts _ and navy blue shirts. They all wear a button
identifying them as a volunteer and that they're raising money for
their group.
</P>
<P>
   Because they aren't considered employees, Astroworld is required
to pay any employment taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a great way to raise money, said Scott Nichols,
assistant pastor and minister of music for the Irvington
Pentecostal Church in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, church members began spending their free time at
Astroworld to raise $20,000 to send their choir to Detroit. That
worked so well that now the church is trying to raise enough money
to landscape and buy computers for its school, the Irvington
Christian Academy.
</P>
<P>
   The church should earn about $15,000 between July and the end of
October, said Nichols, which will go a long way toward buying a
computer for every student.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to get volunteers, Nichols said, even the 70 that
Astroworld has requested for Oct. 30. It just took about 10 minutes
out of the church service to get 55 signed up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, who has logged hours of picking up cigarette butts,
said he often goes to the park with his volunteers so he can give
them breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want them to have an enjoyable experience so they
volunteer again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Funny circumstances can pop up, he said. For example, lawyers
and accountants who volunteer are sometimes supervised by
16-year-olds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOME ARE NOT AMUSED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As attractive as the volunteer opportunity is to some groups,
it's a turnoff for other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Miller, president of the Parent Teacher Organization at
Herod Elementary in Houston, floated the idea of working at
Astroworld at a recent PTO meeting. The response was less than
enthusiastic, with parents offering to ``write a check,'' instead
of spending their free time making snow cones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be making enough money to do it,'' Miller said
later. She said she would give it more consideration if the wages
were higher _ something on the order of $10 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our PTO does too much already,'' she said. ``It's hard enough
to get (parents) to come to school and read to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
