<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES-BRAVES MATCHUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Buster Olney's scouting report on the World Series: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YANKEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pitching &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The experience of the Yankees' starters should be a major factor
in this series, as they take advantage of the reckless
aggressiveness of the Braves' lineup. Orlando Hernandez, David Cone
and Andy Pettitte will all throw off-speed pitches and breaking
balls to the fringes of the strike zone, or just out of the strike
zone, and try to tempt the Braves' hitters. Roger Clemens, who
starts Game 4, pitched poorly against Boston and Atlanta pounded
him for six runs in six innings in July, but Clemens pitched much
better at Yankee Stadium (3.56 ERA) than on the road (6.20) this
year. Mariano Rivera and Ramiro Mendoza were exceptional against
the Red Sox, but the other middle relievers _ Jeff Nelson, Mike
Stanton, et al _ have been erratic, and are a concern as the World
Series begins. Watch the match-ups of Hernandez versus Ryan Klesko
(5-for-5 in his career) and Andruw Jones (2-for-4).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hitting &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, as always, is the standard-bearer; Jimy Williams,
the Boston manager, felt that Boston's failure to cope with Jeter
and Chuck Knoblauch was a major factor in the Red Sox defeat. Paul
O'Neill, recovering from a broken rib, swung better in the last
games of the league championship series, but he still isn't driving
the ball with his usual authority. The Yankees should be successful
in driving up the pitch counts of Tom Glavine, John Smoltz and
Kevin Millwood in particular, and they will need the middle third
of their lineup _ Tino Martinez, Darryl Strawberry, Scott Brosius,
Ricky Ledee _ to capitalize on opportunities created by the top of
the order. The Yankees' matched up poorly with Boston's left-handed
relievers late in games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Defense &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Just when Manager Joe Torre finally dealt with the Chuck
Knoblauch issue head on and decided to remove him in the late
innings, Luis Sojo's availability is now a question mark. But
Knoblauch's confidence seems to come and go, and after dealing with
his throwing problems publicly this week, he seemed far more
relaxed; earlier this year, he played much better after talking
about it. O'Neill and Ledee will have trouble in the expanded
outfield of Turner Field. The Yankees' pitchers do a poor job of
holding on runners, and when opposing runners steal _ and the
Braves will be aggressive _ it's usually the fault of the pitchers
most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; X-factor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' hitters are good at making adjustments, and it may
be that if the World Series lasts five, six or seven games, the
veterans in Torre's lineup will adjust to the Atlanta left-handers,
as they become more familiar with them. John Rocker, Mike
Remlinger, Terry Mulholland might have a far more difficult time
late in the series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ATLANTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pitching &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' starting pitching has been the foundation of the
team for years, and that hasn't changed, especially when Atlanta
plays at home _ the Braves had a 3.21 ERA at home, compared to 4.06
on the road. Tom Glavine, the Game 1 starter, is like the Yankees'
Andy Pettitte in that he needs the home plate umpire to call
strikes on pitches low and away to right-handed batters; otherwise,
he might be in trouble. Greg Maddux can be dominant, but he also
has been knocked around some this year. Kevin Millwood is probably
the best of the Braves' pitchers right now, and he will pitch Game
3 and would pitch Game 7. The Braves' bullpen is much deeper than
that of the Yankees, with middle men Russ Springer, Kevin
McGlinchy, Terry Mulholland and Mike Remlinger. John Rocker is the
closer and when he threw first-pitch strikes this year, batters hit
just .136 against him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Offense &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' hitting philosophy is patience; the Braves' is
aggressiveness. Almost all of them are free swingers, and almost
all of them are capable of stealing bases. Atlanta did manage to be
patient in the first inning of Game 6 against the Mets and scored
five runs against Al Leiter, and they need to be more patient
against the crafty Orlando Hernandez and the relentless David Cone,
who rarely gives them pitches to hit. Once they get on base, just
about everybody in their lineup, except for the catcher Eddie
Perez, will look to run and create offense. The Yankees, like other
teams, probably will try to make sure that Chipper Jones, the
likely MVP winner in the NL this year, doesn't beat them; they'll
pitch around Jones and go after Brian Jordan and Ryan Klesko, who
follow Jones. They'll all remember the dangerousness of Andruw
Jones, who slugged two homers in the first game of the World Series
in `96.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Defense &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a great outfield, with Gerald Williams, Andruw
Jones and Brian Jordan, and all of the can throw. Bret Boone is the
best second baseman not named Roberto Alomar, and the catcher Eddie
Perez has a reputation for working well with pitchers; that's what
kept him in the big leagues for years. But Chipper Jones has not
played as well at third this year _ sometimes he seems to have
trouble on the hard infield of Turner Field _ and Walt Weiss has
minimal range at shortstop. Ryan Klesko is a terrible first baseman
who probably would be replaced late in games, when the Braves had
the lead, by Brian Hunter, who is much better.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; X-factor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The weakness of the Yankees' pitching staff clearly is its
middle relief, but to get into that, the Braves must find a way to
build the pitch counts of the Yankees' starters. They have to be
more patient, win at least one or both of the first two games at
Turner Field and establish themselves right away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
