<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-VECSE     10-22 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ATLANTA MANAGER WAS ONCE A YANKEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bobby Cox had as many bad knees as his teammate,
Mickey Mantle _ just not as many home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Most people do not remember that Cox escaped the minor leagues
after eight long years, and in 1968 and 1969 he played third base
for a Yankee team that had fallen on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had players like me,'' Cox says, alluding to his .229 and
.215 batting averages. ``But it was great to be around Hall of
Famers like Whitey Ford and Mickey Mantle. My first season was
Mickey's last. He could still play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox still enjoys the only city and the only franchise he ever
represented as a player. He walks around New York on his
reconstructed knees and sometimes people recognize his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on television a lot,'' explains this very noticeable
employee of the Turner empire.
</P>
<P>
   His main identification is man who has managed 2,725 games with
the Braves and the Toronto Blue Jays and then the Braves again, and
another 98 in the post-season. Saturday night the Braves will take
on his old team in the first game of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Many public fignd to forget the humble people they once
were, have great gaps in the tapes of their lives. Take it from
somebody who covered the Yankees back in those bad old days: Cox
was a decent guy, scuffling to hang on in the major leagues,
grateful just to have the chance. And at the age of 58, Cox has
never forgotten the insecurities of the marginal ball player.
</P>
<P>
   The optimistic public persona of Manager Cox is directly traced
to Ralph Houk, his Yankee manager, who was known for his Pollyanna
pronouncements. When Marshall Bridges served up a grand slam in the
1962 World Series, Houk took a defiant puff on his cigar and
informed reporters, ``He only made one bad pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   One did not laugh at such pronouncements from Houk, whose
nickname to lazy headline writers was Major, because of his rank
from a battlefield commission during World War II. Once asked if
losing a doubleheader was the worst thing that ever happened to
him, Houk calmly replied, ``Yeah _ except for the Battle of the
Bulge.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Houk rarely spoke of the war, but his
background still showed in the way he stuck up for his civilian
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the pleasure to play for Ralph, and he was as supportive
as they come, and a real tough guy,'' Cox said the other day. ``But
he knew the value of communication, with players who normally
didn't play. The superstars always take care of themselves. It's
the other guys you have to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox was one of the other guys. His knees gave out in the spring
of 1970, and he agreed to finish his career with the Yankees' AAA
team in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I was going to go back to college in California,''
Cox said. ``My agenda was to be a high-school football coach.''
</P>
<P>
   He was days away from leaving baseball when he was sought out by
Lee MacPhail, the Yankee general manager and one of the more
genteel lifers in the baseball industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee said there was going to be an opening in Fort Lauderdale,
and he thought I should take it,'' Cox recalled. ``I always wanted
to manage, but I always felt somebody should ask you first. He
convinced me, and it was the best decision I ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever gracious to people he knew way back when, Cox makes sure to
thank his two mentors whenever he sees them, or can send a message
to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really loved managing right away,'' Cox said. ``I approached
it that I was going to get everybody on my team to the major
leagues. I almost killed myself. We had an extended camp in Fort
Lauderdale into June, and I had 45 players and was pretty much by
myself. There was a workout at 10 a.m.and another at 3 p.m. and
then the regulars at 5 p.m. I loved every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living in the clubhouse, because I didn't have a lot of
money and I was there so much anyway,'' Cox said. ``One of the
executives said it didn't look so great sleeping in Ralph's office,
so I took a motel room.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a game over .500 the first year. And, yes, four of his
pitchers would have brief shots in the major leagues. ``Not bad for
the Florida State League,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   He moved up the Yankee chain until he managed the Braves from
1978 through 1981, (replaced by Joe Torre, who wound up in the
playoffs his first season), Toronto from 1982 through 1985 and then
he became general manager of the Braves, returning to the dugout in
1990, always remaining a player's manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get on a player, and have, as good as anybody in the
world,'' Cox said. ``But certainly when we leave, we understand
each other, and it hasn't been printed and nobody knows about it.
At least most of the cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Most. Nobody has missed Cox's annoyance with John Rocker for
taking on the vicious fringe of Shea Stadium, although Cox notes
that some of the language ``would make the mildest man want to
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves seem to regard Cox with the same professional
appreciation that the Yankees had for Houk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bobby does a great job with the tactical side of the
game,'' said Tom Glavine, who will start Saturday night. ``What
makes a good manager is calling the right players, and then it's up
to the players to execute. But it's just a joy to play for the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times when I know I've pitched a terrible
game, and I read the newspaper and I'm seeing some of the things
Bobby says and I'm wondering if he was watching the same game,''
Glavine added.
</P>
<P>
   Cox was purposefully polite about Bobby Valentine of the Mets in
the past series, but he eagerly calls Torre a ``class act,'' and
praises George Steinbrenner for his intensity. Anybody looking for
a grudge match will not find it here. Bobby Cox sounds proud of
their stewardship of his old team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
