<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES MONEY TO RUN A CAMPAIGN, BUT IT TAKES IDEAS TO GET MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sooner or later, it's bound to happen. Some candidate will drop
out of the race for the Republican presidential nomination and will
NOT blame his failure on the front-runner's fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, maybe it won't happen. Maybe the money thing
is just too convenient an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Even Elizabeth Dole fell into the trap the other day when she
shut down a presidential campaign that was going nowhere fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line remains money,'' said Dole, explaining that
she couldn't compete with the record-setting fund raising of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush or the virtually unlimited financial resources
of publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be futile to continue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   We might have expected something more elegant and less
self-serving from Dole, who is unquestionably one of the classiest
individuals ever to wade into the muck of electoral politics. Then
again, maybe she figured that if it was good enough for Lamar
Alexander and Dan Quayle, it was good enough for her.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, it's hard to begrudge Dole the meager comfort of a
ready-made and seemingly plausible pretext for the precipitous
collapse of a campaign that she and others had assumed would be
highly competitive.
</P>
<P>
   This ``money is the message'' alibi has become the official
face-saving device for unsuccessful candidates in recent years.
Dole has as much right to use it as a rationalization for the
failure of her campaign as anyone else does.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the current preoccupation with campaign finance
reform as the would-be solution to every problem associated with
politics and government. A candidate who has little or nothing to
offer can distract the public from his or her lack of ideas by
whining about his or her lack of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Since money is considered the source of all evil in politics,
candidates who don't have money can pass themselves off as victims
of the predatory money machine.
</P>
<P>
   This money-is-the-problem theory undeniably makes a great excuse
for politicians who can't get their campaigns off the ground. As a
basis for analyzing what's going on in an election campaign,
however, it's about as valuable as a future-book wager on Quayle
for president.
</P>
<P>
   We're always hearing how awful it is that certain candidates are
forced to drop out of the race before a single citizen ever gets a
chance to step into the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that bucks are becoming more important than the
ballot,'' Republican presidential candidate John McCain told The
Associated Press after the Dole campaign bit the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Many pundits _ and many politicians who have trouble raising
money _ talk about the fund-raising aspect of seeking office as if
it's an illegitimate part of the political process. But where do
these folks think the money comes from?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Bush has raised nearly $60 million _ but he
didn't get that money from some mysterious kingmaker who decided
that Bush should be president and wrote a check to make it happen.
Yes, Bush relies in large part on a network of experienced
fund-raisers but most of the money is contributed in amounts of
$1,000 or less _ often much less _ by individuals who believe that
he is the best person to represent the Republican Party in next
year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true about Al Gore and Bill Bradley on the
Democratic side. The millions they have raised are the result of
the esteem and/or loyalty they command among potential
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are drawn to a candidate's positions on issues or
his aura of leadership or merely the perception that he is
``electable,'' campaign contributors are voting with their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   McCain commented that Elizabeth Dole lost ``the battle of
bucks'' rather than the ``battle of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Dole had truly been competitive in the battle of ideas _
if she had articulated compelling ideas and shown an ability to
sell them to the electorate _ then she'd have been competitive in
the battle of bucks as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
