<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5234 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     10-22 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN AND SHUT CASE OF PUBLIC BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was clear this wasn't going to be a run-of-the-mill
professional seminar when the CEO of a non-profit group created to
invest billions of public dollars complained about having to
conduct business in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists from across the state convened in Austin this month
for the annual Freedom of Information conference sponsored by the
Freedom of Information Foundation of Texas. This year's meeting was
titled Access 2000, and topics ranged from how the Internet is
affecting access to information to horror stories from reporters
and citizens who had the devil of a time getting their hands on
what is supposed to be public information.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``What happens when public contracts go private?'' seminar,
Thomas Ricks, president and CEO of the University of Texas
Investment Management Co., said that the edict from the UT Board of
Regents _ his bosses _ for his group to abide by the open meetings
laws that govern state agencies is going to stifle honest
discussion about the company's activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is public access vs. the quality of
deliberations,'' Ricks said. ``Open meetings are scripted, devoid
of fireworks and controversy. The level of deliberation will suffer
because of the risk of having it misconstrued or scrutinized by the
media. Open meetings will drive critical self-evaluation
underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, isn't that a fine how-do-you-do from a man overseeing more
than 11 billion ``public'' dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A little background may be in order for readers not familiar
with UTIMCO.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas System is funded through the Permanent
University Fund, money that comes from surface income and mineral
receipts from state-owned land. That money is partly doled out for
academic programs and facilities in the University of Texas System
and the Texas A&AMP;M System. The rest is invested in equities, stocks
and bonds that generate dividend and interest income.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, the UT Board of Regents, with the blessing of the
state Legislature, created UTIMCO, a non-profit management
corporation whose only job is to invest the endowment and operating
funds that are under the purview of the regents.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, UTIMCO has handled more than $11 billion of
University of Texas endowment money as well as the PUF.
</P>
<P>
   The first three years of UTIMCO's existence have been rocky ones
when it came to relations with folks wanting to know how and with
whom that money was being invested. Decisions were made behind
closed doors, even though the fund managers were working with
billions of public dollars. It wasn't until this summer that the UT
Board of Regents finally directed UTIMCO to abide by the same open
meetings rules that every other state agency has to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear from Ricks' comment Oct. 8 that he's less than
happy about this development.
</P>
<P>
   The need for savvy investment of state money isn't at question.
Texas' institutions of higher learning should be able to enjoy the
same benefits from the booming economy and red-hot investment
markets that private investors have seen in this decade. That's one
of the reasons for Proposition 17 on the Nov. 2 ballot. It will
allow more flexibility in how the Permanent University Fund is
invested, revising a more than 120-year-old constitutional
provision that strictly limits the Board of Regents from taking
advantage of today's economic and investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Prop 17 isn't the problem; the vehicle that the board of regents
is using to make those investments might be.
</P>
<P>
   UTIMCO held its first open meeting on Sept. 22, 1999, more than
three years after the investment mechanism was formed.
</P>
<P>
   In the dark days _ days when information about how investments
were being decided was unattainable _ serious questions arose about
relationships between board members and the companies that received
millions of dollars of state money for investment purposes. The
Houston Chronicle has been dogged in its pursuits of open meetings
for UTIMCO. In a, article March 22, 1999, the Chronicle reported
that UTIMCO directed $252 million to private investment funds run
by friends and associates of board chairman Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   His name is certainly familiar to professional sports fans as
the owner of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Hicks was not pleased by the Chronicle's
coverage, accusing the newspaper of constructing ``an elaborate and
false scheme to explain a series of completely separate
transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't just been those pesky media people questioning
UTIMCO's operations. State auditors expressed concerns about the
potential for conflicts of interest for UTIMCO's board members and
criticized the secrecy of its investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because private investments ... may create subtle
relationships among the parties involved, strong controls are
needed to ensure that potential conflicts of interest are
adequately identified, resolved and disclosed,'' the Chronicle
reported as findings of state auditors in a 1996 report.
</P>
<P>
   Without question Hicks is a adroit businessman, and his presence
on the UTIMCO board, along with eight other highly qualified men
and women, is an asset to the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas voters must be able to serve as the check and balance
as to how public dollars are being invested. State appointments
must not become opportunities to feather one's nest, or the nests
of friends and business associates. The only way to assure that
that doesn't happen is to keep meetings and records open.
</P>
<P>
   The media's ``scrutiny'' of UTIMCO's activities is being done on
behalf of all Texans. Mr. Ricks, get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV24-     10-22 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARVING OUT A HIDEAWAY WHERE IT'S ALREADY HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 24) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been spending a lot of weekends down at the family farm in
Maryland sitting on a knoll overlooking a field of soybeans that
slopes down to a stream that winds through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   There's a great blue heron living somewhere nearby. I see it in
the evenings, flapping slowly along the edge of the trees. Now and
then, a hawk will sail over the field, looking for mice and voles.
Sometimes I hear its high-pitched ``screee-screee!'' from the
trees. Is it talking to its mate? Warning off other predators? Just
celebrating the light filtering through the canopy?
</P>
<P>
   I've wandered over these fields since I was a little girl. The
curves of the hills are as familiar to me as the lines of my own
body. But now, I'm looking at everything with new eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I've decided I want to build a house on this knoll, on the farm
my family has lived on for 200 years. A simple house so molded to
the land that a person walking down the old farm road would be
surprised to see it come into focus. Should it be shaped like a
small, weathered barn, I wonder, with big doors that roll open to
let in the light? Or should it be an earth house with a sod roof
that could be planted with meadow grasses? Maybe Maryland is too
muggy, too heavy with clay for such a design.
</P>
<P>
   Why not power it with a little windmill? And the sun, now that
solar cells are cheaper and smaller. And when the mosquitoes start
biting, I think ``screened porch'' _ but that doesn't go with a
barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you should put an old trailer down there and live on
that hill for a while,'' said a friend who built her own house on
family land in Vermont 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then I would learn important things I've never really noticed
all these years. Exactly how the light slants through the trees
that act as a hedgerow at the top of the field. Where the water
drains during a hard rain falling on heavy clay soil. How hot it
gets in summer, how buggy, how dry, how dark. There are no lights
from roads or other houses down there, just the moon and the stars.
</P>
<P>
   And now I will get to know them, lying on my back at night,
charting the course of Cassiopeia and Orion. I'll know where the
sun rises from behind the trees in the winter, and where it comes
up in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   I'll hear the first peepers start their chorus from the wet spot
at the bottom of the field, where my grandfather built a drainage
system. Two generations later, the channels are worn, the stones
are in disarray, the wetland is reasserting itself. And I think how
nice it would be to encourage a wet meadow here, full of tall
grasses and redwinged blackbirds.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want any gardens, in the usual sense, around the house.
For one thing, the deer would eat them. But that's not the real
reason. I just don't want to change the character of the place. I
want to keep this patchwork of agriculture rolling out from all
sides of my house: the burnished, cinnamon fields of soybeans; the
feed corn, drying to a pale platinum; the newly plowed land, as
crumbly as chocolate cake, where the string bean vines were just
turned under and winter wheat was planted.
</P>
<P>
   The land's productivity is part of its powerful beauty, and
perennial beds would not do here. They belong up around the old
farmhouse and barns, where there is plenty of room for roses and
lilacs, a whole field of ornamental sunflowers, a new asparagus
patch, and kitchen garden. That is where the clan gathers, for
scrapple and eggs, ham and biscuits and talk, talk and more talk.
My mother somehow keeps track of four children, 11 grandchildren
and all their dogs, lovers and friends.
</P>
<P>
   But down in the meadow, snuggled up against the trees, will be
my little retreat. Big enough for a friend or two, and maybe
another dog. A big kitchen and a wood stove. A very loud stereo. A
place where I can cut up a little (maybe more than a little).
</P>
<P>
   I've imagined this house for years. I've lived in parts of it,
on a salt marsh in Ipswich, Mass.; by the Nissequogue River in St.
James, on Long Island. I almost bought a barn on Shelter Island one
year. And an acre of land on Long Island the next. But every time I
almost cinched the deal, that little hill in Maryland kept tugging
at my heart.
</P>
<P>
   So now I'm just saying yes. And it feels good and solid, as if
I've landed. It's not just a house I will be building. I want to
bring city kids here, and local children, too, to make dams in the
stream and to try to find the spring peepers who stop peeping,
maddeningly, when you stalk them.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they will help me plant a bird habitat around my earth
house: hawthornes, crab apples, American cranberry, viburnums and
witch hazels. Cedars, too, and something good for shade, like a
sugar maple.
</P>
<P>
   The woods by the stream are more beautiful than any garden.
Autumn clematis blooms all over the blackberry brambles and
multiflora roses. A grove of walnut trees edges the stream, and a
sycamore leans so low over the bank I can sit on its mottled trunk
and dangle my feet over the water. I could add some dogwoods and
redbuds, a little shadblow, maybe. And I don't want to clean up too
much. The animals wouldn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   The deer know the best places to cross the stream, and when I
follow their trails, I discover things, like the turtle who lives
on a little island where a fallen tree has dammed the water, making
it deep enough to teach a kid from Red Hook up in Brooklyn how to
swim. Or the tree I saw last Sunday, following a deer path through
the brambles to the top of my hill: every orange-red leaf was full
of light. Maybe it was my sugar maple. And it had been there all
along.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
