NYT-10-22-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-CO     10-22 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The fabric of life in cotton
country
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICKSBURG, Miss. _ Sitting in the Beechwood Restaurant and
Lounge, doodling math in between advertisements printed on the
place mat, trying to figure out how much is 50,000 bales of cotton
...
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, still in Louisiana but almost to
Mississippi, I'd stopped for gas at a little store located, as best
I can tell, almost exactly in the center of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   I was paying the lady at the counter when somebody behind me
hollered out as if they'd seen a long-lost friend, ``Joe! How you
doin'?''
</P>
<P>
   I whirled around, ready to shake hands with a buddy a far way
from home. Only then did I realize that there was more than one Joe
in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of farmers, Joe and somebody whose name I didn't catch,
were greeting each other enthusiastically. No telling how long it
had been since they'd seen one another _ maybe a month, maybe just
yesterday morning _ but they were eager to catch up on the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rain hurt you any?'' one asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' the other said, as if rain had never mattered one way
or another to him in his whole life. ``My cotton's picked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gonna be a good year, Joe,'' the first allowed. ``I expect the
gin will do 50,000 bales.''
</P>
<P>
   On down the road, stopping the night at Vicksburg, I was still
pondering the immensity of a good year of cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty thousand bales!
</P>
<P>
   Wow! That's ... Well, that's a cotton-pickin' lot of cotton.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I was doodling, in between the advertisements
printed on the placemat and in between courses at Beechwood
Restaurant and Lounge, which has been doing business in the same
location on old Highway 80 for four decades, good years and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Ask local folks where you can find a good steak, and they'll
direct you to Beechwood. I missed it twice in the dark, going one
way, then the other and back again.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the manager had forgotten to turn on the big
sign out front. Even so, the parking lot was full to overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   That's mainly due to James Williams. He's the chef. You can't
miss him. Beechwood has his kitchen set up at the front of the
dining room, so as to display him in the big windows looking out on
the highway.
</P>
<P>
   He has been cooking since he was 9 years old, learning from his
father and grandfather, both chefs themselves. Never mind the
degree he has from a famous cooking school. He credits his success
to the secret family recipe for marinating meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``No piece of meat it can't break down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stuff is good for meat and, it would seem, also good for
what ails you. His grandfather lived to 104. His father is 95,
doing well in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Note, however, that James Williams' recipe book, just $4.95, is
dedicated to his mother, who always believed in him.
</P>
<P>
   If you should stop by, ask James Williams about the marinating
sauce. Maybe he'll tell you the recipe. When I asked, he changed
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. I did manage to find out something about cotton.
</P>
<P>
   One bale is 55 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty thousand bales, stacked one on top of the other, would be
2.75 million inches tall, or almost 230,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Empire State Building, by comparison, is 1,250 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Good year for cotton, Joe.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
