<P>
   SINGLE-CHILD (New York) _ In contrast to suburbia, where two or
more children is the norm, Manhattan has become a veritable
only-child paradise. Demographers using figures supplied by the
city, say that the single-child family is now the most-common
family unit in Manhattan. More than 30 percent of all married women
on the island in their early 40's _ that is, women who are largely
past childbearing age and whose family size is most likely set _
have only a single child. By Nancy Hass. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-CUBAN-BAND (New York) _ It was shortly before 8 p.m. on
Thursday, and Diane Ghioto, the owner of Isla, a spanking new Cuban
restaurant on Downing Street in Manhattan, stood overseeing the
polishing of windows and chrome table tops. A small crowd of music
industry executives had showed up to welcome the Buena Vista Social
Club band, who, since their last visit to New York, last year, have
toured the world and have become an international sensation as
masters of son cubano, the rural folk style that forms the
foundation for much of Latin music, from mambo to salsa. By Douglas
Century. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAGS-FAMOUS-FACES (Undated) _ The more Magazines need
celebrities, the more leverage the famous _ or their
representatives, publicity agents _ has gain over the decisions
that magazines used to think of as their own, like who to assign to
photograph and write about them, how to edit the layouts and what
questions to ask in interviews. By Steve Garbarino. Photo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL-LOUNGE (New York) _ Since it opened at Grand Central
Terminal on Sept. 30, the Campbell Apartment, as the lounge is
called, has been packed almost nightly, drawing a stream of the
curious, who between cocktails, crane their necks to take in the
30-foot wood-beam ceilings. The hall, which resembles a
13th-century Italian palazzo, was once the private offices of a
tycoon named John W. Campbell. By Nina Siegal. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Anne Raver considers building a home
on family land in Maryland. But will there be a garden? &QL; 
