<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MAGS-FAMOUS-FACES-ART     10-22 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGS-FAMOUS-FACES-ART-$ADV24-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW I REALLY GOT THAT STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Oct. 24)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By STEVE GARBARINO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently entered into high-level negotiations for an interview
and photo shoot with a young Hollywood actress, soon to co-star in
her first big-budget movie. Her publicity agent dictated the terms:
Star Girl wouldn't wear fur in photographs. My magazine couldn't
discuss her relationship with her boyfriend (also an actor). We had
to mention in the photo credits the cosmetics line she endorsed.
And most important, we couldn't pose her in provocative clothing:
no bikinis, lingerie or cleavage, despite the fact that Star Girl
had made her initial splash baring her breasts in a steamy thriller
only a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, we agreed to it all. Believe me, if we hadn't,
somebody else would have.
</P>
<P>
   I am the style director of US magazine, but I've also held
similar jobs at Detour and Interview, and stories like this could
be echoed a hundred times by my counterparts at other glossy
magazines. It's no secret that we are increasingly relying on
Hollywood celebrities to sell our shiny sheets, to a public whose
appetite for the minutiae of stars' lives _ their shoes, houses,
favorite toothpastes _ seems to know no bounds.
</P>
<P>
   The more we need celebrities, the more leverage they _ or their
representatives, publicity agents _ gain over the decisions we used
to think of as our own, like who to assign to photograph and write
about them, how to edit the layouts and what questions to ask in
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations editors must go through with publicists are so
time-consuming that many magazines have created a new job:
so-called celebrity wranglers, editors who are better at
power-lunching, writing thank-you notes and sending flowers than at
smoothing out copy.
</P>
<P>
   Typically listed as West Coast Editor on mastheads, they cozy up
to the celebrities and publicists poolside in Hollywood, while we,
back in New York, grudgingly abide by whatever deals they make.
Actual editors have never been pushed further away from the
subjects they're featuring in their pages.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make an entertainment editor fantasize about
working for Sports Afield. Big-horn sheep _ you don't suppose they
have publicists, do you?
</P>
<P>
   Here, under the new rules, is how the game is played. Before a
publicist gives the go-ahead for a magazine to photograph and
interview a star, it's common practice for the editor to agree not
to bring up taboo topics _ a former addiction, a current love, a
sordid rumor. The stars would love it, though, if we would tout
their upcoming movies even before we've seen them.
</P>
<P>
   We permit the publicists to help pick the photographers who will
shoot their clients, and sometimes even the writers. This requires
a lot of back and forth, overnighting photographers' portfolios and
writers' clips. Many times, the publicists already know exactly who
they want. They're just putting us through the motions so as not to
look, well, controlling.
</P>
<P>
   If a photographer is known for making over famous faces,
``experimenting with their look,'' as publicists say, they will
likely reject the suggestion. ``We had a situation with him
before,'' they will say vaguely.
</P>
<P>
   Other rejections are more specific. I've heard a photographer
who regularly shows in art galleries dismissed with the line, ``He
makes all the guys he shoots look gay, and the girls all come out
looking like drag queens.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, magazine photographers are working in a style
called modern realism, meaning they portray subjects with a sullen,
disaffected or caught-off-guard look. But publicists see only that
Cover Girl could use a little makeup, that Cover Boy needs a shave
and haircut.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   What's particularly galling is that publicists aren't
professional editors; 9 out of 10 times, their choice of
photographer is dreadful, based on whether an upbeat,
conventionally flattering picture will result. There is little
interest in portraiture that reveals a subject's inner life.
Publicists want a puffy article and a pretty picture, nothing more.
It's what their clients pay them for.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, we editors brought it on ourselves. About two
years ago, style and fashion magazines decreed that supermodels
were passe, and they began going after movie stars as cover
subjects. The results are on the newsstands: the cover of the
October issue of Vogue features Winona Ryder, Harper's Bazaar has
Michelle Pfeiffer and the latest Allure has Patricia Arquette. Back
then editors thought: ``Enough with models. Models are late, models
are moody. Mostly, though, they're boring.'' A bit naively, we
believed that actors had character, a ``story'' to tell.
</P>
<P>
   How wrong we were. Do you want your writer to really get to know
a cover subject? You'll be lucky if the publicist allots more than
a ``chat and chew'' _ an hourlong interview over lunch. They're so
very busy, these movie stars. If a writer's clips suggest he or she
likes to get personal _ say, dipping into a Jacuzzi with the star
as part of the reporting _ publicists will deem the reporter ``too
controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, the result has been lame stories and boring
pictures. Almost everybody looks and sounds alike. With magazines
promoting more and more movie figures, too many are being sold to
readers as the Next Big Thing, but most fall short of stardom.
Consider the ballyhooed former cover subjects Matthew McConaughey,
Liv Tyler and Elisabeth Shue, all of whom graced multiple magazines
a while ago; they've turned out to be reliable, working actors _
but no big deals.
</P>
<P>
   After a dozen years in the business, I'm hardened to the process
of ``giving cover.'' Little surprises me. But it still came as a
shock late last year when a celebrity backed out entirely at the
last minute. I was the editor of Detour magazine, and Sean Penn had
agreed to grace our December cover. We agreed to let him help
select both writer and photographer through his publicist. We
compiled a wish list of literary, tough-guy writers we imagined
would appeal to Penn, including Barry Gifford, Denis Johnson, Harry
Crews and David Mamet. All were either rejected by Penn or
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   For a photographer, we proposed Richard Burbridge, well known
for his pockmarks-and-all portraits. We assumed Penn and his agent
would approve. No dice. ``He blinds people,'' the publicist said.
``They get black eyes from his flash-bulb technique, and they don't
go away for days.'' (A few months later, The New York Times
Magazine assigned Burbridge to shoot Penn for its cover without any
objection from the actor's representatives.)
</P>
<P>
   We kept lobbing out names of other photographers, but suddenly,
weeks before the magazine was due to be shipped to the printer,
Penn withdrew from the story altogether. His father had recently
died, it was explained; quite understandably, he was reeling from
his loss. So were we.
</P>
<P>
   The apologetic publicist offered another of his clients: Winona
Ryder, and we happily agreed, but it was not to happen. The
photographer the publicist wanted was known for extravagant expense
sheets, and Ms. Ryder's schedule would cause the magazine overtime
production costs. Now, it was our turn to back away.
</P>
<P>
   After one other aborted effort involving another actress, it
became too late to shoot an original cover, so we frantically
reviewed pictures of actors already in-house.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Hudson, who bore a striking resemblance to her famous
mother, Goldie Hawn, and was set to co-star in an ensemble comedy,
``200 Cigarettes,'' seemed like a possibility. Calls were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may not be ready for a cover yet,'' her publicist told me,
concerned that too much attention too early could hinder Ms.
Hudson' career. But he eventually gave a thumb's up, on the
condition that he could approve the cover shot.
</P>
<P>
   I liked a semi-sexy portrait of Ms. Hudson in a black leather
coat with her red underwear peeking out. It was flirty, but not
tacky.
</P>
<P>
   The publicist, though, thought it was too provocative and voted
for a black-and-white shot of Ms. Hudson in a long evening gown. It
was flat, and I said no. Then he delivered his ultimatum: If we
used the ``panty shot,'' as he called it, his agency, with its
roster of A-list stars, would boycott our magazine in the future.
We gave in. The result: the worst-looking cover in my tenure as
Detour's editor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
