<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     10-22 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV24-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OUT DAMN STAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When I took up an area rug, the rubber mat under it bled
through to the floor, making a yellow stain. How can I clean that
stain?
</P>
<P>
   MARY ANNE FITZGERALD, Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try cleaning it with paint thinner; apply the thinner and let
it sit for 30 seconds; add thinner if it starts to evaporate. Then
rub vigorously with the cloth you applied the thinner with. Then
wipe everything up with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, dip very fine steel wool in paint thinner
and rub lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Another treatment is to spray the stain with WD-40, wait 15
minutes, and wipe it all up with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My two-family house has a center chimney, with the furnace of
each apartment feeding into the chimney. Some of the clay flue
liner tiles in the chimney have broken and we took them out. Some
liners have stayed in place. I cannot find a company that will take
out the rest of the liners and put in a metal flue. I can only find
companies that want to drop in stainless steel liners. Is this OK?
</P>
<P>
   TONI SANDONATO, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is if the chimney is big enough to accommodate two liners.
Two liners that fit snugly in the chimney will also keep any flue
liners that remain in the chimney in their place. If the two
burners are gas, you might be able to install one stainless steel
liner and allow each furnace to duct into it. Two is better than
one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The 25-year-old fireplace and chimney in my Cape Cod house
are made of old bricks and are leaking water into the house. A man
said he would seal them with a sealer, once a year. I don't like
sealing every year. Can I apply a skimcoat of mortar to the brick?
</P>
<P>
   MARGARET RUTKOWSKI, Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't blame you for not wanting to have the chimney sealed
once a year; that can get expensive, and it also points out the
shortcomings of clear sealers. They might do a yeoman job, but only
for a year. That is not long enough. Yes, you can skimcoat the
chimney with mortar; it is called parging, and will be a permanent
leak-proof job. While the brick chimney is essentially a rough
finish and mortar will stick to it, I suggest you apply a bonding
agent to the chimney before skimcoating, to make the skimcoat stick
better.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing about sealer. A regular clear sealer will seal the
chimney against outside water, but it also can seal in moisture and
cause interior leaks and decay of the bricks. There is a cure for
that, too: chimney sweeps have a sealer they call Chimney Saver; it
waterproofs the bricks but allows interior moisture to evaporate,
preventing not only leaks but also decay. If you use a sealer, use
Chimney Saver, which must be installed by a pro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new house was built in 1909, with a built-in cast iron
tub. The ceiling below the tub is all bubbly and cracking,
indicating a leak. A plumber suggested caulking around the tub. Is
there any other way of stopping the leak?
</P>
<P>
   CLAUDIA SORGI, Hingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Caulking around the tub both at the floor and where tub meets
wall may stop leaks from showering and spilled water. If so, all's
well and you can repair the ceiling, and repaint.
</P>
<P>
   But if the leak is in the drain or supply pipe (most likely the
drain, particularly if the leak occurs only during a shower or when
the tub is draining), the only way to find it is to take down the
ceiling below the tub and simply take a look, and take it from
there.
</P>
<P>
   If you can find the leak, fix it, and now replace the ceiling
that you would have had to do anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new rubber roof is less than a year old, and has developed
a hole about 4 by 4 inches. Is there a patching material I can use
to fix it?
</P>
<P>
   JUDY KEYMONT, Stoughton
</P>
<P>
   A. First off, call the roofer; the roof is in warranty (for
about a year, generally), and the roofer is, or should be,
responsible for fixing it, no matter what caused the hole. Getting
him to fix the hole is another matter. Fixing it yourself might be
iffy, because I don't know if the rubber roof material is available
as a patch. If it is not, and you still want to or have to fix it,
you can try this: Buy any kind of sheet rubber or rubber-like
compound, and adhesive to go with it, and glue it over the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Another trick is to buy a tire repair kit; if you can get the
patch big enough, glue it down with the stuff that comes with the
tire kit. If it holds against a high-pressure tire, then it should
do well on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. One of my tenants wants to put a satellite antenna on the
roof. It is 18 inches in diameter. Would such an antenna cause
leaks?
</P>
<P>
   STEVE RIVARD, Woburn
</P>
<P>
   A. Anything secured to the roof can cause leaks, especially if
the fastener is not caulked or treated with roofing cement. Make
sure it is secure enough to prevent the wind from rocking it loose.
</P>
<P>
   And, a small dish like that can be mounted, instead, on the
wall, where it will not cause leaks and can be heavily secured.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
