<HEADER>
A5264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     10-22 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, Oct. 23. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PAPON (Paris) _ The manhunt for Maurice Papon ended
swiftly and successfully Thursday night when the Swiss police
arrested the 89-year-old Nazi collaborator, who was registered
under a false name and hiding in a modest hotel in one of Europe's
most exclusive ski resorts. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-FUTURE (Undated) _ Two days after he became the first
democratically elected president in Indonesian history, Abdurrahman
Wahid spent the day closeted with five eminent local economists.
That Wahid would spend his second day in office grappling with
economic matters is no surprise. The political upheaval that
vaulted this mysterious man to power had its roots in an economic
crisis. While the political drama may be over, the economic crisis
rages on. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Republican leaders in Congress
announced a plan on Friday to reduce government spending across the
board by 1.4 percent. The cuts, a total of $4.5 billion in the
current fiscal year, would apply to every government program for
which Congress controls the annual financing. The Republicans said
the plan would allow them to approve a budget without tax increases
and without dipping into Social Security reserves. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
