<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-GUILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING BEGINS FOR CONTROL OF THE SCREEN ACTORS GUILD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Voting is under way in what has become an unusually
contentious battle for control of the Screen Actors Guild, the
union representing some 97,000 movie, television and commercial
performers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Masur, the film and television actor, who has been
president of the guild for four years, is facing an energetic
challenge from William Daniels, the veteran stage, screen and
television actor. Daniels is backed by an upstart faction called
the Performers Alliance that has steadily accumulated seats on the
guild's national board in recent elections and now hopes to
consolidate those gains with a sweep of the union's national
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone asks me, Why are you doing this?'' said Daniels, who
is 72. ``This is a job a lot of people would avoid. My whole
experience in the Army was, never volunteer for anything. But they
approached me and asked me to do it and, I have to tell you, I've
learned a lot in the last four or five weeks. Something has to be
done, because the union's current leadership is not paying
attention to half of its members.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballots were mailed to the guild's members Oct. 13 and are due
back on Nov. 3, with an announcement of the results two days later.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Performers Alliance and Masur's slate, which is called
ProAct, complain that the contest has become increasingly fractious
and personal, with frequent attacks on Masur for what opponents
describe as an autocratic management style and on Daniels for his
admitted lack of union experience. In recent weeks, a third
candidate has entered the race, Angeltompkins, a film and
television actress and national board member who has run
unsuccessfully against Masur in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fire, though, has been between Masur and Daniels,
largely because their contest is a mirror of the continuing battle
between the union's current leadership and the alliance. The
conflict seems to focus on how the union should be run and how
confrontational it should be in its dealings with the entertainment
conglomerates and with its own staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Performers Alliance began as a group of Hollywood-based
actors who were angry with declining wages and what they saw as an
unresponsive national union leadership, said Chuck Sloan, an
alliance member of the guild's national board and one of Daniels'
advisers. In the last two elections, the alliance won a working
majority on the union's Hollywood board, though not enough votes to
dominate the entire national board when votes from New York and
elsewhere in the country are included.
</P>
<P>
   Masur believes that the alliance is too confrontational _ in its
rhetoric, in its approach to union issues and in the way its
members treat the union's national staff and behave during board
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for people to realize that this is no
longer 1974 and not every issue of interest to performers can be
resolved across the bargaining table,'' Masur said. ``It's my sense
that the opposition seems completely ignorant of the fact that
critically important problems require in-depth analysis and
strategic thinking and must be addressed in an organized and
focused manner on the legislative front, the public policy front
and in outreach to our highest profile members.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these actions are part of their agenda. The only thing
they talk about is contract. Because of my opponent's complete lack
of knowledge and experience and his advisers' myopic view of
contract negotiations as the only thing of import to members, I
think it would be a tragedy for this organization if that old way
of thinking were to prevail at this union.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Daniels said, is not his lack of experience but the
union's failure in recent years to take a harder line in contract
talks and in enforcement of those contracts. ``The industry knows
this union is a soft union,'' he said. ``They know this union
doesn't want to strike.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Daniels and his supporters believe that Masur
maintains too much day-to-day control of union activities and has a
tendency to look after the interests of the more successful actors
at the expense of those struggling at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Of the guild's 97,000 members, about half are based in Southern
California, a quarter in New York and the rest scattered around the
country. All of the union's national officers are up for
re-election _ president, treasurer and recording secretary _ as
well as four national vice presidents and about one-third of the
seats on the 105-member national board.
</P>
<P>
   At heart, Masur said, the alliance challenge is a power play by
a group that saw significant gains in recent elections and now
wants to turn that into control of the entire union. The result, he
said, would be more fractious behavior during meetings of the
Hollywood board _ that portion of the national board that
represents Hollywood-based actors, which is now dominated by
alliance members _ and more tension within the union.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance members see it differently, of course _ not as
obstructionism but as activism on behalf of struggling actors.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever view prevails, Daniels said, perhaps the group that
wins the election will be able to find a calmer path to the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will have a healing process,'' he said. ``There
are a lot of good people on both sides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
