<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NITEOUT-CUBAN-BAND-AR     10-22 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-CUBAN-BAND-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH THE BUENA VISTA SOCIAL CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24)  
 (af)  
 By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was shortly before 8 p.m. on Thursday, and Diane
Ghioto, the owner of Isla, a spanking new Cuban restaurant on
Downing Street, stood overseeing the polishing of windows and
chrome table tops. ``Everything has to be just right tonight,'' she
told her staff of waiters in guayabera shirts as they awaited the
arrival of the Buena Vista Social Club.
</P>
<P>
   A small crowd of music industry executives showed up to welcome
the band, who, since their last visit to New York, last year, have
toured the world and have become an international sensation as
masters of son cubano, the rural folk style that forms the
foundation for much of Latin music, from mambo to salsa.
</P>
<P>
   The Buena Vista Social Club, a loose collective, was back in
town, for a sold-out show at the Beacon Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 9 p.m., they arrived, led by Ry Cooder, the
guitarist and producer who first brought Buena Vista to an American
audience. They looked somewhat weary, having stepped off a bus from
Atlanta, by way of Washington. Several were wearing souvenir
Georgia peach ball caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happily tired,'' the diminutive, 80-year-old pianist Ruben
Gonzalez said through an interpreter. ``I'm tiredly happy.'' While
other members enjoyed mojitos, the classic Cuban drink of crushed
mint and lime and white rum over ice, Gonzalez contented himself
with a tall glass of milk.
</P>
<P>
   At a semicircular white leather booth, Ibrahim Ferrer camped out
with his wife. At 72, the silky-voiced Ferrer _ dubbed the Nat King
Cole of Cuba _ looked boyish in his trademark tan-colored Kangol
cap and canvas K-Swiss sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Even indoors, he did not take off his polar fleece pullover or
loosen the thick wool scarf wrapped around his neck to protect his
vocal chords. He beamed when Ms. Ghioto sat down and presented him
with a gift-wrapped box. ``Oh, Ibrahim loves dominoes,'' said
Caridad Diaz Surita, Ferrer's wife, when his fingers tore off the
tissue paper.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer explained, ``In Havana, we play until the early hours in
the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:30, a Champagne toast was raised by David Bither, the
senior vice president of Nonesuch Records, as he presented
individual Grammy Awards to Messrs. Ferrer and Gonzalez that they
had won in 1998 but did not collect at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only going to talk for a few minutes, because we Cubans
are brief,'' Ferrer said. Gonzalez, dressed in an open-neck
charcoal-gray shirt, told the guests that he felt ``requete bien''
_ a Spanish phrase that translates as ``better than good.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the various Buena Vista projects has resulted in
a remarkable late-life transformation for many of the band members.
``Buena Vista Social Club,'' the acclaimed documentary about the
band by the Dutch filmmaker Wim Wenders, released this year,
details Gonzalez's 30-year struggle just to play the piano, after
his original instrument was eaten my wood worms.
</P>
<P>
   Before his career's resurrection, Ferrer was shining shoes for
cigarette money in the Havana streets.
</P>
<P>
   Were these maestros aware that they'd arrived in America on the
wave of a great Latin explosion, with crossover records by Ricky
Martin and Jennifer Lopez topping the charts, and a novelty hit by
Lou Bega, ``Mambo No. 5,'' blending '50s Cuban rhythms with the
flavor of hip-hop? Several musicians offered indifferent shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Translating their overlapping responses, Bernardo Palombo, an
Argentine composer who acts as the band's interpreter, said: ``In
Cuba, the younger people still don't give a damn about this music.
They follow American rap and commercial salsa. The younger
musicians told Ibrahim many times that he was a relic. `Go and sing
in the cemetery,' they told him.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the night, waiters strolled past, offering Cuban
delicacies like grilled sugar-cane chicken and bacalao fritters.
Tony Jimenez, a tenor saxophonist, commented that while the food
was delicious, ``it has a Mexican touch of spiciness _ back in
Havana we don't use so much spice.''(The chef, Aaron Sanchez, is in
fact Mexican-American.)
</P>
<P>
   In Isla, Ms. Ghioto and Kate Webb, a designer, have faithfully
recreated the breezy, opulent atmosphere of Havana's
pre-revolutionary years _ down to the restaurant's script logo,
borrowed from the guest book of a 1950s Cuban hotel. Through clouds
of cigar smoke, bronze-faced great-grandfathers were twirling their
dancing partners across the cobalt-blue floor. ``None of these guys
needs Viagra,'' one young woman said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   As the dancing grew more frenzied, Andrea Strong, Isla's
manager, began to worry that the plates of hors d'oeuvres weren't
going to be enough. ``These Cuban guys have big appetites,'' she
said. ``They're hungry and they're drinking and they need more
food.'' Ms. Ghioto went into the kitchen in a rush, exclaiming,
``We have a special request from Ibrahim _ he wants more
tostones.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Ghioto passed out cigars _ Cuban, of course _ Ferrer
shook his head, staring at the hand-rolled robusto with a wistful
smile. ``I stopped smoking about a month ago,'' he said. ``The
doctor suggested that it's not good for my bronchitis.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on Downing Street, people were lighting up their cigars, and
passersby had stopped to gape at the collection of elderly men
dancing to ``Dos Gardenias.''
</P>
<P>
   The white-mustached Gonzalez had gone from milk to stronger
spirits and was now feeling euphoric. ``When you come to Havana,
ask for Ruben Gonzalez,'' he told a complete stranger. ``You don't
need my address because everybody will tell you where to find me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
