<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGICAL JOURNEY ON HOLD FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, Oct. 28.) 
(th) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The plan was simple: We had four free plane tickets, and we
decided to go to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   A quick weekend jaunt. Maybe we'd take in Epcot's millennial
celebration or the new Cirque du Soleil.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, the trip was intended to introduce our youngest to
the classics. Yes, it's a parent's penance to be required to ride
Small World and Dumbo the Flying Elephant with each of their
children by age 3.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no stranger to doing Disney, having lived in Central Florida
for 30 years. I've visited the parks yearly since I was 10, when
there were still E tickets and hokey special effects. I remember
the thrill of going through The Haunted Mansion, Pirates of the
Caribbean and Space Mountain for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   My son and I had annual passes to the parks when he was a
preschooler, and just because we had moved a few hundred miles
north, I didn't want to deprive my daughter of that Disney magic.
</P>
<P>
   My husband was a harder sell. Having grown up in the Midwest,
he's a Mouse skeptic if there ever was one. One of his firm
resolves in life was to never set foot on Disney property,
believing, like Carl Hiaasen, that Disney ``is so good at being
good that it manifests an evil'' (from ``Team Rodent: How Disney
Devours the World.'') But even Jim was willing to go along for the
sake of second-child equity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't to be.
</P>
<P>
   First came the stomach virus with amazing staying power, able to
leap from person to person in a single fortnight. We left for the
airport on the children's first day back on solid foods.
</P>
<P>
   Did I give in? NO!
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to Disney World,'' I said with conviction.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon at the airport, I settled into a vinyl chair and
watched TV reports of Hurricane Irene, spinning her green arms
toward Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're GOING to Disney World,'' I muttered to The Weather
Channel reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, our plane was ready to board. We could see it out the
window. But the crew was flying in from Boston and had been delayed
and would be in Atlanta by ... 8:45 p.m. No, 9:45. Well, make that
11. Oops, 12:40 a.m. -- maybe.
</P>
<P>
   I held our screaming 3-year-old (``I wanna go HOME! I wanna go
HOME! Don't care about Mickey Mouse, I wanna go HOME!'')
</P>
<P>
   I looked over at my husband, at The Weather Channel, at my
exhausted, wane children trying to curl up on the bright orange
airport chairs. I pictured us all dragging into the hotel suite at
3 a.m. and waking to Irene's dark and dreary embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to Disney World,'' I said wearily, and we
headed home.
</P>
<P>
   We slept 11 hours and woke to a sunny, cool morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear it's raining in Florida,'' my husband said.
</P>
<P>
   I hit him with the pillow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still going,'' I warned. ``Come wind or rain or plague
or pestilence or pilot problems. Just as soon as I can
reschedule.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You're only 3 once, after all. All too soon, Sarah will realize
that Mickey and Minnie are just employees dressed like giant
rodents, elephants can't really fly and that endless, chipper song
is downright irritating.
</P>
<P>
   We have to get her there while the stardust is still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
