<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5276 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-CAMPBELL-LOUNGE-$ADV2     10-22 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-LOUNGE-$ADV24-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE OTHER HALF LIVED IT UP IN GRAND CENTRAL STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday Oct. 24)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time and again this summer, Michael Kane was drawn up
a marble staircase at Grand Central Terminal, then up two more
flights in the terminal's southwest corner to a glass door guarded
by ornate metal gates. Behind those doors, he had heard, was a hall
that resembled a 13th-century Italian palazzo, once the private
offices of a tycoon named John W. Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept coming by and asking, `How long is it going to be?'''
said Kane, a marketing manager at The New Yorker, who on a recent
night was finally seated in the restored room, which has been
turned into a lounge. ``Then I forgot about it, until my friend
called tonight to say it was open.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of those in the elegant bar mentioned that they, too,
had been drawn by the promise of a certain mystique.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's that immediate intrigue,'' said Ted Brumelene, an
architect who was having a drink with his brother while waiting to
catch a train. ``What was that space? Why was it hiding? It's like
sneaking into someone's living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened on Sept. 30, the Campbell Apartment, as the
lounge is called, has been packed almost nightly, drawing a stream
of the curious, who between cocktails, crane their necks to take in
the 30-foot wood-beam ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   They admire the deep blue Moroccan-inspired rug, the overstuffed
couches set against stone walls and the huge steel safe installed
by Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've really done here is blend the modern with
something that is not post-modern but truly antique,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   The bar's owner, Mark C. Grossich, is a specialist in retro
night life _ he founded a chain of cigar bars _ and he has adopted
a persona to fit: a young fogey in a custom double-breasted suit
with antique polka-dot silk scarf peeking out of the breast pocket
and suede bench-made shoes. He says the key to his success is
avoiding trendiness and creating instead a classic ambiance that
encourages people to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, trendy means loud and abusive and intense,'' he said.
``We do not want to be the flavor of the month or the year. We want
to be in it for the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   That claim may sound just a bit disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Grossich's chain of smoking lounges, known as Bar and Books, are
as heavily themed as anything from the Disney Imagineers. Each
contains built-in bookshelves or floor-to-ceiling humidors. At the
height of the cigar craze, he owned four of them, but now he
operates two. It was Grossich's reputation in the lounge business
that prompted the Metropolitan Transportation Authority to ask him
two years ago to restore the Campbell Apartment. He said he jumped
at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Bar and Books we were manufacturing history,'' he
said. ``With the Campbell Apartment we could leverage the real
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   By his account, he spent $1 million renovating the space,
working with Connie Beale, an interior designer in Greenwich,
Conn., to restore the ceiling, stone fireplace and stained-glass
windows. He added a few touches of his own, like an expansive bar
with blue leather stools.
</P>
<P>
   Grossich has gathered many stories about the Campbell
Apartment's original owner, who was the chairman of the Credit
Clearing House, which was later taken over Dun &AMP; Bradstreet.
Campbell rented the space beginning in 1923, using it as a private
office by day and holding lavish parties by night. Legend has it
that even his boxer shorts were custom-made, along with his shirts
and shoes, and that he never wore socks.
</P>
<P>
   Grossich is quick to admit that he's not the bon vivant Campbell
was reputed to be. He shies away from the role of host, rarely
mingling with customers. On any given night, he might be found on
the Campbell Apartment's balcony playing pool with a custom-made
cue. Or he might be standing near the front door, smoking his
favorite cigar, a Temple Hall Maduro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the spirit of John Campbell would be quite pleased,''
he said recently, surveying the crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
