u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     10-22 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Oct. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chilly Canadian gales will buffet parts of the Great Lakes on
Saturday in the wake of a formidable but weakening low pressure
system over Ontario. Gusts to 45 mph or more are possible across
northern Michigan, owing to the large contrasts in barometric
pressure between the low and a high centered over the central
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Father east, waterspouts are possible over Lakes Erie Ontario as
a pocket of very cold air several thousand feet above the surface
drifts over relatively tepid water.
</P>
<P>
   Showers of snow and rain will speckle the region from the Great
Lakes to the mountains of western Pennsylvania, northern West
Virginia and western Maryland, with some of the high ground
whitened by Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, moderate rains will douse parts of northern New
England the first part of the day as a secondary area of low
pressure associated with the Ontario low exits slowly into the Gulf
of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   In its wake, variable clouds with limited intervals of sun will
prevail over the rest of the Northeast seaboard as cold air aloft
promotes the growth of cumulus clouds. Sunday will be windy and
chilly across the entire Northeast seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will also invade the Southeast, with temperatures
dropping off into the 30s and 40s on Saturday night as far south as
northern Florida. Meanwhile, a weekend warming trend will commence
in the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The recent spell of dry weather in the Pacific Northwest will
come to an end Saturday as a cold front and a trailing jet stream
disturbance arrive from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TEXAS CHILL
</P>
<P>
   Record chill invaded the lower Rio Grande Valley on Friday
morning as the mercury sank to 48 degrees at Brownsville, Texas,
the lowest reading ever recorded on October 22. In fact,
Brownsville has not been as cool since April 17 and the last time
readings fell below 48 degrees was on March 15. Oddly, the autumn
cool snap in south Texas has come because a much colder air mass is
surging southward into the Mississippi and Ohio valleys. This has
forced rather cool and very dry air well south into Texas. The
brunt of the new cold air mass will be felt in the East during this
weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
