<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5279 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-WAR-POWERS-HN     10-22 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WAR-POWERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MEMBERS CHALLENGE CLINTON'S AUTHORITY TO BOMB YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Does the White House or Congress have the right to
send American troops into battle?
</P>
<P>
   That constitutional question was argued Friday before a federal
appeals court here as 31 House members urged the three-judge panel
to let them challenge President Clinton's decision to order the
bombing of Yugoslavia in March and continue the attack beyond 60
days.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers maintained that Clinton violated the 1973 War
Powers Act by failing to get congressional approval for the
bombing. The act requires the approval for ``introduction into
hostilities'' of U.S. forces lasting more than 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's 60-day period ended on May 25 without
congressional approval, the House members, led by Rep. Tom
Campbell, R-Calif., sued, saying that president was legally
required to end the bombing. Clinton refused, and the bombing
continued until June 10 when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
agreed to withdraw his troops from the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a federal judge dismissed the lawsuit, saying the House
members didn't have standing to sue because they failed to show a
``constitutional impasse'' between the president and Congress in
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Paul Friedman said Congress and the
White House had not come to ``an actual confrontation'' about the
Yugoslav bombing campaign. He added that Congress had sent
``distinctly mixed messages'' about whether it supported or opposed
Clinton's commitment of U.S. forces in the allied bombing that
began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman noted that on April 28, the House approved several
conflicting measures. It voted against a declaration of war,
against withdrawal from the war, for a requirement that Congress
give its approval before the dispatch of any ground forces, and, in
a 213-213 vote, against a resolution to support the air war. The
Senate never voted on any measure condoning or condemning the
Yugoslav campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Congress takes a firm stand on one side of the issue, and
the president firmly resists that stand, members of Congress have
no legal right to sue over Clinton's military actions, Friedman
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Campbell and the other House members asked the
three-judge panel of the Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia to reverse that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Jules Lobel, attorney for the House members, said the bombing
campaign was the best case to date to test the War Powers Act. He
argued that the 213-213 vote against the resolution to support the
air war showed that Congress was against the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, they (the administration) flagrantly ignored (the War
Powers Act),'' Lobel, a law professor at the University of
Pittsburgh, told the judges. ``The question here is since Congress
stepped up to the plate and performed its duty, will the courts do
so?''
</P>
<P>
   But the judges appeared reluctant to take on that duty. ``You're
putting a lot of pressure on the judiciary,'' said Judge Laurence
Silberman, who was U.S. ambassador to Yugoslavia from 1975 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Silberman told Lobel that if the judges ruled in his favor, they
would force courts to decide which military conflicts reach the
level of being called a war. ``Are we at war with Iraq or Korea?''
he asked. ``I don't know, and I don't know if the court should have
to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobel replied, ``You would have to blind yourself to reality to
say the (bombing of Yugoslavia) wasn't a war.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyer William Schultz, representing the
president, argued that Congress never took a ``firm stand'' against
the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was there overwhelming support for the bombing?'' he asked.
``No. But nor was there overwhelming support to end the bombing.
Frankly, Congress didn't know what it wanted.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the Constitution, Congress has the power to declare war.
But over the years, particularly during the Cold War, presidents
often dispatched troops without prior authority.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the wake of Vietnam, Congress sought to rein in
executive war-making by passing the War Powers Act, which
essentially delegates to the president the power to make war for a
limited period. It requires the president to report within 48 hours
after introducing U.S. forces into hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does not declare war or otherwise explicitly
authorize its continuation, the president has 60 days ``to
terminate any use'' of U.S. forces, with a 30-day extension, if
necessary, to extricate them safely. Under the war powers law, if
Congress votes funds for the troops, that does not mean it is
sanctioning the war.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973 every president has scorned the act as an
unconstitutional infringement of executive power but has issued
reports on the dispatch of troops. Most recent conflicts _ Ronald
Reagan's invasion of Granada in 1983 and President George Bush's
invasion of Panama in 1989, Clinton's 1998 strikes against Sudan
and Afghanistan _ have ended before the 60 days ran out. In the few
cases where forces stayed longer, the president either had
congressional approval _ such as Bush in the 1991 Persian Gulf War
_ or worked out a compromise with Congress that provided some color
of authority _ such as the agreement with Reagan to keep troops in
Lebanon in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
