<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SINGLE-CHILD-ART-$ADV     10-22 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGLE-CHILD-ART-$ADV24-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE ARE FAMILY: MOM, DAD AND JUST ME 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 24) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By NANCY HASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few weeks ago, Mia Walker, a former television
producer who is just about to have her second child, asked some
friends to give her a ``nonshower.'' Absolutely no presents, she
insisted. Instead, as she tearfully told her girlfriends gathered
in an East Side brownstone, she wanted them to assure her she
wouldn't ``disappear down a black hole'' as a mother of two in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was ecstatic to be having another baby, she said,
she couldn't help but be a little worried about fitting her new
double stroller into the elevator, or giving up the ease of jumping
on the subway or visiting museums and restaurants with just a
toddler, versus a toddler plus an infant.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walker was experiencing a classic New York syndrome: two
children puts you in a different universe. ``I'm really happy about
having another baby, but there is something looming about the onset
of child No. 2 in New York,'' she said. ``When you have one kid
here you have the world at your fingertips.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to suburbia, where two or more children are the
norm, Manhattan has become a veritable only-child paradise.
Demographers, using figures supplied by the city, say that the
single-child family is now the most-common family unit in
Manhattan. More than 30 percent of all married women on the island
in their early 40s _ that is, women who are largely past
childbearing age and whose family size is most likely set _ have
only a single child. Add to that the number of women under 40 with
one child, and you have a raging plurality that the demographers,
Andrew Beveridge and Susan Weber of Queens College, say could top
40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the national figure for women ages 40 to 44 who
have ever been married and have just one child is about 21 percent,
according to Census Bureau data.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs, only children are still often considered a
curiosity, sometimes even a sad one. But in Manhattan, there is
virtually no stigma attached to them. They are as much a part of
the cultural fabric of the city as the unique circumstances that,
in a word, breed them: small, expensive apartments, a huge
proportion of women who delay marriage and childbearing to pursue
careers, inadequate public schools and sky-high private school
tuitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nowhere else that the two-parent, one-child ratio is
regarded so positively,'' said Len Covine, 46, an architect who
lives in SoHo with his wife, Sophie, and their 5-year-old daughter,
Lena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking on the streets here you can forget about the whole SUV
thing, the whole play-date thing, the whole soccer-mom thing,'' he
said. ``Instead, you can remember the museum thing, the Central
Park thing, the matinee thing, the hop-into-a-taxi thing. Having a
child here, one child, is completely different than the family
experience anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Another parent-of-one, Anita Farrington-Brathwaite, whose
daughter, Monet, is 8, said: ``I feel I have the best of both
worlds. I have a career that's really meaningful to me, and I have
a great deal of time to devote to my daughter. I really shudder at
the thought of having to spread myself thinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Farrington-Brathwaite, an undergraduate dean at New York
University, grew up in Queens and was herself an only child. She
said she never thought of having more than one. ``I grew up knowing
that I had a really good deal, that my parents, who really didn't
have that much money, were able to give me security I wouldn't have
had otherwise,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Farrington-Brathwaite, whose husband is also a college
administrator, lives in a two-bedroom NYU-subsidized apartment and
sends her daughter to the Little Red School House, a private school
that has a large percentage of only children. ``There is no way I
could have done that if I had more than one child,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that New York has been dubbed safe again and small-town
schoolyard shootings are still fresh in the public's imagination,
fewer couples seem to be moving out of town right after the birth
of their first child. Then, a few years later, at the time most
people decide to have a second child, these couples are loath to
move. ``New York,'' said Ms. Walker, who has returned to school to
become a psychotherapist, ``just gets in your blood.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Ms. Walker and her husband, who recently left a
family business to start an Internet venture, many people simply
decide not to have another child. Where members of an earlier
generation might have felt guilty or conflicted about that
decision, fearing they were depriving their child of sibling
companionship, today a large body of research shows that only
children do not suffer social or intellectual repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   And a welcome aspect of having an only child in Manhattan is
that such families do not stand apart, parents say. Amy Virshup,
40, a journalist who has a year-old son, Nicholas, lives with her
husband, an architect, in an Upper West Side building that may
stand as a microcosm of Manhattan: among the 24 apartments, there
are seven couples with one child. Each of the children is old
enough to suggest that the parents are unlikely to be planning
more. ``The only person who asks me when I'm going to have another
kid is my cleaning woman,'' Ms. Virshup said. ``She says I'm
lazy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With so many only children in town, the usual services and
activities for infants and toddlers take on a special tinge. Play
groups and luncheon clubs that specialize in first-time mothers _ a
disproportionate number of the total mothers in the city _ have
sprung up everywhere. ``When I grew up as an only child, it was
awful,'' recalled the novelist Dani Shapiro, 37, whose son, Jacob,
is now 5 months old. ``I was the only one in my entire private
school class. But I know that if I don't decide to have another
baby, Jacob will have lots of kids in his class who are only
children. That really makes a huge difference to me.''
</P>
<P>
   While the percentage of only children in Manhattan is the
highest in the United States, there has been a subtler boom in
one-child families across the country. Only children are the
nation's fastest-growing family demographic. Three-person families
have grown from 10 million in 1972 to more than 15 million today,
and between 1980 and 1990, the most recent census, there was a 76
percent increase among women nearing the end of childbearing with
one child. That trend, plus the rising number of childless couples
(nearly 18 percent), has lowered the United States birthrate to
less than two per family. Demographers trace the decline to a
rising divorce rate, higher costs to rear and educate children, a
rise in the number of working women and a rising age of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Although choice is not always a factor in the decision to have
an only child _ infertility is rising as women delay marriage and
childbirth into their 30s _ more people than ever are consciously
opting to have just one, experts say, especially in Manhattan.
``Here there is a self-selection factor,'' said Dr. Kathleen
Gerson, an NYU sociologist and the author of ``Hard Choices: How
Women Decide About Work, Career and Motherhood'' (University of
California, 1985). ``They say, `If staying in New York means having
only one kid, I'll do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Only children may no longer be seen as deprived, but their
parents still sometimes come in for criticism for being
self-centered or for spoiling their offspring. ``We seem to have a
generation of Eloises in Manhattan,'' said Danielle Crittenden, a
cultural critic and the author of ``What Our Mothers Didn't Tell
Us: Why Happiness Eludes the Modern Woman'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1999). ``Our standards for what we think we need to give our
children, in space and in things, is outrageous, absurd. Children
are like consumptive items, like a Jaguar. It's very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gerson, who has a 16-year-old daughter who is an only child,
said she is now interviewing 18- to 30-year-olds for her research,
many of whom are themselves only children and ``take having only
one kid pretty much as a given.''
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions may well be influenced by the remarkable
turnaround in the attitude of psychologists and child-rearing
experts. Until the 1970s, the prevailing wisdom among experts, and
society in general, was that having an only child was tantamount to
cruelty. This view, shaped by turn-of-the century studies of the
pioneering psychologist G. Stanley Hall, held that only children
were spoiled and self-centered. ``Being an only child,'' Dr. Hall
wrote in 1892, ``is a disease in itself.'' Dr. Hall's influence was
profound: surveys throughout the years have shown that the primary
reason people cite for having a second child is to make sure their
first child isn't maladapted, Dr. Gerson said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last 20 years, there has been a 180-degree shift.
Now, experts say there is virtually no difference between only
children and first-born children in self-esteem, generosity,
popularity and relations to parents. In fact, many studies show
that only children score higher on I.Q. tests and are more popular
with peers than children with several other siblings. The
psychologist Toni Falbo published a review of 141 studies in 1984
and concluded, ``Only children scored significantly better than
other groups in achievement motivation and personal adjustment and
were in all other respects indistinguishable from children with
brothers and sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanning volumes on child-rearing in Barnes &AMP; Noble, it is
virtually impossible to find a condemnation of the choice to raise
an only child. A new generation of name-brand experts in
child-rearing has emerged, all of whom insist that Dr. Hall's
studies had no basis in fact, including Ann Laybourn of the Centre
for the Study of the Child and Society at Scotland's Glasgow
University and Susan Newman, author of ``Parenting an Only Child''
(Doubleday, 1990). Last year, the journalist Bill McKibben wrote
``Maybe One'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1998), an ecological defense of
only childhood that used a battery of new studies as ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   To cynics, and some parents of more than one child, it may be
hard not to wonder if psychology is not merely reflecting changes
in the societal landscape. With more women in the work force by
choice or necessity, and higher rates of infertility, it may seem
all too pat that new research shows that only children are not
disadvantaged. ``There is no doubt that we have a great ability to
mold our ideas of what is good for our children based on what is
good for us,'' Dr. Gerson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
