<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JASPER-DAD-$ADV24-1ST     10-22 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-DAD-$ADV24-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF THIRD SUSPECT IN JASPER SLAYING SAYS SON INNOCENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 24) 
(Eds.: Trial begins Monday) 
 
(Sub to include added information) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Ohio _ Louis Hezebicks was dreaming of being reunited
with his son, Shawn Berry, whom he last saw as a toddler 20 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He was hoping that Shawn and his older brother would drive
Shawn's battered, gray Ford pickup the 1,270 miles from Texas to
northeastern Ohio for a grand reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Then a network television news report about a racial crime
caught his eye. Three white men had dragged a black man to death
near Jasper, Texas, where his sons lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and saw this picture of this gray pickup truck ...
and I knew right then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the confirmation of his worst fears came
when his son, Shawn, was identified as one of the three white men
arrested in one of the most vicious racial crimes in modern
history.
</P>
<P>
   The truck he had hoped would bring his sons to him had instead
been used to drag James Byrd Jr. almost three miles down
back-country roads. His decapitated body had been found in front of
a black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, now 24, goes on trial for capital murder Monday in
Jasper, Texas, for his role in the June 7, 1998, slaying. Juries
have already convicted his two companions at the time, Bill King,
also 24, and Russell Brewer Jr., 32. Both were sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
   Berry claims he had no part in the murder and tried to stop the
other two when they began beating Byrd in a forest clearing before
they chained him to the truck. Berry admits, though, that he was
driving in the early morning hours of June 7, 1998, when he stopped
to pick up Byrd, 49, as the older man staggered home drunk from a
party.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after Berry's arrest, Hezebicks called the Jasper
County Jail and was allowed to talk briefly with his son. ``He
called me Dad,'' Hezebicks said. ``He told me he didn't do it. And
I have to believe him because he's my son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that anybody who has any part of me in them
could do anything like that. I feel so bad about the Byrd family.
What a terrible thing for them to go through,'' Hezebicks said in
his first interview about the Jasper case.
</P>
<P>
   He heads the shipping department of an electronics company in
this blue-collar town about an hour's drive from Cleveland. At 43,
he suffers from emphysema and said financial problems may keep him
from making the long trip to Jasper to be with his son during the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go down there and just walk around and talk to
people, if they'd talk to me,'' he said. ``I'd like to see the Byrd
family and tell them how sorry I am for all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's parents and sisters have embraced relatives of the other
two defendants during the earlier trials. They have asked for
justice, not retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to talk to that sheriff down there or somebody and
see if there's any way I could just see my son and hug him,'' he
said. ``I may never get to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would also like to visit with Shawn's girlfriend,
Christie Marcontell, and the couple's toddler son, Michael Montana.
</P>
<P>
   If Berry is convicted of capital murder, he faces either life in
prison or the death penalty. In either case, his visitors in prison
wouldn't be allowed to touch him. If he gets a life sentence, he
wouldn't be eligible for parole for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never see him come out,'' Hezebicks said. ``I won't live
that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Berry was the second son born to Hezebicks and Kathleen
Berry, high school lovers whose relationship began when he saw her
across the cafeteria in Geneva Junior High School.
</P>
<P>
   She was a couple of years older, hungry for adventure. He would
ride his bicycle, cutting through a trailer park to the street
where she lived with her parents across from her grandparents' mink
farm.
</P>
<P>
   He was barely 17 and still in high school when their first son,
Louis Berry, was born. Hezebicks said he wanted to get married, but
their parents and even a minister suggested they live together
instead, he recalled. He said he worked 48 hours a week at a gas
station while trying to finish high school and take care of his
little family.
</P>
<P>
   By then, her &UR;  &LR; parents had moved to Jasper County and Kathie, as
she was known, restlessly moved back and forth between Ohio and
Texas. Eighteen months after Louis, Shawn was born. He had his
mother's green eyes, but in adulthood, his dark hair and slender
build is much like Hezebicks'.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie was a ``free spirit,'' Hezebicks remembered, who was more
interested in having good times than trying to build a family. She
took off to Texas with their sons. On Dec. 12, 1976, she married
Don Hopson in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Hezebicks said he even wondered sometimes if he really was
Shawn's father. Then last month he watched an interview of his son
on the CBS-TV program ``60 Minutes II.'' ``There's no doubt now,''
he said. ``We just look too much alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathie and Don Hopson were together just two years, long enough
to have a daughter. Hezebicks said he got a phone call from Kathie,
saying she had gotten a divorce and wanted to come to Ohio but
couldn't make the trip alone with three small children. He flew to
Beaumont, Texas, and drove her and the kids to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long, however, before he learned that the divorce
wasn't final and that money was still owed on the car she was
driving. Hopson and his family arrived to pick up the baby daughter
and ended up taking the two boys back to Texas as well. Kathie's
parents in Kirbyville got custody of the boys.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last Hezebicks ever saw of Shawn. His mother kept
up with the boys over the years, exchanging letters and pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hopson remained a father figure for Shawn and Louis. They
lived with him and his parents at different times over the years,
even though he and their mom had both married other people by then.
At one time, they lived with Hopson in a house on Huff Creek Road,
near where Byrd was slain. In the ``60 Minutes'' interview, Berry
said he and his dad, meaning Hopson, had lived on that road.
</P>
<P>
   Hopson committed suicide in 1990. By then, Shawn was 15 and
Louis 17 and they were largely on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials in Jasper say they have no idea where
Berry's mother is.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1991, Kathleen Wright, as she was then known, was
sentenced to seven years in prison after pleading guilty to a
charge of delivery of a small amount of cocaine. Records indicate
that &UR;  &LR; she never went to prison, but was paroled after serving about
three months in county jail.
</P>
<P>
   She was indicted in a similar case in 1993, but records indicate
she was never arrested on that charge.
</P>
<P>
   Hezebicks eventually married, had three daughters, divorced and
remarried. He and his family live in a Civil War-era house near the
center of his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Although he says he at last has the family he always wanted,
Hezebicks says he has always wondered about his sons. ``There was
always this piece of me that was missing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then a couple of years ago his wife, Gina, began a search for
the boys on the Internet. She gave Hezebicks phone numbers to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even remember what I found or how I found it,'' she
said. ``I just tried everything I could think of and we started
coming up with some numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one night about three years ago, Louis, who had learned of
his father's search, called him.
</P>
<P>
   That phone reunion led to a few visits by Louis Berry. He once
spent several months living with the Hezebicks and even found a job
there.
</P>
<P>
   Louis went back to Texas, but said he planned to return. Perhaps
he would come back with Shawn, and maybe with their girlfriends.
They would make the trip, he said, in Shawn's gray pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure wish they had come up here before all this happened,''
Hezebicks said.
</P>
<P>
   He is convinced his son was in the wrong place at the wrong
time.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, however, contend that Shawn Berry was a thrill
seeker who eagerly joined in the brutal slaying with his buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish there was some sort of way I could go back and
make this all just not happen,'' Hezebicks said. ``If I could go
down there and chain myself to the back of a pickup truck, I'd
gladly let myself be drug down that road if it could make Mr. Byrd
come back. Nobody deserves what happened to that poor man.''
</P>
<P>
   If his son is acquitted or somehow eventually released from
prison, Hezebicks said he would urge him to move to Ohio, change
his name and start a new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my way, their names would have always been
Hezebicks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to just walk around down there in Jasper and talk to
people and ask them if they know my son and what they think about
him,'' he said. ``I'd like to know if they think he's somebody who
can do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
