<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-JAPANESE-AMERICAN-MEM     10-22 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-AMERICAN-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABBITT SAYS `NEVER AGAIN' AT JAPANESE AMERICAN MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A few months after the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor
on December 7, 1941, Masaji Inoshita, his parents and nine brothers
and sisters were forced to leave their California farm and move to
an internment camp in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   This, despite the fact that Inoshita and his siblings were born
in the United States and had never set foot in their ancestral home
of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his anger at the government for questioning his loyalty,
Inoshita readily signed up when U.S. Army recruiters came to the
internment camp looking for volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Inoshita spent more than three years with the Japan-American
442nd Regimental Combat Team fighting in Italy and France while his
family remained at the Gila River Internment Camp surrounded by
barbed-wire fences and armed guards. More than 33,000 Japanese
Americans served in U.S. forces during World War II and the 442nd
would become one of most decorated units in U.S. military history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we had to prove ourselves,'' Inoshita said of his
decision to fight for the country that had imprisoned him and
120,000 other Japanese Americans during World War II. ``I was born
here. This is my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 years later, Inoshita, age 80, represented the Gila
River Internment Camp during a ground-breaking ceremony Friday for
the National Japanese American Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will sit in a triangular park between the U.S.
Capitol and Union Station and is expected to be open to the public
in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending were representatives from the nine other
internment camps the U.S. government set up to confine Japanese
Americans during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The monument will contain the names of the more than 800
Japanese Americans who died fighting in World War II as well as the
names of the 10 internment camps on a curved granite wall.
</P>
<P>
   The center of the monument will be a 14-foot bronze statue of
two Japanese cranes struggling to free their wings from barbed
wire.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Akamu, a third-generation Japanese-American sculptor, said
she designed the statue to depict Japanese Americans' struggle to
free themselves from the camps and become fully recognized U.S.
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial is being paid for with $10 million in private funds
but it will be turned over to the United States Park Service when
it is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, who oversees the Park Service
said, ``This monument is here to say this must never, ever happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., who helped the National
Japanese American Memorial Foundation raise funds for the memorial,
told the audience, ``The American government could not make a
distinction of those who were leading the attack on Pearl Harbor
and Americans who were by accident of birth of Japanese ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial ``is a reflection about that time and the progress
that has been made over the years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta was also the author of 1988 legislation in which the
United States government formally apologized to the Japanese
Americans forcibly imprisoned during the war. The law also
authorized the payment of $20,000 to each of the 82,000 internment
camp survivors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. ADDITIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mineta was 11 years-old when he and his family were forced to
leave their San Jose, Calif., home for an internment camp shortly
after President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed Executive Order 9066
on Feb. 19, 1942, authorizing imprisonment of people of Japanese
heritage from the West Coast out of fear that they would align
themselves with the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt's action followed a wave of hysteria that swept the
region in the weeks following Pearl Harbor. Thousands of people
prepared for an attack on California as rumors spread that Japanese
ships were spotted off Santa Barbara and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   From San Diego to Seattle, people of Japanese heritage were
relocated to the 10 camps. Some Japanese Americans were sent as far
away as Colorado and Arkansas where they stayed until the war ended
in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
