<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDNIGHT IN THE GARDEN OF EXCESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (For release Thurs., Oct. 28)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Be careful of too much success. Your house could
become so famous they'd have to install a porta-potty across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   In this center of southern charm and intrigue, where men fought
duels and ladies wilted, you can quickly tell you're at Mercer
House, the red brick mansion where antique dealer Jim Williams shot
his young assistant and lover Danny Hansford. Right in the middle
of Monterey Square, among the old oaks dripping with Spanish moss,
is a portable toilet for the comfort of tourists who come to stare
at Mercer House.
</P>
<P>
   You must know about Jim and Danny. If you came to Savannah and
didn't know them or Selena or Adler or Lester or Lady Chablis
because you hadn't read ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and
Evil,'' you wouldn't catch half the references on the tour bus.
Savannah has been around a lot longer than The New York Times best
seller list but given the preponderance of ``Midnight'' gewgaws
hawked just about everywhere, you'd think it was the city's only
real claim to fame.
</P>
<P>
   The book is nothing to be ashamed of. It's a good story based on
bizarre and real events and well written but it's no classic.
Flannery O'Conner, who lived in Savannah, was a writer of classics.
There are bookstores that give her her due but she doesn't have a
coffee mug and a refrigerator magnet in her name. Nor, apparently,
does fellow Savannahian poet Conrad Aiken.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no escaping ``Midnight'' and renditions of its
cover, the statue of the Bird Girl, which is reproduced in
bookends, cookbook covers and Christmas ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   You don't see any obvious voodoo priestesses or people drinking
martinis in cemeteries, nor standout drag queens, at least none as
hot as Lady Chablis, who still occasionally performs around town
and has her own Web site and book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midnight's'' author, John Berendt, who made an estimated $9
million so far just on the hardcover, comes back now and again,
recently for a party to kick off the paperback version. Every
interview with him that's seemingly ever been done is plastered on
some wall in some gift shop or bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The book has been out since 1994. It's sold 2.5 million copies
in hard cover alone. It was on the best seller list for four years.
It's a good yarn and stacked with sex and violence and that
peculiar decadence that oozes Southern. But after a couple of days
of seeing it everywhere, you kind of begin to hate the thing.
</P>
<P>
   At one gift store, with three rooms singularly devoted to
``Midnight,'' a clerk sat watching a football game, perhaps trying
to drown out the movie soundtrack which played the same song,
``Skylark,'' over and over. A potential customer said she'd
purchase her postcards elsewhere. ``I don't like to encourage this
kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   One guidebook says that the book has brought in more than $10
million in tourist revenue. It's even boosted real estate prices.
And while some locals are said to be fed up to their feathers with
``Midnight'' hype, others are loving the attention and waiting for
it to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   They're getting ready to film a movie in Savannah with Will
Smith and Matt Damon, directed by Robert Redford, according to a
waiter who also whispered that downstairs at that very moment Matt
Damon was dining with Winona Ryder. They like going to his
restaurant because they can be left alone, he said, going on to
tell the surrounding tables the same news, as well as sharing the
code name they use when making reservations. He said we also might
keep an eye out for Redford.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah's done others. Here is the park where Forrest Gump sat
on a bench and defined life. Here is the restaurant where Julia
Roberts spied on her husband in ``Something to Talk About.'' Before
I went there I imagined Savannah looking like a scene out of
``Prince of Tides,'' but that movie was actually filmed up the road
at Beaufort, the same place where they filmed ``The Big Chill.''
Maybe high school kids would learn geography better if they could
link famous movies to different parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   What's happened in Savannah, though, is more than having a movie
crew come to town to memorialize its pretty face. Here it's life
imitating art imitating life. Before Jim Williams met author
Berendt he was embroiled in a debate with another city figure over
how the town was growing. Some of the graceful old homes were being
ripped down and turned into parking garages. Now Jim is dead, his
lover is dead, Berendt is rich and Savannah is saved, in a manner
of speaking.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
