<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY AND THE BEASTS: IT'S A MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Horenstein claims he doesn't know very much about animals.
Yet his appreciation of them is graphic.
</P>
<P>
   In two new books _ ``A is for . . . ?'' (Harcourt Brace) and
``Creatures'' (Pond Press) _ the photographer invites readers into
a secret realm in which even the most recognizable animals become
riddles.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, he translates into film a truth that the most
ardent nature lover knows well _ animals are ultimately unknowable.
No matter how much you learn about them, there is still mystery.
That's how it is with a great romance.
</P>
<P>
   Horenstein found himself looking straight into the eyes of some
animals. Connecting. But also wondering. ``Who the hell knows
what's going on in there?'' he says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   In these books, as well as in a current exhibit at the New
England School of Photography on Commonwealth Avenue, Horenstein
surprises in brown-toned portraits of zoo and aquarium animals.
</P>
<P>
   With soft, sensual images produced using black-and-white film
and color processing, Horenstein, a seasoned photographer who
teaches at the Rhode Island School of Design and has written a
classic textbook on photography, shows off a passion for form _
concentrating on lines and curves rather than cliched, standard
images.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, it's just a part of an animal we see. And not the
parts one might expect. His giraffe shot doesn't include the neck.
No trunk to depict his elephant. And there isn't even a glimpse of
a shell in his tortoise portrait.
</P>
<P>
   With the children's book ``A is for . . . ?,'' this becomes a
game in which the reader has a letter from the alphabet and a small
segment of an animal as clues. And guessing which animal is not
always so easy. You have to think. Sometimes hard.
</P>
<P>
   Horenstein knows the feeling. ``I love animals,'' he says, ``but
I really don't know what's going on with them.'' The photographer
says his editor pushed him ``to look for mystery'' in the animal
world, and that, in fact, is what he always saw.
</P>
<P>
   Through four years of lugging 60 or 70 pounds of camera
equipment into various zoos and aquariums, often working with
natural light, Horenstein was often surprised:
</P>
<P>
   By the cownose ray (looking exactly like a society matron, pearl
necklace and all) who kept coming back to stare at him. ``I
definitely had a feeling she was watching me,'' Horenstein says.
</P>
<P>
   By the cheetah at Roger Williams Park Zoo who sat up suddenly at
the sound of dinner approaching and gave Horenstein an unusual
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   By the delicate fingernails on the walrus's flipper.
</P>
<P>
   And by the beauty of the hippo's back, which appears on the
cover of ``Creatures,'' taken with a cheap camera picked up at the
last moment during a trip to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Horenstein's pictures surprise too. He makes a duck look
pensive. A beluga look blissful. And akomodo dragon appear wise,
notmenacing.
</P>
<P>
   And now Horenstein is hooked. Though he's documented lots of
worlds with his camera _ flowers, baseball, bicycles _ he's
plotting his next animal adventures. He'll be checking out animals
in European zoos for a possible ``Creatures Redux,'' and he's
looking into fellowships that just might help him keep his eye on
animals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good night with Goodall: Famed chimpanzee expert Jane Goodall is
back in the spotlight with a new documentary and companion book
both called ``Jane Goodall: Reason for Hope.'' The show airs twice,
Nov. 7 at noon, and Nov. 8 at 10 p.m. on WGBH-TV (Ch. 2). ``Reason
for Hope'' traces Goodall's spiritual journey from a child growing
up in Bournemouth, England, to National Geographic pinup girl in
Tanzania in the 1960s, to the revered globe-trotting naturalist she
is today.
</P>
<P>
   What drove Goodall to share her thoughts about spirituality? The
woman seems incapable of fudging. In a 10-minute interview
conducted just before a talk she gave at Harvard a few weeks ago,
she revealed that the family home in Bournemouth is in desperate
need of repair, and the offer from the publisher was just right.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the film, narrated by Harrison Ford, is as
uplifting as it is moving, with great archival footage, recent
scenes, and music from Bobby McFerrin accompanying Goodall's
thoughts. Despite the ongoing destruction of chimpanzee habitat,
and the horrifying conditions in which so many lab chimps are kept,
Goodall dares to be optimistic as she travels constantly around the
world to raise awareness and funds.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times recently poked fun at Goodall, calling her
latest adventures ``a little icky-poo.'' But at the same time, the
writer also referred to chimpanzees as monkeys. They're apes _ the
chimps, that is. ``Reason for Hope'' gets the proverbial two
opposable thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
