<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5326 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-GREGORYPECK-TEX     10-22 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GREGORYPECK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR CONVERSATION WITH GREGORY PECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My agent told me, `You could be a big Western star.' But I
liked to talk,'' Gregory Peck says, chuckling. Instead, Peck
emerged as the kind of actor who starred in more different types of
movies that audiences hold close to their hearts than perhaps any
other major actor. Certainly, the stars of Peck's era _ Henry
Fonda, James Stewart, John Wayne, Cary Grant _ made pictures that
audiences took to, but they rested in a specific type of persona.
</P>
<P>
   Peck combined warmth, masculinity and good looks, and he varied
his film resume in a career that varied from ``The Gunfighter'' in
1950 to ``Roman Holiday'' in 1953 to ``The Omen'' in 1976. And even
to working with Alfred Hitchcock on ``Spellbound'' (''He was not an
actor's director,'' he remarks of Hitchcock, although Peck politely
describes the experience as ``satisfying'' and ``pleasant.''
Hitchcock's direction consisted of ``just drain your face of all
emotion.'')
</P>
<P>
   Peck's more of a protean actor. In the cable special, ``A
Conversation With Gregory Peck,'' running this month on TCM,
audience members _ literally from all over the globe _ stand up to
testify about the effect a Peck performance had on them. Peck will
offer a similar opportunity to audience members this afternoon at
Bass Performance Hall, when, as part of the Fort Worth Film
Festival, he turns his life into a one-man show and takes questions
from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came from the theater,'' Peck muses, ``where the idea was to
do a variety of things. I guess I could've gotten into a groove,
but I wanted to take a chance.'' What Peck isn't as well regarded
for is that his roots as an actor are very similar to those of
Marlon Brando and James Dean. Studying at New York's Neighborhood
Playhouse with Sanford Meisner _ a seminal teacher who encouraged
his students to look upon acting as behavior rather than simple
representation _ Peck brought a searching quality to his work,
which contradicted his broad-shouldered confidence. That training
gave Peck an important tenet upon which he could build his work:
(Meisner) ``kept hammering on acting as doing. I would always
remind myself of that. I had to learn to be a movie actor. And it
took some time, I must say. But I never found acting for film
difficult. I never felt put upon by it at all.'' Peck credits yet
another teacher for the elegant way he moves on screen _
dancer/choreographer Martha Graham, with whom he studied for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Peck feels that he came into his own in his second film, ``The
Keys of the Kingdom,'' in which he was an aging priest who plays
over all the deeds of his life. ``When I did `Keys,' I was very
sincere,'' he notes, then adds, ``I learned to put a little gravy
on it.'' He definitely ladled on the flavor for ``The Macomber
Affair,'' an adaptation of Ernest Hemingway's short story ``The
Short Happy Life of Francis Macomber'' and one of the best literary
translations ever brought to the screen. (It wasn't his last
Hemingway protagonist; Peck also starred in ``The Snows of
Kilimanjaro.'') He found himself attracted to leads that were less
than classical protagonists. ``That's true,'' he responds,
modestly. ``I did play some nonheroes in my day. Quite a few of
them, actually. But (starring in an adaptation) of the Great
American Novel was not daunting.''
</P>
<P>
   That capacity to make a deeper contact with an audience isn't
something that just happens, Peck believes. Proof of that is the
work that it took to get ``The Yearling'' _ the damp-eyed classic
adaptation of Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings' book, in which he plays the
father of a young boy who develops a special relationship with his
pet deer _ to the screen. ``I was pretty green at the time. (The
movie was made in '46.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scene when we named the little fawn, we had to keep him
in the shot. And the deer didn't want to stay in the shot. It was
110 degrees _ I remember they would come and rub us down with cool
chamois cloths between takes _ and the deer just refused to stay
put. It kept walking off. It took 76 takes in all to get it.''
Which may explain why Peck appears to be so patient and thoughtful
in the film; he learned it the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, Peck's roughest time came on his most ambitious
role, starring as the obsessed Captain Ahab in director John
Huston's ``Moby Dick.'' ``Young people still come up to me and say,
`I remember ``Moby Dick''; it shook me up.' But it got mixed
reviews when it cam out. I took a little lambasting for it when it
came out. And it was difficult, shooting all that stuff on the
water was very trying for all the actors. But I never regretted
trying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Peck limited his men-wrestling-with-damage roles to
literary adaptations. He fights his conscience in, of all things,
the romantic comedy ``Roman Holiday,'' which was the first of his
collaborations with director William Wyler. ``I met Wyler at
Grauman's Chinese (the legendary movie theater in Hollywood) at the
premiere of `Twelve O'Clock High.' '' And how did Peck get the lead
in ``Holiday''? ``Well, (Wyler) said to me, `Can you play comedy?'
I told him I played the Mischa Auer part in `You Can't Take It With
You' onstage. And I was funny.'' Not only is he funny, but he's
complicated. Peck is a journalist secretly running around Italy
with a princess-in-hiding (Audrey Hepburn) and wondering whether he
should expose her. ``(Holiday'' takes on even more resonance in
light of the tragedy surrounding the death of Princess Diana.)
</P>
<P>
   And one of the biggest moments in ``Roman Holiday'' is a test of
truth, when Peck and Hepburn stick their hands in the mouth of a
stone idol _ which will bite it off if they're lying (and both are)
_ and Peck pretends to withdraw only a stump. ``That's an old trick
of Red Skelton. Wyler thought it was corny, but he said, `It's only
film.' '' Peck says with a laugh. `` `Go ahead and do it.' '' It
seems, too, that Peck was falling in love with Hepburn, as the
world would when ``Holiday'' was released. ``Well, of course. She
was luminous.'' Even though it was her first starring role, Peck
pushed for Hepburn to get a credit equal to his: ``She deserved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peck reflects on the relationship that audiences have with his
films, the affection that sent so many young people into law school
after seeing his heroic country lawyer Atticus Finch in ``To Kill a
Mockingbird.'' ``They don't get it out of there unless you put it
there,'' Peck says. ``You deal in feelings, but you can't get too
sloppy about it. But not all of my movies touch off the hair of the
back your neck. Sometimes, it's just work. And that can be a good
thing, too. But in those cases where the movies came to mean
something, I can't think of one that I did not respond to when I
read the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean,'' he laughs, ``that's why you say, `Yes!' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
