<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AIR-FUTURE23-COX     10-22 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FUTURE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAGAZINE SEES 'GRIDLOCK' IN U.S. AIR TRAFFIC
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The normally staid and technical magazine Aviation
Week is pushing the alarm button in a special report filled with
dire predictions of worsening congestion, narrower safety margins
and increasing delays in air travel.
</P>
<P>
   After evaluating the worldwide air traffic system, David M.
North, the magazine's editor-in-chief, writes in Monday's issue,
``we found that Europe is indeed in a state of crisis with delays
and gridlock, and the U.S. is rapidly approaching that point.''
</P>
<P>
   With an expected 50 percent increase in the U.S. flying public
over the next decade, the report predicted that an average travel
day in 2010 will have the feel of a current Wednesday before
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The report blames the problems on an ``archaic'' air travel
infrastructure and the failure of the Clinton administration, the
U.S. Transportation Department and Congress to act on
recommendations made by three commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger discontent has yet to unite into a movement strong
enough to force action, said the report, despite a doubling of
complaints filed with the government this year compared with 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine outlines an action plan including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Splitting the Federal Aviation Administration into two parts,
one to oversee safety and the other to provide air traffic
services.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gradually privatizing the air traffic control system,
described as using outmoded methods that are incapable of handling
current traffic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Using all of the $10 billion Airport and Airway Trust Fund,
which is collected from airline ticket taxes, toward building and
expanding airports and runways. Some of those funds have been used
to reduce federal deficits in the past.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guaranteeing better treatment of passengers, including minimum
seat space in economy class.
</P>
<P>
   Even with such improvements, the magazine offered a pessimistic
outlook for the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, the U.S. air travel system has been allowed to go so
long without a workable and sustained plan for modernization that
it is too late to have a solution in place before things get
worse,'' said North's editorial.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Brenner, spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, acknowledged that problems exist but argued that
the government is making improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system is beginning to show strain,'' he said, but ``the
administration has worked diligently over the past several years to
bring a new way of doing business and to modernizing the air
traffic control system.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the air traffic equipment is now being updated to
handle increasing traffic. He added, ``Congress is now working on
the reauthorization bill that should contain some changes that
should assist us.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Aviation Week concluded that the government effort has
fallen short and pinned hopes on a new administration that would
make the problem a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   Said the magazine: ``Unless this reform is addressed quickly,
the air transport system could slowly grind to a halt in some
sectors. Much worse, the margin of safety now in place with
everyone doing their job, could be seriously eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenner dismissed safety concerns. ``We will never compromise
safety,'' he said. ``We'll slow traffic down before we compromise
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
