<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NASCAR-EVERNHAM-NYTR &LR;      10-22 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-EVERNHAM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY EVERNHAM MOVES TO DODGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Evernham could have played it safe. He could have stayed at
Hendrick Motorsports. The deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   Rick and John Hendrick, who own and run what many regard as the
most powerful team in Winston Cup, knew Evernham wanted to be more
than just Jeff Gordon's crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   So they had worked out an arrangement whereby beginning next
year, Evernham was to become chief operating officer and general
manager of Hendrick Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   But at the last minute, Evernham turned them down.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he opted for a new role, electing to head up Dodge's
return to Winston Cup racing in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   For Evernham, it was a challenge, just as molding an unproven
driver and a new team into a consistent winner had been. But once
Gordon and that team, the Rainbow Warriors, reached the pinnacle of
success, some of the fire left Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I was making a big enough contribution
anymore,'' he said. ``I felt like they could go on without me and
keep winning and I was right. They are going to go on and get
better even if I'm not there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, a change benefits everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge brought Evernham in because of his innovative skills and
his methodical pay-attention-to-every-detail approach.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he is excited about starting a program from ground
zero. Others are excited for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when you're starting with a blank sheet of paper,
you can make everything the very best,'' said Ford's Robert Yates,
one of the most respected and successful car owners in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evernham knows how to organize things,'' said Yates, who owns
the cars driven by Dale Jarrett and Kenny Irwin. ``He knows the
sport from the inside. He knows the people.`He shouldn't have a
problem getting guys to work for him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Evernham left Hendrick, he brought along Ed Guzzo, who had
been chief mechanic on Gordon's car.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to rely heavily on the engineering manpower at
Dodge, which Lou Patane, in charge of DaimlerChrysler's motorsports
program, said will be freely available to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be directly involved with the race team in design and
fabrication,'' Patane said. ``We've got a lot of development work
to do. Not only do we intend to compete, we intend to win, and few
people know more about winning at this level than Ray Evernham.''
</P>
<P>
   While courting Evernham, Dodge also tried to lure Gordon into
coming along as his driver. But Gordon elected to stay put,
recently signing what has been called a ``lifetime contract'' with
Hendrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have had Jeff Gordon, and we talked
about it,'' Evernham said. ``But we both decided this was the best
thing for me to do, and that staying with Hendrick was the best
thing for him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we decided that, there was no effort to say `come with
me.' We shook hands, and we're still good friends,'' Evernham said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Evernham isn't concerned with who will end up
driving his cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the focus is on building a competitive car and a
competitive race team,'' Evernham said. ``Like they say in Field of
Dreams, if you build it, they will come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be doing some testing next year, and we'll need
somebody to do that,'' he said. ``But first, we want to build the
race team and then as drivers become available, hopefully they'll
take a look at us.''
</P>
<P>
   So Evernham is off on a new venture, already counting down the
days to the 2001 Daytona 500, when Dodge makes its debut.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SCIENCE-ILLUSTRATION-     10-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-ILLUSTRATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING IS BELIEVING, SO ILLUSTRATIONS ARE AN ESSENTIAL PART OF
SCIENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC MESSINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the inventor of the lightning rod, Sir William Harris,
needed to illustrate the phenomenon of electricity for a new
treatise, he decided against a minutely observed etching or a
complex numerical chart. Instead he lined several pages of the
manuscript with gold-leaf and then simply ran an electric current
right across them.
</P>
<P>
   If the experiment didn't quite capture electricity itself, it
certainly caught its aftermath. Harris' book, ``Observations on the
Effects of Lightning on Floating Bodies,'' published in 1823, still
bears the series of ragged burn marks that sizzled across the
pages.
</P>
<P>
   But was Harris engaging in a pictorial gimmick or something
more?
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing Is Believing,'' an exhibition that opens Saturday, at
the New York Public Library, argues such illustrations are more:
they are an essential part of the creative process, playing a
critical role in the history of scientific and medical ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists or historians of science know these images; they
just haven't taken them that seriously in conjunction with the
text,'' said Miriam Mandelbaum of the library's rare books
division, who was the co-curator of the show with her colleague
Jennifer B. Lee. ``It's like words convey the ideas, and the images
are seen as pretty additions _ like children's book pictures or
something. We're showing that the relationship between text and
image is much more complicated. Images can make ideas more
accessible, forceful, popular.''
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Mandelbaum, even the most famous illustrations have been
undervalued in terms of their importance in communicating ideas,
whether they are medieval renderings of an Earth-centered cosmos or
the first X-rays of the human body in the late 19th century. The
exhibition, which is dominated by works from the library's own
collections, includes some of the seminal scientific texts of the
last millennium, with Darwin's 1859 masterwork, ``Origin of
Species,'' and Sir Isaac Newton's ``Principia Mathematica'' (1687)
among them.
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Edward Tufte of Yale, who has written extensively about
information design, goes further, arguing that an image is often
indivisible from an idea. ``If you think about it, most scientific
problems are either inherently visual or inherently mathematical,
and the words are a human code, a layer of abstraction away from
the underlying mathematical visual phenomenon,'' he said. ``It's
hard to imagine how you could reason about anything of any
complexity that's physical without involving vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider Andreas Vesalius' ``De Humani Corporis Fabrica'' or
``The Structure of the Human Body,'' the first book to detail human
anatomy. Over time the richly illustrated 1543 work revolutionized
medicine by showing that anatomy should be learned directly from
the dissection of human bodies (and not animals) and by introducing
the scientific method.
</P>
<P>
   Or William Harvey's publication of ``De Motu Cordis,'' ``On the
Motion of the Heart,'' in 1628. His explanation of how blood
circulates _ arguably the greatest medical discovery in history _
is persuasively captured in graphic drawings delineating the veins
and arteries of body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Medical and scientific illustrations haven't always received the
recognition they deserve, argues Tufte, who will be speaking as
part of the library's lecture series, because of ``accidents of
publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vesalius' sumptuously colored original copy was hand painted for
Emperor Charles V, so it was not mass-produced. By the end of the
19th century, however, the process of chromolithography made color
printing cheap and pervasive. That's why another of the show's
displays, Prang's Prize Babies (1888), a saccharine print of six
rosy-cheeked infants, could be sold door to door.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the original manuscripts of da Vinci or Galileo
or Newton, they integrate words and images _ it's all part of a
coherent verbal-visual narrative,'' Tufte explains. ``The problem
is when their manuscript then passes through economizing
printers.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said: ``You can see how, say, Newton talks about
prism ABC'' in the manuscript, ``but he doesn't then put a picture
of prism ABC in the back of the book. The publisher does that.
Newton has it in the text.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
