<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-BOWDENS-NYTR &LR;      10-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWDENS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FSU-CLEMSON GAME PITS FATHER AGAINST SON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., S.C., W.Va.)  (mk) 
 By BRIAN ETTKIN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The acorn did not fall far from the family
tree, even as the dummy swung from a branch in effigy.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden was coaching West Virginia 25 falls ago, in the
midst of his worst season ever, and his son Tommy, a receiver on
the 1974 team, was among the first to see it. Tommy strode to the
tree on the college campus and intended to remove the unflattering
caricature of his father, but a school security guard stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy says, `This is public property. You can't take that
guy down,''' recalled Tommy, Clemson's coach. ``I said, `But that's
my father.' And he said, `Well, you still can't.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is how Tommy unequivocally proved he is his father's son.
Instead of clenching his fists in anger, Tommy disarmed him with
Southern charm.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Bowdens nearly always do, he won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I said, `I'm not trying to cut it down. I am trying
to add more stuffing,''' Tommy said. ``He's fatter than what y'all
made him out to be.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby and his wife, Ann, say that of their six children, Tommy
is the one most like his father. He kills you with kindness before
his football team treats you unkindly. Christian fundamentalists
who coach so unconservatively.
</P>
<P>
   When coaches Bobby and Tommy make history in Saturday's first
father vs. son Division I-A football game, in Clemson's Death
Valley, you'll see similarities in demeanor and Florida State's and
Clemson's offenses. Tommy influenced Bobby to incorporate the
shotgun formation when Charlie Ward was FSU's quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   It will be as if Tommy was born for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy still has an old profile that compares the personality
traits of the Bowden boys and their father. The readings for Bobby
and son Terry, the former Auburn coach who now serves as a college
football analyst for ABC, were askew in several categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You connect the dots and all that, then you send it in,''
Tommy said. ``Mine and my father's are graphically in line in every
category.''
</P>
<P>
   Take fear, for example. Neither Bobby nor Tommy throw caution to
the wind ...unless it's a spiraling football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy stayed out of trouble,'' Bobby said. ``This (son) would
do that, or this one would do this. But not 'ol sweet Tommy. Tommy
hated whippings. I could spank Terry and he'd say, `Hurry and get
through, so I can get back out and do it again.' Tommy, boy, it
would just kill him if you ever had to spank him. That's where he
was like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy is one of the three Bowden boys who followed the siren's
call of their father's whistle and became coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Steve, who is in private business, and Terry and little
brother Jeff, FSU's receivers coach, Tommy never veered from the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 years ago, when young Tommy had to write an
autobiography in sixth grade, choosing his vocational pursuit was
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a college head football coach were the direct words,''
Tommy said. ``Probably like most kids at that age, they choose the
profession that their father is in. That's why I chose it at that
time, but I never really deviated from that. That's the only thing
I really had strong feelings about.''
</P>
<P>
   Both compete fiercely. When Tommy coached receivers, his charges
were known for their blocking. Now, when Bobby watches game film
with Jeff and sees an FSU receiver miss a block, he'll remark:
``Tommy's receivers wouldn't have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's just kind of twisting the knife a little bit,''
Jeff said. ``He's a lot more hard-nosed than maybe people think.''
</P>
<P>
   It felt like a dagger had been jabbed into Tommy's rib cage
during a game against Southern Methodist, when he played for his
father at West Virginia. Tommy broke a rib, which punctured a lung,
but even as he was gasping for breath, he was responsible for
shuttling plays into the offensive huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember his daddy saying, `Tommy, you've got to get those
plays in quicker,''' said Dave Van Halanger, FSU's strength coach
who played on that West Virginia team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, I'm taking them in as fast as I can,'' Tommy replied
and continued to play. After the game, doctors poked a hole through
his chest, inserting a tube so the lung could be reinflated. The
scar remains, Bowden's badge of courage.
</P>
<P>
   A victory against Tommy would be Bobby's 300th in Division I.
Bobby is fifth in major-college career victories and won the 1993
national championship. Terry went 111-52-2 in 15 years, including
an undefeated season, in 1993, at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy is 21-7, after transforming downtrodden Tulane into a
winner; he now is attempting to return Clemson to a position of
national power.
</P>
<P>
   But during the '74 season, the Mountaineers' faithless tossed
beer cans in the Bowdens' front yard and planted ``For Sale''
signs. Tommy was incensed when he read a letter to the editor in
the school paper, ripping his dad and claiming the players lacked
confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy clipped and saved the article, and months later, after
somebody recognized the name of the author, Tommy and five of his
larger teammates marched to the man of letter's frat house and
demanded a retraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned completely white,'' said Van Halanger, who was among
the muscle on hand. ``He said, `Yeah, no problem. I'll do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy had won again.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
