</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Penn State 7-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 20 at Purdue 5-2
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, in handing Michigan State its first loss, Drew
Brees of Purdue passed for 509 yards. Penn State's defense (eight
sacks against Ohio State) should be tougher. Its offense is led by
quarterback Kevin Thompson, despite a slight separation of his
passing shoulder, and Eric McCoo, who rushed for 211 yards against
Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9 Tennessee 4-1
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 at Alabama 5-1
</P>
<P>
   A clash of Southeastern Conference powers. In its last three
games, Alabama beat Arkansas, Florida and Mississippi, all
nationally ranked, and averaged 451.3 yards in total offense. As
quarterback Andrew Zow said, ``People are now starting to take us
seriously.'' Alabama can run and Tennessee can stop the run.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Nebraska 6-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 18 at Texas 5-2
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Ryan Nunez of Texas said of Nebraska, ``Take that
logo off their helmets and they're just another team.'' Maybe so,
but Nebraska has one of the nation's best defenses, and in its last
game it rushed for 439 yards against a good Iowa State defense.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Florida State 7-0
</P>
<P>
   at Clemson 3-3
</P>
<P>
   For the first time ever in major-college football, the head
coaches are father (Bobby Bowden of Florida State) and son (Tommy
Bowden of Clemson). The father should collect career victory No.
300, especially with Peter Warrick back at wide receiver.
