<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5360 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ARCHITECTURE-CENTURY1     10-22 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-CENTURY1STAKE24-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To the suburbs and back
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 24.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As this century expires, politicians, media and a new
generation of planners are waging war on suburban sprawl. The
contemporary equivalent of the medieval plague, suburbia has been
blamed for everything from the Columbine High School murders in
Colorado to the increase in deer road kill in upstate Michigan, not
to mention the road rage-inducing commutes that metro Atlantans
endure every day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Cassandras who warned of the consequences of
unplanned and unlimited growth even before the turn of the 19th
century, we built countless residential subdivisions, strip
shopping centers and regional malls to create the perpetual
gridlock that has finally gotten America's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``During recent elections, there were more than 250 development
and growth measures on state ballots,'' says Michael Stanton,
president of the American Institute of Architects. ``This suggests
to me that the state of our environment has become an issue to the
average citizen. People are reacting to a nagging sense that
something has gone wrong with the way we live.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it is time to address the mess we've made. We should,
however, understand the factors that brought us to that point, or
we might, to alter the old saw a bit, be condemned to repeat
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawl is a result not only of historical forces, planning
philosophy and geography, but also of American ideals. To change
living patterns, do we have to modify minds and hearts as well as
zoning laws and streetscapes?
</P>
<P>
   Forget a chicken in every pot. What Americans have always wanted
is a house with a yard. In a country in which life is not centered
around the cathedral or the palace, our homes have truly become our
castles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American idea that cities could be made almost entirely of
free-standing private houses with their own gardens was an original
notion, at least in Western culture,'' architectural historian
Witold Rybczynski writes in his book ``City Life.'' ``It was a
powerful cultural idea that would later create all sorts of
difficulties as urban areas spread ever more widely to accommodate
this desire.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a plot of one's own runs deep. Thomas Jefferson
envisioned America as the land of rural self-reliance. The pioneers
fulfilled their manifest destiny with a little house on the
prairie. America started building suburbs by the mid-19th century.
No wonder returning World War II soldiers leapt at the chance for a
tract house in Levittown, the subdivisions in New York and
Pennsylvania whose name became synonymous with suburbia. The desire
has not abated until recently, when some have come to question
whether the costs outweigh the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Suburbia is the ying to the American city's yang. According to
David Galernter, author of ``A History of American Architecture:
Buildings in Their Cultural and Technological Context,'' we began
moving out of cities in response to industrial factories belching
smoke, overpopulation and the shifting social order caused by
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The development pattern of concentric rings of residential
suburbs segregated from commercial zones became defining
characteristics of the American experience,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   American capitalism egged on unplanned, or expedient, growth.
Chicago, for instance, gave up itide to the railroads. The
Windy City also gave birth to the skyscraper, which changed the
scale of cities and the real estate value of downtown property. In
fact, it helped create the idea of downtown as distinct from
residential neighborhoods and reinforced the segregated planning
patterns. (Even the ranch house, the stereotypical suburban home,
originated in part in Chicago with Frank Lloyd Wright's horizontal,
open-plan Prairie houses; Wright also invented the carport.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, suburbs kept expanding because they could. Unlike
Europe, America boasted lots of open space, and, thanks to Henry
Ford, we had the means to go where we wanted. The Model T first
rolled off the assembly line in 1913. By 1925, Americans owned
about 20 million cars.
</P>
<P>
   We like to paint all suburbs with the same damning brush. But
prized intown neighborhoods such as Ansley Park were originally
suburbs before growing cities absorbed them. Some of our earliest,
pre-automobile suburbs were more compact because their residents
depended on rail or trolley. The street was a public space rather
than a conduit for cars. Places such as Chestnut Hill, outside
Philadelphia, had their own commercial centers, too. Unfortunately,
post-automobile subdivisions were more like Radburn, N.J. Built in
1928 and billed as a town for the motor age, it featured open
space, curving roads and cul-de-sacs, and, since the street was
given over to cars, houses turned their backs on the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The suburbs really started sprawling after World War II, with
the swelling population of returning GIs and their families and
low-cost government mortgage loans. By 1950, developer Levitt and
Sons was producing a four-room house every 16 minutes. Folk singer
Pete Seeger immortalized the result in Malvina Reynolds' ``Little
Boxes,'' his famous song about ticky-tacky suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   Strip centers and malls closer to home quickly replaced downtown
as retail and even civic centers. Between 1960 and 1970, a total of
8,000 shopping centers were built. In the next two decades, the
number swelled by 25,000. Commercial development followed the
population. Atlanta's Perimeter Mall area typifies the resulting
``edge cities,'' aggregations of office parks, shopping malls and
subdivisions navigated only by car. They obviated the need to go to
the city at all.
</P>
<P>
   As the suburbs grew, cities withered. Between 1930 and 1945
urban centers stopped gaining population. Already blighted by
industry and slums, they suffered at the hands of wrongheaded
zoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the early movements advocating orderly planning had a
provision for regulating private property, so zoning became the
planning device,'' says Randall Roark, a professor of urban
planning at Georgia Tech. ``Though zoning laws were intended to
protect residential districts from commercial encroachment, they
ended up isolating pieces of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of zoning, modernist planning and architecture
was almost lethal. Planners in the thrall of French architect Le
Corbusier came close to instituting his vision of ``La Ville
Radieuse,'' a cityscape of high-rise islands connected by roadways.
The refined sensibilities of the best modernist structures, like,
say, Mies van der Rohe's Seagram Building in New York, devolved
into acres of cheaply constructed, flat-top, curtain-wall buildings
as boringly uniform and placeless as the suburban subdivisions were
accused of being. Siting them as lone objects in paved plazas made
the city more lifeless. Applying those architectural and planning
principles to low-cost housing only ensured more slums. Urban
renewal it was not.
</P>
<P>
   President Dwight D. Eisenhower's Interstate Highway Act of 1956
paved the way for more urban destruction, as expressways rolled
through downtowns and neighborhoods. No wonder planning patriarch
Lewis Mumford called the cloverleaf the national flower.
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders tried all manner of attempts to revive their
cities _ pedestrian main streets, festival marketplaces, aquariums,
tax incentives _ with limited success. They even brought
suburban-style housing and shopping into the city. Faced with lousy
schools, crime and urban decay, Americans continued to decamp to
the green beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, cities garnered support. In 1961, Jane Jacobs
blasted modernist planning and advocated for dense, mixed-use urban
blocks in ``The Death and Life of Great American Cities.'' That
same year, architect John Portman, in the true spirit of urban
renewal, anchored the convention business downtown by building the
Merchandise Mart. The 1972 demolition of Pruitt-Igoe, a high-rise
housing project in St. Louis, was official acknowledgment of the
failure of these environments for improving the well-being of poor
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Other forces came into play. The preservation movement
popularized the idea of finding new uses for old buildings we
ordinarily tore down. In 1965, old warehouses near Fisherman's
Wharf in San Francisco were revived as Ghirardelli Square. The
grass-roots fight to save the Fox Theatre in the 1970s was
Atlanta's benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Architect Robert Venturi and his co-authors incubated
postmodernism in their 1966 book, ``Complexity and Contradiction in
Architecture.'' Whatever one thinks of that movement, buildings
designed under its banner introduced some variety into the
cityscape _ remember the splash Philip Johnson's One Atlantic
Center made when it opened in 1987 _ and also called attention to
the importance of context in building cities.
</P>
<P>
   On the neighborhood front, London architect Leon Krier tried to
resurrect the organization of the pre-industrial city. He was
mentor to Miami architects Andres Duany and Elizabeth
Plater-Zyberk, who put ideas into practice in Seaside, the Florida
Panhandle resort that rehabilitated small lots and carefully
orchestrated public spaces, not to mention the front porch, the
picket fence and walking. It was ground zero for new urbanism, the
philosophy of planning that preaches a return to old values.
</P>
<P>
   Other anti-sprawl voices have sounded in the past two decades.
To promote denser development close in, Portland, Ore., drew a
growth development line in the outskirts and will not extend water
and sewer lines beyond that point. Next year Milwaukee will start
dismantling the freeway system that carved up its downtown. All
over the country, the children of those who had turned up their
noses at the city started moving back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5361 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ARCHITECTURE-TIMELINE     10-22 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-TIMELINE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Architecture timeline during the last 100 years
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 24
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1897
</P>
<P>
   The Flatiron Building, the oldest skyscraper in downtown
Atlanta, is finished. Its creator is Bradford Gilbert, who also is
credited with designing the first steel-framed skyscraper in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   1906
</P>
<P>
   McKim, Mead and White, the leading purveyors of the beaux-arts
style in America, start Pennsylvania Station in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Candler Building, named for original owner and Coca-Cola Co.
founder Asa Candler, rises on Peachtree Street.
</P>
<P>
   1909
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lloyd Wright completes the Robie House in Oak Park, Ill.,
the exemplar of his Prairie style.
</P>
<P>
   1910
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Herndon, wife of
</P>
<P>
   black business magnate Alonzo Herndon, designs their home, now a
museum, on University Place in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1912
</P>
<P>
   Odd Fellows Building by William A. Edwards is built on Sweet
Auburn, the heart of black
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's business district.
</P>
<P>
   1913
</P>
<P>
   The Healey Building in downtown Atlanta, with its rotunda space,
is designed by Bruce and Morgan and Walter T. Downing.
</P>
<P>
   1916
</P>
<P>
   The Fagus Shoe Factory in
</P>
<P>
   Germany, designed by Walter Gropius and Adolf Meyer,
</P>
<P>
   introduces the glass curtain wall.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University quadrangle designed by Henry Hornbostel.
</P>
<P>
   1919
</P>
<P>
   The Bauhaus, the famous art and design school directed by Walter
Gropius, opens in Weimar,
</P>
<P>
   Germany.
</P>
<P>
   German architect Ludwig Mies van der Rohe makes
</P>
<P>
   a model for a glass
</P>
<P>
   skyscraper.
</P>
<P>
   1920
</P>
<P>
   The Temple, designed by Philip Shutze, opens in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1922
</P>
<P>
   Competition for the
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Tribune Tower turns into a survey of architecture, a
competition between the traditional and modernism. Raymond Hood's
gothic-style design wins this round, but the battle is joined.
</P>
<P>
   1923
</P>
<P>
   French architect who
</P>
<P>
   calls himself Le Corbusier
</P>
<P>
   publishes ``Vers une Architecture.'' Proclaiming the house as
``a machine for living,'' the manifesto states the aesthetic and
structural principles of modernist architecture.
</P>
<P>
   1924
</P>
<P>
   Schroder House, in Utrecht, the Netherlands, designed by Gerrit
Rietveld, features De Stijl
</P>
<P>
   architecture and is Mondrian in three dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   1925
</P>
<P>
   The Bauhaus moves to Dessau, Germany. Its building, designed by
Gropius, features International Style hallmarks: absence of
ornament, planar surfaces and a flat roof. The school merges art
and craft and integrates fine arts, decorative arts and
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   1928
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler Building is built in New York. William van Alen's
art deco style makes for a lasting landmark.
</P>
<P>
   1929
</P>
<P>
   Mies van der Rohe's Barcelona Pavilion, an exemplar of the
International Style, is destroyed. It's rebuilt for the 1992
Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Theatre in Atlanta, one of the great escapist movie
palaces of the period, turns heads.
</P>
<P>
   1932
</P>
<P>
   A landmark exhibition of the International Style, curated by
Philip Johnson and Henry-Russell Hitchcock at the Museum of Modern
Art in New York, introduces modernism to America. They spread their
ideas through the book ``The International Style: Architecture
Since 1922.''
</P>
<P>
   1935
</P>
<P>
   President Franklin D. Roosevelt dedicates the nation's first
</P>
<P>
   housing project, Atlanta's
</P>
<P>
   Techwood Homes.
</P>
<P>
   1936
</P>
<P>
   Wright builds Fallingwater in Bear Run, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   1937
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Bridge goes up in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   1940
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller Center, a model of the integration of high-rises and
public space, opens in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Varsity in Atlanta is billed as the world's
</P>
<P>
   largest drive-in.
</P>
<P>
   1942
</P>
<P>
   In the Church of St. Francis in Brazil, Oscar Niemeyer merges
national idiom, baroque expression and local tiles of colonial
churches with modernist precepts and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   1943
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Valley Authority's Fort Loudoun Dam is built near
</P>
<P>
   Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   1949
</P>
<P>
   Philip Johnson builds his iconic Glass House on his Connecticut
estate, the beginning of various
</P>
<P>
   buildings there that express the periods in his career.
</P>
<P>
   1958
</P>
<P>
   Mies van der Rohe's Seagram Building in New York, designed with
Johnson, exemplifies the refinement of modernism.
</P>
<P>
   1959
</P>
<P>
   Wright's Guggenheim Museum opens in New York.
</P>
<P>
   1961
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta architect John Portman, acting as his own developer,
builds the Merchandise Mart, the first step to anchoring downtown
Atlanta's convention business.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Jacobs publishes her seminal book, ``The Death and Life of
Great American Cities,'' a thoughtful dissection and dismissal of
modern urban planning.
</P>
<P>
   1962
</P>
<P>
   Architect Eero Saarinen's designs for Dulles International
Airport in Virginia and the TWA Terminal at New York's John F.
Kennedy International Airport are completed.
</P>
<P>
   1965
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium opens.
</P>
<P>
   Portman builds the first tower of Peachtree Center in downtown
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1966
</P>
<P>
   Robert Venturi, Denise Scott-Brown and Stephen Izenhour publish
``Complexity and Contradiction in Architecture,'' which helps
inspire the shift to postmodernism.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. National Historic Preservation Act is enacted, which
encourages the preservation of our architectural history.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Foundation, a high-water mark in corporate
architecture, is built in New York.
</P>
<P>
   1967
</P>
<P>
   Portman's Hyatt Regency Hotel is the first major hotel built in
downtown Atlanta since 1920. Its soaring lobby launches atrium
mania in hotels around the
</P>
<P>
   country.
</P>
<P>
   1972
</P>
<P>
   The Omni, designed by Thompson, Ventulett, Stainback &AMP;
Associates, anchors the west side of downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Kahn's Kimball Art
</P>
<P>
   Museum, one of the most widely admired museums in the country,
opens in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Pruitt-Igoe, a modern-style
</P>
<P>
   housing project-turned-slum, is destroyed in St. Louis, an
admission that government planning has gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   1973
</P>
<P>
   The silhouette of the Sydney Opera House in Australia becomes a
worldwide landmark.
</P>
<P>
   1974
</P>
<P>
   Southern Bell purchases the Fox Theatre, intending to tear it
down. The prospect ignites a successful grass-roots effort to save
it, which in turn inaugurates the preservation movement in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1977
</P>
<P>
   The insouciant and high-tech Pompidou Center by architects
Richard Rogers and Renzo Piano makes a splash in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   1978
</P>
<P>
   California architect Frank Gehry's additions to his modest Santa
Monica, Calif., home announce a new architectural presence,
vocabulary and use of everyday materials such as plywood and metal
fencing.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T headquarters in New York, the so-called Chippendale
building, is designed by Johnson. It
</P>
<P>
   adds more momentum to
</P>
<P>
   postmodernist historicism.
</P>
<P>
   1980
</P>
<P>
   The beaux-arts Carnegie Library in downtown Atlanta is replaced
by
</P>
<P>
   brutalist Marcel Breuer's design for the Atlanta-Fulton County
Library.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas architect Fay Jones designs the Thorncrown Chapel, an
architectural gem in Eureka Springs.
</P>
<P>
   1981
</P>
<P>
   Bond and Ryder Architects design a moving site for the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr.'s tomb on Auburn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   1982
</P>
<P>
   Architect Michael Graves goes postmodern with such designs as
the Humana Building in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   MARTA's Peachtree Center station, the most striking of Atlanta's
mass-transit stations, is described as ``Piranesei meets
high-tech.''
</P>
<P>
   1983
</P>
<P>
   Richard Meier's modernist design puts Atlanta's High Museum of
Art on the map.
</P>
<P>
   1984
</P>
<P>
   Graves designs the Michael C. Carlos Museum at Emory University
and its addition in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   1986
</P>
<P>
   Seaside, a resort, opens in the Florida Panhandle. It becomes
the rallying point for new urbanism, a return to traditional
neighborhood development.
</P>
<P>
   1987
</P>
<P>
   One Atlantic Center ushers in the postmodern trend in commercial
architecture in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1988
</P>
<P>
   I.M. Pei's pyramid for the
</P>
<P>
   Louvre, one of the French government's so-called ``Grand
Projects,'' injects modern architecture into the fabric of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta firm Scogin Elam &AMP; Bray struts its imagination with the
Clayton County Headquarters Library.
</P>
<P>
   1989
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta City Council passes the Atlanta Preservation
</P>
<P>
   Ordinance, which helps to
</P>
<P>
   save older buildings from destruction.
</P>
<P>
   1994
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Housing Authority decides to raze the Techwood and
Clark Howell Homes housing projects and build a mixed-income
community called
</P>
<P>
   Centennial Place.
</P>
<P>
   1996
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta spruces up for the
</P>
<P>
   Olympics with sports venues, streetscapes, public art,
Centennial Olympic Park and a stadium that will become home for the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   1997
</P>
<P>
   Two landmarks go up: Meier's Getty Center in Los Angeles and
Frank Gehry's Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain. The Guggenheim is
considered one of the century's finest buildings.
</P>
<P>
   1999
</P>
<P>
   Piano is hired to design a master plan for the Woodruff Arts
</P>
<P>
   Center in Midtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Intown development and housing are hot again in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Catherine Fox for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
