<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-GENERATIONS-HN     10-22 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GENERATIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND GENERATION PROTESTS DEAL TO TEAR DOWN ILLEGAL OUTPOSTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIVAT HAREL, West Bank _ Shira Drori was 2 years old in 1975
when Israeli soldiers forcibly removed her family from a mobile
home perched on a West Bank hilltop.
</P>
<P>
   She was still a child the first time she trekked up a rocky hill
with her mother, Daniella Weiss, a founder of Israel's religious
settler movement, to help others stake claims to remote West Bank
land.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Drori watched as settler leaders from her mother's
generation sent trucks to tear down two of 12 West Bank outposts
that the government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak has deemed
illegal. Drori, now 26, stood and protested with the sons and
daughters of other icons of Israel's religious settlement movement.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, their pragmatic parents made an unprecedented
deal with Barak's government to peacefully evacuate the 12
outposts.
</P>
<P>
   But Drori and the other young protesters remain defiant and
pledge that settlers will not come down from the hilltops quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we don't succeed in preventing everything Barak is
doing, at least we didn't sit in our homes and say, `This is it',''
Drori said. ``We have to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling themselves the Second Generation, these young settlers
have picked up where their parents _ settlers who carved enclaves
in the heart of Hebron and the hills of Samaria in the 1970s and
'80s _ left off, staking claim to vacant West Bank land and defying
government orders to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Drori, have moved into the new settlements that have
cropped up in the West Bank over the last three years in a
last-ditch attempt to prevent the land from being handed to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put pressure on the Israeli government,'' said
Malachi Levinger, 26, whose father, Rabbi Moshe Levinger, helped
found a militant Jewish settlement in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Second Operation started operating in earnest two months ago,
when Barak's government began serious discussions about dismantling
some of the outposts. But the idea for the group has germinated
since the day six years ago when Daniella Weiss met some young
settlers who were cultivating land near one of the hilltop
settlements dismantled this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that they were very pure and idealistic and
dedicated,'' Weiss said. ``So I started to understand that I should
cultivate the young ones to believe in their ability to settle''
the land.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of an organization called Amana that was founded
by their parents, the young people followed their elders' example.
They cut dirt roads into the rocky hills, brought in water towers
and trailers, and hooked their new homes to telephone and
electricity lines.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed since their parents' day. Early settlers
blazed an unknown trail in new territory captured from Jordan in
the 1967 war. Much of the Israeli public respected the drive to
settle the land.
</P>
<P>
   Today's young settlers are grabbing hilltops in a different
political climate, analysts say. Peace agreements govern relations
between Israelis and Palestinians. Most Israelis are resigned to
the emergence of a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   And many see the settlers as an obstacle to peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents' generation operated in what was, in many ways, a
political and ideological vacuum,'' said Joseph Alpher, a political
analyst who directs the Middle East office of the American Jewish
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no peace process,'' said Alpher, former acting head
of the Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies at Tel Aviv University.
``Now, 80 percent of Israelis think there will be a Palestinian
state.''
</P>
<P>
   That reality has forced the veteran settlers to alter their
strategy. Though they once stood in opposition to any government
willing to cede territory to the Palestinians, the pro-settlement
National Religious Party today is part of Barak's centrist
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the old leaders say they realize that the dream of
settling all of biblical Judea and Samaria _ today's West Bank _
ended with the signing of peace agreements with the Palestinians.
Their objective now is to save as many settlements as they can.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the agreement with Barak. The settlers' council agreed to
dismantle the 12 outposts deemed illegal peacefully and without
interference from the Israeli army. So far, they have taken down
six uninhabited ones without incident. Dismantling the other six,
inhabited by a few militants, may prove more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Settler leaders say the compromise amounted to an official seal
of approval for 30 other West Bank settlements that otherwise might
not have been allowed to stay. The agreement, they believe, was a
smart move.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's government as well as settlers critical of the
compromise portray the deal as a crucial precedent. Now that Barak
has proved he can remove outposts _ with settler compliance, no
less _ it will be easier to tear down additional settlements in a
final peace agreement with the Palestinians, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Barak can say, `So what, you've already dismantled a few
settlements. What's a few more?''' Drori said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Second Generation seems to consist mainly of young
idealists who feel that the older generation of settlers has grown
tired. One analyst called the group ``a few kids at a lonely
outpost''
</P>
<P>
   Second Generation members say that they are ready to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just say, `Oh, there's a peace process, so we should
forget our ideology,'' Drori said. ``We know we have to do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
