<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5367 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ARCHITECTURE-FUTURE24     10-22 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-FUTURE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Future may require change in way designers, builders work
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 22.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No crystal ball can show us what our architectural
environment will look like in the next century, but chances are it
will be designed differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a whole new generation of technology that
will change how we think of architecture and empower the
profession,'' says Atlanta architect Mack Scogin. ``It will
re-establish architecture's role in the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Scogin says he thinks that new technologies, from the laser
cutter and computer programs to high-speed 3-D and digital cameras,
will forge a closer link between architects and construction
technology. He believes it will revive the classical tradition of
the designer and maker working side by side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will completely change the nature of the profession
during the next 20 years,'' he says. ``It's going to leave a lot of
people in the dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Scogin is among those who sees a redensification of the city in
the future. This is, indeed, already happening. But the decisions
we make now will determine how successful that process is. In
California architect Eli Naor's view, the future health of our
cities will depend on the transportation systems designed in the
next few decades. Given finite energy sources, pollution, gridlock
and the other sprawl-induced ills, the willingness to embrace more
compact development also will be decisive.
</P>
<P>
   That will entail hard personal decisions. For instance, the
trend toward ever-larger, energy- and land-eating houses will have
to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the recycling we do is meaningless unless we make the
right macro decisions, such as how big our house is, where we live
and what kind of car we drive,'' says Michael Stanton, president of
the American Institute of Architects.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the broader development, he warns that no city or
suburb can afford to be an island anymore if the larger issues of
livability are to be addressed. ``The biggest challenge will be to
deal with regional governance _ of water, transportation,
schools,'' says the San Francisco architect. ``We have so many
redundancies. The lack of (regional governance) is our biggest
hindrance to progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of wise development, both inside and
outside city boundaries. A recent Atlanta Journal-Constitution poll
suggests that residents of Gwinnett County, for instance, have come
to believe that the developers wield too much power over land-use
decisions. Atlanta has some rethinking to do as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps Atlanta will get to the stage where it realizes its
desirability as a place to live,'' Stanton says. ``The most
desirable places _ San Francisco, New York, London _ are the
hardest places to build. Atlanta needs to get to the point that it
doesn't feel it necessary to accept every development that comes
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5371 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ARCHITECTURE-CENTURY2     10-22 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-CENTURY2NDTAKE24- </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: started moving back.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, governmental concern about air quality is such
that federal funds that would once have been spent on highways now
are earmarked for projects that support pedestrians and public
transit. The Environmental Protection Agency has blessed the
Atlantic Steel project in Atlanta, which is supposed to transform a
138-acre brownfield into a vanguard model of a new kind of urban
renewal, with emphasis on transportation alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, even Atlanta, a favorite example of suburban sprawl, is a
microcosm of urban repopulation. Older homes are selling at
astronomical prices. Infill development and adaptive reuse of
warehouses and office buildings as residences abound, from the
pre-Olympics loft conversions in the Fairlie-Poplar historic
district downtown to construction on Peachtree Street in Midtown.
In Buckhead, developers are building pretend lofts. Centennial
Place, a mixed-income project, is replacing the Techwood and Clark
Howell Homes housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   This shift brings its own set of problems. Held up as the savior
that will deliver us from sprawl, new urbanism has become such a
powerful buzzword in Atlanta of late that uttering the term in
connection with a project is like holding a cross up to a vampire.
It's not enough to build one apartment close to the street.
Construction must be planned in concert with alternatives to the
car. Indeed, if public transportation doesn't meet the needs of our
growing population, the city will be as gridlocked as the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   This brings up one of the keys to achieving any meaningful
change in the suburbs or the city: the recognition that there is no
single answer, but rather the need for interrelated and
well-coordinated planning that encompasses zoning, infrastructure
(such as water and sewers), construction and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Blueprint Midtown is an exemplar of such a plan. It addresses
land use, finance, retail, housing, traffic and transportation,
even marketing to get the word out. A zoning ordinance will soon be
introduced in Atlanta City Council that will give the plan
legislative teeth. Susan Mendheim, Midtown Alliance president,
asserts that there is much potential for change intown, where there
is still a lot of open land used for surface parking or the sites
of unused buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opportunity is everywhere,'' she says, ``and you don't even
need to change the infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey planner Anton Nelessen, consultant to Blueprint
Midtown, sees cities all over the country embarking on planning
crusades to solve their problems. He is working in Milwaukee, which
is trying to solve its traffic/pedestrian problem through a program
called ``park once.'' It will encourage people to leave their cars
in decks near the expressway by offering a phalanx of
transportation alternatives, including trolleys and water taxis on
the Milwaukee River.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge in urban redevelopment is bringing the
middle class back,'' says Georgia Tech professor Roark.
``Gentrification is not the way to go. You need a mix of income
brackets and ages as well as housing types, shopping amenities and
transportation choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Improving public schools, which is out of planners' hands, will
be critical: Schools draw families.
</P>
<P>
   Roark, who works with the Georgia Conservancy on smart growth
initiatives, sees such thinking popping up all over the state.
Covington is in the midst of planning, so that it can accommodate
growth without losing the small-town qualities its residents
cherish. The Georgia Conservancy is tackling the area along Ga.
316, where fields lie ripe for development. Commuter rail will be
critical there.
</P>
<P>
   ``County planning will be the key in making or breaking smart
growth,'' says Roark. ``The counties need to exercise their
land-use control to support intelligent development.''
</P>
<P>
   Change is possible, but it means thinking differently. One of
our new century's resolutions should be to think smaller _ smaller
lots, more compact neighborhoods _ so that people can be closer to
public transportation. It should also be thinking bigger _ giving
up one-niche neighborhoods and understanding the symbiotic
connection between the city and suburbs, giving up fiefdoms for
regional planning.
</P>
<P>
   Americans will have to temper their love affair with the
automobile. We will need to give up some autonomy by accepting
regional planning solutions, but public officials have to repay
that trust by acting wisely. For instance, they will have to see to
it that public transportation is more economical and convenient
than private vehicles; few people will abandon their cars purely
out of concern for the ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in the new century we'll see a better balance between
home and community, which has been off-kilter for at least half of
this one. That shouldn't mean rewiring human nature. The need for
communal connection is just as basic as home. After all, when
modern suburbs and cities excised traditional spaces for
interaction _ the commons, Main Street _ we gathered at malls. As
Roark says, ``The village is still the basic unit (of culture). The
suburb is nothing more than a village. Urban or suburban, people
are looking for a sense of community and a place where the car
doesn't dictate the quality of life or the shape of the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelessen has uncovered that sentiment as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I conduct my lifestyle preferences surveys,'' he
says, ``people invariably want the same thing _ pleasant places
with a human scale and natural beauty in which they can interact
with other people.''
</P>
<P>
   OUR CENTURY SERIES SO FAR
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS: ``America Finds Its Voice,'' May 23.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO: ``When Magic Came Out of Thin Air,'' July 4.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION: ``A Medium's Massive Power,'' July 25.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER: ``Art, Commerce
</P>
<P>
   Compete for Center Stage,'' Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE: ``A Leap From Old World
</P>
<P>
   to New,'' Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   VISUAL ART: ``The Spirit of Modern Art,'' Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC: ``One Nation Under the Blues,'' Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   If you are interested in obtaining copies of our Century in the
Arts series, contact the staff of the Stacks Information Service at
404-526-5668.
</P>
