<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-COALMINING-NOVELIST1S     10-22 1809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COALMINING-NOVELIST1STTAKE24-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    West Virginia novelist runs for governor to challenge coal's
hold on her home state
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 24.
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. _ Coal is everywhere here. Barges brimming
with the black stuff slice the green waters of the Kanawha River in
the heart of Charleston. Trains filled to overflowing stretch to
the far horizon near every active coal mine in the southwestern
wedge of the state. Because the substance is such an integral part
of West Virginia's history, its identity and its economy, coal has
long been a battlefield _ first between mine owners and union
organizers, but nowadays between warriors for the environment and
defenders of the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an issue split neatly along racial, socioeconomic,
age, gender or even family lines. ``I Love Coal'' bumper stickers
show up on everything from beat-up pickups to brand-new Volvos, as
do the ones that read ``I Love Mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you love coal and mountains?
</P>
<P>
   Not around here. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, miners had to dig coal out of these mountains
with picks and shovels. Today, gigantic, multimillion-dollar
earth-moving machines chew it out. Very simply put, miners no
longer extract coal from the mountain. Now machines remove the
mountain from the coal.
</P>
<P>
   Locals call this technique ``mountaintop removal.'' Mining
officials call it something a little more palatable: ``mountaintop
mining.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Giardina, a novelist, professor and now a candidate for
governor from the newly formed Mountain Party, calls it war.
</P>
<P>
   For years, she has been a relentless environmental activist,
speaking at rallies and writing passionate broadsides against water
pollution, deforestation and anything else that threatens the
pristine beauty of her beloved Appalachia. With Big Coal, though,
the stakes are higher than ever. Tired of waiting for Democrats and
Republicans to do the right thing, this soft-spoken woman who
relishes her solitude is walking into the most brutally public of
arenas: politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider this a defense of my home,'' she says quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Her well-traveled Mazda Protege sports three bumper stickers:
``Almost Level, West Virginia,'' ``I Love Mountains'' and ``I'm Pro
Mountain and I Vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Giardina has spent all but eight years of her life in this
beautiful, sometimes violent, coal-hardened region. She grew up in
a coal camp in McDowell County, in the southernmost tip of the
state. Her grandfather and two uncles were miners; her father was a
company bookkeeper, and her mother was a nurse. In 1963, her father
was laid off and the family moved to Kanawha County.
</P>
<P>
   She set two of her novels, ``Storming Heaven'' (which TNT has
just announced that it plans to make into a TV movie) and ``The
Unquiet Earth,'' in coal camps, drawing much from family lore and
from the true, tragic experiences of early union organizers in West
Virginia and Kentucky. She still recalls the ``traumatic loss of
community'' that followed the shutdown of her father's mine, a
memory that's jarred every time she points out the remnants of coal
camps along the roadside _ ghost towns where thriving communities
used to be.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the damage has been done, it's difficult for anyone
to imagine a future without coal, much less plan for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no easy answers,'' Giardina concedes. ``It's not as
easy as saying we need to replace coal with this other industry.
After coal, we almost need a statewide Marshall Plan. ... We've got
an emergency here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 12, Giardina made her first official stump speech as a
candidate, to a handful of people at the annual Putnam County
homecoming. By the time the big parade started at 1 p.m., thousands
had pitched their picnic camps across the courthouse grounds in
Winfield. But at 11:30 a.m., when political candidates were invited
to the small Lions Club stage to speak briefly, only a few dozen
were on hand.
</P>
<P>
   With the strains of a gospel quartet's ``Let Us Have a Little
Talk With Jesus'' still hanging in the air, Giardina took the
microphone first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small-business people are the heroes of this state,'' she told
the gathering. ``They come in, create jobs and they stay. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be one of the few candidates to tell you coal is
on the way out. We can either wait for that day to come and moan
about it, or we can plan for it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only candidate who's going to talk to you about
post-coal.''
</P>
<P>
   Four elderly women lining one side of a picnic table in a prime
shady spot listened politely as she began and broke into
simultaneous applause when the topic turned to life after coal.
Four elderly men standing nearby kept their hands in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The parade that capped the day's festivities in Winfield drew
people from the surrounding communities of Nitro, Eleanor, Duff,
Buffalo and Pocatalico (home of the Poca High School Dots,
naturally). Even the red-smocked clerks at the IGA grocery store
across from the courthouse left their checkout lines long enough to
cheer for the candidate _ or beauty queen or marching band _ of
choice.
</P>
<P>
   This was politics at its purest, its most immediate, its most
comprehensible. And its most uncomfortable for someone not given by
temperament to pressing the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard walking up to people and saying, `Hi, I'm Denise
Giardina, and I'm running for governor.' Over and over again. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is important,'' she adds. ``Until now I've only
talked to people at environmental rallies, which really is
preaching to the choir. From now on we have to concentrate on more
events like this, getting to people who don't know much about us.''
</P>
<P>
   `I hope it breaks your heart'
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gibson, a 53-year-old retired maintenance worker turned
environmental activist, recently moved a mobile home onto his
family's 50-acre homeplace on Kayford Mountain, just south of
Charleston. Some 300 of his kinfolk are buried there, on a site
overlooking what used to be another mountain peak. Now it more
closely resembles a dust bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The ground drops several hundred feet into a scene from an
apocalyptic movie, with magnificent equipment parked near huge
stacks of coal and rubble. A choking coat of white dust turns
everything green to gray on the surrounding roads and hillsides.
And in the near distance, flat-topped buttes crusted over with
rough grass _ a very different shade of green _ and a few stunted
trees replace what used to be peaks.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing Giardina, a reporter and a photographer to view
the mine site from his unusual vantage point, Gibson shakes his
head and looks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope what you saw here just breaks your heart,'' he says
slowly and evenly. ``I hope it breaks your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot more hearts would be broken, Giardina says, if more West
Virginians had the chance to see firsthand before-and-after scenes
of these mines. But Gibson is one of a very small number of
landowners who won't accept lucrative offers from coal companies to
mine property that has been in families for generations. And access
to any of the mines being worked is strictly controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down from Kayford Mountain, Giardina says, ``Most West
Virginians have never seen this. They have no idea. ...''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, an environmental group called the West
Virginia Highlands Conservancy and 10 coal field residents filed
suit in federal court, claiming not only that mountaintop removal
destroys the environment but that existing laws meant to mitigate
the damage are not being enforced. Three of the 10 residents have
since dropped out of the lawsuit, but each side continues to
present its case.
</P>
<P>
   Coal officials don't deny that mining operations change the
landscape. But they're doing as little permanent damage as
possible, they say, while still extracting a resource that people
demand.
</P>
<P>
   The subjective nature of beauty makes it difficult to imagine
this debate ever ending. And the sheer power of Big Coal _ it
accounts for 7 percent of West Virginia's state product, provides
more than one-third of its business-tax revenue and is very
generous with campaign contributions _ makes even talking about the
environment troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other numbers that can't be explained away. West
Virginia is 49th among the 50 states in household income. And in
this very poor state, the poorest counties are the southern ones,
where most of the coal mines are.
</P>
<P>
   ``People out here don't have a lot of options,''
</P>
<P>
   Giardina concedes. ``It's impossible not to have sympathy for
them. But if coal has been so good to us, why are we still one of
the poorest states in the country?''
</P>
<P>
   State employment records raise deeper doubts about the
not-so-distant future: Mountaintop removal employs 4,317 workers in
West Virginia, less than 1 percent of its job force. Overall,
mining employment in the state has fallen from 130,000 in the 1940s
and '50s to 16,000 now. Machines do most of the work. And if mining
continues at current rates _ with no acceleration _ coal reserves
in West Virginia will be depleted in less than 30 years, according
to a recent analysis. After that, mining won't be an issue at all
here. It's the interim, though, that has environmentalists working
at fever pitch. Many mountains can be razed in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coal is an outlaw industry,'' Giardina declares. ``I'm all for
business, especially small business. But coal is not a business.
It's a monster. It's the evil empire, as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic alternatives aren't clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to something besides coal is a difficult, slow
process,'' Giardina says. ``It's difficult because of the land
ownership in those areas _ most land is owned by corporations and
leased to coal companies. But I've talked to lawyers, who've said
that the governor could use eminent domain _ just like with
highways _ to condemn some of the property and then recruit small
industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's a difficult area to attract industry to
because the school systems are poor, and a lot of places don't even
have good water available. So it wouldn't be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   High-technology industry should be pursued, she says, and
tourism is one source of revenue that hasn't been explored enough,
especially in some of the areas that haven't already been
moonscaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``And lately I've been studying up on windmills and wind
turbines, which are used a good bit out West,'' she adds. ``It
seems that an operation like that could work on some of these
flattened mountaintops. You could hire people who used to mine coal
to build and maintain them. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5375 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-COALMINING-NOVELIST2N     10-22 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COALMINING-NOVELIST2NDTAKE24-C </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va.: things to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic analysts cite an encouraging influx of jobs over the
past few years, in service industries such as telemarketing,
discount stores, travel-related industries including hotels-motels,
and amusements. But there is no one core industry that can replace
Big Coal. Or pay as well: Whereas coal miners earn around $50,000 a
year, the average store employee might expect to make $13,500.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Underwood, the incumbent governor _ and a former coal
company executive _ has created a task force to look at economic
diversification. And the state's congressional delegation has vowed
to help recruit clean, high-tech industries. But to Giardina, the
diversification efforts under way are too little, and far too late.
</P>
<P>
   Many third-party obstacles
</P>
<P>
   Getting onto the ballot as a third-party candidate in West
Virginia isn't easy. Obtaining signatures from 13,000 registered
voters, in a state where party allegiances run deep and only 20
percent of eligible voters care enough to show up on Election Day,
is hard enough. But the biggest impediment may be a convoluted
state law: Independent candidates are required to tell every
potential signer that putting their name on a petition forbids them
from voting in either the Democratic or Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to tell them they can go to jail if they're caught,''
Giardina says. ``Trouble is, the state dropped the penalty portion
of the law, but kept the law itself intact. We still have to say
they can be punished, though. It's nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this month the Mountain Party sued the secretary of state,
seeking to clarify the law, and got a hearing scheduled for Nov. 4.
On Oct. 15, the state Democratic Executive Committee filed a motion
to intervene in the lawsuit. In the motion, Democratic Party
Chairman Pat Maroney and co-Chairman Steve White argue that anyone
who signs a petition for Giardina and then votes in the primary
would be ``casting a vote twice in the gubernatorial primary.''
</P>
<P>
   While the lawyers hash out the issue, a loosely knit group of 60
volunteers fans out across the state, showing up at political
rallies, the state fair or any other place where there's a crowd,
with clipboards in hand and petition speech well-rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of politics in West Virginia,'' says Missy Anthony,
an early and enthusiastic volunteer for Giardina. ``You can't tell
the difference between the Democrats and the Republicans anymore.
Denise offers something that we need: another option. And a glimmer
of humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers _ and the candidate _ know they face long odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many legal and historical factors that make
third-party candidacies especially difficult in this state,'' says
Paul Owens, political editor of the Charleston Daily Mail, one of
two daily newspapers in the capital city. ``And if people have to
actually write in her name _ if Denise doesn't make it on the
ballot _ that's a real problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent newspaper column, Owens contrasted Giardina's
fledgling candidacy with the most famous third-party victory of
late: Jesse Ventura's ascent to the governor's office in Minnesota
last November. None of the factors that made that possible, Owens
says, exist in West Virginia, a state of entrenched party
loyalties, no public campaign funds and more restrictive
registration rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters who believe in Giardina and her message should, by all
means, support her,'' Owens concluded in that column. ``But they
shouldn't fool themselves that she has any real chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The true value of a third-party candidacy is clear to Owens, who
has observed West Virginia politics for eight years. In this case,
Giardina is bringing up issues the other nominees would prefer to
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``You basically have an incumbent governor who makes almost no
concession to people who are concerned about mountaintop removal,
and a Democratic front-runner who says he supports `responsible'
mountaintop mining,'' Owens says. ``But `responsible' can mean
whatever you want it to mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denise is going to get 90 percent of her support from
Democrats,'' Owens predicts. ``You just don't find many Republicans
who are concerned about mountaintop mining. Oddly enough, the
people who have been most hostile to Denise's candidacy are liberal
Democrats, who believe that she is going to be responsible for
handing the governor's job back to the Republican incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Giardina says that two top-ranking officials of the
state Democratic Party, apparently concerned about the effect she
would have on the election, offered her a state House seat if she
would drop her gubernatorial crusade. And at the Putnam County
homecoming, Democratic front-runner Bob Wise _ who performed his
traditional clog-dancing routine in the parade _ confronted
Giardina with a stern challenge: ``I hope you can live with
yourself if Underwood gets re-elected.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Charleston Gazette recently, Thomas Rodd, a former deputy
state attorney general, wrote a stinging column labeling Giardina's
campaign ``creepy,'' ``phony'' and a ``power trip.'' He questioned
her legitimacy as a candidate, criticized her supporters'
intentions and warned of dire setbacks to environmental causes as a
backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Politics isn't pretty. Even this early in the campaign _ the
party primaries aren't until May _ Giardina vows that she's in it
for the long haul. Even if thereare many issues, such as school
consolidation and health care, that she's still learning about:
``Maybe people are actually ready to hear a politician say, `I
don't have all the answers, but I think we can work together to
find them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Human contradictions
</P>
<P>
   When some disgruntled Democrats first approached Giardina about
running for office, her immediate reaction was, ``Yeah, right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought about it,'' she adds, ``and this may sound
hokey, but I prayed about it. And it just felt like the right thing
to do right now. My life is kind of cleared out in other ways, and
this is something I feel really strongly about. It seems like a
constructive thing to do for the next year and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Moral responsibility is a topic that Giardina returns to time
and again in her fiction. Whether her novels are set in medieval
England or Nazi Germany, she revels in sin and redemption, right
and wrong, the human condition and its spiritual underpinnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human beings are so fascinating,'' she says,
</P>
<P>
   ``capable of such wonderful deeds and such horrible deeds. All
of us, no matter how good we are, struggle with certain questions,
and we're never really sure if we're doing the right thing. Finally
we just fall back and say, `I just have to do what I have to do'
and hope that something redeeming comes out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At its best, politics is almost pastoral for Giardina. ``You
meet people and they tell their stories. You see people afraid of
losing their job. You see people really in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   And though she admits to a certain naivete, she insists that
politics is still capable of doing good. In Putnam County, she
issued a challenge to all other candidates running for office in
West Virginia: to donate 10 percent of all money raised to charity
after the election next fall. Sure, it's politics, she says, but
why not at least let all that money go for something worthwhile?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at least as cynical as the next guy,'' Owens, the
political editor, wrote recently, ``but I think
</P>
<P>
   Giardina's idea is a breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   If all the candidates who ran for governor and the state
Legislature in 1996 had taken Giardina's pledge and given away 10
percent of their campaign contributions, West Virginia charities
would have collected $570,000.
</P>
<P>
   And so, with $7,000 in the bank and 6,000 signatures on the
ballot petition, Giardina settles into campaigning, trading in her
treasured solitude and writing ways for endless hand-shaking and
self-introductions. Occasionally, while tooling around the mountain
highways on the way to or from a political rally, she's taken aback
by what her life has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while it strikes me how odd it is to be doing
this _ running for governor! I should be writing books!''
</P>
<P>
   While not sure she'll even get onto the ballot, much less get
elected, Giardina's motivations for being part of the campaign are
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``These mountains are special,'' she says. ``If you grow up
here, you get attached to the landscape. They're like a security
blanket. You can feel them around you when you go to sleep at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long pause, she adds with a smile, ``And if nothing
else, there might be some great fiction coming from all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa K. Weaver writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
