<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     10-22 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CAPITOL HILL OFFICES, LAWMAKERS DISPLAY THEIR FAITH  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Southern House members are lining up behind a new
campaign to post the Ten Commandments in public buildings, agreeing
to display a copy in their own offices on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Critics dismiss the gesture as a gimmick, but the move reflects
the powerful role that religion continues to play in American
politics. At a time when Democrats and Republican squabble over
budget numbers while most Americans tune out, conservatives believe
they can engage voters by turning to religious and moral issues.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Janet Parshall said the campaign serves as
``a reminder for our nation that the Ten Commandments belong in the
public square.'' Parshall's group, the Family Research Council, is
pressing schools and other public buildings to display a copy of
the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   The roster of lawmakers who have agreed to post the Ten
Commandments includes Republicans Robert Aderholt and Spencer
Bachus of Alabama, Jim DeMint of South Carolina, Cliff Stearns of
Florida and Walter Jones of North Carolina. Mike McIntyre of North
Carolina is one of the few Democrats to join the effort.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre, who already displays a tableau of the Ten Commandments
in his office, said they held a special ``history, heritage and
hope'' for Americans. ``They're the fundamental legal code of
Western civilization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Republicans have repeatedly backed the Ten
Commandments as a symbol. They've passed resolutions supporting a
state judge in Alabama who displays a copy behind his bench, and
they've passed other measures supporting states that allow such
postings in public buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Lynn, executive director of Americans United for the
Separation of Church and State, predicted that the courts would
eventually strike down the latest efforts to grant a government
endorsement to religious displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would personally feel more comfortable if members hung the
Bill of Rights rather than the Ten Commandments in buildings,''
Lynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Starved for Attention
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., would be the first to tell you that
his recent 24-hour fast to draw attention to the plight of
struggling Third World countries was a small sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bachus, who wants the United States to forgive up to $1
billion in debt owed to it by foreign nations, said the break from
food wasn't easy. He rejected the advice of doctors who told him
that weaning from meals would be a good idea before going without
all food for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about his fast a few hours before it started, Bachus
quipped: ``Just thinking about it yesterday, I ate three packs of
M&AMP;Ms.''
</P>
<P>
   Money Men
</P>
<P>
   A new report from a campaign watchdog group shows that
politicians aren't just good at collecting money, they've developed
a knack for giving it away too.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who held safe seats in the last election cycle still
collected millions of dollars for their campaigns. But many of them
wound up giving some of their cash away to their political parties
or fellow candidates. Such a move engenders good will among allies
and makes it easier to ask for favors later.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics, in its ``Sharing the
Wealth'' report, found that candidates who were coasting to
re-election gave $22.4 million to political parties and other
candidates. The parties, which can collect unlimited donations,
claimed the lion's share of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The top contributors to political parties include Sen. Richard
Shelby, R-Ala., who doled out $500,000 to the GOP, and former
Louisiana Rep. Robert Livingston, another Republican, who handed
out $602,000 to his party.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, who briefly laid claim to the House speaker's post
before leaving office last winter because of a scandal related to
an extramarital affair, also was generous in handing out money to
other candidates, contributing $66,361.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Whacked
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole won kudos from friends and admirers on Capitol
Hill after dropping out of the presidential race. But Texas Gov.
George W. Bush quickly picked up her endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry that she had to end her quest prematurely, but I am
equally delighted to lend my support to Gov. Bush,'' said Rep.
Howard Coble, R-N.C., who called Dole an ``important voice'' in the
GOP. An aide to Coble said Bush supporters were on the phone to
Coble's office within an hour of Dole's announcement, seeking the
lawmaker's support.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., congratulated her close friend Dole
for her ``grace and dignity,'' but quickly hopped on board the Bush
bandwagon. ``With Elizabeth's departure from the race, it's
critical that we all unite behind Gov. Bush,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
