<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Oct. 23 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration and top
Republican lawmakers announced early on Friday that they had
reached an agreement to overhaul the nation's financial system,
repealing Depression-era laws that have restricted the banking,
securities and insurance industries from expanding into one
another's businesses. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars, photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-KLAN-MARCH (New York) _ An appeals panel reverses a lower
court ruling and says that the city does not have to allow Klu Klux
Klan members to wear their masks at a planned rally on Saturday.
Klan members may wear their hoods and robes, but Klan lawyers
continue to work the legal system to reverse the latest ruling on
the masks, in time for the planned rally, which may or may not take
place after all. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Republican leaders in Congress
announced a plan on Friday to reduce government spending across the
board by 1.4 percent. The cuts, a total of $4.5 billion in the
current fiscal year, would apply to every government program for
which Congress controls the annual financing. The Republicans said
the plan would allow them to approve a budget without tax increases
and without dipping into Social Security reserves. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Washington) _ A look at scheduling as a campaign
strategy in the rivalry and maneuvering between the Gore and
Bradley camps. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-KHALKHALI (Qom, Iran) _ Much about Ayatollah Sadegh
Khalkhali these days _ his simple white smock, his bare feet, his
shuffling gait, his concern for his visitors' well-being _ speaks
for an almost penitential gentleness. Long gone are his days as the
chief judge of Iran's revolutionary courts in the early 1980s, when
his name was enough to strike terror, his word sufficient to set
execution squads to work with their gallows, their shootings and
their stonings. Twenty years ago, Khalkhali was the Islamic
revolution's Robespierre, the grim avenger who condemned hundreds
and possibly thousands of men and women to death, some of them
after trials that lasted only five minutes, or after no trials at
all. He made his grim mark on the American consciousness in April
1980, when, in cleric's robes and turban, he was reported to have
poked at the charred bodies of American commandos killed in the
failed attempt to rescue hostages from the U.S. embassy. By John F.
Burns. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-WORLDSERIES-FANS (Atlanta) _ Even within Atlanta's gauzy
fantasy of itself as the chivalrous competitor, far too polite to
pour beer on an enemy fan, there is room for a dream of serial
slaughter. Faced with the possibility of vanquishing not just one
but two New York baseball teams in a single October, including one
with the name that represents everything Atlanta seems to recall
hating, the city is becoming positively bloodthirsty as the World
Series nears its opening here on Saturday night. In an entirely
genteel and courtly way, of course. By David Firestone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
