<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-JETER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PERFECT DAY IN THE PERFECT LIFE OF DEREK JETER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Derek Jeter eases out of the dugout at Yankee
Stadium or glides along the streets of Manhattan or hustles through
a hotel lobby in any city, it is fascinating to watch the people
who find themselves near him. They point, they whisper, they nod.
Some squeal.
</P>
<P>
   There was an overly aggressive woman who followed Jeter out of a
bar in Boston during the All-Star Game break and hounded him until
he had escaped in a cab. There was a hopeful teen-ager who jumped
up and down at Kennedy Airport when she learned that Jeter was on
her flight. There was a man at a restaurant in New York who ambled
to a pay phone before babbling about being 10 feet from Jeter. Yes,
that Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   It is just as revealing to watch how Jeter reacts to these
stares, glares and advances. With his shifting green eyes and his
honed intuition as his only bodyguards against the world that
demands access, Jeter enforces his own protection.
</P>
<P>
   I am nice, but I am not a mannequin, his body language
announces. I will give you some time, but do not push and make me
uncomfortable, he communicates without moving his lips. Watch him
bob, weave and stay in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether you're in the spotlight, you have to be
wary of how you're perceived,'' Jeter said earlier this week. ``I
think you want to be perceived as someone that you are. You don't
want to get in trouble. You shouldn't want to get in trouble. If
you are in the spotlight, you have to be more careful with what you
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is the dynamic player who symbolizes these successful
Yankees, the youngest player, the most popular player and maybe
even the most indispensable player. Jeter is synonymous with the
Yankees and winning because he has reached the post-season for five
straight seasons, including the last four as the slick starting
shortstop. He keeps getting better and never acts as if playing is
any less enjoyable than a free vacation to Maui.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' Joe Torre said, ``he's the coolest cat in town.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not a coincidence that the Yankees have rocketed to the
top of the baseball world at exactly the same time that Jeter
strolled into the Bronx. The Yankees will continue pursuing their
third World Series championship in four years when they face the
Braves in Game 1 on Saturday night, an experience that has become
commonplace for Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've been in the right place at the right time,'' said
Jeter, who this season set career highs in average (.349), home
runs (24), runs batted in (102) and runs (134). ``We've been
winning since I've been here. I think it would be tough where
you're losing. It's something I've never experienced and don't want
to experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter claimed that he does not consider himself different from
other 25-year-olds, other than having a better job. Sure. Jeter is
the most recognizable player on the best team in baseball, the lead
actor in a traveling soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes being that guy,'' Paul O'Neill said. ``A lot of
people don't need that and don't like it. He does. He's not playing
to become a star, but he likes being here, winning, playing well
and being that person.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone rings in Jeter's apartment or in a hotel room on the
road every day with the same message from Charles or Dorothy, his
parents; the same advice that they have given Derek since he was a
boy in Kalamazoo, Mich., and signed contracts with his parents that
would describe academic and athletic goals for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jeter has asserted himself as one of the premier players
in the major leagues, has been on the cover of GQ and endorses
everything from shoes to a cereal called Jeter's, the calls do not
stop. If anything, they intensify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell him we hope he's making good decisions,'' Dr. Charles
Jeter said. ``He's been fortunate, so don't mess up. We tell him to
be wary of who he's with. We do this often. We trust him, but we
ask about everything. It's routine.''
</P>
<P>
   With a confident gait, Jeter struts through the Yankee
clubhouse, teasing teammates and neatly adapting to different
situations. There are things he will not do or say, ways that he
will not act and that will not change. It is futile to try to get
Jeter to budge.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to the Chad Curtis incident in August, when Curtis
chastised Jeter in front of his teammates for acting nonchalantly
alongside Seattle's Alex Rodriguez during a bench-clearing
squabble. Jeter, who was privately irked by the attention his
action received, said: ``I guess the best way to put it is, you
asked me if I'm worried about something Chad Curtis said. No, I'm
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron, the career home run king, sought out Jeter and
introduced himself before the All-Star Game, causing Jeter to gush,
``Can you believe that?'' Jeter was selected by Michael Jordan to
help launch a line of athletic apparel, an invitation he called
``overwhelming.'' Jeter once stared up at a music video on a
clubhouse television in Tampa, Fla., and expressed a desire to date
the singer Mariah Carey, which he eventually did. Now he does not
discuss Carey or other women he dates, figuring gossip writers can
do their own reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is this side of Jeter: He speaks about his family more
than any father with triplets, he is very close with Don Zimmer, a
68-year-old coach, and he had enough foresight to begin his own
Turn 2 Foundation for children with substance abuse problems. He
was only 22 when he recruited his father over a pizza in a hotel
room to leave his job as a psychologist and run the foundation,
which has raised $600,000 in less than three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think too many people realize how much he really wants
to do the right thing,'' Dr. Jeter said. ``He takes being a role
model seriously. Sometimes, I wonder if people realize how
important it is to him. He wants to do everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, Jeter does. He is still a bachelor making $5
million in salary alone, meaning there are always temptations.
Jeter says he is cautious, but still has fun, so those late nights
he reportedly spends at the China Club, Moomba and Jimmy's Bronx
Cafi cannot all be blamed on creative writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going out with Jeter,'' David Cone has said, ``is like going
with Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's life is such that he sits by his locker answering
questions about whether his life is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not perfect yet,'' Jeter said. ``It's getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday, he will likely become the first $100 million Yankee and
maybe the team's first captain since Don Mattingly. He is gradually
constructing a potential Hall of Fame career, and it is reasonable
to discuss 3,000 hits for a player who has 807 at 25. Jeter dodges
talk about legacies _ bobbing, weaving and staying in control while
focusing on today. It should be another perfect day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing something that I've always wanted to do for as long
as I could remember,'' Jeter said. ``That's play shortstop for the
Yankees, go to the World Series and win championships. It's like
everything is this big dream story. If I was writing a story when I
was younger, this is exactly how I would have written it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
