<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SMOG-PROBE-HNS &LR;      10-22 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOG-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS OFFICIALS TARGET 25 PLANTS IN SMOG PROBE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Texas officials say they have narrowed their search
for the cause of an unusual ``smog episode'' earlier this month to
25 plants that handle two specific chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, they have said they suspected a chemical leak at an
unknown industrial facility was to blame for the outbreak of high
smog readings Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But state records show there were no company reports of
accidental releases involving the two targeted chemicals on that
day or the day before.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests the high smog readings Oct. 7 _ including the
Houston area's highest in a decade _ may have resulted from a
chemical leak that wasn't reported to government officials, as
state regulations require.
</P>
<P>
   The series of high pollution readings showed up in a striking
northward progression, one after another, at seven area monitoring
stations.
</P>
<P>
   The highest reading _ 251 parts per billion of ground-level
ozone, at nearby Deer Park _ was double the national health
standard's permissible maximum. The other six stations also had
ozone readings above the standard.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone, smog's main ingredient, is a respiratory irritant linked
to lung damage. High ozone levels also indicate the presence of
other chemicals that produce ozone when they react in sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   These ozone-forming chemicals include ethylene and propylene,
the two that officials are now scrutinizing in connection with the
Oct. 7 episode.
</P>
<P>
   That day's high ozone levels occurred at sites where monitors
also detected the presence of ethylene and propylene.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone measurements increased as the levels of those two
chemicals declined at the same monitoring station _ a telltale sign
that they were reacting to form ozone, said Patrick Crimmins, a
spokesman for the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Regulations permit routine, controlled releases of the two
chemicals _ along with many other ozone-forming chemicals and other
air pollutants _ at numerous industrial facilities in Harris and
Galveston counties.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest company-reported data available, 33
Harris County plants regularly release ethylene and 38 regularly
release propylene. In Galveston County, six release ethylene and
seven release propylene.
</P>
<P>
   Crimmins said the TNRCC's investigation is focusing on 25 plants
because of an analysis of wind directions recorded Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Ethylene and propylene could have been blown from those 25
locations toward the pollution-monitoring sites where the high
ozone levels occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The high smog readings Oct. 7 pushed Houston ahead of Los
Angeles as the metropolitan area with the most days when at least
one ozone measurement exceeded the health standard. As of Friday,
the Houston area had 46 such days and the Los Angeles area had 43. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
