<SLUG> BC-DELTA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small Delta group votes for union
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By a razor-thin margin, a small group of Delta Air
Lines workers has voted to join the Transport Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   The vote among pilot ground-training instructors marks the first
union win in decades at Delta, the least-unionized major airline.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as Atlanta-based Delta faces organizing drives among
much larger groups, including ramp workers and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The National Mediation Board on Friday said 55 of 107 eligible
instructors submitted ballots supporting a union, with 54 voting
for the TWU and one voting for another group. A majority of
eligible workers must vote for unionization, so supporters won with
a single vote to spare. The results still must be certified by the
NMB, which would consider any company appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman John Kennedy said he was unaware of any plans to
challenge the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that (the instructors) have chosen an
outside entity to become involved in the relationship between them
and their company,'' he said. He added Delta would work
``professionally and constructively with their representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The TWU, which in coming months will enter initial contract
talks for the instructors, hailed the vote as ``just the
beginning,'' predicting ``others will soon follow.'' The union said
it will seek a vote ``in the very near future'' among Delta's
10,000 ramp workers. It sought a vote among rampers in 1997, but
the NMB ruled that it lacked the required employee support at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Flight Attendants also is trying to organize
Delta's 20,000 attendants and hopes for an election next year. A
union must get signed cards from 35 percent of eligible workers
before the NMB will call an election.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Delta's 9,200 pilots and 175 flight dispatchers were
its only unionized groups. The airline, which contends workers are
paid and treated as well or better than those at other carriers,
has long been resistant to other organizing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But activity heated up after employee cutbacks during a
financial slump in the early 1990s, followed by a management
overhaul. Employee organizers in the current campaigns say they
primarily want the security and negotiating rights afforded by a
union contract.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is vigorously fighting the drives, and Chief Executive Leo
Mullin has issued personal memos urging workers not to support
further unionization.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
