<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINARY TRUSTEE WHO TANGLED WITH DRUGS WORKS TO KEEP OTHERS
DRUG-FREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ted Stone robbed convenience stores and shot a man during the
early 1970s. Now the rugged-looking North Carolinian is a respected
trustee of Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``God gave me a second chance,'' Stone said this week during a
break at the seminary's fall trustee meeting. ``This is a land of
second chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's is a remarkable story of an up-and-down life. He grew up
in Durham, N.C., which is still his home. He was on the right path
during his years in high school and college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do everything right,'' he said. ``I even wanted to
become a minister.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stone got sidetracked _ for a while.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Wake Forest University and went into business,
working long hours as a real estate salesman and as the owner of a
thriving florist business in Durham.
</P>
<P>
   To keep himself going, Stone remembered the advice of his
fraternity brothers in college, who had urged him to take
``uppers'' to stay awake during all-night study sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had refused to take them in college,'' he said. ``I was
afraid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But when business pressures increased, he began overdosing on
amphetamines, or ``speed,'' to keep his energy level high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from taking two a day to 15 a day,'' he said. ``I
became very violent. I bought a gun and started robbing stores for
the thrill of it. I shot a man in a robbery. Luckily, he didn't
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone was convicted of armed robbery and attempted murder and
served four years and three months in Central State Prison in
Raleigh, N.C., and in Caledonian Prison Farm in northeast North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Since his release in 1976, he has spent his life warning people
that drugs _ both legal and illegal _ can destroy your life.
</P>
<P>
   Legal drugs are also dangerous, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who eat valium tablets can have just as many troubles
as those who snort cocaine,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1998, Stone walked across America, carrying an
American flag. He spoke in schools, churches and prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When prisoners see me, it gives them hope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to mark the year 2000 by trekking from the Texas-Mexico
border near Laredo northward through Fort Worth and all the way to
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk every step of the way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his walks he averages 16 miles a day. Then an associate
picks him up and takes him to a speaking engagement or a hotel. His
ministry is supported by his own funds and by donations.
</P>
<P>
   He addressed students at the Fort Worth seminary this week and
urged them to sign cards pledging they would not abuse drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sign something, you are more likely to keep your
promise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said about 200,000 people have signed the pledge cards.
During one of his walks, Stone persuaded Gov. Gary Johnson of New
Mexico to sign a card. Johnson advocates legalization of such drugs
as cocaine, heroin and marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Johnson doesn't use drugs. I agree with him that we
need to have a national dialogue about drug abuse,'' Stone said.
``But I think legalizing drugs would make them easier to obtain and
would put more people in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist Convention, the nation's largest
non-Catholic denomination, now has a task force for drug-abuse
prevention, which was suggested by Stone.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he asked the Fort Worth seminary to include more
drug-abuse prevention courses in its curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls from pastors all the time telling me one of their
people has a drug problem and they don't know what to do,'' Stone
said.
</P>
<P>
   After he got out of prison, Stone did graduate work at
Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary and Duke University. He
spent five years as a member of the North Carolina Mental Health
Commission and has served as chairman of the Durham County
Substance Abuse Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Stone's writings, he declared, ``America's youth needs
a new set of heroes. There can be no better hero than a family
member or friend who embraces sobriety and self control as the key
to happiness, success and inner peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Stone is not a hero in his own eyes, his incredible
efforts to warn people about drug dangers lifts him into the class
of some of those needed champions.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
