<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-FUTURE-1     10-22 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-FUTURE-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S NEW LEADERS FACE A DAUNTING TASK: ECONOMIC REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two days after he became the first democratically elected
president in Indonesian history, Abdurrahman Wahid spent Friday
closeted with five eminent local economists.
</P>
<P>
   That Wahid would spend his second day in office grappling with
economic matters is no surprise. The political upheaval that
vaulted him to power originated from an economic crisis. While the
political drama may be over, the economic crisis rages on.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Baird, the World Bank's representative in Jakarta, likens
Indonesia to a drowning swimmer who has broken the surface after a
fierce struggle. ``Now they've got to swim 10 miles to shore,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's economy is still the sickest in Asia, with its banks
and many of its companies paralyzed by debt. Modest growth has
returned, but not enough to offset the devastating effects of the
recession. Inflation and interest rates have returned to earth,
though few banks have any money to lend.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, rose to its highest level
Friday since last summer. But at an exchange rate of 6,800 rupiah
to the dollar, it is still worth only a third of what it was before
the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most disturbing to a populist leader like Wahid, some 20
million people have slipped under the poverty line since the crisis
began two years ago, according to the World Bank. This crippling
loss of wealth has left one-fifth of Indonesia's 200 million people
living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``His principal economic agenda has to be domestic,'' said
Eugene K. Galbraith, an economist and expert on Indonesia. ``He
must sew the place together after it was rent apart over the last
two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's agenda is likely to be reinforced by his newly elected
vice president, Megawati Sukarnoputri. Although Megawati's support
comes from Jakarta and other cities, while Wahid's constituency
tends to be rural, both built their reputations as champions of
social justice.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, Wahid, 59, has tried to allay fears that he would
depart from the policies of his predecessor, B.J. Habibie. In a
speech after he was sworn in on Wednesday, he pledged his fealty to
open markets and the need to make Indonesia competitive. Those
statements seemed aimed at the financial markets, and if the robust
performance of the rupiah has been any guide, they hit home.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, economic analysts note, Wahid has little
room for maneuver. Indonesia cannot do without the $43 billion
rescue package assembled by the International Monetary Fund, the
World Bank and other agencies in 1997. That money comes with strict
policy prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still very much in a straitjacket for the next year or
two,'' said Umar Juoro, an economic adviser to Habibie. ``The new
government will have to be quite careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the IMF and the World Bank recently halted the flow of
aid amid suspicions that Jakarta was trying to cover up a growing
bank scandal. The agencies said they may soon resume the aid,
following a Supreme Court ruling in Indonesia earlier this week
that required the government to release the results of an outside
investigation of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not finally resolved, but this was an important step,''
said Hubert Neiss, the director of Asia-Pacific operations of the
monetary fund. ``We'd have to see evidence that a legal prosecution
is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic analysts express optimism that Wahid will pursue legal
action against the officials implicated in the banking scandal.
Much of his appeal, they note, is rooted in a perception that he
symbolizes a break from Indonesia's corrupt past. But they also
point out that the president has more pressing priorities, among
them assembling a cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid and Megawati met on Thursday night, just after Megawati
was sworn in as vice president, to begin drawing up a cabinet.
Political analysts said names could be announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Given his ecumenical style, experts believe that in addition to
senior officials from his own party, Wahid is likely to draw some
from Megawati's party and even from Golkar, the party of Suharto
and Habibie, whose patrimonial rule was abruptly terminated by the
Parliament this week.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of cabinet ministers will be particularly crucial
because neither Wahid nor Megawati has the aptitude or interest to
delve into the nitty-gritty of policy-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them are essentially symbolic leaders,'' said Rizal
Ramli, an economist. ``They will need a proactive cabinet to
compensate.''
</P>
<P>
   How proactive remains to be seen. Some expect Megawati's chief
economic adviser, Kwik Kian Gie, to assume a senior post like
finance minister. Kwik, an outspoken ethnic Chinese economist,
ruffled feathers last June when he suggested that Indonesia should
peg the value of the rupiah to the dollar, a policy that is
anathema to the monetary fund.
</P>
<P>
   Others predicted that Kwik's views would disqualify him. Indeed,
in some political betting parlors Friday, Fuad Bawazir, a finance
minister under Suharto, was being mentioned as a possible finance
minister in the new government.
</P>
<P>
   Neiss said Wahid had expressed his support for the fund's
program in a meeting with some of its top officials. Wahid has a
few pet projects, like increased aid to farmers, that go beyond the
existing program. But Neiss said they could be accommodated without
ripping up the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural policy is a nettlesome issue in Indonesia. Last
year, the devaluation of the rupiah and a damaged distribution
system caused a shortage of rice, Indonesia's staple. Skyrocketing
prices led to food riots in eastern Java. While Indonesia has
adequate stores of rice this year, economic analysts said Wahid was
keenly aware of the danger posed by any future shortages.
</P>
<P>
   H.S. Dillon, an agricultural economist, said Wahid may grant new
subsidies to rice farmers. If so, he could clash with the IMF,
which has pushed Jakarta to eliminate subsidies and tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Given Indonesia's perilous finances, Wahid will not be in a
position to hand out much. Under the IMF's program, Indonesia now
has a targeted budget deficit equal to 5.8 percent of its gross
domestic product. Economists warn that this number will swell as
the government spends tens of billions to bail out its debt-ridden
banks and corporations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, the government's total debt was $51 billion. The
World Bank estimates this will grow to $136 billion by the end of
this year, largely because of the cost of the bank bailouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be their biggest headache,'' said Mari
Pangestu, an economist at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Jakarta. ``They've got to reduce
expenditures, including some sensitive ones, like fuel subsidies.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Indonesia cut fuel subsidies, in May 1998, it
ignited fierce riots that forced the resignation of Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding the banks is the nut that Wahid must crack,
economists said, if he is to restore the economy. The government
has made some progress _ closing 66 private banks, taking over 12,
and recapitalizing eight. But the state-owned banks remain a mess,
with most hopelessly insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has been distracted in its efforts by the political
tumult and the banking scandal, which involves one of the nation's
leading private banks, Bank Bali, and the state agency that is
responsible for taking over troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
   The longer Jakarta dithers, the more the clean-up will cost.
Earlier this year, the government estimated the cost at 300
trillion rupiah, or $43 billion. Now, economists say, it is closer
to 500 trillion rupiah, or $72 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers can seem insurmountable, even to the most
optimistic of government officials. After all, Indonesia had a
total gross domestic product of only $96.8 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there has been remarkably little doomsaying in Jakarta this
week. That is because the elections of Wahid and Megawati produced
something more precious than gold in Indonesia: a sense of
stability.
</P>
<P>
   Stability is crucial to Indonesia both at home and abroad. At
home, it will reassure domestic business people, not least the
ethnic Chinese entrepreneurs who spirited billions of dollars out
of the country after anti-Chinese riots last year. Abroad, it will
lure foreign investors back to the country.
</P>
<P>
   It was two years ago this month that Suharto appealed to the IMF
to rescue Indonesia's hemorrhaging economy. Indonesians hope that
Suharto's humbling plea and Wahid's proud ascension will come to be
seen as bookends in their country's turbulent journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope they select a team that can manage the economy,''
Ms. Pangestu said. ``But let's start with law and order _ and peace
on the streets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
