<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5413 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-PAMHOUSTON-TEX     10-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PAMHOUSTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO KNOW PAM HOUSTON _ WRITER, ADVENTURER, PERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``A Little More About Me''
</P>
<P>
   By Pam Houston
</P>
<P>
   Personal essays
</P>
<P>
   Norton, $23.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing in common with Pam Houston, the Arctic musher; or
Pam Houston, the Salmon River rafter; or Pam Houston, the Himalayan
trekker. But Pam Houston, the person? We are kindred spirits.
</P>
<P>
   I came to this conclusion five years ago while reading Houston's
first book of short stories, ``Cowboys Are My Weakness,'' which
describes in raw, wrenching and hilarious detail several women's
unsuccessful romantic interludes with a series of hard-lovin',
range-rovin', noncommittal types. At the time, I was living in
Chicago and dating a vegetarian MBA student who had ridden a horse
twice in his life. Yet I still felt an abiding connection with
Houston's words. Yes, even then.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happened with ``Waltzing the Cat,'' her second
book of short stories, and it's deja vu all over again with this
next installment, a collection of deeply personal essays titled,
``A Little More About Me.'' This time, Houston does away with the
thin veil that previously separated her fiction from her real life.
This time, she gives the reader herself _ imperfections,
insecurities and all.
</P>
<P>
   Houston wrote these essays over a difficult five-year period.
She divorced. She watched her best friend die of cancer. She buried
her mother. She started questioning her motivations and exploring
the childhood influences that shaped her adult self. ``The Long Way
to Safety,'' the introductory essay, not only sets a mood _
introspective, funny, unabashedly real _ it sets a theme.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is, foremost, the quintessential thrill-seeker _
something readers of her previous fiction might or might not have
picked up on. She's a daredevil skier and an whitewater rafting
addict, an Alaskan hunting guide and avid explorer of the
farthest-flung corners of the globe. These are the fascinating
adventures on which she takes her readers. ``I've never felt like
I'm on vacation,'' she writes, ``if there's not a little bit of
suffering involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic landscapes of the American West intoxicated Houston
as a young woman, and she has yet to glance back east (except for a
depressing stint in Ohio). Her love of the land is maternal in its
intensity, and she professes an insatiable need for flora, fauna,
mountain and river. Houston lives on a 120-acre Colorado ranch
along the Continental Divide and, she notes, is four hours from the
nearest health-food stores.
</P>
<P>
   But it's her penchant for pushing the envelope _ she's come
close to death on more than a couple of occasions _ that Houston,
in her mid-30s, begins to question. With each essay, she gives
readers a few more coordinates with which to map her inner
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Little by little, we learn about her embittered mother, her
angry and impossible-to-please father, her habit of choosing men
whom she feels the need to impress, her irrationally competitive
side, her paralyzing insecurities about her body. These are the
facts that bring Pam Houston off the tundra and into our lives.
This stuff, we can relate to.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of these essays lies in the interconnectedness of
Houston's physical conquests and emotional struggles. Her
adventures become metaphors: A near-fatal hunting expedition in
Alaska gives her strength to end a bad relationship. A brutal
midwinter camping trip with a new boyfriend is, in the end, ``a
great big love test'' for the guy. A failed attempt at scaling the
biggest Grand Teton becomes a lesson in priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But the most affecting essays find Houston nowhere more exotic
than strolling down a San Francisco beach, lying on a doctor's
examination table or sitting on her front porch. These pieces make
up a section called ``One Long Look in the Mirror,'' and they probe
deepest into Houston's soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a house that was filled with anger and
bitterness, so much rage that I was afraid nearly all of the
time,'' she writes in ``Pregnancy and Other Natural Disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The violence in my house was bred of resentment: my mother's
resentment over sacrificing a promising acting career to get
pregnant, my father's resentment over many things, including giving
up his most-eligible-bachelor status to marry my mom. If we believe
the theory _ and I do _ that we repeat our childhood traumas over
and over as adults until we get them worked out, that is at least
one explanation for why I keep finding myself in the middle of all
those tornadoes and hypothermic 3:00 a.m.s and all those near
misses with grizzly bears. It also explains why I was so afraid to
give them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's prose is clear and straightforward. She's less likely
to pen a sublime turn of phrase than to allow the power of her
words to build up over the course of several rhythmic sentences.
Her insights almost sneak up on you.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one story of our lives,'' Houston writes, ``and
we tell it over and over again, in a thousand different guises,
whether we know it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Pam, bring it on. I'm ready for a lot more about you.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
