<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POUND-BARRED-ART- &LR; (TR     10-22 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POUND-BARRED-ART- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PLACE FOR EZRA POUND IN CATHEDRAL'S POETS' CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
 (TRIMS)- NYT  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dean of the Cathedral of St. John the Divine has
overruled a vote by a group of prominent American writers to honor
Ezra Pound with a place in the Poets' Corner of the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The Very Rev. Harry S. Pritchett Jr. said in a letter to the
writers last week that the cathedral could not commemorate Pound
because of his anti-Semitic writings and broadcasts from Fascist
Italy during World War II and the lingering pain they have caused
members of the cathedral's congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The dean's decision is but another chapter in a dispute that has
shadowed Pound's reputation for more than 50 years. Can the work of
Pound, who is arguably the greatest American poet of the 20th
century, be judged separately from his political stands and moral
life?
</P>
<P>
   The Poets' Corner electors had voted to honor Pound and F. Scott
Fitzgerald, and Pritchett said in an interview that he intended at
first to accept the nominations. But when some members of the
cathedral's congregation learned of the nomination, they signed a
letter of protest and threatened to demonstrate if the Poets'
Corner went ahead with plans to install a carved stone to
commemorate Pound.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter the dean said he had ``struggled deeply'' over the
decision but had concluded that because of Pound's ``destructive
prejudices and anti-Semitism'' and the hurt that still lingers from
them, he could not agree to honor him.
</P>
<P>
   The Poets' Corner, in keeping with the Episcopal Cathedral's
tradition as a spiritual center for the arts, is modeled after the
appearance of the Poets' Corner in Westminster Abbey. It was
founded in 1984 to celebrate American writers.
</P>
<P>
   Carved flat stones of about 2 by 3 feet are laid side by side to
commemorate 33 writers in the corner, which is on the north side of
the cathedral's nave. They include Edgar Allan Poe, Walt Whitman,
Emily Dickinson, T.S. Eliot, William Carlos Williams and William
Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   The electors who chose Pound and Fitzgerald were led by Daniel
Hoffman, a former poetry consultant at the Library of Congress and
the cathedral's poet in residence. The panel has 13 established
writers and poets, including John Updike and Robert Pinsky. Pound's
nomination was supported by a majority of the votes but fewer than
Fitzgerald's.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the electors defended their votes for Pound, voicing
repulsion with his political activity but citing him as a seminal
poet, but others could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   One member, the poet Donald Hall, said Friday: ``I nominated
Pound and I know the horrendous things that Pound did, and I also
know that he was a great American poet not only in his own work,
but a great facilitator of the work of other American poets, from
Robert Frost to T.S. Eliot to James Joyce, who was another
beneficiary of his generosity. I admire him and I suggested him for
his poetry, but there were so many generous things in his career
before he became a megalomaniac and paranoiac. I think that the
malice of his madness is not relevant to his stature as a poet.''
</P>
<P>
   In broadcasts from Italy from January 1941 to July 1943, Pound
blamed Jews and other groups for the world's economic problems. He
was indicted for treason in 1943 and was arrested by American
forces and imprisoned in 1945 in a special cage at an Army
installation near Pisa. Later that year he was judged mentally
unfit to stand trial and was confined to St. Elizabeths Hospital, a
mental institution in Washington. In 1958 he was released through
the intervention of Frost, Eliot and other major poets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 the poet Allen Ginsberg visited Pound in Italy, and
Pound offered what some took to be an apology for what Pound called
his ``stupid suburban prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   To Marsha Ra, a warden of the cathedral's congregation and a
leader of the protest against honoring Pound, the statement was not
enough. Pound is ``not representative of Christian values,'' Ms. Ra
said in an interview. ``He was giving anti-Semitic radio broadcasts
while my relatives were being gassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ra, who was born a Jew and converted to Christianity, said
she had lost 15 cousins in the Holocaust. ``The belief in art for
art's sake is neither Christian nor Jewish,'' she said. ``We are
not a temple to the Muses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ra, a librarian, circulated a petition in the congregation
that was signed by a 100 members and forwarded to Pritchett.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, the cathedral's poet in residence, called Pound's
anti-Semitic statements ``vituperative and incoherent,'' but said,
``We had hoped the general public by now would agree with the
electors and would celebrate the heroic achievements of his work as
distinguished from the prejudicial opinions and comments of his
crazy economic theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Others on the electors' panel were John Updike, Robert Pinsky,
Rita Dove, Dana Gioia, Rachel Hadas, Michael Harper, Carolyn Kizer,
Grace Schulman, William J. Smith, Molly Peacock and Henry Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said that there was no formal debate about Pound before
the vote because his name had been put forward several times in the
past. ``The votes were cast after long reflection by each of the
electors who voted for Pound,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said, ``I believe that the dean is within his rights. I
clearly nominated him knowing that some or many people would
object. But if the literature is the criteria he belongs there, and
in fact his absence is utterly ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The question of Pound's moral guilt and the shadow it casts over
his poetry continues to preoccupy Pound scholars, said Tim Redman,
author of ``Ezra Pound and Italian Fascism,'' published by
Cambridge University Press. Redman, who is working on a new
biography of Pound, said that without doubt Pound was deeply
anti-Semitic, ``and he contributed to a climate of opinion that
enabled the Holocaust to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Redman said he believed that Pound was fully aware of the moral
weight of his actions. ``It is interesting that the anti-Semitism
does not enter Pound's poetry,'' he said. ``He knew that it was
morally wrong. The most important thing to Pound was to be known as
the great poet. He would not contaminate that which he held dearest
with this.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Pound's daughter, Mary de Rachewiltz, whose mother was Pound's
companion, Olga Rudge, said in a telephone interview from northern
Italy, where she lives, that her father's anti-Semitic utterances
had always been misunderstood. ``He tried to stop the war,'' she
said. ``He tried to keep America out of European embroilment, to
follow the line of John Adams and Jefferson and people who had
worked for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all say things when we are angered and misunderstood and
teased into something,'' Ms. de Rachewiltz said. She said that she
was disappointed with the reversal and had planned to attend the
ceremony. ``I thought it was time to be magnanimous,'' Ms. de
Rachewiltz said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pritchett said his decision presented him with ``an incredible
ethical dilemma that reaches beyond this incident.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it has to do with the relationship between art and
the artist's own ethics and the broader community,'' he said. ``It
is a question of developing an esthetic theology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5417 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-IRAN-KHALKHALI-ART-2T     10-22 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-KHALKHALI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR IRAN'S ROBESPIERRE, THE IMAGE IS SOFTER BUT THE HEART IS
UNFORGIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A MAP is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUM, Iran _ Much about Ayatollah Sadegh Khalkhali these days _
his simple white smock, his bare feet, his shuffling gait, his
concern for his visitors' well-being _ speaks of an almost
penitential gentleness. Long gone are his days as the chief judge
of Iran's revolutionary courts, when his name was enough to strike
terror, his word sufficient to set execution squads to work with
their gallows, their shootings and their stonings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drink your tea, it will get cold, it won't be good for you''
Khalkhali said, several times, to a visitor who dropped in
unannounced at his home here in the holy city of Shiite Muslims. It
is a two-hour drive across the desert from Tehran. Once, he
hastened away to fetch his wife, saying she could speak German,
then returned apologetically to say she felt unwell. Later, he
bobbed up to fetch copies of his books on Islamic theology, signing
several as mementos.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Khalkhali was the Islamic revolution's
Robespierre, the grim avenger who condemned hundreds and possibly
thousands of men and women to death, some after trials that lasted
only five minutes, or after no trials at all. He made his grim mark
on the American consciousness in April 1980, when, bushy-bearded,
in cleric's robes and turban, he was reported to have poked at the
charred bodies of American commandos killed in the failed attempt
to rescue hostages from the U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
   In this nation of 60 million, struggling now to emerge from the
shadows of the Islamic revolution and build a more magnanimous
society, the mere mention of Khalkhali makes people uneasy, as
though summoning his memory alone might set the tumbrels rolling
again. Even the Iranian government, caught between a reform faction
that wants more democracy and a rearguard of clerical hardliners
that wants the clock to remain stopped at 1979, behaves as if it
would rather have Khalkhali forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   For Khalkhali, 73, it is a double bind. Conservatives who want
nothing to disturb the power of the ruling clerics regard him as a
liability now better discarded. But he is an embarrassment, too, to
reformers, since he has announced his support for those favoring
more democracy, tolerance and respect for law. Caught between the
two views, in a sort of no-man's land, watched around-the-clock by
a police guard that doubles as a cordon to try and keep visitors
away, sits Khalkhali.
</P>
<P>
   It is a life far removed from the days of blood and revolution.
His house is modest and sparsely furnished, and its garden wall
scribbled with graffiti, not for the revolution but for the local
soccer club. Khalkhali said that he was in demand as a teacher of
Islamic law at the theological colleges that are clustered in Qum,
but a room stacked to the ceiling with copies of books he has
written suggested otherwise. When other leading ayatollahs in the
city were asked where he lived, several professed not to know.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, his conversion to the reform cause is less
astonishing than it seems. The overwhelming popularity of the
reformers, and of the 53-year-old cleric who is their
standard-bearer, President Mohammed Khatami, has caused a wave of
surprising political conversions, even if few are as striking as
Khalkhali's. Those urging more accountable government include
former student leaders who seized the American embassy, as well as
other high-ranking clerics who only a few years ago were counted as
zealots of Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, a two-hour conversation suggested that Khalkhali is
not so much a new man as the old one with a reformed sense of what
is politically correct. Along with his elaborate courtesies, he
conveyed the old revolutionary's sense of a world filled with
enemies and plots.
</P>
<P>
   He was with Khatami ``100 per cent, more or less,'' he said, but
not with the ``troublemakers'' who attached themselves to the
reform cause. ``There are always troublemakers, everywhere,'' he
said. ``Our enemies in the western world would like nothing better
than for us to fall into chaos, but it won't happen, I can assure
you.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When the talk turned to the American rescue raid, he said he
wanted a message passed to former President Carter, who ordered the
raid in April 1980 in a bid to free 56 embassy hostages held in
Tehran since the previous November, only to have the mission
collapse when an American helicopter and a C-130 transport collided
while re-fueling in the Iranian desert. Carter excoriated Khalkhali
after news reports described the Iranian cleric as having poked the
bodies of eight American servicemen killed in the raid, and having
held up one of the skulls.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's paramount
leader, had sent him to the crash site at Tabas, in the desert 500
miles southeast of Tehran, with instructions to see that the
Americans' bodies were properly looked after. What the reporters
had seen, he said, was not him poking or cutting the bodies, but
using a penknife to cut the knots on the Americans' death shrouds,
which were dirty and made of plastic, so that they could be
replaced with the clean white muslin shrouds prescribed by Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``How crazy can a man be, saying I was cutting up bodies,
calling me a monster?'' he said, referring to Carter. ``The truth
is, I felt sorry for the Americans, especially those who were
black, because Ayatollah Khomeini had told me to treat them with
dignity. My attitude was, when they came here to kill us, they were
our enemies, but after they died their care was entrusted to us by
God. It was God who saved us, because it was He who sent the
sandstorm that caused the American helicopters to have problems,
even before the crash.''
</P>
<P>
   When the talk turned to the executions, Khalkhali became
animated again, gripping the arms of his chair and saying that
there was nothing _ ``absolutely nothing!'' _ to regret. Contrary
to Western reports, he said, he had only directly ordered the
execution of ``100 or so'' people, leaving others to be sentenced
by judges under his command. In any case, he said, moving to a
bookcase to pull down a copy of the decree by Khomeini appointing
him to head the revolutionary courts, ``Everything I did, I did
under the holy authority of the Imam. I did only what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Accounts from the period describe Khalkhali as the ultimate
hanging judge, roaming Iran in pursuit of new victims, presiding
over secret trials that ended with the execution of hundreds of
officials and military officers who had served Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi, Iran's ousted ruler, even eating ice-cream outside a
prison where executions had taken place. Later, as head of a
special anti-narcotics task force known as the ``hit squad,'' he
condemned still more people. Other victims included scores of Kurd
tribesmen who were caught up in rebellions in Iran's
Kurdish-majority regions.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he proved too harsh even for Khomeini. In December
1980, after a bloodbath that lasted nearly two years, Khomeini
bowed to the demands of more moderate elements in the new
government who had protested the widespread use of torture and
execution in the anti-narcotics drive, and dismissed Khalkhali. But
by then, his actions had helped to mold an image of the Islamic
takeover as unremittingly vengeful and violent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it were true that he had said he would execute all of
his victims a second time if they were ``to walk the earth again,''
he replied, ``Well, they're not going to walk the earth again, are
they? But if they did, the answer is yes, yes, absolutely, I'd
execute them again, especially Hoveyda; he sold Iran to America.''
The reference was to Amir Abbas Hoveyda, prime minister in the
shah's government for 12 years until 1977. Hoveyda was credited
with policies that brought wider prosperity and educational
opportunity to Iran, as well as a close military and political
alliance with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hoveyda was executed by firing squad in April 1979, after
Khalkhali dismissed his pleas at a cursory trial. One common
account in Tehran is that Hoveyda was awaiting appeal of his
sentence when he was called away from writing a defense document
and summarily shot.
</P>
<P>
   When some in the revolutionary government challenged his
methods, Khalkhali asked whether they had in mind Western or
Islamic legal principles, and added: ``Under Western principles,
criminals have top lawyers and other matters to escape the law.
Yes, it's true, I never paid attention to these principles.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of reflection in Qum, Khalkhali said that he was
more sure than ever that his methods were correct. ``Remember, it
was a revolution, and there was no time for reflection,'' he said.
``If we hadn't executed them, they would have executed us the next
day. In any case, didn't you Westerners hold a trial at Nuremberg,
and execute the Nazis? I don't see the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In afterthought, he added: ``When I stand before God, I have
complete confidence that I will be judged favorably for what I have
done. There will be no questions about the executions, not a single
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
