<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL `IN THE WORKS' AS SIDES CLOSER ON OVERALL SPENDING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House and congressional budget negotiators
said Friday they were close to agreeing on overall spending levels
for the Year 2000 budget, but the sides were still far apart on
funding priorities and how to pay for some increases wanted by both
Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is in the works. We can get there. In terms of
spending we are ... really close. But it's policy differences that
are holding it up,'' said one Republican official close to the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the negotiators were searching for common ground at
a Capitol Hill meeting, Republican leaders were busy attacking
President Clinton as a big-spending liberal intent on paying for
his favored programs by raising taxes and raiding the Social
Security Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally held within earshot of where negotiators were
talking, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, and other GOP
leaders charged that if Clinton and the Democrats get their way in
next year's budget, retirees will end up suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats continue to fight us all the way because they want
to increase spending. To all the Democrats who want to raise taxes
or raid Social Security to balance the budget, the Republican
Congress says no,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments drew an angry response from Clinton and the
Democrats, who already have been stung by negative Republican
campaign ads being aired in key parts of the country that depict
Democrats as little more than criminals who want to pilfer Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican attacks, Clinton charged Friday, defy history.
Noting that Republican House leaders spoke publicly four years ago
about possibly phasing out the Social Security and Medicare
programs, Clinton said it was cynical of them to portray themselves
now as the guardians of Social Security who are trying to keep evil
Democrats from spending it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton said he was ``committed to turn the other
cheek'' until he sees if he can strike a deal with the GOP on
overall spending for next year. ``I guess it's easier when you're
not running for anything to do that,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   But White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart did not turn the
other cheek. Speaking to reporters, he accused DeLay of playing
politics with the budget in an attempt to enhance Republican
efforts in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The open question is whether ... the strategy he has
articulated of bringing the Democrats to their knees is the
strategy of the Republican Party,'' Lockhart said. ``That is not a
strategy that's looking after the interests of the American people.
It is a strategy that is designed for maximum political advantage,
and in that environment, if that is the overall guiding principle
of the Republicans, this is going to be a long, tough battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans gave notice Friday of just how difficult the
budget battle could get. Despite a veto threat by Clinton, they
unveiled a plan to cut federal spending across-the-board by about
1.5 percent next year to help head off any borrowing from Social
Security money to underwrite next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   They said the reduction would require government departments and
agencies to eliminate waste. Republican aides said that without the
reduction, the final GOP spending plans for next year could end up
tapping the Social Security Trust Fund for at least $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have already passed 12 of the 13 appropriations
bills needed to fund government operations through the 2000 fiscal
year. They will likely pass the last and largest of those measures
_ a bill covering labor, health and education _ early next week.
Clinton has signed seven of the bills sent to him, but has
threatened to veto the rest unless Republicans agree to spend more
money on foreign aid and to hire teachers and police officers, and
unless they remove provisions he says could hurt the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed paying for those programs by closing
corporate and foreign tax loopholes, raising cigarette taxes, and
penalizing polluters. But those ideas have been rejected by
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't raise taxes and we won't raid the Social Security
Trust Fund. End of story,'' said one Republican leadership aide.
``We're willing to negotiate all the details, but not the big
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, meanwhile, are pressing ahead with their plan
to pass all 13 appropriations bills before striking a deal on
overall spending with Clinton, even though the president has
already vetoed two bills and will likely veto at least three more
when they reach his desk.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriations bills contain accounting techniques to help
pay for increased spending that Republicans wanted. The accounting
measures include borrowing from the 2001 budget and declaring as
``emergencies'' some routine spending matters such as the 2000
Census.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for us to say that we've done our work, we're going
to have to pass every appropriations bill (without) dipping into
the Social Security Trust Fund monies,'' said a GOP aide. ``But
right now we're about $5 billion over where we're supposed to be.
That's where the one percent across-the-board cut comes into
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders are planning to force a vote in the House
next week on their 1.5 percent cut of all government programs, with
the exception of Social Security, Medicare and welfare benefits.
Pay increases next year for lawmakers and federal workers, which
has already been signed into law by Clinton, also would not be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, however, contends that an across-the-board cut
would be too harsh for some agencies to absorb even though next
year's budget is expected to be 3-percent to 4-percent higher
overall than 1999 spending.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
