<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUIET HELP OF FAMILY MEMBERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind., Pa.)   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. _ Linda K. Williams ticked off her expenses:
rent for the small, neatly furnished apartment that she shares with
her teen-age son, electricity, phone, groceries, medicine, life
insurance, occasional evenings out, new clothing, the bus commute
to work, the boy's allowance and lunch money.
</P>
<P>
   The expenses total nearly $19,000, but her take-home pay as a
secretary is only $15,700. How does she make ends meet? Gradually,
Ms. Williams explained how her sisters help, and also a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The boyfriend _ Ms. Williams is 43 and divorced _ shops with her
occasionally for food and clothes and bought her the delicate gold
chain that she wore during a recent interview at her apartment
here. But the four sisters are Ms. Williams' real safety net. Each
earns more than she does, and they often appear at her home with
food or detergent or some other household item they have bought for
her while shopping for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I let my finances get to me, I would be way down there, and
I am way up here,'' Ms. Williams said. ``If I lose my job, my
backup plan is my sisters. They are going to help me, I know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So will government, of course, through unemployment insurance,
Medicaid, food stamps and other support payments. But help from
family and friends, particularly boyfriends in the case of single
mothers, is turning out to be a huge part of the social safety net
in an era when new jobs are constantly being created, most of them
at $10 an hour or less.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans like Ms. Williams find themselves
struggling to make ends meet on family incomes below $20,000 a
year. Roughly 20 percent of the nation's 104 million families fall
into this category.
</P>
<P>
   Family help, in cash or in kind, is hardly new. It is routine
practice in immigrant communities, and it became a means of
survival during the Great Depression, when in-laws, elderly parents
and close friends often shared an apartment or home, contributing
what income they had to the household's upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   Until Social Security benefits began to increase annually just a
generation ago, it was common for grown children to support their
parents financially through old age. And among the wealthy, parents
still often provide the down payment for a married son or
daughter's first home in an upscale neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But as the nation grew wealthier after World War II and the
self-supporting nuclear family became the ideal, and often the
norm, help from family declined somewhat, even among blue-collar
workers and others at the lower end of the income scale _ only to
rebound over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists have detected the widespread practice in recent
research, and it was evident in interviews with low-wage workers in
Middle American cities like Indianapolis, where incomes and living
costs closely match the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of resources being shared within a nuclear family or
a household,'' said Kathryn Edin, a University of Pennsylvania
sociologist. ``Our official statistics encourage that view. But
resources are shared more broadly in a social network, which helps
to explain why poor people are not flocking to homeless shelters or
to charity in greater numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have a situation where your grandmother gives you
money, and you might not pay her back in cash,'' she continued.
``But you are expected to help her when she is sick, clean her
house or shop for her. Reciprocity is important.''
</P>
<P>
   The contributions of boyfriends or biological fathers, often not
living in the household, are also undercounted, Ms. Edin has found.
Her research, which has involved dozens of poor families in several
cities over the last six years, found that such men often provide
important if intermittent help in forms like cash gifts to a single
mother, clothing for the children, or name-brand sneakers for a
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you add up the formal and informal, you find that twice as
many families are receiving support as official statistics
suggest,'' Ms. Edin said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and grandparents play big roles in the support network
for many low-income households, partly because much of their
working lives came before wage stagnation crippled the incomes of
low-skill workers and before the minimum wage lost so much ground
to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Pinner, 35, a receptionist and clerk, is plagued by
break-ins and burglaries at the home she rents. She will soon move
with her two children to a home in a better neighborhood that her
father owns and that she will rent from him _ an improvement in
circumstances that she says she could not have managed on her
income of $15,500 a year without his help.
</P>
<P>
   Her father worked for 34 years on a Chevrolet assembly line and
has a union pension. ``He picks me up in the morning and drives me
to work,'' Ms. Pinner said. ``If we don't have anything to eat,
he'll help. Maybe once a month he pays for the shopping, and my
aunt gives me a few dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Administration views family support as a valuable
supplement to government benefits like the earned income tax
credit, rent subsidies, training, Medicaid and the like. The
Republicans emphasize community support for the poor, charity being
one element and family help another.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the policy mix of either party is strong
endorsement of higher wages. That would be achieved in part through
a greater increase in the current minimum wage of $5.15 an hour
than either Al Gore or Bill Bradley, the two contenders for the
democratic presidential nomination, have proposed so far.
</P>
<P>
   Neither proposal would exert the sort of upward pressure on the
wages of the poorest workers that the minimum exerted in its heyday
back in the 1960s. And a higher wage, after all, is the solution
favored by the working poor themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
