A5456 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-LA-Z-BOY-$ADV2     10-22 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-LA-Z-BOY-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLUMBER IS OVER AS LA-Z-BOY EXPANDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.C., Miss., Ohio)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE LEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, La-Z-Boy Inc. had a somewhat sleepy image: a midsized
Midwestern company that was modestly well run and known for its
signature product _ a comfortable reclining chair. But a string of
acquisitions _ three announced this year _ have some investors
thinking there may be a lot of spring in this 72-year-old business,
which is based in Monroe, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 28, La-Z-Boy announced its biggest deal: a plan to
acquire Ladd Furniture, based in Greensboro, N.C., for $267.2
million, including debt of $101.5 million; the deal is expected to
be completed early next year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, La-Z-Boy announced that it would buy Bauhaus USA, a
furniture maker in Saltillo, Miss., for about $60 million; that
purchase closed in June. And in April it announced that it would
acquire Alexvale Furniture of Taylorsville, N.C., for undisclosed
terms. That deal is expected to close this year.
</P>
<P>
   After all the acquisitions are completed, La-Z-Boy will be the
largest publicly traded home furniture company, with sales of more
than $2 billion, just ahead of Furniture Brands International.
La-Z-Boy hit the $1 billion sales mark only two and one half years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The deals will broaden La-Z-Boy's product mix. Ladd has done
well in two markets where La-Z-Boy has had no presence: children's
furniture and furniture sold to hotels and other institutions. The
Bauhaus line of upscale contemporary furniture gives La-Z-Boy a
path into chains owned by Federated Department Stores and May
Department Stores, two big retailers with which La-Z-Boy has had
few dealings.
</P>
<P>
   ``La-Z-Boy has been very successful at making acquisitions and
going after niche markets, and they've been able to do that without
missing a beat in earnings growth,'' said Elliott L. Schlang,
managing director of the LJR Great Lakes Review, a research firm in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has not neglected its core business. In April,
La-Z-Boy introduced the Oasis, a recliner that sells for about $999
and features in one armrest a cooler that can store a six-pack; its
sales are going well according to Gene M. Hardy, La-Z-Boy's
secretary and treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   La-Z-Boy shares closed at $17.9375 on Friday, down 27 percent
from a 52-week high of $24.5625 on July 1 and just 11.7 times
analysts' estimates for fiscal 2000 earnings. Schlang has a 52-week
target of $33 on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attribute the lackluster stock price to concerns that
higher interest rates will slow new-home sales, thus dampening
furniture sales. Rivals have suffered too. Furniture Brands, which
closed at $17.75 on Friday, is down 34.9 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect La-Z-Boy to post profits of 41 cents a share
when it reports fiscal second-quarter results on Nov. 3. That would
be up 17 percent from the quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   For its first quarter, ended July 24, La-Z-Boy posted profit of
25 cents a share, nearly double the figure a year earlier and ahead
of analysts' expectations of 21 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Hale, an analyst at Bank of America Securities,
recommends La-Z-Boy stock and has a 52-week target of $29. One
worry is whether La-Z-Boy has the expertise to manage the various
brands. ``I have some concern that they are a bit disparate,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lance James, a longtime La-Z-Boy investor who runs the Babson
Enterprise II fund, sees the stock's low price-to-earnings ratio as
a buying opportunity. After the Ladd announcement, he raised his
La-Z-Boy stake to 3 percent of the fund's assets. And La-Z-Boy
itself has been buying back shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're a long-term investor or a value investor,''
James said, ``this is everything you're looking for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
