<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-PAPON-675&AMP;ADD-     10-22 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PAPON-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS HAND OVER NAZI COLLABORATOR TO FRENCH POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The manhunt for Maurice Papon, the 89-year-old Nazi
collaborator, ended swiftly when the Swiss police arrested him late
Thursday at a modest hotel in one of Europe's most exclusive ski
resorts, where he was hiding under a false name.
</P>
<P>
   As the officers were arresting Papon, who fled France rather
than begin his 10-year sentence for sending hundreds of Jews to
Nazi death camps, he began complaining of chest pains and was taken
by ambulance to the prison ward of a hospital in Bern.
</P>
<P>
   But late Friday the Swiss expelled him, saying they would not
harbor anyone convicted of crimes against humanity. He was handed
over to French police officers who were ready with a helicopter to
take him to a prison outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Papon was supposed to have reported to the prison on Wednesday.
Instead, he disappeared. In a defiant statement to the press, he
said he had chosen ``exile'' rather than spend his last days in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said he had spent most of the last 10 days
living quietly in various small hotels in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Arrogant and combative, Papon has always refused to take any
blame for the roundup of Jews for deportation during World War II,
despite his signature on numerous transportation orders when he was
an official of the collaborationist Vichy government.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing to flee France, he said he was making an
``honorable'' choice, one made ``by some of the most noted men in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   But his efforts to disappear into Switzerland collapsed on
Thursday after a French appeals court upheld his conviction of last
year and the authorities were able to issue an international
warrant for his arrest at 7 p.m. that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, Swiss police officials went to the Post Hotel
in the resort of Gstaad, tipped off to Papon's presence by the
French government.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel employees said police had asked to see the guest register
and spotted Papon's alias _ Robert Roche-Foucauld _ listed for Room
115. The name is familiar to French speakers through the widely
known maxims of the 17th-century author La Rochefoucauld and so was
likely to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel manager, Ruedi Widner, said the officers were
concerned that Papon might try to commit suicide and asked how best
to get into the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to call and tell him that there was a fax for him
and that we would be bringing it up,'' Widner said. When the
officers entered the room, he added, Papon looked stricken and
complained of chest pains but was later able to walk out of the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said Papon was carrying about $6,000 in French,
Swiss and American money. He also had three passports, two with his
own name and one for Robert Roche-Foucauld. He also had various
driver's licenses with still other names, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Papon's dramatic efforts to escape punishment transfixed the
French. His trial, more than 45 years after the events took place,
forced the nation to relive a part of France's history that many
would rather have forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   More than 74,000 Jews were transported from France to Nazi death
camps, though until Papon was tried, no high-ranking official of
the Vichy government had been held accountable for aiding in their
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Papon's ability to stay out of jail and then disappear even
after he was convicted was particularly shocking for his victims
and their families, many of whom questioned the government's
commitment to punishing the former collaborator, who after the war
rose in the ranks of the government to become budget minister.
</P>
<P>
   French officials tried to explain that Papon benefited from a
loophole in the law once the courts set him free during his trial
for health reasons. Once he was out of jail, there was no mechanism
to take away his passport until the appeals process began, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   But after suffering days of criticism on the subject, French
government officials were clearly relieved that Papon had been
apprehended quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we were not impotent,'' said Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin. `'We acted swiftly. I'm naturally profoundly satisfied by
this. But I have to say I am not surprised.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those who had tried for years to put Papon in jail also
expressed their relief. ``This thing has been going on now for 18
years,'' said Serge Klarsfeld, who did much of the research that
was used to convict Papon. ``There is an enormous satisfaction in
thinking that soon we will see it end.''
</P>
<P>
   Juliette Benzazon, 69, who lost her immediate family in a round
up ordered by Papon, said that now that he was in jail she could
finally mourn properly for her parents. ``I guess this means that
maybe in the end you do have to pay for what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Swiss officials said that Papon remained calm once he was
arrested and slept in the ambulance most of the way between Gstaad
and Bern. Swiss officials said they found him in satisfactory
health.
</P>
<P>
   Papon apparently hoped that Switzerland would take him in
because it does not recognize crimes against humanity. But Swiss
officials, already subject to criticism that they did little to
return Jewish assets after the war, were quick to say they would
have nothing to do with such thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is meant to signal that we do not want people
like him in Switzerland,'' Swiss Justice Minister Ruth Metzler said
Friday afternoon at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial, Papon was confronted with numerous examples of
his signature on deportation orders. But he steadfastly maintained
that he had worked to undermine German efforts and helped the
French resistance though no such evidence was ever presented.
</P>
<P>
   In making his appeal, lawyers planned to argue that Papon could
not defend himself properly because witnesses were dead. In
addition, they said he had been questioned about convoys of Jews
that were not part of the charges against him and cited other
violations of judicial procedure.
</P>
<P>
   However, Papon's appeal was automatically rejected on Thursday
because he failed to report to prison. Under French law, he was
required to report for at least one night before the appeals
process could begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
