<HEADER>
A5460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MONTENEGRO     10-22 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MONTENEGRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS PLAY DOWN POSSIBILITY OF CONFLICT WITH MONTENEGRO  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Yugoslav officials on Friday played down the possibility
of armed confrontation between Serbia and Montenegro, saying the
Montenegrins would themselves decide whether to remain within
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A Yugoslav deputy prime minister said there was little chance
that Serbia would use force against its sister republic. Serbia and
Montenegro are the last two component republics of Yugoslavia, and
Montenegro has been moving slowly toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never resolve the problems that exist between Montenegro
and Yugoslavia with force,'' the official, Tomislav Nikolic, a
member of the ultranationalist Radical Party, told a private
Serbian television station.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia made similar
conciliatory comments 11 days ago in a major speech in the southern
Serbian city of Leskovac.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the people of Montenegro, may they decide their fate by
themselves without casting even the shred of a doubt on the
continuity of the Slav perception of goodness, the Montenegrin
feeling for chivalry and the European feeling for civilization,''
Milosevic said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, the president of Montenegro, Milo Djukanovic,
dismissed Milosevic's comments as manipulative and insincere.
Speaking in Prague at a new conference with President Vaclav Havel
of the Czech Republic, Djukanovic said: ``I'm afraid it's just
another attempt to manipulate the public. For Milosevic and
Yugoslavia, it's just another attempt to gain more time and to
prolong his days in power.''
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic, who broke with Milosevic two years ago, said it was
self-evident that the Montenegrins would decide their own fate. The
issues for him were ``democracy and decentralization,'' he said,
and whether they were possible for Montenegro in a Yugoslav
Federation run by the autocratic Milosevic. In 1992, Montenegro
chose to remain inside Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats believe that neither Milosevic nor Djukanovic
want a confrontation now, but they fear that the situation in
Montenegro is unstable and potentially explosive. Djukanovic has
spoken recently of creating a separate Montenegrin currency within
days of any formal Yugoslav devaluation of the dinar.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Milosevic's party spokesman, Ivica Dacic, said: ``The
Serbian people certainly will never be an obstacle for the
Montenegrins to have their own country.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least 40 percent of Montenegro's population of 650,000
people support Milosevic and his allies and are sharply opposed to
any break in ties with Serbia. Western diplomats believe that a
declaration of independence could provoke civil war in Montenegro,
with or without Milosevic's meddling.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav military has about 12,000 men stationed in
Montenegro, while Djukanovic has built up a militarized police
force that is roughly the same size.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, Djukanovic made proposals to Belgrade for a sharply
restructured Yugoslavia that would become a more equal
confederation, with Montenegro responsible for its own currency and
army. After a long silence from Belgrade, Milosevic proposed
party-to-party talks on the future scheduled to begin on Oct. 26.
</P>
<P>
   If the talks do not succeed, Djukanovic has spoken of a
referendum on independence, which his officials now say could take
place as soon as February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BAPTISTS-HINDUS23-COX     10-22 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-HINDUS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptists criticized for Hindu brochure
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Hindu from Kashmir, Subash Razdan says he's not
living in hopeless darkness _ no matter what the Southern Baptist
Convention insists.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the nation's largest protestant group will publish
its latest ``prayer guide,'' offered as a reference for Southern
Baptists. From it, members can learn the shortcomings of Hinduism
then pray for its adherents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they trying to do, start a Holy War?'' asked Razdan.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta resident chairs the board of trustees for the
National Federation of India-American Associations, representing
nearly 300 groups and 1.3 million Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Razdan leafed through the 16-page booklet in disbelief Friday.
It's similar to earlier Baptist publications that recommended
prayer for Jews and Muslims. Coming this spring: a prayer guide for
Buddhists. ``You can make Christianity look good, but don't make
any other religion look bad,'' Razdan said.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly outlandish to Razdan and others is the Baptist
claim that ``Hindus do not have a concept of sin or of personal
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's patently false,'' said Paul Courtright, an expert on
Hinduism and director of Asian Studies at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense,'' Courtright said, ``it's equal opportunity
misrepresentation of all forms of non-Christian traditions. I
suppose they'll probably go after Catholics next. I find it
loathsome.''
</P>
<P>
   The pocket-sized guides _ available from the Southern Baptist
Convention's International Mission Board in Richmond, Va. _
coincide with Divali, the major Hindu festival of lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was planned,'' said Wendy Norvelle, spokeswoman for the
International Mission Board. ``It's an optimum time to seek things
of spiritual truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The booklets ``incorporate our interpretation of what they
believe,'' Norvelle said. ``It's read through the light of what we
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Moore, who edited the Hindu prayer guide, said earlier
booklets were unfairly represented as evangelical conversion
manuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not encouraging people to go out on the streets and
buttonhole every Hindu they see,'' Moore said. ``But it would be
wonderful if the opportunity arises.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many Christian conversions resulted from previous
guides, Moore said, ``No records are being kept. The records are in
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   The missionary movement in India began in the early 1800s,
Courtright said. One effort was to convert Hindus to Christianity,
the other was to provide social services. What lingers is a fuzzy
understanding of the religion, say critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The representation of Hinduism as steeped in idolatry,
superstition and strangeness is one of the enduring themes of
Western perception of India,'' Courtright said.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist brochure portrays Divali in a mystical darkness and
suggests Christian prayer for the faithful so ``that the power of
Satan will be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's baloney,'' Razdan said. ``Hindus have the reincarnation
of seven lives. That's based on how good your deeds are in the
past. ... All religions talk about the same love.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
