<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WTTH-RUBIN-ART     10-22 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WTTH-RUBIN-ART-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH JAMES B. RUBIN: RESURGENCE ASSET MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Fla., Mass., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24)  
 (af)  
 By HILARY ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to James B. Rubin's line of work, it's fine to be
a control freak. As chief investment officer and co-chairman of
Resurgence Asset Management, a $1 billion manager of hedge funds
and other investments in White Plains, N.Y., Rubin often strives to
influence the fates of companies in which he has invested.
</P>
<P>
   And these are not just any companies. As a so-called vulture
investor, Rubin, 45, specializes in distressed companies that are
likely to go bankrupt. In 10 years, he has found that the more say
he has in how a company is reorganized _ that is, how the creditors
are paid under Chapter 11 of the United States Bankruptcy Code _
the greater the returns for the funds he manages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate buying things that are popular,'' Rubin said. ``We'd
rather look at things that nobody is looking at and, in fact, that
everybody hates. The more complicated, messy and involved, the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider his $250 million Re/Enterprise funds. Since their start
in August 1989, the offshore and domestic versions of this hedge
fund have returned 25 percent before fees, annualized, through
Sept. 30. After fees, that number is 20 percent. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index returned 16.6 percent, annualized, over the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, Rubin started the $500 million Resurgence funds,
which function basically as private equity pools. They tend to
invest in companies requiring longer holding periods than other
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Although they hold 40 percent in cash, the funds, through Sept.
30, have returned 50 percent, annualized, since their inception,
after fees, on their investments that have been completed and sold.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin got his start in the business in 1982, when his employer
at the time, the Atlantic Metal Hose Co., an industrial pipe maker,
filed for Chapter 11. As a vice president, he stayed on after the
company was bought and renamed Atlantic Johnson, but it was
liquidated in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   After working with R.D. Smith &AMP; Co., a brokerage firm
specializing in distressed companies, he teamed with M.D. Sass
Investors Services, a diversified investment firm, to start the
hedge funds in 1989. M.D. Sass markets the funds, and its chairman,
Martin D. Sass, is co-chairman of Resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin makes two kinds of investments. One is ``control
positions,'' in which he owns a large chunk of a company's bonds or
other debt and then takes an active role in the company's
reorganization. He generally holds his stakes for several years
before selling them.
</P>
<P>
   In Rubin's ``core strategic positions,'' which are smaller and
shorter term, he is usually a passive investor.
</P>
<P>
   Resurgence holds stakes in 15 companies; six are control
positions. Re/Enterprise holds stakes in 20 companies; eight are
control positions.
</P>
<P>
   In evaluating a company's finances, Rubin's staff creates a
spreadsheet to estimate long-term returns. The firm's typical goal
for each investment is a 50 percent annual rate of return before
fees, he said, but it is willing to accept annualized gains as
little as 25 percent, if the risks are fairly low.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's analytical process is rigorous. First, Resurgence
evaluates the asset values of a company, piece by piece, to
determine what it is worth as a continuing business and what it
would be worth if it were closed and sold off piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   The staff reads through bond indentures, and Rubin tries to
decide how best to reorganize the company out of bankruptcy _ for
example, whether it should have any debt at all and, if so, how
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like going into a situation that gives every appearance of
being a train wreck, disassembling it, analyzing every microbe and
then putting it back together like it's a puzzle and seeing if, in
doing so, we can create value,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In January 1992, Rubin started acquiring what would be a
controlling position in the secured bank debt of the Seaman
Furniture Co., a retailer based in Woodbury, N.Y., that had
recently declared bankruptcy. In the October reorganization, the
bank creditors he led acquired a controlling equity stake in the
company in exchange for its debt. Rubin then led the effort to
rebuild the business, hiring new management.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1997, Rubin, along with Carl Marks &AMP; Co. and the
T. Rowe Price Recovery fund, took the company private in a
leveraged buyout, paying $25 a share _ up from about $4 at the time
of the reorganization. They have now paid back most of the debt
they took on. And management has improved operations, in part by
introducing a more focused merchandising strategy. It also more
than doubled the number of stores in the chain, to 47. The funds
have earned annualized returns just shy of 40 percent in the seven
and a half years they have been involved in Seaman.
</P>
<P>
   The story may not be over yet. Rubin's funds are the largest
creditors of Levitz Furniture, a retailer in Boca Raton, Fla., that
entered bankruptcy in September 1997. ``There's the possibility of
putting the two companies together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as a vulture investor, Rubin doesn't always build things.
After the Caldor Corp., the discount department store chain, filed
for bankruptcy in September 1995, Rubin decided not to buy the bank
debt, then selling at 90 cents on the dollar. But he continued his
research. To determine the value of the retailer's leases on its
145 stores, his group spoke with dozens of local real estate
brokers. He and his analysts then estimated that the value of
Caldor's stores _ about $150 million _ was more than double the
company's or bank's estimates, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the spring of 1998, he bought bank debt at an
average price of 58 cents on the dollar. By late summer, Rubin's
funds owned two-thirds of the debt and Robert T. Symington, a
senior vice president at Resurgence, was heading the bank
creditors' steering committee. In that position, Symington
pressured Caldor to allow the banks to see the actual store leases,
which proved to be twice as valuable as his estimate, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank committee convinced Caldor management to liquidate
rather than reorganize, a process that is now nearly complete.
Returns to Rubin's funds have been more than 100 percent,
annualized.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Rubin invested in Arch Communications Group, a paging
company based in Westborough, Mass. In May, he bought the bonds of
the Mobilemedia Corp., a bankrupt company in Fort Lee, N.J., that
Arch was about to buy. As part of the merger, which was completed
in June, his funds received rights to buy Arch stock, which they
exercised, and their Mobilemedia bonds were swapped for more Arch
shares. Resurgence now holds 19 percent of Arch stock.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's picks aren't always winners. In the early and
mid-1990s, it was forced to sell its positions in the Cadillac
Fairview Corp. and Envirodyne Industries when their reorganizations
did not work in Rubin's favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
