<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5477 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT &LR;      10-22 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ONE-UPS BRADLEY WITH POLITICAL LEAP FROG 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So here is a little oddity from the campaign trail:
Former Sen. Bill Bradley discussed child poverty at a Baptist
church in New York City on Thursday. Vice President Al Gore,
Bradley's only rival for the Democratic presidential nomination,
gave a speech about child poverty at a Methodist church in
Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? Not really.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign all but admits it is engaged in what can only
be called pre-emptive scheduling. In a field where two candidates
hold similar views on similar topics and even use similar language,
being first is one of the few ways for a candidate to try to
distinguish himself.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Gore campaign has been eyeing Bradley's
schedule and having Gore speak first on the same topic. Last month,
Bradley was planning to give a speech on health care when Gore
scheduled his own speech on the same topic a few days before.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp has lots of reasons for pre-emptive scheduling.
One is that Gore advisers see Bradley getting credit for and being
taken seriously on a range of issues that Gore has worked on for
years. And it's not just that. Bradley also appears to be
benefiting from press coverage of his speeches with a steady rise
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to allow anyone, even if they just decided to
run for president, to jump onto an issue that we've been working on
for a long time,'' said Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore. ``This
campaign is not going to stand for officious intermeddlers when it
comes to an agenda that we've been working on for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, a spokesman for Bradley, says the Gore camp is
nervous because Bradley is more thoughtful and bolder than Gore.
``This is not a coincidence,'' he said of the scheduling. ``They
are seeing the appeal of what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, Bradley worked on many of these issues,
including poverty, racial matters and gun control, while he was in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the similarity in topics is unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be talking about the same things because we
are talking to the same Democratic primary electorate,'' said
Elaine Kamarck, Gore's top domestic policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both candidates gave speeches on the environment this
week.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore campaign takes serious pride in its scheduling
prowess. In September, Gore aides could not pick up the telephone
fast enough to tell reporters that the vice president was adding a
stop in Rhode Island to a trip the next day to New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it wanted to draw attention to the fact that Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican front-runner, who had been
delayed by bad weather, had skipped seeing a group of Rhode Island
school children but managed to attend a fund-raising event.
</P>
<P>
   Gore swooped in to provide the forlorn wee ones with the
presidential-style campaign they had been promised.
</P>
<P>
   One purpose of such scheduling hijinks is to demonstrate a
campaign's flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a quick campaign, this is a nimble campaign,'' Lehane
asserted, acknowledging that being fleet of foot can help counter a
long-held impression that the Gore campaign is so clogged with
bureaucrats that it cannot react swiftly to changing events.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign has almost reveled in the opposite
impression. Aides like to say they are proceeding at Bradley's own
inner pace and have their eye on the big picture. They take pride
in not reacting to daily blips on the screen, implying that the
Gore campaign is revealing its desperation with sudden reactive
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore advisers recognize that Bradley comes
across as more likable, relaxed, less rehearsed than Gore, but,
they say, Gore has a better command of issues and his ideas are
more workable. So to the extent the Gore campaign can use its
scheduling of speeches to prompt a comparison of the candidates'
views, the Gore camp believes it can benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get both the press and the voters to focus on where
we stand and where he stands, we think we do well in that
comparison,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Gore campaign has even carefully timed its
formulation of the vice president's views. Last month, The
Advocate, a gay magazine, ran an interview with Bradley in which he
said he opposed same-sex marriage. The Gore campaign put out a
statement later that day saying that Gore also opposed same-sex
marriage, a position Gore had been ``reviewing'' for some time.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore campaign also used the opportunity to draw
attention to Bradley's support for changing the 1964 Civil Rights
law to include protection for gays. The Gore campaign says that
proposal has hurt Bradley among black voters, who worry that
reopening the civil rights law would give conservatives in Congress
a chance to restrict it.
</P>
<P>
   And the countermoves also encompass endorsements. Because
Bradley, a former basketball star, has such a natural following
among professional athletes, Gore has even reached into that world
for support. He recently won the endorsement of Shaquille O'Neal,
star player for the Los Angeles Lakers, whose coach, Phil Jackson,
is one of Bradley's best friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
