<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5479 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     10-22 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBERS THAT DON'T MATTER MUCH THESE DAYS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The questions may be italicized)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   21. 65. 23.
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not a lock combination, a partial lottery entry or a
quarterback's signals. Through Friday, those numbers are the gains,
in percentage points, that the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, the NASDAQ
composite index and the Dow Jones industrial average have recorded
over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   For those who own the so-called average stock, which has
declined over the last year, the performance of the market's major
indexes probably doesn't mean very much. Nor is it likely to matter
for those who worry about rising interest rates, inflation and Year
2000 issues. Still, with stocks bobbing as much as they have
recently, it is worth remembering where we were a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Smith, chief investment strategist at Prudential
Securities, talked last week about the crosscurrents pulling on
investors just now, and why he doesn't expect much from the market
for some time to come, even though he likes stocks. Here are
excerpts from the conversation: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Stocks have been range-bound for awhile now. What is the
market trying to sort out? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Essentially, we have come to an important crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand is the thought that the inflation cycle is
kicking in, and the Fed will have to fight it. In the process of
doing that, the central bank will ultimately wind up clobbering the
economy and push it into recession. If you think that is going on,
you see higher interest rates, lower stock multiples and eventually
lower earnings. That sounds a lot like a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative view is that while prices are rising, inflation
has to be higher than it was last year, because a year ago we were
looking at deflation.
</P>
<P>
   Could inflation come back to pre-financial-crisis levels of
around 2.5 percent, which is the level we were at before 1997? You
either believe that is normal, or that we are going to go through
that level to some cyclically ugly high number.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, uncertainty prevails about which view is right, and
that is not good for the stock market. We are in big trouble when
we waffle.
</P>
<P>
   We are probably going to need a couple of more quarters to sort
this out. Either the inflation trend will keep going up, or it will
flatten out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where does the Y2K issue fit into all of this? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Y2K is a bravado issue. No one admits to changing their
investment strategy because of Y2K. But underneath you have to
think it is another dose of uncertainty, another reason to be
nervous. No one is really nervous themselves, but they are all
nervous someone else will get nervous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So how will this all get sorted out? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I am persuaded by the pre-1997 case that we are merely going
back to levels of inflation and interest rates that existed before
the onset of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that oil prices can't go up or some other act
of God can happen.
</P>
<P>
   If we are all battened down and worried and get into January and
see the world is working, I think there will be a relief rally that
could be quite substantial. Even so, I would not be surprised at
all if major market averages are within 5 percent to 10 percent of
where they are right now in six months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. But based on your asset allocation model, you far prefer
stocks over anything else. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Since July, the model has been 10 percent cash, 10 percent
bonds, 5 percent in real estate investment trusts and 75 percent in
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   I am optimistic about stocks. Even if the market stays in a
trading range, it will still be a market in which you can make
money. It is a market of stocks as opposed to being in the stock
market. It comes down to finding good earnings stories and keeping
your wits about you, particularly now. There are a number of
sectors that have been battered that next March will have stocks
that have come way up from the previous fall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What sectors do you like most? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think an opportunity has just been created in oil service
stocks, which have been absolutely hammered, from Nabors Industries
to Schlumberger.
</P>
<P>
   That is also true with some of the retailers, like Gap, which
have been knocked down a good bit on the theory that the Internet
and interest rates will kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Even in technology, there has been a lot of controversy about
Y2K creating a significant slowdown in software.
</P>
<P>
   This is a big story for next year, because as well as technology
has done, demand could actually accelerate next year. Everyone has
to have an Internet strategy, which means some infrastructure for
the Internet, not just here but globally.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks like Compuware and Oracle are selling at low multiples
comparable to their growth rates. This is an area where next March
you will be looking and will be sorry you didn't move into in late
October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
