<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV24-B     10-22 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV24-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE, DURING AND AFTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 24, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is like a war but it is not a war. It has had its beginnings
but its end is not yet in sight. Eventually there will be an
Afterward. Governance will be changed in some as-yet unforeseeable
way.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden rise of the Internet amid the telecommunications
revolution in the 1990s is for the present generation what World
War I, World War II, and Vietnam were for three earlier generations
on six continents. By that I do not mean particularily the
experience of victory or defeat (though there will be plenty of
that.) I mean an unexpected shift of previously accepted horizons;
a sequence of far-off events accelerating, coming closer and closer
to home and daily life, entailing a series of life-altering choices
by a wide array of people, especially the young: in short, a
galvanizing event. That's what it means, after all, to define a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   And a generation-defining event is what the Internet/World Wide
Web/e-commerce/dot.com story is all about. How else to account for
the increasing hysteria of press coverage of the last couple of
years, especially in the business press? A fellow here in
Massachusetts suddenly found himself worth $2.3 billion on paper
when his company, Sycamore Networks, went public. That is pretty
interesting news, no doubt about it. But it does not mean it is
going to happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   Watching school-leavers wrestle with the possibilities,
overhearing the doubts and fears of the older generation, observing
middle-aged adults fondly looking back, it is easy enough to think
along these lines. But the feeling finally crystallized for me one
day earlier this month while reading Charles Ferguson's new book
``High Stakes, No Prisoners: A Winner's Tale of Greed and Glory in
the Internet Wars.'' How to characterize it? I wondered. Where does
it fit in?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly my mind flashed back to an issue of Life magazine in
1965 or 1966, and a story about Pete Dawkins that I had read as a
young man. As an All-American football player at West Point in
1958, Dawkins had captured America's imagination. He had been
president of his class, captain of the cadet brigade, Rhodes
Scholar. And now he was in Vietnam, playing in the Big Stadium at
last.
</P>
<P>
   The war was tough, punishing work, Dawkins told his interviewer,
but he had asked for it. The tasks of nation-building were complex.
``When you are used to beef and potatos, and suddenly you're eating
pigs' intestines and pigeon beaks and fishheads _ well, anybody who
says that doesn't take some doing has a lot tougher stomach than I
do. Or else he's a bloody damn liar.'' ``Pete Dawkins Takes the
Field,'' headlined the magazine. ``He wins applause from Saigon
schoolgirls.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was all true, up to a point. But then that was the
build-up phase. There was so much more to the story of America in
Vietnam than that.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar way, Ferguson's account of how he gave up punditry
and in 1994 co-founded a company _ Vermeer Technologies _ has the
tenor of a 392-page war story. Sure enough, software to enable
individuals to create and manage Web sites was the right idea at
the right time. Twenty months later he sold the company to
Microsoft for $133 million, and its FrontPage came to be another
synonym for the Microsoft approach to the marketplace: bundled with
its Office suite, denounced by critics as an ``evil'' program for
its propensity to handcuff users and exclude competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson is a lively writer, a peripatetic guide to everything
from restaurants to painters. He provides a terrific inside account
of the journey from inspiration to start-up to IPO to takeover
target and life afterward in Berkeley and Silicon Valley. He is a
fascinating witness to the battle between Netscape and Microsoft in
the years between 1994 and 1997, the rough tactics employed, and
there are asides on nearly every business that touched his own,
including the administration of the Justice Department (though
current antitrust chief Joel Klein doesn't make the index.) For Net
buffs, the book is a fascinating read _ about as interesting as
Dawkins' story (today he is a top manager at Citigroup.)
</P>
<P>
   But the book is an account by a participant in a particular,
relatively early battle; it is so much more narrow than the war
itself. Nor does Ferguson go to the heart of what is important
about membership in his generation. You have to see a generation
unfolding in time. Historians are still trying to see whole the
sprawling action of World War II, for example.
</P>
<P>
   And Vietnam unfolded in Washington, New York, Paris, Moscow and
Beijing as well as Saigon and Hanoi, enfolding not just soldiers
like Dawkins, but resisters, politicians, diplomats, business
executives, newspeople and such _ not to mention the 50 million
Vietnamese at the center of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a generation must have its makers. No less than soldiers do
entrepreneurs like to put themselves at the center of events.
Historian Robert Wohl, author of ``The Generation of 1914,'' has
written that a historical generation is not defined by
chronological time or borders alone. ``It is not a zone of dates;
nor is it an army of contemporaries making its way across a
territory of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more like a magnetic field at the center of which lies
an experience or a series of experiences. It is a system of
references and identifications that gives priority to some kinds of
experiences and devalues others _ hence it is relatively
independent of age. The chronological center of this experiencial
field need not be stable; it may shift with time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is essential to the formation of a generational
consciousness is some common frame of reference that provides a
sense of rupture with the past and that will later distinguish the
members of the generation from those who follow them in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the clearest formulation ever made of this
include-me-in/include-you-out principle is the wonderful speech
that Shakespeare put in the mouth of King Henry IV on the eve of
the battle of Agincourt in 1415. No anniversary of the battle would
ever pass, Harry told his troops:
</P>
<P>
   ``From this day to the ending of the world,
</P>
<P>
   But we in it shall be remembered;
</P>
<P>
   We few, we happy few, we band of brothers;
</P>
<P>
   For he that sheds his blood with me
</P>
<P>
   Shall be my brother; be he ne'er so vile
</P>
<P>
   This day shall gentle his condition;
</P>
<P>
   And gentlemen in England now a-bed
</P>
<P>
   Shall think themselves accursed they were not here,
</P>
<P>
   And hold their manhoods cheap whiles any speaks
</P>
<P>
   That fought with us on Saint Crispin's day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohl argues that such frames of references must derive from
great historical events _ wars, revolutions, plagues, famines and
economic crises. Only historical events can supply ``the markers
and signposts with which people impose order on their past and link
their individual fates with those of the communities in which they
live,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But what if there is no war? I have long thought of the years
around 1980 as one kind of a watershed (Paul Volcker, Margaret
Thatcher, Ronald Reagan, Deng Xiaoping, Lech Walesa, Pope John Paul
II); of 1989 (the fall of the Berlin Wall) as another: optimism and
pessimism about the possibilities of government and all that. But
more than either of those events, this Internet thing implies a
Before, During and After. A land rush, yes, but not just any land
rush. Probably not since voyages to the New World has there been
anything quite like this removal from one place to another.
</P>
<P>
   One sure thing: like a war, the current mania will end. I had a
friend years ago who worked for Newsweek magazine in Saigon. He
kept track of the war by framing the cover stories on which he
worked over 15 years. There must have been a couple dozen covers on
his wall before he died. There have been no more than another dozen
Vietnam cover stories in all the years since then. The last one was
a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
