<HEADER>
A5488 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SOLDIERS-BOS &LR;      10-22 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SOLDIERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROOPS IN CHECHNYA SENSE PERIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELKOVSKOYE, Russia _ From his hastily dug trench, Russian
paratrooper Ruslan Tashbaltayev aimed his machine gun across a
pasture in northern Chechnya to guard against Islamic militants
attacking his unit from the north. In another trench 200 yards
away, Sergeant Mikhail Bulgakin watched warily for rebel fighters
who might sneak across the Terek River from the south.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military says it controls this part of Chechnya, but
from the point of view of these soldiers, the question is who is
surrounding whom.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby town of Shelkovskoye, angry villagers described
the hardships that arrived along with Russian troops two weeks ago:
detentions, beatings, civilian deaths, tight restrictions on travel
out of town, and a sundown-to-sunrise curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Russian leaders say the people here were happy when Russian
troops ``liberated'' this and 33 other villages from Chechen
rebels. But as one Shelkovskoye resident put it, ``This is a
concentration camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian warplanes and artillery are battering rebel-controlled
territory in Chechnya's mountainous south with daily bombardments.
On Thursday, rockets slammed into the Chechen capital, Grozny,
killing at least 143 people at a central market, according to the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The prarie land north of the Terek River is supposed to be the
success story. Moscow says it has restored order here, with the
hearty support of the local population.
</P>
<P>
   But on the ground in northern Chechnya on Wednesday, it did not
look that way. The campaign to restore Moscow's rule over the
region, autonomous since Russian troops withdrew after a disastrous
1994-1996 war, appeared to be stalled in a quagmire of violence and
mutual mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the problem is that the Russians, who say their
campaign is aimed at ``eliminating Islamic terrorists'' it blames
for a series of bomb attacks in Moscow and southern Russia, have
not figured out how to distinguish their enemies from peaceful
citizens, and often treat them the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens, many of whom abhor the violent anarchy brought on
their homeland by rival warlords during three years of virtual
independence, have an even deeper hatred of the Russians for the
senseless brutality of the last war, in which tens of thousands of
civilians died in indiscrimate air and artillery attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, the Kremlin's
presidential hopeful whose popularity has skyrocketed over his
leadership of the Chechnya campaign, said Moscow has learned from
its mistakes. Putin, who travelled to the combat zone Wednesday,
repeated his pledge not to storm Grozny and promised to restore
schools, hospitals, gas, and pensions, services that many
communities have gone without for three years. Speaking to
reporters in a barracks at a heavily guarded Russian military base
after the visit, Putin declared the operation a success so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleasantly surprised that the first thing they asked me
was, 'You won't leave us, will you?' '' Putin said after meeting
with Chechen villagers during a brief stop in the village of
Znamenskoye, 30 miles northwest of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Putin did not take journalists with him. Instead, Russian army
Lieutenant General Gennady Troshev piled a group of Western
reporters, the first to travel to Russian-occupied Chechnya since
Russian forces invaded this month, into four military helicopters
and flew them at treetop-level to a well-guarded field near
Shelkovskoye, a town of 8,000 some 30 miles northeast of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not hear one negative word about the federal
troops,'' Troshev said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the reporters appeared in Shelkovskoye, escorted by an
armored column and heavily armed troops, the villagers had nothing
positive to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moscow is full of pigs,'' said Nazhmuddin Mirzayev, a police
officer in Shelkovskoye, his words punctuated by the far-off rumble
of Russian artillery. ``The Russians do not say an honest word.
They bomb us, and no one answers for their tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirzayev described a recent tank attack on a bus carrying
refugees from the bombardment in Grozny. He produced the driver,
Adam Madagov, who said 15 women and children had died.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the villagers said they wanted nothing to do with the
Islamic radicals, and some, partially confirming Putin's theory,
said they would accept Russian rule in return for a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   But no one found the current situation normal. The lights and
gas are not on yet. Villagers need a pass to travel out of town to
tend their garden plots. The Russians bring the villagers shipments
of humanitarian aid, but they also conduct constant searches for
terrorists that the villagers find oppressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit at home all day as if we are in a cell, as if we are
animals,'' said Geberto Epserkhanov, who said his son was detained
and beaten by Russian paramilitary police because ``they didn't
like his face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Much more of this and we will go over to the other side and
start fighting the Russians,'' said one man who refused to give his
name.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with these comments, Troshev, evidently surprised to
see things going so badly, brusquely told a reporter to ``stop
making these things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders said their forces would stay out of the
villages if the residents kept the rebels out. A Russian officer
said many of the villagers pretended to be peaceful citizens during
the day, only to launch hit-and-run attacks at night. He also said
Chechens had been terrorizing the 500 ethnic Russians living in the
village.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are all so peaceful, who is killing our soldiers on
patrol at night?,'' the officer said. ``Who is killing our people?
We are not foreigners here. This is our country, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders have not acknowledged any losses in the town.
But they are also not taking any chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know where the enemy might attack from,'' said
Tashbaltayev, the paratrooper in the unit dug in outside of town.
``They are using the tactics of jackals, hiding and running around
in small groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems faced by this unit epitomize the dilemma posed by
the Russian strategy of setting up a defensive perimeter on the
Terek to prevent the militants from attacking Russian regions
outside of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they stay in defensive positions north of Grozny, they will
increasingly become targets of Chechen hit-and-run attacks,''
defense analyst Pavel Felgenhauer wrote in The Moscow Times this
week. ``If the Russian troops go further south, they will get
embroiled in bloody battles with resolute rebel forces.''
</P>
<P>
   To imagine what those would look like, all one needs to do is
travel to Novolakskoye, a mountain hamlet just over the border from
Chechnya in the Russian region of Dagestan, where Chechen-led
militants invaded last month. Federal troops drove them out, but
lost dozens of men and destroyed the village. Few homes are intact,
administration buildings are gutted, even the local cemetary was
ruined. With winter on the way, villagers wonder how they will
survive in the ruins of their houses. Promised federal aid has yet
to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one here was happy to see the (militants) come,'' said
Gadzhi, a a muscular local policeman toting a machine gun. ``But no
one is happy with the way we have been treated since the army
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Felgenhauer's solution is for Russia to find a face-saving way
to negotiate a peace deal with Chechnya's president, Aslan
Maskhadov, and retreat. Putin made it clear that he will not be
following that advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave Chechnya three years of virtual independence,'' Putin
said, ``and the president lost control of the situation within
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops have closed in to between three and 10 miles of
Grozny, according to conflicting reports. Whatever the actual
distance, it is close enough for Russian forces to shell and pour
rockets into the city.
</P>
<P>
   Already, more than 170,000 people have fled the bombardments,
which the Chechens said are indiscriminately killing civilians.
Russian generals originally denied that claim, but faced with
reporters who have witnessed the damage, Russian cabinet ministers
Wednesday acknowledged civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what do you want us to do, warn them in advance, `Dear
citizens, we are going to bomb this area, please go away?' '' said
Russia's information minister, Mikhail Lesin. ``The Chechens did
not warn anyone before they blew up apartments in Moscow and killed
200 people? How can you question our attitude toward these
people?''
</P>
<P>
   But how do the Russians pick out suspected terrorists from among
the peaceful population? Said government spokesman Andrei Korotkov:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no ready answer to this question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
