<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Poetry may be italicized) 
(af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Old-Line Business Group Is Trying to Play Catch-Up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 65-year-old Business Council, an exclusive club of 100
big-company chief executives like John F. Smith Jr. of General
Motors and John F. Welch Jr. of General Electric, has been showing
its age. Despite its reputation for legendary speakers and
deal-making opportunities at its thrice-yearly meetings, some
chiefs from the fastest-moving sectors of the economy, including
Bill Gates and Michael D. Eisner, have declined to join.
</P>
<P>
   But the Business Council is trying to catch up with the times,
as the two-day meeting beginning on Wednesday evening will show. On
the scene in Boca Raton, Fla. _ a switch from Colonial
Williamsburg, the site since 1992 _ will be two new-economy members
who have joined in the last year, Scott McNealy of Sun Microsystems
and John Chambers of Cisco Systems. Michael Dell became a member in
May but won't attend this week.
</P>
<P>
   The program includes old standbys like Alan Greenspan and Bill
Bradley, but with the Internet as the main focus, some speakers
will be decidedly younger. Four teen-agers will expound to their
elders on ``Growing Up Digital'' in a panel led by Don Tapscott,
who wrote a book by that name and is chairman of the Alliance for
Converging Technologies in Toronto. Mary Meeker, the Internet
analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, will moderate a discussion
among four E-commerce chief executives whose names, even now, would
never make the member list.
</P>
<P>
   There is buzz, too, among some members that the membership
committee may extend an invitation to Hewlett-Packard's Carleton S.
Fiorina, who during the summer became the first woman to be named
chief executive of a company in the Dow Jones industrials. If she
joins, she would be right behind Crandall Close Bowles, the chief
executive of Springs Industries, who became the group's first
female member a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and Bill Gates will be there, too _ not as a member,
but as a Friday morning speaker.
</P>
<P>
   _Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catering to Wall Street &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Martha Stewart, even a stock certificate, issued for the
initial public offering last Wednesday of Martha Stewart Living
Omnimedia, must have just the right, homey touch. Known for what
some call attention to detail, and others call obsessive control,
she had the stock certificate designed in-house.
</P>
<P>
   She also served 3,000 breakfasts, including brioches filled with
eggs and herbs, from a white tent, decorated with autumn leaves,
outside the New York Stock Exchange. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Venture Capital Crooning &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Timothy C. Draper's efforts to ingratiate himself in New York
last week offer any evidence, transplanting the Silicon Valley
ethos even to the financially fertile soil of Manhattan will yield
an uncertain harvest. To celebrate plans for his Draper Fisher
Jurvetson venture capital firm to open a New York branch, he got
the crowd at a New York Venture Group breakfast to sing along with
the words he handed out to ``New York, New York.'' His last two
verses:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll build a new brand
</P>
<P>
   Some Web-based hot app
</P>
<P>
   Throw in some viral marketing
</P>
<P>
   And it's a wrap.
</P>
<P>
   If we can leave no doubt
</P>
<P>
   IPO take it out
</P>
<P>
   We'll all get rich!
</P>
<P>
   The In-ter-net.''
</P>
<P>
   When his quavering off-key croaking was done, the critics
pounced. ``We hope you didn't come to New York for a Broadway
career,'' one questioner said.
</P>
<P>
   Draper, having said that New York's legal, financial and media
businesses were headed for extinction, and that the Internet was a
better long-term growth play than any other organized religion, for
once turned modest. ``I'll keep my day job,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
