<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ATTACK-DENIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW FLIP-FLIPS ON MISSILE ATTACK AS TOLL RISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ So much for the streamlined new propaganda machine
Russia created to tell its side of the campaign against Islamic
rebels in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   As the death toll Friday climbed to 143 from the powerful
explosions that rocked a crowded market in Chechnya's capital,
Grozny, Russian officials repeatedly contradicted themselves over
whether their forces were responsible.
</P>
<P>
   In a sequence that would have been comical if not for the tragic
context, Russian officials first denied involvement in the attack,
the worst in Grozny since fighting erupted three weeks ago. Then,
as incontrovertible evidence mounted, they admitted it.
</P>
<P>
   Then they blamed the bombing on rival Chechen gangs.
</P>
<P>
   The string of confirmations and denials strained Russia's
already dubious credibility about its operation in the Caucasus at
a most inopportune time.
</P>
<P>
   Friday in Helsinki, Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin tried
to assuage Western leaders' concerns about reports of
indiscriminate violence in what Moscow calls a campaign to wipe out
Islamic militants based in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Russia blames the militants for two attacks on a southern
Russian region and for a series of blasts this summer that killed
nearly 300 people. The militants deny involvement in the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Chechnya's separatist government and journalists in
Grozny said up to 10 missiles slammed into the market and other
parts of the war-devastated capital, killing 143, according to the
Chechen Health Ministry. Some 300 were wounded, and thousands more,
fearing new attacks, fled, joining 184,000 refugees from three
weeks of Russian airstrikes and artillery attacks on Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Video footage from Grozny showed the shattered stalls of the
wrecked marketplace, splinters of wood, twisted metal, and dried
pools of blood. Chechens displayed chunks of metal etched with
military-style serial numbers, supporting their claim that the
projectiles were surface-to-surface missiles fired by Russian
forces advancing on Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that this was a surface-to-surface rocket,''
independent defense analyst Pavel Felgenhauer said Friday. He said
the missiles were probably launched from a radio-controlled system
that can be accurate from as far as 40 miles away. Russian forces
have advanced to within 3 to 10 miles of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military immediately denied that claim soon after
the attack, which occured some time after 5 p.m. Thursday. But
Friday, Russian military spokesman Alexander Veklich said the
attack was a ``special operation'' to destroy an arms bazaar
Russian intelligence had discovered at the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Civilians don't walk at nighttime in a place where arms are
sold to bandits and terrorists, they sit at home,'' Veklich added
in remarks shown on Russian NTV television. ``Those hit in the
attack were arms peddlers supplying bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, weapons, which most Chechen men own, were sold at one
part of the market. But vendors there mostly sell food, clothing,
and household items.
</P>
<P>
   News agencies reported dozens of civilian victims, including
many women and children, at the marketplace and in Grozny
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials changed their story again. Domestic
intelligence chief Nikolai Patrushev described the blast as an
inadvertent explosion of munitions hidden at the market by the
militants. Patrushev is hardly credible in Russia; the last time he
appeared in public, it was to explain that his agents had faked a
bomb scare in a Russian city to see how citizens would react. They
were terrified.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Mikhailov, codirector of the Russian agency set up to
avoid this kind of confusion over Moscow's official line on
Chechnya, said he was ``70 percent certain'' that the blast was
caused by rebels who wanted to stir up Chechens and attract more
fighters for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Putin seemed to agree with Mikhailov, suggesting rival Chechen
gangs may have caused the Grozny explosions. He also denied any
Russian involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the maze of denials may be in the military's initial
denial that airstrikes were carried out against Grozny on Thursday.
Felgenhauer noted that the generals did not deny launching a
missile attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
