<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-WOES-BOS &LR;      10-22 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-WOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADERS FACE TALL TASK  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA _ ``Merdeka'' means freedom in Indonesian, and it is
arguably the most emotionally powerful word in the language,
chanted by crowds with raised fists and sang in patriotic anthems.
</P>
<P>
   It was long a touchstone of the battle against Dutch colonialism
in 1945, but for most of the population too young to remember that,
it now stands for the end of 32 years of corrupt, autocratic rule _
a new ``merdeka'' that began Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year and a half ago, Indonesia was ruled by an entrenched
former general who brooked no dissent, and it seemed inconceivable
that three leaders of the largely impotent opposition could ever
ascend to power. But this week they did, and now they face the task
of transforming this wounded and fractious nation of 210 million
people into a working democracy _ the world's third largest.
</P>
<P>
   Many Indonesians were still pinching themselves Friday, giddy
with disbelief that they finally got what they wanted: Moderate
Muslim cleric Abdurrahman Wahid and nationalist Megawati
Sukarnoputri are president and vice president. Muslim leader Amien
Rais, a firebrand who whipped up student protesters last year, is
speaker of the assembly, the third-highest post.
</P>
<P>
   None of this guarantees peace and quiet or a stable future. The
current honeymoon period will end, but the basic needs of the
nation will need to be addressed: an administration cleansed of
corruption; a restructured and equitable economy; civilian
political control over the military; ethnic, religious, and
regional harmony; and national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   How well old friends Wahid and Megawati work together and whom
they include in their cabinet will be major determinants of
Indonesia's delicate transition to democracy. They won election
after the candidates of the long-ruling Golkar party and the
military withdrew, and the new government will be expected to repay
that gesture by giving members of the old regime key cabinet
positions, which they could use to slow reform.
</P>
<P>
   It also remains to be seen how patient their supporters will be.
The ouster of former president Suharto could never have happened
without pressure from students and urban masses who crippled the
nation with desperate street protests. And it was the violent
demonstrations after Megawati lost the top job to Wahid that helped
pressure the national assembly to award her the vice presidency as
a consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it was the masses who set the pace for Indonesia's
convulsive transition out of authoritarian rule, and they are
likely to rise up again if they are unhappy with the result. The
first democratically elected parliament in four decades fast
discovered this week that it cannot ignore the ``parliament of the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People were very disappointed _ you saw the trouble when
Megawati didn't win the presidency,'' said police Sergeant Hadi
Wahono, 22, who was standing guard at an intersection where riots
had broken out. Like the other half-million members of the armed
forces and police, Wahono was prohibited by law from voting in
parliamentary elections last June, but he said ``the military and
police want a vice president and president that are good for the
people. So if everyone likes her, we like her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesians don't like the military in politics anymore,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Such words from a uniformed officer would have been unimaginable
when Suharto, a former military man, ruled with an iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where the military has long wielded unquestioned
power, it was equally unexpected when armed forces chief General
Wiranto suddenly withdrew from the race for vice president. One
Western diplomat with sources in the military said Wiranto's move
was less a matter of grace than of pressure by political parties
who vowed to hand him a humiliating loss if he tried to claim a top
civilian post for the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know what to expect from Wahid, a Muslim cleric,
or Megawati, a former housewife whose popularity derives from her
father, Indonesia's founding president Sukarno. Neither has held
elected office before. And neither has offered a plan for
addressing the monetary crisis, separatist violence, or the loss of
confidence in government that underlies the tension.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has said he wants reconciliation, and though he said in an
interview four months ago that he would form a committee to decide
how to deal with the widespread corruption under ousted president
Suharto, he added tellingly, ``We have to repent and forgive him. I
think the people will listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wahid is a moral signpost for at least 35 million
Muslims in his religious organization, a forgive-and-forget
approach is unlikely to satisfy the majority of Indonesians who
resent the Suharto clan enriching itself at the public trough while
millions survived on a few hundred dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   Another unknown is how the two leaders will deal with the former
ruling part ,and the newly potent Islamic bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia is 88 percent Muslim, but Wahid has said religion
should be separate from the state. That has eased concerns among
Christians, Hindus and secular Muslims, but he will have to fight
to bring along Islamic conservatives in parliament, many of whom
voted against Megawati because she is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Dari, the armed forces chief under Sukarno who was
imprisoned for 29 years under Suharto, said the Wahid/Megawati
combination will be a potent one, because both are resonant moral
symbols for different segments of society _ religious Muslims on
one hand and populist, secular nationalists on the other. Moral
force may be exactly what Indonesians are looking for after decades
of rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Dari said he told Megawati that the ``problem for Indonesia is
trust. We have an economic crisis and a crisis of confidence. For
the economic crisis, you have so many PhD's who can solve it. But
for the confidence crisis, it is personal. And you are the one who
has the trust of the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
