<HEADER>
A5500 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-(TRIMS     10-22 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS ANNOUNCE PLAN TO CUT SPENDING; VETO EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ohio)  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in Congress announced a plan
Friday to reduce government spending across the board by 1.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts, a total of $4.5 billion below the amounts Congress has
already specified for federal departments and agencies in the
current fiscal year, would apply to every government program for
which the lawmakers control the annual financing _ from farm
subsidies to highway construction to the purchase of warplanes _
although not to benefit programs like Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders said the plan, which is sure to draw a
presidential veto, would allow them to approve a budget without tax
increases and without dipping into Social Security reserves. At a
rally on the Capitol lawn, they said all the cuts would come from
what they called ``waste, fraud and abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in good budgets, there is still some wasteful spending,''
said Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House Republican whip. ``If the
president doesn't like this plan, maybe he ought to show us his.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, President Clinton's budget director, said that the
president's plan was the budget he sent Congress in January and
that the Republican plan was irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``An across-the-board cut makes no sense at all,'' Lew said in
an interview. ``It would take every priority and reduce it equally
_ important public health programs, education, public safety,
critical defense needs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make choices,'' Lew added. ``That's what governing
is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the new Republican plan was announced only by leaders
of the House of Representatives, Senate leaders have accepted it,
said John Czwartacki, the spokesman for the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said they would attach the omnibus spending cut
to the final spending bill to go through Congress, the measure to
provide financing for the Departments of Labor, Education, and
Health and Human Services, and for the District of Columbia. They
said the House would approve the bill and send it to the president
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is considered certain to veto the bill not just because
he opposes the spending cuts but also because it does not include
money he requested for 100,000 new teachers in public schools
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to veto two spending bills Congress sent him this
week, one for the Interior Department and cultural agencies, the
other for the Departments of Commerce, State and Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Lew was at the Capitol Friday to meet with the top lawmakers of
the committees that deal with spending measures. Both sides said
later that the meetings had been cordial but that no tangible
progress had been made in resolving the many differences. The
meetings are to resume on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican plan, each department and agency would be
responsible for deciding how to apply the spending cut. At the
Defense Department, where the budget is about $260 billion, a 1.4
percent cut would amount to $3.6 billion. At the National
Institutes of Health, with a budget of about $15 billion, the cut
would be about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Office of Management and Budget calculated that if the
cuts were applied equally within departments as well as among them,
the effects would include a lack of a full complement of
immunizations among 4,700 children and a loss of 154 agents at the
FBI and 164 agents at the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said those kinds of calculations were preposterous.
Some agencies might decide to lay off workers, they said, while
others might decide to trim purchases or limit travel.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said the departments and agencies would be subjected to
the kind of budgetary discipline that every successful business
applies.
</P>
<P>
   One item that will not be affected is the $4,600 congressional
pay increase that Congress approved in July, raising senators' and
representatives' salaries by 3.4 percent, to $141,300. In budget
terminology, this falls into the category of mandatory and not
discretionary spending.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All in all, this was not a day on which the hot political
oratory over the budget showed any sign of abating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats continue to fight us all the way, because they
want to increase spending,'' DeLay declared.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Joe Lockhart, the president's press
secretary, questioned whether DeLay was ``speaking for himself, or
whether the strategy of bringing the Democrats to their knees is
the strategy of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is ``the overall guiding principle of the Republicans,''
Lockhart said, ``this is going to be a long, tough battle.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Democrats took issue with the Republicans' contention that their
plan would not tap into Social Security reserves. The numbers came
out that way, Democrats said, only because Republicans jury-rigged
the books so that billions of dollars in spending would be shifted
into the next fiscal year, and because they used an accounting
device that ordered the Congressional Budget Office to use its own
spending and revenue estimates in some cases, and Office of
Management and Budget estimates in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting device, called directed scorekeeping, allowed
Republicans to show $18 billion less in spending than they would
have otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   But after years of taking beatings from Democrats on Social
Security, Republicans say they have managed at least to neutralize
the issue with their recently adopted principle that none of the
money raised in Social Security taxes should be used for other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion polls show that Republicans may have gained slightly
with respect to the issue. In a national poll last week, the Gallup
Organization asked people whether they had more faith in Clinton or
in Republicans in Congress ``to act responsibly with the government
funds set aside for Social Security benefits.'' Fifty percent said
they trusted the president more, and 41 percent answered
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In August, in answer to a slightly different question before
Republicans began their current offensive, 52 percent said they had
more confidence in the president to handle Social Security, and 35
percent sided with the Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-FANS-     10-22 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUNCING THOSE HATEFUL YANKEES WITH POLITENESS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even within Atlanta's gauzy fantasy of itself as the
chivalrous competitor, far too polite to pour beer on an enemy fan,
there is room for a dream of serial slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the possibility of vanquishing not just one but two
New York baseball teams in a single October, including one with the
name that represents everything Atlanta seems to recall hating, the
city is becoming almost bloodthirsty as the World Series nears its
opening here on Saturday night. In an entirely genteel and courtly
way, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution is offering its readers a
series of posters showing a Braves tomahawk firmly embedded in a
New York apple. There is no apple juice luridly dripping from the
wound, however, and the poster slogans are a bit less than
incendiary: ``N.Y., N.Y., One to Go,'' ``Kiss Our Grits,'' and the
inevitable ``Yankees, Go Home.''
</P>
<P>
   The local sports radio station has urged listeners to call in
and unburden themselves of their bitterness toward New York City.
There were complaints about the unimaginable rudeness of New York
fans in the recent Mets playoff, and a few bad memories of Jim
Leyritz's home run in Game 4 of the 1996 World Series that sparked
an eventual Yankee victory over the Braves. But the most vociferous
listener called in to rail against Billy Joel.
</P>
<P>
   This World Series has brought out a peculiar and often
conflicting set of emotions in Atlanta. There is, without question,
a deep-rooted resentment here against New York and the Yankees and
the cultural domination for which they stand, and a thirst to
finally crush the century's leading baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   A few extremists, including Gov. Roy Barnes and Mayor Bill
Campbell, have even invoked the Civil War, challenging their
counterparts in New York to put a Braves hat and jersey on the
statue of Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman in Grand Army Plaza for
every series game the Braves win. (Their concessionary offer hardly
seems equivalent, however: Yankees garb on the statue of former
President Jimmy Carter at the State Capitol.) Late Friday, Gov.
George E. Pataki rejected the offer as disrespectful.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta seems reluctant to let loose its long-buried primal
scream of frustration against New York, to admit that it is
annoying to hear Don Imus describe Atlantans as a bunch of
``redneck goobers,'' as he did on his radio program Friday morning.
Fans would rather trill their Indian doom chant and wave their red
tomahawks than boo or curse or discuss the genealogy of New York
players. Doing so would lower Atlanta to the raw, unwashed level of
a Yankee bleacher creature, which is one of the primary reasons for
hating New York in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fairly passive sports town,'' said Stephen Shapiro,
known to all as ``Steak,'' who as president and afternoon host of
the Sportstalk 790 AM radio station here has taken daily abuse from
Imus in a staged bit of North-South shtick. ``People don't get as
emotional about baseball, because they see it as entertainment. You
go to Yankee Stadium and it is really hard-core. You go to Turner
Field and it's this family-friendly Southern entertainment. It's
not a jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is not a traditional Southern city, of course, though it
can legitimately claim to be the capital of the South. There is
nothing sleepy or slow-paced about it, and its individual residents
are no more or less friendly than people in St. Louis or Denver or
Cleveland. But as a group, people in the region seem more relaxed
about their entertainment than in the North, more aware that even
college football _ a far more dominant local pastime _ is basically
just a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be those kinds of fans,'' said Thomas Cook, a
local defense lawyer with Braves season tickets. ``You can come
here and wear a Mets or Yankees cap and not worry about getting
soaked with beer. I mean, those guys up north will boo their own
team if they get mad at something. Down here, that would never
happen. We would just sit still.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not imply a lack of support for the team. Both the
Braves and the Yankees had among the best attendance figures in
Major League Baseball this year, with the Yankees, in third place
in attendance at 3,292,343, barely edging the Braves, in fourth
place at 3,284,897. But that easygoing relationship with the team,
combined with a record so successful during the decade that winning
seems routine, has led to a few anomalies, like the large blocks of
empty seats at Turner Field during the early games of the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just aren't going to inconvenience themselves
for a 4 p.m. playoff game, because we've had so many,'' said Rick
Beard, a Braves fan who is executive director of the Atlanta
History Center. ``If they have to drive back into traffic after
work on a Tuesday night, they might not do it if they can watch on
TV. I don't want to say they're fair-weather fans, but if the
Braves ever stop being successful, it will be interesting to see
what happens to their fan base.''
</P>
<P>
   In unguarded moments, a few fans will admit they actually hold
the Yankees in a kind of secret awe, as the original template for
the year-after-year success the Braves have had this decade.
Beating the Cleveland Indians in the 1995 World Series was
pleasant, but the matchup did not hold the power of these two
teams. A few Braves players may have infuriated Mets fans with
derisive comments during the National League championship, but
there has been no such disrespect in the leadup to the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are what baseball is all about,'' said Manuel
Maloof, a well-known retired politician who owns Manuel's Tavern,
for years the saloon of choice for many elected officials,
journalists and police officers. ``Anytime you play them, anytime
you have a chance to beat them, well, that's the biggest thing
there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people remember with some fondness that Joe Torre's
brother, Frank, played first base for the old Triple-A Atlanta
Crackers and that Joe Torre played for and managed the Braves many
years before he took over the Yankees. Many other people are still
a bit shell-shocked when they recall how the Yankees lost the first
two games of the 1996 Series to Atlanta, and then went on to win
the next four.
</P>
<P>
   Robert McDuffie, the concert violinist, who is such a fervent
Braves enthusiast that former Gov. Zell Miller gave him Bobby Cox's
old warmup jacket, said Atlanta was grasping for a moment of
national validation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta has its set of insecurities, and it very much wants to
be taken seriously,'' said McDuffie, a Macon native who now lives
on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. ``People are tired of those
jokes about how the best restaurant in Atlanta is Hooters. To beat
the Yankees, finally, would be the ultimate act of
one-upsmanship.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
