<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHER DECIDES TO DESTROY BIOGRAPHY OF GOVERNOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: A longer version of this story will move as a 1STLD by 9:45
p.m. ET.) 
(th) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ St. Martin's Press, the publisher of a controversial
biography of George W. Bush, took the ultimate step to kill the
disputed book Friday, issuing an alert to the nation's booksellers
to return thousands of copies for destruction by shredding or
burning because they no longer trust the author.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the publishing house announced the recall of the
books just hours after receiving the results of a company inquiry
and a private detective's report that it said matched photographs
of the book's author, J.H. Hatfield, with a criminal mug shot of a
felon convicted of hiring a hit man 11 years ago to murder his
boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're heat, furnace fodder,'' Sally Richardson, the
president and publisher of St. Martin's trade division, said of the
books. The publishing house this month had shipped out more than
70,000 copies of Hatfield's ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and the
Making of an American President.''
</P>
<P>
   Such recalls are rare in the publishing industry, but this one
came in a season when other companies were forced to pull books
because of shattered trust _ from an author accused of making up a
Holocaust identity to a biographer who simply plagiarized the words
of other books. The incidents have raised questions about the
industry's ability to serve as a literary gatekeeper in screening
out unsavory or dishonest authors.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield's 368-page book included claims from anonymous sources
that Bush _ the Texas governor and leading contender for the
Republican presidential nomination _ was arrested in 1972 on
cocaine possession charges that were later expunged from the record
by a judge as a favor to Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   In statements Friday, St. Martin's executives did not take issue
specifically with the disclosures, which have been denied by the
Bush family, but instead said they no longer consider the author
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be sure what else he lied to us about or to the
attorney who did the legal review of the book,'' said David Kaye,
the general counsel for St. Martin's Press. ``Therefore we can't
continue to trust what he told us.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press, housed in the Flatiron Building, is a
publisher of popular books, and is a division of Verlagsgruppe
Georg von Holtzbrinck, which also owns the literary publishing
houses of Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux and Henry Holt. Earlier this
year, St. Martin's published Monica Lewinsky's tale of broken
presidential romance after other top publishers had publicly
scorned the title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0246 </DOCNO>
