<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SEND IN MORE CLOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK RICH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no faster way for a politician to offend PC
sensibilities on the left than to attack gun control and
affirmative action. There's no faster way to offend PC
sensibilities on the right than to defend flag-burning and gays in
the military. What major politician would dare offend the left and
right? As far as I can determine there's just one, Jesse Ventura,
who in his notorious interview in Playboy not only took all these
positions but further riled the entire political spectrum by
dismissing Tailhook as ``much ado about nothing'' and religion as
``a crutch for weak-minded people.'' Then he mocked the single
largest bipartisan constituency in the country _ the overweight.
The only way he could have topped that would have been to call for
the mandatory spaying of household pets.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Minnesota governor has been declared dead by the same
seers who failed to predict his election in the first place (and
who also failed to notice that most of his bombshells were public
well before the Playboy interview, in his best seller, ``I Ain't
Got Time to Bleed.'') It was duly noted that the governor's
approval rating dropped 19 points after the feeding frenzy (though
no one added that, at 54 percent, his number is indistinguishable
from Bill Bradley's or Al Gore's). ``His national star has dimmed
considerably,'' concluded Newsweek this week, in reporting that
Ventura had promised (none too convincingly) to muzzle himself.
``He's a joke,'' said Eleanor Clift on CNN. ``He sounds like a
wacko,'' echoed Steve Roberts of U.S. News &AMP; World Report. And so
slams down the iron curtain of Washington's conventional wisdom:
The Ventura fracas is just another diversion in 1999's celebrity
circus of politics, another manifestation of what ``Nightline''
calls the ``silly season'' and a Wall Street Journal headline
upbraids as ``defining politics down.''
</P>
<P>
   But silly may be in the eye of the beholder. Yes, the brawl
shaping up between Pat Buchanan and Donald Trump over the Reform
Party's presidential ticket (and its $12.6 million in federal
campaign funds) is a sideshow likely to relegate its Pyrrhic victor
to the political fringe. And yes, Ventura's own political future,
which will be tied to his still-embryonic (and so far mixed) record
as governor, is far from certain. Yet for some of us there's a
lift, even hope, in watching Ventura function as a bull in the
china shop of a stultifying campaign culture. The silly season we
should really worry about as we head into 2000 is not that of the
governor's effronteries, or of the Reform Party melee, or of Warren
Beatty's pleas for the down-and-out from a ballroom in Beverly
Hills, or of barely rumored candidacies that the media miraculously
inflate into 48-hour talkfests (Cybill Shepherd, Arnold
Schwarzenegger, Jerry Springer, Oprah). The real silly season is
the one to which the supposedly grown-up, professional politicians
are subjecting us day after day.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find a major candidate in either party who will
risk offending anyone by uttering an unscripted remark, countering
an ideological orthodoxy or choosing a wardrobe that might not sit
well with a pollster or focus group. Seventy-five years after the
Scopes trial, even evolution is too hot an issue for most of them
to handle. The apotheosis of this cautious vacuousness _ the
ultimate un-Ventura _ was Elizabeth Dole, who mercifully dropped
out of the Republican race this week. In running what she kept
describing as a campaign of ``substance,'' she took no-holds-barred
stands in favor of ``promoting integrity in government'' and
against illegal drugs. Her one fledgling attempt to challenge her
party's pieties, a call for modest gun control, was followed by a
headlong retreat into I Am Woman, I Won't Roar. Even after she
withdrew on Wednesday, blaming George W. Bush's daunting lead in
the money race for her demise, she couldn't muster a strong (or
even coherent) stand on campaign finance reform when invited to do
so by Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bush is any gutsier. ``Compassionate conservatism'' is
a slogan that, simply translated, means: I'm in favor of charity,
and I'm not Newt Gingrich. But who is Bush? He couldn't bring
himself to help usher the isolationist and Jew-baiting Pat Buchanan
out of the G.O.P. When Bush gave a speech that seemed to stand up
bravely to his party's hard right by spanking Robert Bork, it
turned out that what many saw as a damning reference to Bork's
best-selling screed, ``Slouching Towards Gomorrah,'' was
inadvertent. (``He may not even have realized he was referring to a
book,'' cracked Bork of Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
