<HEADER>
A5527 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS &LR;      10-22 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORRIS STANDS UP TO TYSON BLUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson says he knows why he's at the MGM Grand
Garden Arena Saturday night,
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bringing the pain, baby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Orlin Norris knows why he's at the MGM Grand Garden, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they thought I was a good, safe opponent for Mike, but
I'm not,'' the former WBA cruiserweight champion said of Saturday
night's ``Late Night With Mike Show'' on Showtime. ``I'm a good
fighter, a thinking fighter, a smart fighter who isn't afraid of
Mike Tyson or anyone else. I'm nobody's pushover. He said he's
going to bring the pain. So what? I fought a lot of guys who said
that and a lot of guys who never said that and I always felt pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had 55 fights. I don't know of too many times when I
didn't feel the pain. It's part of the game, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed, especially when Tyson is involved. Frans Botha
learned that in January when he got cocky after easily winning the
first four-plus rounds of their fight. Botha was on the edge of the
kind of upset that could have finished Tyson as the compelling
figure in a division his presence (or absence) has dominated for
nearly 15 years. But he never got to see that moment because he
made one mistake.
</P>
<P>
   One mistake and Botha felt the pain . . . but only after
somebody woke him up.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they did, more than five minutes had passed since
he'd visited the dark room where punchers like Tyson can send you.
One right hand to the face when Botha made the mistake of standing
in front of his opponent, instead of moving to his left, and he saw
the black lights.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Tyson is being paid $10 million on an evening when
tickets are being sold to MGM employees for the 4 percent sales tax
to try and wallpaper the house. The broadcast is being given away
by Showtime in an effort to rekindle interest in a fading star who
still fascinates the public, but no longer automatically commands
their dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he follows the plan, it's a two-round fight,'' said Tyson's
head trainer, Tommy Brooks. ``If he doesn't, it's a four-round
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   When the 34-year-old Norris hears this he's not happy about it,
although he concedes there are reasons he's a 12-1 underdog. The
most obvious is his lack of size and punching power. Most boxing
experts believe that will preclude Norris from doing what Botha did
in the first four rounds of his fight with Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Botha was big enough to wrestle with Tyson inside and tie him
up, negating his power in close. He was also able to land with
enough stinging power to stop him short, not truly hurting him but
preventing Tyson from getting into position to throw the crushing
body shot, short uppercut, or booming right that have long been his
trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that, Botha eventually made a mistake and paid dearly
for it, a mistake Norris insists he can avoid regardless of what
the experts think.
</P>
<P>
   ``You push Mike back, bully him a little bit, and it changes the
whole perspective of the fight,'' said Norris (50-5, 26 KOs).
``He's so used to doing it to other guys, he doesn't like it when
somebody does it to him. He didn't like it when (Evander) Holyfield
did it. He didn't like it when (Buster) Douglas did it. He didn't
like it when Botha did it. The way I look at it, if Holyfield can
do it, I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is Holyfield was a proven warrior, a fearless
fighter with an obsession for bringing a little pain himself. Bring
it he did the two nights he was in the ring with Tyson. Can a
journeyman like Norris do the same?
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlin Norris is a good fighter but I don't care how well he's
prepared,'' said Tyson (46-3, 40 KOs). ``I'm prepared to knock him
cold. My timing and speed are much better. I'm throwing sharper
punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I was more of a loose cannon. I thought I
could conquer the world. I didn't think a guy with a gun could beat
me. Now I still feel I can conquer the world, but I know it takes a
lot of hard work and sacrifice. I've done the work. I've made the
sacrifices. I still have a way to go, but just like night follows
day I'm going to be heavyweight champion again.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Tyson first has to turn light into night for Norris
after they climb into the well-lit center of the Grand Garden
Arena. If he can, it doesn't mean he's back, but it does mean he
will have brought what he said he was bringing to this job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bringing the pain, baby,'' Tyson has promised. If he is,
Norris may feel pain like he's never known. If he isn't though,
Orlin Norris could turn into a pain for Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect me to box Tyson and take him into the later
rounds and that's what I'll do,'' Norris said. ``The longer the
fight goes, the larger the advantage is for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to back him up. If I back him up, I can
fight him on the inside. When he's coming forward, I want to stay
back and defend myself with punches. Tyson's going to hit me and
I'm going to hit him. I'm not afraid of that. When he hits me, I'm
just going to hit him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see where he's changed much, stylewise, since I beat
him (when both were amateurs 18 years ago). He was easily
frustrated then and he still gets easily frustrated. He's like a
car that has no reverse, but when you're hitting someone in the
face there's nowhere to go but back.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you get hit in the face yourself like Frans Botha did.
Then there's nowhere to go but to sleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
