<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5529 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-RICH-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-N     10-22 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of Bush.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who look down their noses at a former wrestler widely
admire the former Texas Rangers owner for his prowess at raising
money and genial personality. But where's the beef? Everyone's so
exhausted from looking for the cocaine that Bush still need not
offer any other substance. While the Minnesota governor was dourly
cross-examined by George Will on ABC for his Playboy gag about
hoping for reincarnation as a ``38-double-D bra,'' the Texas
governor has been able to finesse his opposition to the test ban
treaty with a three-sentence press release.
</P>
<P>
   Gore does have beef _ detailed policy positions that do not
challenge administration boilerplate so much as tinker around the
edges. He is as timid on the subject of Bill Clinton as Bush is on
Pat Buchanan; he'll no sooner take on a labor union than his
opponent will the NRA. Though Ventura is always condescended to
about the feather boas and Mylar tights he wore in the wrestling
ring, at least he limited his appearances in contrived costumes to
his stints as a paid entertainer; as governor he usually wears
street clothes. By contrast, Gore is now adopting various costumes
while vice president, trying to buff his image by throwing off drab
Washington duds for snazzier suits (if sans Mylar) as well as
chinos and polo shirts. In his search for an ``authentic'' identity
_ a journey ``from wooden to plastic,'' in the words of a New York
Post headline _ the man has morphed into a male model out of a
Dockers or Home Depot ad.
</P>
<P>
   The antidote to Bush's vacuity and Gore's playacting is not
necessarily mere authenticity; Trump, after all, is nothing if not
authentic _ authentically fatuous _ and Ventura can turn
authenticity into shtick, at which point it becomes authentic
boorishness. What's actually needed is leadership, and leadership
sometimes involves telling people what they don't want to hear,
even at the price of crossing pollsters, the triangulating
consultant of the moment or voters.
</P>
<P>
   This week the theoretically insurgent Democratic alternative to
Gore, Bill Bradley, delivered a speech on child poverty in America
full of idealism but scant on outside-the-liberal-box thinking or
calls for real sacrifice from America's haves on behalf of the
have-nots. (If the policy differences between the two Democrats
remain as incremental as they are, their scheduled seven debates
may prove six too many.) At least John McCain, on the Republican
side, is willing to tilt at his own party's orthodoxy on some
issues, like Kosovo and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Why not go further? In his 1998 race, with a push from
Minnesota's same-day registration law, Ventura drew young,
turned-off voters who are increasingly no-shows in elections, even
after telling state university students that he opposed increasing
tax subsidies to their education. Bill Hillsman, the Minneapolis ad
man who was instrumental in the Ventura campaign, points out that
such twentysomethings are ripe for recruitment into the political
system because, far from being slackers, they're actively involved
in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The levels of volunteerism throughout the country among young
people are skyrocketing,'' Hillsman says, and the statistics bear
him out dramatically. While only about 20 percent of Americans
between 18 and 24 voted in the past two elections, nearly 46
percent of that same age bracket volunteered for groups like
Habitat for Humanity in 1998, up from 38 percent in 1995, according
to figures soon to be released by Independent Sector, a coalition
of volunteer organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that so few civic-minded Americans vote is damning _
not of the no-show voters, but of the so-called ``serious''
politicians whose homogenized, flattering platitudes fail to engage
them. At a time when most Americans, not merely the young, take a
pass on Election Day, there may well be an untapped hunger for a
candidate of any stripe, with or without a boa, who instead of
pandering to America will kick it in the pants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
