<SLUG> BC-FAN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE 28 TACKLES, THOMAS IS NOT HAPPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The statistics tell us that Henry Thomas,
the Patriots' right defensive tackle, has 28 tackles, with 13
coming on the first hit. But that doesn't delight the 13-year
veteran out of Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   No statistic can please him. The 6-foot-2-inch, 277-pounder from
Houston is like that. Nothing can ever get him to feel that he's
holding his own in the middle of the defensive line, even though
Thomas is, indeed, playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing below average,'' said Thomas, who is now in his
third year with the team. ``You can't ask me that, though, I'm not
the guy to ask. I'm never happy. I never feel I'm doing great. I'm
never happy. There's always something more I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   What especially gets on Thomas's nerves are his sacks. He has
none, zip, zero. One was taken away from him during the opening
game against the Jets. A half-sack for a 3-yard loss was withdrawn
from next to his name after last week's game against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to improve my pass rush. I don't have any sacks. I've
got to get (Denver's Brian Griese) to the ground. That's my whole
plan. I've got to get this quarterback down,'' Thomas said about
his goal for Sunday when the Broncos come to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The statistics people) said other people (reached the
quarterback) before me. I'm not even going to argue about it, it
just gets me madder. I've been getting back there, getting some
decent rushes, but I do have to improve a lot on my pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking about getting past my man, so it kind of makes me
slow down, and miss some sacks, and not be in position I should be
in. That's what I've been working on for the past two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is playing despite a broken left baby toe. He's not sure
exactly how it happened, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an occupation hazard,'' he said. ``After Sunday's game,
it was a little sore, so we X-rayed it and it was broken.''
</P>
<P>
   He's still practicing while wearing a special shoe that will
keep the toe from being smashed again. ``There's not a whole lot
you can do with it, but just put ice on it,'' Thomas said. ``It
hurts, but 13 years of doing this, some of the pain is different
than others. I just tape the little toe to another toe and it's
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas sprained his ankle in the seventh game last season. ``It
was where the ligaments get stretched out really bad,'' he said.
``When I played with that, I had to walk on crutches for two days
and there were some days I couldn't get up. I couldn't put any
weight on it, it was that bad, so when it came to going to
practice, it was forget about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game should be interesting. The Patriots have a 4-2
record, having lost their last two outings, and the Broncos have a
2-4 record and have mustered wins in their last two games,
including last week's 31-10 decision over visiting Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Griese completed 19 of 31 passes for 363 yards with two
touchdowns and an interception against the Packers. Tailback
Olandis Gary, stepping in for the injured Terrell Davis, ran for
124 yards on 37 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, (Griese) played great, he had a good command, a
good feel for the game,'' said Thomas. ``He made the checks and he
didn't make a lot of mistakes. It's been a gradual improvement.
I've seen him getting better each week. The last game gave him
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Griese has completed 56.8 percent of his passes (100 of 176)
with seven touchdowns and seven interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Patriots won't have to worry about Davis, Thomas
knows their problems are far from over. ``Gary runs the ball in the
same style (as Davis), the same pound-you-to-the-ground-type
runner. He's going to get to the point where he sees those backside
cuts and he'll be gone,'' Thomas said. ``He's gaining confidence.
He's just starting out, but it will take a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone's in the hole, though, they'll both pop you, so you
have to bring them down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
