<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-22 1784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING THROUGH THE PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Parcells likes to say, ``You are what you are.'' And Arthur
Pappas will tell you in a hurry that Pedro Martinez and Nomar
Garciaparra are special.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us some extraordinary performances,'' said Pappas,
the Red Sox' team doctor who helped negotiate the two star players
through injury and into the lineup when both could have easily
decided to stay on the bench rather than risk further injury. ``I
don't know of any other pitcher who could have done what Pedro did
in the playoffs,'' Pappas said Friday, referring to Martinez
pitching with a strained back muscle. ``He is one of these rare
human beings who can have his brain control his muscles. If he
couldn't, there is no way he could have gone on and did what he
did. He changed his whole way of throwing after the injury, and
still went out and pitched all of those (17) scoreless innings. It
was remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar had a very badly bruised and swollen (right) wrist. If
he swung and missed the ball, it really hurt him. And the
difficulty he had in the field throwing the ball can probably be
attributed to the injury. When he went to his right to field a
ground ball and then had to jump and throw the ball across his body
to first, it really hurt. The motion where he had to roll his wrist
toward his little finger caused him a lot of pain. Both of them
deserve a lot of credit for what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was hit on the right wrist Sept. 25. ``He damaged
the tendon and the nerve in the wrist,'' Pappas said. ``He had five
days rest before he played again. We injected the area, but when he
first came back it started to hurt more. It became more sensitive.
But he didn't want to sit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro strained the muscle under his right shoulder blade. It's
a very important muscle for the throwing motion. He could not raise
his arm to throw with the same motion he used during the season. He
adapted his entire body to be able to pitch. Before he went in to
relieve in the (fifth and final) game in Cleveland, I told him I
thought he could go two to three innings. He went six scoreless.
Then he pitched seven scoreless against the Yankees last Saturday,
with a changed motion. He couldn't throw as hard, but he adapted to
what his body would allow him to do with the injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas spoke to Martinez Friday before the pitcher left for his
Dominican home. ``I gave him a set of exercises. He will be back
here to be checked in either late November or early December,'' he
said. ``I think with rest and the right exercise, he will be fine.
No surgery. I think it will be the same with Nomar. That wrist just
needs some rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm very pleased with progress of Ramon Martinez. He has
really done well. He, too, has a set of exercises, different than
Pedro, because his involves the rotator cuff. Both Pedro and Ramon
always stay in great shape and work hard, so you know they will do
everything to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worse players. Better games. That's the way it is in the
National Football League this season, where the running game has
virtually vanished. Don't think the Patriots are the only ones who
can't run the football. There are only a handful of teams that can.
At this point in the season, would you believe that 41 percent of
the games have been decided by 3 points or fewer? Just a year ago,
it was only 27 percent. And how about 63 percent of the games,
nearly two out of every three, decided by 8 points or fewer?
</P>
<P>
   ``We love it out here,'' said Robert Walker, who works with the
sports book at the Mirage in Las Vegas. ``The underdogs have been
winning (on the point) spread more than ever, and the heavy hitters
(big gamblers) like to bet the favorites, so it's been going great
so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is suffering from a trickle-down effect. There are not
enough good quarterbacks to support 31 teams. And you can count the
number of quarterbacks anyone would put the label ``great'' on with
one hand. Steve Young is nearly finished in San Francisco. Dan
Marino is hurting in Miami, and not the Dan of old. John Elway has
retired. Randall Cunningham, last year's star, has been benched.
Vinny Testaverde, Pro Bowler of a year ago, is out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Just take a look at the AFC West. Here are the five starters:
Jon Kitna (Seattle), Brian Griese (Denver), Elvis Grbac (Kansas
City), Erik Kramer (San Diego), and Rich Gannon (Oakland). How
about AFC Central: Stoney Case (Baltimore), Tim Couch (Cleveland),
Jeff Blake (Cincinnati), Neil O'Donnell (Tennessee), Kordell
Stewart (Pittsburgh), and a hurting (bad ribs) Mark Brunell
(Jacksonville), who has three touchdown passes to date.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams are averaging better than 30 points, both in the
NFC, Washington with Brad Johnson and St. Louis with Kurt Warner.
Only one team in the AFC is even averaging 25 points per game,
Miami (28.0), and it will be going with Damon Huard at quarterback
for the immediate future. The trickle-down comes with opposing
defensive coordinators disregarding any respect they have for the
running game, and forcing teams to throw. No one can run anymore. A
year ago this time, in the sixth week of '98, there were 124
rushing touchdowns scored in 81 games. This year, there were just
109 scored in 86 games. Teams are not hesitating to bring a safety,
usually held back to defend the pass, up to play the run. Just
watch Lawyer Milloy, the best in the league at what he does, flying
around the field for the Patriots. He's leading the team in tackles
from the safety position.
</P>
<P>
   The league tried to make it harder for kickers this year,
forcing them to use new footballs every game. New balls are
supposedly harder to kick than old ones. Wrong. There are 262 field
goals already this year (in fewer games) compared to 229 a year
ago. Get used to it. There's a greater lack of quality quarterbacks
than ever. Between free agency and the salary cap, this is the NFL
game of the future. The rosters are thin. The talent too spread
out. There will be fewer beatings and closer games. The better
quarterbacks get beat up over time with everyone rushing the
passer. Brett Favre's Packers are averaging 20.4 points per game;
Doug Flutie's Bills, 19.7 per game; and Jake Plummer's Arizona
Cardinals, 13.7 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer? Wasn't he the ``next coming'' in the preseason
magazines? Before you get too tough on Drew Bledsoe, you better
take a good look around and see who everyone else has to play with.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is the latest on Byron Dafoe from Harry Sinden: ``At the
request of an outside source, and I'm not going to say who that is,
I called Dafoe up and gave him this offer, after saying I wouldn't
do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would raise our initial offer of $3 million a year, to
$3,150,000 a year, and would throw in another $150,000 if he just
did what he did a year ago _ win one playoff round. The $3,150,000
was guaranteed, and if he won the playoff round, he would get $3.3
million. I told him, `Take this offer,' and I gave him 24 hours to
do it. He came back in with another proposal, which, if we accepted
it, and he did what he did last year, win one playoff round, would
have averaged out to $4,996,000 a year. I told him to forget it.
Our offer was non-negotiable. Our offer has gone back to $3 million
a year. The other one was pulled off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden thinks the assertion that the Bruins are winless over
their first nine games because the present players are lamenting
Dafoe and Dimitri Khristich is laughable. ``Players are interested
in themselves. It has always been that way,'' Sinden said. ``The
first thing that they are interested in is their own well-being. We
have a lot of guys coming up for new contracts next year. You don't
think they are trying to bust a gut to score every goal and get
every point they can? How do you come in and talk about wanting
more money when you have nothing to show for it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura may not have been happy when his jubiliant
teammates wouldn't let him round the bases on what should have been
a game-winning grand slam last Sunday, but thousands of gamblers
were thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen anything like it,'' said Walker of the
Mirage. ``The over/under on the game was 7 1/2 runs. Almost all of
the action was on the under. When the score ended, 4-3, Mets, the
people who had the under won. And almost everyone bet on the under.
I'd say that it cost us $200,000 at least here in Vegas, and the
rest of the country and the Caribbean would add up to millions. The
bettors came away happy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 3 and the bases loaded in the bottom of
the 15th inning against the Braves, Ventura hit the ball out of the
park. Home run, almost always. That should have made the score 7-3,
New York, and a total of 10 runs, which would have made the over
bettors the winners. Instead, they became losers when Ventura was
stopped by his teammates between first and second base and never
went any farther. ``We held up paying off the bet for 30 minutes,
making sure the official score was going to be 4-3. It was,'' said
Walker. ``If he had just gone to second base and touched it, it
would have been 5-3, and we (the book) would have made the money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matt Damon is a classy guy. The movie superstar, who was part of
the celebrity home run hitting contest during the All-Star Game
weekend in Fenway Park in July, is sending groundskeeper Joe Mooney
to the Boston College-Notre Dame game in South Bend, Ind., next
month. Mooney has been a big Notre Dame fan his whole life. Damon,
a Cambridge native, was given the run of the park by Mooney that
week and wanted to respond to Mooney's kindness. A friend mentioned
Mooney's love for Notre Dame, so Damon is sending him on the trip,
all expenses paid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nick Buoniconti, with tears in his eyes, called it ``coming
home'' when he picked up a $10,000 check from his former Patriot
teammates to go toward the Miami Project. Since his son, Marc, was
paralyzed in a college football game, Buoniconti has made it his
life's work to raise money, looking to cure paralysis. He now has
personally raised more than $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one will have to hold a fund-raiser for Jim O'Brien. The
former Boston College basketball coach, now at Ohio State, recently
agreed to an eight-year extension, which a Columbus, Ohio, paper
pegs at $833,000 per year. That comes to $6.64 million if he
collects all of it. Obie gets $175,000 in base pay; $200,000 for a
TV show; $233,333 from Nike; and $75,000 for radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
