<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON STUDIES, SURVEYS AND PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having a Ball &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not unheard of for marketing consultants, whose mission is
searching tirelessly for creative ways to stand out from the crowd,
to go, shall it be said, a wee bit over the top.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: a square gray envelope that appeared in the
mail last week, adorned with cryptic doodlings and a crimson circle
in the dead center containing the address. On the flap was a single
word, Play, in a loose freehand.
</P>
<P>
   That, it transpires, is the new name of a Richmond consulting
firm formerly called Opus Marketing. The change ``gives clarity to
the company's business approach,'' the announcement explains
helpfully. The company's founder, Andy Stefanovich, whose official
title apparently is ``In Charge of What's Next,'' is quoted as
saying, ``Play is not simply a name, but a brand and business
philosophy that evolved from our creative development process.''
</P>
<P>
   It gets better. ``Play is not simply a company brand,'' the
announcement elaborates. ``Play is a practice, an ideology, a
vision, a movement. Play is flexible and organic in its application
and theory.''
</P>
<P>
   The headline on the announcement mentions a ``unique IPO to
launch a new era.'' But no, the company isn't going public. ``Play
is so much more than a name change,'' Stefanovich is further quoted
as saying, that ``we felt it required as momentous an announcement
as a traditional IPO, emulating its size and scope.''
</P>
<P>
   So the company is doing, yes, an ``Initial Play Offering.'' An
unlimited number of ``shares'' of the company's creativity are
offered at $0 a share to those who register on the company's Web
site. Those who sign up are actually joining an electronic mailing
list to receive ``valuable e-mail updates on creativity in
business'' from the company.
</P>
<P>
   The company describes its new logo as an image of a red
playground ball (``Smell the rubber. Hear the bounce.'') followed
by a line. For their business cards and stationery, employees are
supposed to write the company's name on the line in their own hand.
(``Play your way.'')
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the company's Web address,
www.lookatmorestuff.com, is left unexplained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
