<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE HILL III, AD AGENCY CO-FOUNDER, DIES AT 67 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George (Jay) Hill III, one of the leading figures in New England
advertising and a co-founder of Boston ad agency Hill Holliday
Connors Cosmopulos, died Friday of cancer. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described ``tongue-tied Yankee,'' Mr. Hill often let his
work do his talking, creating ads for everything from Vermont
condominiums to Kansas politicians and luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, ad campaigns he helped create received some of
the highest honors the advertising trade bestows. In an industry
with New York at its epicenter, Mr. Hill often forced Madison
Avenue to take notice and pay attention to Boston, said Adweek New
England editor Judy Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay Hill was one of the first people to bring New England
advertising to a national level,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Warner, Mr. Hill pioneered some of the ad world's
present-day vocabulary, his ideas then turned into cliches by a
subsequent generation of copycat admirers.
</P>
<P>
   About a decade ago, a creative team under Mr. Hill's command
developed a campaign called ``Real life, real answers'' for John
Hancock Financial Services.
</P>
<P>
   The realism and intimacy of that campaign was regarded as a
breakthrough by the industry, and the ad was honored with a Grand
Prix award from the prestigious Cannes Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay Hill was, among other things, a great writer,'' agency
cofounder Jack Connors recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community has lost the greatest ad copywriter I've ever
seen,'' added Steve Cosmopulos, another agency cofounder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Mr. Hill helped develop a 1978 Super Bowl ad for Wang
Laboratories; it was believed to have been the first time a
high-tech company advertised during the big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wang ads changed the way that high-tech companies did their
advertising, and John Hancock ads did the same for financial
services companies,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, it was not readily apparent that Mr. Hill was destined
for advertising greatness. In that year, he threw in $1,500, along
with three other men to open a new Boston ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agency was called Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos, and its
small office kept a bucket full of dimes handy so if its telephone
line was tied up, business could be conducted on the pay phones on
Newbury Street.
</P>
<P>
   If Connors was the salesman who could make the successful pitch,
Mr. Hill was ``the guy who did the ads,'' his wife, Virginia Graham
Drew Hill, recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Among the early clients for whom Mr. Hill did ads were such
politicians as former Boston Mayor Kevin H. White and former US
Senator Bob Dole, a Kansas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has come a long way. Thirty years after that bucket
of dimes, and three years after Mr. Hill retired as chairman, Hill
Holliday was sold to New York communications conglomerate, the
Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag for that transaction was estimated at more than
$100 million. By the time of the sale in 1998, Hill Holliday was
the second largest ad agency in New England, with $707 million in
capitalized billings for that year.
</P>
<P>
   Today the agency creates ads for such clients as Dunkin' Donuts
Inc., Fleet Boston Corp., Fidelity Investments, as well as John
Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising is nothing if not a collaborative art, and Connors
recalled that Mr. Hill had a personal comfort level that allowed
him to surround himself with extraordinary talent.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hill may have been quiet and confident but he also had a sly
wit about him. In its early years, the agency was trying to create
an ad campaign for a developer of Vermont condominiums at a time
when few people knew what a condominium was.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hill's ad for the condos read: ``All the advantages of
upcountry life but none of the horse manure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hill was born in Cambridge and grew up in Brookline. He was
a graduate of Harvard University and served in the Army. When not
creating ads, he often devoted much of his spare time to the
Massachusetts Horticultural Society.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, Mr. Hill leaves three sons, David of Berkeley,
Calif., John of Bluemont, Va., and Peter of New York City. He also
leaves two sisters, Stacie Barta of South Hampton, N.Y., and
Elizabeth Pitney of Durham, N.C., and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
