<SLUG> BC-SYCAMORE-IPO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWLY MINTED STOCK DROPS $85, BUT STILL ENDS DAY UP 386 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not often that a stock can drop $85 in an afternoon and
still be a spectacular success, but it happened Friday to Sycamore
Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore's highly anticipated initial public offering was priced
at $38 but began trading at $270.875. The shares closed at $184.75,
an increase of 386 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore ended the day with a market value of $14.4 billion, far
more than the $9.5 billion value of 3Com Corp., a larger and older
maker of communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But Sycamore, based in Chelmsford, Mass., is considered the
leader among a new breed of small companies that are developing
equipment to enhance the efficiency and functionality of optical
communications networks, which transmit bits of data using pulses
of light rather than electricity. Sycamore was also the first of
the group to offer stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The offering was underwritten by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
Lehman Brothers, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and Dain Rauscher Wessels. At
$38, the offering price could be considered aggressive, especially
for a company that did not exist two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the stock opened at 12:45 p.m. amid what one person
close to the deal described as a ``feeding frenzy.'' Within 15
minutes, the stock rose to about $200, where it remained for most
of the afternoon. About 7.5 million shares were sold in the
offering, or about 10 percent of the company, and 9.9 million
shares traded hands Friday. It appeared that most of the
institutional investors who had been able to buy at the offering
price sold quickly to those who had been shut out.
</P>
<P>
   The day's explosive trading could raise questions about whether
the deal's underwriters left money on the table that went to the
initial institutional buyers of the stock rather than to Sycamore.
</P>
<P>
   From Sycamore's perspective, however, more than $280 million was
raised, and the primary purpose of the offering was to create a
publicly traded currency. That currency can set a floor for
negotiations should Sycamore agree to be acquired and could allow
Sycamore to pursue acquisitions of its own more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the value of their holdings, Sycamore's top executives
could even pursue corporate acquisitions on a personal basis. Desh
Deshpande, the company's chairman, holds about 16.3 million shares
_ about 21 percent of the company _ now worth about $3 billion.
Daniel E. Smith, the chief executive, holds about 14.7 million
shares, worth roughly $2.7 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
