<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-KLAN-MARCH-ART-NYT     10-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KLAN-MARCH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT SAYS KLAN CANNOT WEAR MASKS AT RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) (th) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal appeals court blocked a lower court
decision on Friday and barred the Ku Klux Klan from rallying in
lower Manhattan on Saturday with their faces shielded by masks. The
decision was a victory for the Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
rejected the Klan's arguments that a state law that bars the
wearing of masks during most rallies violated its members' First
Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Klan group, the Church of the American Knights
of the Ku Klux Klan, had argued that if its members were forced to
unmask themselves, they faced retaliation because of their
unpopular views.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York
Civil Liberties Union, which is representing the group, said his
clients were considering an emergency appeal to Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg of the U.S. Supreme Court in the hope that she might
overturn the appeals court order.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel also said that the American Knights plan to proceed with
their demonstration from 2 to 4 p.m. Saturday outside the State
Supreme Court at 60 Centre St., although he refused to say whether
the group would abide by the law and remove masks. The two Klan
members who are organizing the rally and who testified in a court
hearing on Thursday were in Siegel's offices Friday night, but
would not grant interviews, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who was in Indianapolis on a political
visit on Friday, praised the ruling. ``I can't imagine a better
victory for decency and common sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court of appeals has upheld the wisdom of the police
department saying this is an organization that wore masks in order
to kill people,'' he said. ``The police department has a public
safety reason that's very, very sound in saying that you should not
be able to do that in hiding, anonymously.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also repeated his criticism of the lower court ruling
on Thursday night, when two U.S. District Court judges, sitting
together, ordered the city to allow the Klan to wear masks in the
rally, and elicited a promise from a top city lawyer that no
arrests would be made, despite the state law.
</P>
<P>
   In the court of appeals Friday, Siegel argued that the mask law
violated the Constitution because the Supreme Court has held that
there is a right to anonymous free expression.
</P>
<P>
   But the judges, signaling that they saw the case as a close one,
sided with the Giuliani administration, which had contended that
the law did not single out Klan members but was on the books to
make it more difficult for any demonstrator to engage in wrongdoing
or violence because he might have felt emboldened by anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are mindful that this case raises difficult questions of
law and perhaps questions not as simple as sometimes portrayed,''
said Judge Jose A. Cabranes, who announced the ruling from the
bench in the name of the full panel, which also included Judges
Amalya L. Kearse and Roger J. Miner.
</P>
<P>
   Cabranes indicated that the panel found no error or abuse in
discretion by the lower court when it found that the enforcement of
the mask law by the police had not been based on the content of the
Klan members' speech, which would be impermissible under the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But Cabranes said that the panel had concluded that the Klan
case was not the same as others in which the Supreme Court had
found certain activity, such as anonymous pamphleteering, to be
protected under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We conclude that this case is distinguishable,'' he said,
``from those cases in which the Supreme Court has protected the
anonymity of organizations and individuals seeking to exercise
their First Amendment right to association and speech.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
