<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-EARNINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE SHARES DROP 5% ON PROFIT FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares in Gillette Co. fell 5 percent Friday in heavy trading
after the Boston-based maker of razors, batteries, and small
appliances said Thursday it would be hit with an unexpected drop in
fourth-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette insists that it will rebound to its customary
impressive form some time next year, but the company's fourth
warning about profits since the spring prompted many Wall Street
analyst to lower their earnings forecasts for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   According to First Call Corp., nearly all the analysts who
follow Gillette lowered their full-year earnings estimates for 2000
Friday. The consensus estimate had been $1.41 per share; after the
revisions, many analysts now expect Gillette to earn about $1.29 a
share for 2000, First Call said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a significant downward revision for a company in the
consumer staple business,'' said Charles L. Hill, First Call's
director of research.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gillette said it would not meet expectations for
the fourth quarter, in part, because of a plan to cut razor-blade
shipments as a result of new inventory management techniques
adopted by many European retailers.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Gillette has been buffeted by economic
turmoil in some of its overseas markets and by unfavorable currency
exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   While its razor, oral care, and Duracell battery businesses have
been generally strong, Gillette's Braun appliance division and its
stationery business have been a drag on the company.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette also said Thursday it would consider selling or
discontinuing its stationery lines and some of its Braun appliance
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Eric Kraus said that with Gillette taking appropriate
corrective measures to address its challenges, ``things bode very
well for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Jones analyst Tony Vento suggested that Gillette was
attempting to contain all its problems to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a clean slate for 2000,'' said Vento, adding, ``No
question, investors are growing increasingly impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Gillette shares closed at 36,
down 1 7/8. That was an improvement over the low point shares hit
in after-hours trading following Gillette's warning Thursday. At
one point, shares traded at 33 1/2 on Instinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LA-GOVERNOR23-COX     10-22 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GOVERNOR23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    La. governor eases through campaign
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ He's surely one of the calmest incumbents on
record.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Gov. Mike Foster was so sure he would be re-elected to
a second term today that he has refused all invitations to debate
his challengers. He has spent little time touring the state to drum
up support. And he hasn't come close to exhausting his $3 million
war chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows what he stands for,'' said Trey Williams,
Foster's campaign manager. ``He doesn't want to waste his time in a
debate with opponents beating on him for an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Several challengers have accused Foster of being afraid to
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cannot stand toe to toe with William Jefferson,'' said John
LaPlace, campaign manager for U.S. Rep. William Jefferson (D-New
Orleans), who is Foster's main challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Another Democratic candidate, Phil Preis, has sent a mascot
dressed as a duck around the state to make his point that Foster
has been ``ducking'' debate opportunities. The mascot mockingly
plays off Foster's love of duck hunting. Preis even sent the duck
to the governor's mansion in Baton Rouge on Wednesday. Foster
invited the duck inside for coffee and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits agree Foster's campaign slogan could have been, ``I'd
rather be duck hunting.'' While his challengers campaigned, the
governor spent Friday shopping for a motorcycle for his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials predicted a light turnout in an election that
includes statewide offices _ including two held by indicted
incumbents _ and 10 proposed constitutional amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls indicated Foster would win in today's election,
which pits all 12 candidates against each other, regardless of
political party. If no candidate gets more than 50 percent, there
will be a Nov. 20 runoff. If Foster wins as predicted, then he'll
be free to pick up his gun and head for the swamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Foster will be in the blinds when the season opens
rather than sweating out the final week of a runoff campaign,''
predicted Jack Wardlaw, a columnist for the New Orleans
Times-Picayune.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a pro-business, pro-gun, anti-abortion Republican, has
the good fortune of serving Louisiana during a time of prosperity.
The state is doing better economically than it has in 30 years. And
he is credited with creating more jobs, reducing sales taxes and
renewing interest in improving the state's dismal record on
education.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the good economic times, a strong Democratic
challenger might have had a chance against Foster. But Jefferson's
lackluster campaign has not threatened Foster's wide lead in the
polls. Observers say it's because he is a black candidate in a
state that has never had a black governor, and because he is from
New Orleans. The rest of the state tends to view the Big Easy as
too liberal. In polls, Jefferson gets roughly 20 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   But La Place said polls usually underestimate black votes and
that Jefferson's support is broader than it seems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since 1975 that we've had an incumbent
who is popular and an economy that's going well,'' said Wayne
Parent, a political science professor at Louisiana State
University. ``Everyone is asking, where are the fireworks?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
