<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: STILL OPTIMISTIC
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. George Mitchell met with political leaders in
Belfast in what appeared to be the final sessions of his
seven-week-old review intended to end a stalemate over guerrilla
disarmament. David Trimble, head of the Ulster Unionists, said:
``Unlike some others, we have not written the review off. We are
still here to see if progress can be made.'' Gerry Adams, head of
Sinn Fein, the political ally of the Irish Republican Army, said
there was still ``a tiny possibility of a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: JIANG ENDS VISIT
</P>
<P>
   President Jiang Zemin ended a five-day visit to Britain with a
speech at Cambridge University rejecting the demands of protesters,
who dogged his appearances, that China change its policies on Tibet
and human rights. He argued that countries with different social
systems should treat one another as equals. Jiang is on a 17-day
tour to Britain, France, Portugal, Algeria, Morocco and Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET APPEALS
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Gen. Augusto Pinochet filed an appeal with the High
Court challenging a magistrate's decision approving a Spanish
application for the extradition of the 83-year-old former Chilean
dictator to Madrid to stand trial on torture charges. The step is
likely to carry the case, which is now more than a year old, well
into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: LEGISLATOR FREE TO LEAVE
</P>
<P>
   In a reversal, a court ruled that Merve Kavakci, who was elected
to Parliament this year but denied her seat because she sought to
take her oath of office while wearing a Muslim head scarf, is free
to leave the country if she pleases. An earlier decision forbade
her to do so. Ms. Kavakci, 31, was stripped of her Turkish
citizenship after it was learned that she had obtained an American
passport.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: JAIL VISITS CUT
</P>
<P>
   The government has suspended humanitarian visits to three jailed
Marxist guerrillas in the second month of a hunger strike in demand
for better prison conditions for political prisoners. The three
leaders of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, who are being
held in a prison in the port of Callao, were last visited by Red
Cross doctors more than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: POLLS FAVOR OPPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the presidential vote, final polls indicate that
Mayor Fernando de la Rua of Buenos Aires will win an easy
first-round victory to end 10 years of Justicialist party rule. A
Gallup poll showed the opposition Alianza coalition candidate with
51 percent of the vote and the Buenos Aires Governor Eduardo
Duhalde, a Justicialist, with 34 percent. The poll, which
questioned 1,787 people, had a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: 2 MORE RUN FOR MAYOR
</P>
<P>
   Prominent politicians from two opposition parties have added
their names to a lengthening list of candidates for Mayor of Mexico
City. Andres Lopez Obrador, a former president of the Party of the
Democratic Revolution, the main leftist party, and Santiago Creel,
a congressional deputy from the center-right National Action Party,
have begun campaigning for the vote on July 2, when Mexicans will
also elect a president.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: SLAIN PREMIER CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   After more than a decade, federal prosecutors have finally
charged the slain Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi in a kickback scheme
in an arms deal with the Swedish company Bofors. Also charged were
Martin Ardbo, a former chief of the company, and an Italian
businessman, Ottavio Quattrocchi, a friend of Gandhi's. The case
has been a part of India's political landscape since 1989, when it
played a role in Gandhi's election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SETTLEMENT CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   The Settlers Council has dismantled an uninhabited illegal
outpost in the West Bank that protesting yeshiva students prevented
from being torn down. In an agreement with Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, the council agreed to help evacuate 12 settlements, and by
week's end five had been cleared, settlers announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
