<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ASKED WHY HE IS SO RARELY IN NEW HAMPSHIRE, BUSH GETS TESTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related story, BUSH-BOOK) 
(th) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEENE, N.H. _ On his first campaign swing through New Hampshire
since early September, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas tried Friday to
turn questions about why he is not spending more time here into an
attack on his priorities as a family man.
</P>
<P>
   His voice got louder and his tone sharper as he told reporters
that he would not be attending a forum along with other Republican
presidential candidates at Dartmouth College next Thursday because
he will be with his wife, Laura, who is being honored by her alma
mater, Southern Methodist University, in Dallas that evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is my priority,'' he said, ``and if it costs me
votes for honoring my wife, then so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would not be attending another candidates' forum in
Durham, N.H., Friday night, either, because he had promised last
July to attend a state party dinner in Sugarbush, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a man who keeps my word,'' he said after an appearance at
a fire station in Newport on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   While front-runners like Bush are typically less enthusiastic
about appearing alongside the competition, some Republicans here
have questioned Bush's relatively rare appearances in the state,
which holds the nation's first presidential primary next February.
Those Republicans wonder if Bush has concluded that he has the
nomination sewn up and can afford to take New Hampshire for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   David Currier, the vice chairman of the Republican Party in
Belknap and Merrimack counties, said party members expected to see
candidates more often than they had seen Bush, whose visit to the
state was his fourth this year. Currier allowed that he guessed
Bush had simply been too busy tending to his duties as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, voters ``are going to be looking for him, and there may
be some disappointment that he's not there,'' Currier added. ``It
behooves any candidate to be here as much as he can. Between now
and the primary, he needs to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   John Dowd, the Rockingham County party chairman, said he
believed that ``it's a little bit of a problem'' for Bush, and
added: ``He still has time to correct it and show his face more. If
he kept it up, it would hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was last in New Hampshire on Sept. 7 and 8; he canceled a
scheduled trip on Sept. 19 after a shooting in a church in Fort
Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Asked repeatedly Friday about why he had not been around more,
Bush at one point interrupted a reporter's question to say, ``The
important question is, How many hands have I shaked?''
</P>
<P>
   And Friday, certainly, the answer was lots. After his talk at
the fire station in Newport, he stayed for about an hour to greet a
couple of hundred people who heard a cranked-up tape of country
songs like ``Boot Scootin' Boogie'' and ``This Ain't No Thinkin'
Thing,'' while they waited to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Bush said: ``This is a state that requires one-on-one
campaigning. I just got a chance to do a lot of it. I'm taking
nothing for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   All the other major candidates have been in New Hampshire at
least twice as often as Bush. Vice President Al Gore has visited
the state 14 times this year, and his Democratic challenger, former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, has made 11 trips. Among the
Republican candidates, Steve Forbes has made 18 trips to New
Hampshire, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, 17, and Gary L. Bauer, 10.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bush's Republican opponents have been calling him a
``stealth candidate.'' He has, though, agreed to participate in a
forum sponsored by WMUR-TV on Dec. 2. And a spokeswoman for the New
Hampshire Republican Party said Bush had committed to spending part
of every week here for the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began his campaign day at the Country Kitchen, a diner on
the outskirts of Newport, where he poured coffee and kidded with
the breakfast crowd. Asked whether he was a regular or a decaf
drinker, he said, ``I'm not taking a position.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Newport, when he was asked about potential running
mates, he said, ``I'm not going to tell you her name.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, as he always does, that it would be premature to start
kicking around names at this point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
