<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5587 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     10-22 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE FUN WITH TED AND JANE? YAWN ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta, Atlanta, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. Just typing the word makes me a little queasy. Couldn't
the World Series start someplace else? For the fifth time in this
decade, we're going to be subjected to Ted and Jane, the moronic
Tomahawk Chop, protests from American Indian groups, and the
virtues of Tom Glavine and John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully, is anyone in your neighborhood talking about this
World Series? Any kids in the back yard pretending to be Chipper
Jones? Wouldn't all of us have rather seen Yankees-Mets? Or Red
Sox-Mets?
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta in the World Series is boring. The Braves always get
here, but they never win (OK, they won in 1995, but that was
against a Mike Hargrove-managed Cleveland team).
</P>
<P>
   Braves-Yankees is like Pepsi-Coke. It's big, fat, and
predictable. What we really could have used this year was a little
Dr Pepper in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   For Bostonians, the best part of this World Series is going to
be watching Roger Clemens try to salvage his reputation in Game 4
Wednesday night in New York. It'll be his first World Series
appearance since Game 6 in 1986 when he either took himself out, or
was yanked by a cowardly John McNamara. Clemens got himself traded
to New York from Toronto so he'd have this opportunity, though he
didn't think he'd be playing the Al Nipper role for the Bronx
Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rocket is only going to start once and the rest of the
time we'll be bored by the Braves, the winningest team of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has won eight straight division titles in the '90s. The
only years in this decade in which the Braves did not make the
playoffs were 1990 (when they finished last), and 1994 (when a
strike killed October). But in seven post-1990 baseball
tournaments, the Braves have gone home losers six times. They've
earned their reputation as the Buffalo Bills of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It's wildly unfair, of course. What the Braves have done in this
decade is astounding. They've won and won and won. But they've had
too many chances to win it all, and we are tired of watching them
fall in the Fall Classic. Admit it, wouldn't this Series be more
fun if camera-hog Bobby Valentine were calling the shots from the
NL dugout?
</P>
<P>
   Unless Pete Rose wrestles Bud Selig to the ground, the best bet
to enliven the 1999 World Series is John Rocker, the country boy
reliever who runs to the mound the same way Wendell Kim takes his
position in the third base coach's box. Rocker infuriated New
Yorkers when he insulted Mets fans during the National League
Championship Series, then invited more abuse by yelling at them
after beating their team. He also totaled his car while driving on
a Georgia freeway the day before the Braves-Mets finale. He is to
the 1999 Braves what Oil Can Boyd was to the '86 Red Sox. He is
guaranteed to be the most quoted Braves player in this series.
</P>
<P>
   But there are not enough Rockers in the Atlanta clubhouse. Can
you really stand anymore stories about Glavine's family coming in
from Billerica and the psychologist who sits behind home plate
wearing a red shirt whenever Smoltz pitches?
</P>
<P>
   The city of Atlanta simply doesn't deserve baseball's showcase,
just as it didn't deserve the 1996 Olympics. This forever will be a
football town where folks care about Georgia, Georgia Tech, and the
Falcons. The Braves failed to sell out their first four postseason
games against the Astros and Mets. The World Series will probably
sell out, but only because it draws ``event'' people. ``What do you
think coach Cox will do here, Rhett?''
</P>
<P>
   Eight consecutive postseason appearances is a lofty achievement
and speaks highly of the work done by general manager John
Schuerholz and president Stan Kasten. Bobby Cox is a terrific
manager and Atlanta players have overcome tremendous obstacles to
get back here. They won 103 games, most in the major leagues. And
they badly want to win this World Series so they can officially
claim to be the team of the decade. It's pretty tough to be the
team of the dedade if you win only as many World Series as were won
by the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's routine brilliance has become boring and the Braves
play in a city that has no appreciation for what they've done. How
about Yankees in five, just so we don't have to come back here?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
