<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIAN-SUIT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Davidian lawsuit set for trial May 15
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The civil lawsuit by surviving Branch Davidians
and others against the federal government will go to trial on May
15, 2000, according to an order issued Friday by U.S. District
Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection for the lawsuit against FBI sharpshooter Lon
Horiuchi will be the court's first proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Horiuchi is the lone defendant remaining in the Davidians'
lawsuit. Horiuchi, who was in a sniper position at Mount Carmel, is
accused of firing at the Davidians on the day of the fire that led
to the death of David Koresh and 75 followers. That claim is based
on a report filed by FBI Special Agent Charles Riley, who stated he
heard gunfire coming from the direction of the sniper position
where Horiuchi was stationed.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury case against Horiuchi concludes, the three
remaining nonjury claims against the United States will commence,
Smith ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues are whether the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms used excessive force during the Feb. 28, 1993 raid on
Mount Carmel, during which there was a shoot-out that killed five
Davidians and four ATF agents; whether the FBI used excessive force
on the day of the fire, specifically the allegation that FBI agents
fired shots into the Davidians' residence and possibly kept them
from fleeing; and whether the FBI was negligent regarding the start
of the fire as well as extinguishing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a fair schedule to both sides,'' said Mike
Caddell, the lead attorney for the plaintiffs. ``It should give us
a reasonable opportunity to examine the evidence and get ready for
trial, assuming the government gets off its duff and starts turning
things over. Judge Smith issued his ruling to turn over the
evidence on Aug. 9. Here it is two months later and most of the
important evidence is still not in Waco. That's not the judge's
fault, however. If we feel the government is not being cooperative,
we will raise that issue at the appropriate time.''
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesman responded briefly to Smith's
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand a date has been set, and we'll be there,''
spokesman Myron Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was set for trial Oct. 18. However, Smith pushed
back the trial's start because of the government's problems in
responding to his order to produce evidence and the request by
Special Counsel John Danforth that he be allowed time to get his
office up to speed before both sides started discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery in the lawsuit will begin immediately, Smith ordered,
and conclude by March 31, 2000. However, discovery regarding the
reports and testimony of experts will continue until April 15,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs have until Feb. 1, 2000, to make an application
to reconsider the dismissal of any defendant from the case,
according to Smith's order. His ruling in July removed many
plaintiffs from the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Although noting that the government is complying with his order
to transfer all original documents and evidence in the case to the
court's jurisdiction, Smith gave the government 30 days to provide
inventories that explain what is contained within the ``mountains
of sealed boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also ordered the issues of liability and damages to be
bifurcated, meaning they will be tried separately.
</P>
<P>
   As he has stated before, Caddell said Friday that he was not
opposed to splitting up the arguments for liability and damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the judge that would be fine,'' Caddell said. ``Is
there any doubt in anyone's mind that there are damages in this
case? It's not whether the plaintiffs were damaged, it's who is
responsible? It's a whodunit. That's what this case is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
