<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-JET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE WILLING TO ABANDON JOINT FIGHTER TO SAVE F-22 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A PHOTO is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To save its expensive F-22 fighter from
congressional budget-cutters, the Air Force is willing to sacrifice
another, less-costly new fighter _ to the consternation of the Navy
and the Marines who also want to use the cheaper aircraft, a senior
Air Force official said.
</P>
<P>
   The less-expensive plane, the Joint Strike Fighter, is unusual
in that it was being developed for the Air Force as well as the
Navy and the Marines. But a senior Air Force official, speaking on
the condition that he not be identified, said this week, ``It may
not be cost-effective to continue with the Joint Strike Fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have alternatives for the Joint Strike Fighter _ but not
for the F-22,'' the official said. ``We have to have the F-22.''
</P>
<P>
   By raising the prospect that it would pull out of the program to
develop the Joint Strike Fighter, the Air Force was starting a
battle within the Pentagon and was signaling Congress that it could
not tolerate the loss of the F-22. The strategy indicated a
willingness to barter away the Joint Strike Fighter so Congress
would not kill financing for the F-22, which would be the most
expensive jet in history at a projected cost of at least $125
million a plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a solution to not funding the Joint Strike Fighter:
upgrades of old systems,'' the senior Air Force official said.
``It's easier to imagine using older systems instead of the Joint
Strike Fighter for the Air Force. It's possible but not ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides angering the Navy and the Marines, the Air Force
strategy would probably be opposed by Secretary of Defense William
Cohen, who has been adamant that all three services support the
Joint Strike Fighter, which was to become the workhorse for the
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force can't make a decision on the JSF because it is
being built for several services,'' said Kenneth Bacon, a Pentagon
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But after the NATO air war over Kosovo, which U.S. pilots,
aircraft and weaponry took credit for winning, the Air Force has
had a loud voice both in the Pentagon and in Congress _ and that
has the Navy and the Marines worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of a service willing to eat their second-
and third-born children to keep the first-born child alive,'' said
a senior Pentagon official opposed to the Air Force position on the
jet. ``It's an example of their fascination with fighter jets and
their willingness to do anything to keep the F-22 alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it clear that all members of Congress would be impressed
with the Air Force argument about abandoning the Joint Strike
Fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerry Lewis, the California Republican whose Appropriations
subcommittee originally recommended against financing the F-22,
said it was unimaginable ``that anyone at the Pentagon would be
seriously thinking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Pentagon has pursued its fighter modernization program,
Lewis and other senior congressional leaders have questioned
whether the United States can afford $350 billion over the next
decade to develop three fighter jets: the F-22, the Joint Strike
Fighter, and the Navy's Super Hornet.
</P>
<P>
   Congress indicated a willingness earlier in this year's budget
battle to kill financing for the F-22, but relented and preserved
$2.5 billion for research and development. The Air Force has made
the F-22 a priority because it would be the next generation
air-to-air combat fighter with stealth capabilities and advanced
computer and radar systems.
</P>
<P>
   Canceling one of the programs would save up to $3.8 billion a
year, according to a study by the Center for Strategic and
Budgetary Assessments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The JSF is the most vulnerable because it's not even in
production,'' said Steven M. Kosiak, author of the study. ``The
idea of deferring the Joint Strike Fighter makes a lot of sense
because, through modifications and upgrades, you can use the F-16
as an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   At an average cost of $30 million a plane, the Joint Strike
Fighter is considered inexpensive, although the project could cost
$223 billion, according to the Congressional Budget Office. Boeing
and Lockheed Martin are competing for that contract, the largest in
military history.
</P>
<P>
   The project was intended to show that the Pentagon could build a
plane with cutting-edge technology at a low cost for three
services. But that would require the Air Force to buy 1,763 planes,
or more than half of the 2,752 Joint Strike Fighters scheduled to
be produced. The Marines would buy 609 of their model, which can
take off and land without a runway; the Navy would buy 380 planes
that would be modified to operate off aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the Air Force were to drop the Joint Strike Fighter,
it would not change our needs,'' said Capt. Aisha M. Bakkar-Poe, a
Marine spokeswoman.``We need it. We need it on time, and we are
very confident that some means will be found where we would be able
to field that aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Top Pentagon officials agreed, and say they believed the Air
Force might be overreacting to the battle they faced in Congress
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
