s f BC-INVEST-APPLE-COMPUTER     10-22 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-APPLE-COMPUTER-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO PLAY THE INTERNET, WITH APPLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of Apple stock and earnings is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to look at Apple Computer Inc. in a different
light: as an Internet stock. As Apple points out in advertising for
new versions of its popular iMac computer, 90 percent of iMac
owners are connected to the Internet _ an astonishingly high share
_ and most of them got wired the first day they owned the machine.
So maybe Apple is an Internet platform company.
</P>
<P>
   Consider also that the latest versions of the Macintosh
operating system contain a metasearch tool called Sherlock that
links to powerful Web engines, like Alta Vista, Infoseek, Lycos and
Hotbot, and prioritizes their results.
</P>
<P>
   In MAC OS 9, Apple's latest version of the operating system,
which shipped last week, the improved Sherlock 2 channels make
searching easier and more powerful by grouping similar sources
together and returning more relevant results. It also adds a
shopping channel. So maybe Apple is an Internet portal company.
</P>
<P>
   Add the vast number of sites running video using Apple's
Quicktime technology, or created on Macintoshes running
Web-designing tools like Adobe's InDesign and you have a liberal
sprinkling of Internet pixie dust.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the 80.6 percent run-up in Apple shares this year,
to $73.9375 on Friday, they still trade at a discount to those of
other personal computer manufacturers like Dell Computer or
Gateway, let alone to a pure Internet play like Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has a price-to-earnings ratio of 23.2, versus 53.9 for
Dell and 45.1 for Gateway. (Yahoo's market capitalization is over
100 times trailing 12-month revenues; its P/E ratio is not
considered meaningful, because its net income is so small.)
</P>
<P>
   With numbers like these, some analysts say there is still strong
potential for an increase in Apple's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has been on a roll since its co-founder, Steven P. Jobs,
returned in 1997 as interim chief executive. The successful launch
of the iMac a little over a year ago was followed by splashy
rollouts of the G3 desktop machines, new G3 Powerbooks and the
iMac's portable cousin, the iBook.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seemed that Jobs and company could walk on water,
they stumbled in the third quarter, announcing a shortfall in
earnings early because of inadequate chip supplies for the new G4
desktops and flat-panel displays for the iBook.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get the fastest versions of the G4 microprocessor in
time, Apple cut the speed rating of the new G4 machines by 50
megahertz without cutting prices. Then, in a move that surely
tested even devoted Mac loyalists, the company canceled existing
orders, only to reinstate them later for anyone who ordered before
Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Apple managed to beat analysts' revised estimates, as well as
its own predictions, by 6 cents a share for the fourth fiscal
quarter and predicted a strong December quarter. Of 20 analysts
polled by First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company
earnings, six rated Apple as a strong buy, six as a buy, seven as a
hold and one as a weak sell.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Mazzucchelli of Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York is among
those calling it a strong buy, with a 12-month price target of $90.
``There's more growth to come,'' Mazzucchelli said, ``and if you
look at how much negative perception there is still in the market,
that shows you the potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's prospects as an Internet play are an added bonus for
what is already a robust growth story, said Mazzucchelli, noting
that the company received orders for 150,000 iMacs in the three
months after its introduction, but booked 250,000 orders for the
new models in just one week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple's not talking about it,'' he said, ``but should they
find a way to leverage their immense Internet installed base, which
is growing at a huge rate, you can make a case for at least part of
the business to be valued as an Internet company.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple executives have been coy about possible Internet service
offerings, saying only that they have nothing to say now.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts are bullish on Apple's Internet prospects. ``I
don't think Apple can reinvent itself, but I do think it can
rejuvenate itself via the Web,'' said Geoffrey Moore, president of
the Chasm Group, a Silicon Valley consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover, as the market migrates from product to service,
Microsoft isn't getting it. Steve might get it,'' he said,
referring to Jobs and adding that a truly distinctive Apple
Internet service could prove a winner if it attracts enough Mac
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much money would Mac loyalists part with? I think quite a
lot, if the experience were truly Mac-like,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Apple is busy adding loyalists through the iMac. The
company is establishing the iMac as the slickest platform for
surfing the Web, much as the original Macintosh was the clear
choice for desktop publishing or today's Wintel machines are the
standard for running Microsoft Office.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has established its Internet status ``in very subtle
ways,'' said Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, who also
has a 12-month target of $90 on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't beat you over the head saying `we're an Internet
company,''' he said. ``They've done it with their platform, and,
suddenly, with the launch of the new iMacs, it dawns on everybody.
Their claims are not overstated and they're really starting to pan
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5599 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-GLOBAL-TRADE-2TAK     10-22 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-GLOBAL-TRADE-2TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CHIEF EXECUTIVE AT CENTER OF DISPUTE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELIZABETH OLSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ It was a formula that worked for decades: arcane
technical expertise plus family control plus Swiss security and
stability. And it made Societe Generale de Surveillance the world
leader in the obscure but vital field of cargo inspection and
verification.
</P>
<P>
   After 80 years in business, so many buyers, sellers and customs
officials around the globe had come to depend on SGS to inspect and
certify goods being imported or exported and to curb customs fraud
that the company amassed a commanding market share _ estimated at
70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Then the wheels came off. In late 1997, Swiss authorities
accused the company of having made payments to Pakistani political
leaders, including former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and her
husband, to secure a major contract with the government of
Pakistan. Though apparently no Swiss laws were broken, the scandal
cost SGS the contract and threw the company into tumult.
</P>
<P>
   Squirming in an unaccustomed spotlight of harsh publicity, SGS
has since replaced its management, restructured itself and embarked
on a new business strategy. But its ability to climb out of its
steep downturn has been hampered by public squabbling among its
directors and awkward questions about Swiss-style corporate
governance.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the turbulence is Elisabeth Salina Amorini, 44,
a lawyer and the granddaughter of a founder of SGS. Mrs. Salina, as
she is known, joined the company's board in her 20s and went on to
serve as chairwoman and chief executive, a very rare role for a
woman in Swiss business circles.
</P>
<P>
   At odds with her is another SGS director, the Munich-based
financier August von Finck, sometimes called ``the silent baron''
for his reclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Salina resigned as chief executive in August 1998 and as
chairwoman last October after SGS reported that its profits were
collapsing, driven down by the cancellation of contracts with
Pakistan and Indonesia and by the sharp contraction in Asian trade
caused by the region's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   She was succeeded in the chairman's post by Max Amstutz, an
associate of von Finck. A long-time company executive, Antony
Czura, became chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, SGS reported a loss of about $210 million on
revenues of $2.29 billion, after years of steady profits. During
the year, the company's stock plummeted to 230.5 Swiss francs a
share from 3,565 francs in 1997; it has rebounded and slumped again
several times since and closed on Friday at 1,700 Swiss francs, or
about $1,150.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mrs. Salina has been able to retain the backing of an
important group of shareholders and to keep her seat on the
company's board, where she remains a controversial figure. Her
critics blame her for the company's troubles and say she is
domineering and tries to cling to authority, derisively referring
to her as ``Queen Elisabeth.'' Supporters say she has championed
shareholders' rights and served the company loyally, if
imperfectly.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions in SGS's board room burst into the headlines here
in May with an extraordinary snub of Mrs. Salina. Swiss law makes
directors liable for their corporate actions unless the company's
board approves an annual release, as most companies routinely do.
But SGS's board voted not to release Mrs. Salina for 1998, exposing
her to legal action for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous!'' Mrs. Salina fumed during an interview at
her home in an elegant Geneva neighborhood. ``I was treated like a
criminal.'' She accused Amstutz of orchestrating the move to punish
her for refusing to resign from the board.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The board met in emergency session an hour before the scheduled
annual meeting and voted to nullify the voting rights of nearly
half the company's shares. Those shares, held in a pool, mainly
belonged to the families of Jacques Salmanowitz, Mrs. Salina's
grandfather, and the other founders of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Shares belonging to von Finck, Deutsche Bank and Swiss Life were
also part of the pool. Since then the pool has splintered. The
family shareholders, who hold 27 percent of the company, are
contesting the board's action in court, while von Finck and Swiss
Life have withdrawn from the pool and increased their stakes a bit,
to 13.6 percent and 7 percent. Deutsche Bank. with 3 percent,
remains in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Amstutz accused Mrs. Salina of ``not doing a
proper job'' and neglecting the commercial side of the business in
favor of government contracts, which generated almost 88 percent of
SGS's net income in 1997. Amstutz, 70, a veteran of Holderbank, the
huge cement concern, denied that Mrs. Salina had been singled out
unfairly, though she was the only director not given a release.
</P>
<P>
   Conceding that the move was ``highly unusual,'' Amstutz said,
``This is a clear signal that the board is not satisfied, and that
we can go to court against her.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts say a suit against her would be unlikely to succeed
because of the difficulty of proving a direct link between the
actions of one executive or director and movements in the company's
stock price.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Mrs. Salina said that while she was in charge she
acted only in concert with other directors and executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made mistakes, but the biggest one was not insisting after
two years that we find another CEO,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She is holding fast to her board seat. ``Unless they vote me
out,'' she said, referring to stockholders, ``I will serve.''
</P>
<P>
   The board-room drama has called into question not only SGS's
reputation for integrity and stability, which is crucial to its
business, but also the adequacy of shareholder protection in
Switzerland. The censure of Mrs. Salina was approved by only 14
percent of the outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an alibi to move her out, and it violates basic tenets
of corporate governance,'' said Andre Baladi, a Geneva financier
and a minor SGS shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Some shareholders worry that von Finck is trying to force Mrs.
Salina and the other 56 founding family members to sell out,
enabling him to acquire SGS without paying a takeover premium.
Company representatives said von Finck would not respond to
requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   SGS has signed five new government contracts so far this year,
but it remains stung by its difficulties in navigating what can be
a murky line between legitimate commissions and illegal bribes. It
has adopted a new code of ethics barring any payments to secure
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it _ the Pakistan incident and the
other problems have damaged SGS on all fronts,'' said Czura, the
chief executive. ``It made everybody realize that we had to change
or the brand would be irrevocably damaged.'' Czura was interviewed
in the company's temporary offices because its historic
headquarters building is being expensively refurbished _ another of
Mrs. Salina's decisions that has drawn criticism.
</P>
<P>
   To repair its bottom line, SGS has sold off insurance, health
care and biotechnology subsidiaries to concentrate on agricultural,
mineral and oil inspection services, consumer product verification,
international certification and government services. It is aiming
to reduce its payroll from 40,000 last year to 32,000 by next June.
</P>
<P>
   Czura said he expected the company's turnaround to take three
years. The losses have stopped, and SGS forecasts a profit of $66
million for 1999. But Pierre Tissot, an analyst at Lombard Odier
here, wants to wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've done so far is only a first step,'' Tissot said.
``They have a long way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
