<HEADLINE>
ALLISON'S ACHES ADD TO BRUIN'S WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The hits just keep on coming for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jason Allison left practice early Friday because of a
sore left wrist. That's not to be confused with his ailing right
forearm and wrist that have hampered Allison since the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Allison injured his left wrist during practice Tuesday in
Phoenix prior to the club's departure for Los Angeles when he
collided with teammate Hal Gill. It felt better the next day and he
was able to play against the Kings, but he said it was made worse.
</P>
<P>
   Allison said if the wrist feels Saturday like it did Friday, he
won't be able to suit up for Saturday night's game against the San
Jose Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to the net and I turned and I didn't see him,''
said Allison, who jammed the wrist into Gill's chest. ``It hurt,
but then it went away and felt better. Then after the game, I did
it a couple of times again and aggravated it.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrist was very swollen Friday, and Allison wasn't able to do
much during the team's workout at the Ice Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a coincidence, bad luck,'' said Allison. ``I don't
even want to talk to (trainer Don Del Negro) about it because
enough is enough with this kind of thing. I just tried to go out
and ignore it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Allison, the wrist wouldn't allow him to
ignore it. He said he didn't know what was wrong with it, but
didn't think anything was broken. He said he thinks it could be a
sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it feels like it did (Friday), I wouldn't be able to
play,'' he said. ``I couldn't even make a hard pass. But that could
be the swelling, too. I haven't taken any anti-inflammatories yet.
It's pretty sore.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said his right forearm and wrist were actually improving
to the point where he could take faceoffs. But in the game against
the Kings, Allison, who won four draws and lost just one, had to
stop taking them because his arm was acting up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to feel it again,'' he said. ``I took a couple
of big draws, one in our own end. I started feeling it again so I
said I couldn't take any more. I might have taken one if it was on
the right side at the end of the game. It's something I have to
feel out. If it starts to get a little sore, I have to lay off
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison is also still hampered by a sprained ankle he suffered
just prior to the start of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to talk about that,'' he said, a healthy
dose of frustration in his voice. ``It's not really bothering me in
games. But I've felt it a couple of times lately; it might just be
tired maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goaltender Rob Tallas won't be able to play Saturday night.
Tallas took a shot off the right ankle during warmups Wednesday in
Los Angeles, but was still outstanding in the tie with Kings. John
Grahame will get the start, but it's possible Tallas will be in the
pipes for the trip finale in Anaheim Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sore still,'' said Tallas, who made 38 saves
against the Kings. ``I felt fine out there (Friday), but as
practice wore on, you could feel it getting sorer and sorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas has been consulting with Bruins goalie coach Gerry
Cheevers by phone. Tallas said Cheevers has encouraged him to be
more aggressive against shooters. Tallas thinks it has made a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas met up with former Bruins therapist Tim Trahant, who is
living out West and going to acupuncture school. Tallas said
Trahant treated him with acupuncture the day before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed it,'' he said. ``It's different. It's more of
a difference in your mind at first. I didn't know if I believed in
it or not, but it was a fun thing to do and it was a good
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Rob DiMaio, who injured his hip and missed the game
in Los Angeles, skated Friday. ``It feels pretty good,'' said
DiMaio. ``It's up to (coach Pat Burns), but I'll tell him I think
I'm OK.'' . . . Burns put Landon Wilson on the right wing with
center Joe Thornton and left wing Sergei Samsonov. ``We'll try
it,'' said Burns. ``We'll see what happens.'' Wilson played a
strong game against the Kings . . . Assistant coach Jacques
Laperriere was on the injured list Friday. He twisted his knee
earlier in the trip, and had to stay off skates because of the
swelling.
</P>
</TEXT>
