<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MEMPHIS-DEVELOP-ART-2     10-22 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMPHIS-DEVELOP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD HATS AND CRANES ABLOOM IN MEMPHIS' CITY CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Texas, Ga., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Fourteen years ago, Dean Jernigan, son of a
carpenter and a department store clerk, sensed the stirrings of a
trend. ``I saw major consumption,'' he said, ``a society that likes
to collect things.'' Too many things for attics and storerooms.
</P>
<P>
   So Jernigan built some you-rent-it garages on Summer Avenue, the
street where an entrepreneur opened the nation's first Holiday Inn
in 1952. Jernigan turned out to have been similarly prescient.
Society's itch to consume and collect became an engine of the
nation's most prosperous, most acquisitive decade in at least a
century. More than 300,000 customers are now paying Jernigan's
Storage USA from $60 to $200 a month to park the jetsam of their
affluence in 34 million square feet of garages in 31 states at 500
sites, including 30 in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   His good fortune is contributing to a rebirth of Memphis'
downtown. Ravaged since the 1970s by white flight to the eastern
reaches of the city and the Shelby County suburbs beyond, the city
center is now abloom with hard hats and cranes.
</P>
<P>
   With several big projects under way among the boarded-over
buildings and check-cashing shops, downtown Memphis is savoring the
bounty of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of prosperity filtering through hundreds of
communities these days. Previously whipsawed by three- or four-year
spurts of growth that crashed in recessions, most cities are
reaping unaccustomed benefits from the nearly nine years of
uninterrupted economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of many cities like Dallas, Nashville and Atlanta has
been orchestrated by coteries of business and political leaders.
But there is less such cohesion in Memphis. Instead, this city has
sprung open to the fantasies of businessmen who with more freedom
than those of many other cities can go off and build something big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memphis is not an establishment-driven city,'' Henry M.
Turley, a leading downtown developer, said. ``It is an
entrepreneurial city.''
</P>
<P>
   In Memphis, prosperity has broken out in all directions.
Jernigan is building the city's first downtown baseball park, a
$75-million, five-story, 14,000-seat home for the Redbirds, a minor
league team of the St. Louis Cardinals. Jernigan, 53, and his wife
and partner in philanthropy, Kristi, 36, bought the team and
brought it to Memphis. They are renovating the abandoned William R.
Moore Building, adjacent to the ball park, for a new home for
Storage USA, including an apartment for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Directly east, out Poplar Avenue beyond midtown, toward the
suburbs of Germantown and Collierville, cheek-by-jowl neo-Colonial
mansions and upscale malls are replacing older, midscale, mostly
closer-in malls built in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary art galleries, new for Memphis, have opened. At the
four-year-old Ledbetter Lusk Gallery on Poplar Avenue, David Lusk,
an owner, points to a large surreal painting by Colin McLain,
formerly of Memphis, now of New York and Provincetown, Mass. It
depicts faceless men in black and white striped prison suits. The
suits have vests and white collars. They might be swindlers and
frauds, or they might be the workaholic slaves of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Colin McLain could not have sold here 10 years ago, even for
$1,000,'' Lusk said. ``That one is $4,500. Our average price now is
probably $5,000, $6,000.''
</P>
<P>
   A little south of the upscale mall housing the gallery is the
big Mall of Memphis, once a citywide center of shopping, now
catering mostly to black Memphians. At least six shops sell
jewelry, mostly watches priced below $1,000 and gold bracelets and
chains for men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south is a wholly different kind of commerce. Running
mile upon mile along Shelby Drive, past the airport and runways of
Federal Express and the new sorting plant of United Parcel Service,
are the low-lying blocks of mostly gray, largely windowless
buildings with the gaping square holes of loading docks, a mark of
the city's emergence as the leading jet-age cargo hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the general cargo warehousing business,'' said W.
Neely Mallory, who has moved onto Shelby Drive, far beyond the
cotton warehouses downtown that built the family fortune. ``We're
in everything from rolls of paper to bubble gum to Nintendo
games.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The speed with which all those goods come and go sharpens
Memphis' edge in today's economy, Mallory said. At midcontinent
intersections of road, river and air traffic, Memphis has
positioned itself to exploit modern industry's demand for
just-in-time delivery of goods at the instant that factories,
stores and consumers need them and not a day before.
</P>
<P>
   It is downtown, however, where prosperity is blinding.
Employment in construction, most of it downtown and at the airport,
has jumped nearly 60 percent in seven years. Besides the new
stadium, developers are rebuilding Beale Street, the railroad
station and the convention center. New office buildings, movie
theaters, condominiums and stores are opening in century-old
shells.
</P>
<P>
   W.J. Michael Cody, 63, former U.S. attorney for the Western
District of Tennessee, works for a 91-year-old law firm downtown,
housed in an exotic Romanesque three-story building that was once
the home of the now-defunct Tennessee Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting ready to spend $4 million for a new four-story
building to tie into this one,'' Cody said. ``The prosperity has
been translated into our confidence to spend that kind of money and
make a commitment to downtown Memphis. We wouldn't have done it in
a less prosperous time.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown development has been spurred, too, by the Shelby County
mayor, Jim Rout, and by the Memphis mayor, Willie Herenton, who
recently won re-election to a third four-year term. They have
provided generous tax breaks and regulatory relief to give
developers incentives to build.
</P>
<P>
   One agent of the downtown's rebirth is Joseph R. Hyde III, 56,
who founded Autozone, a nationwide chain of 2,700 car-repair shops
that he started in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Hyde, known by the nickname Pitt, put his corporate
headquarters on the site of an abandoned cotton warehouse, the
first company to build downtown in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have done it if Pitt Hyde hadn't done it,''
Jernigan said of his own decision to move into the Moore Building.
Hyde is paying $3.75 million for 25-year rights to name the ball
field Autozone Park, and he is now leading the fund-raising to
expand the National Civil Rights Museum, site of the assassination
of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and a top tourist
attraction.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   An earlier agent of downtown revival was Jack Belz, 71.
Twenty-four years ago, Belz paid $675,000 for the opulent old
Peabody Hotel, which was then shuttered, and said he had poured $45
million into restoring it.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, in partnership with Turley, Belz has expanded
into developing close-in and stylish, high- and middle-income
houses on the South Bluffs of the Mississippi riverfront and on Mud
Island, a sandbar in the Mississippi separated from downtown by the
narrow Wolf River.
</P>
<P>
   Turley has built his home in South Bluffs, one with a goldfish
pond in the vestibule, buttons he flicks like light switches to
fill the house with the blues and jazz, and soaring glass walls
overlooking his black-bottom pool, the wide Mississippi and the
forest beyond.
</P>
<P>
   With his tie loose and seat belt unfastened, he takes the wheel
of his silver BMW convertible sports car and rolls out his
cobblestone driveway for a tour of the more than $200 million in
projects he has developed in and around downtown.
</P>
<P>
   He passes Cordelia's, the grocery store he built and named for
his mother, and the two riverfront warehouses where he is building
loft apartments. He passes his and Belz's 132-acre Harbor Town
development on Mud Island and crosses the Wolf River back to the
mainland and the north side of town. He comes to the bleak, partly
boarded-over Hurt Village and Lauderdale Courts, two public housing
projects filled with crime and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Belz and Turley have agreed to forgo their customary profit to
manage the rehabilitation of the 1,000 living units there for
mixed-income, public and private housing.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with his new prosperity, Turley said: ``You got a big old
wad of money in your pocket. The rich economy gives you economic
resources, and it gives you psychic resources.'' Whether for good
or for evil, he said, ``it enables you to do more of what you want
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In Memphis, the building is a spontaneous eruption. Local
government has helped fuel it with financial incentives. But
Memphis, unlike Dallas or Atlanta or Pittsburgh, lacks a boss or a
large and coherent coterie of business leaders to join the
government in steering development.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, a blue-blood class of cotton, lumber and
warehousing merchants ruled Memphis. Through the most of the first
half of this century, the Tammany-like boss Edward H. Crump was in
charge, but he leaned on the merchant clans to get things done.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, such an absence of coherent leadership can
be a problem. Herman C. Ewing, president and chief executive of the
Memphis Urban League, said: ``We have difficulty getting consensus
on items that warrant answers, like tax policy and development. We
live in a city where the merit of an idea takes second place to who
endorses it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
