<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGREEMENT TO OVERHAUL NATION'S FINANCIAL SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and top Republican lawmakers agreed
to overhaul the nation's financial system, repealing Depression-era
laws that have restricted the banking, securities and insurance
industries from expanding into one another's businesses. The
agreement, reached after a compromise over lending rules for the
disadvantaged, concludes decades of attempts to rewrite the
nation's banking laws and catch up with a marketplace that has
already seen broad consolidations. ``It's probably the most heavily
lobbied, most expensive issue to come before Congress in a
generation,'' said Ed Yingling, the American Bankers Association's
chief lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   MANNESMANN IN VODAFONE SIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone Airtouch, the world's leading mobile phone operator, is
said to be considering a hostile bid for Mannesmann of Germany, its
partner turned rival with its purchase of Orange, another British
wireless company. Vodafone insisted in public that its relationship
with Mannesmann was unchanged, but British press reports said
Vodafone's chief executive, Christopher Gent, was furious at the
German company.
</P>
<P>
   CLOUDS LIFT OVER WALL STREET JOURNAL
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal's managing editor, Paul Steiger, turned
down an offer to head all financial news operations at CNN, ending
more than a week of uncertainty. Also, company and labor union
negotiators resolved a fight over retirement benefits, ending more
than seven months of sometimes-tense talks.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE MANAGEMENT TO TAKE CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, the nation's largest trash hauler, said that
it expected to take a third-quarter charge and have lower 1999
earnings because an audit found irregularities with its accounting.
It did not estimate the size.
</P>
<P>
   SCHWAB'S WEB SITE IN 2-HOUR CRASH
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab's Web trading site failed for almost two hours,
the third disruption in three days, because of a software problem.
The firm is the largest Internet broker.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS SURGE ON BANK BILL OPTIMISM
</P>
<P>
   Stocks powered ahead as traders saw the banking bill paving the
way for big financial mergers. The Dow Jones industrial average
gained 172.56 points, to end at 10,470.25. For the week, the Dow
was up 450.54 points, its best weekly gain since July. The Nasdaq
composite index rose 14.57, to 2,816.52, and the S.&AMP;P. 500 index
added 18.04, to 1,301.65.
</P>
<P>
   STIFF COMPETITION FOR EL AL ORDER
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Airbus Industrie are competing aggressively for a
$400 million order from El Al. That is not large by industry
standards, but the Israeli deal is of symbolic importance, and
politicians are weighing in, too.
</P>
<P>
   BP AMOCO SETBACK IN RUSSIAN DEAL
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco has suffered a harsh setback in its struggle to
preserve a $571 million investment in Sidanko, a bankrupt Russian
oil conglomerate. Tyumen Oil, a Sidanko rival, acquired
Kondpetroleum, a bankrupt oil producing subsidiary of Sidanko.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD BANK INVESTIGATES RUSSIAN
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank is investigating Leonid Grigoriev, a former
member of Russia's delegation. He is suspected of secretly passing,
for payments, information about the World Bank's plans to aid the
Russian economy to Inkombank, a Moscow bank whose license has been
revoked. He was placed on leave from a Moscow research group.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. WITHDRAWS BACKING FOR DRUG
</P>
<P>
   A federal health advisory panel withdrew its recommendation that
all infants be immunized against the virus that causes a severe
diarrhea after the vaccine was linked to a potentially fatal bowel
obstruction. The manufacturer, American Home Products, withdrew the
vaccine from the market last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
