<SLUG> BC-MA-REGATTA-CHARLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROWERS FROM ALL OVER THE WORLD CONVERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The scullers sat around a couple of tables at
the Cambridge Boat Club Friday afternoon, catching up on what
they've been up to since August and St. Catharines. There was Jamie
Koven and Leslie Burns Rawley, Luka Spik and Rumiana Neikova, Juri
Jaanson and Marnie McBean and another half dozen of the global
elite, talking shop on the eve of the world's largest two-day
rowing regatta.
</P>
<P>
   The Head of the Charles, which will take over the river for the
35th time Saturday and Sunday, is more than a monster boat race.
It's the autumnal gathering of the clan, the last chance to
converse and compete before the ice sets in.
</P>
<P>
   The Head is 6,500 rowers from more than two dozen countries
competing in 40 races. It's faxes and e-mails zipping across
oceans, Cambridge phones ringing on Slovenian time, tents rigged
along Memorial Drive from Harvard down to Boston University,
borrowed shells and oars, oarsmen from Bulgaria sleeping on futons
in Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing like this at home,'' says Georgina Douglas,
Australia's top female sculler. ``We have the Head of the Yarra,
with maybe 100 crews.''
</P>
<P>
   There'll be 156 crews in Saturday afternoon's club eights alone.
When the first event was held in 1965 (patterned after the
traditional Head of the River races in England) only two boats had
entered by the deadline, forcing organizers to work the phones to
get the list up to a respectable 90.
</P>
<P>
   This year, more than 10,000 rowers wanted in. The Head has long
since become the aquatic Woodstock. What the Boston Marathon is to
road racing, the Head of the Charles is to rowing. If you pull an
oar anywhere from New Zealand to Croatia, you want to dip it in the
Rivah, just once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity you can't miss,'' says Douglas, who flew
from Melbourne via Auckland and Los Angeles on Tuesday to race here
and will head Down Under again on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's more than the class reunion aspect that attracts. The Head
offers a unique challenge _ 3 miles upstream on a river that can be
placid or roiling, with winds blowing heads here, tails there,
racing single file against the clock under half a dozen bridges
with 300,000 people watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to race flat out and look around at the same
time,'' said Koven, who'll be chasing his third straight men's
singles crown Sunday. ``It's tough not to know how you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Head race, the guy who's overtaking you might be a mile
downstream. When Koven won two years ago, he didn't know he had
until they told him. ``I had absolutely no idea,'' he said. ``I
started in the middle of the pack. I knew I had a good race, but. .
.''
</P>
<P>
   At the championship level where the world medalists are, a good
race is the minimum required these days. Now that race officials
have made a point of bringing in top international talent, Sunday's
marquee events are nearing World Cup level.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the charm of the Head is its universality and its
informality. A boatload of urban high school girls from O'Bryant in
Boston's Roxbury section can line up in the same race with the
Radcliffe novices. The US men's crew, which won the world title a
dozen years ago, can take on the U.S. crew that did it two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   A sweep oarsman can switch to sculling and challenge a gold
medalist just for fun. A sculler can step into an eight and race
against the Germans. Halloween is but a week away. Why not change
your identity on the water?
</P>
<P>
   The Head is rowing's masked ball. Crew names can be obscure,
misleading. The Princeton Training Center is the US men's eight.
The Alte Achter Boat Club is the 1972 US Olympic crew, silver
medals still untarnished.
</P>
<P>
   But what is the Black Sheep Rowing Club? The Rude &AMP; Smooth BC?
The Fat Cat RC? Do the Arsenal Diner Chow Hounds eat on the paddle?
Do their own mothers recognize the Wide Load Boat Club?
</P>
<P>
   No matter. If they know port from starboard, can row 3 miles and
can meet the entry requirements, they are welcome to go bow to bow
with Olympians at the gathering of the clan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
