<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-BARNES&AMP;NOBLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON SUES BIG BOOKSELLER OVER SYSTEM FOR SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazon.com has filed suit against its rival Internet book and
music seller Barnesandnoble.com, accusing it of illegally copying
Amazon's patented checkout system and demanding an immediate end to
its use.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed on Thursday night in U.S. District Court in
Seattle, is the latest chapter in a storied and sometimes litigious
rivalry. But if Amazon.com is successful in the suit, it could have
broad ramifications for the development of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers that use variations of the popular ``one click''
checkout method, which allows customers to make repeat purchases
with one click of the mouse instead of having to fill out credit
card and billing information with each shopping trip, could be
forced to desist or pay a licensing fee to Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon stopped short of saying that was its goal, but the
possibility was not lost on it. ``This litigation just goes to
Barnesandnoble.com,'' said an Amazon spokesman, Bill Curry. ``But
we clearly have a patent, and this is a sign we want to protect our
intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon started using one-click technology in September 1997, but
did not receive a patent for it until Sept. 28 this year.
Barnesandnoble has offered Express Lane, its one-click checkout,
since early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one-click feature is one of Amazon.com's signature
strategies for differentiating itself from the competition and
building loyalty among its customers,'' Amazon wrote in its
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Customer loyalty is especially important to Amazon now, as the
company is expanding well beyond its original book format to
electronics and toys and all manner of items in hopes of becoming
the Internet shopper's primary destination. Arguing that the
infringement is causing irreparable harm, Amazon is seeking
monetary damages and an immediate injunction preventing
Barnesandnoble.com from using Express Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com called the lawsuit an attempt to retaliate
for its growing popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the allegations to be completely without merit, and
we will vigorously defend our position,'' said a spokesman, Gus
Carlson. ``Traffic to our Web site was up substantially today
because of the publicity. We thank our competitor for the
incremental sales.''
</P>
<P>
   The two mammoths of book-selling have a colorful history of
feuding that includes both threatened and actual litigation. In
1997, Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc., the parent company of
barnesandnoble.com, filed suit against Amazon claiming that its
slogan, World's Largest Bookstore, was false advertising. The suit
was settled out of court with neither side paying damages.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Amazon made threatening noises when Barnes &AMP; Noble
tried to acquire the distributor Ingram Book Group. The deal was
canceled, and litigation was never initiated.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and patent experts differ on the strength of Amazon's
case, but agree that the effect could be far reaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this patent did hold up, it could put a damper on Internet
growth,'' said Ken Cassar, a digital commerce analyst at Jupiter
Communications, an Internet research firm. He estimates that half
the retail sites on the Web have an ``automated wallet'' _ a
process that stores billing and address data for repeat customers.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce companies are increasingly turning to patents to
protect their business interests. Last week, Priceline.com filed a
patent infringement lawsuit against Microsoft saying that the
software giant's Expedia.com site had copied its model of allowing
customers to bid for plane tickets and hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the first of what will be a bloody round of
patent wars on the Web,'' predicted David Kline, author of
``Rembrandts in the Attic: Unlocking the Hidden Value of Patents,''
to be published by Harvard Business School Press in January.
</P>
<P>
   Patents covering software or programming related to Web sites
are the fastest-growing sector at the U.S. Patent Office, said
Robert Greene Sterne, of the Washington-based intellectual property
law firm of Sterne, Kessler, Goldstein &AMP; Fox. He said the suits
might over the long term give a real advantage to Web companies
that were the first to build technological applications that
everyone else wants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
