<SLUG> BC-FBC-WARRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FSU'S WARRICK REINSTATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEMSON, S.C. _ In the middle of the hoopla surrounding the
Bowden family reunion for Saturday night's game between Clemson and
Florida State, another element was added Friday _ the return of
All-American and once-Heisman Trophy frontrunner Peter Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' senior wide receiver was reinstated to the team
Friday and is expected to play after school president Sandy
D'Alemberte agreed to let Warrick plead guilty to a lesser charge
of misdemeanor petty theft rather than the felony charge Warrick
originally faced after he and a teammate received more than $400
dollars of designer clothes at more than a 90 percent discount at a
Tallahassee department store earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   A new university law prohibits any athlete convicted of a felony
charge from participating in intercollegiate athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick still must serve 30 days on a work program, pay $295 in
court costs, and $579 in restitution to the Tallahassee store. He
is also on one-year's probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the support shown me through this,'' Warrick said
in an apologetic statement released by the school. ``I am glad to
get the chance to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, arguably the best receiver in college football and a
prime contender for the Heisman Trophy, missed two games during the
investigation, essentially dropping him from the Heisman race.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was reached after 48 hours of heavy negotiations
in which Warrick's lawyers argued against any jail time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out for the best,'' said Seminoles coach Bobby
Bowden, ``but it was a screwed up mess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has paid the consequences for his mistake and then some,''
Florida State athletic director Dave Hart Jr. said. ``It's time to
move past it.''
</P>
<P>
   Warricks' lawyer, John Kenny, called the settlement fair for his
client, the state, the school, and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not wearing stripes, he's not in jail, and that's a
significant determining factor for the university,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
