<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ZAPOTEC-SCHOLAR-NYT &LR;      10-22 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPOTEC-SCHOLAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDIAN BECOMES A SCHOLAR AND HELPS WRITE THE FIRST ZAPOTEC
DICTIONARY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico, Calif.)   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first thing you should know about Felipe
Lopez, who immigrated from Oaxaca 21 years ago in the trunk of a
smuggler's car, is that his name is not really Felipe Lopez, and
that he does not really consider himself Mexican.
</P>
<P>
   True, Felipe Lopez is the name on his legal documents, but in
his native Indian language, and his home, his real name, he
insists, is Lieb. Mexico, he says, is a society that renders
Indians like himself all but invisible, pressuring them to
assimilate in the dominant Spanish culture. So Mexico feels less
like his true homeland, he says, than his newly adopted one, which
gave him the opportunity to sweat in hot kitchens for years earning
low wages.
</P>
<P>
   But all that, remarkably, is in the past. For the great triumph
in the life of this quietly intense man is that he has turned a
corner by finally coming to a point, after years of strife, where
he can now define himself by what he is rather than by what he is
not.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lopez, 37, is proud to call himself a Zapotec Indian and
a scholar, a man whose native language, never before written down,
now has its own two-volume dictionary. Lopez, who barely got
through the sixth grade in his home village but is a doctoral
candidate here, helped write the volumes, a Zapotec-English-Spanish
dictionary that has charted new ground in the study of Mexico's
indigenous languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think it's a dream, is this real,'' said Lopez,
sitting in his office at the University of California at Los
Angeles. ``I was taught to feel ashamed of being an Indian. I was
taught that someone like me could not think of doing this. I had to
show them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``them'' he had to show were both the many Mexicans who, he
said, look down on Indians as well as Americans who expect little
from illegal Mexican immigrants beyond cheap labor. What was
particularly striking about his achievement, several experts said,
was that it would have been difficult in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a language that would probably never have been
described if this had not been done here,'' said Pamela Munro,
Lopez's co-author and a linguist who has prepared dictionaries for
several American Indian languages. ``I don't know why there aren't
more dictionaries like this being done in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez's native language is spoken by 1,000 to 2,000 people in
his home village, San Luis Quiavini, in central Oaxaca state. It is
related to several dozen other languages generally referred to as
Zapotec, but which are distinct. The group of languages is spoken
in geographic pockets in Oaxaca by perhaps 400,000 people, Ms.
Munro said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the spread of popular culture and Spanish language
schools, she said, Zapotec and a number of other indigenous
languages in Mexico are slowly dying.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez ponders such facts with resentment. He said that he was
taught to regard Zapotec as a liability and that it was a subject
of humiliation in his contacts with the world outside his village.
</P>
<P>
   The stain of those early impressions so colored his perceptions,
he recalled, that when he first began to discuss the idea of a
dictionary with Ms. Munro six years ago, he told her that it would
be a simple project because the primitive language had a vocabulary
of perhaps 100 words. The final volumes contain more than 9,000
entries; Ms. Munro said the language, which uses a complex system
of tones, is one of the most maddeningly difficult she had
encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said that he grew up speaking no Spanish until he went to
school, and that this left him feeling marginalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids made fun of me,'' he said, ``but I didn't even understand
what they were saying.''
</P>
<P>
   He left school after the sixth grade to work on his family's
farm, and when he was 16, he began the great adventure of his life.
He took buses north and eventually slipped across the border by
paying a smuggler.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up in Los Angeles with some relatives, working as a
dishwasher in a Chinese restaurant. By then, he spoke a smattering
of Spanish, but virtually no English, leaving him feeling awed by
the new country but almost completely isolated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself, `Either I will become what they say I am, or I
will better myself,''' Lopez said. ``That was what motivated me.''
</P>
<P>
   So he worked his way through various restaurant jobs and
eventually became a cook, all the while slowly improving his
English and Spanish. He said he finally realized he could earn even
more if he could learn enough English to communicate with all the
waiters and the staff. So he decided to attend an adult education
course, an experience that lasted exactly one class.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said he was taken by surprise when the teacher asked him
to point out the parts of a sentence on the chalkboard. He said he
stood there paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what a verb was,'' he said. ``I realized I was
illiterate.''
</P>
<P>
   The bell rang, ending the painful moment, but the episode sent
him with a new found zeal on his great odyssey. He never went back
to the class, he said, but he began to teach himself the answer to
that first question: what is a verb?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez threw himself into his studies and progressed through a
series of programs after work. In 1984 he received his high school
equivalency diploma. Shortly afterward he began taking courses at
Santa Monica College, a two-year institution.
</P>
<P>
   Even after earning the two-year degree, he was reluctant to
consider going for his bachelor's degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for me,'' Lopez said he told a friend who encouraged
him to go on. ``No one in my town has even been to college. I don't
have what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   He decided, though, that he had nothing to lose, and he applied
to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost praying I wouldn't be accepted,'' Lopez said.
``If I was turned down, I thought all my problems would be solved.
I wouldn't have to face all those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was accepted, and began taking classes in the fall of
1991. He received his undergraduate degree in Latin American
studies in 1994, and his master's degree two years later. He then
entered the doctorate program in urban planning, a degree he hopes
to use to help villages like San Lucas Quiavini find ways of
developing that will not stamp out the native language and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, now married with two children, became a legal U.S.
resident under the Immigration and Reform Control Act of 1986,
which allowed Mexicans and other immigrants living illegally in
this country to obtain legal citizenship. He became a citizen in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo E. Hernandez, the director of the Chicano Studies
Research Center at UCLA and the publisher of the Zapotec
dictionary, said the project was a milestone not just for Lopez but
also for the university by making it clear that the study of Indian
cultures would be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This speaks loudly to our colleagues now that this kind of
thing will be a part of the center,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez takes some satisfaction in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of times I thought, `If it's not me, who will do it?'''
he said. ``Why did I go through all these hardships?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
