<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTING AROUND THE DECADE QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Throughout much of the 1980s, George Steinbrenner
boasted of the Yankees' won-lost record, the best in the decade, he
proudly and pointedly claimed, but Major League Baseball wasn't
giving out trophies for the best cumulative record, so the owner's
claim of superiority fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a decade later, a variation on the Steinbrenner theme has
arisen and, legitimate or not, it will be played out as the Yankees
and the Atlanta Braves play the final World Series of the 1900s.
They will meet, beginning at Turner Field on Saturday night,
against the backdrop of a questionable controversy:
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees win their third World Series in the last four
years, will they be the team of the decade? Or will it be the
Braves based on their having by far the best won-lost record and
eight consecutive division championships?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people on both teams who addressed the issue Friday
questioned the legitimacy of the designation, saying their primary
goal was to win this World Series. But David Cone acknowledged that
it made for an interesting debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not first and foremost in players' minds,'' said Cone,
the Yankees' Game 2 pitcher. ``It's not added pressure. It's nice
to be part of that debate, though.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves finished the '90s with 925 victories and 629 defeats.
The Yankees had an 851-702 record, finishing 73{ games behind the
Braves. The Yankees' record in the 80's was 854-708. This is the
Braves' fifth World Series in the '90s, but they have won only one
of the previous four. The Yankees have won the World Series twice
in the past three years, matching the pair the Toronto Blue Jays
won in 1992 and '93.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely the team of the last five years,'' Cone said.
``You want to go 8 years, 10 years, 12? Make it what you want. Team
of the decade? OK, whatever. In the '90s, the Braves are the best
in the regular season. No one could touch them. As far as World
Series championships, if we get three, nobody else has three.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves could have avoided the entire debate had they won the
World Series another time or two, in 1991, for example, when they
lost the seventh game to Minnesota, 1-0, in 10 innings; or in 1996,
when they won the first two games against the Yankees and had a 6-0
lead in Game 4. But they didn't _ thus, the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard a decade talked about as much,'' said John
Smoltz, one of the two players who has been with the Braves the
entire decade (the other is Tom Glavine). ``I never remember anyone
talking about the '80s, or the '70s. I've never seen anyone come up
with a formula to dictate who is the team. I think we get a little
carried away in the scheme of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz lamented the way others in baseball and out have
diminished the Braves' accomplishments just because they have not
won more World Series. ``I think what we've done,'' he said,
referring to the division titles, ``has caused a major dilemma
because nobody's ever done this.''
</P>
<P>
   But members of the Yankees did not belittle what the Braves had
done. Nor did they leap into the ``team of the decade'' debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could care less,'' catcher Joe Girardi said. ``We're worried
about one World Series _ 1999. How many players were here the whole
10 years? For the organization it might be important, and for the
fans to talk about it might be important. But for the players,
you're lucky if you get to play in the big leagues for five years,
let alone play for one team for a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux, the Braves' second-game starting pitcher, said the
World Series was big enough and did not need the additional hype of
a longer view of the teams competing for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want another World Series ring,'' he said. ``I want that
more than I want to be labeled the team of the '90s. They don't
really give you a ring for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hirdt is an objective but knowledgeable observer of the
relative achievements of the Braves and the Yankees. He is
executive vice president of the Elias Sports Bureau, baseball's
official statistician.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Yankees win this year, I hope the focus will be on
their winning the World Series and on this team,'' he said. But if
the focus is on team of the decade, he added, ``are they going to
have Kevin Maas and Alvaro Espinzoa come in for a celebration of
the 1990s?''
</P>
<P>
   Hirdt saluted the Braves as a ``tremendously consistent team''
but said: ``The artificiality of the decade doesn't add any luster.
It wasn't as if they were waiting for the '90s to start so they
could start winning division championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Melvin, general manager of the Texas Rangers, put the
question in perspective from the point of view of an official of a
club that is not a contender for the designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes back to that old philosophy,'' Melvin said. ``What
would you rather do, win one World Series and be in the Marlins'
situation or be like Cleveland and be a team that's there every
year but hasn't won the World Series? I ask people that question
and get various answers. Personally you'd like to win the World
Series, but you can't do it if you're not going to be a consistent
ball club and win every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have won the division championship every year (except
the no-championship strike season of 1994) that John Schuerholz has
been their general manager. He said there was no more fitting end
to the 1900s than having the teams with the best records of the
last decade playing in the final World Series.
</P>
<P>
   On the matter of team of the '90s, though, he said: ``I don't
know about that. I don't do titles or designations. We just try to
win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet a few days earlier, Schuerholz did take credit for the
Braves' accomplishments in the '90s. ``With respect to winning
world championships, they're tied for the best in this decade,'' he
said, referring to the two World Series the Yankees and the Blue
Jays have each won. ``From that perspective, I tip my cap to them.
For continuity of success, more games won, highest winning
percentage, divisions won, league championships appeared in,
winning 100 games three years in a row, I tip my hat to our
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   As he tipped his imaginary hat, though, he flashed a ring that
had engraved on the side the words ``Team of the '90s.'' When he
was asked about that phrase Friday while talking to a group of
reporters, Schuerholz did not duck the question or quickly bury his
hand in his pocket. ``Yeah,'' he said, ``but someone was kind
enough to write that, and we stole it from one of you guys, so we
can't take credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
