<HEADLINE>
FOUR CHILDREN REPORT ILLNESS FROM COKE PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four schoolchildren in Belgium said Friday that they experienced
nausea, headaches and rashes after drinking Coca-Cola products
bought from a vending machine near their school. But a spokesman
for Coca-Cola Co. in Atlanta said the soft drinks were not the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the Coca-Cola is perfectly normal and of high
quality,'' said the spokesman, Randall W. Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   One of the children, all of whom are 12 and live in Tienen, said
she felt ill after finishing off a half-liter bottle of Coke. The
other three reported similar symptoms after drinking
orange-flavored Fanta, also from a half-liter bottle. The remaining
Fanta has been sent for testing to the University of Leuven, and
results are expected today or tomorrow, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   The cola came from a plant in East Kilbride, England, owned by
Coca-Cola Enterprises, Coke's biggest bottler, Donaldson said. The
Fanta was bottled at a Coca-Cola Enterprises plant in Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
   The Antwerp plant was shut for 10 days in June by the Belgian
authorities after hundreds of people reported feeling ill after
drinking Coke products in various parts of Belgium. Some of the
products were traced to Antwerp, while others came from a plant in
Dunkirk, France.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints prompted the largest recall of Coke beverages in
company history, and about 17 million cases were destroyed after
being removed from store shelves and people's homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian police sealed off the vending machine used by the
children, in Tienen, in the eastern part of the country. Coca-Cola
executives have tested bottles from the same batch and found
nothing wrong, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the experience of last time, they need to be very
upfront and proactive in communicating to the public about this,''
said Bill Pecoriello, a beverage analyst for Sanford C. Bernstein.
``They need to cut off any concern before it snowballs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
