<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-SERVICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS REACH ACCORD TO LIFT BANKING BARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers exulted Friday that finally, after more
than two decades of work, they had agreed on a bill to tear down
the Depression-era firewalls that generally keep banks, insurance
companies, and stock brokerages from buying each other or offering
each other's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a long time, but we have finally brought our financial
services industry into the modern world,'' said Representative
Marge Roukema, Republican of New Jersey, after four days of
intensive talks between lawmakers and the White House ended with a
deal at 2 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, it is the industry that brought Congress into the
modern world.
</P>
<P>
   By winning lawsuits and ad hoc victories before regulators,
financial service companies already have eroded many of the walls
between banks, brokerages, and insurance companies. And that is why
a bill that entailed years of work and millions of lobbying dollars
may not produce noticeable changes for consumers, at least not in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business community was way ahead of the public sector on
this,'' said Senator John Kerry Friday. ``What's happening is more
a codification of what has already been going on, so that you have
a single standard that applies to the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the current laws, which were enacted after the
financial meltdown of the late 1920s and 1930s, bar banks from the
insurance business. But under a 1996 Supreme Court decision, banks
won the right to sell insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies, in turn, were barred from banking. But they
routinely offer savings products once associated only with banks,
such as CDs and investment vehicles that include checking accounts.
So have brokerages, which are barred from buying banks but still
offer a range of cash-management accounts that include checking.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, most of the remaining barriers between the
various sectors of the financial services industry would be
removed. A local insurance agent, for example, would now be able to
sell banking products, such as loans and mutual funds. Banks also
would be able to underwrite insurance, in addition to selling
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the industry sees the bill as a victory. Small
banks, for example, argue that creating more super-sized financial
firms might harm consumers, though they acknowledged that mergers
would take place with or without the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every study that's been done shows that the larger the
institution, the higher the rate the consumer pays on loans and the
lower the rate they get on their savings,'' said Ron Ence of the
Independent Community Bankers of America.
</P>
<P>
   All this assumes the bill will become law, which is likely. The
House and Senate passed the financial services bill earlier this
year, and Friday they ironed out the differences that existed among
themselves and with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House is very pleased with the results of Friday's
negotiations,'' said Joe Lockhart, spokesman for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is not final until formal legislative language is
drafted, and some lawmakers held out hope that they could persuade
the White House to reverse course and demand changes to two
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not settled,'' said Representative Edward Markey,
Democrat of Malden. He said black and Hispanic groups, as well as
advocates for privacy rights and the poor, might be able to
persuade the White House to withdraw its support and reopen
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   One dispute involves the Community Reinvestment Act of 1977,
which requires banks to make loans in the communities where they
draw deposits. The law is credited with pushing banks to offer
credit in poor and minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative aides said that the deal reached Friday would
require federal regulators to audit banks for CRA compliance
whenever the bank asks to enter a new, nonbank line of business.
Currently, banks are supposed to be reviewed every 18 months to two
years, though in practice reviews often come every three years.
</P>
<P>
   If regulators find that the bank is not complying with the
lending law, then they can reject the bank's application to enter
new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   However, some lawmakers were angered that the final bill drops a
House provision requiring banks to maintain a satisfactory CRA
rating even after they enter new businesses. If a bank's CRA rating
flags, the House had said, then regulators could demand that it
divest of its new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the new law would allow small banks to submit to
CRA reviews every four years or five years. The definition of
``small banks'' includes 80 percent of US banks, said Josh Silver
of the National Community Reinvestment Coalition, which lobbies for
a stronger CRA and fair lending laws. ``This severely limits the
application of the CRA to small banks,'' he said. ``It is a step
backward.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law would allow a company with banking, insurance, or
securities arms to swap personal information about consumers among
its various units. Companies said that will help them offer better
services to consumers, but privacy advocates, including Markey,
said people would find their sensitive credit card and tax
information given to telemarketers and stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
   A company can also disclose personal information to other firms
with which it does business, but customers have to be notified and
can block the data sharing.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also prevents nonfinancial companies from moving into
the banking business.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, commercial firms are barred from owning banks but can
buy a single savings and loan under a limited charter called a
unitary thrift. This law threatened small, rural banks, which said
that a company like Wal-Mart might set up branches in each of its
stores.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Ence of the community bankers' group, ``If you
mix commerce and banking, you jeopardize the impartial allocation
of credit. Credit may be allocated on internal business decisions,
rather than on merit, and that's dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
