<HEADER>
A5635 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PENSIONS-ART-$ADV     10-22 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PENSIONS-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SMALL CHANGE AS PENSION PLANS ARE CONVERTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of 4 examples of pension plans is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24)  
 (af)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hundreds of companies have switched to cash-balance pension
plans. But outraged employees who have seen the value of their
pensions shrivel have spurred lawmakers to investigate and have
pressured some companies, including IBM, to reverse themselves.
Here are some common questions about the plans: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do cash-balance plans differ from traditional pensions? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With old-fashioned pensions, employees earn most of their
retirement benefits toward the end of their careers, because
benefits are calculated using factors including years of service
and final pay. Under cash-balance plans, workers accrue benefits
evenly over their careers. Their employer deposits a percentage of
their pay in their accounts every year and guarantees they will
grow by a certain percentage annually. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who wins and who loses if a company converts to a
cash-balance plan? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. That depends. Some companies let employees stay with the old
plan. But at others, employees must switch, and some have seen the
value of future benefits drop 20 percent to 50 percent. Generally,
younger employees, especially job hoppers, can do better under
cash-balance plans because they will accrue benefits faster. But
middle-aged and older workers often do worse because conversions
come just as they reach the age when the old formula begins to
sharply bolster the value of pension payouts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does a company get out of switching to a cash-balance
plan? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Plenty. For starters, many see savings right off the bat.
Before it backed down, IBM said the switch would save $200 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. Companies love predictability, but they don't
have much with old-fashioned pensions. Since they invest pension
reserves in stocks and bonds, which have been in a bull market,
many now have overfunded pensions. But not long ago, many had
underfunded pensions. A drop in the markets could put them back
there.
</P>
<P>
   With cash-balance plans, companies are responsible only for
paying out the annual percentage of the employee's pay plus the
yearly promised increase in the account. That growth rate is
typically linked to Treasury bond rates. Thus, the company is more
certain about what it will owe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are switches to cash-balance plans legal? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. That depends on whom you ask. Conversions cannot cause a
current or retired employee to lose retirement benefits, nor can
they discriminate illegally against older workers. Federal law is
also clear that pension plans are voluntary, so any employer can
terminate or alter a plan, as long as it doesn't take away benefits
already earned or violate age-discrimination rules. Companies may
also be limited by union contracts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are government officials looking at the issue of conversions
to cash-balance plans? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. The Internal Revenue Service and Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission are investigating whether the plans
discriminate illegally. Proposals have been made in Congress to
widen disclosure about conversions or scale back companies' ability
to switch plans in ways that hurt older workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE23-COX     10-22 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crew chief accepts fine for profanity
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ Todd Parrott, crew chief for Winston Cup
points leader Dale Jarrett, doesn't have any dirty words to say
about NASCAR's penalty against him.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott was fined $5,000 by the sport's governing body for using
profanity during ESPN's telecast of the Talladega race last
weekend. Parrott, Jarrett and team owner Robert Yates agreed to
wear microphones, but Parrott said he was assured that there would
be a delay in broadcasting the conversations over the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not really upset with the fine,'' Parrott, who issued
a public letter of apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR has got a job to do, just like I do. They've got to
control the sport. Something got out on television that should have
never got out on television and it got out on television again that
night (in the replay). NASCAR had a right and they had to do
something. I understand totally.''
</P>
<P>
   Team members of the Ford No. 88 say Parrott was truly
embarrassed by the incident. And it never was a laughing matter
with Parrott, even though others in the racing community have been
teasing him. Yates joked that he thought about requiring Parrott to
wear a bar of soap around his neck this weekend at North Carolina
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Seriously), Todd doesn't have a dirty mouth,'' Yates said.
``He doesn't need to use four-letter words to get his point across.
When you get into a heated battle and you've had it on all day
long, and the car runs terrible, you just forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember back with Davey Allison, we knew were miked and we
knew we were live. The car ran out of gas on the backstretch at
Pocono and he said some bad things, like, 'Where's the wrecker?'
and he emphasized it like 'I want the (expletive) wrecker' and
that's not the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly want to keep this sport clean. I've always been
proud to go around and tell people that watch our sport that it's
night and day different than some of the TV shows you see at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who qualified third for Sunday's Pop Secret 400, has
been masterful at avoiding controversy this season as his team
chases after the Winston Cup championship. Jarrett, however, could
not bite his lip when asked about the disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a few words I could put with (my opinion), but I don't
have the money to pay the fines,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to enhance the sport (by wearing the
microphones). We were told one thing by the people who aired the
race. Unfortunately, that didn't happen. I think it would be a
really good idea for ESPN to pay the fine for Todd because it was
their fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
