<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS23-COX     10-22 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rebuilt Avalanche still solid contender
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Colorado acquired Theo Fleury late last season,
many people favored the Avalanche to win its second Stanley Cup in
four years. But the Dallas Stars rallied from a 3-2 series deficit
to beat Colorado in the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fleury is in New York, the beneficiary of the Rangers'
free-agent spending spree that also snared Valeri Kamensky and
Sylvain Lefebvre.
</P>
<P>
   So, what has Colorado done? Just turned to Generation Next and
made itself a slightly cheaper but no less talented contender for
the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the additional absence of Peter Forsberg until at least
late November because of offseason shoulder surgery, Colorado still
is one of the NHL's top teams. Atlantans will get a chance to see
for themselves tonight, as the Avalanche and budding standouts
Chris Drury, Milan Hejduk and Alex Tanguay play the Thrashers in
Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, 1-3-2 and coming off a five-day layoff, is looking for
its first home win. Colorado, 4-3-2 and tied for first in the
Northwest Division despite only two home games, isn't the kind of
team against which a victory comes easily _ anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colorado is very, very good,'' Thrashers coach Curt Fraser
said. ``The Avalanche _ all that skill and speed, like Detroit.
They're always on the go, trading scoring chances. They count on
Patrick Roy to stop the other team and he usually does.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy, fourth all-time among NHL goalies in victories, has been
his usual stellar self in goal, while captain Joe Sakic had at
least one point in Colorado's first eight games. But the Avalanche
also is counting heavily on second-year standouts Drury and Hejduk
and promising 19-year-old rookies Tanguay and defenseman Martin
Skoula.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Drury, a one-time Little League World Series hero from
Trumbull, Conn., won the Calder Trophy last season as the NHL's top
rookie, while right wing Hejduk finished third in the voting.
Hejduk, 23, has a team-high six goals and his eight points rank
second to Sakic's 11. Drury, 23, has seven points, tied with
Tanguay _ the leading candidate for the rookie award this season.
Playing left wing on a line centered by Sakic, Tanguay has three
goals and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're missing some key guys, but I think the young
guys (are) filling the holes real well,'' Sakic said. ``I like what
we have here. I like our chances this year. We're going to get
better. We're going to have a shot at (the Cup.)''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hartley, in his second season as coach, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have high expectations,'' Hartley said. ``We managed to
keep the core players on this team and we feel real good about the
young prospects. You look at every dynasty team. They always make
moves with older players at the end. You have some growing pains,
but that's part of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always talk about experience in this business, but new
blood is always a sign of new life. I think it's rubbing off on
everyone. There's fresh air in the dressing room. We're in a good
situation. We just have to let the kids get adjusted to the NHL
level, and I'm sure that they're going to have good seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Pierre Lacroix, who still has the NHL's
third-highest payroll at $42 million, also feels good about his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are blessed with great depth in this organization,''
Lacroix said before the start of the season. ``We're excited about
what some of our young kids bring to us. I guess you could say
we're at a crossroads, but both roads are nicely paved for us to
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
