<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-SERIES-DEBATE23-C     10-22 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-DEBATE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yankees or Braves: '90s debate renewed
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before he ever saw it, Tom Glavine had heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   And even when he got possession of his 1995 World Series
championship ring and read ``Team of the Decade'' that ran around
the side, the notion seemed innocuous enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just another thing on a ring,'' Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the proclamation was made with a half a decade to run.
Even if there has not been another World Championship to follow it.
Even if the New York Yankees will be seated in the dugout the next
few nights.
</P>
<P>
   The team of the what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off a championship and the success we'd had, maybe it
wasn't so far-fetched,'' Glavine said. ``But, obviously, the last
few years, the Yankees have had a little to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   This World Series already is unique, in that for the first time
in history, the teams with the best records over the decade are
meeting in the final game of that decade. That distinction alone
would be enough to fill out a marquee _ if not for this Team of the
Decade issue, which has been whipped to shreds by the media this
week.
</P>
<P>
   As Yankees reliever Jeff Nelson asked, ``Was there a team of the
'80s?''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, was there a team that wore such a designation so
eagerly and so early?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's purely a subjective thing, but the Braves, for me, are
the team of the decade, regardless of who wins this World Series,''
Houston Astros general manager Gary Hunsicker said. ``Yes, getting
to the World Series is the goal of every team, but consistency is
more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the No. 1 criteria for evaluating a franchise,''
Hunsicker said. ``It's not by a landslide vote, believe me. But I
do feel the Braves are clearly the team of the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Their victory total in the 1990s (925 games) not only far
outstrips the Yankees' (851) but represents the second-highest
total in the past 40 years, behind the 1970s Cincinnati Reds, who
won 953. Not since the Yankees of the 1950s made the World Series
eight times has a franchise appeared as regularly as the Braves,
who have made five trips in the 1990s. And unlike Casey Stengel's
Yankees, the Braves have had two and then three rounds of
postseason play to maneuver through.
</P>
<P>
   The eight consecutive divisional championships, saluted on
Turner Field's left-field upper deck, are an unprecedented
achievement. Perhaps more remarkably, the Braves have faced seven
different franchises in their eight visits to the NLCS. The Braves
remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was easy, some of these (other) teams would have done
it,'' Braves general manager John Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, winning can be graded by degrees. While the addition
of a third postseason round has thrown another kink into October's
road, no one has changed the grail. Winning a World Series remains
the standard, even if harder to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you judge the team of the decade?'' Texas Rangers first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro asked this month. ``Is it on championships
alone or on postseason appearances? How do you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for the Yankees. They'll take the big trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, let's admit it,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``When you
work for George Steinbrenner, just getting to the postseason is not
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't we the team of the century?'' Yankees general manager
Brian Cashman asked. ``World championships, that's the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have 24. Even with that history, to win a third
World Series in four years, as they can in the next eight days,
would set this era apart. No Yankees club has won it all so
frequently since the run of five in a row from 1949-53.
</P>
<P>
   Then how to explain away the early '90s? While the Braves were
appearing in _ and losing _ the 1991 and '92 Series, the Yankees
were not competitive, fielding second-division teams from 1990 to
1992. Those clubs finished an aggregate 62 games out of first.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the '94 season and all of the postseason wiped
out by the strike, it was not until 1996 that the Yankees actually
won the AL East. That same year, the Braves took their fifth
division championship in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm talking about team of the decade, I was saying the
Braves, Braves, Braves,'' Torre said. ``They're there every single
year, going to postseason play. To me, that's emblematic of a very
successful franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its years of excellence, however, the Braves still
have questions to answer. They still have their 1-3 showing in the
World Series and three failures in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say if (the Braves) hadn't won the NLCS, they wouldn't
be looked at in the same light,'' said Ozzie Smith, whose St. Louis
teams won just one of three World Series in the 1980s. ``They still
won't be put on a higher pedestal until they win another World
Series. Because I think (having the chance) to go to eight World
Series and you only come away with one world championship, that's
not what people expect from a team that finishes first every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Schuerholz says the team-of-the-decade business
came not from the organization but from the media, when it was
tossed about in the afterglow of the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stole this from either the press or the media. We thought
it sounded good,'' Schuerholz said. ``We didn't designate outselves
that. Hopefully, it will be validated.''
</P>
<P>
   They have only one way to do that, which further elevates the
game's premiere event as the 1990s come to a close. So, it's not
just baseball anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of playing for one year,'' New York's David Cone said,
``we're playing for 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
