<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-SERIES23-COX     10-22 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves `confident' in rare underdog role
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Color the Braves nostalgic.
</P>
<P>
   They're back in the World Series for first time in three years
and fifth time this decade. They're surrounded again by the masses
of reporters, well-wishers, ticket-seekers and baseballs to be
signed.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not exactly what had this team doing a little
reminiscing heading into tonight's Game 1 of the World Series at
Turner Field. These Braves, who've been hanging around for eight
consecutive postseasons now, are getting a new perspective. They
may actually be looking up.
</P>
<P>
   According to newspaper columnists around the country and
oddsmakers in Las Vegas, the Braves are something they never are
anymore: underdogs. And that's quite all right with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expects us to win, so it takes a little of the pressure
off,'' Chipper Jones said. ``Everybody can play free and easy and
play hard and take some chances here and there. We feel confident.
We know we can play with them. There shouldn't be any doubt in
anybody's mind. We've just got to go out and prove it at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves may be gunning for ``Team of the '90s'' recognition,
which would be solidified with a second World Series title this
decade. But the Yankees are going for ``Team of the Century'' title
and a 25th World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees, going for a third World Series championship in
four years, are the ones fighting their shadows. Last year,
including the postseason, the Yankees won 125 games to set a
major-league record, including a World Series cakewalk over the
Padres in a four-game sweep. This Yankees team still won 98 games
in the regular season, but the 16-game drop-off was the biggest in
the American League.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have a bigger payroll, pushing $90 million compared
with the Braves' $62 million, and a bigger market. More media
pressure. More hype. More jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got the ring,'' Jones said. ``We're trying to take it
from them. Winning 125 games last year and they've got pretty much
the same personnel. We've been doing it with smoke and mirrors,
ham-n-egging them, and they're just killing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves got 31 of their 103 wins this regular season in their
final at-bat. They arrived in October short of the power they're
used to _ minus Andres Galarraga and Javy Lopez _ but with the
added dimension of speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this year our Braves team ... the feeling is we'll
find a way to win,'' John Smoltz said. ``We don't rely so much on
the home run and pitching, same old formula.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees also play a lot more National League-like that most
American League teams, which makes this an intriguing matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves finished first in the major leagues with a 3.63 ERA.
The Yankees are sixth with a 4.13, but throw in the American
League's use of the designated hitter, that's right on par with the
Braves. The Braves hit 197 homers to the Yankees' 193. The Braves
had more stolen bases (148-104), but the Yankees counter with the
highest on-base percentage in baseball at .366 and one of the
highest batting averages (.282).
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably have to give them the advantage man-for-man,''
Jones said. ``We do have pitching and we are capable of playing
good baseball. Hopefully we have that caliber of play in us at the
right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Yankees and Braves met in the 1996 Series, the Fall
Classic has featured an upstart _ the wild-card Marlins in 1997 or
the from-outta-nowhere Padres in 1998. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves may be considered underdogs, but then again that has
to be measured in degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the injuries they had this season, the Braves still
felt some serious heat when they got up 3-0 on the Mets and lost
two in a row to face the prospect of becoming the first
major-league baseball team to blow a 3-0 lead in a best-of-seven
series.
</P>
<P>
   They also know what lurks behind their image as ``Team of the
'90s'' _ the old Buffalo Bills reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Smoltz nor Tom Glavine nor Greg Maddux, the pitching
trio that underscores this decade-long run, seemed to feel like
much of an underdog on Friday afternoon, shrugging upon being asked
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the odds?'' asked the Las Vegas transplant Maddux,
who then added: ``I don't care. I'm not bettin' ... It really
doesn't matter. It's not like you look and see you're a 14-to-5
favorite and say `Oh, I don't have to work as hard today.' You just
want to go out and play the game right, as good as you possibly
can, and take your chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
