u s BC-FBC-PREDICTIONS23-COX     10-22 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PREDICTIONS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tide-Vols again SEC benchmark
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ Gen. Robert R. Neyland, Tennessee's Hall of
Fame coach, had a stock answer when anyone asked how good his team
would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Neyland would say. ``Ask me again after the
third Saturday in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-one times in this century, most often on the third
Saturday in October, Tennessee and Alabama have met on the football
field. Until the emergence of Florida in the 1990s, the game always
was the benchmark by which the two programs measured themselves.
Invariably, the winner knew it had the inside track to the SEC
championship.
</P>
<P>
   More history will be made today when Tennessee returns to the
Alabama campus for just the fourth time. Alabama previously had
chosen to play its home games with Tennessee at Birmingham's Legion
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are ranked in the top 10, national television will be
here, and the Crimson Tide faithful will be ready to have the Big
Orange in Bryant-Denny Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be neat to see Tennessee's players walking in
here,'' said Alabama running back Shaun Alexander. ``It's going to
be an athletic, big-time football game.''
</P>
<P>
   The game isn't always on the third Saturday in October anymore.
But it is no less meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   This week's picks: SEC
</P>
<P>
   _ Kentucky (5-2) at Georgia (5-1), 12:30 p.m., WXIA. This game
is very dangerous for the Bulldogs. Hal Mumme is licking his chops
about going against a defense that gives up a lot of yards. Georgia
again finds a way to win, but it won't be easy. Georgia, 31-28.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tennessee (4-1) at Alabama (5-1), 3:30 p.m., CBS. The Vols
will keep Alabama running back Shaun Alexander under control, but
will they be able to handle the rest of the Tide's wide-open
attack? Look for Tennessee, which had a week off, to exploit a
young Alabama secondary. Tennessee, 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   _ LSU (2-4) at Mississippi State (6-0), 6 p.m., ESPN2. LSU has
won seven in a row over the Bulldogs, but the Tigers have virtually
no confidence after four consecutive losses. Mississippi State has
had a week off to rest and will play like it. Mississippi State,
24-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vanderbilt (4-3) at South Carolina (0-7), 7 p.m. The
Gamecocks' 17-game losing streak has to end sometime. Why not
against the Commodores? This week's Upset Special. South Carolina,
14-13.
</P>
<P>
   ACC
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida State (7-0) at Clemson (3-3), 7 p.m., ESPN. FSU's
Bobby Bowden goes for career win No. 300 against son Tommy. Despite
the warm and fuzzy talk about the father-son angle, the old man, as
he is affectionately called in Tallahassee, wants another national
championship. The boy has to pay. Florida State, 42-14.
</P>
<P>
   _ N.C. State (4-3) at Duke (1-5), noon, Fox Sports Net South.
N.C. State still has bowl aspirations, so this is a game the
Wolfpack needs to win. The Dookies have beaten Virginia and pushed
Georgia Tech to the limit the past two weeks. N.C. State, 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   _ North Carolina (1-5) at Maryland (4-2), 3:30 p.m., ABC. UNC
coach Carl Torbush is under fire because the Tar Heels not only are
losing but are looking ugly doing it. Maryland is pushing for a
bowl and is looking for payback after losing eight of nine games to
UNC this decade. Maryland, 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alabama-Birmingham (3-3) at Wake Forest (3-3), 3:30 p.m. UAB
is coming off a 24-21 overtime win over Cincinnati, which beat
Wisconsin earlier this season. Wake Forest won't believe the
Blazers are that good and it will cost them. Alabama-Birmingham 31,
Wake Forest 24.
</P>
<P>
   Top 25
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2 Penn State (7-0) at No. 16 Purdue (5-2), 3:30 p.m.
Purdue knocked off Michigan State last week but won't be able to
play giant-killer two weeks in a row. Look for defensive
coordinator Jerry Sandusky to turn All-American linebacker LaVar
Arrington loose on Purdue quarterback Drew Brees. Penn State 28,
Purdue 17.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 3 Nebraska (6-0) at No. 18 Texas (5-2), 3:30 p.m. If Texas
can get its running game going, quarterback Major Applewhite will
have a chance. The Longhorns, however, will have trouble stopping
the Cornhuskers and quarterback Eric Crouch. Nebraska, 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 7 Kansas State (6-0) at Oklahoma State (3-2), 12:30 p.m.
Kansas State has won 18 Big 12 games in a row but will not have an
easy afternoon in Stillwater. Look for this to be a tight one.
Kansas State, 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 11 Michigan State (6-1) at No. 17 Wisconsin (5-2), noon,
ESPN2. After losing to Purdue last week, Michigan State needs a win
to keep its Rose Bowl hopes alive. Wisconsin's Ron Dayne will test
an MSU defense that gives up 40 yards rushing per game. Michigan
State 21, Wisconson 13.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rest: Michigan 34, Illinois 6; Texas A&AMP;M 24, Oklahoma 14;
Marshall 51, Buffalo 7; BYU 28, UNLV 13; East Carolina 31, Tulane
20; Southern Miss 21, Cincinnati 17; Ohio State 17, Minnesota 10;
Miami 24, Boston College 21.
</P>
