<SLUG> BC-UNITED-UNITED </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Airline's Cost-Cutting Vexes Bay Area Travel Agents  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bay Area travel agents are seeing red after United Airlines led
other major carriers in slashing commissions for ticket bookings
from 8 percent to 5 percent.
<P>
   Some agents are now refusing to book flights on United, the
world's largest carrier. Others are deliberately steering clients
to other airlines. And some who cannot avoid a United booking are
charging customers an extra $20 ``service fee'' to make up the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   United handles about 65 percent of flights into and out of the
Bay Area, and many travelers insist on flying the airline because
of its frequent-flyer programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all ticked off _ insulted,'' said Susan Campos, vice
president of Pacific Heights Travel Service in San Francisco. ``If
the airlines didn't have us, there would be huge lines at the
airport. It would be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of airline tickets are sold through travel
agencies, according to the American Society of Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   Internet chat groups frequented by travel industry professionals
have been buzzing since United's decision was announced two weeks
ago. E-mail has also circulated among travel agents trying to build
a consensus for a coordinated response.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this grassroots movement, travel agents
throughout the country have said they will take countermeasures
against United.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruckus, United did not budge from having once again
led the way in reducing commissions paid to travel agents. In 1997,
it was the first to cut commissions to 8 percent from 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, all other major U.S. airlines quickly followed
suit.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; No Comment From United
</P>
<P>
   A United spokeswoman declined to discuss the latest commission
cut and subsequent outcry from travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed instead to an October 7 statement from United chief
executive Jim Goodwin, who described the move as ``part of our
continuing efforts to examine all facets of our cost structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines was the first to act in 1995 when it lowered
commissions to 10 percent and capped payments to travel agents at
$50.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are doing this in part to cut out the middleman by
encouraging passengers to purchase tickets directly from each
carrier via the Internet. However, many travelers still prefer the
old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   According to Preview Travel, a leading Internet travel agency,
online air bookings totaled $777 million in 1997, while travel
agencies did about $126 billion in business that same year.
</P>
<P>
   But with lower commissions, Campos is now tacking a $20 service
fee onto all her United bookings. ``It would be ridiculous for me
not to do that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sherry, a spokeswoman for the watchdog group Consumer
Action, said she was not surprised that some travel agents are
passing their costs along to customers. ``If the airlines don't pay
it, who do they think will?'' she asked. ``The consumer,
obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   But smaller, less well-heeled agencies are finding that their
customers will not tolerate the idea of making up for the airlines'
cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did that, my clients would not come here,'' said Maria
Kucharszky, owner of Pegasus Travel in Daly City. ``They are
looking for the lowest possible fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other small-agency operators, she said she was barely
breaking even with 8 percent commissions. At 5 percent, Kucharszky
said she may have to close her business.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else can you do?'' she said. ``Hotels are not paying as
much, car-rental companies are not paying as much. I don't know
what I am going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ruden, the travel agent group's senior vice president for
legal and industry affairs, shrugged off the travel agents'
discontent as ``expressions of anger from people who feel
disempowered and helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   He also stressed that the travel agent's group is in no way
encouraging its 11,000 member agencies to boycott United or any
other airline, pointing out that such a move could violate
antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't organize boycotts,'' Ruden said. ``We don't condone
boycotts, and we don't know of any.''
</P>
<P>
   He may want to get into contact with Lincoln Chu, owner of
All-Ways Travel in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely leaning against booking United now,'' he said.
``Whichever airline helps us, we're going to help them. Whichever
dings us, we're going to retaliate.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Chu figures it, the average ticket booking is $250. So
if each of the roughly 40,000 travel agencies nationwide denied
United just one booking a week, the airline would be out more than
$500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel agencies and airlines should be partners,'' Chu said.
``If you arbitrarily cut commissions down, what kind of partnership
is that? It's getting to the point where we can't make a decent
living.''
</P>
<P>
   United is estimating that the lower commissions will result in
savings to the airline of about $150 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Those savings may grow if, as many travel agents fear,
commissions are subsequently lowered again to 3 percent and then
ultimately eliminated altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The handwriting is on the wall,'' said Richard Birchard, head
of Fog City Travel in the Financial District.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that many agencies are trying to adjust by shifting
their focus away from ticket sales and more toward vacation
packages, where profit margins are higher.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Clark, manager of San Francisco's Dirt Cheap Travel, said
travel agencies will keep operating until ticket commissions
finally reach zero, ``and then everyone will go out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she said she does not see much value in a
boycott of United. ``But if someone calls seeking a ticket, I'll
book the best connection, and it just might not be United. Know
what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
