<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-PACBELL_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 Crew Cuts Line, Irks Callers in Downtown S.F.  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A construction crew building an office and apartment complex on
Third Street in San Francisco sliced into a Pacific Bell cable late
Thursday, cutting phone service to some downtown customers.
<P>
   Most of those affected were tenants in the Hearst Corp.
Building, which houses about 71 businesses. About 80 percent of the
building lost phone service around 5 p.m. Thursday, and many were
still without a dial tone late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The outage also affected some pay phones and a few residences in
the area, according to the phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell officials said about two-thirds of the customers had
their service restored by yesterday morning and the rest would be
back on line by 8 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty inconvenient,'' said Robert LaVine, an attorney
who works in the Hearst Building. ``Of all the days, I left my cell
phone home today.''
</P>
<P>
   Some offices had a single line working, while others were
completely silent.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Cassidy, a spokeswoman for Pac Bell, said the outage
occurred when a construction company, trying to anchor a new
building to the ground, bore into the street at a 45-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contractor inadvertently damaged the cabling while trying
to anchor the building,'' Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   The company was a subcontractor for Pankow Cos., which is
building a 44-story highrise with apartments and offices at Third
and Jessie streets.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy said the phone cables are clearly marked so that
accidents like this don't occur. She said she was unsure why the
cut happened.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Pankow Cos. did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1909, the Hearst Building houses law firms, technology
companies and even the western branch of the U.S. Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Novie, an architect with Aaron Green and Associates, said
the outage was making it difficult for the firm to stay in contact
with employees and customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally have seven lines going. Now we only have one,''
Novie said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Green, the firm's owner, said he thought the company that
caused the outage should refund money to the affected businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is money and we're losing time on our projects. It's a
big inconvenience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But downstairs at Arca Technologies, it was business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our phones are working,'' said Darren Castles, CEO of Arca.
</P>
<P>
   Was it divine intervention? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Winstar as our phone company. We don't have Pac Bell,
so we're not affected,'' Castles said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
