<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER EARLY STRUGGLES, GLAVINE REGAINS OLD FORM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The changeup had deserted him and the strike zone had
shrunk and then the doubt crept in on Tom Glavine. The defending Cy
Young award winner, who will start Game 1 of the World Series for
the Atlanta Braves on Saturday night, had such an
uncharacteristically poor beginning to this season that opponents,
for at least a few months, could believe that one of the most
reliable pitchers of the decade was perhaps wearing down, befuddled
by a newly consistent strike zone that seemed to take away the
outside corner on which he thrived.
</P>
<P>
   He began the season 0-3, then dropped to 3-7, and all the while
he stood on the mound _ getting hammered by teams like the Florida
Marlins _ and produced a string of adjustments that amounted to
almost no progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go through when you're constantly going out
there, not quite sure what you're going to bring out there, what's
going to be working or what's not,'' Glavine said. ``There were
very few times this year that I walked out to the mound and felt,
`OK, I'm going to pitch a good game.' I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he does. In Glavine (14-11), the Yankees will face a
pitcher renewed. Although he led the league in hits allowed (259),
and struggled in the early innings _ 60 of the 115 runs he allowed
this season came in the first three innings _ Glavine won 11 of his
last 15 starts.
</P>
<P>
   In his last five starts, dating from mid-September and including
the division series and the National League Championship Series, he
is 4-0 and has allowed just seven earned runs in 35 innings. His
post-season earned run average is 1.38 and he was masterly against
the Mets in Game 3 of their championship series, shutting them out
on seven hits for seven innings to win, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Although he pitched well against the Yankees in his one
interleague start against them _ he gave up two runs on six hits in
six and two-thirds innings to open the second half of the season _
Glavine did not truly regain his form until a start against the
Mets on Sept. 28, when he allowed two runs in seven innings. Six
days later, he allowed the Mets just one run in seven innings, a
performance that catcher Eddie Perez said was his best of the year.
Glavine used his fastball to set hitters up before getting them out
with a changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like the whole first half of the year, every time I
went out to pitch, I was making some kind of adjustment,'' Glavine
said. ``Then the second half of the year, it seemed like I pitched
a couple good games, then something would go wrong, I'd make an
adjustment, pitch a couple good games. I pitched the game against
Montreal in late August and I had made a couple of adjustments the
game before. I thought, `OK, this is where I want to be.' And I
went out and probably pitched my worst game of the year and reached
my lowest point frustration-wise. From that point on, the only
thing I tried to do was be as natural as I could. That's pretty
much been it for me since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, along with John Smoltz, has been one of the few
constants on a Braves team that has employed a remarkable bit of
re-engineering year after year yet remained dominant in the
National League throughout the 1990s. Glavine won Game 6 of the
1995 World Series to secure the Braves' only championship in four
previous tries during the decade, with a magnificent performance
that held Cleveland to one hit in eight innings for a 1-0 victory.
Glavine would have pitched Game 7 of the 1996 World Series and,
although he lost Game 3 to David Cone, he pitched well, allowing
four hits and two runs in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've meant everything,'' Manager Bobby Cox said of Glavine
and Smoltz, the Game 4 starter. ``Without them, we wouldn't be here
today. Tommy, I think, is on top of his game right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In seven World Series starts, Glavine is 4-3 with a 1.75 e.r.a.,
and Cox configured his rotation so that Glavine, who was the third
starter in the rotation behind Greg Maddux and Kevin Millwood in
the division series and league championships series, could start
Game 1 and then be available to pitch Game 5 in Yankee Stadium to
take advantage of whatever edge left-handers are supposed to have
in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine has undoubtedly had an edge over the two Yankees who
will bat left-handed against him: Paul O'Neill and Tino Martinez
are a combined 7 of 38 (.184) in their careers facing Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   With the incessant tinkering that marked the first half of his
season now over, the Yankees will see the familiar Glavine. He is
reluctant to blame the edict that umpires call a more consistent
strike and instead blames himself. ``I struggled because of the
strike zone because I was throwing too many balls in the heart of
it,'' Glavine said. ``I don't have the stuff to get away with that.
I cannot be throwing the ball down the middle of the plate, and too
many times during the first eight weeks of the year, I was doing
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of making some mechanical adjustments.
You've got to look in the mirror and figure out where the problem
was, and the problem was me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5653 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NURSERY-NURSERY_SFCHR     10-22 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSERY-NURSERY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Cupertino Nursery Thrives  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
``Fusarium leaf spot,'' pronounced Pam Leong, a horticulturist at
Yamagami's Nursery in Cupertino, as she examined a green draceana
leaf marred by brown blots.
<P>
   ``It's a fungus spread by splashing water,'' Leong informed a
customer, reading from a 3-inch-thick guide book. ``It's not
usually harmful.''
</P>
<P>
   Working beside Leong in Yamagami's ``Info Center,'' a shed lined
with reference books in the middle of the spacious nursery, Carolyn
Villa-Scott clucked over a rotted dahlia. The owner confessed she
had left the droopy plant in a bucket of water. ``That's a no-no,''
said Villa-Scott. ``But we'll replace it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamagami's has been serving up advice and greenery to South Bay
gardeners since the area was known as Santa Clara Valley, rather
than Silicon Valley, and Cupertino was famous for apricots, not
Macintoshes.
</P>
<P>
   Taro Yamagami, a second-generation Japanese American, bought the
nursery's De Anza Boulevard property in 1948, shortly after
returning from service in World War II. Yamagami had grown up in
the Central Valley and helped liberate Italy as part of the famous
Japanese-American 442nd Regimental Combat Team, the most highly
decorated unit in the war.
</P>
<P>
   The young businessman's first venture was a fruit stand in the
midst of the apricot orchards. De Anza Boulevard then was a
two-lane road known as Highway 9, and Yamagami's customers were
mostly weekend beachgoers on their way to Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   As the valley began to develop, Yamagami started stocking
flowers and other plants to sell to new residents. In a few years,
the business was transformed into a full-fledged nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Yamagami's is run by Preston Oka, 53, a third-generation
Japanese American. Oka's father, Mas Oka, was Yamagami's first
general manager; Mas Oka and his wife, Betty, bought the business
in 1963, when Taro Yamagami decided to focus on landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Yamagami's has flourished under Preston Oka, who took over from
his father in 1985. At Yamagami's 50th anniversary party last year,
Oka noted that the business now racks up $500,000 in sales some
months. That's more than an entire year's sales in 1974, when Oka
started working at Yamagami's full time.
</P>
<P>
   The booming South Bay economy _ and a January freeze that hurt
many South Bay gardens _ has certainly helped Yamagami's, which
expects a 25 percent sales increase of  &LR; this year despite
competition from superstores and gardening Web sites. But much of
Yamagami's success can be chalked up to careful thought and
planning by Oka and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preston is an aggressive, innovative and creative''
businessman, said Elaine Thompson, executive director of the
California Association of Nurserymen. ``He is always looking at how
to market, how to bring the best to his customers, and that sets
him apart. His whole plan has really worked because the nursery has
grown tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Source of Information
</P>
<P>
   Oka, whose business sits across the street from a Woolworth's,
decided years ago that he couldn't compete on price. Instead, he
made Yamagami's a leading local resource for information and
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to feel like, `my God, the big chains are robbing
me,''' said the affable Oka. ``But now I look at them with respect.
In some ways, they make my business stand out. If they're offering
(the lowest) price, it would be foolish for us to play that game.''
</P>
<P>
   While other nurseries may employ a handful of certified
horticulturists, Yamagami's has 10. To attract the most qualified
people, Oka offers health insurance, profit-sharing bonuses and
even a 401(k) investment plan for full-time staff.
</P>
<P>
   One of Yamagami's most popular features are signs displayed
around the nursery that detail plants' traits and preferred growing
conditions. The information comes from a database of 11,000 plants
that Oka and staffers have assembled over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some signs are written in Mandarin to accommodate the nursery's
growing Chinese clientele. Yamagami's also employs a Mandarin
speaker and a Cantonese speaker to assist Chinese shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Atherton, a Saratoga Sarasota  &LR; landscaper, said she sends
clients to Yamagami's to learn about plants and choose what they
want in their gardens. Then she buys the plants more cheaply
through a wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We install whole yards and we can't afford to buy all of our
plants from Yamagami's,'' said Atherton. ``But a lot of times I'll
look for extraordinary things there and so do my clients. They
often have new (varieties) and colors before anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Oka is well aware that many people use Yamagami's as an
educational resource but do much of their buying elsewhere. ``It's
a service we provide,'' he said drolly. ``But really we don't mind.
That customer is going to buy from us sometime in the future. It's
like free advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Atherton said she enjoys visiting Yamagami's because it is
arranged so nicely. ''Right now there are these beautiful
arrangements of pumpkins and hay. Sometimes when I'm sick and tired
of my customers and my business, I go down there and remember why I
love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamagami's pleasant environment is no accident _ it's the result
of more strategic decisions by Oka.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Yamagami's was quite crowded, with 20 percent of
the floor space devoted to aisle and 80 percent to displays.
</P>
<P>
   After reading studies showing that wider aisles might boost
sales, Oka designed a 50-50 floor plan and bought more shopping
carts. Although the amount of items product  &LR; on the floor was
dramatically reduced, there has been a healthy rise in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Another experiment that paid off was a decision to offer fewer
varieties of plants. A central table displaying pink, white and
purple cyclamen used to contain four varieties of plants, requiring
frequent restocking and tricky inventory management, Oka said.
</P>
<P>
   By featuring just one type of plant, stocking is easier and the
presentation is more dramatic, Oka said. Sales at that table have
risen nearly 50 percent since the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do a few things well, as opposed to doing many
things average,'' says Oka.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kanemoto, Yamagami's general manager, points to other small
changes that he believes have helped boost Yamagami's business over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Rose bushes were recently moved to the back of the nursery,
forcing rose seekers to walk past rows of other tempting items.
``It's the same principle as locating milk at the back of a
convenience store,'' said Kanemoto.
</P>
<P>
   Yamagami's also offers noontime seminars on topics like planter
arranging that attract more than 25 people per day. The seminars
are free, but many attendees stay and shop afterward.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Dry Place to Shop
</P>
<P>
   One innovation that provided a dramatic payoff for Yamagami was
the installation of a fabric canopy over the nursery in the early
1990s. During the heavy rains of 1997, ``we were high and dry while
our competitors were drowning,'' said Kanemoto. ``For the year, our
sales were up 8 percent while other nurseries were down 25 to 50
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its healthy sales and strategizing, Yamagami's future is
somewhat uncertain. It is currently  &LR; negotiating its lease with a
trust that represents Toya Yamagami, Taro's daughter and heir. Taro
died in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Oka hopes the lease will be extended. ``Seventeen families are
depending on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the business continues, Oka will encourage his 12-year-old
daughter, Brittany, to one day take over. But he said he will
handle the generational transfer the way his parents did, without
overt pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents were very smart,'' Oka said. ``They told me, `You
can do whatever you want, but the door is always open.' At the same
time, they taught me how to tend the plants, how to do the buying.
They sucked me in with kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
