<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5656 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      10-22 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pac Bell Price Hike Rebuked  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A state regulator is recommending that Pacific Bell only be allowed
to raise prices for directory assistance calls to 35 cents, not the
50 cents the phone company requested.
<P>
   In a proposal released this week, Public Utilities Commissioner
Carl Wood also recommended that Pac Bell's request to cut the
number of free 411 calls from five per month to three be denied.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's proposal differs significantly from what Pac Bell asked
for and from what an administrative law judge recommended in
August. The judge, Michael Galvin, said Pac Bell should be allowed
to raise its directory assistance rates from 25 cents per call to
46 cents each. He also said the company should be given permission
to lower the number of free 411 calls per month.
</P>
<P>
   The two proposals are on the PUC's agenda for November 4. It's
unclear how the full commission will vote.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell had asked the PUC for permission to raise 411 rates to
$1.10, although it said it only planned to charge 50 cents per
call.
</P>
<P>
   The request drew the ire of consumers, who deluged the PUC with
phone calls, letters and e-mails protesting the increase. The PUC
said it received more than 41,000 contacts from consumers, almost
all opposing the rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said the customer outcry, combined with a lack of
competition in the marketplace, should preclude Pac Bell from
getting a large increase. He said Pac Bell should not be allowed to
charge more than 35 cents for 411 calls, because customers don't
have any real alternatives for directory assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though local DA  &LR; (directory assistance) is classified as
a partially competitive service, Pacific Bell retains an effective
monopoly'' over the service, Wood wrote in his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Charging 35 cents is reasonable, he said, because Pac Bell says
claims  &LR; its cost for providing directory assistance is about 33
cents per call. Wood said the company should not be able to recoup
much more than its costs.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the onslaught of new area codes makes it necessary
for people to call 411 more frequently for phone numbers, since
they won't have access to telephone books for every region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that any increase ... could be a substantial
hardship on those customers who, for various reasons, are dependent
on affordable local DA service,'' Wood wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Pac Bell officials said the recommendation is unfair because
it wrongly assumes that there's no competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious to anybody following the marketplace there is
competition in 411,'' said John Britton, a spokesman for Pac Bell.
``And the competition is charging from 95 cents to $1.40 for the
same information.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance carriers such as MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T offer both
local and national directory assistance to customers for a fee.
Consumers can also get directory assistance for free off the
Internet at sites such as 555.1212.com and Infospace.com.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said Pac Bell needs an increase to cover costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pac Bell is losing money on this service. We need to cover
costs and at the same time give the consumer the best bargain,''
Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates said Wood's proposal is a fair
alternative to Pac Bell's request and takes into account the
enormous consumer interest in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commissioner Wood's proposal is fair to consumers and it's
also fair to Pac Bell,'' said Paul Stein, an attorney with The
Utility Reform Network. ``There's no competition for local
directory assistance and the public has overwhelmingly opposed a
rate increase. We still believe that Pac Bell hasn't justified any
rate increase.''
</P>
<P>
