<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-SYCAMORE-IPO-ART-B     10-22 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SYCAMORE-IPO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY COMPANY'S PUBLIC OFFERING SETS OFF STOCK FRENZY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sycamore Networks Inc., a tiny Chelmsford, Mass., company with
just two customers, set Wall Street on fire Friday with its initial
public offering of stock, as its share price exploded fivefold,
from an opening price of 38 to a close of 184 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Sycamore, a manufacturer of fiber-optic network
products for carrying Internet traffic, worth $14 billion, setting
a record for the highest market value achieved by an Internet
company in its first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes Sycamore, a company with little more than $11
million in revenue since May when it shipped its first product,
Massachusetts' fourth-highest-valued company, dwarfing Staples
Inc., Raytheon Co., and TJX Cos., the operator of TJ Maxx clothing
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying the hell out of this stock,'' said Steven
Tuen, director of research for IPO Value Monitor in New York.
``It's just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sycamore stock frenzy was driven mostly by individual
investors, eager to get in on a company that is expected to develop
the next generation of communications equipment. Much of the
trading Friday was in smaller blocks of 100 to 200 shares, Tuen
noted, an indication that large institutional investors weren't the
only buyers. Individual investors ``don't want to miss out on the
opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, small investors did miss out on most of the profit. The
only people allowed to buy into the 7.5 million shares offered at
38 a share were large customers of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the
offering's underwriter. Those who sold immediately after trading
opened at 12:30 were able to fetch 270 7/8. Throughout the day,
Sycamore's stock drifted back down somewhat, dropping by more than
86 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   The market exuberance over Sycamore is just the latest in a
string of record-setting initial public offerings, or IPOs, of
Internet-related companies, demonstrating an almost insatiable
demand for a relatively limited supply of such stock.
</P>
<P>
   It also highlights a hot new area in high-tech: Internet
infrastructure, the physical building blocks that allow
unprecedented numbers of people to pipe into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Companies similar to Sycamore also have logged impressive IPOs
in recent months, including Juniper Networks Inc., in California,
which started at 34 a share in June and closed Friday at 261 1/4.
California-based Redback Networks Inc., which began at 23 a share
in May ended trading Friday 120 1/16, while Foundry Networks Inc.,
also in California, went public at 25 a share and closed Friday at
162 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like 20 years ago when the economy was driven by oil, the
economy for the next 25 years will be driven by the networked
economy,'' said Desh Deshpande, who founded Sycamore with Daniel E.
Smith just 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Deshpande and Smith are now billionaires, at least on paper.
Deshpande, who owns 16.3 million Sycamore shares, is worth just
under $3 billion, while Smith's 14.7 million shares are worth about
$2.7 billion. The two, however, cannot cash in on their stock for
at least six months, when a ``lock-up period'' expires.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Deshpande and Smith are not likely to sell their
shares en masse, said Stephen Lacey, managing editor of IPO
Reporter, a newsletter in New York. ``You don't want to sell it all
at once,'' Lacey said. ``You want to do it in a controlled
environment through a secondary offering.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Deshpande and Smith can claim to have launched one of
the most successful IPOs in history. Its 386 percent gain is the
fourth highest in the first day of trading for an IPO, according to
Jay Ritter, professor of finance at the University of Florida. On
an absolute dollar basis, Sycamore's increase of 146 3/4 is the
largest ever first-day gain, Ritter said. Its market capitalization
_ $14 billion _ is also the highest realized by a company on its
stock market debut.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Yahoo Inc., a popular Internet portal based in
Santa Clara, Calif., was worth $850 million at the end of its first
day on the stock market in April 1996, according to Ritter.
</P>
<P>
   Few are predicting whether there will be a hangover next week
from the Sycamore IPO, mostly because there are few precedents to
help set a course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry itself is so new that it's difficult to find
anything comparable to this,'' said Lacey of the IPO Reporter.
``It's just pretty crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many high-tech observers are bullish on Sycamore's
future as a company. Some are taking their cues from Cisco Systems
Inc., a well-heeled California rival to Sycamore that in August
paid $7 billion for Cerent Corp., a maker of fiber-optic products.
Others are noting that Deshpande and Smith are proven entrepreneurs
and managers, having built Cascade Communications in Westford into
a telecommunications powerhouse that was sold for $3.7 billion in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what makes Sycamore so hot is that Cisco has declared
the area to be hot'' with its purchase of Cerent, said Joseph P.
Lassiter, professor of management at the Harvard Business School.
``But it's also because Dan and Desh have proven they know how to
run a company, not just build a prototype and sell it off. The
market is now saying it loves them, and that's huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, are more skeptical about Sycamore's $14 billion
valuation, larger than the $9.9 billion market capitalization of
Raytheon Co., a defense contractor in Lexington that has $20
billion in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter noted that Sycamore has a great deal of competition, not
only from well established companies such as Cisco, Nortel Networks
Corp., Lucent Technologies Inc., and Ciena Corp., but also from
newer firms such as Redback, Juniper, and Foundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition will make it difficult for any one of these
companies to make really big profits,'' Ritter said. ``If one of
them had a monopoly, it would be easier to justify these
valuations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
