<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5665 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-ART-2N     10-22 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: insurance business.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Glass-Steagall Act was enacted after the stock market crash
of 1929 and the ensuing banking crisis and Great Depression. On the
day it was signed, along with the National Industrial Recovery Act
and other measures, President Franklin D. Roosevelt called the
package ``the most important and far-reaching legislation ever
enacted by the American Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind Glass-Steagall, named for the two lawmakers who
wrote it, was that confidence in America's financial house could
best be restored if bankers and brokers stayed in separate rooms.
Such a separation, it was thought, achieved two purposes.
</P>
<P>
   First, it would reduce the potential conflicts of interest
between investment banking and commercial banking that were thought
to have contributed to the speculative frenzy in the stock markets.
Under the 1933 Banking Act, commercial banks could receive no more
than 10 percent of their income from the securities markets, a
limit so restrictive that most simply abandoned business on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it would provide a safe harbor for the money of ordinary
Americans by enabling them to put their money in accounts that were
protected by deposit insurance and insulated from more speculative
investments like stocks. (The 1933 act also established Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., which now insures bank deposits up to
$100,000.)
</P>
<P>
   Over time, federal judges and regulators chipped away at the
Glass-Steagall Act and other restrictions on cross-ownership of
banks, insurance companies and securities firms, enabling, for
instance, Citibank to merge with Travelers Group last year to form
Citigroup, the world's largest financial services company. But
large hurdles remained that have discouraged the expansion by banks
into new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough in Friday's legislation came in a backroom
meeting at the Capitol soon after midnight, when a group of
moderate Democrats from the Senate _ led by Christopher Dodd of
Connecticut and Charles Schumer of New York _ forced a compromise
between Gramm and the White House over the legislation's effect on
the Community Reinvestment Act, a 1977 anti-discrimination law
intended to encourage lending to minorities and others historically
denied access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, whose state is home to the nation's largest insurance
companies, and Schumer, with strong ties to Wall Street, have long
sought legislation to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act. Both men said
in interviews Friday that they moved to strike a compromise after
it became apparent that the legislation might be killed, as it was
last year by Gramm, over the debate about the Community
Reinvestment Act.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm had maintained that he did not want anything in the bill
that would expand the application of the Community Reinvestment Act
because it is unnecessarily burdensome to banks. He had sought a
provision that would exempt thousands of smaller banks from the
law. He also wanted a provision that would expose what he has
described as the ``extortion'' committed by community groups
against banks by requiring the groups to disclose any special
financial deals that the groups extract from the banks.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House found that provision unacceptable and had
its own ideas about community lending. It wanted the legislation to
prevent any bank with an unsatisfactory record of making loans to
the disadvantaged from expanding into new areas of business, like
insurance or securities.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had insisted that the president would veto any
legislation that would scale back minority-lending requirements.
Four days of intense negotiations between Summers, Gene Sperling,
the president's top economic policy adviser, and Gramm, while
moving the two sides closer, failed to resolve the differences.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5666 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-ART-3R     10-22 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the differences. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such was the state of play Thursday evening when Gramm decided
to force the issue by having the House-Senate conference committee
vote on his proposed compromise, which the White House had already
rejected for failing to block banks with bad lending records from
expanding to new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   When Gramm's measure was defeated by one vote, it quickly became
clear that there would be no law unless Gramm could get some
Democrats to break from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials had spent all day making sure that
the Democrats remained solidly against the measure until their
concerns about the Community Reinvestment Act could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving calls from executives of some of the nation's
leading financial companies, Dodd and Schumer began trying work a
compromise. An agreement was quickly reached on the issue of banks
and expanded powers _ no institution would be allowed to move into
any new lines of business without a satisfactory lending record.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers bogged down on Gramm's insistence that all
community organizations disclose to the regulators what benefits
they get from banks. Some Democrats expressed the fear that Gramm's
proposal would require the Boy Scouts to file reports with the
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the following agreement was reached that both the
White House and Gramm said they could accept:
</P>
<P>
   _ Banks will not be able to move into new lines of business
unless they have satisfactory lending records.
</P>
<P>
   _ Community groups will have to make disclosures to regulators
about certain kinds of financial deals with banks that they have
pressed to make loans under the Community Reinvestment Act.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wholesale financial institutions, a new kind of business that
takes large uninsured bank deposits, cannot be affiliated with
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small banks with satisfactory or excellent track records of
making loans to the underserved would be reviewed less frequently
under the Community Reinvestment Act. As a practical matter smaller
banks are reviewed on average about every three years. The deal
struck Friday allows banks with less than $250 million in assets
and all rural banks to undergo examination once every five years if
their last exam resulted in an ``outstanding'' grade and every four
years if they last scored ``satisfactory.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, Congress has tried unsuccessfully to
rewrite the nation's financial services laws and repeal
Glass-Steagall, particularly as many other industrial nations had
no similar restrictions on their banks. But until recently, the
three main industries affected by the legislation _ banks,
securities companies and insurers _ had competing interests and
were able to lobby any legislation to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed in recent years as the lines between the
industries began to blur and there became a broad recognition that
a deregulation of financial services could be beneficial to
insurers, bankers and securities firms alike. Once the three
industries rallied around the legislation, they became a formidable
political force, raising millions of dollars for lawmakers and
pressing both Republican leaders in Congress and the White House
for new legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-NYT &LR;      10-22 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON REACHING BACK TO JUMP-START CAREER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ Mike Tyson started this year against Francois
Botha on Jan. 16, a bout that was supposed to kick off an ambitious
schedule of four fights designed to help Tyson regain respect and
viability in the heavyweight division. He was coming off an
18-month layoff resulting from the revocation of his boxing license
in Nevada for biting Evander Holyfield's ears during a June 29,
1997, bout.
</P>
<P>
   As with most things in Tyson's boxing career, the plan did not
go as scripted. He went to jail in Maryland and served three and a
half months of a one-year sentence on two assault charges, and when
he got out he weighed 280 pounds and was in no shape to fight.
Shelly Finkel, his adviser, Dan Goossen of America Presents, his
promoter, and Jay Larkin, the senior vice president of programming
at Showtime, haggled over Tyson's next opponent. They settled on
Orlin Norris, a former cruiserweight champion who has fought one
round in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after an uneven performance against Botha, Tyson, a
former two-time world heavyweight champion, steps into the ring
Saturday night against Norris (50-5) to restart his boxing career
for the fourth time in four years in a scheduled 10-round bout at
the MGM Grand Arena here. The bout will be televised by Showtime on
a broadcast that starts at 11 p.m. If he wins, Tyson plans to be in
the ring again next Feb. 26, possibly in New York at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case against Botha, Tyson (46-3) will be under a
microscope. Everyone associated with him wants to see whether he
has completely chipped away the rust from his 18-month layoff
before he fought Botha. Tyson swung wildly for the fences and
missed for four rounds until Botha walked into a big right hand and
was knocked out in the fifth. At times Tyson looked like a novice
boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm rusty, I'm rusty,'' Tyson said. ``But I'm still
sensational.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is trying to reach back for some of the tools that helped
him club his way to his first heavyweight title 10 years ago. He
rehired Jay Bright as an assistant trainer to work with Tommy
Brooks, who first worked with Tyson for the Botha fight. Bright is
a disciple of Cus D'Amato, Tyson's first trainer, who helped guide
the boxer to a world championship at age 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike, over the course of being away and inactive, got loose in
the style that Cus had taught him,'' Bright said. ``I'm here to
tighten him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright said he had been reminding Tyson of the key points of
D'Amato's training: keep his hands up peek-a-boo style and his head
moving side-to-side, move forward and stay in position to punch,
and target the chin, temple and liver. Tyson, 33, who weighed in at
223 pounds (the same as against Botha), looks fit and trim and even
dropped two sparring partners with punches in the gym this week.
But no one knows what will happen when he climbs into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, 34, who will earn $800,000 to Tyson's $10 million, will
try to frustrate Tyson by staying away from him. Norris, who
weighed in at 218, does not have the power to knock Tyson out, but
can frustrate him. Tyson warned Norris at a news conference earlier
this week that he was ``bringing the pain, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it,'' Norris said. ``I've never had a fight where the
next day I didn't feel some kind of pain. This is part of boxing.
I'm not afraid of him. I know he's going to hit me and I'm going to
hit him. I don't want to get hit with a clean shot. If he hits me,
I want to be at the end of his punches.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks and Bright have been telling Tyson not to go looking for
the quick knockout. They have told Tyson to keep doing what he
needs to do and a knockout will come, because Norris will make a
mistake and leave an opening. Tyson just needs to be in the right
position when Norris makes his error.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Tyson can maintain his head during a frustrating fight
is another matter. He built his career on being a knockout artist.
A waltz to a decision would not serve Tyson's purpose of advancing
his career into the contender status.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is also in a position to add a jolt of excitement to the
sport, dismissing Oscar De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad. ``I don't
put those guys in my category,'' Tyson said. ``I'm in two different
orbits than those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   If he wants to be in orbit with the winner of the
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight unification rematch scheduled
for Nov. 13 in Las Vegas, then he has to look better than he did
against Botha to prevent his career from idling.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
