<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5672 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-VANITYFAIR-REVIEW-     10-22 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VANITYFAIR-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A&AMP;E'S `VANITY FAIR' KEEPS SATIRE INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest production of William Makepeace Thackeray's ``Vanity
Fair'' begins with an artist's model picking her nose.
</P>
<P>
   Its first hour ends with a pig grunting in front of the
colorless expanse of Queen's Crawley, home of the baronet Sir Pitt
Crawley.
</P>
<P>
   A viewer needs no additional notice that Thackeray's satire
hasn't been prettied up. If anything, this six-hour version,
showing Sunday and Monday on the A&AMP;E cable channel, is scrappier
than the BBC's two past productions of ``Vanity Fair.''
</P>
<P>
   And Becky is as Sharp as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Davies, who previously adapted ``Pride and Prejudice''
and ``Emma,'' is at pains to separate Thackeray's world from the
lush certitudes of Jane Austen, and director Marc Munden is his
lively accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who have come to expect the lovely greens, blushing
blooms and stately pace of the Austen shows will find a different
vision here.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Vanity Fair'' lighting tends either toward harsh or
deliberately muted. Its depiction of England is so frothy that it's
practically French, and Munden loves to zero in on his characters'
more unsavory physical attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Teeth are a sort of a specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of the Napoleonic Wars, we follow the
orphaned and penniless Becky Sharp up and down the social ladder.
She can be admired for her pluck, but it's amazing she'd want to
mix with the vile upper classes on display here. The makers of this
miniseries broaden Thackeray's smirk into a derisive chortle.
</P>
<P>
   Thackeray serialized ``Vanity Fair'' in 1847 and 1848, and
subtitled it ``A Novel Without a Hero.'' Davies' script holds truer
to that than earlier screen treatments. Played flirtatiously by
Natasha Little, Becky is, as she's described in the final hour, a
heartless mother and a faithless wife. To say nothing of insincere,
selfish and shallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you get what you deserve,'' Becky says to her sappy
friend Amelia Sedley (Frances Grey), and then adds as a comment to
herself, ``and I hope that I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one of Becky's few moments of introspection. Mostly she's
good at picking herself off the canvas _ she's surely Scarlett
O'Hara's prototype _ and resuming her ardent pursuit of
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, Little's Becky is more coquettish than interesting.
But Little succeeds a lot in creating an anti-heroine who's
consistently ahead of the men in her life. Like, about 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   The man she marries is Rawdon Crawley, sympathetically played by
Nathaniel Parker. Rawdon is a dashing dragoon and hero of Waterloo,
a doting father, a dissolute gambler and a too-trusting husband.
Except for Rawdon's inability to secure a fortune, the depiction
calls to mind another ``Gone With the Wind'' parallel, Rhett
Butler.
</P>
<P>
   The knaves in Becky's life are the show's most vivid
inhabitants. Jeremy Swift is much like a young Peter Ustinov as Jos
Sedley, Amelia's cowardly, self-serving brother. His trip to a spa
on the second night is a laugh-out-loud scene.
</P>
<P>
   Munden's tooth studies center on Gerald Murphy as the brutish
aristocrat Lord Steyne and David Bradley as the coarse, lecherous
old Sir Pitt Crawley, who hires Becky as a governess.
</P>
<P>
   Becky's sojourn at the Crawley estate spans Sunday's second
hour, and it is a wickedly delightful patch of pure loathsomeness.
The pig is part of what Becky jokingly calls the ``arcadian
simplicity'' of the place.
</P>
<P>
   It's there that another of the show's colorful supporting
characters materializes. She's Sir Pitt's immensely wealthy and
just plain huge sister (Miriam Margolyes). Watch her carriage sag
when she's gruntingly heaved into it.
</P>
<P>
   Balancing all the depravity in the novel, and the miniseries, is
the virtuous Capt. William Dobbin (Philip Glenister), who loves
Amelia but holds his silence for years because she has married his
best friend and fellow cavalry officer, George Osborne (Tom Ward).
</P>
<P>
   Dobbin is no ladies' man, but he is wise, generous and
unassuming. When this noble specimen makes his grand entrance into
the miniseries, and into Amelia's life, his military helmet
collides with a chandelier and is knocked unceremonious- ly from
his head.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance of a century and a half, you might hear
Thackeray cackle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
