<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT     10-22 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, OCTOBER 23
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-UNIONS-CLINTON-GORE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Oct. 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Oct. 3,
about an alliance of environmental groups and labor unions to
protect jobs and the environment referred incorrectly to a World
Trade Organization ruling on a United States law banning the import
of shrimp caught in nets that endanger sea turtles. An appellate
panel of the trade organization ruled that the United States must
stop applying the law in a discriminatory manner. It did not
overturn the law.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LEAD-LAWSUIT-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Oct. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Oct.
13, about the Rhode Island Attorney General's suit against paint
manufacturers for the cost of removing lead paint from buildings
included an erroneous reference to a comparable issue in New York.
The city sued a group of manufacturers in 1989; it is not merely
looking at the possibility. The suit is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT (moved on Monday, Oct. 18) and
BC-CONGRESS-MINORITIES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Oct. 20)
</P>
<P>
   Two New York Times News Service articles sent on Monday, Oct. 18
and Wednesday, Oct. 20, about Republican opposition to President
Clinton's nomination of Carol Moseley-Braun as Ambassador to New
Zealand referred incorrectly to a Confederate flag that was at
issue in 1993 when Ms. Moseley-Braun, as Senator from Illinois,
persuaded the Senate to reject a renewed patent for an emblem for
the United Daughters of the Confederacy. (A similar error occurred
in an earlier article, on July 23, 1993.) The emblem included the
Stars and Bars, the first national flag of the Confederacy _ not
the later Confederate battle flag.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MATTEL-EARNINGS-NYT (moved on Thursday, Oct. 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Oct. 21,
about Mattel Inc.'s third-quarter results misstated the company's
expectations for future profit. It expects to earn 70 to 80 cents a
share for the full year, not for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-CHAMBERLAIN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Oct. 12)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Wilt Chamberlain sent by the New York Times News
Service on Tuesday, Oct. 12, misstated his year in college when he
led the University of Kansas to the N.C.A.A. title game. He was a
sophomore, not a junior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
