<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 10/22/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WEBSTER, Mass. -- Oct. 22, 1999 --
FRANCO-NEWENGLAND-BOS, 10-22 -- French students outside St. Anne's
School in Webster. As Franco-Americans in New England examine the
state of their culture, they use a common word to discuss their
half-hidden presence: ``la survivance,'' which carries connotations
of both preservation and persistence. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- PENTAGON-JET, 10-22 -- To
save its expensive F-22 fighter from congressional budget-cutters,
the Air Force is willing to sacrifice another, less-costly new
fighter - to the consternation of the Navy and the Marines who also
want to use the cheaper aircraft, a senior Air Force official said.
The less-expensive plane, the Joint Strike Fighter, is unusual in
that it was being developed for the Air Force as well as the Navy
and the Marines. (Lockheed Martin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- NY-KLAN-PROFILE, 10-22 --
Two Ku Klux Klan leaders, James W. Sheeley, left, and Jeffery L.
Berry, outside Federal Court in Manhattan on Thursday, where they
heard arguments on their plans to rally in New York City. A federal
appeals court blocked a lower court decision Friday and barred the
Klan from rallying in lower Manhattan on Saturday with their faces
shielded by masks. The decision was a victory for the Giuliani
administration. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- BANKS-CONGRESS, 10-22 --
Sens. Phil Gramm and Jim Bunning conferring Thursday. After a week
of difficult negotiations among Gramm and President Clinton's top
economic advisers over a bill to overhaul the nation's financial
system, it became evident Friday that there would be no new law
unless an agreement can be reached over the legislation's effect on
rules that encourage banks to make loans to the poor. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MEMPHIS, Tenn. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- MEMPHIS-DEVELOP-2,
10-22 -- Among the signs of rebirth in Memphis is a proliferation
of new art galleries. David Lusk, co-owner of a gallery, sold a
Colin McLain that a developer put in his recreation room. ``A Colin
McLain could not have sold here 10 years ago, even for $1,000,'' he
says. ``Our average price now is probably $5,000, $6,000.'' (Rollin
A. Riggs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) MEMPHIS, Tenn. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- MEMPHIS-DEVELOP-1,
10-22 -- A baseball stadium under construction for the Redbirds, a
minor league team in the St. Louis Cardinals' farm system, is one
of the signs of rebirth in Memphis. Ravaged since the 1970s by
white flight to the eastern reaches of the city and the Shelby
County suburbs beyond, the city center is now abloom with hard hats
and cranes. (Rollin A. Riggs/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LAGUNA WOODS, Calif. -- Oct. 22, 1999 --
RELIGION-COLUMN, 10-22 -- The Rev. Mel White (shown) will meet
Saturday with the Rev. Jerry Falwell. The goal was simple: a civil
exchange of views between two groups that disagree profoundly over
gay rights in church and state. The two ministers also promised to
avoid harsh language on the issue in the future. The meeting is to
take place at Falwell's Thomas Road Baptist Church in Lynchburg,
Va. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- OBIT-EGGER-B&AMP;W, 10-22 --
Roscoe L. Egger Jr., a commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service
in the Reagan administration, died Oct. 14 at the Mayo Clinic in
Rochester, Minn. He was 79 and lived in Green Valley, Ariz. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LAKE CITY, Fla. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
24 -- CRASH-MAIN-6-COX, 10-21 -- Tammy Nessmith and her son,
Brandon, at the gravesite of Spc. Thomas Nessmith. Tammy was
pregnant with Brandon when her husband, then 22, crashed while
flying an AH-1F Cobra over a pineapple field in Hawaii on March 5,
1996. (Virginia Marshall/Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MONTGOMERY, Ala. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
24 -- CRASH-MAIN-5-COX, 10-21 -- Maj. Stan Nessmith stands in front
of an F-105 Thunderchief at the Maxwell Air Force Base in
Montgomery. Nessmith's only brother, Spc. Thomas Nessmith, 22, and
Chief Warrant Officer David E. Glamuzina, 46, were killed when the
AH-1F Cobra they were flying crashed into a pineapple field in
Hawaii on March 5, 1996. (Skip Peterson/Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SEATTLE -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
CRASH-MAIN-4-COX, 10-21 -- Lt. Michael A. Aguilar was killed when
his an OH-58 Kiowa Warrior crashed into a Nevada hillside. ``If
they knew something was wrong with it, why did they let it go on?''
asks Michael's father, Ernest Aguilar, an Army veteran of two wars.
``Something should have been done.'' (Dan McComb/Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) FREEMONT, Ohio-- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24
-- CRASH-MAIN-3-COX, 10-21 -- Josephine Miller looks at a portrait
of her late husband, Tom, which was taken while he was in Vietnam.
Miller, a member of the Indiana National Guard and a father of two,
was killed when his helicopter crashed in an Indiana pine forest.
(Skip Peterson/Dayton Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BISHKEK, Kyrgyzstan -- Oct. 22, 1999 --
KYRGYZSTAN-DEMOCRACY, 10-22 -- In Kyrgyzstan, the idea of popular
sovereignty may be taking hold. With local Parliamentary and
presidential elections scheduled for next year, this remote nation
could become the first democracy in Central Asia's long history.
``We are making every effort to assure that these elections will be
fair and transparent,'' says President Askar Akayevk, who has
refused to say whether he will run for re-election. (Staton R.
Winter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- POUND-BARRED, 10-22 -- Ezra
Pound was denied a memorial stone in the Poets' Corner at the
Cathedral of St. John the Divine in Manhattan. The dean of the
cathedral overruled the electors who had selected the poet.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KHARTOUM, Sudan -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- SUDAN-ARTIST, 10-22
-- Rashid Diab at his small art gallery in Khartoum. Two months
ago, Diab, 43, abandoned a good life in Madrid to return to Sudan,
which he wants to make self-reliant artistically by teaching young
artists to mix their own paint, to make their own materials for
etching, to find local stone for sculpture. ``In America or Europe,
many people doubt the existence of good African artists,'' he says.
(Ian Fisher/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) QOM, Iran -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- IRAN-KHALKHALI, 10-22 --
Twenty years ago, Ayatollah Sadegh Khalkhali was the Islamic
revolution's grim avenger, condemning possibly thousands of men and
women to death, some of them after trials that lasted only five
minutes, or after no trials at all. The Iranian government, caught
between democratic reform and a clerical hardline ethic, behaves as
if it would rather Khalkhali - who now supports reform - be
forgotten. (John F. Burns/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- LEGO-ROBOTS-2, 10-22 -- A
pirate ship, as assembled with Legos by Edward Rothstein, the
writer of the accompanying article. Part of the appeal of a Lego
model is that it displays its origins by showing its mechanical
skeleton; that skeleton is all the more astonishing because it can
be reorganized to form an entirely different body. (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- LEGO-ROBOTS-1, 10-22 --
R2D2 from ``Star Wars,'' as assembled with Legos by Edward
Rothstein, the writer of the accompanying article. The results
might seem a far cry from the model towns that children began
building out of interlinking Lego pieces in the 1950s, but there
are deep connections between the old and the new. (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A, 10-22 -- Greg Smith, chief investment
strategist at Prudential Securities. ``Y2K is a bravado issue,'' he
says. ``No one admits to changing their investment strategy because
of Y2K. But underneath you have to think it is another dose of
uncertainty, another reason to be nervous.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
SINGLE-CHILD-2, 10-22 -- Andrew and Erica and their three sons live
on the Upper East Side. Despite the fact that Manhattan has become
a veritable only-child paradise, big families still flourish east
of Central Park. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
SINGLE-CHILD-1, 10-22 -- As an only child, Monet Brathwaite, 8,
exemplifies a trend in New York City. With her are her parents,
Michael Brathwaite and Anita Farrington-Brathwaite. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
CAMPBELL-LOUNGE, 10-22 -- The Campbell Apartment, now a lounge at
Grand Central Terminal. Since it opened on Sept. 30, the Campbell
Apartment has been packed almost nightly, drawing a stream of the
curious, who between cocktails, crane their necks to take in the
30-foot wood-beam ceilings. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
NITEOUT-CUBAN-BAND, 10-22 -- Ibrahim Ferrer, left, and Ruben
Gonzalez of the Buena Vista Social Club, clutching their Grammys.
The success of the various Buena Vista projects has resulted in a
remarkable late-life transformation for many of the band members.
``I'm happily tired,'' says Gonzalez, 80. ``I'm tiredly happy.''
(Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
MAGS-FAMOUS-FACES, 10-22 -- Actors are the new cover stars and the
pressure is on to snag them. The negotiations editors must go
through with publicists are so time-consuming that many magazines
have created a new job: so-called celebrity wranglers, editors who
are better at power-lunching, writing thank-you notes and sending
flowers than at smoothing out copy. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24
-- CRASH-MAIN-2-COX, 10-21 -- James Browne and his wife, Patricia,
place roses on the casket of their son, Lt. Michael J. Browne, who
was killed flying a helicopter that Navy investigators later
determined was not safe to fly. ``They're willing to sacrifice as
acceptable risk the lives of military personnel,'' says Browne.
(Brian Phillips/Dayton Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DAYTON, Ohio -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24
-- CRASH-MAIN-1-COX, 10-21 -- Michael Browne in his dress blues.
Browne was killed flying a helicopter that Navy investigators later
determined was not safe to fly. (Courtesy of the Browne Family)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
BIZ-FIVE-QUESTIONS-B&AMP;W, 10-22 -- Juan Somavia of Chile, the new
director-general of the International Labor Organization. ``What
does the ILO do when it finds that markets are not working?'' he
asks. ``We have to promote entrepreneurship. Unless you generate
more work in the world, we'll continue to have a series of
problems. And to insure decent work, there's no substitute for
organize, organize, organize.'' (G. Cabrera/International Labor
Office Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
