(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KHARTOUM, Sudan -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- SUDAN-ARTIST, 10-22
-- Rashid Diab at his small art gallery in Khartoum. Two months
ago, Diab, 43, abandoned a good life in Madrid to return to Sudan,
which he wants to make self-reliant artistically by teaching young
artists to mix their own paint, to make their own materials for
etching, to find local stone for sculpture. ``In America or Europe,
many people doubt the existence of good African artists,'' he says.
(Ian Fisher/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) QOM, Iran -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- IRAN-KHALKHALI, 10-22 --
Twenty years ago, Ayatollah Sadegh Khalkhali was the Islamic
revolution's grim avenger, condemning possibly thousands of men and
women to death, some of them after trials that lasted only five
minutes, or after no trials at all. The Iranian government, caught
between democratic reform and a clerical hardline ethic, behaves as
if it would rather Khalkhali - who now supports reform - be
forgotten. (John F. Burns/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- LEGO-ROBOTS-2, 10-22 -- A
pirate ship, as assembled with Legos by Edward Rothstein, the
writer of the accompanying article. Part of the appeal of a Lego
model is that it displays its origins by showing its mechanical
skeleton; that skeleton is all the more astonishing because it can
be reorganized to form an entirely different body. (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- LEGO-ROBOTS-1, 10-22 --
R2D2 from ``Star Wars,'' as assembled with Legos by Edward
Rothstein, the writer of the accompanying article. The results
might seem a far cry from the model towns that children began
building out of interlinking Lego pieces in the 1950s, but there
are deep connections between the old and the new. (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A, 10-22 -- Greg Smith, chief investment
strategist at Prudential Securities. ``Y2K is a bravado issue,'' he
says. ``No one admits to changing their investment strategy because
of Y2K. But underneath you have to think it is another dose of
uncertainty, another reason to be nervous.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
SINGLE-CHILD-2, 10-22 -- Andrew and Erica and their three sons live
on the Upper East Side. Despite the fact that Manhattan has become
a veritable only-child paradise, big families still flourish east
of Central Park. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
SINGLE-CHILD-1, 10-22 -- As an only child, Monet Brathwaite, 8,
exemplifies a trend in New York City. With her are her parents,
Michael Brathwaite and Anita Farrington-Brathwaite. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
CAMPBELL-LOUNGE, 10-22 -- The Campbell Apartment, now a lounge at
Grand Central Terminal. Since it opened on Sept. 30, the Campbell
Apartment has been packed almost nightly, drawing a stream of the
curious, who between cocktails, crane their necks to take in the
30-foot wood-beam ceilings. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
NITEOUT-CUBAN-BAND, 10-22 -- Ibrahim Ferrer, left, and Ruben
Gonzalez of the Buena Vista Social Club, clutching their Grammys.
The success of the various Buena Vista projects has resulted in a
remarkable late-life transformation for many of the band members.
``I'm happily tired,'' says Gonzalez, 80. ``I'm tiredly happy.''
(Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
MAGS-FAMOUS-FACES, 10-22 -- Actors are the new cover stars and the
pressure is on to snag them. The negotiations editors must go
through with publicists are so time-consuming that many magazines
have created a new job: so-called celebrity wranglers, editors who
are better at power-lunching, writing thank-you notes and sending
flowers than at smoothing out copy. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BUFFALO, N.Y. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24
-- CRASH-MAIN-2-COX, 10-21 -- James Browne and his wife, Patricia,
place roses on the casket of their son, Lt. Michael J. Browne, who
was killed flying a helicopter that Navy investigators later
determined was not safe to fly. ``They're willing to sacrifice as
acceptable risk the lives of military personnel,'' says Browne.
(Brian Phillips/Dayton Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DAYTON, Ohio -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24
-- CRASH-MAIN-1-COX, 10-21 -- Michael Browne in his dress blues.
Browne was killed flying a helicopter that Navy investigators later
determined was not safe to fly. (Courtesy of the Browne Family)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
BIZ-FIVE-QUESTIONS-B&AMP;W, 10-22 -- Juan Somavia of Chile, the new
director-general of the International Labor Organization. ``What
does the ILO do when it finds that markets are not working?'' he
asks. ``We have to promote entrepreneurship. Unless you generate
more work in the world, we'll continue to have a series of
problems. And to insure decent work, there's no substitute for
organize, organize, organize.'' (G. Cabrera/International Labor
Office Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
