<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-BOOK-1STLD-WRITE     10-22 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING DISTRUST OF AUTHOR, PUBLISHER WITHDRAWS BOOK ON BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for complete writethru with 500 additional words at
end.)  (th) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ St. Martin's Press, the publisher of a controversial
biography of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, took the unusual step of
recalling the disputed book Friday, issuing an alert to booksellers
around the country to return thousands of copies for shredding or
burning because company executives no longer trusted the author.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the publishing house announced the recall shortly
after getting confirmation that photographs of the book's author,
J.H. Hatfield, matched police photographs of a felon convicted of
hiring a hit man 11 years ago in an unsuccessful attempt to murder
his boss using a car bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're heat, furnace fodder,'' Sally Richardson, the
president and publisher of St. Martin's trade division, said of the
books. The publishing house this month had shipped more than 70,000
copies of Hatfield's ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and the Making
of an American President.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield did not return phone calls seeking comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Such recalls are rare, but this one comes in a season when other
companies have been forced to pull books because of shattered trust
_ from an author accused of making up a Holocaust identity to a
biographer who simply plagiarized the words of other books. The
incidents have raised questions about the industry's ability to
screen authors.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield's book included claims from anonymous sources that Bush
_ the leading contender for the Republican presidential nomination
_ was arrested in 1972 on cocaine possession charges that were
later expunged by a judge as a favor to Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   In statements Friday, St. Martin's executives did not take issue
specifically with the disclosures, which have been denied by the
Bush family, but instead said they no longer considered the author
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be sure what else he lied to us about or to the
attorney who did the legal review of the book,'' said David Kaye,
the general counsel for St. Martin's Press. ``Therefore we can't
continue to trust what he told us.''
</P>
<P>
   The recall came a day after The Dallas Morning News reported
that Hatfield had been convicted of felony. Executives at St.
Martin's said earlier that Hatfield had called it a case of
mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush biography first surfaced as a proposal more than a year
ago and St. Martin's paid a modest advance of five figures. It
accepted the book on the strength of a recommendation by a
Manhattan literary agency, Richard Curtis Associates, and what it
considered Hatfield's solid resume as a Texas journalist and the
author of the unauthorized biography of actor Patrick Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   In its promotional material, St. Martin's described Hatfield as
the winner of the ``prestigious Isaac Asimov Foundation Literary
Award for Outstanding Biography in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Science Fiction Writers of American and Asimov's widow,
Janet, said that they have never heard of such an award dedicated
to Asimov, who was not known for his biographies.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal records indicated that a James H. Hatfield was
convicted of plotting to kill his bosses at a Dallas real estate
investment firm in a February 1987 car bombing. The plan failed.
The bomb apparently malfunctioned when the two executives turned
the ignition of their car inside a downtown parking garage
</P>
<P>
   In June 1992, according to court records, Hatfield pleaded
guilty to a federal charge of making false statements. He was
accused of falsifying his signature to cash checks from Housing and
Urban Development programs that totaled more than $22,000.
</P>
<P>
   The biography did face a legal review by a Washington law firm,
said Kaye, who noted that lawyers initially vetted the entire book
and later a final chapter, which was added in late sumer and
contained the sensitive information about Bush's supposed arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said Hatfield's background was not part of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that in my experience is not a part of the
legal process unless something comes up in the course of it that
would raise a question that would be more specific,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said the company was now faced with the issue of how it can
protect itself from dishonest authors.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at St. Martin's insisted that the book was not
affected by time pressures, even though the publication date of the
book was moved to October from January to compete with other
biographies of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, the cycle for publishing has been compressed to
as little as four months from what used to be about nine months,
leaving little time for reviews.
</P>
<P>
   One executive familiar with the company said St. Martin's latest
travails reflect broader problems in American publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the more corporate publishers become the more
pressures they face and they start to distance themselves from
rigorous investigations of the books they publish,'' the executive
said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press is a publisher of popular books, and is a
division of Verlagsgruppe Georg von Holtzbrinck, which also owns
the literary publishing houses of Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux and Henry
Holt.
</P>
<P>
   This September, Morgan Entrekin, the president and publisher of
Atlantic Press, halted publication of a disputed biography by a
Scottish author, James Mackay, after acknowledging that he had not
inquired into the writer's history of plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   And in October, several international publishers _ including
Random House Inc.'s imprint Schocken Books _ were forced to
consider whether to halt publication of a memoir after the original
German publisher disclosed preliminary results of a historian's
report about the author, Binjamim Wilkomirski.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that the author had lied about his identity
as a child survivor of Holocaust camps. A year earlier, his
American editor and translator had insisted that it was not the
role of a publisher ``to vet every manuscript and every author on
an adversarial basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
