<P>
   (NYT27) WEBSTER, Mass. -- Oct. 22, 1999 --
FRANCO-NEWENGLAND-BOS, 10-22 -- French students outside St. Anne's
School in Webster. As Franco-Americans in New England examine the
state of their culture, they use a common word to discuss their
half-hidden presence: ``la survivance,'' which carries connotations
of both preservation and persistence. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- PENTAGON-JET, 10-22 -- To
save its expensive F-22 fighter from congressional budget-cutters,
the Air Force is willing to sacrifice another, less-costly new
fighter - to the consternation of the Navy and the Marines who also
want to use the cheaper aircraft, a senior Air Force official said.
The less-expensive plane, the Joint Strike Fighter, is unusual in
that it was being developed for the Air Force as well as the Navy
and the Marines. (Lockheed Martin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- NY-KLAN-PROFILE, 10-22 --
Two Ku Klux Klan leaders, James W. Sheeley, left, and Jeffery L.
Berry, outside Federal Court in Manhattan on Thursday, where they
heard arguments on their plans to rally in New York City. A federal
appeals court blocked a lower court decision Friday and barred the
Klan from rallying in lower Manhattan on Saturday with their faces
shielded by masks. The decision was a victory for the Giuliani
administration. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- BANKS-CONGRESS, 10-22 --
Sens. Phil Gramm and Jim Bunning conferring Thursday. After a week
of difficult negotiations among Gramm and President Clinton's top
economic advisers over a bill to overhaul the nation's financial
system, it became evident Friday that there would be no new law
unless an agreement can be reached over the legislation's effect on
rules that encourage banks to make loans to the poor. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MEMPHIS, Tenn. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- MEMPHIS-DEVELOP-2,
10-22 -- Among the signs of rebirth in Memphis is a proliferation
of new art galleries. David Lusk, co-owner of a gallery, sold a
Colin McLain that a developer put in his recreation room. ``A Colin
McLain could not have sold here 10 years ago, even for $1,000,'' he
says. ``Our average price now is probably $5,000, $6,000.'' (Rollin
A. Riggs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) MEMPHIS, Tenn. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- MEMPHIS-DEVELOP-1,
10-22 -- A baseball stadium under construction for the Redbirds, a
minor league team in the St. Louis Cardinals' farm system, is one
of the signs of rebirth in Memphis. Ravaged since the 1970s by
white flight to the eastern reaches of the city and the Shelby
County suburbs beyond, the city center is now abloom with hard hats
and cranes. (Rollin A. Riggs/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LAGUNA WOODS, Calif. -- Oct. 22, 1999 --
RELIGION-COLUMN, 10-22 -- The Rev. Mel White (shown) will meet
Saturday with the Rev. Jerry Falwell. The goal was simple: a civil
exchange of views between two groups that disagree profoundly over
gay rights in church and state. The two ministers also promised to
avoid harsh language on the issue in the future. The meeting is to
take place at Falwell's Thomas Road Baptist Church in Lynchburg,
Va. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- OBIT-EGGER-B&AMP;W, 10-22 --
Roscoe L. Egger Jr., a commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service
in the Reagan administration, died Oct. 14 at the Mayo Clinic in
Rochester, Minn. He was 79 and lived in Green Valley, Ariz. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LAKE CITY, Fla. -- Oct. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
24 -- CRASH-MAIN-6-COX, 10-21 -- Tammy Nessmith and her son,
Brandon, at the gravesite of Spc. Thomas Nessmith. Tammy was
pregnant with Brandon when her husband, then 22, crashed while
flying an AH-1F Cobra over a pineapple field in Hawaii on March 5,
1996. (Virginia Marshall/Dayton Daily News)
