KYRGYZSTAN-DEMOCRACY, 10-22 -- In Kyrgyzstan, the idea of popular
sovereignty may be taking hold. With local Parliamentary and
presidential elections scheduled for next year, this remote nation
could become the first democracy in Central Asia's long history.
``We are making every effort to assure that these elections will be
fair and transparent,'' says President Askar Akayevk, who has
refused to say whether he will run for re-election. (Staton R.
Winter/New York Times Photo) LITE
