<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS     10-22 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG NOTES OF DISCORD MAR THE YANKEES' CHAMPIONSHIP TENOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The uncertainty of his future with the Yankees and the
questions about his shoulder gnawed at David Cone. But after the
Yankees defeated Texas in the first round of the playoffs, Cone
spoke with his teammate Chili Davis and they agreed: this is not
the time to worry about such matters, not when the Yankees are
pursuing another championship.
</P>
<P>
   Cone and his Yankee teammates plan to ignore the many underlying
difficulties and tensions in the organization when they begin the
95th World Series here Saturday against the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ideal match-up for the final baseball championship of
this century. Like the Braves, the Yankees won more games than any
other team in their league during the regular season. Both teams
are loaded with established stars: Derek Jeter, Roger Clemens and
Bernie Williams for the Yankees, and Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and
Chipper Jones for the Braves. There are at least two scheduled
pitching matchups that will pit former Cy Young Award winners
against each other. Both teams are commonly viewed as hard-working,
hustling teams that possess general toughness and class.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez will pitch Game 1 on Saturday for the Yankees,
against the Braves' Tom Glavine. But before then, the Yankees will
have a difficult roster situation to determine. The father of Luis
Sojo, the veteran utility infielder, died on Thursday, and the
Yankee is expected to be unavailable for the immediate future. The
Yankees were trying to determine this evening whether he would be
able to play in any game. Major League Baseball has rejected the
Yankees' request to temporarily replace him on the World Series
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo is just one of a number of Yankees players who has coped
with the illness or death of a parent this season. Scott Brosius'
father died, and the fathers of Paul O'Neill and Andy Pettitte have
had heart trouble for much of this year _ difficult situations that
have made a tough year even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Yankees played with exuberance and near perfect
harmony and won a record 125 games.
</P>
<P>
   But after the blockbuster trade of David Wells and two others
for Clemens on the first day of spring training, the rapture
eroded, under the unyielding pressure on the Yankees to repeat
their incredible performance. Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, was
told he had prostrate cancer in spring training. The dugout coach,
Don Zimmer, Torre's longtime friend, stepped in for Torre, but
within three weeks he was sparring with the principal owner George
Steinbrenner over the handling of pitcher Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   A number of players slumped, the Yankees played inconsistently
in early May before Torre came back and restored calm, and the
Yankees ground out another strong year. But along the way, the
tension that strained relations between the front office members
located in Tampa, Fla., and the major league staff in New York _
which had been smooth last year _ manifested itself again this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   There was disagreement over how to best use some players,
catcher Jorge Posada, in particular; some of the officials involved
in player development have wanted Torre to play Posada more, while
Torre has used Joe Girardi in about 40 percent of the games. That
debate has flared recently, since Girardi began receiving the bulk
of the playing time in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Some player moves were done in spite of the wishes of the major
league staff. When the Yankees lost the first two games of the
series against the Mets in July, pitcher Ed Yarnall was sent to the
majors, despite the fact that Torre and others didn't know what
role he might play.
</P>
<P>
   In September, pitcher Jeff Juden was promoted to the majors _
again, the major league staff in New York was at a loss to
understand why. Executives involved in development, who work more
closely with Steinbrenner on a daily basis, want the major league
staff to be more cognizant of using younger players, while the
staff has been resentful of what they believe is some
second-guessing. ``We've been winning,'' one person working at
Yankee Stadium said recently. ``Two titles in three years. So why
don't they leave us alone? Everything is coming out of Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chambliss, the hitting coach, may be fired after the
season, regardless of whether the Yankees win the World Series. The
Yankees have waited to decide whether to pick up Paul O'Neill's
option for next season. Girardi likely will leave and may sign with
the Chicago Cubs, near his hometown. Davis is expected to retire.
Other players, such as Brosius and Pettitte, may be traded in the
effort to contain the budget, and the uncertainty sometimes has
made the season difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Success in 1996 was a renewed experience for the Yankees.
Winning in 1998 was history-making. Winning in 1999, with all the
expectations, has been burdensome.
</P>
<P>
   But as he spoke to Davis that day earlier this month, Cone _ who
could pitch his last game for the Yankees in the World Series _
agreed this was no time to worry about that. ``It doesn't really
matter right now,'' Cone said Friday afternoon as he stepped onto
Turner Field, underneath perfect fall sunshine. ``All that matters
now is winning another World Series and adding to the legacy of
this group of players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have gotten used to doing this, Torre was saying
Friday, playing effectively through turmoil and concerns, putting
aside problems and focusing on the task at hand. The Braves mirror
the Yankees in many ways: they have an accomplished pitching staff
and a roster of players deep in post-season experience.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta won the World Series in 1995, and the Braves and Yankees
met in the 1996 World Series, the Yankees dropping the first two
games before winning the next four. The Braves have been the
favorite to win the World Series in most years of this decade,
while the Yankees recently have been regarded as one of the best
teams ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are steeped with experienced pitchers, the Yankees
with savvy hitters. ``I don't know that they're smarter than other
teams,'' Glavine said. ``I think they have a better ability to
stick to their approach better than other teams do. They're good at
going up there and having a game plan and sticking to their game
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Davis: ``You've got all their Cy Young Award pitchers, and
we've got Clemens and David Cone with five. It's going to take good
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi laughed when asked how the Yankees felt about being
overconfident. ``There's no overconfidence in here,'' he said.
``The people in here don't care if we're favored or we are
underdogs. We've got to win four games against a good team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
