<HEADLINE>
TROJANS LOOKING FOR LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's maligned seniors had a sympathizer this
week, even as they were singled out by coach Paul Hackett for their
inconsistent play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as old as the seniors,'' redshirt junior quarterback Mike
Van Raaphorst said. ``I take responsibility also, it's not just the
seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst has filled in admirably since Carson Palmer broke
his collarbone, and has the same number of interceptions (three) in
159 pass attempts as Palmer had in 53.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a lot of criticism on how Mike is doing but I think
he's doing pretty well,'' wide receiver Windrell Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is fooling themselves that the Trojans (3-3, 1-2)
wouldn't be a different team if they had had Palmer for all six
games _ if for no other reason than because Palmer was viewed as a
team leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the team looks at any one player (now). Before
the season, the team was looking at Carson,'' Hayes said. ``When we
lost him, I guess everything just went up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are still searching for someone to fill that void.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say a senior needs to do it, but somebody
needs to do it,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   Strong could play: Although he's practiced only three days at
safety, former tailback Frank Strong will be listed as a backup
today and could see significant action later in the season,
according to Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be interesting to see him progress,'' Hackett
said. ``I expect before the season is over, he will be a strong
contributor.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a position: Three years ago, Stanford's Randy Fasani
was the most highly recruited quarterback in the nation. But he's
never been able to get near the starting lineup, so last year
Fasani tried a few plays at tight end.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Fasani made another change and practiced at
linebacker, and there is a good chance he will play against USC.
</P>
<P>
   Fasani is the third-string quarterback, stuck behind starter
Todd Husak and Joe Borchard, just as he was last season, when he
was limited to just 16 pass attempts. This year, he has played in
five games but thrown only six passes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Fasani went to coach Tyrone Willingham and asked if
he could play defense, and Willingham told him he already had been
pondering the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to waste another year of eligibility,''
said Fasani, who was named the No. 1 quarterback in the nation by
three major recruiting publications during his senior season (1996)
at Del Oro High near Sacramento. ``It was getting to the point
where I just couldn't stand being on the sideline, I wanted to play
real badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Fasani intends to return to quarterback for spring drills to
compete for next year's starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Good line: Stanford's offensive line has been marvelous
protecting the quarterback. The Cardinal have allowed just eight
sacks in six games, best in the Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal defense is almost as good at getting to the
quarterback, with 28 sacks, which ties USC for second-best in the
conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
