<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLASTS IN CHECHEN CAPITAL UNLEASH NEW WAVE OF REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOVY SHAROY, Russia _ A fresh flood of Chechen refugees swept
westward Friday down the main highway into Ingushetia, the
neighboring republic, propelled by fear of a widening war with
Russia after explosions killed scores in Grozny, Chechnya's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the blasts flattened a downtown market and destroyed
a car carrying five passengers, Ingush officials said 3,000 more
Chechens had arrived, which raised the count to about 185,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the disaster at the Grozny market also appeared to have
levied a political cost on Russia, whose depiction of the Chechen
war as a relatively low-level antiterrorist operation came under
sharp criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's standing was not enhanced by a series of verbal
backflips over its responsibility. Military officials first denied
any role in the explosions on Thursday, then declared Friday that
Russian special forces had destroyed the market to stop arms
trading.
</P>
<P>
   It was left to Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, in his debut
before European Union ministers in Helsinki, Finland, to contradict
the military, saying that ``reports of some kind of special
operation'' were not correct, and that Chechens themselves had
probably blown up the market.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Friday at the Chechnya-Ingushetia border, a thin,
black-haired man who identified himself as Ruslan, 37, stood beside
a beat-up minivan with his wife, three children and belongings
packed inside, and said that was beyond belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine what they are saying?'' he asked. ``They are
saying that the terrorists did this. But it is the Russian forces
that were doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   In tears, his wife left her seat and joined him. ``What are they
doing to us?'' she shouted. ``What have we ever done to the Russian
people? They've taken our oil and they don't even leave us a piece
of bread.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The explosions in Grozny were a major topic at the European
Union session, where some officials were clearly disbelieving and
at times bluntly critical of the Russian explanations.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the European Parliament, Lord Russell-Johnston,
expressed shock at the death toll and accused the Russian
government of human rights violations and lawbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   The current president of the European Union, Prime Minister
Paavo Lipponen of Finland, said the group was ``deeply worried
about the deteriorating situation'' in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, the Russian government was vigorously asserting
that civilian deaths in Grozny could not be compared to the
civilian deaths caused by NATO attacks last spring in Yugoslavia,
attacks that Moscow has denounced as criminal rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the White House expressed concern about the
situation in Chechnya. But officials voiced no direct criticism of
Russian conduct of the war, in which more than 2,000 civilians are
said to have died since the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's clear is that there's a tragic situation there with
terrible loss of life,'' the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart,
said. But he added that there were ``conflicting reports and
statements'' about the marketplace blasts, noting, ``We are working
hard to find out what the facts are.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   What occurred, and precisely where, was still being sorted out
in Grozny Friday. With three dramatically opposing accounts,
Russian officials have not made the chain of events any clearer.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the explosions were reported Thursday evening and
attributed to Russian missiles or artillery, the Defense Ministry
denied that any aerial operations had been conducted over Grozny
that evening, and said it had played no role in the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   By early Friday, military officials had executed a partial
about-face. A spokesman for Russian forces in Chechnya, Aleksandr
Veklich, said unidentified special forces had in fact destroyed the
market after receiving ``reconnaissance data'' on Thursday
indicating that it was a storehouse for terrorist weapons and
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the special operation,'' he said, ``the market,
together with the weapons, ammunition and arms traders, was
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Veklich repeated that no air attacks had been executed and that
no civilians were in the market area at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Civilians don't walk at nighttime in a place where arms are
sold to bandits and terrorists,'' he said. ``They sit at home.
Those hit in the attack were arms peddlers supplying bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   But within hours, Russia's internal security service had denied
that it blew up the market. And in Helsinki, Putin revised the
military's declaration to deny, more or less flatly, that Russian
forces had anything to do with the blasts. Rather, he said,
responsibility lay with Chechen terrorists or rival gangs.
</P>
<P>
   An air force spokesman, Anatoly Kornukov, said reports that the
market had been destroyed by rockets were ``disinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   But to journalists who were in Grozny at the time of the
explosions and who viewed the carnage Friday morning, the evidence
of some form of artillery or aerial attack seemed substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports Thursday night that missiles had struck a
hospital maternity ward and a mosque, killing nearly 40 people,
appeared by daylight Friday to be exaggerated or unfounded.
Reporters on the scene said that bodies had been stacked in one
mosque, and that a maternity center near the market had suffered
only indirect damage from an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   But some form of explosive did strike a car in the hospital
yard, The Associated Press reported Friday, killing all five of its
occupants. At the market Friday, Chechens displayed ragged shards
of metal with military-style markings, describing them as the
leavings of a Russian missile or missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists familiar with the market also disputed claims that
it was an arms bazaar. Many Chechen men carry guns, they noted, and
perhaps four or five dealers among the market's many stalls sold
weapons, but the explosions occurred in a section that sold
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen health officials put the death toll at 143. The
International Committee of the Red Cross said its workers had
counted 245 wounded at three city hospitals. None of these
estimates could be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for Chechnya is equally muddy. In Helsinki, Lipponen
told Putin it was time for ``immediate negotiations with
representatives of Chechnya,'' adding that the European Union's
members ``do not accept a military solution to the Chechen
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin said he agreed, adding: ``Political issues can be resolved
via political means only. Chechnya's status will be determined by
political means. The problem is whom to talk to and who is
considered legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   On the front, the Russian news service Interfax quoted Chechen
military leaders as saying Russian forces were moving troops and
armored equipment south through Chechnya, using pontoon bridges to
cross the Terek River. A spokesman for the Chechen president, Aslan
Maskhadov, said the northern suburbs of Grozny were under intensive
artillery bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of the conflict was reflected in a statement from
the Islamic fundamentalist rebel who commands forces battling the
Russians, Shamil Basayev, who said: ``We are fighting to protect
our land and the religion of Allah. Our motto is: `Victory or
Paradise.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
