<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BABY-RECOVERED23-COX     10-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-RECOVERED23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reunion with baby ends Atlanta mother's anguish
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Jay Croft
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After a joyous reunion Friday, the family of an
8-month-old baby kidnapped and taken to Tennessee said they harbor
no ill will toward the teen-ager who police said snatched the
infant at gunpoint from his mother's arms near an Atlanta bus stop
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens to her is up to God, not us. We have nothing
against this woman,'' said the child's grandfather, Willie
Yarbrough, as he stood Friday afternoon at the door of the family
home in southwest Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Yarbrough, his wife, Elizabeth, and daughter, Natalie Evans,
mother of the kidnapped baby, had spent a sleepless Thursday night
praying for the safe return of Elijah, named for the prophet who
bypassed death and ascended directly to heaven in a chariot of
fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't talk to each other, we only talked to God, because
we knew God was the only one who could save Elijah,'' the
grandfather said.
</P>
<P>
   Their prayers were answered Friday morning, when they heard from
friends who saw it on television that a baby believed to be Elijah
had been recovered alive and well in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, the baby's mother arrived at the Decherd,
Tenn., police station, where the kidnap suspect was being held and
the infant cared for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to say, thank you, Jesus Christ, for finding my
baby,'' Evans, 20, said. ``I would like to thank everybody who
helped me find my baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans left Decherd with Elijah 20 minutes after arriving in the
tiny hamlet. He had been examined at Southern Tennessee Medical
Center in nearby Winchester and found to be healthy and unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Beth Westbrook, 17, is accused of grabbing the infant from
Evans' arms Wednesday night as the mother walked toward her house
after getting off a MARTA bus.
</P>
<P>
   Evans told police a young woman appeared suddenly, pointed a gun
at her and wrested the child from her, disappearing into a thick
patch of woods.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday morning, Atlanta police received a call from
someone who told detectives Westbrook had the baby and was headed
toward Franklin County, Tenn., where Westbrook has family, said
Atlanta police Deputy Chief C.B. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The caller was anonymous, but the caller said they believed
the infant was with Westbrook and that they were headed to
Tennessee. We then called the Franklin County authorities with a
description and some other information, and they went to a house in
Decherd, where the baby was found unharmed,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested the teen-ager and charged her with kidnapping
and aggravated assault, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not get a chance to talk to (Westbrook) in Tennessee,''
he said. ``She waived extradition to Atlanta, she is being brought
back, and we'll continue the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said police are at a loss as to motive. ``That's
something that may come out later when we question her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Decherd Police Chief Glenn Summers said Westbrook has been a
frequent
</P>
<P>
   runaway and fled state custody last June when police issued a
notice to arrest her. ``This kid's been running since she was 14
years old,'' the chief said. Summers said Westbrook apparently took
a bus from Atlanta to Tennessee on Thursday night. She then called
her boyfriend's aunt to pick her up, the chief said. When the aunt
asked the teen about the baby, ``She kept saying the baby was
hers,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicious, the woman discovered Westbrook had been in Atlanta
and called police, Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook was arrested at her boyfriend's home Friday morning.
Summers said the girl had been living in the Atlanta neighborhood
for about three months and was a ``casual acquaintance'' of Evans.
Summers would not identify the boyfriend or his family.
</P>
<P>
   No one else is expected to be implicated in the abduction, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook's mother was in Franklin County Juvenile Court and
``in shock'' Friday morning when the young woman waived extradition
to Georgia, Summers said. Robin Swindle, 35, was Westbrook's
softball coach when the girl was 14. ``She was a good kid back
then, just beginning to get wild,'' Swindle said. ``Typical
teen-ager, they all were. I got them for an hour away from their
parents, and you know how they are. She was the only girl on the
whole team who would come to practice in full makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   At Decherd City Hall, Elijah _ wearing a light blue jumper _ had
charmed the office staff, who fed him, gave him medicine for a
sinus infection, and remarked on what a sweet baby he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, we don't know if we want to let him go. He seems to
be teething, too. I can't see any teeth, bless his little heart,''
said JoAnne Van Hooser, an administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Television news crews from Atlanta, Chattanooga, Huntsville and
Nashville, Tenn., set up their vans outside City Hall, and drivers
waved and gave the thumbs-up sign.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of about 2,500, Decherd is about 25 miles west
of Chattanooga. A stretch of U.S. 41 runs through town with
fast-food restaurants and small shops lining it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's excited everybody in town,'' said City Hall worker Rita
Isbell. ``People are calling and asking what has happened in
Decherd that we're getting so much attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Elijah's grandmother held the baby up. ``Hey, Granny's baby,''
she said, smiling at the infant. ``We prayed before we got here and
we're still praying.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Lee, a city clerk, beamed: ``Oh, I'm so glad. That was so
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
