<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL FASHION? PINSTRIPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brian Jordan had just finished taking batting practice
Friday afternoon at Turner Field, and he was engulfed by a swarm of
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He was giving all the stock answers yes, I'm excited to be in my
first World Series, oh sure, the New York Yankees are a good team,
etc., etc. when someone wondered if the Yankees' gallant World
Series comeback against the Atlanta Braves in 1996 would have a
carryover effect on his team.
</P>
<P>
   He shook his head firmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way... this is a different year and the Braves are a
different ball club,'' said the Braves' RBI-producing right
fielder, a one-time Atlanta Falcon starting safety who's been given
credit for instilling a toughness in an Atlanta team that lacked
such a quality in previous seasons. ``I just know I wasn't with the
Braves in 1996. What happened in the past won't affect us now. We
respect the Yankees. But we don't fear anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that the Yankees, who have won 25 world
championships during the 20th century, will close out the
millennium in another World Series.
</P>
<P>
   It's also fitting that the Braves, who have won eight straight
division titles, five National League pennants and one world title
this decade, will be making an appearance in this sacred October
event.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that these two organizations are meeting
again in the World Series, inasmuch as their owners, the Braves'
Ted Turner and the Yankees' George Steinbrenner, have spent huge
amounts of money to stock their teams with a gaggle of high-priced
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan is right when he says this is a different Braves
team than the one that three years ago lost four straight World
Series games against the Yankees after opening with two victories.
</P>
<P>
   This Braves team that commences proceedings tonight against the
Yankees at Turner Field has had to endure the loss of two of its
top batsmen, Andres Galarraga (diagnosed with cancer) and Javy
Lopez (knee injury), and also had to withstand a bruising playoff
challenge from the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   This Braves team has displayed a stubborn resolve that was
conspicuously missing from those recent ones who were known to fold
up under duress.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the wary hunch here is that Yankees once again will
emerge victorious and earn their third world championship in four
years against a Braves team determined to claim that
media-instigated Team of the 90s designation.
</P>
<P>
   While the current Yankees didn't come close to matching the
achievements of last year's club that won 125 games and established
a legacy of greatness, they still affect an aura of cool
self-confidence and matchless poise.
</P>
<P>
   While the current Yankees had several uncharacteristically dark
stretches during the past summer, they have been performing at peak
efficiency during the playoffs, sweeping the Texas Rangers in three
games and then winning four of five against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   While the current Yankees don't have a MVP candidate like a
Chipper Jones, they do have the same cast intact that cut a
frightening swath across the baseball landscape in 1998 with names
like Derek Jeter, Paul O'Neill, Tino Martinez, Bernie Williams,
Scott Brosius, Chuck Knoblauch, Orlando (El Duque) Hernandez,
Mariano Rivera, David Cone and Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, they also have a newcomer, chap named Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves aren't the San Diego Padres, who surrendered meekly
to the Yankees a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   This won't be a four-game wipeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is that we win,'' says the Braves' veteran
coach, Pat Corrales, who sits next to the team's manager, Bobby
Cox, during games. ``Anything less, and we won't be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   The same, of course, goes for the Yankees, who have more good
hitters in their lineup and also have slightly superior depth with
people like Chili Davis, Darryl Strawberry, Jim Lyritz, Chad Curtis
and Luis Sojo all available for pinch-hit duties at Turner Field
where the DH won't be used.
</P>
<P>
   As the Houston Astros, the Mets and every other team in the
National League can attest, the Braves' starting pitchers Tom
Glavine, who opens tonight, five-time Cy Young Award winner Greg
Maddux, John Smoltz and Kevin Millwood can be stifling. And the
same goes for their relievers like John Rocker and Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful the Yankees will score many runs few teams ever do
against the Braves and the Mets' nine-run Tuesday night explosion
was an aberration but it's doubtful the Braves will, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have two extraordinary hitters in Jones and Jordan,
but most of their others never will be threats for batting honors,
notwithstanding Eddie Perez's robust, series-MVP hitting against
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it will be for the Yankees to manufacture hits,
it might even be more difficult for the Braves, especially against
Hernandez, the Yankees' starter tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being with the Yankees less than two years, El Duque
already has proven to be one of his sport's prime big-game
pitchers, as he showed a year ago when he shut down a Cleveland
team that had taken a 2-1 ALCS lead against the Yankees, as he
showed against the Padres in the World Series, as he showed against
both the Rangers and Red Sox in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The wily Cuban exile throws a variety of pitches from a variety
of angles, none of which affords opposing hitters clean cuts at the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte and Cone both have histories of performing
exceptionally well in high profile games. And the other Yankee
starter, Roger Clemens, is one of the most dominating pitchers in
baseball if he pitches like Roger Clemens instead of like that
impostor who embarrassed himself a week ago against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker might be receiving all the publicity because of his
stalwart work against the Mets and his feud with their fans but the
Yankees have the top reliever in the game in Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are solid defensively, although with notable
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, a one-time Golden Glover with the Minnesota Twins,
has become a liability at second base because of his erratic throws
and the Braves' first baseman against righthanded pitchers, Ryan
Klesko, has a knack for turning every fielding play into a wild
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   As for the teams' field commanders, Bobby Cox has been
celebrated in baseball lore for past World Series blunders, but he
has managed flawlessly this season so far.
</P>
<P>
   I still don't know if Joe Torre can manage or not he was fired
by the Mets, Braves and St. Louis Cardinals but he certainly seems
to be able to pull all the proper levers on a team brimming with
talent.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees work counts deftly, deliver hits when needed most,
don't make mistakes and know what it takes to win games, traits
possessed by their championship predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The storied lineage favors the Yankees, and they should close
out business in six memorable games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
