<HEADER>
A5739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATE23-COX     10-22 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush not missed at N.H. debate
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. _ The five men chasing the leader in the Republican
presidential race generally ignored the absent Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas on Friday in a lively televised debate, the first of the
2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who campaigned in New Hampshire earlier in the day, was in
Vermont for a GOP fund-raising event when the forum aired on New
Hampshire Public Television and C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   He has no plans to schedule debates until December, saying
voters are not yet paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Gary Bauer was the only candidate to
mention Bush by name. And Bauer talked about Bush only when the
moderator, Cokie Roberts of ABC News, brought up Bush's comments
about the Senate vote Thursday to ban certain late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush agreed with the Senate vote, but said that people should be
allowed to disagree on abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's comment was nonsensical,'' said Bauer, a
strong foe of abortion rights. ``I wish he were here so we could
talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hourlong debate, however, most of the candidates
showed no such restraint. ``The fact that George Bush wasn't here
is an insult to the voters of New Hampshire,'' said publisher Steve
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``An incredible insult,'' Bauer chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), running second to Bush and
seeking middle ground in an effort to attract independent voters in
New Hampshire, took a softer approach. ``I'm sure Governor Bush
will be joining us'' at future debates, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The first meeting was a civil affair, each candidate laying out
basic campaign themes and not facing follow-up questions.
</P>
<P>
   They all criticized the Clinton administration's foreign policy.
McCain described a ``feckless, photo op'' foreign policy that too
easily sends U.S. forces into action.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes and Alan Keyes, the former U.S. diplomat, charged that
Clinton has cut deals with corrupt regimes in Russia and China.
Bauer and Keyes also called for restricting trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   McCain talked repeatedly about ridding Washington of ``special
interests'' by reforming the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is gridlocked by special interests,'' he said in
answer to a question on health care. ``Why do you think it is we
couldn't give patients some fundamental rights. The Democrats are
in the grip of the trial lawyers, and Republicans are in the grip
of the HMOs and insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes offered his detail-oriented plan for ``putting America on
a true path to prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   In third place in polls here, Forbes touted his plan to impose a
flat 17 percent tax on income, allow Americans to invest their
Social Security taxes in the stock market, and cap government
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who jabbed at Forbes in their battle to appeal to social
and religious conservatives, said his flat tax proposal is fairer
to working families than is Forbes'.
</P>
<P>
   And Bauer also prominently mentioned that he ``spent eight years
serving Ronald Reagan,'' part of his claim to Reagan's mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes said that Republicans who campaign on economic proposals
would not persuade Americans to put a Republican in the White House
during the current economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do face a serious crisis,'' Keyes said. ``It's a moral
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), who does not register in polls in New
Hampshire, talked about his Senate experience and took partial
credit for children's health care initiatives and the defeat of
Soviet forces in Afghanistan in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he ``convinced'' President Reagan to send Stinger
missiles to Afghan fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
