<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NH-REPUBS-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      10-22 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-REPUBS-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINUS BUSH, GOP HOPEFULS KICK OFF DEBATES IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first televised debate of the 2000 presidential campaign,
five Republican candidates excoriated President Clinton on Friday
night for his stewardship of foreign policy and virtually ignored
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the front-runner who did not take
part.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates, appearing at the University of New Hampshire in
Durham, needled one another on health care, abortion and relations
with China. But there were no raised voices in the hourlong session
as the contenders, sitting casually in a semicircle, offered mostly
like-minded prescriptions on education, taxes, trade and moral
values.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest words were saved for a politician who will not even
be on the ballot next year: Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration has conducted a feckless photo-op foreign
policy which may cost us in American blood and treasure in the next
century,'' said Sen. John McCain of Arizona. ``This administration
has failed to understand that we have to have a concept of what we
want the world to look like, where our threats and our interests
and our values lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher, joined in the attack,
declaring that the Clinton administration was ``adrift, indecisive
and just making plain bad judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it in Russia,'' Forbes said, ``where we are today
subsidizing by giving billions that these kleptocrats in the
Kremlin steal, subsidizing a new system of serfdom in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, clearly referring to Clinton, said,
``One thing I do believe is that our president of the United States
should run our foreign policy, and not the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary L. Bauer, a conservative leader, upbraided the
administration, accusing it of having weakened the military.
``Reagan had to spend a lot of time rebuilding the American
military because of the neglect of previous presidents,'' Bauer
said. ``And I'm afraid the next president is going to have to do
the same because of the neglect of Bill Clinton and Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   And Alan Keyes, a former State Department official, said, ``We
should not follow the Clinton administration in the surrender of
American sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate, sponsored by New Hampshire Public Television, New
England Cable News and The Union Leader of Manchester, offered
viewers the chance to see all but one member of the newly shrunken
field before live cameras for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Elizabeth Dole withdrew from the race. Pat
Buchanan, who on Monday is expected to announce that he will leave
the Republican Party to seek the Reform Party nomination, did not
participate either.
</P>
<P>
   The event was broadcast live nationally on C-Span as well as in
New Hampshire by the state's public television station.
</P>
<P>
   This state is expected to hold the first primary on Feb. 1.
Surveys have shown for months that Bush has a commanding lead in
the state, although McCain has gained ground in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's name was not even uttered until more than 50 minutes into
the program when the moderator, Cokie Roberts of ABC News, asked
the candidates about remarks by the governor on abortion. Bush, who
said he could not participate because he was committed to an
appearance in Vermont, said he agreed with Senate Republicans in
prohibiting certain late-term abortions, but said that people
should be allowed to disagree on abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's comment is nonsensical, in all due respect to
him,'' Bauer said. ``I wish he was here so we could talk to him
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, saying there was ``too much polarization,'' was not as
blunt as others in denouncing abortion. ``We need to talk about
many ways that we can work together, both pro-life and pro-choice
people who share the goal of eliminating abortion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders who were on stage did jostle over a few issues,
including whether the United States should repeal
most-favored-nation status for China because of human rights
abuses. Bauer, who was the most aggressive in taking on his
opponents, made clear he was for repeal, then turned to Forbes and
said, ``Steve, would you repeal most-favored-nation status for
China or not?''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes sidestepped the question, saying he supported measures
that would let the Chinese know ``that if they make mistakes, if
they do something wrong, there will be consequences to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   That response did not satisfy Keyes, who also favors repeal. He
interjected, ``We just need a clear answer to that very simple
question.''
</P>
<P>
   After Forbes complained that Americans were losing control of
their decisions on medical care to the government and to health
maintenance organizations, Bauer said, ``Steve, that sounded real
good, but we've got to go beyond generalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiding some of his opponents for their positions on health
maintenance organizations, Bauer said, ``I can't believe there were
some in my party that thought it was a wise move to come out
against my 76-year-old mother being about to deal with that HMO
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, McCain responded: ``Washington is gridlocked by special
interests. Gary, why do you think it is that we couldn't give
patients some fundamental rights?'' He added that, ``The
Republicans are in the grip of the HMOs and the insurance companies
and their huge six- and seven-figure donations.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch quickly upbraided McCain, saying, ``I just don't agree
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes also attacked McCain for not speaking more forcefully when
he said he favored the abolishment of Roe vs. Wade, the Supreme
Court decision legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, senator,'' Keyes said, ``I think the abolition of
Roe vs. Wade would deserve a little louder affirmation than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
