<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BUSH-BOOK-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      10-22 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNVERIFIED ACCOUNT SPAWNED MANY NEWS REPORTS
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An old allegation about George W. Bush, recycled by anonymous
sources in a book that has been withdrawn by its publisher, was
widely reported last week, even by news organizations whose
reporters had long since decided that the rumor was probably false.
</P>
<P>
   Day by day, more news organizations published accounts of the
old rumor that in 1972 Bush was arrested for cocaine possession and
that there was a coverup involving Bush's father, former President
George Bush. Some played their accounts prominently, others buried
them deep within political reports printed on inside pages, and
virtually all included denials from the candidate or his campaign
spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fast-changing ecosystem of the news business, an
anonymously sourced account about the leading Republican
presidential contender lived as a news item. Denials, first by the
Bush campaign and later by the former president, made some editors
judge the allegations more newsworthy, not less.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the online magazine Salon started things off with a
report, flagged on its front page, on the book, ``Fortunate Son:
George W. Bush and the Making of an American President,'' by J.H.
Hatfield. The magazine's editor, David Talbot, said it was
newsworthy to report something that St. Martin's Press, which he
described as a reputable New York publisher, had been willing to
print. Acknowledging that the allegations had circulated for months
without proof, he said, ``The fact they put it between hard covers
made it news.''
</P>
<P>
   That same day, the candidate denied the rumor at a campaign stop
in Phoenix. The denial became the springboard for reports by The
Associated Press, CBS Radio News, The Arizona Republic, The Dallas
Morning News, The New York Post and The Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Wilk, the managing editor of The Dallas Morning News,
said that the details had been published in another report on an
inside page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why go with the denial? It was out there,'' Wilk said. ``We
gave him an opportunity to respond. He chose to respond. I think we
should pass that along to readers. But we make judgments every day
where things go and where in the body of a story the statement
goes. And that tells the reader something.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, there was another denial _ this one by former
President Bush, who called the rumor ``a vicious lie.''
</P>
<P>
   This led to brief news accounts in The Washington Post, The Los
Angeles Times, The Atlanta Constitution and The St. Louis Post
Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Diehl, The Washington Post's assistant managing editor
for national news, said Friday that Post reporters had looked into
the rumors early in the week and that they had failed to check out.
But when the former president issued his statement, Diehl said, the
action was unusual enough to be newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Diehl said, ``You don't want to publish a denial that only has
the effect of publicizing allegations that you think have no basis.
That's why we didn't do anything with reporting Monday. Sometimes
other people or things or events make it news that has to be
reported.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Salon _ whose initial report about the allegations
was still posted on line _ began publishing skeptical pieces about
St. Martin's Press. Talbot said that whatever relevant facts or
context were missing from the earlier article were available in the
later coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But it was The Dallas Morning News that revealed that a man
convicted in 1988 of solicitation of capital murder, a man who had
served five years in prison in Texas, bore the same name _ James H.
Hatfield _ as the book's author, had a biography that matched the
author's and was under the supervision of a parole agency in
Arkansas, where the author now lives.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, News editors posted this report on the
newspaper's Web site. On Thursday, St. Martin's Press announced it
would suspend promotion and distribution of the book.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts of the publisher's decision were displayed more
prominently, in most cases, than any earlier reports. The New York
Times displayed its report _ its first to mention the allegations _
on the front page on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Times, which had spent several days investigating the
rumors, held off printing anything until the action by St.
Martin's. Bill Keller, the managing editor, said Friday: ``Without
verification, why would we want to traffic in unsubstantiated
charges? Once you've made that decision _ the fact that either Bush
or his father is forced by the dynamics of the campaign to deny
it'' is not an occasion to report it.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by St. Martin's, Keller said, changed the picture.
``The publishing house suspended publication of a book because of
these disclosures about the author. That made for a pretty
interesting story. It would be hard to tell that story without
saying what was in the book that made it so controversial. But in
that context it is easier'' to highlight the flimsiness of the
charges, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
