<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KLAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE KLAN LOSES FIRST AMENDMENT DECISIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, October
23: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision by a federal appellate panel upholding New
York City's right to forbid masked Ku Klux Klan members to stage a
rally Saturday in lower Manhattan was a legal victory for Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani but a low moment for the First Amendment and a
city that prizes freedom of expression. Few would quarrel with
Giuliani's depiction of the Klan as a ``disgusting, horrible
organization that represents the very worst of American history.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the city is allowed to selectively target the
free-speech rights of a deservedly unpopular group like the Klan,
it diminishes the rights of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the three-judge appeals panel overturned
Thursday's ruling by two district judges that rebuffed the city's
attempt to block the ``white pride'' rally. The city had cited a
rarely invoked provision of the state penal code that makes it
unlawful to be masked or disguised in a public place except in
connection with a masquerade party and with the permission of city
officials. The Police Department refused to permit the rally if
Klan members insisted on wearing their traditional masks, saying it
would make it hard to identify people in the event of violence.
</P>
<P>
   No testimony suggested that Klan members were likely to engage
in violence. But the lower court recognized that the Klan's
fearsome masks _ themselves a form of symbolic hate speech _ afford
members protection against threats of physical and economic
retaliation for their views.
</P>
<P>
   In its reversal, the appeals panel said the city was not trying
to bar the rally because of the Klan's views but merely enforcing
an existing state law. That interpretation conveniently ignored the
city's selective invocation of the anti-masking provision. It also
raced past a line of Supreme Court cases protecting the anonymous
speech of pariah groups, and other federal court rulings tossing
out similar anti-mask provisions on First Amendment grounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
