<HEADER>
A5755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT     10-22 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HEALTHY BATTLE OF AGENDAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, October
23: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of a real contest for the Democratic
presidential nomination, if any were needed, can be found in the
fact that both Vice President Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley are
moving aggressively to lay out specific policy positions on various
issues. This is a positive development. In the early stages of a
campaign, candidates tend to narrow the field of fire by avoiding
detailed agendas and sticking with safe generalizations. For
different reasons _ Bradley because he wants greater credibility
and Gore because he needs greater traction _ neither man has that
luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Both have offered prescriptions for improving the health care
system. On Thursday, Bradley offered some bold ideas on poverty
while Gore risked the wrath of the oil companies with a challenging
proposal on offshore drilling.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's antipoverty program aims to reduce the number of
children below the poverty line, now 13.5 million, by half over the
next eight years. The plan would cost about $10 billion a year, and
for the most part would involve strengthening existing programs
like the earned income tax credit, Head Start and the minimum wage.
Gore has strongly supported many of these same strategies. The real
contest now will be to see who can better impress upon the voters
the moral need to address this critical problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, returned to one of his signature issues, the
environment, with a promise to ban any new drilling for oil and gas
along the Florida coasts. Like Bradley's poverty proposal, this one
builds on previous actions. Former President Bush and President
Clinton both imposed moratoriums on new drilling leases off the
Florida and California coasts. Gore would go beyond that to prevent
drilling by companies that already hold leases potentially worth
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   This will almost certainly bring legal action from the
companies, and at the very least will cost the federal government
money if it has to buy back leases. Nevertheless, Gore's proposal
is one more important step in the continuing effort to repair the
destructive legacy of the Reagan years, when James Watt, the
secretary of the interior, handed out offshore drilling leases like
peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is designed to reassure those environmental groups
that feel Gore lost some of his enthusiasm for their cause during
the Clinton years. It is also likely to force Bradley to be more
precise about his own environmental agenda beyond his general
remarks in New York on Tuesday. His voting record in Congress has
pleased environmentalists, but only occasionally has he assumed a
leadership role. This is what campaigns are supposed to do _ force
candidates into a clearer definition of themselves and their
beliefs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
