<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-MIAMI-2TAKE     10-22 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-MIAMI-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MIAMI, AN EARLIER PARALLEL TO BROOKLYN MUSEUM CONTROVERSY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIREYA NAVARRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Several years ago, an art museum here challenged the
sensibilities of the community. Much uproar ensued. The mayor and
city commissioners reacted by trying to cancel the museum's lease.
The museum went to court, and won. The First Amendment prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Brooklyn Museum of Art in its current battle
with New York's mayor, Rudolph W. Giuliani, might take comfort from
the tale of the victory of the Cuban Museum of Arts and Culture
over the city of Miami in 1991. But a closer look at the Miami
dispute, which foreshadowed the Brooklyn case in many ways,
provides a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, the Miami museum is out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody closed their doors to us,'' said Ramon Cernuda, a
book publisher and art collector who served on the museum's board
for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum languished like a wounded animal for many years.
Eventually, they succeeded in crushing us,'' he said, referring to
the museum's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the stated religious basis of the objections against the
Brooklyn Museum of Art's ``Sensation'' exhibition, the controversy
here revolved around politics. It began in 1988, when the Cuban
museum, devoted to preserving the cultural heritage of a people
divided by Cold War politics, held a fund-raising auction that
included the paintings of artists who lived in Cuba or had not
criticized the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   The auction provoked a commotion among Cuban exiles here and
divided the museum's board of directors between those who viewed
the artists as representatives of the Communist leader of Cuba,
Fidel Castro, and those who argued for tolerance and artistic
freedom. The auction took place, but emotions were at such a high
pitch that one protester bought one of the Cuban paintings for $500
and then proceeded to set it on fire on a Miami street.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy raged for the next three years, leading to the
resignation of more than a dozen museum trustees, two pipe bomb
explosions (one at the museum, the other under the car of a museum
official), numerous city investigations and three city audits of
museum finances. Finally, Miami officials began eviction
proceedings, claiming that the museum, housed in a former Little
Havana firehouse since 1982, had violated its $1-a-year lease by
selling artwork on its premises.
</P>
<P>
   The museum sued. It alleged that the city's real motivation was
its objections to the exhibiting and auctioning of Cuban works of
art, and contended that the city was violating the museum's First
Amendment rights. In a May 1991 decision, Judge James Lawrence King
of U.S. District Court agreed and stopped the eviction, ruling that
``the First Amendment must assure that government does not curtail
valid expression because a majority, a plurality, or any segment of
its constituency wishes to prohibit or penalize that expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Bade Goodman, a spokeswoman for the New York City Law
Department, said New York officials were not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``That case is only a lower-court case,'' she said. ``That
decision does not bind the courts up here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Floyd Abrams, the First Amendment lawyer who is representing
the Brooklyn Museum of Art in its lawsuit against New York City,
called the Miami case central to the New York dispute and said it
was of immense ``persuasive value at the district level and on any
appeals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In both cases you have a city responding to art of which it
disapproves by seeking to punish the museum that displayed it,'' he
said. ``The cases are very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Any legal parallels notwithstanding, the two museums were in
vastly different positions and ran different risks when controversy
befell them, several former officials of the Cuban museum said.
With a $23 million annual budget and a world-class collection that
ranges from ancient Egyptian art to American paintings spanning
several centuries, the Brooklyn Museum of Art, they say, will
surely survive its current turmoil. Although New York City has
withdrawn financing from the museum and has threatened to cancel
its lease, polls show solid support for the institution, which
dates to the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Cuban museum, which was founded in 1973 to
showcase Cuban culture only, counted on an annual budget of about
$200,000, drawn mostly from the state of Florida and Cuban-American
companies. Its actions were deemed offensive by a powerful segment
of the population _ the conservative exiles who have made Miami
home for the 40 years since the Cuban revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The case here prompted no international debate, no solidarity
statements from other arts organizations, the former trustees said.
The public rejection was so extensive, they said, that most funding
sources dried up and the museum limped along, first with grants
from the Ford Foundation, and later with donations from its
directors, who eventually narrowed the museum's scope to exile
artists only and changed its name to the Cuban Museum of the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum never recovered from the controversy,'' said Jose
Alonso, an art dealer who served on the museum's last board. ``It
had the stigma of being politically incorrect. We tried to
fund-raise and I had people on the phone calling me a Communist.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hostilities, however, the Cuban museum managed to
survive until this year, when news that Miami had placed the museum
building on a list of properties it could sell to resolve a
municipal financial crisis prompted museum directors to explore
their options. In June, they decided to donate the museum's
500-piece collection of original artwork and historical memorabilia
to the University of Miami's Lowe Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   (Miami officials, as it turned out, kept the property and have
turned it into a community service center. Laura Billberry, Miami's
asset management director, said city officials decided to hold onto
it because the city had achieved financial stability before a sale
was necessary.)
</P>
<P>
   Former trustees insist that the museum was not the building but
the collection, and said they were optimistic that it could now
thrive under the aegis of a bigger cultural institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a healthy Cuban Museum of the Americas,''
said Maria C. del Valle, a real estate and art lawyer here who
served on the museum's last board, which is now an advisory group
to the Lowe Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The fate of freedom of artistic expression in Miami, however, is
less certain. Today, violence, protests and verbal attacks still
greet some of the few Cuban artists who risk coming here. Michael
Spring, executive director of the Miami-Dade County Department of
Cultural Affairs, said most Miami art institutions did not sponsor
the work of artists who are still in Cuba out of both sensitivity
and fear to offend.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The psychological and real wounds of Cuban exiles here in
Miami are still so fresh that artistic decision-making takes that
into account,'' he said. But he added, ``If you're trying to build
an audience for the arts, you're certainly not going to program
against the grain as a practical matter.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Local laws also make it difficult for a cultural institution to
stray. A county law prohibits the county and any county-funded
institution from doing business with anyone who does business with
Cuba. That includes recipients of cultural grants. The local law is
more stringent than federal law, which exempts informational
material like books, records and paintings from restrictions
imposed by the American economic embargo of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been improvement, said Cernuda, the former Cuban
museum trustee. Los Van Van, Cuba's most popular dance band, has
been able to perform here despite large protests, he said, and
private galleries sell and exhibit Cuban paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the works of Manuel Mendive, the Cuban artist
whose painting was burned in 1988 by a protester, were sold at a
Coral Gables gallery without incident, Cernuda noted. ``We started
this work of presenting artistic expressions without censorship,''
Cernuda said. ``Back then it was considered crazy. Today, there's a
segment wide enough so that these expressions can't be censored.
That was won in the battle of 1989 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost because the institution couldn't survive, but we
contributed to creating a climate of artistic freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
