<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SET FOR DREADED SPREAD ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ Technically, Oregon State's offense is called
the spread because its numerous wide receivers spread the defense
from sideline to sideline. But for UCLA's purposes, the spread
could be called the dread.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (3-4, 1-3) couldn't have asked for a tougher matchup
today in their showdown to avoid last place in the Pacific-10.
They've lost three of their past four games, their confidence is so
thin it's transparent, they haven't won on the road this season and
they must win three of their final four to qualify for a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   All that, and now their porous pass-defense faces the No.1
passing attack in the Pac-10 and the No.2 total offense  &UR; !ital! &LR; in
the nation.!off! Thanks to new coach Dennis Erickson and his spread
offense, the once-lowly Beavers are averaging 489 yards per game,
including 327 through the air.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's defensive deficiencies are well-documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team's in the spread and you miss an arm tackle, the
guy can go for 10 yards,'' said Bruins coach Bob Toledo, whose team
has missed an arm tackle or 20 this season. ``This will be a real
challenge for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The spread offense, which uses four- and five-receiver
formations, was created 30 years ago by Granada Hills High coach
Jack Neumeier to help his struggling team compete against bigger
and faster opponents. It remained obscure until Cal State
Northridge coach Jack Elway copied it at Cal State Northridge and
later San Jose State. (Elway's son, John, played for Neumeier at
Granada Hills.)
</P>
<P>
   Elway hired Erickson to coach offense at San Jose State, and
Erickson has preached the spread ever since _ at Idaho and
Washington State, Miami and Oregon State. Most Pac-10 teams use it
for third-and-long situations, but only Oregon State and Washington
State base their playbooks on it. The Beavers use the spread on
second-and-four, third-and-two, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The system uses two formations _ four receivers and one running
back, or five receivers and no running backs _ and it's designed to
create numeric mismatches.
</P>
<P>
   If the defense has six players assigned to pass coverage and
five to the run (one defender for each offensive lineman), the
Beavers use tailback Ken Simonton, who's averaging 151 yards per
game, tops in the Pac-10 and fifth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   If the defense commits six players to the run and five to the
pass, then several receivers have one-on-one matchups with
cornerbacks. It's little wonder quarterback Jonathan Smith is
second in the Pac-10 in passing (277 yards per game).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have just five (players committed to run defense),
they'll kill you with the running game,'' Bruins defensive
coordinator Bob Field said. ``You have to have one more guy to stop
the run than they have (blocking for it). But once you do that, you
limit your pass-coverage options.''
</P>
<P>
   The spread will prevent UCLA from playing its base defense (four
linemen, three linebackers, four defensive backs) and force the
Bruins into pass-oriented formations.
</P>
<P>
   They'll use one linebacker (true freshman Marcus Reese) with
five or six defensive backs, and that's when the trouble starts.
UCLA's cornerbacks and safeties have blown coverages and missed
tackles for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way (the Beavers) isolate you with the spread,'' Toledo
said, ``it really makes you defend differently, and it makes you
coach differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the way UCLA's secondary has performed, maybe
different is better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
