<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOIS-AD-AGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOIS CHAPTER 11 SIGNALS A SHIFT IN AD INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An era may be coming to an end in New York
advertising. George Lois, the colorful, outspoken art director who
has created some of the best-known campaigns of the last four
decades, has filed for bankruptcy for his agency company, Lois/USA.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of several big accounts was a primary cause of the
filing. Lois/USA had about 280 employees handling accounts with
billings estimated at $303.6 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lois, who began his advertising career in 1956 after working as
a designer, was one of the foremost figures in advertising's
so-called creative revolution in the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day, but I've had a helluva career,'' Lois,
co-chairman and co-chief executive at Lois/USA, said in a telephone
interview Friday from his office in midtown Manhattan. ``I've done
the kind of work I've wanted to do for 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by executives of Lois/USA to file for Chapter 11
protection in U.S. Bankruptcy Court on Wednesday is indicative of
the intensifying competitive pressures in the advertising industry.
In the past, agencies that lost large clients could retrench,
regroup and recover. But that has become increasingly difficult in
recent years, as shown by the swift closings of agencies like
Smith/Greenland; Geer, DuBois, and Ally &AMP; Gargano.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, I could go to the media and work it out,''
Lois said, referring to the companies to which Lois/USA owed money
for commercial time and ad space. ``Not now.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a petition filed in Manhattan, Lois/USA, which also
has offices in Los Angeles, Chicago, Dallas, Houston and Austin,
Texas, has assets of almost $57.7 million but liabilities of almost
$72 million.
</P>
<P>
   A ``deepening liquidity crisis'' brought on by a change in
lenders and the sudden and unexpected loss of certain key clients
forced the bankruptcy, according to the petition filed on behalf of
Lois/USA by the law firm of Togut, Segal &AMP; Segal.
</P>
<P>
   Trade publications had reported financial problems at the Lois
Chicago operations, which lost accounts from Corona beer, local
Chevrolet dealers and two big drug chains, Osco and Sav-on.
</P>
<P>
   Operations have been suspended in Chicago and New York, Lois
said, adding that a small agency in Los Angeles is remaining in
business. The bankruptcy court has been asked to approve a deal to
sell back the Texas operation, known as Fogarty Klein &AMP; Partners,
to the managers there who sold it to Lois/USA in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lois, who is 68, contributed to the famous Volkswagen Beetle
campaign at Doyle Dane Bernbach and was later involved with
landmark ads for products like Wolfschmidt vodka, Naugahyde and
Coty cosmetics at his own agency, Papert, Koenig, Lois. He also
designed many famous covers for Esquire magazine in the late '60s
and early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lois helped popularize the cry ``I want my MTV!'' for the
cable music channel and gathered a gang of nonsinging celebrities
to warble, ``I read it every day'' for USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking it on the chin,'' Lois said, ``but I've had worse
days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
