<HEADER>
A5777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-KLAN-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      10-22 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KLAN-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHRUNKEN SPLINTERED KLAN STILL LURES DISAFFECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Note time element, Saturday rally 
(ko) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago and at the behest of some new friends,
James W. Sheeley left the upstate home he shares with his mother
and twin brother and drove eight hours to western Pennsylvania.
There, a large cross in flames melted away his life's frustrations,
and he knew what he wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   His search had ended. No longer would Sheeley, a 46-year-old
employee of a small computer-services company, have to hunt the
Internet for an organization that understood the root of his pain:
that ``other groups are encouraged to have pride, but not whites.''
The Church of the American Knights of the Ku Klux Klan understood;
so did its imperial wizard, a bearded, chain-smoking,
barrel-chested convicted felon named Jeffery L. Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sheeley is a member of the fastest-growing Klan faction in
the country _ a growth measured in tens, not thousands _ as well as
being its grand dragon for the realm of New York and New Jersey.
Although his attendant duties of letter-writing and recruitment may
carry no more glamour than those of a Kiwanis official, he revels
in his position of authority.
</P>
<P>
   At a Klan rally scheduled for Saturday in lower Manhattan, which
Klan members say will be the first in the city, Sheeley's
hood-and-robe set will be distinguished from the simple white of
others by the green cape draped across his back, the green stripes
on his sleeves, and the various patches that signal his elevated
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I have very high status,'' he said. ``When I go to
these events, they know who I am.'' (Nonmembers may know, too,
since a federal appeals court on Friday denied Sheeley and his
colleagues the right to wear masks.)
</P>
<P>
   It seems that everybody knows the Ku Klux Klan. A distinctly
American white-separatist organization, its membership soared into
the millions in the early 1920s, with strong local followings in
Yonkers, southwestern Connecticut and Long Island. Today's
permutation of the Klan finds its members, estimated by analysts to
be fewer than 4,000, struggling to outdo other separatist groups
like the Aryan Nation and Christian Identity in provocative
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   And by no means do its members present a united front. Various
factions have splintered from other factions, sometimes for reasons
as basic as some grand dragon yearning to be called imperial
wizard.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League, the Southern Poverty Law Center and
other organizations that monitor the Klan say that in recent years
a schism has formed over a movement toward a more sophisticated
Klan, once personified by former Klan leader David Duke of
Louisiana. ``This group is trying to present the new Klan, in
three-piece suits and focusing on white rights, instead of using
racial epithets,'' said Gail Gans, who tracks the Klan for the
Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   But that position, which critics say is merely racism wrapped in
politically correct language, offends members who like their
crosses in flames, their epithets in plain words and their T-shirts
adorned with racist cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Thom Robb, a Klan leader in Arkansas who
advocates an end to wearing hoods and robes in public, except on
rare occasions. The defection from his organization was so great
that, Ms. Gans said, only 31 people showed up for his group's
annual Christmas party last year. ``As far as the robe's concerned,
we're trying to reach people in the general population,'' Robb
said. ``If the racial movement doesn't like that, that's too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in contrast to Robb is Sheeley's mentor, Berry, of
Indiana. Berry has fully embraced the use of racist literature, the
taunting rallies that flirt with violence, and the wearing of hoods
and robes.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who is 46, likes to quote Rodney King's plea that people
get along with one another, and describes himself as a ``white
civil-rights leader.'' Although he did not return calls seeking
comment, he has said in the past that he holds no malice in his
heart, only a desire to celebrate his heritage.
</P>
<P>
   To the Anti-Defamation League, however, Berry impeaches that
position almost every time he speaks at one of his many rallies.
Last October, for example, he traveled to Jasper, Texas, after the
arrests of three white men charged with killing a black man by
tying him to their truck and dragging him for two miles. In a
speech laced with racial epithets, he declared his hatred for
blacks and Jews and challenged blacks to describe ``one thing your
race has accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the distinction of leading a small Klan group, Berry
might be just another troublemaker in the Indiana county of DeKalb,
officials there say. ``I've spent more time than I'd want to on
him,'' said Monte Brown, the county prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   There have been repeated police visits to Berry's neighborhood,
where he and his neighbors have swapped complaints of gunshots,
bomb explosions and physical confrontations. He was also convicted
several years ago of a felony charge involving a car-repair scam,
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   But as a Klan leader, Berry has become a person of some
notoriety, juggling requests for interviews, boasting on ``The
Jerry Springer Show'' and traveling around the country in his role
as smiling provocateur _ even though he is estimated to have only a
few hundred active followers. (Berry, like most Klan members,
declines to provide membership figures.)
</P>
<P>
   Analysts acknowledge the temptation to see the Klan of the late
1990's as pathetic, almost funny; Berry, for example, occasionally
publishes a newsletter called Thoughts Under the Hood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tempting to treat them as a joke,'' said Chip Berlet,
senior analyst at Political Research Associates, a nonprofit
institution in Somerville, Mass. ``But they'll be back. You have to
assume that there's always going to be these groups, and you have
to stand up to them even if they appear to be in a period of
collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheeley, a grand dragon but nevertheless a relative neophyte in
the world of the Klan, has a much more benign interpretation. He
said his 82-year-old mother, Edith, and his twin brother, John, had
no problem with his avocation because ``they know I wouldn't belong
to an organization that's illegal or violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his association with the Klan forced him to resign in
1997 from the state Department of Corrections, where he had spent
18 years working first as a clerk and then as an inmate counselor.
He stepped down after an internal investigation found that he had
Ku Klux Klan magazines and other white-supremacist literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about hate,'' he said of the Klan. ``It was the idea
that I was frustrated to see that whites have no rights. Other
groups are encouraged to have pride, but not whites. And that
irritated me. I looked around for white organizations to join, and
I kept coming back to the Klan.''
</P>
<P>
   And to Berry. On Thursday afternoon, the two men walked into a
federal courtroom together to hear arguments on their plans for a
rally. Sheeley, a wisp of a man with tinted glasses, seemed even
smaller alongside his imperial wizard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man I like, admire and respect very much,'' the grand
dragon said. ``He's Mr. Klan as far as we're concerned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
