<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5780 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-HUGHES-NYT &LR;      10-22 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HUGHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H. STUART HUGHES, 83, HISTORIAN OF MODERN EUROPE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   H. Stuart Hughes, a historian who wrote extensively on the
intellectual history of modern Europe, died on Thursday in San
Diego, where he lived as a professor emeritus of the University of
California at San Diego. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes wrote 12 books _ six on intellectual and cultural
history, two general histories, three collections of essays, and an
autobiography. Six remain in print.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, as a history professor at Harvard University,
Hughes spoke out for nuclear disarmament and against American
military involvement in Vietnam. He was co-chairman with Dr.
Benjamin Spock of the National Committee for a Sane Nuclear Policy,
and later was chairman of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, the Federal Bureau of Investigation asked the State
Department to have its embassies monitor his activities while he
was in Europe on a sabbatical. His case helped bring that practice
to public attention and prompted the department to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   He was a native of New York and a grandson of the former Chief
Justice Charles Evans Hughes. Hughes, whose first name was Henry,
graduated summa cum laude from Amherst College in 1937 and received
a Ph.D. in history from Harvard in 1940. He also studied at the
universities of Heidelberg and Munich.
</P>
<P>
   In World War II, Hughes served in the Army and was discharged in
1946 as a lieutenant colonel in the Office of Strategic Services.
After two years as chief of research for Europe at the State
Department, he returned to Harvard to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes was Gurney professor of history and political science
until 1975, when he joined the San Diego faculty. He assumed
emeritus status in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 35 years, Professor Judith Markham
Hughes; their son, David M., of Berkeley, Calif.; a daughter and
son from a previous marriage, Sandra L. Hughes, of Chevy Chase,
Md., and Kenneth S., of Arlington, Va.; and five grandchildren.
Hughes' previous marriage, to the former Suzanne Rufenacht, ended
in divorce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
