<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ELAL-JETS-NYT &LR;      10-22 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELAL-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOT OF ATTENTION FOR A SMALL EL AL PLANE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Airbus Industrie released blueprints for a synagogue
in the sky: a converted business-class lounge, complete with ark
and Torah.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, not known as a patron of the arts here, helped haul in
64 tons of Alaskan ice for a Seattle sculptor's installation at
Jerusalem's city gates.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, European ambassadors and American cabinet
members were button-holing Israeli officials, promoting the
purported advantages of the Airbus 340 over the Boeing 777, or vice
versa, and hinting at diplomatic consequences should the sale go
the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Flying synagogues and melting arctic ice cubes are two of the
more visible products of a yearlong public relations battle between
the world's dominant aircraft manufacturers, which are vying to
supply Israel's national airline with its next generation of
midsize jets.
</P>
<P>
   But when El Al's board meets Monday to award the contract, it is
the invisible but palpable pressure from the United States and the
European Union that may prove decisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a campaign that clearly has a political aspect,'' said
Alan Dupiech, an Airbus spokesman. ``There is strong political
pressure in Israel from the U.S., but for the first time there is
nearly an equal response from Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The competitors acknowledge that their aggressive campaigns here
are disproportionate to the sale's size: El Al is deciding between
three B-777s and two A330s and two A340s, an approximately $400
million order that would expand its long-range fleet by 900 to
1,000 seats. Airbus and Boeing fill contracts on that scale almost
every month.
</P>
<P>
   But for both companies, Israel and its airline are a powerful
symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's dependence on American military and economic help has
made it loath to place big aircraft orders anywhere except the
United States. El Al is one of the few remaining all-Boeing
international airlines, and Boeing wants to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had more high-level executive visits per potential
airplane sold than in any sales campaign ever,'' one Boeing
executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has also had more high-level Washington help than usual
for a three-jet contract. Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers
raised the issue with Israel's finance minister, and Commerce
Secretary William M. Daley pressed Boeing's case here this month
with Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to lose competition because it fuels the next
deal,'' Daley said. ``You get on a roll. Boeing was on that roll
for a long time, with no competition, or very little from Airbus.
Airbus is now a very real, serious competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's fear, and Airbus' hope, is that an El Al contract would
give Airbus bragging rights in a midsize market that is expected to
double from 1,500 jets now to 3,000 in two decades. If Airbus can
sell here, it reasons, it can sell anywhere, because of a
perception that Israel would buy European jets only if they were
clearly superior, technically and economically.
</P>
<P>
   For Boeing, though, the American connection is more carrot than
stick. In one pointed display of its resources, Boeing senior
executives were holding a weekend meeting with Israeli military
industry leaders to discuss new contracts with local
subcontractors, which already total $150 million yearly _ much of
it financed by United States military appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   John Leahy, the executive vice president in charge of commercial
sales for Airbus Industrie, lashed out on Tuesday at what he called
unfair support for Boeing from the United States. But the Europeans
have applied leverage of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the French, German, British and European Union
ambassadors to Israel trooped into the office of Industry and Trade
Minister Ran Cohen to make their own pitch for Airbus. After
expressing hope that the sale would be ``independent of political
considerations,'' the ambassadors promised that an Airbus order
``would undoubtedly lead to more extensive Israeli-European
cooperation in the sphere of aeronautics,'' according to a ministry
account of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   That promise is tempting. Airbus, based in Toulouse, France, is
controlled by the newly merged military giants Aerospatiale of
France and DaimlerChrysler Aerospace of Germany, in partnership
with British Aerospace and Construcciones Aeronauticas of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's competitive but small state-run aeronautics industry
has been seeking European supply deals and technological
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four planes is not a huge thing, but collaboration
with a $10-billion-plus program certainly is,'' one Airbus
executive said.
</P>
<P>
   After listening, Cohen told the four diplomats what almost
nobody here believes: Israel's government ``is not involved in the
independent El Al decision, which will be made exclusively on
economic and technical grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   As a state-owned airline with a board of political appointees,
it is difficult for El Al not to be perceived as a division of the
government. Officials here worry openly about the repercussions on
Capitol Hill if El Al were to spend $400 million on European
aircraft at a time when Israel is lobbying for a special $1.2
billion congressional appropriation to cover the costs of
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus also worries about Washington. In 1997, after an advisory
committee urged El Al to buy the midrange Airbus 320 instead of the
Boeing 737, El Al's board rejected the recommendation and opted for
Boeing planes instead.
</P>
<P>
   To seal the deal, Boeing cut its price by 6 percent, a discount
Airbus said it never had a chance to match. ``Two years ago we were
defeated at the ultimate minute by a decision that was hard for us
to understand,'' Dupiech said this week. ``Even if we lose this one
due to politics, we will know that we tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to debunk the notion of an all-American company fighting
a wholly European competitor, Airbus says it provides more than
100,000 jobs in the United States. ``Israelis say they have to back
United States industry, but 40 percent of the content of the A340
is American,'' Dupiech said. Besides, he said, ``If American and
United can buy Airbus, why can't El Al?''
</P>
<P>
   In their final presentations to El Al this week, the main
battleground was price. Though neither company would disclose its
terms, company officials agreed privately that on a per-passenger
basis, the four Airbus jets were cheaper than the three Boeing
planes.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has countered with a proposal to guarantee discounted
prices now for future El Al purchases, and has argued that keeping
the fleet homogeneous will bring additional savings in training and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take every customer seriously,'' said Jim Frank, the Boeing
salesman responsible for trying to secure the deal, ``but when a
customer is using only Boeing equipment, it takes on a higher level
of importance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
