<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, BRUINS' HOUSTON GETS TO SHOW WHAT HE CAN DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ While teammates base their days on plays made
and effort given, UCLA safety Lovell Houston uses different
criteria. Can he walk without pain? Can he carry his books to
class? Should he prep for surgery?
</P>
<P>
   Houston, a freshman safety, will make the first start of his
career today against Oregon State's high-powered spread offense,
which is second in the nation in yards per game (489). But compared
to Houston's past 15 months, the spread's a cinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've felt since I've been here,'' he said.
``I'm finally ready to show I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, of Denver, was one of the top recruits in UCLA's
No.1-ranked class of 1998. He missed his first training camp
because of a strained thigh and was forced to redshirt. He had
surgery on one shoulder in October and surgery the other in
January, each the result of high school injuries. He missed spring
practice, arrived healthy for training camp '99, then strained the
same thigh in double days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were days when it was really, really hard,'' he said.
``After the shoulder surgery, I could barely carry my books to
class. I didn't know if they'd heal right and if I'd be able to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good coming into fall camp, then I pulled my quad, and
that broke me down. I kept thinking, `This is finally supposed to
be my time.'''
</P>
<P>
   The thigh eventually healed and Houston became the Bruins' top
kickoff returner after his 95-yard touchdown return at Stanford.
This week, the coaches asked him to switch from reserve cornerback
to starting safety to replace inconsistent senior Eric Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows how he's going to play,'' defensive coordinator Bob
Field said. ``He's young, and he's going to make mistakes. But he's
a good athlete, and against (the spread offense) he doesn't have
the usual range of responsibilities. He doesn't have to be as
involved with the running game as he would against a normal
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   New surface: The Beavers had the worst AstroTurf in the
Pacific-10 for years. Now, $1.2 million later, they might have the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best turf I've been on,'' Beavers coach Dennis
Erickson said. ``We haven't lost any players (to turf-related
injuries). It's not like the old turf here.''
</P>
<P>
   Full squad: Despite a slew of injuries and illnesses, the Bruins
brought the league-maximum 60 players to Corvallis. The last two
spots went to walk-on tailback Mike Vanis and seldom-used safety
John Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Vanis, who weighs 170 pounds, practiced at fullback this week
because of injuries to the regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're as low (on manpower) as we've been since I've been
here,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
