<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI EMBRACES GOP, AND INDIANAPOLIS CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ As part of his effort to cast himself as a
dutiful member of his party, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani campaigned here
Friday for the Republican candidate for mayor who is seeking the
seat held by the outgoing Republican incumbent. The current Mayor,
Stephen Goldsmith, is also the chief domestic policy adviser to
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had never met or spoken to the Republican candidate,
Sue Anne Gilroy, before Friday, he praised her in a brief
endorsement speech at the City-County Building for her ``fiscal
responsibility'' and added that ``Sue Anne's background and public
career tell me she'll be a fine Mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gilroy, Indiana's secretary of state, is in a tight race
against Bart Peterson, a real estate developer and Democrat who was
the chief of staff to former Gov. Evan Bayh, who is now a U.S.
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani reserved his most extravagant praise for Goldsmith, who
is not seeking re-election and intends to devote more time when he
leaves office to Bush's campaign for president.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said his appearance here was to ``repay a debt'' to
Goldsmith, who he said had helped him with ideas and policy after
Giuliani lost in his first race for mayor of New York City in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind enough to spend a lot of time with me,'' Giuliani
said, adding, ``Many of the ideas that we were able to put into
place in New York I can trace to what I learned from Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith, who like Giuliani is a favorite of the Manhattan
Institute, the conservative research group, has made a national
reputation for himself by privatizing city services.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has never been forgiven by many prominent
Republicans for endorsing Mario Cuomo, a Democrat, for governor in
1994, has in recent months embraced his party as he prepares to run
against Hillary Rodham Clinton for the U.S. Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, Giuliani endorsed Bush, whose extraordinarily
successful fund-raising operation could help Giuliani in his
pursuit of the $20 million he says he needs to run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith said he invited Giuliani about a month ago to appear
in Indianapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
