<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EDUC-MERIT-2TAKES-NYT     10-22 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-MERIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WHAT THE DESERVING DESERVE AND WHETHER THEY GET IT  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (How to define and judge merit has been at the center of bitter
debates over college admissions and affirmative action. Reports
last month that the Educational Testing Service, creator of the
most widely used college entrance examinations, was considering a
program to identify disadvantaged students set off a whirl of
protest. The plan, labeled ``Strivers,'' has been shelved, but the
debate over merit continues. The New York Times asked educators how
they would define that elusive term. Times staff member Joyce
Jensen compiled their responses.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Merit is greatness cut down to size. Beauty and courage are
heroic feats, and fashionable ancestors are luck; but anyone can
achieve merit. The substitution of merit for approved bloodlines in
awarding prizes and building institutions was one of this nation's
most humane, democratic accomplishments. It is now unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   Different people admire different things _ which doesn't excuse
us from making judgments about merit. No responsible parent ever
says: ``In view of the philosophical difficulties, the idea of good
behavior is hereby abolished and my children are invited to do
whatever they feel like. And the weaker ones are advised to take
out accident insurance immediately.'' Recognizing merit is a moral
obligation of parenthood, and also of intellectual life. We have a
duty to seek out future Shakespeares (even future Thurbers!) and
urge them on. We make mistakes; ``merit'' is no infallible Sherpa
guide to intellectual life. But it's the only guide we have.
</P>
<P>
   _ David Gelernter, a writer who teaches at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   When Boston College, the Boston Celtics and Bank Boston pick new
recruits ``on the merits,'' they invariably choose very different
people. Why? Because the three organizations have very different
objectives. What choosing ``on the merits'' means is picking the
people who will help most to fulfill the legitimate purposes of the
institution.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to college admissions, grades and test scores help
predict which students will succeed academically (although not as
reliably as many people think). But grades and scores say little
about which applicants will best fulfill other important aims of a
college such as contributing to the education of their classmates
or to the welfare of society following graduation. That is why
colleges take many other characteristics into account.
</P>
<P>
   Race is such a characteristic, and for several reasons. As
students overwhelmingly attest, racial diversity enriches
everyone's education and helps prepare everyone to live in an
increasingly multiracial society. Minority students also have
special opportunities to benefit society by helping to meet the
widely acknowledged need to diversify professions and leadership
positions in America. Thus, race becomes one valued element in a
richly diverse student body in which all admitted students are
academically qualified and ``meritorious,'' having all been judged
especially likely to further the legitimate purposes of the
institution.
</P>
<P>
   _ Derek Bok, former president of Harvard University and, with
William G. Bowen, the author of ``The Shape of the River: Long-Term
Consequences of Considering Race in College and University
Admissions.''
</P>
<P>
   There are doubtless many forms of merit in the eyes of God. But
selective institutions of higher learning are best advised and best
equipped to judge applicants on the basis of their academic merit,
as measured by grade point averages adjusted for course difficulty,
class rank and scores on standardized tests. These indicators allow
us to predict with considerable confidence who will flourish in
college or graduate school and who will barely scrape by or drop
out.
</P>
<P>
   But some groups earn higher grades and have better academic
records than others. Thus, Asian Americans _ just 4 percent of the
population _ are 27 percent of the undergraduates at Cal Tech, 25
percent of those at Columbia and 20 percent of those at Harvard.
Jews are similarly overrepresented at the top schools.
</P>
<P>
   If groups with large numbers of star students are hugely
overrepresented at elite institutions, groups with fewer high
achievers will inevitably be underrepresented. Pretending that such
applicants have academic skills they lack does nothing to resolve
the real problem, and indeed deflects attention from it. Nothing
less than radical reform in K-12 education is required to make
students from underrepresented groups fully competitive with
others.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephan Thernstrom, the Winthrop Professor of History at
Harvard University and, with Abigail Thernstrom, the author of
``America in Black and White.''
</P>
<P>
   We may never agree about what constitutes merit. But a thought
experiment modeled after John Rawls' ``original position'' can help
us decide what's fair. Suppose you have no idea what genes your
unborn child would have, what sort of family or neighborhood he
would grow up in, or what kind of school she would attend. Under
this ``veil of ignorance,'' how would you want selective colleges
to choose their students?
</P>
<P>
   I think most parents would want colleges to consider their child
as a ``whole person,'' weighing all his accomplishments,
determination and intentions, in light of the obstacles he has
faced. This is in fact what many elite institutions try to do. As a
practical matter, though, we can never identify all the factors
that affect a person's achievement, much less assign objective
weight to their relative importance. So what's the next fairest
alternative? If parents were operating in a vacuum of knowledge
about their child, I suspect they would want selective colleges to
admit students based on grades, not tests. Both grades and tests
reflect a mix of achievement and effort, but grades seem less
fickle because they're averaged over multiple years, subjects and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Meredith Phillips, who teaches at the University of California
at Los Angeles, edited ``The Black-White Test Score Gap'' with
Christopher Jencks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EDUC-MERIT-NYT &LR;      10-22 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-MERIT-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Christopher Jencks. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his brilliant 1958 satire, ``The Rise of the Meritocracy,''
the British sociologist Michael Young argued that the real
consequences of meritocracy are to leave intact the vast
inequalities of a traditional class society while convincing both
the winners and the losers that they deserve their lot in life.
</P>
<P>
   Meritocracy's dirty little secret is that the content of
``merit'' in any given society is defined by the powerful. In
Victorian England, the cultivated Anglo-Saxon ``gentleman'' with a
classical education was the highest embodiment of merit; in Maoist
China, his equivalent was the militantly loyal Communist who
possessed expertise useful to the regime.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States today, the prevailing definition of merit
is a strange mishmash of grades, test scores (especially
standardized multiple-choice tests), extracurricular activities and
that elusive quality called ``character,'' a criterion that was
introduced at America's leading universities only in the 1920s,
when ``too many'' Jews succeeded in meeting the academic
qualifications. The demise of affirmative action in California and
elsewhere has generated calls to redefine merit, and such a
reconsideration is long overdue. But if the past is any guide to
the future, we should not forget that the subjective definitions of
merit that give gatekeepers broad discretion _ the alternative
currently favored by many advocates for minorities and the poor _
can as easily serve purposes of exclusion as inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jerome Karabel, a professor of sociology at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Universities try to determine merit by admitting students who
have demonstrated both intellectual ability (a trait) and
conscientious determination (an act) to do college-level work in
their chosen field. By looking at both standardized test scores and
high school grades, colleges attempt to measure both traits and
acts. A student who scores 1300 on his SAT but barely passed his
high school classes probably won't do very well at a highly
competitive university. But neither will a diligent student whose
hard work earned him a B average in high school but who scores 800
on the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   Most traditional affirmative action programs have been aimed at
black and Hispanic students who fall into this second category.
Worse, many programs admit black and Hispanic students with both
lower test scores and grades than whites and Asians. Unfortunately,
hope rarely triumphs over experience, and such students often fare
poorly in schools where they must compete with more able, or better
disciplined, students.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to determine merit solely on the basis of effort are
doomed to failure, but so is the assumption that ability trumps
all.
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Chavez, president of the Center for Equal Opportunity in
Washington and former director of the U.S. Commission on Civil
Rights under President Reagan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-N     10-22 0861
