<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRATE AT MANNESMANN DEAL, VODAFONE WEIGHS RESPONSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By ALAN COWELL and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Despite a show of public nonchalance, Vodafone Airtouch
PLC, the world's leading mobile phone operator, is privately
considering a range of options including a hostile bid for
Mannesmann AG after the German company's move into the British
wireless market, executives close to the discussions said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann, an acquisitive engineering and telecommunications
conglomerate, offered $33 billion on Thursday for Orange PLC, the
No. 3 British wireless operator, setting itself in direct
competition with Vodafone Airtouch on its home territory, and even
though the two giants have major partnership deals in Germany,
Italy and France.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the situation emphasized that Vodafone had
reached no final decision on its response and was looking over a
palette of possible moves toward Mannesmann, its
partner-turned-rival. And in public, Vodafone insisted that its
relationship with Mannesmann was unchanged, though British press
reports said Vodafone's chief executive, Christopher Gent, was
furious at the German company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have agreements in place with Mannesmann, and we look
forward to continuing to work with them,'' a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts, however, said Mannesmann's move had
fundamentally shifted the balance of power between the two
companies. ``Vodafone has to do something if only to fight for
their place in Europe,'' one analyst said. ``If they don't, their
position would be diluted. There's a lot of sentiment in all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mannesmann's acquisition of Orange is completed, the German
company will reinforce its position as the biggest cellular phone
operator in Europe. Moreover, the deal would rupture what analysts
depict as an unofficial turf agreement between Mannesmann and
Vodafone Airtouch by bringing them into direct competition for
customers in Britain and leaving them to battle for European market
share.
</P>
<P>
   Top Vodafone executives met on Thursday with the company's
advisers to review possible responses, but reached no clear
decision on which course to take, according to executives close to
the discussions. One option was to depict a bid for Mannesmann as
friendly to avoid a loss of face, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said the chances of an offer would partly depend
on the fortunes of Mannesmann's stock, which has slumped since its
share-and-cash bid for Orange was announced early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are concerned that the price it offered for the
five-year-old cellular company, a money loser, is too high. And if
Mannesmann shares continue to fall, that would lower the cost of a
bid by Vodafone, which is currently valued around $60 billion. In
Frankfurt Friday, Mannesmann's shares declined 2.2 percent more, to
140.3 euros, or $149.77.
</P>
<P>
   The German company secured a 12 billion euro interim loan to
finance part of the cash component of the Orange deal from a group
of five banks, including Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Any move for Mannesmann by Vodafone would face regulatory and
other problems. European Union and British antitrust authorities
could be expected to scrutinize an acquisition that gave Vodafone
Airtouch _ itself created only in January _ dominance in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, British competition rules could mean that Vodafone would
have to shed Orange if it acquired Mannesmann, analysts said.
``Vodafone would actually be paying two premiums on Orange and
subsequently have to dispose of Orange, possibly at a discount,'' a
research note from Salomon Smith Barney said.
</P>
<P>
   The note estimated the market value of the Mannesmann-Orange
combination at 90 billion euros, or about $96 billion. ``And
assuming a 20 percent premium on top of that, the size of the deal
would be very large,'' it said. Salomon put Vodafone Airtouch's
market value at 125 billion euros, or $133.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a Mannesmann shareholder resolution dating from
the 1970s forbids any single shareholder from owning more than 5
percent of the company's voting rights, although that restriction
is to expire late next year.
</P>
<P>
   A Mannesmann spokesman parried questions about a possible
Vodafone offer, saying, ``We basically do not comment on such
rumors.'' Vodafone also withheld comment.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone has an estimated 31 million customers worldwide, 13
million of them in Europe. After absorbing Orange, Mannesmann would
have about 20 million customers in Europe, drawn substantially from
the dominance of its D2-Mobilfunk network in Germany, its newly
acquired Omnitel network in Italy and from Orange's 3.5 million
British customers.
</P>
<P>
   The European mobile phone market is expected to double over the
next two years. In a frantic scramble for that market in recent
days quite apart from the Mannesmann-Orange deal, France Telecom
offered $8.94 billion for E-Plus, Germany's third-largest wireless
provider, while Deutsche Telekom said Friday that it would pay $2
billion for the cellular operations of the Mediaone Group in
Poland, Hungary and Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
