<HEADLINE>
JOHN E. SANDERS, GEOLOGIST, DEAD AT 73 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John E. Sanders, a geologist and a longtime professor
at Barnard College who was also a major figure 20 years ago in a
plan to clean up the Hudson River, died Wednesday at a hospital in
Sleepy Hollow, N.Y. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death has not been determined, said his daughter,
Stephanie Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who lived in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., was a specialist in
sedimentary geology, and much of his research was on the geology of
the New York region.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, as chairman of the Hudson River PCB Settlement
Advisory Committee of the New York state Department of
Environmental Conservation, Sanders was also influential in working
out the details of a $200 million plan, with money from the state,
the federal government and General Electric, to clean up 30 to 40
so-called hot spots in the Hudson River that were contaminated with
PCBs, polychlorinated biphenyls, chemicals that have been
associated with birth defects, skin disorders and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was born on May 5, 1926, in Des Moines. He earned a
bachelor's degree from Ohio Wesleyan University and a doctorate
from Yale University. He taught at Yale from 1954 until 1964, and
also served as a visiting assistant professor at Wesleyan
University from 1956 until 1957.
</P>
<P>
   From 1969 to 1989, he taught at Barnard; he also taught at
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and was a senior research
associate at Columbia University's Hudson Laboratories. In 1990, he
became professor emeritus at Barnard. He also taught at Hofstra
University. He worked as a consultant at a law firm, specializing
in environmental law, for several years after he retired from
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders wrote ``Physical Geology'' (Harpers College Press, 1976)
and, with G.M. Friedman, ``Principles of Sedimentology'' (John
Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1978).
</P>
<P>
   Besides his daughter, Stephanie, of Silver Spring, Md., he is
survived by his wife, Barbara Sanders; two sons, Philip, of
Poquoson, Va., and Thomas, of Hawthorne, N.Y.; three sisters, Mary
McBride, of Napa, Calif., Alice Grant, of Plainwell, Mich., and Pat
Webb, of Sarasota, Fla.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991022.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5909 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN     10-22 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE FRESHMEN GETTING SOME ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It wasn't a fancy plan. Just run and catch, run
and catch, day after day.
</P>
<P>
   All summer, Joe Gilliam went to his high school field in Fresno
and prepared for the transition to college football. His former
coaches threw him passes and sent him on routes.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam remembers their post-workout conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said: `You'll just have to work hard,' '' Gilliam said,
``and they will notice you.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Cal State Northridge coaches have noticed Gilliam and
several other top Matadors recruits who are part of one of CSUN's
best freshman recruiting classes.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam, a wide receiver who made his first start last week
against Sacramento State and had eight catches for 99 yards and a
touchdown, did exactly what he needed to do to make an impact at
CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   He and, most notably, offensive lineman Nick Longshore and
fullback Crayton Milton, have mostly avoided the dreaded scout
team, where most first-year players are sent.
</P>
<P>
   Although hard work can pay off, so can luck.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam played last week because Aaron Arnold was out with a
shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries meant playing time for Longshore, a left tackle from
Canyon High who also was impressive in fall camp, and defensive
backs Bryson Atkins (Alemany) and Travis Campbell (Westlake) have
traveled, a rarity for a team that can only have 58 players make
road trips.
</P>
<P>
   Milton, a 260-pound fullback, has been playing recently to
bolster the Matadors' running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing plays a huge role,'' said Jeff Kearin, CSUN's interim
head coach. ``Joe Gilliam, we had every intention of redshirting.
The same for Nick Longshore. The hardest thing for freshmen is
really being ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And adjusting to a life where they are no longer the star
player. Just last year, Marquis Brignac was one of the top players
in the L.A. City Section, a record-setting tailback who led Taft
High to a City title.
</P>
<P>
   Now Brignac is fifth-string.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stay humble, day in and day out,'' said Brignac, who
will redshirt the season. ``It's a `starting over' process. Coming
out of junior high, and going to Taft, nobody knew me there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I can do, compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin's challenge is to keep freshmen such as Brignac and D.J.
Hackett, a wide receiver who was an All-Southern Section selection
at San Dimas High, motivated to stay in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Egos at this level can bruise easily, and thoughts of
transferring can be more than fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great program is able to redshirt their freshmen so they are
here for five years,'' Kearin said. ``I try to tell them why they
are doing it, and that it's to their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett seems to have gotten the point. He progressed slowly in
fall camp and his chance for playing this season was dashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really accustomed to catching hard (passes),''
Hackett said, ``so that put me behind. The people in front of me
are better than me, so I'm not complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the freshmen should look at CSUN sophomore quarterback
Marcus Brady, who redshirted his first year and is now one of the
top players in the Big Sky Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed focused and paid attention,'' Brady said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
