<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-PARALEGALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARALEGAL DIVORCE FIRMS ACCUSED OF SKIRTING LAW
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They call out with flashy signs, subway banners and
ads in the Yellow Pages, promising to deliver hassle-free divorces
at rock-bottom prices. Some say they can do it by mail, while
others assure ``no signature required.''
</P>
<P>
   They are paralegal firms, and their owners say they provide a
beneficial service to those who cannot afford or do not need legal
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But many lawyers, judges and advocates for the poor say these
businesses sometimes skirt the law and subvert people's rights.
</P>
<P>
   The debate came to the fore last month after Steven Singer, the
chief divorce court clerk in Manhattan, pleaded guilty to counts of
taking bribes from paralegal services and high-volume law firms in
exchange for expediting divorce papers.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Kramer, who owns the Divorce Center, says his and other
paralegal firms offer a legitimate service to people who do not
have complicated divorce issues and that people need such services
because the matrimonial courts are too difficult to navigate alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's divorce packet is terrible and impossible to
understand,'' said Kramer, whose two-decade-old company has about
250 offices in New York and New Jersey. ``The courts are very
difficult to deal with and intimidating, and usually the people
behind the counter are very unhelpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say they generally charge $1,500 to $2,500 for
uncontested divorces. Some of the paralegal services say an
uncontested divorce application can be written up and filed for
$150 to $400 on average.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the services sometimes allow one party in a
divorce to take advantage of the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases one party says there is no property, but they
lie, and unless you put the time in to discover this, you will
never find out,'' said Eleanor Alter, a divorce lawyer who is
chairwoman of the Lawyers Fund for Client Protection of the State
of New York. ``Sometimes things like this happen just because of
sloppiness, and sometimes it's desire to do the least amount of
work for the most profit. But you are really talking about serious
rights that can be terminated, and then a person has to spend a lot
of money to rectify the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses specializing in legal matters like uncontested
divorces have boomed over the last decade as court procedures have
been streamlined and computer software programs have been developed
to help people handle basic legal documents. Besides uncontested
divorces, many paralegal firms deal with bankruptcies,
tenant-landlord disputes, wills and property closings.
</P>
<P>
   New York began streamlining its matrimonial court system in
1993, when it introduced new rules that set a rough timetable for
dealing with divorce cases and gave the court system more
responsibility for expediting them. Simple cases are supposed to
take no more than six months, while complex cases are supposed to
be resolved within 12.
</P>
<P>
   A little over a year ago, courts in all counties began using the
same simplified packet for uncontested divorce cases. In some
counties, judges outside matrimonial court and specially designated
lawyers _ called referees _ can now grant uncontested divorces,
further speeding the process.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators of the system say such changes have reduced the
time it takes for a divorce. Contested divorces in New York City
are now routinely handled in about 400 days, compared with more
than 800 days in 1993, according to court statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The court system does not keep information on how long it takes
to get an uncontested divorce, but lawyers and judges say this
process appears to be moving more quickly than in years past. The
average uncontested divorce in Manhattan can now be had in about a
month and a half once the paperwork has been filed, lawyers and
paralegals say, though it can still take six to eight months in
other counties, like the Bronx, which have fewer people trained to
handle such cases.
</P>
<P>
   The paperwork, while easier to understand than before, remains
complicated, and small mistakes, like using the wrong color paper
for certain forms, can cause court clerks to return divorce
documents for refiling, lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than it used to be when I got divorced, but I'm a
paralegal, and even I have a hard time with these forms,'' said
Heather Woolfolk, who went to Manhattan Supreme Court recently to
pick up a divorce packet for her sister.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the paralegal firms say the firms have sometimes been
used to rush divorces through the system, even when there are
complicated monetary issues at stake. Those who suffer, they say,
often are immigrants who do not know their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Other times, lawyers and judges say, unscrupulous ``divorce
mills'' will perform ``sewer service'' by processing and notarizing
the paperwork for a client but never serving the papers on a
spouse. When there is no response, the client can receive a default
divorce judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jacqueline Silbermann, the state administrative judge for
matrimonial matters, said she had seen many cases in which divorce
papers were improperly served and signatures were forged. She said
that in some cases where paralegal firms were used it turned out
that signatures were notarized out of the presence of the signer or
there turned out to be no notary at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``My remedy was to have an inquest, to say the divorce would not
be signed unless both parties came in,'' she said. ``It turned out
that some of these documents had been made up whole cloth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
