<HEADER>
A5924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JOURNAL-EDITOR-NYT &LR;      10-22 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING EDITOR WILL REMAIN WITH WALL STREET JOURNAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two questions hanging over The Wall Street Journal's
future were answered Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's managing editor, Paul Steiger, ended more than a
week of uncertainty by turning down an offer to head all financial
news operations at CNN. A few hours later, company and labor union
negotiators ended more than seven months of sometimes tense
negotiations with an agreement to resolve the volatile issue of
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Steiger nor any spokesman for CNN would comment on the
resolution of the protracted deliberations or on speculation about
the cable network's efforts to replace Lou Dobbs, one of the
best-known financial journalists on television. Dobbs left last
summer for a job at a Web site, Space.com.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking on the condition of anonymity, one person who
talked to one of the parties in the tug of war over Steiger said
that the editor had informed Dow Jones' chief executive, Peter
Kann, of his decision Thursday morning and called Tom Johnson, the
chief executive of CNN, Thursday evening. Friday morning, Steiger
told a group of top editors that he intended to remain in the
managing editor's job, which he has held since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Steiger's decision surprised some executives at CNN. ``I'd just
been telling a friend that I was betting Steiger was coming here,''
one nonplused CNN executive said Friday, adding that he had spoken
with Steiger earlier this week. Exactly what tipped the scales in
The Journal's favor was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   What tipped the union negotiators in favor of a tentative
agreement early Friday was the guarantee of company contributions
of a minimum of 10 percent and up to 12 percent of employees'
salaries as retirement benefits, through two new retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   The company paid out some $40 million in retirement benefits to
roughly 5,500 employees in 1998 under the current arrangement,
which calls for a 15 percent retirement contribution. The new
agreement _ if ratified by the membership of the Independent
Association of Publishers' Employees/Communications Workers of
America Local 1096, which represents 2,400 of the Journal's 8,200
employees, most of them reporters or editors _ would have saved the
company $8 to $10 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The initial proposal to cut retirement benefits almost in half
infuriated many members of the union. It led last April to a
demonstration at Dow Jones' annual meeting, led by Pulitzer
Prize-winning reporters. More recently, it provoked dozens of
overtime claims, which were not honored _ a decision that is the
subject of a pending appeal to the National Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Chen, the president of Local 1096, said Friday that ``the
current profit-sharing plan had no bottom, no safety net.'' He
added, ``The significance of this is that for the first time there
is a guaranteed retirement benefit of 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract also provides for wage increases of 9.5 percent
over three years. A 3 percent increase for 1999 is retroactively
effective to May 1. Another 3 percent takes effect May 1, 2000, and
the final 3.5 percent increase takes effect May 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones' current profit-sharing plan remains in effect through
1999. Next year, two new plans will be established: a pension plan
to which the company will contribute 7 percent of an employee's
salary in one lump payment, and a new 401(K) retirement plan to
which the company will contribute 3 percent of an employee's
salary, paid monthly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company will match up to 2 percent of an
employee's salary if the employee also contributes 2 percent,
according to the agreement signed by the two lead negotiators:
Peter Skinner, Dow Jones' general counsel, and Chen.
</P>
<P>
   The contract will now be sent to the union's board, and
subsequently to its membership, for approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
