<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MORTIMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENELOPE MORTIMER, 81, AUTHOR OF `PUMPKIN EATER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Penelope Mortimer, an English author who drew on her complex and
often turbulent relationships with men in writing novels like ``The
Pumpkin Eater'' and a heatedly debated account of the romantic life
of Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mother, died on Tuesday at a London
hospice. She was 81 and lived in Willesden, a suburb in north
London.
</P>
<P>
   Her dozen novels focus on the upper middle class in Britain.
``The Pumpkin Eater'' (1962), which dealt with a troubled marriage,
was made into a successful film in 1964 starring James Mason and
Anne Bancroft.
</P>
<P>
   Her novel ``My Friend Says It's Bulletproof'' (1968) is loosely
based on an affair she had with a lawyer on a trip to Canada.
``Long Distance'' (1974), which tells Kafka-esque story of a woman
confined to a bizarre institution, was one of the few novels to be
published in its entirety in The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mortimer also wrote two highly praised volumes of memoirs
and several television screenplays, including her adaptation of
``Portrait of a Marriage,'' the 1973 biography of Vita
Sackville-West and her husband, Harold Nicolson, by Nigel Nicolson,
their son.
</P>
<P>
   Shown in the United States in 1992 as a three-part series on
``Masterpiece Theater'' on PBS, the programs were upsetting to many
viewers because of their portrayal of homosexual liaisons and
lesbian love scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mortimer was well known if not always beloved in Britain for
her biography ``Queen Elizabeth: A Life of the Queen Mother''
(1986), which delved into the subject's romantic life before her
marriage to the future King George VI.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mortimer, the former Penelope Ruth Fletcher, was born in
Oxfordshire, the daughter of a vicar who periodically professed to
have lost his faith in God. When she was 16, she attended the
Central Educational Bureau for Women in London to learn secretarial
skills.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, she married Charles Dimont, a Reuters correspondent
with whom she lived in Vienna and observed the German annexation of
Austria. Divorced in 1949, she married John Mortimer, the author,
the same year.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by a son, Jeremy Mortimer of London; five
daughters, Madelon Dimont Burk of France, Caroline Bennett of
London, Julia Mankowitz of London, Deborah Rogers of Cornwall,
England, and Sally Silverman of Bristol, England, and 11
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s and '60s the couple were frequently photographed at
London society events and, The London Daily Telegraph's obituary
said, they ``seemed to represent the last word in marital chic.''
Behind this facade, however, Ms. Mortimer had frequent bouts of
depression. The marriage ended in divorce in 1972.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
