<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FELLS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FELLS ACRES FINALITY 
</HEADLINE>
 ACRE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is likely that the Fells Acres Day School case will be argued
as long as there is a criminal justice system. Was it the
horrendous case of child molestation that prosecutors described and
that sent Violet Amirault and her son and daughter to prison? Or
was it a gross miscarriage of justice borne on winds of hysteria
reminiscent of the witch trials of 17th-century Salem?
</P>
<P>
   The case was among the first of a nationwide wave of child
molestation cases that had the country in an uproar in the 1980s.
In the end, some 40 Fells Acres children bore witness against their
teachers and described fantastic scenes and acts that to this day
stretch credulity. There were charges that overzealous prosecutors
coached and manipulated the children, only a few of whom testified
in court, to make them say things they might not otherwise have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the child molestation bubble burst. Many cases across
the country failed to stand up under scrutiny, and the
investigative practices of prosecutors were shown to be faulty.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the Fells Acres case, two juries believed the
prosecution, and after an appeal, the Supreme Judicial Court of
Massachusetts sustained the convictions, overruling a lower-court
reversal.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have a curious compromise designed to please everybody
and nobody. Violet Amirault has died of cancer, and her daughter,
Cheryl Amirault LeFave, is set free as long as she promises not to
protest her innocence on television, does not make money off her
case, and stays away from children. The state does not admit her
innocence, and she, as she has steadfastly maintained, does not
admit guilt. The state is willing to limit her sentence to time
served but doesn't want to deal any longer with the question of
guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there is enough doubt about the leading of child
witnesses in this case to release Cheryl Amirault LeFave from
prison, but what about her brother, Gerald, who has been in jail
since 1986 on a 30- to 40-year sentence? There is an inconsistency
here that promises to keep the Fells Acre case alive for a long
time to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
