<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-HITLER-BOS &LR;      10-22 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HITLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINAL SOLUTION FOR HITLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Berlin construction workers accidentally dug up part of Adolf
Hitler's bunker last week, fueling the debate about what historical
relics should be saved and what are best left buried.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin city officials made the right call when they stuck by a
1994 decision not to preserve the former Nazi leader's compound.
The construction crew was told to cover up the 20-foot slab of
concrete believed to be the roof of Hitler's bunker and to continue
building a new street and government offices over the remains,
which beneath a plot of grass south of the Brandenburg Gate.
</P>
<P>
   That is fitting symbolism _ smothering the hard, ugly power of
the past under modern political foundations. A country cannot
obliterate its history, nor should it try, but it most definitely
can move on.
</P>
<P>
   No one should forget why the concrete is there, just as no one
should forget the evil that Hitler unleashed upon the world. But
that heinous time is best recalled in solemn walks through
Holocaust memorials and museums. It can also be remembered through
countless books and movies that tell the story of the madman who
sought to annihilate the Jewish people and dominate the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Putting parts of his bunker on display, or excavating whatever
might still be found in the dust of the bombproof strongholds
Hitler built for himself and his associates, would serve no purpose
other than feeding morbid curiosities. Such a display might also
attract neo-Nazi groups and become a rallying place for racist
violence.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Hitler's birthday, April 20, has been a rallying
date for hate group demonstrations and attacks _ it may have been a
catalyst for the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995 as well as the
Columbine High School shootings in Colorado last spring. Hitler
does not deserve a shrine. His memory stands as a warning to the
world on the crest of a new millennium: Beware the hater and do not
follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
