u w BC-ARMY-ASSAULT-NYT &LR;      10-22 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-ASSAULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOP NONCOMMISSIONED OFFICER CHARGED WITH SEX ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the highest noncommissioned officers in the
Army has been charged with sexually assaulting a female sergeant in
Germany last April in the latest in a series of embarrassing
sex-related incidents in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials announced on Thursday that Sgt. Maj. Riley Miller
had been accused of forcible sodomy, kidnapping, indecent assault
and maltreatment of a subordinate.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued in Heidelberg, Germany, the Army said the
crimes were believed to have been committed in Hanau, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Montgomery Meigs, commanding general of United States Army
forces in Europe, said Miller was relieved of his duties on Sept.
22 pending an investigation. In its statement, the Army stressed
that the defendant was presumed innocent until and unless proven
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Meigs said the accusations made it impossible for Miller to
carry out his duties.
</P>
<P>
   As the top noncommissioned officer in Europe, Miller has one of
the most prestigious posts among the enlisted ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is 51 and has 30 years of service, including Vietnam
combat for which he was awarded numerous decorations, The
Washington Post reported in its Saturday editions. The Post said
the woman he was accused of attacking was a sergeant who served as
his driver. He is married and had served in his post about three
years, The Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the accusations surfaced, Miller was a strong candidate to
be the next sergeant major of the Army. A predecessor in that
position, Gene McKinney, had been accused of sexual harassment. In
1998, he was convicted of obstruction of justice and demoted to
master sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the armed services have had to deal with
numerous sex-related episodes, some involving adultery or
fraternization _ military charges that have no real parallel in
civilian life _ and some involving harassment or assault. The
accused have ranged from enlisted men and women to generals.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's announcement did not describe Miller's new duties,
nor did it say whether he was still receiving his full salary. If
convicted of all charges, he could be given a dishonorable
discharge, sentenced to prison and forfeit his benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
