<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FORESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING THE FORESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's far-reaching decision to extend protection
to 40 million acres of national forest highlights the largest
single treasure still vulnerable to timber industry ambitions. The
17-million-acre Tongass rain forest in Alaska, not covered by
Clinton's action, is still in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Every woodland has unique characteristics that distinguish it
from others _ terrain, type of tree, the animals and birds that
live in it. The Tongass is special even in this company. It is the
last native growth of woodland fed by steady flows of moist air
from the Pacific _ the only surviving temperate rain forest in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, its streams are spawning zones for the Pacific
salmon, an important economic resource in itself. Those salmon are
put at risk by logging roads, which can still be built in Tongass
in the absence of action by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Tongass issue pits Clinton, who has done a great deal to
protect forest tracts during his presidency, against Senator Ted
Stevens, an Alaska Republican who is a dogged supporter of
timbering operations in the Tongass. As chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, Stevens can threaten any piece of
legislation involving money in retaliation for moves to protect
Tongass.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's support of forest protection should stand him in good
stead in dealing with the Tongass issue before he leaves office.
The highest level of protection _ ``wilderness'' designation _
requires congressional approval, an unlikely course given the
political realities that Stevens typifies. But Clinton made good
use of his executive powers in starting a process that will ban
road building and other development in the 40 million acres covered
by his recent action. Congress lacks the power to overturn such
action without legislation the president would likely veto.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching over millions of acres, the Tongass is a precious
asset that deserves the fullest reasonable protection before
Clinton leaves office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
