<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-22 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SCHOOLS-BOS     10-22 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDS NOW, VOUCHERS MAYBE LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an encouraging indicator that partisanship may not freeze all
action on Capitol Hill, the House this week turned back an
ill-advised school voucher program and voted to continue one of the
nation's most basic and successful education programs _ Title I.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, Title I has directed federal money to
students, most of them poor, who are at least two grade levels
behind their peers. While results have varied from state to state,
the overall impact has been to equalize educational opportunity
across the country. The program accounts for more than half of the
federal dollars spent for education progams in kindergarten through
Grade 12.
</P>
<P>
   The reauthorization of Title I, which carries a price tag of
$8.3 billion to help 10.5 million students in the next five years,
had little direct opposition. Chairman William Goodling of the
House Education and Workforce Committee was a strong supporter
because of accountability provisions that have been added.
</P>
<P>
   But the House majority leader, Dick Armey, tried to attach a
voucher plan that would give parents of low-performing students up
to $3,500 to send them to private or parochial schools. Fifty-two
Republicans, including Goodling, joined in defeating the voucher
proposal, 257-166.
</P>
<P>
   Vouchers had the support of most of the Republican leadership,
but the proposal was misguided. Vouchers can drain public funds
from public schools, making them worse for the students who remain
and diminishing hope for improvement. Vouchers can also raise
constitutional church-state difficulties. And there is no assurance
that they would produce better learning.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence on the effectiveness of vouchers should be gathered
carefully on a pilot basis. The issue is already under study in
Milwaukee, in Florida, and before the US Supreme Court, which is
considering an Ohio voucher case. There is no need for a nationwide
program that could produce disastrous results for many schools and
students.
</P>
<P>
   The House did well to reauthorize Title I, with minor
improvements, and not make the issue more complex and contentious
than it needed to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-99 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
